<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BERKOW-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: TYSON'S SELF-ABSOLUTION  
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By IRA BERKOW   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Once again Mike Tyson in a minute takes full blame for his
actions.
</P>
<P>
   Until the next minute, when he generously absolves himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's no one's fault but mine,'' he told the five-man Nevada
State Athletic Commission Monday, which was deciding whether to let
him back in the ring a year and a half after he presumably mistook
Evander Holyfield's ears for an entree. ``Some people are sheltered
and protected,'' he went on, ``born with a silver spoon in their
mouth. They don't know what it's like to be hungry and scared and
have to have courage.''
</P>
<P>
   The implication is clear, it wasn't his fault: It was the
neighborhood. Tyson grew up in mean circumstances in the
Brownsville section of Brooklyn, and it was inevitable that he
would become a convicted rapist and perpetrator of other crimes,
misdemeanors and assorted crude behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, all kids like Mike who from the age of 12 grew up in a
nine-bedroom Victorian mansion on 10 acres of land on the Hudson
River are disadvantaged,'' said Teddy Atlas, a one-time assistant
trainer for Tyson when they both lived in the Catskills home of the
trainer Cus D'Amato.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was treated like a prince,'' said Bill Cayton, who, along
with Jimmy Jacobs, managed Tyson in his early years, after taking
him out of a reform school and sending him to D'Amato. ``We spent
nearly a half-million dollars on him from the time Mike was 12 to
when he was 18.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlas added: ``A lot of people in many different fields have
come out of Brownsville, and other poor areas, and not gotten into
anything near the kind of trouble Mike Tyson's got into.'' He named
three: Eddie Mustafa Muhammad, Floyd Patterson _ former boxing
champions _ and Rodney Tyson.
</P>
<P>
   Rodney Tyson? He is Mike Tyson's older brother, who at 37 is
five years older than Mike. Rodney grew up in the same place with
the same mother and for a while the same father, who would leave
their home when Mike was 6. Rodney Tyson went to the Navy and
studied pharmacy and is, at last report, employed by a Los Angeles
druggist.
</P>
<P>
   Rodney Tyson could not be reached for comment Wednesday, but in
a Newsday interview several years ago, he said that his brother had
always been ``volatile,'' going back to when he was 9. ``As long as
he's doing something with his hands without putting them in other
people's pockets, we're happy,'' Rodney said, as a kind of family
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   As a boy Tyson became a pickpocket on public buses, rolled
drunks and mugged old ladies of their purses. By the time he was
13, he had been arrested 38 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all had hard lives,'' Mike Tyson told Mark Kram in the
Playboy interview in the November issue. He said the family had
been on welfare. ``Humiliating.'' And yet, he said: ``Brownsville
was happy, too. Nothing big, just going to the pool. Gambling
without anybody getting killed or robbed over a dice game.
Laughing. Cooking food outside and music. That was fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone grows up differently; the combination of environment
and genetic makeup and the early impacts of life are not the same
for any two people. But Tyson seems to be as divided internally as
few others are.
</P>
<P>
   Is he rationalizing, or is he simply lying, or denying when he
speaks so self-servingly and ambiguously about himself? He bit
Holyfield's ears because he was head-butted. He didn't punch two
motorists in August but ``if I did, I was unconscious, and I'm
sorry.'' And so on.
</P>
<P>
   The Nevada commission had wondered what the future looked like
for him _ and for the ears of his possible opponents. They sought a
psychological evaluation to see if he was mentally capable of going
back into the ring.
</P>
<P>
   The conclusion reached by a host of medical authorities was that
Tyson was normal enough to return to his brutal sport. The report
added that Tyson suffered from ``rage,'' and it should be monitored
with mental therapy, but the commission properly decided to allow
him, after having served a year's suspension, to again earn a
living in his vocation. As to the rage: Tyson has said ominously
more than once that ``I know I will blow one day.''
</P>
<P>
   The hope is that we've seen the last of Mike Tyson the Reprobate
and will be treated forevermore to Mike Tyson the Reformed, as he
has, yes, promised yet again.
</P>
<P>
   It is unlikely, however, to happen until he finally believes
that the fault, dear Mike, is not in Brownsville, but in yourself.
</P>
<P>
   Which leaves society _ in the ring and out _ with this alarming
question: Can Mike Tyson reach a benign insight before he
``blows''?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
