<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SERIES-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTE FOR THE RECORD BOOKS: ONE HUNDRED TWENTY-FIVE
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ They needed the sweep on Wednesday night. They
needed it for history.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees were going to win their 125th game anyway, one of
these nights, but four straight against the Padres was the way to
punctuate this special season, to make the final statement of who
they are, what they have accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   They even had a fitting obstacle to becoming only the 16th team
to sweep a World Series: Kevin Brown, the fierce-looking
right-hander, who runs and hits and pitches. However, Andy Pettitte
was even better, shutting down the Padres, 3-0, as the Yankees won
their 24th world championship _ a record for North American team
sports, forging ahead of the Montreal Maroons/Canadiens of the
National Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   With 125 victories this year, the Yankees won more games than
any baseball team in history. Even factoring in the higher totals
from the four-year-old system of a three-tiered championship, the
Yankees are now worthy of being compared to the 1927 Yankees, the
1975 Cincinnati Reds, the Oakland A's of the early 70s, or teams of
earlier decades that few of us can remember or judge adequately.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like a sweep, just so we can finish it,'' Joe Torre said
before the game. ``When it's all said and done, and we look back
and you start comparing, then I think we can get caught up in it.
But right now we can't afford that luxury.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre prefers to compare his team to a dynasty from another
sport _ the old Boston Celtics of the National Basketball
Association (remember that league?).
</P>
<P>
   ``They were such a good team team,'' Torre said, using the word
as both a noun and an adjective. ``Nobody really cared if anybody
scored 30 points, with Russell in the middle and Ramsey, and all of
those people, they worked together as a unit, and it was fun to
watch them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Celtics gained in stature from worthy opponents in the
finals, whether it was the St. Louis Hawks of Bob Pettit or the Los
Angeles Lakers of Jerry West and Elgin Baylor. The 1996 Yankees
will be remembered as the team that lost two and then bounced back
to win four straight against the powerful Atlanta Braves.
</P>
<P>
   These Yankees would not have gained much luster from a long
series with the Padres, unless there were epic games, heroic
doings. A sweep was the way to go, and its value was enhanced
slightly because Brown was able to take the mound Wednesday night,
bruised shin and rheumy eyes notwithstanding.
</P>
<P>
   It was Brown who helped the Florida Marlins _ not exactly a
dynasty for the ages under the callous stewardship of Wayne
Huizenga _ win the World Series last year.
</P>
<P>
   Given the two travel days, one hot pitcher can dominate a World
Series. If Brown had come into Yankee Stadium and shut down the
Yankees, their entire destiny could have been threatened. What good
are 114 victories if you lose the World Series?
</P>
<P>
   However, Brown was weakened in that first game by a bug that was
going around the Padres. According to their resident expert on
infectious bacteria, Jim Leyritz, the bug was brought onto the
Padres' charter ``by some of the kids or wives.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a possibility that if the Padres could somehow carry
the Yankees deep into this World Series, then the nasty little
microbes might make a leap from the affected San Diego players to
the Yankees via an unwitting host _ namely the shuffling baseball
writers, their health and morale already undermined by the bad
hours, the bad food in stadiums, the bad ergonomics in crowded
press boxes, plus the foul air on airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees showed no signs of waiting for some epidemic or
slump or negative moon rays to affect them. They had destroyed
everything in their path since the first week, when they lost three
straight and the tabloids and the talk radio people were choosing
Torre's replacement. Honest, that really happened.
</P>
<P>
   It may be mere whimsy to try to compare teams of different
generations, but these Yankees were clearly a model of good
character, good fundamentals, good strategy, good training, good
athleticism, in their own time. It has been clear since the spring
that this was a special team, that it would not self-destruct. The
Yankees wanted their 125th victory sooner rather than later, and
they got it. They were like that for this entire long and glorious
season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
