</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SERIES-PETTITTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: PETTITTE'S POSITIVE THINKING PAYS OFF 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Andy Pettitte was relieved before he ever threw a
pitch against the Padres Wednesday night because his father, Tom,
was released from the hospital Wednesday after undergoing double
heart-bypass surgery last Thursday. So as Pettitte tried to guide
the Yankees to a World Series sweep, it was comforting for him to
know that his father was watching on television from home in Deer
Park, Texas. He was safe.
</P>
<P>
   The relief about Tom's health was obvious as Pettitte talked
about his father on Tuesday. The reverence was just as apparent as
he talked about how Tom tutored him as a pitcher from the time he
was 8 years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the reason that I'm even here,'' said Pettitte. ``He's
been my pitching coach from the first time I picked up a baseball.
I want him to have a good time with this.''
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte made certain that his father and the Yankees would
enjoy Wednesday night forever with a superb pitching performance
that allowed them to beat the Padres, 3-0, in Game 4 and win their
second World Series Championship in three years.
</P>
<P>
   After being passed over to start in Game 2 or Game 3 and after
ending the season as the biggest question mark in the rotation
other than Hideki Irabu, Pettitte ended his season in style.
Wednesday night, Pettitte was like the Pettitte of old, stopping
the Padres on no runs and five hits for seven and one third
innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it's been a great season,'' said Pettitte. ``It's been
unbelievable the way that we have played. And that would be a great
way for me to end this, I guess, dismal or sub par season. I'd like
to be able to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider it done as Pettitte ran his scoreless streak in the
World Series to 15 2/3 innings. It was a redemptive outing for
Pettitte, who was not seriously considered to start sooner after
being pounded for four homers by the Indians in Game 4 of the ALCS.
Even though Pettitte probably benefited from the rest because of
the anguish over his father's condition, he was not happy about
being pushed to the end of the rotation. When the left-hander was
asked if he thought starting the fourth game would be helpful, he
bluntly said, ``Not really.''
</P>
<P>
   So Pettitte reminded manager Joe Torre and everyone else what he
can do and what he had done in Game 5 of the 1996 World Series.
Pettitte outpitched John Smoltz when the Yankees nipped the Braves,
1-0, in Game 5 and he provided more of the same artistry in
subduing the Padres Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to dwell on the problems I've had this year,''
said Pettitte. ``I'm going to think positive. You need to be
positive instead of negative out there.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the same type of advice Pettitte had dispensed to his
father, imploring him to relax and enjoy watching his son pitch for
the Yankees. But Tom has admitted that it is difficult for him to
do. Before Pettitte pitched Game 2 of the Division Series against
the Rangers, his father worked the graveyard shift at a chemical
plant and did not watch the game because he said it annoys him to
hear his son get criticized.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not fun listening to people beat up on your kid,'' said
Tom two weeks ago. ``I've always been more critical of Andy than
any New York fan or New York media, but he's my kid. I can do that.
To hear other people ripping your kid hurts.''
</P>
<P>
   When Pettitte rushed to Texas for his father's surgery on
Thursday, he admitted that he was frightened. But even as
Pettitte's father was lying in a hospital bed, he tried to soothe
his son and get him to focus on the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I left he was still in I.C.U. and he had tubes in him and
stuff like that so he could barely talk to me,'' said Pettitte.
``He always talked about baseball. He told me not to worry about
him, he's going to be fine and get ready to pitch my game.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre could not be blamed for starting Orlando Hernandez in Game
2 and David Cone in Game 3 because Pettitte had been too
inconsistent. For a pitcher who was 16-10 with a 4.24 earned run
average, Pettitte was not reliable. Even after Pettitte throttled
the Rangers in the division series, the Yankees wondered if he had
emerged from his drought. He had not as the Indians treated him
like a batting practice pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   But Pettitte came back on 11 days rest and was terrific. He
squeezed through a bases-loaded jam in the second and erased Ruben
Rivera off second in the seventh when he corraled Carlos
Hernandez's chopper and caught Rivera between second and third. It
was the kind of night that made lots of fathers and sons smile, but
none smiled as broadly as the Pettittes.
</P>
<P>
   ``All any parent wants is for his son to do well and to be
treated fairly by people,'' said Tom Pettitte, earlier this month.
``You want him to get a shot to do what he wants.''
</P>
<P>
   Andy Pettitte got it, he seized it and the Yankees are champions
again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
