</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SERIES-STEINBRENNER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BOSS IS LOVING IT, AND HE WON'T LET GO 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JACK CURRY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ George Steinbrenner's team was getting ready to win
another World Series championship and soar into baseball history as
one of the best teams ever, but the principal owner, for once, was
straining for words. In the hours before Game 4, Steinbrenner was
searching for the proper way to describe this team, this team for
the ages. He settled on calling it astounding, with unbelievable as
a close second.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, however, Steinbrenner did not struggle for the
right words when he was asked about the possibility that he would
sell the Yankees, especially now that their already handsome value
should increase with their 24th World Series title in hand.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner has acknowledged having had sale discussions with
Cablevision, which also owns the Knicks, the Rangers and Madison
Square Garden. The possible purchase price for the Yankees is said
to range from $500 million to $900 million, and Steinbrenner
admitted recently that the discussions have included a tiered
pricing system depending on how far the team advanced in the 1998
post-season.
</P>
<P>
   According to people in baseball with knowledge of the talks,
Steinbrenner would remain in power for three years. In a telephone
interview Wednesday, the 68-year-old owner repeatedly declined to
answer questions about a possible sale, but he did not sound ready
to cede his ownership.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will tell you this, I'm never going to be in a situation
where I have a token role,'' Steinbrenner said. ``Like having
someone say, `Sell it to me and you can do a little.' I am going to
contribute by being in majority ownership. I'm very happy with all
of my people and everything that is happening now.''
</P>
<P>
   In one move, Steinbrenner could sell the Yankees for an
extravagant amount, avoid the wrangling over the fight for a new
stadium and avoid dealing with sticky free-agent issues like the
one involving Bernie Williams that will cloud the assembling of the
1999 team. But he said nevertheless that his youngest son, Hal, and
his son-in-law, Steve Swindal, were interested in eventually
operating the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, neither Hal nor Hank Steinbrenner, the owner's sons,
nor Swindal has seemed open to this possibility, and Yankee
officials have long stressed that no one in Steinbrenner's family
wants the responsibility of running the organization. Posturing or
not, Steinbrenner said: ``I've got sons and a son-in-law. If Steve
and Hal told me they like running this thing, I can walk away. If
my family wants it, I should be willing to give it to them. I'm
convinced that they do want it. You think I'm intense? Those two
are wrung out after each game. You should see how hard they take
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Hal Steinbrenner, 29, has been listed as a general partner of
the Yankees since 1996; Swindal, 43, is in his first season as a
general partner. Both have stayed in the background, and
Steinbrenner's most significant praise for them was for the
development of the Yankees' Web site.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even know how to turn on the computer,'' said
Steinbrenner. ``You should see what they do.''
</P>
<P>
   When Steinbrenner was reminded that he could stroll into
baseball's sunset after one of the best seasons ever, with a far
bigger fortune for generations of Steinbrenners _ and all without
ever having to worry about payroll questions, stadium issues,
revenue sharing or unfavorable headlines as he approaches 70 _ he
did not seem eager to leave a position that has made him perhaps
the most recognizable owner in sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me say this, I want to put my family in a position where
they can be sure that they can take over this team,'' Steinbrenner
said. ``There are different rumors and different prices. I've just
told people I won't deal with that right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner would not specifically discuss the impending free
agency of Williams or Scott Brosius, although it appears that the
third baseman is more likely to remain with the Yankees than the
center fielder. Some Yankee officials are convinced that Williams
is already planning to leave because Scott Boras, his agent,
realizes the Yanks will probably not offer him the $12 million or
more a year he is expected to seek. Although Steinbrenner pledged
to work ``pretty hard'' to keep the team intact, he admitted that,
inevitably, there will be changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you will see that,'' Steinbrenner said. ``Everybody
knows that. I hope some of the people who are here are convinced of
how great it is here. If you talk to some of the people who left,
I'm sure they'd tell you they wish they were here.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Yankees having won the Series in dazzling style, there
will be pressure to keep the team together. But after the 1996
World Series, the Yankees allowed John Wetteland, that most
valuable player of that Series, and Jimmy Key, who won the
clinching sixth game, to sign free-agent contracts with other
teams. Steinbrenner reasoned that there would be as much pressure
on the possibly departing players to stay as there would be on him
to retain them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing in an Old Lady, but we dress her up pretty darn
good each season,'' Steinbrenner said, referring to Yankee Stadium.
``It's a privilege to be a Yankee. It really is. No team in sports
has ever won 24 championships, and we're about to. You've got to
like this situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner likes symmetry, another reason why he loved the
idea that the Yankees were about to snatch their 24th title. The
Yankees have a World Series design that lists the different years
of their titles, and it has bothered Steinbrenner for two years
that the first three lines housed six championship years each and
the fourth line had only five years and a lonely asterisk.
Steinbrenner can now look forward to erasing the asterisk.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been astounding,'' he said. ``That's the best way to
describe it.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
