<P>
   (NYT24) SAN DIEGO -- Oct. 21, 1998 -- BBO-SERIES-1, 10-21 -- The
Yankees' Scott Brosius relaxing Wednesday before game 4 of the
World Series with the Padres. Brosius slugged two home runs Tuesday
night in game 3, including a three-run shot in the eighth inning
that gave the Yankees a 5-4 victory over San Diego and a commanding
three games-to-none lead in the best-of-seven series. (Barton
Silverman/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT23) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 21, 1998 -- STARR-HUBBELL, 10-21 --
After meeting with independent counsel Kenneth Starr, Webster
Hubbell and his wife, Suzy, leave federal court Wednesday in
Washington. Starr offered a broad defense to the repeated criticism
that he had overreached in his investigation of President Clinton's
inner circle, using the forum of an appeals court where he sought
to reinstate his criminal tax case against Hubbell. (Justin
Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT22) WASHINGON -- Oct. 21, 1998 -- CLINTON-IMPEACH, 10-21 --
White House cousel Charles Ruff and President Clinton's attorney,
David Kendall, second from left, look on as White House Special
Counsel Greg Craig speaks to reporters in Washington after meeting
with members of the House Judiciary Committee. Republican and
Democratic lawyers squared off in an often contentious first
meeting Wednesday to begin defining the contours of impeachment
hearings. (Paul Hosefros/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT21) NEW YORK -- Oct. 21, 1998 -- SUB-TERRORIST-CIRCLE-B&AMP;W,
10-21 -- Behind this door and a flight up was the Alkifah Refugee
Center, photographed in 1993. Officials say terrorists met at the
center, now defunct. (Dith Pran/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT20) BURBANK, Calif. -- Oct. 21, 1998 --
VOICEOVERS-AD-COLUMN, 10-21 -- Carlos Alazraqui at work as the
voice of the Taco Bell chihuahua in the Nickelodeon animation
studios in Burbank. Though a handful of star voices have always
earned big money, both the amount of money and the number of actors
chasing it have exploded in the last five to 10 years. ``It's
stupid money,'' says Alazraqui, 36, of the lucrative pay scale.
(Kim Kulish/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 21, 1998 -- MICROSOFT-ANTITRUST,
10-21 -- Netscape President Jim Barksdale enters the U.S. District
Court in Washington on the third day of the government's antitrust
lawsuit against Microsoft. Throughout the morning and afternoon
sessions Wednesday, John Warden, Microsoft's lead lawyer,
frequently tried to goad Barksdale to concede key points in
Microsoft's defense. (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) MONTGOMERY, Ala. -- Oct. 21, 1998 -- ALABAMA-GOVERNOR,
10-21 -- Alabama Gov. Fob James Jr., celebrates a runoff victory
July 1 in Montgomery. As the clock ticks down in the pugnacious
Republican's campaign for re-election, most polls show him trailing
Lt. Gov. Don Siegelman. ``I'd be real surprised if he can pull this
one out,'' says one prominent Republican strategist in Alabama,
speaking on the condition of anonymity. (Alan S. Weiner/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) HARTFORD, Conn. -- Oct. 21, 1998 -- SMART-GUNS, 10-21 --
This 9-millimeter semiautomatic pistol from the Colt's
Manufacturing Co. looks like many other guns of its type. But pull
the trigger, and nothing happens. Only when a shooter puts on a
special wristband containing a tiny radio transmitter does a
squeeze of the trigger fire the weapon. The gun was shown at the
company's factory in Hartford. (George Ruhe/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- Oct. 21, 1998 --
SAN-FRANCISCO-BALLET-REVIEW, 10-21 -- From left, Kristin Long,
Parrish Maynard and Katita Waldo in ``The Vertiginous Thrill of
Exactitude.'' After William Forsythe's astonishing new ballet shot
out with cannonball force at the start of the Tuesday evening
program, one wondered how the San Francisco Ballet could go on to
match the fabulous dancing in this ballet or even the Forsythian
oddity of its title. (Sara Krulwich/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. -- Oct. 21, 1998 --
VIOLIN-MAKER-2-COX, 10-12 -- This violin is owned by Lucius
Passavanti. Parts of the instrument were first made in 1928 for
Passavanti's father, Gerado. When Gerado died, the pieces of his
partially completed violin went into a box for 68 years. The
instrument was completed by Zoltan Toth, a violin maker from Port
St. Lucie, earlier this year. (Bill Ingram/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) PORT ST. LUCIE, Fla. -- Oct. 21, 1998 --
VIOLIN-MAKER-1-COX, 10-12 -- Violin maker Zoltan Toth, 78, with a
violin he made for Lucius Passavanti. Toth, a celist by trade, has
been making violins since he was 17. (Bill Ingram/Cox News Service
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) WASHINGTON -- Oct. 21, 1998 -- CONGRESS-SPEND, 10-21 --
President Clinton signing the 1999 Budget on Wednesday in the Oval
Office. Although the Senate approved the budget bill in the
morning, some senators who voted against it are complaining about
the process and the pork. In signing, the president uses a pen for
each letter. The pens are later handed out as gifts. (Stephen
Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) MISSION VIEJO, Calif. -- Oct. 21, 1998 --
CIR-HIRING-CHECKS, 10-21 -- Katrina Haines, 27, with her dog,
Bogie, at a park in Mission Viejo. When Ms. Haines applied for a
job, a background check turned up arrests - but for someone with
the same name, not her. ``It was so ridiculous, it was laughable,''
she says. ``But it was no joke.'' (Davis Barber/New York Times
Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) BEAUFORT, S.C. -- Oct. 21, 1998 -- CIR-SCHOOL-COMPUTERS,
10-21 -- Melissa McFeely, a sixth-grade teacher at the Robert
Smalls Middle School in Beaufort, helps students using a laptop. A
school program allows parents to lease a laptop for their kids for
$15 a month if the family is unable to afford one. (Wade Spees/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) LOS ANGELES -- Oct. 21, 1998 -- CIR-DIVORCE-KIDS, 10-21
-- Maralyn Facey, creator of Kidmate, talks to her daughter Claire
Elowitt, left, as her other daughter, Stephanie Demetriou, looks on
in the background at their home in Los Angeles. Kidmate might be
described as the Turbotax of child custody and visitation battles.
Priced at $450, it is designed to simplify an unpleasant chore.
(Kim Kulish/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) LOS ANGELES -- Oct. 21, 1998 -- CIR-POSTEL-INTERNET,
10-21 -- John Postel, the Internet pioneer who recently died, was a
symbol of the Old Guard who built the internet. Postel is seen in
his home in Los Angeles in June 1998. (Chris Pizzello/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) SAGAPONACK, N.Y. -- Oct. 21, 1998 --
FERGUSON-ARCHITECTURE-2, 10-21 -- Workers laying the foundation for
architect Mark Ferguson's most monumental effort, the Sagaponack
home of investor Ira Rennert, a 59,000-square-foot columned villa
now under construction. The controversial structure is probably the
largest American house to be built during the second half of this
century. (Lois Raimondo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) BRIDGEWATER, Conn. -- Oct. 21, 1998 --
FERGUSON-ARCHITECTURE-1, 10-21 -- Why shouldn't this man be
smiling? Mark Ferguson does nothing but build houses for
millionaires. ``We'd love to do something for a client with modest
means,'' he says, his voice tinged with regret. ``The problem is to
support the kind of labor, the details we specialize in, our
expertise in custom design.'' (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Oct. 21, 1998 -- SANDRA-BERNHARD-MOM-2, 10-21
-- Sandra Bernhard, actress and mother of 16-week-old Cicely, gets
comfortable with Robert Verdi, her decorator and confidant. Ms.
Bernhard's studio has the look of a seraglio for one: lots of
bedding; piles of embroidered velvet and lace-trimmed pillows in
dark, old master shades; a huge teak-framed mirror tilted against
the wall. ``Sandra has such a variety of moods,'' says Verdi. (Fred
R. Conrad/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Oct. 21, 1998 -- SANDRA-BERNHARD-MOM-1, 10-21
-- Sandra Bernhard, actress and mother of 16-week-old Cicely,
stands in her studio apartment, framed by iridescent silk-chiffon
curtains. ``I don't get caught up in the cliches of being a
mother,'' snaps Ms. Bernhard, in bare feet, a B-movie A-line skirt
and not an ounce of baby fat. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) UNDATED -- Oct. 21, 1998 -- HOME-IMPROVEMENT-B&AMP;W, 10-21
-- When an overhead garage door fails to operate properly, the
problem can usually be traced to one of these causes: the mounting
screws that hold the brackets or tracks have worked loose so the
door sticks or binds as it moves; the rollers that guide the door
have jumped the holding track; the hinges or rollers bind because
they are dirty, corroded, or damaged; the springs have lost some of
their tension. (Edward R. Lipinski/New York Times Photo) *LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NEW YORK -- Oct. 21, 1998 -- GARDEN-AGNELLI, 10-21 --
Marella Caracciolo, her husband, Sandro Chia, and their daughter,
Constanza, in New York. Ms. Caracciolo, 33, and her aunt, Marella
Caracciolo de Castagneto Agnelli, 71, have written the text for a
new book, ``The Agnelli Gardens at Villar Perosa,'' which is filled
with fuzzy pictures of very beautiful gardens in the Piedmont
region of Italy, virtually secret gardens that have never been
opened to the public. (Fred R. Conrad/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. -- Oct. 21, 1998 -- BREAST-REPAIR-AZR,
10-08 -- Dr. Barbara Pockaj uses a doll to demonstrate to her
patients a process of breast reconstruction surgery. Dr. Pockaj, a
surgeon at Mayo Clinic Scottsdale, is an advocate of breast
conservation procedures in reconstructive surgery. She says that
only about half of eligible women receive the more conservative
procedure. (Mona Reeder/Arizona Republic Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) HOUSTON -- Oct. 21, 1998 -- TEXAS-FLOODS, 10-21 -- Dale
Sheen stands in his flooded kitchen Wednesday in Houston. Flooding
across central and southern Texas has worsened since nearly 2 feet
of rain fell over the weekend. The statewide death toll has risen
to 22. (Ben Desoto/Houston Chronicle Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
