<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 02:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0469 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-SERIES-ART-580&AMP;AD     10-22 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SERIES-ART-580&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKS SWEEP SERIES AND ASSURE LEGACY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: The following story is an added starter on The New York
Times front page) (ART ADV: Ten photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ The New York Yankees have been a team greater than
the sum of its parts all year, and how fitting that on the night
they completed a sweep of San Diego in the World Series and secured
their own corridor in history, a pitcher who struggled in recent
weeks drove them over the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Pettitte, dropped to the back of the Yankees' rotation for
the World Series, applied the final stroke to their mosaic
Wednesday night, pitching seven and one-third shutout innings and
outdueling Kevin Brown in a 3-0 victory over the Padres in Game 4.
Pettitte, throwing sinking fastballs, generated 15 groundball outs,
rewarding the faith Manager Joe Torre demonstrated in him in the
final month of the season.
</P>
<P>
   In completing their first World Series sweep since 1950, the
Yankees won their 24th championship and their second in three
seasons. They finished the year with 125 victories and 50 losses in
the regular season and post-season combined, shattering the
previous record of 118. Their winning percentage of .714 is the
third best in history for World Series winners, behind the 1927
Yankees (.722) and the 1909 Pittsburgh Pirates (.717).
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees will be honored with a parade that will begin at
11:30 a.m. Friday in Battery Park and extend up Broadway to City
Hall.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees took a 1-0 lead in the sixth inning on Bernie
Williams' groundout, then added two runs in the eighth inning
against Brown on two walks and two hits, including a run-scoring
single by Scott Brosius, who was named most valuable player of the
Series. When the top of the eighth inning was over with the Yankees
leading by 3-0, Brown walked off the field and sarcastically tipped
his cap to an umpire, upset over an earlier call and defiant to the
end.
</P>
<P>
   In the Padres' eighth, Pettitte walked Quilvio Veras and allowed
a single to Tony Gwynn with one out, and the crowd of 65,427 _ the
largest ever to see a baseball game in this city _ was screaming
for a comeback. Right-hander Jeff Nelson relieved Pettitte and
struck out the right-handed-hitting Greg Vaughn, but when Nelson
fell behind switch-hitter Ken Caminiti, two balls and no strikes,
Torre called for his closer, Mariano Rivera.
</P>
<P>
   Caminiti lined a single to right field and Paul O'Neill fired
the ball into second base, conceding the run. But Tim Flannery, the
San Diego coach, had stopped Veras at third, and so the bases were
loaded.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Leyritz, the former Yankee with a taste for cowboy boots and
a penchant for post-season home runs, ambled to the plate, the
potential lead run. But Leyritz lined out to Williams in center
field, an out that effectively finished the Padres and Brown and
guaranteed the Yankees' their legacy.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball glory engulfed the Yankees after Mark Sweeney grounded
to third base with two out in the ninth and Brosius threw to first
base for the final out, then threw his hands into the air. Rivera
dropped to his knees near the mound, and the other Yankees piled on
him.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankee catchers, Joe Girardi and Jorge Posada, jumped and
high-fived each other, and they all hugged. Chuck Knoblauch, the
smallest Yankee, was lifted off his feet over and over.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres' relievers walked off the field as the Yankees
celebrated, and Rivera turned and hugged Trevor Hoffman, San
Diego's closer, just before the Yankees retreated to their
clubhouse to sray each other with Champagne _ the good stuff, Dom
Perignon, as promised by their owner, George Steinbrenner.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
