<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 02:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0471 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-SERIES-ART-2NDTAK     10-22 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SERIES-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 SAN DIEGO: George Steinbrenner. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Brown was fighting a sinus infection and the Yankees in Game 1
last Saturday, and eventually both wore on him. The Yankee hitters
patiently waited for him to throw strikes, and Brown threw 64
pitches in the first 3 innings. After the fifth inning, he was bent
over in the runway to the clubhouse, feeling horrible, warning the
coaching staff that he might need relief in the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Brown made it to the seventh and fell apart, and the Yankees
scored seven runs in the inning. Over the last few days, Brown was
rarely seen on the field, remaining in the clubhouse and receiving
treatment. He went to the mound Wednesday night apparently feeling
much better, stronger, more capable of coping with the Yankee
hitters.
</P>
<P>
   Throwing a variety of fastballs _ sinkers, cutters, four-seamers
_ that ranged from 88 to 96 mph, Brown dominated the Yankees early,
needing only 45 pitches to get through the first four innings. When
waiting for a sign from catcher Carlos Hernandez, Brown would stand
with his legs slightly apart, mouth turned down, arms hanging, a
gunfighter's stance, a pitcher with a gunfighter's mentality.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte was far less overpowering, but no less effective, and
he donned his own peculiar stare _ cap curled low as if to hide his
eyes, mouth turned down, shoulders square. Right away, Pettitte
learned that the baseball gods had been kind to him: To succeed, he
needs a home-plate umpire who will call strikes on fastballs low
and away from right-handed batters. Durwood Merrill, the umpire in
Game 2 of the American League division series, had an extremely
wide strike zone and Pettitte thrived against Texas, allowing one
run in seven innings. When Pettitte pitched Game 3 of the AL
Championship Series, John Shulock interpreted the strike zone
strictly, giving pitchers almost nothing off the outside corner.
Cleveland pounded Pettitte for four home runs in four and
two-thirds innings.
</P>
<P>
   Pitching to Veras in the Padres' first Wednesday night, Pettitte
threw a sinking fastball low and away. Strike 1, said the plate
umpire, Dana DeMuth, and Pettitte had the kind of target he could
throw to time and again. He got 10 ground-ball outs in the first
five innings.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte did flirt with trouble in the second inning, walking
Leyritz with one out. Ruben Rivera hit a chopper through the middle
that glanced off Pettitte's glove and away from shortstop Derek
Jeter. Leyritz stopped at second.
</P>
<P>
   Using his curveball, Pettitte struck out Hernandez, but with
Brown on deck, Pettitte pitched around the No. 8 hitter Chris
Gomez, loading the bases. Brown is a good hitter, and yet he tried
to drop a bunt, pushing the ball about 10 feet in front of home
plate. Girardi scrambled from behind the plate and threw to first
for the third out.
</P>
<P>
   Brown and Pettitte dueled through the fourth _ when Jeter got
the Yankees' first hit _ and through the fifth _ when the Yankees
had runners on second and third and one out and could not score
because Girardi grounded back to Brown, the runners holding, and
Pettitte struck out.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees broke through in the sixth. With one out, Jeter
hit a high bouncer toward shortstop and, running hard all the way,
as he always does, easily beat the throw from Gomez. Then O'Neill,
his World Series batting average hovering barely above .100, turned
on a low fastball and pulled it into the right-field corner, the
ball skidding on the hard outfield surface and reaching the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter raced around second, turned at third and stopped, while
O'Neill rambled into second base. With one out, the Padres infield
played in, an attempt to prevent Jeter from scoring the game's
first run.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who acknowledged before the game that this might be
his last one with the Yankees, swung fully and bounced a chopper
off the plate, the ball caroming high toward the pitcher's mound.
Moving on contact, Jeter broke from third. Brown waited for the
chopper to come down, then leaped and reached with his bare right
hand to grab the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Brown glanced homeward, but Jeter was already knocking Hernandez
off his feet with a slide, and Brown had to settle for an out,
throwing to first. The Yankees scored 965 runs in the regular
season, another 59 in their first 10 games of the post-season, but
it was this particular run that put them ahead in the game they
were playing for the championship they had been seeking since
reporting to spring training in February.
</P>
<P>
   Brown pitched out of further trouble, striking out Brosius to
end the inning. Now it was a matter of whether Pettitte and his
support could hold the lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
