<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 02:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0474 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-SERIES-CHASS-COLU     10-22 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SERIES-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERIES VICTORY CAPS OFF YANKEES' STUNNING SEASON
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ On the night the Yankees won the World Series with a
four-game sweep of the San Diego Padres, the outfielders for both
teams could almost have taken the night off. That was the kind of
game Andy Pettitte and Kevin Brown pitched.
</P>
<P>
   With both pitching brilliantly and allowing few balls to travel
beyond the infield, the Yankees won, 3-0, scoring their first run
on _ what else _ an infield out. And Derek Jeter, who scored the
run, reached base on _ of course _ an infield hit. Not to mention
that when the Padres threatened to tie the score in the seventh
inning, the key play that foiled their attempt was an infield
bouncer that Pettitte snared.
</P>
<P>
   So the Yankees ended their improbably great year as they played
most of it, beating teams with good pitching and airtight defense.
The kind of hitting they produced in winning 114 games during the
regular season, the hitting that helped produce a remarkable run
differential of 309, did not emerge last night.
</P>
<P>
   But Pettitte, who had a statistically successful but
artistically shaky season, showed that one was the only
differential he needed in sparking the Yankees to victory No. 125.
His performance was reminiscent of the 1-0 victory he pitched
against Atlanta in Game 5 of the 1996 World Series.
</P>
<P>
   But this game was unusual for its follow-the-bouncing ball
pattern. To be sure, some balls reached the outfield. The two runs
the Yankees scored in the eighth inning that iced the game and the
Series came on such balls, though the run-scoring single by Scott
Brosius barely looped over the infield and Paul O'Neill helped load
the bases with an infield single.
</P>
<P>
   When Chris Gomez hit a fly ball to O'Neill in right field for
the final out in the seventh inning, it was only the second out the
Yankees had recorded in the outfield, the first since Greg Vaughn's
fly ball to Ricky Ledee in left field that ended the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   In between, Pettitte got 15 outs in the infield, four on balls
hit back to him, and he struck out four. Brown, in his eight
innings of pitching, also fielded four grounders for outs, induced
nine other infield outs, struck out eight and permitted the Yankees
only three outfield outs.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth inning, the Yankees batted baseballs to the
outfield twice. Tino Martinez led off by lining a single through
the infield to left field, and after Brosius took a third strike,
Ledee lined a double to right field. Suddenly the Yankees had their
first scoring chance of the game.
</P>
<P>
   But Joe Girardi rapped a one-bouncer back at Brown, who checked
Martinez at third before turning and throwing out Girardi at first.
He then struck out Pettitte, ending the threat. The Yankees,
however, would not be deterred.
</P>
<P>
   With one out in the sixth, they resumed their infield attack.
Jeter hit a slow bouncer toward short and just beat the throw from
Gomez for a single. O'Neill then lashed a double to right, and
Jeter scooted to third.
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams was the next batter, and he hit a high bouncer
to the mound. Brown, who had fielded three previous bouncers and
turned them into outs, reached up for the ball and grabbed it with
his bare hand. He looked home but saw he had no play there, so he
threw to first base to get Williams, though he got him on a
questionable call by Umpire Tim Tschida.
</P>
<P>
   Jeter, who had broken from third as soon as Williams had swung,
scored the first run of the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres had taken their shot at scoring with infield help in
the second inning. After Ken Caminiti grounded out, Jim Leyritz
walked and Ruben Rivera rapped a high bouncer back at the mound.
Pettitte jumped for the ball and got his glove on it, but he
couldn't hold it and the hit put Padres at first and second.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte struck out Carlos Hernandez for the second out, but he
pitched around Gomez, walking him on four pitches and loading the
bases for Brown.
</P>
<P>
   The pitcher, who batted .207 during the season, decided to keep
the ball deliberately in the infield. With one strike, he bunted up
the first base line, but the ball didn't travel far and Girardi
pounced on the ball and easily threw him out.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth inning Gomez hit a bouncer back at Pettitte that
struck him on his left leg, but he quickly grabbed the rebound and
threw out Gomez.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Gwynn began the next inning with a roller toward first.
Martinez fielded the ball and dived for Gwynn, but the crafty
veteran slid and hooked the base with his left foot. The single did
not help. Two ensuing grounders produced a forceout and a double
play.
</P>
<P>
   It was in the seventh that the Padres staged their most serious
threat since the second.
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz began the inning appropriately enough by grounding out
to first on a close play. But then Rivera hit a double to right.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte then reverted to the pattern that had worked, inducing
Hernandez to hit a bouncer back to him. He fielded the ball and
turned to see where Rivera was, and when he saw the runner far
enough off second, he threw there, and Rivera was out in the
ensuing rundown.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez batted next and actually hit the ball to the outfield, but
O'Neill caught it for the third out, and the Yankees went to bat
and scored two more runs to clinch the final victory of their
glorious season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
