<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-MANAGER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS TO OFFER DAVEY JOHNSON MANAGER POST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY MATT MCHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO -- The Los Angeles Dodgers will offer Davey Johnson
the job as their new manager, team and baseball sources said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who won the 1986 World Series title with the New York
Mets and division championships in Cincinnati and Baltimore during
the past four years, becomes just the fifth manager during the
Dodgers' 40 years in Los Angeles, but the third in less than five
months.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, 53, was selected over Kevin Kennedy, the product of
Woodland Hills, Calif.'s Taft High School who has managed the Texas
Rangers and Boston Red Sox and now is working as a commentator for
ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   Well-known for turning ballclubs around quickly, Johnson
inherits a team that finished 83-79 in 1998 but whose
underachieving led to the trading of franchise player Mike Piazza
and the firings of manager Bill Russell and General Manager Fred
Claire.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson will be offered the job today, less than 24 hours after
the New York Yankees closed out the 1998 World Series with a 3-0
victory over the San Diego Padres.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, who recently has lobbied for the post, is scheduled to
fly to Los Angeles today and will be introduced Friday during a
news conference at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Dodgers General Manager Kevin Malone refused to comment
Wednesday on Johnson's hiring as he was leaving Qualcomm Stadium.
``We will talk to (the team's ownership) in the morning, and I
think we can move quickly from there,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson did not return phone calls to his home in Orlando, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Major League Baseball rules prohibiting any major
announcements during the World Series, Malone used the past several
days to confer with club President Bob Graziano and representatives
from the new owners at Fox.
</P>
<P>
   Graziano attended Tuesday's Game 3 in San Diego and was
scheduled to return to Los Angeles before Game 4. But with the
decision on Johnson pending, Graziano stayed and watched the game
with Malone, new farm-club director Bill Geivett and Malone
assistant Ed Creech.
</P>
<P>
   Since Johnson interviewed with the Dodgers on Saturday in New
York, Malone has been in regular contact with Fox executives Peter
Chernin and Chase Carey.
</P>
<P>
   Malone had been turned down by Felipe Alou, who decided to stay
with the Montreal Expos. Amid speculation that Malone was angling
for managers tied to other teams, San Francisco's Dusty Baker and
Minnesota's Tom Kelly said they did not want to manage the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Kennedy, who returned home to the Los Angeles suburb of Tarzana
on Wednesday night, said he had not heard from the Dodgers. He was
a minor-league field coordinator in 1994 when Malone was the Expos'
general manager.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was the manager in Baltimore during the 1996 and '97
seasons and twice led the Orioles to the American League
Championship Series.
</P>
<P>
   Malone called Johnson a maverick who brings out the best in
teams but often runs afoul of upper management.
</P>
<P>
   He clashed with the Cincinnati Reds' fiery owner, Marge Schott,
and was let go after the Reds went 85-59 in 1995 and defeated the
Dodgers in the National League division series.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson quickly was hired by the Orioles and won 88 games in
1996 and 98 in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   He battled with Bobby Bonilla -- now with the Dodgers -- over
Bonilla's use as a designated hitter.
</P>
<P>
   But Johnson's biggest problems were with outspoken owner Peter
Angelos, who overruled several trades Johnson had encouraged.
</P>
<P>
   Malone was the assistant general manager in Baltimore during
Johnson's tenure with the Orioles.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was out of baseball this season. In 10 years as a
major-league manager, he has a .575 winning percentage, tops among
active managers.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-98 0251EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
