<HEADER>
A0504 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-     10-22 0822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BLINEBURY-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FranBlinebury
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1998, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
SAN DIEGO _ The sun sets in the west.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   The waves come to the shore.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Congress does nothing.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   There are some things you can always count on.
</P>
<P>
   They weren't the noisiest team. Just the team that made the
loudest bang.
</P>
<P>
   When the Padres' Mark Sweeney hit the last ground ball to third
base and Tino Martinez gathered in the final out of a 3-0 win that
wrapped up a sweep of the World Series, it only confirmed what the
baseball world has known since, oh, about last April.
</P>
<P>
   They weren't the most flamboyant team. Just the best team.
</P>
<P>
   The headlines say these are not the Yankees of Ruth or Gehrig or
DiMaggio or Mantle or all the rest. But the record books will say
they are better.
</P>
<P>
   125-50.
</P>
<P>
   That is not overcoming all obstacles. It is smashing them,
crushing them, annihilating them, reducing them to ashes.
</P>
<P>
   Truth be told, these poor Padres never had a chance. Not against
this pin-striped funnel cloud that left everything in its path
looking like the remnants of a trailer park.
</P>
<P>
   They could beat you with their bats, their gloves, their arms,
their heads and their hearts.
</P>
<P>
   ``To have the kind of record we had right from the very start
and to have a team that never took a day off, that is incredible,''
said manager Joe Torre.
</P>
<P>
   What is amazing is that these 1998 Yankees did it in a more
convincing style than any of their glamorous predecessors _ and all
the while managed to stay as individually anonymous as the grounds
crew.
</P>
<P>
   Think about the Yankees and their incredible heritage. From the
Babe to the Mick, from the Iron Horse Gehrig to the Yankee Clipper
DiMaggio to Mr. October Jackson, they are the most storied
franchise in American sports. And yet along comes a collection of
talent where only shortstop Derek Jeter can be legitimately rated
as a possible future Hall of Famer. And this team moved to the top
of the heap.
</P>
<P>
   The MVP of the World Series, Scott Brosius, was the perfect
representative. One year after he batted .203 in the lonely
baseball outpost of Oakland, he owned these four games _ hitting
.471 with two home runs and six RBIs _ and the biggest city in the
land.
</P>
<P>
   In a season when baseball celebrated a return to the nation's
consciousness with the great home-run chase of Mark McGwire and
Sammy Sosa, it was a bit ironic that it was this amorphous Yankee
blob that took it all. Big Mac and Slammin' Sammy indeed made the
summer memorable. But it was this cohesive, deadly effective group
that made October all its own.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees were the team that played with the most heart from
the start of the season, so it was fitting that the pitcher who
took them the last step of their journey was Deer Park's Andy
Pettitte, who had that most vital organ on his mind.
</P>
<P>
   It was just six days earlier when Pettitte's father, Tommy,
underwent double-bypass heart surgery back in Houston. Leading up
to this Game 4 start, there had been so much talk and so much
speculation about how much focus the younger Pettitte could put
into this game.
</P>
<P>
   So all Pettitte did was to pitch 7 shutout innings and limit the
Padres to five hits. They might as well have been in shackles for
the way Pettitte shut them down.
</P>
<P>
   They scored the only run they really needed in the sixth on an
infield single by Jeter, a double by Paul O'Neill and aBernie
Williams chopper back to the mound that didn't come down in time
for San Diego ace Kevin Brown to make a play at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Do the best teams just happen to be the luckiest? Or do they
always make their own luck?
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees treat each game like it's a piata. They keep hitting
it and hitting it, smacking it and banging it, figuring that it
will eventually bust open and the prizes will fall at their feet.
</P>
<P>
   They have more ways to beat you than a mongrel has fleas.
</P>
<P>
   It was a season that seemed fated, preordained, with these
Yankees being pushed on from so many different directions. They
were trying to finish off the grand run for their teammate Darryl
Strawberry, who was snatched from their midst with colon cancer at
the start of the AL playoffs. They were trying to win for Joltin'
Joe DiMaggio himself, who watched from a hospital bed in Florida,
recovering from pneumonia.
</P>
<P>
   It was a year to be remembered after setting a record with a
114-48 mark in the regular season. And yet they faced a postseason
where all they could do was win it all or be perceived as failures.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more you win, the more everybody expects you to win,''
Torre said. ``And the thing that concerned me most was not winning
the World Series and having someone look down their nose at what we
accomplished. I think that's where the pressure came from.''
</P>
<P>
   So they rose to meet it.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Something to count on.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
