<HEADER>
A0507 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-YANKS     10-22 1044
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-WORLDSERIES-YANKSPADRES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES ARE WORLD-BEATERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; SAN DIEGO _ Hold a prism to this most splendid of baseball
summers, and through the brilliant swatches of blue (Sammy Sosa)
and red (Mark McGwire) and even orange (Tony Gwynn), all the
refracted colors ultimately fade to a thin black pinstripe.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Yankees, 50 years after the death of Babe Ruth, 25
years after the arrival of George Steinbrenner, and two years since
their last World Series title, last night concluded what history
may judge the finest of all seasons by beating the San Diego
Padres, 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   What is undisputed is this: No team has ever won more games than
the Yankees of Brooklyn-born manager Joe Torre and fifth-string
left fielder Ricky Ledee, batting champion Bernie Williams and
reborn Scott Brosius, the supremely intense Paul O'Neill and the
cancer-stricken Darryl Strawberry, the rebellious David Wells and
the brave Orlando Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to take a back seat to no one in my lifetime,'' Torre
said. ``I've never had a more courageous group, a more determined
group.''
</P>
<P>
   With their 125th win of 1998, they became the first team to
sweep a World Series since the 1990 Cincinnati Reds, who dispatched
the Oakland A's of McGwire and Jose Canseco, and the first Yankee
team to sweep since the 1950 club of aging Joe DiMaggio and rookie
Whitey Ford bounced the Whiz Kids of Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will probably be talked about forever,'' said World
Series MVP Brosius. ``You could look at it and say we probably had
the best single season of all time.''
</P>
<P>
   In the course of their four-game ouster of the Padres, whose
winter will be haunted by the two three-run leads they could not
hold, the Yankees not only won their 24th World Series, they also
forced the abdication of the King, Jim Leyritz.
</P>
<P>
   The former Red Sox DH, who in a previous incarnation hit two
postseason home runs for the Yankees that became the stuff of myth,
then hit four more for the Padres this fall, went 0 for 10 in this
Series, lining out with the bases loaded to end the eighth last
night.
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz also made a dubious defensive decision at first base
that jump-started the Yankees' two-run rally in the top of the
eighth. With Jeter aboard first on a walk and the Yankees ahead,
1-0, Leyritz fielded O'Neill's high chopper. But instead of
flipping to the pitcher, Kevin Brown, who was at the bag, Leyritz
elected to make the play himself, sliding into the bag. First base
umpire Tim Tschida, making one final controversial decision in a
postseason nearly overshadowed by judgment calls, ruled O'Neill
safe, enraging Brown.
</P>
<P>
   TV replays appeared to support Tschida.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I was too close (to Brown) to throw it,'' Leyritz
said. ``But after watching the replays, I guess I could have.''
</P>
<P>
   An infield out advanced the runners, and Brown intentionally
walked Tino Martinez, loading the bases. Brosius, the World Series
MVP who won Game 3 with a three-run home run, then made it 2-0 with
a flare over a drawn-in infield that didn't reach the outfield
grass on the fly.
</P>
<P>
   A third run scored on a sacrifice fly by Ledee, and a still
steaming Brown tipped his cap, a la Pedro Martinez, to Tschida as
he left the field.
</P>
<P>
   Lefthander Andy Pettitte set aside his poor outing in the
American League Championship Series by reviving memories of his 1-0
win over the Braves in the '96 World Series. Pettitte, who on the
eve of the Series had flown to Texas to be with his ailing father,
held the Padres to five hits in 7 1/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as I saw Andy's first pitch, I knew we were in great
shape,'' Torre said. ``I go back to '96 and know there's an
enormous heart there, and what's been going on in his life, to go
out there and match Kevin pitch for pitch in front of those frantic
fans, it was just appropriate to win a game like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte departed after Quilvio Veras walked and Gwynn singled
with one out in the eighth, then turned the game over to a bullpen
that was impenetrable in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   Closer Mariano Rivera, who did not give up a run in 13 1/3
postseason innings, dropped to his knees in prayerful exultation
after third baseman Brosius, putting the coda on the best year of
his life, threw out Framingham, Mass.-born Mark Sweeney on a roller
to third for the final out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the biggest moment is that third out,'' Brosius said,
``throwing the ball and knowing it's going to end the game and end
the season. There's nothing better than coming up and seeing the
players' eyes and that sense of achievement and accomplishment and
excitement. It was just a great scene.''
</P>
<P>
   Brosius, who hit a three-run home run in the clinching game of
the ALCS against the Indians, won MVP honors after batting .471 (8
for 17) in the Series, .268 higher than the .203 he hit for A's
last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I'm a litte wet right now, but it's a great feeling,''
said Brosius, bathing in champagne when only a year ago, he was
eating pizza and watching the World Series on TV.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their distress at being swept _ the Padres have lost
seven straight Series games dating back to '84, when they made
their only other appearance _ San Diego players rewarded the
largest crowd in their history (65,427) by returning to the
Qualcomm Stadium field after the game. Steve Finley threw baseballs
into the upper deck. Trevor Hoffman, to one last chorus of ``Hell's
Bells,'' tipped his cap. Manager Bruce Bochy and several players
took a microphone and thanked the fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a hell of a run,'' Bochy said. ``We weren't expected
to win our division, we weren't expected to beat Houston or
Atlanta, and I can't say enough about the hard determination our
club played with.''
</P>
<P>
   But from April to October, the Yankees forced everyone to pull
over to the side of the road. They have now won more championships
than any other team in professional sports history, one more than
hockey's Montreal Canadiens.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little young to know about those teams in the early
1900s,'' said the 24-year-old Jeter. ``But we were 125-50. Not too
many teams can say that. You can argue we're the best of all
time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-98 0252EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981022.0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 02:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0508 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-PADRES-SERIESLOSS     10-22 0752
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-PADRES-SERIESLOSS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PADRES PLAYED SECOND FIDDLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ The San Diego Padres may have pleased a few voters
with their second World Series appearance in 14 years. With a
proposal for a new stadium on the local ballot and the future of
baseball in the deep south of California hanging in the balance, it
was nice timing.
</P>
<P>
   But the rest of the National League won't like it one bit that
their representative was humbled by the New York Yankees in a
four-game sweep that in glorious hindsight was almost too easy. The
Padres were competitive in three of the games. But they learned the
hard way that the team that won an American League-record 114 games
during the regular season and went 11-2 in the postseason was far
superior to any they faced all year.
</P>
<P>
   Plain and simple, this was a mismatch. The Yankees are the best
team in baseball, maybe of all time. Twice in this series, they
beat Kevin Brown, perhaps the NL's most talented starter. They
outlasted Sterling Hitchcock, who beat Randy Johnson of Houston,
Tom Glavine of Atlanta, and John Smoltz of the Braves in the NL
playoffs. To beat the Yankees, it took more than a quality start.
And that was the best San Diego could do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Give credit to the Yankees,'' said Padres general manager
Kevin Towers. ``They've got a hell of a club. I don't know where
they have any weakness. Position by position, they have youth and
speed available. They also have experience, speed, and defense. Add
to that power, wonderful starters, and a great bullpen, a great
manager _ and more _ and you can understand why they won so many
games.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres knew the jig was up Tuesday night when they lost
their second three-run lead of the Series _ and their third
straight game. No team had ever overcome a such a deficit, and the
Padres weren't about to set a precedent. But they wanted to give
the record San Diego baseball crowd of 65,427 at Qualcomm Stadium
something to be proud about Wednesday night. With Brown on the
mound, they had a chance to prolong the series, it was thought.
</P>
<P>
   Not against this juggernaut. Brown was outdueled by Andy
Pettitte as the Yankees completed the sweep, 3-0.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are the best team we've played all year,'' said Brown.
``But it's difficult to evaluate this series because I thought we
had a better team than what showed up here. There are a combination
of reasons for that. I know one thing. These guys don't have to
hang their heads. Nobody expected us to do that. Nobody was willing
to give us credit or give us a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Leyritz, who went 0 for 10 in the series, took the blame for
a play at first in the eighth that helped break the game open for
New York.
</P>
<P>
   With a runner on first and the Yankees ahead, 1-0, Paul O'Neill
hit a high chopper that Leyritz fielded at first. But instead of
tossing to Brown, he slid for the bag himself. Despite Brown's
protests, umpire Tim Tschida ruled that O'Neill was safe, and the
Yankees went on to score twice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I could beat O'Neill to the bag,'' said Leyritz, who
began the season as the Red Sox DH. ``I didn't think I could get
the ball out of my glove in time to flip it to Kevin. After I
watched the replay, I saw that I could have. It was a judgment
thing on my part.''
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz knew what it was like in the other locker room. He was a
Yankee World Series hero in 1996, a major part of the celebration.
This year he'll celebrate, he said, but first he must tip his cap.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have 114 victories,'' he said, ``and they came along and
beat us four in a row. We have a pretty strong ball club ourselves.
Unfortunately, we didn't execute this week and they did. They have
a right to claim they are the best club in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still, it's not like they went out there and totally killed
us. We feel good about what we did, even though we didn't win a
game. We would have liked to have done better, but we have nothing
to hang our heads about.''
</P>
<P>
   Venerable Tony Gwynn, a World Series loser for the second time
in his fabled Padres career, put this in perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an awesome experience,'' he said. ``I'm sure everybody
wishes it would have turned out better. But the Yankees have a
great club. They did everything they needed to do in the series.
The pitching was great. We were banged up. But I can't take
anything away from the Yankees. They did everything they needed to
do to win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
