<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAST WORTHY OF A CURTAIN CALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  SAN DIEGO _ The 1998 major league baseball season was all
about two things. It was about history and it was about theater.
</P>
<P>
   History was everywhere, from a guy _ excuse me, two guys _ who
hit more baseballs where people couldn't catch them than anyone
else who ever played this game at the top level, to a guy who made
coast-to-coast headlines when he decided to take a day off. And
theater? We had a kid whiffing 20, a Ruth aficionado with a Ruthian
waistline throwing a perfect game _ and we weren't even out of May
yet.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, we had a team, a T-E-A-M from its manager to its
25th man, a team that started off 1-4 and then decided that, all
things considered, winning was a lot more satisfying than losing. A
lot of people know this, but few teams have ever been more
physically qualified or ferociously, and unselfishly, determined to
do something about it.
</P>
<P>
   This was a team that won an American League-record 114 games.
When trouble surfaced in the AL Championship Series, the manager
turned to a (supposed) 29-year-old refugee from Castro's Cuba, a
mysterious character with a throwback pitching style who had
arrived on these shores via a leaky raft, to straighten things out.
The TV movie looms, but until then, we can label the Orlando
Hernandez story as pure theater.
</P>
<P>
   When the man known as ``El Duque'' stopped the Cleveland Indians
in Game 4 of the ALCS, the team relaxed. It began playing baseball
as only it could. It finished off the Indians in three straight,
and Wednesday night The Best Team In Baseball made more history
while providing us with even more theater, completing a four-game
sweep of the National League champion San Diego Padres with a 3-0
victory.
</P>
<P>
   This was, believe it or not, the first Yankee World Series sweep
since 1950, when the second Casey Stengel team (and penultimate Joe
DiMaggio team) knocked off the Philadelphia Phillies' ``Whiz Kids''
in four. That's right. Mickey Mantle never participated in a
Yankees sweep. But Homer Bush has.
</P>
<P>
   In keeping with the theme of the season, the winning pitcher
Wednesday night was Andy Pettitte, by far the most suspect member
of the Yankees' sensational starting pitching rotation. The
26-year-old lefthander had been touched by personal trauma because
on the eve of the World Series, his father underwent serious heart
surgery. When the Series opened, Pettitte was more than 1,500 miles
away, in Louisiana, at his ailing father's bedside.
</P>
<P>
   But Wednesday night he was standing on that mound of dirt, 60
feet 6 inches from home plate, and he was magnificent. Andy
Pettitte was a mediocre 16-11 for a team that was 66 games over
.500 during the regular season, but on this important occasion, he
was man enough to bring his A game. He brought the same breaking
ball and the same control to the mound he had brought in a
wonderful performance against the Atlanta Braves in Game 5 of a
more competitive World Series two years ago. In 7 1/3 innings,
Pettitte limited the Padres to five hits and no runs. Scorned by
many serious Yankee fans as unreliable, he pitched better than
David Wells, better than El Duque, better than David Cone, and,
most important, better than the great Kevin Brown, his mound
opponent Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Ah, Kevin Brown. Now let's talk some theater. Our last look at
this tremendous competitor was the sight of him storming off the
mound at the conclusion of the Yankee eighth, tipping his cap in
mock salute toward first base umpire Tim Tschida, who Brown felt
had missed a pivotal bang-bang play at first during a two-run New
York flurry. Brown felt aggrieved, for sure, but when he simmers
down, he will realize that neither he nor anyone else was going to
interfere with the clear cosmic destiny of this very special Yankee
team. He had pitched well, but by the conclusion of this series, it
was obvious that whatever the Padres would do, the Yankees would do
better.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees were theatrically minded to the very end. What other
team could provide as a partial World Series hero a player who had
begun the postseason in Florida awaiting a call to arms he thought
would never come? That was the case with Ricky Ledee, who was at
that time a clear fourth on the available left-field depth chart
behind Tim Raines, Chad Curtis, and Shane Spencer, and that doesn't
even count Darryl Strawberry.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Strawberry. Did someone say ``theater''? Strawberry was
diagnosed with colon cancer during the Division Series, and when he
swapped a date in the postseason for a trip to the operating table,
that led to the call-up of Ledee, who wound up with six hits in 10
official at-bats, to go with two walks, a sacrifice fly, nine total
bases, and four runs batted in. Did someone say, ``42nd Street''?
</P>
<P>
   This was said to be the season when America rediscovered
baseball, and while the final returns are not in nationwide, we can
safely say that the city and environs of San Diego sure have fallen
in love with the game. Wednesday night's crowd of 65,427 was the
largest ever to see a game here, and when it was over, they refused
to leave. They demanded curtain calls by their fallen heroes, and
they got what they wanted, complete with rousing speeches and pleas
to come back and see us next year.
</P>
<P>
   It was a very uplifting and touching scene. Pure theater, if you
will. We know the Yankee fans would never have been so generous to
their team in defeat, but that's the mootest of all possible moot
points, because the 1998 Yankees knew the concept of ultimate
defeat only as an abstract.
</P>
<P>
   Nope, these Yankees set out to make history, and they did. Along
the way, they gave us great theater. Let's just call it the
``Broadway Diamond Melody of 1998.'' What a team. As they say on
the Great White Way, the Yankees broke every leg they could.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-98 0252EDT &QL; 
