<SLUG> BC-HKN-MIGHTYDUCKS-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS FLATTENED BY ANAHEIM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Their power play dormant and penalty trouble
abounding, the Bruins dug a hole and buried themselves in it
Wedneday night, losing to the Mighty Ducks, 3-0, at Arrowhead Pond.
</P>
<P>
   Their second straight loss dropped them under .500 for this trip
(2-3) with one game remaining. For the season, Boston is 3-3-1.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't help that the Bruins were without right wing Rob
DiMaio, who began serving a two-game suspension for elbowing
Phoenix wing Dallas Drake Monday night. DiMaio likely would've
helped stem the tide against the Ducks' stars, but in the end, what
beat the Bruins was their lack of finish and inability to put
anything past goalie Guy Hebert.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time Boston has been shut out this year, and
the Bruins have generated just one goal in the last two games.
</P>
<P>
   The first period was beyond dull, one of the Bruins' most brutal
on the trip. They looked listless, slow, and tentative while being
outshot, 15-6.
</P>
<P>
   Boston didn't pose much of an offensive threat in the opening 20
minutes. Conversely, the Paul Kariya-Steve Rucchin-Teemu Selanne
combination posed all kinds of problems for the Bruins, putting
five shots on goalie Byron Dafoe. He managed to hold off the Ducks
until less than a minute remained.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie defenseman Mike Crowley, who assisted on the first three
Anaheim goals, tying a club rookie record, blasted a shot from the
left point that Dafoe stopped. However, the goalie couldn't control
the rebound, and it bounced out in front, where Jim McKenzie
backhanded it into the net from the slot with 46.1 seconds left to
give Anaheim a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins looked better in the middle period but were sunk by
penalty troubles that led to two more Ducks goals less than a
minute apart.
</P>
<P>
   The problems began at 13:10 when Steve Heinze was whistled for
holding the stick. Just 42 seconds later, Ray Bourque joined Heinze
in the penalty box for cross-checking, giving the Ducks a two-man
advantage for 1:18. Fifty-nine seconds later, Anaheim made Boston
pay, with Kariya potting his third goal of the season on a play
that is bound to be shown on ESPN's ``SportsCenter'' over and over.
</P>
<P>
   Selanne, off to the far right of Dafoe, rifled a pass through
the crease that went past defenseman Hal Gill and hit the stick of
Kariya. The puck popped up in the air and Kariya, following its
flight, bunted it into the net near the right post at 14:51, giving
the Ducks a 2-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's situation soon worsened. With Bourque still in the box,
Ducks center Travis Green was called for closing his hand over the
puck, creating a four-on-four situation. At 15:18, just 34 seconds
before Bourque's penalty expired and they would've gone on the
power play, the Bruins turned the puck over with the Ducks charging
in for a two-on-one break. Rather than give them the odd-man rush,
Darren Van Impe hauled down Selanne, preventing the rush and
probably a goal. But the Bruins were faced with a four-on-three
situation and the Ducks cashed in at 15:42 to take a 3-0 lead.
Defenseman Fredrik Olausson fired a slapper from the top of the
right circle and the Bruins' deficit had quickly become three
goals.
</P>
<P>
   Selanne's line had eight shots in the first 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Boston had nine shots in the middle period, but the defense
accounted for five.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins put some heat on the Ducks in the third period. Their
best chance came at 10:15 when Bourque's slap shot from the point
clanged off the right post. The puck caromed behind Hebert, and
center Chris Taylor tried for a sweeping backhander on the rebound
at the right post, but the goalie was there to block it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
