<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORRE MAN OF THE HOUR _ AND YEAR _ FOR YANKEES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ In the dazzling reflection of an 11-2 postseason
record and a second championship in three years, it seems the
episode must have happened before the invention of dirt. But there
was a time this season when the New York Yankees were in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   After an 8-0 shelling by the Mariners in the opener of a
three-game April series at the Kingdome, the Yankees were 1-4. The
Bad Apple tabloids were thick with speculation about the imminent
demise of Joe Torre, who might be destined in modern Yankee history
to be the man most suited, by skill and temperament, to manage
baseball's flagship franchise.
</P>
<P>
   According to a Yankee employee here at the World Series, owner
George Steinbrenner called Torre and launched a tirade about the
poor start. An angry Torre slammed down the phone _ an act in club
culture considered professional suicide.
</P>
<P>
   Seconds later, The Boss rang back, demanding to know why he hung
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``You were yelling at me,'' Torre said calmly.
</P>
<P>
   Disarmed by Torre's quiet dignity, Steinbrenner backed down, for
perhaps the first time in his bellicose, 26-year Yankee tenure.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of his voice, Torre prefers to raise World Series
trophies.
</P>
<P>
   Which is not to say he is incapable of deploying the stick.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a meeting in Seattle,'' Torre said. ``We said, `Let's
do something about it. We're supposed to be better than this. We've
got to get angry.' And we started playing well.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing well? The next night, facing the lamentable Jim
Bullinger in his only career Mariner appearance, the angry Yankees
won 13-7, beginning a 24-3 streak. Or, to take it up through
Wednesday night's 3-0 win over the San Diego Padres in Game 4 of
the World Series, 124-46.
</P>
<P>
   Amazing as the raw number is, its achievement was more or less
expected. The Yankees were known in the preseason to be good on
paper, then proved it on grass and turf, and had virtually no
alternative but to do the postseason crush thing because it was New
York and because it was the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``The more you win, the more you expect to win,'' Torre said.
``The thing that concerned me most was not winning the World Series
and having someone look down their nose at us.''
</P>
<P>
   The only view of the Yankees this morning is from far below.
They are at a pinnacle never reached in baseball history. To a man,
the players credit Torre.
</P>
<P>
   They made it a point to do so immediately as they spilled from
the traditional postgame pigpile on the rock-hard infield of
Qualcomm Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I went out on the field,'' Torre said, a little dazed,
``every one of the players came up to me and said, `Thank you,'
before I could say it to them.
</P>
<P>
   ``That knocked me off my stilts a little.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre's reasonableness, steadiness and sincerity have been the
handles that players and coaches have grabbed hard in the
relentless tumult of baseball in the big town for the big boss with
the big tradition that has produced its 24th world champion in 35
Series appearances.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the field, in the clubhouse and the front office, he has a
hand on everything,'' said Mel Stottlemyre, Yankee pitching coach
and Yakima native. ``He managed the pressure so well, and he does
it so quietly.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I don't even know what his relationship with
Steinbrenner is. And maybe that says something in itself.''
</P>
<P>
   He had to guide players from 10 nations, stars from other
franchises, work with an immediate boss more than two decades his
junior and an ultimate superior who throws money and tantrums with
equal ferocity. Torre's ego-less, deferential manner threatened no
one and inspired all.
</P>
<P>
   As a native New Yorker and well-steeped in baseball tradition,
he knows the prestige and pressure of the position so well that he
feels no intimidation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are very high expectations when you wear a Yankee
uniform,'' he said. ``I'm not putting any other ballclub down. It's
just that when you work for George, he's a perfectionist. He always
tries to improve on perfection. When you come to New York, you
understand that getting to the World Series is what it's all
about.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, that's why there was a vacancy for Torre in the first
place. His capable predecessor, Buck Showalter, was let go after
the Mariners beat his Yankees in the dramatic 1995 Division Series,
an event that Yank pitcher David Cone this week called
``devastating ... and the reason Showalter and others lost their
jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   In exchange for his liberal applications of cash at all levels
of his organization, Steinbrenner demands championship and brooks
only the smallest setbacks. Which is why this season's magnum
triumph caused him so much emotion in the champagne chaos of the
clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner was wallowing in his glory, crying and laughing and
spraying. He created a magnificent, albeit expensive, new standard,
and knew the baseball world must leap to catch him.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is as good as any team I've ever had, and as good as any
team I've ever seen,'' he said, his jacket a stinky, sticky mess.
``There's never been anyone better.''
</P>
<P>
   For San Diego, the Series results turned out to be welcome as
snow. For baseball, hoping to follow upon a season of spectacular
individual achievements with a riveting climax, it wasn't so hot
either.
</P>
<P>
   But on a warm evening in Southern California, there was no
disappointment in being in the presence of greatness. Nor was there
any arguing with Steinbrenner.
</P>
<P>
   Only Torre gets the last word with Steinbrenner.
</P>
<P>
   Art Thiel is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-98 0252EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
