<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BB0-SERIES-PETTITTE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pettitte perseveres amid dad's heart surgery, poor league series
By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ This one was for dad.
</P>
<P>
   On a night the Yankees won their 24th world title and during an
emotional time off the field for Andy Pettitte, the lefthander
picked up the pieces and pitched the game of his life.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte, at his father's bedside last week when he had heart
bypass surgery, threw 7 1/3 shutout innings in Game 4 Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   He obviously was able to take his emotions and direct them on
the field. He had struggled in the league championship against the
Indians but really never was in any trouble on this beautiful
night.
</P>
<P>
   Just how awesome was he?
</P>
<P>
   _ He retired the side in the first, third, fourth and pitched to
only three batters in the sixth as his club turned a double play.
</P>
<P>
   _ In the second, he walked Jim Leyritz after one out, then gave
up a hit to Ruben Rivera. But Pettitte came back and struck out
Carlos Hernandez, walked Chris Gomez and got Kevin Brown on a
grounder back to the mound.
</P>
<P>
   _ In the fifth after two were out, he gave up a single to Brown
but came right back and got Quilvio Veras on a grounder back to the
mound.
</P>
<P>
   _ The biggest test came in the seventh when after one out,
Rivera doubled to right. But Pettitte got Hernandez to hit a ball
back to the mound. Pettitte grabbed it, turned towards Rivera and
caught him off second. He then retired Gomez on a flyball to end
the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Petitte did get in some trouble in the eighth when after one
out, he walked Veras and gave up a single to Tony Gwynn. Yankees
manager Joe Torre decided to go to his bullpen, calling for
righthander Jeff Nelson to face the always tough Greg Vaughn.
Nelson did his job, striking out Vaughn, but then fell behind in
the count to Ken Caminiti. On came closer Mariano Rivera with a 2-0
count on Caminiti, who hit the first pitch into right field to load
the bases. Up stepped Jim Leyritz, who hit a line drive to center
for the third out.
</P>
<P>
   So ended a very draining period for Pettitte. But it was not as
if he had not done the job before in the Series.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1996 against the Braves, he won Game 5 by the score of
1-0, going 8 1/3 innings and setting up New York to win a title in
Game 6. This time Pettitte led the final charge.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
