<HEADER>
A0514 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-SERIES-NOTES4-COX     10-22 0575
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SERIES-NOTES4-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McGwire catches foul ball in stands
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It was a good thing for baseball commissioner Bud
Selig that Mark McGwire made it back to the ballpark Wednesday
night.
</P>
<P>
   The new single-season home run king threw out the first pitch
before Game 4, throwing a perfect strike and, of course, receiving
a standing ovation. The Padres had wanted McGwire to throw out the
first pitch on Tuesday night, but the Cardinals first baseman has
been rather busy, making an appearances Monday on the David
Letterman Show.
</P>
<P>
   Also, McGwire grabbed a foul ball that went into the stands,
catching it right in front of Selig. The two were sharing the same
box and it isn't the first time this season that McGwire has saved
Selig.
</P>
<P>
   More second guessing
</P>
<P>
   Padres manager Bruce Bochy continued to get questioned about his
moves in the ninth inning in Game 3 Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   With San Diego down by one run with runners at first and third
and two outs, Bochy had his best left-handed hitting pinch hitter
(John Vander Wal) in the game as a pinch runner, leaving
weak-hitting Andy Sheets to hit. Sheets struck out against Yankees
right-hander Mariano Rivera to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, we thought the matchup with (Mark) Sweeney against
Rivera was our best matchup, so I pinch ran Vander Wal, knowing if
Sheets comes up, we are going to let Andy hit,'' Bochy said. ``He
took two good swings, and so really the non-moves were working out,
we had first and third, and a chance to tie the game. I could have
hit Greg Myers, but we felt like the best chance was to let Andy
hit. And it didn't
</P>
<P>
   work out.''
</P>
<P>
   Help from Zim
</P>
<P>
   While his team is certainly the most talented in baseball,
Yankees manager Joe Torre has received a lot of help from bench
coach Don Zimmer. Many times during a game, Torre will turn to
Zimmer for advice. ``I've always respected Don,'' Torre said. ``He
had coached here a couple of different times, and I thought he
would be a guy I could trust to tell me the truth, be there for me,
and help me in a lot of ways. And I'm glad I made that decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Around the horn
</P>
<P>
   A Yankees victory Wednesday would give New York it's 61st
championship in professional baseball, football, basketball and
hockey since 1901. The city has won 31 in baseball. ... It also
would be the Yankees' 24th title, which would be an all-time record
by sports franchises. Both the Yankees and the NHL Montreal
Canadiens have 23 titles. ...Going into Wednesday's game, the
Yankees had won their last five Series games on the road, their
last loss coming in Game 5 of the 1981 Fall Classic against the
Dodgers. ... Rivera has pitched 12 scoreless innings in nine games
in the postseason, the most since Ken Dayley of St. Louis worked
the same number in 1985. ... The two home runs Scott Brosius
produced in Game 3 was the 41st multi-homer game in Series history
and first by a Yankee since Reggie Jackson went deep three times in
Game 6 in 1977. It was just the third time a third baseman had a
multi-homer game, the others being Cincinnati's Chris Sabo (1990)
and Bob Elliot (1948) of the Boston Braves. ...The Yankees had
entered the Series hitting .229 in the postseason with 36 runs
scored in nine games but entered Game 4 hitting .324 with 23 runs
in three games.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
