<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Yankee clincher: New York wins 3-0 to sweep World Series
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Perhaps it was fitting that Big Mac was only a few
feet away watching.
</P>
<P>
   For in a season where Mark McGwire thrilled the world, the New
York Yankees won it all, completing a four-game World Series sweep
of the Padres with a crisp 3-0 victory Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees finish the season with an incredible 125-50 record,
their 24th world title and second in three years, a team that will
go down as one of baseball's greatest.
</P>
<P>
   And they did it with an awesome display of teamwork, outscoring
the Padres 26-13 and really never feeling threatened by a club that
was obviously overmatched.
</P>
<P>
   Along with McGwire, who was sitting in the commissioner's box,
65,427 fans, the largest crowd ever to watch a baseball game in San
Diego, still held out hope for their Padres. But their team was
simply outpitched this night. While Kevin Brown was good, Yankees
lefthander Andy Pettitte was better, almost unhittable.
</P>
<P>
   Brown and Pettitte battled for five innings without anyone
scoring until the sixth, when the Yankees got a run, in one of
their many ways to score, on an infield grounder. Pettitte kept
holding on, picking up two more runs of support in the eighth, and
then came the bullpen, setting up one final chance for the Padres
to tie it.
</P>
<P>
   With the bases loaded and two outs in the eighth, San Diego's
Jim Leyritz stepped up to the plate against Yankees closer Mariano
Rivera. It was two years ago that Leyritz, wearing Yankee
pinstripes, turned the Series around against the Braves with a
three-run shot off Mark Wohlers. Could he turn around a World
Series again, this time against his former team?
</P>
<P>
   No, not this time as Leyritz drove a ball into center field
where Bernie Williams was waiting for it. San Diego's unbelievable
season had all but ended. Rivera retired the Padres in the ninth
and it was over.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees third baseman Scott Brosius, who had two homers and six
RBIs in the Series, was named the MVP.
</P>
<P>
   But on this night, it was not one man, it was teamwork that
produced the Yankees runs. In the sixth, Derek Jeter singled with
one out and Paul O'Neill followed with a double. Williams then hit
a ball down into the dirt. It bounced high and into the glove of
Brown, who looked home, but didn't make the throw. Bad decision as
the Yankees led. In the eighth, Jeter opened the inning by walking
and O'Neill singled. Jeter would eventually come home on a Brosius
single, O'Neill crossing on a sacrifice fly by Ricky Ledee.
</P>
<P>
   Afterwards, the Yankees celebrated, hugging and crying at the
pitchers mound. A parade awaits in New York. They indeed are great
champions.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
