<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SERIES-TVREVIEW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Game 4's telecast restrained
 &HT;    By Prentis Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When there's pitching duel like the one between the
Yankees' Andy Pettitte and the Padres' Kevin Brown, Fox's job
Wednesday night was not to get in the way of the drama.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, Game 4 became a case where less was more, and producer
John Filippelli appeared to recognize that. The telecast seemed to
have less than the usual amounts of spray charts, graphics and
split screens.
</P>
<P>
   Announcers Joe Buck, Tim McCarver and Bob Brenly, who have done
a solid job throughout the series of not talking too much, kept the
idle chatter to a minimum and gave one of their most concise
performances.
</P>
<P>
   However, when a situation called for more, like Paul O'Neill
barely beating Jim Leyritz to first for an infield single that set
up the Yankees' two-run eighth, Fox had excellent replay angles
that indicated the safe call was correct.
</P>
<P>
   But the better example of recognizing when more was better came
after the Yankees went ahead 3-0. Aggressive camera work that
switched from one dugout to the other conveyed the emotions of the
moment as Padres pitching coach Dave Stewart was captured shouting
in frustation, while the Yankees were seen pumping each other up,
obviously sensing victory was near.
</P>
<P>
   The camera work wasn't quite as active in the bottom of the
eighth when the Padres loaded the bases, and didn't convey the
tension as well.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, Fox did a fine job making the audience aware of Mark
McGwire's presence. Like it did with Sammy Sosa in New York, he was
interviewed from the stands in the first inning. But Fox got lucky
in the fourth when McGwire made a bare-handed catch of a bouncing
foul ball, which naturally warranted a replay.
</P>
<P>
   Fox also came up with its one beauty shot of the Series by
capturing the sun dipping beneath the horizon at the end of the
third inning.
</P>
<P>
   Said Buck: ``The sun is setting on San Diego. The Padres hope
it's not on them.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
