<HEADLINE>
ZEILE SEEKS EXTENSION OR MAY DEMAND TRADE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Texas Rangers third baseman Todd Zeile appears willing to
exercise his right to demand a trade should the organization not be
prepared to discuss a contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   Zeile, scheduled to earn $3.2 million for the 1999 season, can
exercise that right as a player traded while signed to a multiyear
contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the club is unwilling to commit to him beyond the '99
season, then that means he could be traded again by July,'' said
Seth Levinson, who represents Zeile.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers signed Zeile to a three-year contract Dec. 8, 1996,
and traded him to the Marlins on May 16, 1998. The Rangers acquired
Zeile in the July 31 trade that sent two minor-league players _
right-hander Daniel DeYoung and third baseman Jose Santo _ to the
Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   Zeile must exercise his right to demand a trade within a span of
15 days after the conclusion of the World Series, although Levinson
plans to discuss a contract extension with Rangers general manager
Doug Melvin before that time.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers would be forced to trade Zeile by March 15 should
the demand arise or allow the 33-year-old infielder to become a
free agent. That demand, though, would not come without risks for
Zeile.
</P>
<P>
   The veteran third baseman would become a free agent and forfeit
his guaranteed contract for 1999 should the Rangers be unable to
complete a trade, or Zeile could be traded to an undesirable
situation. Rangers win awards Rangers right fielder Juan Gonzalez
and catcher Ivan Rodriguez yesterday captured their fifth American
League Silver Slugger Awards.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez led American League players in runs batted in (157) and
doubles (50) and ranked second in slugging percentage (.630) and
extra-base hits (97), fourth in home runs (45) and total bases
(382), sixth in base hits (193) and 10th in batting average (.318).
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez, who drove in 91 runs with 40 doubles and 21 home
runs, ranked eighth in batting average (.321) and ninth in base
hits (186).
</P>
<P>
   League managers and coaches also chose Orioles first baseman
Rafael Palmeiro, Tigers second baseman Damion Easley, Royals third
baseman Dean Palmer, Mariners shortstop Alex Rodriguez and center
fielder Ken Griffey Jr., White Sox left fielder Albert Belle and
Blue Jays designated hitter Jose Canseco for the award at their
positions. Clayton pursued Rangers general manager Doug Melvin said
he has begun negotiations with Arn Tellem, shortstop Royce
Clayton's agent. Clayton can be a free agent after the World Series
and the Rangers have made re-signing him a top priority.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin said the two sides, ``have talked about numbers,'' but
Tellem is also a basketball agent who is caught up in that sport's
labor negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin said he has also begun talks with Will Clark's attorney
about a possible new contract. Arnsberg promoted The Rangers
promoted Brad Arnsberg, who coached at Double-A Tulsa last season,
to pitching coach at Triple-A Oklahoma.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Tunnell, who coached at Charlotte last season, will replace
Arnsberg at Tulsa.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers also announced that Oklahoma manager Greg Biagini
and Tulsa manager Bobby Jones will return next season.
</P>
</TEXT>
