<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY DEAL IMMINENT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT FRENCH  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ The Los Angeles Galaxy, one of Major League
Soccer's most successful clubs on and off the field, is in the
final stages of being sold to Los Angeles Kings' owner Philip F.
Anschutz, a Colorado billionaire who has been one of the league's
primary investors since its 1995 inception.
</P>
<P>
   The deal, confirmed by two Galaxy officials and by sources with
Anschutz's two other MLS clubs, probably won't be finalized for
another week or so, but a news release is expected today and a
formal announcement will be made Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rumor mill is not too far off the mark,'' said one Galaxy
official, who spoke on condition that he not be identified. ``It's
in the final stages, basically, but it's not by any means a done
deal. Certain issues remain, but they could be wrapped up next
week.''
</P>
<P>
   Another official, who also spoke on condition of anonymity, said
talks began a few months ago, and Galaxy captain Dan Calichman said
he ``heard it was a done deal a while ago.''
</P>
<P>
   L.A. Soccer Partners LP, a consortium headed by investment
banker Marc Rapaport, will make a profit on its $5 million
investment, although the selling price is not known. Reports have
estimated it as between $20 million _ the current price for an MLS
club _ and $40 million.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Rapaport nor general manager Danny Villanueva, also part
of the ownership group, would comment on the sale, and MLS Deputy
Commissioner Sunil Gulati referred questions to Commissioner Doug
Logan, who did not return phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   Anschutz, 58, whose Denver-based Anschutz Corporation's primary
interests are in natural resources, real estate, transportation and
communications, already owns MLS' Colorado Rapids and Chicago Fire,
which will play in Sunday's league championship at the Rose Bowl.
Neither Anschutz nor Robert Sanderman, the chief executive officer
of the Kings and the president of the Fire and Rapids, could be
reached Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This spells nothing but good news for the Galaxy,'' said one
team official. ``(Anschutz's) reputation is that he puts forth
resources to create a winner.''
</P>
<P>
   The Galaxy reached MLS' title game in 1996 and was a Western
Conference finalist this season after winning the conference's
regular-season title with a 24-8 record. The team also led the
league in attendance, averaging 21,784, and has drawn 1.14 million
fans to the Rose Bowl in three seasons, an average of 23,775.
</P>
<P>
   One Galaxy official said it was unlikely that Rapaport or
Villanueva would continue their involvement with the club but that
Anschutz was unlikely to ``clear house.''
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy players, long critical of L.A. Soccer Partners' fiscal
conservatism, were optimistic about the sale, particularly with
regard to a training center. While most MLS clubs have first-rate
practice facilities, the Galaxy's primary training spot has been
the Rose Bowl's Area H, an uneven, sometimes trash-strewn stretch
of grass used as a parking lot during events at the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what it means to us, but we're awfully
excited,'' Calichman said. ``We've never been given anything, never
been treated like professionals (by current ownership), and we hear
great things from the Chicago and Colorado (players), that he's a
great owner.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-98 0252EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
