<SLUG> BC-FBC-FBCCOL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEMPLE'S UPSET TOUGH ONE TO DIGEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Comments like ``upset of the century'' or ``win for the ages''
make me more nauseated than Cade McNown or Mike Van Raaphorst on a
Saturday afternoon. Then along comes a game like Temple's 28-24
victory over Virginia Tech. The Hokies were not just upset, they
were embarrassed by one of the worst teams in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Tech (5-1) _ ranked 10th in the USA Today/ESPN poll and
13th in the Associated Press poll _ blew a 17-0 lead over Temple
(1-6). Did we mention it was homecoming for the Hokies?
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, everybody's in shock, and rightfully so,'' said
Temple first-year coach Bobby Wallace. ``I'm glad we're off this
week because it will take a little while to get everybody's heads
in the right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Just how shocking was this victory? Let's review a few facts:
</P>
<P>
   __ Temple's victory over Virginia Tech was the Owls' first
victory over a ranked opponent since defeating No.16 Pittsburgh
24-21 on Sept. 19, 1987.
</P>
<P>
   __Temple's victory was its first Big East road victory. Not of
the season but for  &UR; !ital! &LR; any &UR; !off! &LR;  season.
</P>
<P>
   __Temple's victory snapped a losing streak at eight games.
</P>
<P>
   __Temple scored 28 points on a Virginia Tech defense that had
allowed just 30 points all season.
</P>
<P>
   __Temple had 28 points, 328 yards and 11 first downs on its
final eight possessions. In its first six, Temple had one first
down and 29 yards.
</P>
<P>
   __Temple quarterback Devin Scott, a freshman, completed 4 of 9
passes, but they went for 155 yards.
</P>
<P>
   __Temple started six freshman and at times played seven freshmen
on defense.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, other Big East coaches fell over themselves defending
the insanity of the Owls beating a Top 25 team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Temple has a good football team,'' Boston College coach Tom
O'Brien said. ``They have a good scheme. It was going to take some
time to get everything to fall into place. Those things happen in
college football now. You could see the athletes they had. I'm sure
they're going to win a couple more.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, right. But if you were in the Big East, you would probably
say the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   The league was 0-4 in bowl games a year ago and is now 4-7
against Bowl Championship Series league opponents. The Big East's
highest ranked team is now West Virginia, which is 13th in both
polls.
</P>
<P>
   The Big East is the only BCS conference without a team in the
top six, and every BCS league but the ACC and Big East have two
teams in the top 12.
</P>
<P>
   __Fargas makes move: Former Notre Dame High School star tailback
Justin Fargas earned the starting job at Michigan this week after
he carried 31 times for a career-high 120 yards to beat
Northwestern 12-6 in a rainstorm last Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is Big Ten football,'' Fargas said. ``This is why I came
out here from California, to play in all sorts of conditions and
play physical football.''
</P>
<P>
   The mystery is why Wolverines coach Lloyd Carr took so long to
play Fargas.
</P>
<P>
   ``From the beginning of the season, we have been trying to find
a tailback who would run with authority,'' Carr said. ``Based on
what Justin did in that game, he may be the guy. He will start ...
because he deserves to start.''
</P>
<P>
   Carr played Fargas after senior Clarence Williams fumbled on the
first series against Northwestern. Fargas drew the bulk of the
carries the rest of the soggy night. Fargas did not fumble once,
even though the two teams combined for 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't really sure what coach had in mind,'' Fargas said.
``I just wanted to be prepared. We all had a great week of
practice. I'm happy I was able to do pretty well.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Carr: ``What you saw there was one of the finest efforts
ever by a true freshman. When you look at him, he doesn't look like
a real strong guy, but that's deceptive. He's strong and has great
speed. I'm still not sure how durable he is. In that regard, he
came out of this game healthy. Whether he can do it week in and
week out, we have to see.''
</P>
<P>
   __Internet follies: The rise of the Internet, and radio via the
Internet, has led to unprecedented amount of bulletin-board
baloney. The latest example came in Indiana's 14-7 victory over
Iowa, after which Indiana defensive end Adewale Ogunleye credited
Hawkeyes coach Hayden Fry for inspiring the Hoosiers.
</P>
<P>
   Ogunleye claimed Fry said on his weekly radio show that the
Hoosiers quit in their game against the Hawkeyes last year and that
they were going to quit again this year. ``I've heard those words
ringing in my ears all week,'' said Ogunleye, one of several
Hoosiers who listened to the show on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Only one problem: Those words were spoken by one of the phone-in
callers, not Fry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh well, I took it as being him and I used it,'' Ogunleye said
with a smile. ``It worked for me.''
</P>
<P>
   __Dubious honor: Illinois coach Ron Turner after freshman Steve
Fitts, a punter, was named a Big Ten co-player of the week for
special-teams play: ``I'm happy for Steve _ he's doing a great job
for us _ but that's not the guy you'd like to have as player of the
week.''
</P>
<P>
   __ This just in: Stanford coaches say former Camarillo High
quarterback Joe Borchard will begin making random appearances for
the Cardinal in relief of starter Todd Husak.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
