<SLUG> BC-FOOTBALL-DEVELOPER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVELOPER GETS TWO-YEAR PACT TO WOO NFL TEAM TO LOS ANGELES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY RICK ORLOV  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles Coliseum officials Wednesday put their
hopes of winning a National Football League team into the hands of
developer Edward Roski Jr., along with their dream of seeing a
revival of the historic but aging facility.
</P>
<P>
   The stadium's commission, in a rare unanimous 8-0 vote, approved
a two-year contract with Roski and his New Coliseum Ventures Inc.
to negotiate with the NFL to win either an expansion team or have
an existing team relocate to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is breathing new life into the Coliseum,'' commission
President Mike Roos said. ``This is telling the NFL that we are
serious about our commitment to have football return to this great
facility.''
</P>
<P>
   NFL team owners will meet Tuesday in Kansas City to decide where
the league's 32nd franchise will be located. Roski will make the
presentation for the Los Angeles Memorial Coliseum, which will be
competing with a proposal from onetime superagent Mike Ovitz for a
site in Carson and a pitch from the city of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're confident we have everything the NFL has asked for,''
Roski said. ``This agreement with the commission tells the league
that we have the credentials to go ahead to seek a team.''
</P>
<P>
   One drawback that developed Wednesday was word that Mayor
Richard Riordan will not attend the meeting because of a conflict
with the kickoff of his Read to Me literacy program. Instead, the
mayor's aides said, he will make a videotaped speech for the NFL
owners, indicating his support for Roski and the Coliseum proposal.
</P>
<P>
   As for Ovitz, Roski said he was not concerned about the
competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are friends,'' Roski said of the former Walt Disney Co.
president and Hollywood heavyweight. ``I would like to see him join
us, but I don't think that will happen as long as he's advancing
his proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're both going to be presenting Los Angeles in the best
light that we can. Both of us are trying to show the NFL that Los
Angeles is ready for the NFL. We just happen to have different
ideas on where it should be played.''
</P>
<P>
   Under terms of the agreement, Roski and his partners will have
two years in which to convince the NFL to place an expansion team
in the facility or work with an existing team to move to Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   The Coliseum Commission will retain the right to talk with
existing teams that approach it about moving, but the Roski group
would be entitled to repayment of up to $5 million for its costs.
</P>
<P>
   Roski said his focus has been on acquiring an expansion
franchise, but added that existing teams might be interested in
moving after next week's presentation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure that there will be a number of existing teams that
may be challenged in their marketplace,'' Roski said. ``You know,
you've got to remember that Los Angeles is the entertainment
capital of the world and NFL football is entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a tremendously big market. Everybody, I think, will be
looking at our presentation, our facility and . . . who knows?''
</P>
<P>
   The only team officials indicated they weren't interested in was
the Oakland Raiders, which left Los Angeles two years ago. Raiders
owner Al Davis has insisted he maintains the rights to Los Angeles
and has a lawsuit pending over the issue.
</P>
<P>
   NFL officials say they will determine which team, new or
existing, plays in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Roski, who co-owns the Los Angeles Kings hockey team with Denver
billionaire Philip Anschutz, raised his profile in the past two
years as he won city approval to build the Staples Center sports
arena. The $300 million facility, to be built on land adjacent to
the Los Angeles Convention Center, will serve as home to the Kings,
and the Lakers and Clippers basketball teams.
</P>
<P>
   While Anschutz remains his partner in the football effort, Roski
stepped forward this week to take the lead role on the Coliseum
plan saying he would borrow $100 million toward the NFL franchise
fee and pay up to $400 million more.
</P>
<P>
   He said he also is planning to borrow $216 million toward the
remodeling of the Coliseum to accommodate between 67,000 and 80,000
fans, and providing 150 luxury suites and 15,000 club seats.
</P>
<P>
   Roski has committed to paying $80 million for the improvements
with the remaining funds coming from the Community Redevelopment
Agency and a ticket tax on all Coliseum events.
</P>
<P>
   Roski has chartered a jet to fly a 30-member delegation to
Kansas City for his presentation, including representatives of his
new architectural firm, NBBJ Associates; city and county officials;
and officials from Merrill Lynch on the financial plans.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL said it does not expect to make a final decision at the
meeting, but wanted to hear on the status of each proposal.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
