<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAYERS GATHER TO MAP STRATEGY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ In a city where everything under the sun has a
betting line attached, no one's ready to lay odds on saving the NBA
season. Not even the NBA players themselves.
</P>
<P>
   As players began arriving Wednesday night for today's union
meeting, the mood was moderately pessimistic that the 113-day-old
lockout would end anytime soon. But neither are the players ready
to resort to desperate measures to jump-start the season.
</P>
<P>
   Decertify the union? Push the matter into federal court and
force NBA owners to end the lockout? Don't bet the farm it'll
happen, at least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's premature,'' said Orlando Magic center Danny
Schayes, a member of the union's negotiating committee. ``It's
certainly out there as a possibility, but I certainly don't think
it's desirable from anyone's point of view.''
</P>
<P>
   ``My understanding of it is kind of like the weapon of mutually
assured destruction,'' Schayes said. ``It's a great way to drop a
nuke. But the idea is to negotiate a deal. That certainly is what
our agenda has been throughout.''
</P>
<P>
   So the players, possibly 200 of the 400-plus union members, will
meet late this morning at Caesars Palace to discuss negotiation
strategies, review contract proposals and take straw polls on where
they go from here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The purpose of us getting together is to decide what to do
next,'' said Schayes, a 17-year veteran. ``The reason we're
including the entire (membership) ... is to make sure everyone
knows what's going on.''
</P>
<P>
   Which, at this moment, isn't much. NBA owners and players have
met only three times since the lockout began July 1, and no
progress has been made in a dispute over how to divide the league's
$2 billion in annual revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Owners want to reduce the players' share _ which reached 57
percent this past season _ and want to impose a strict salary cap
to reach their objective. Players want to retain the current
salary-cap system, with its numerous loopholes, including the
``Larry Bird exception,'' which allows teams to re-sign free agents
at any salary.
</P>
<P>
   Schayes said players have been willing from the outset to place
limits on Bird contracts in order to help contain salaries and
restore the NBA's shrinking middle class. But he said the owners
are intractable.
</P>
<P>
   With both sides entrenched a handful of players in the 19-member
agents advisory committee met Wednesday and discussed a range of
options; financial assistance for players, fund-raising through
exhibition games, and possibly even creation of a new league.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, fans are left as helpless spectators to a high-stakes
game that unfortunately lacks the thrill of, say, Bulls vs. Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It bugs me, but I can understand what (the players) are
doing,'' said 18-year old Sean Kelly, who waited five hours to
catch a glimpse of his hero, Michael Jordan.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly's biggest thrill this day would be to get MJ's autograph,
maybe a snapshot. But he'd gladly trade it for a fadeaway jumper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather have them play,'' he said. ``Hopefully, it doesn't
take too long.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
