<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOO-MUCH-SODA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SODA FOUND TO PROVIDE 8% OF TEEN CALORIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVID R. BAKER AND MELISSA SCHMITT  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Is no snack safe from the food police?
</P>
<P>
   Researchers at the Center for Science in the Public Interest,
who previously exposed the nutritional evils of burgers, burritos
and popcorn, warned Wednesday that American teen-agers have become
dangerously hooked on soda pop.
</P>
<P>
   Teen-agers guzzle twice as much soda as milk. Soda-drinking boys
are worse than girls, consuming an average of 3.33 cans a day, the
center reported. &UR;  &LR; Girls drink about one-third less.
</P>
<P>
   Worst of all, researchers say, is that the fondness for soda is
pushing other, more nutritious foods out of their diets.
</P>
<P>
   ``People's diets are completely unbalanced by soft drinks,''
said Michael Jacobson, the center's executive director. ``It's
crazy that it's gone to this extreme.''
</P>
<P>
   Soda industry executives immediately blasted the report as yet
another attempt to scare the public away from one of its favorite
foods. And teen-agers said the report merely told them what they
already knew, that drinking gallons of sugar water can be bad for
them.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the National Soft Drink Association, called the
report ``an insult to consumers' intelligence.''
</P>
<P>
   Soft drink makers ``have never made a nutritional claim,'' said
Jim Finkelstein, executive vice president of the organization. ``We
simply make a nice, little refreshment product. We've always said
people should maintain a balanced diet.''
</P>
<P>
   Erica Lastufk, 18, of Los Angeles suburb West Hills, working on
her second root beer Wednesday at a San Fernando Valley Taco Bell
in Canoga Park, knows soft drinks are not good for her but finds
them irresistible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm, like, addicted to the stuff,'' she said. ``I drank, like,
two to three cans a day when I was a little kid. I know it's bad
for me, and I'm trying to cut back. I have cavities on my front
teeth from drinking too much soda, and I heard it puts crystals on
your kidneys.''
</P>
<P>
   The researchers said Americans spent more than $54 billion on
soft drinks in 1997. Among teens, the drinks accounted for 9
percent of all calories boys consumed each day and 8 percent in
girls' diets.
</P>
<P>
   The study links growing soda consumption to rising obesity
rates. And it warns that girls who drink soda instead of milk could
be risking osteoporosis later in life because they aren't getting
enough calcium to build up their bones.
</P>
<P>
   To correct the problem, the center recommended that schools stop
selling soft drinks in cafeterias and urged states to impose taxes
on soda sales.
</P>
<P>
   Finkelstein contended that a balanced diet has plenty of room
for soda as a refreshment, not as a serious source of nutrition. As
for the report's claim that teen-agers are drinking soda at the
expense of more nutritious beverages, he said, ``That's a
parental-guidance thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rebekah Kouy-Ghadosh, 17, of suburban Tarzana said it's also
a cost and convenience thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of have no other options,'' said Kouy-Ghadosh, sipping
her second Dr. Pepper of what she said will be five or six by day's
end.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to be drinking sparkling apple juice -- it's really
good -- but soda is everywhere,'' the Los Angeles Pierce College
student said. ``I can't get away from it. It's ubiquitous.''
</P>
<P>
   Josh Spero, 16, of West Hills blames his eight-can-a-day Diet
Coke habit on his parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was raised on it,'' he said, laughing. ``It's affecting my
brain because of all the NutraSweet.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
