<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 02:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0598 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-FARMER-LADN-(SLAN     10-22 0764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FARMER-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FARMER AID
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The signature play of UCLA's season began with a
mistake. In the huddle, quarterback Cade McNown called a formation
that positioned receiver Danny Farmer on the left side, instead of
the right. Farmer realized the error as he trotted to the line.
Once there, he looked at McNown.
</P>
<P>
   No words, just a look _ a look that said, ``Hey, I'm not
supposed to be here, but I'm here.''
</P>
<P>
   They adjusted accordingly, and seconds later connected on a
64-yard touchdown pass that broke Arizona and propelled UCLA to one
of its most impressive victories in years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't explain what happened,'' Farmer said. ``Cade and I
don't talk much on the field. You don't talk. You feel. We don't
interact on the sideline, but we're connected somehow.''
</P>
<P>
   Powered by friendship, familiarity and necessity, McNown and
Farmer have become one of the Pacific-10's most potent tandems.
McNown is third in passing, while Farmer leads the league in
receiving yards per game (105.8) and yards per catch (24).
</P>
<P>
   ``Danny has made some big plays in his career,'' McNown said.
``He's one of the guys I have confidence in. He's got a knack for
finding the open spot, especially against zone coverage. He's got a
good feel.''
</P>
<P>
   So, apparently, does UCLA's aerial attack. The Bruins are
averaging 296.6 passing yards and 46.6 points per game, third in
the nation.
</P>
<P>
   But closer inspection reveals a receiving corps struggling with
injuries and inexperience. Freddie Mitchell is out for the year
with a broken leg. Brad Melsby hasn't regained his freshman form
after missing two seasons with injury and illness. Brian Poli-Dixon
is talented but inconsistent, as his drops against Oregon showed.
Jon Dubravac is learning the offense. Cody Joyce doesn't catch
enough passes in practice to merit time on Saturdays.
</P>
<P>
   Demand is high. Supply is low. Enter Farmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question he's our go-to guy,'' offensive
coordinator Al Borges said. ``With Freddie, we were so complete,
because we had depth and we were talented. Now the cupboard isn't
as full, but it's not bare.''
</P>
<P>
   In their third season together, Farmer, a redshirt junior, and
McNown, a senior, have developed a sixth sense that's as difficult
to describe as it is to stop. McNown trusts that Farmer will catch
anything in sight. Farmer trusts that McNown will throw a catchable
ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even before Freddie got here, I was the only experienced
receiver,'' Farmer said. ``I made it clear to myself that I really
had to perform to a higher level.''
</P>
<P>
   Although they arrived in 1995, McNown and Farmer spent little
time together. McNown was busy running the team. Farmer, a walk-on
better known for his volleyball talents, toiled with the scout
team.
</P>
<P>
   Farmer received a football scholarship the following summer and
joined the rotation. He led UCLA with 31 catches in 1996, including
a memorable 52-yard touchdown against USC. Last season, he made 41
catches and was named honorable-mention All-Pac-10.
</P>
<P>
   Farmer and McNown have grown closer. They play golf and lounge
on the beach, McNown chatting away, Farmer reciting lyrics from
every song imaginable. This summer, McNown took Farmer home, to
West Linn, Ore., and they went fishing and river rafting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our relationship isn't just football,'' Farmer said. ``We've
truly become friends. We complement each other well.''
</P>
<P>
   Farmer is what Borges calls a ``gamer,'' meaning he practices
well but plays great. McNown is the same way, his arm stronger in
games than practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``In practice, Danny does a good job, but you don't really
notice him,'' coach Bob Toledo said. ``But in games, he continues
to make big plays. Some guys have it, some don't.''
</P>
<P>
   Farmer has the genes for it. His father, George, played football
and basketball and ran track for UCLA. His uncle, Dave, lettered in
football at USC. His maternal grandfather, Steve Miletich, played
basketball for the Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   Farmer is the only UCLA football player with an
NCAA-championship ring. As the volleyball team's middle blocker in
1997-98, he has two. Not surprisingly, he authored the signature
sequence in the '98 title drive, making six consecutive kills to
fuel UCLA's rally against Lewis (Ohio) College in the semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   ``In games, I've seen him run balls down that you don't think he
could touch,'' Bruins volleyball coach Al Scates said. ``I've had
some competitive guys, like Karch Kiraly, and Danny's the same
way.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
