A0608 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-REEVES-COL-TEX     10-22 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-REEVES-COL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES CROWN PUTS FITTING END TO UNBELIEVABLE SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ This story would never play on Broadway. Too corny.
Too melodramatic. Way too sappy.
</P>
<P>
   In baseball, though, we love our tear-jerkers.
</P>
<P>
   Quick, before the screen writers behind this incredible baseball
season can come up with yet another plot twist, write this one in
the record books:
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees captured another Emmy as world champions of
baseball, the 24th in their storied history, last night at Qualcomm
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Eat your heart out, Susan Lucci.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Pettitte, who spent last weekend with his father in Houston
as he had double-bypass surgery, outpitched self-imploding Padres
ace Kevin Brown and the Yankees won Game 4 of the 1998 World
Series, 3-0, completing their four-game sweep and placing them
among the great teams in baseball history.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Brosius, whose dad made it to the games here despite
suffering from colon cancer _ I warned you that this was a
tear-jerker _ had a key, bases-loaded run-scoring single in the
eighth, when the Yankees put the game away and Brown blew up
emotionally. The hit clinched the vote for Brosius, homer-hitting
hero of Game 3, as Series most valuable player.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's unbelievable,'' said Brosius, who hit just .203 at
Oakland last season before staging a remarkable comeback in '98.
``Coming off last year, sometimes you wonder what kind of plan God
has for you. To come back and have a year like this, I'm just very
grateful. It's an incredible thrill.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest moment is that third out, knowing that you're
going to throw the ball and end the game and end the season, and
then to see the look in your teammates' eyes as we rushed to the
mound.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the Yankees' 125th victory of 1998 against just 50
losses. Let the baseball historians wrestle with that one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the best team a lot of us will every be a part of,''
right fielder Paul O'Neill said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously to have the best record of all time, to win 125
games is remarkable,'' manager Joe Torre said. ``One-twenty-five
and 50 ... how neat is that? We may not be the best team of all
time, but we have the best record. The 1927 Yankees put the bar up
pretty high and we went over that.''
</P>
<P>
   And, yes, Torre's big brother Frank, celebrating the second
anniversary of his new heart, is doing just fine, thank you.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte, who had flown to Houston to be with his father during
his open-heart surgery last week, gave up just five hits in 71/3
innings and Torre deftly maneuvered his bullpen to ease his team
out of an eighth-inning tight spot.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres helped out with a highly questionable judgment calls
by third base coach Tim Flannery, who inexplicably held speedy
Quilvio Veras at third on Ken Caminiti's line single to right in
the bottom of the eighth, even though the Yankees were conceding
the run and not even throwing to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Sigh. Maybe they should bring those tacky, orange and brown
taco-vendor uniforms back after all.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who may own the best right arm and the worst luck in
baseball, ultimately saw his infamous sinker hurt him as much or
more than it did the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Twice the Yankees chopped the ball off the dirt in front of the
plate to snap a scoreless tie in the sixth. They scored twice more
in the eighth and barely got a ball out of the infield.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who had walked Derek Jeter to start the eighth, lost it
when first-base umpire Tim Tschida signaled O'Neill, who had
dribbled the ball to Leyritz at first, safe on a bang-bang play.
</P>
<P>
   Twice Brown had to be physically restrained from getting to
Tschida, who probably would have been justified in throwing him out
of the game. Brosius' single over a drawn-in Padres' infield plated
one run and Ricky Ledee's sacrifice fly brought home another.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, the good sport that he is, derisively doffed his cap at
Tschida as he left the field at the end of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   You just can't change the stripes on a skunk.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, it didn't matter what kind of stink Brown raised.
This was the Yankees' year and no team could have kept them from
their destiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been around a more determined or more courageous
group,'' Torre said. ``To have the record we had going and to
continue to play well and never take a day off, that was a great
indication to me that we were pretty special.''
</P>
<P>
   So very, very special.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres, like the Rangers and the Indians before them, were
just bit players on the Yankees' stage, no more important than
pieces of movable scenery.
</P>
<P>
   Some were able to speak a few lines (not the Rangers), some (the
Indians) were able to spend a little more time on stage than the
others.
</P>
<P>
   But there was never any question who deserved star billing.
</P>
<P>
   So now it's time to bring on the roses and rise to your feet,
baseball fans. Open the curtains and let the Yankees take their
bows. If ever a team deserved a standing ovation and a round of
``Bravos!'' it is this one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-98 0258EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
