<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 02:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0620 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-WSSIDE-LADN-(SLAN     10-22 0521
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-WSSIDE-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BERNIE'S BIG DECISION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Has Bernie Williams played his final game with the
New York Yankees?
</P>
<P>
   Williams' pending free agency has made his future with the team
an issue throughout the 1998 season and Wednesday night was no
different.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Yankees won their second World Series in the last
three years by sweeping the San Diego Padres on Wednesday, success
alone might not be enough to keep him in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the Yankees had the inside track over other teams,
Williams did not exactly say what New York fans wanted to hear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll say it's probably about as good as any other team right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who turned 30 last week, won the American League
batting title with a .339 average. He had 26 homers and 97 RBI and
is in the prime of his career. Next to Ken Griffey Jr., Williams is
considered the best center fielder in baseball. All that is
expected to make his market value sore well above $10 million per
season.
</P>
<P>
   Williams is part of a premier free-agent class that includes
Padres Game 4 starter Kevin Brown, former Dodgers catcher Mike
Piazza and Houston left-hander Randy Johnson. World Series MVP
Scott Brosius also is eligible for free agency.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have balked at giving Williams anywhere near $10
million annually in previous negotiations. They have offered five
years for $37 million and have exclusive negotiating rights for the
next 15 days.
</P>
<P>
   His agent, Scott Boras, has not made free agency an issue during
this magical Yankees season. But it is a difficult subject to
ignore.
</P>
<P>
   After the 1996 championship season, the Yankees lost closer John
Wetteland and starter Jimmy Key to free agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, if that's going to be the case, we hope we can send him
away with the ring,'' said emotional Yankees manager Joe Torre.
``And though the nature of the games is you're not going to have
everybody back, obviously we all hope we get Bernie back.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough saying good-bye to Jimmy Key and John Wetteland,
too, in 1996. We understand it and I think that's why players want
to take advantage of something special like we have going on right
now. But it is going to be tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams finished the Series with a meager .063 batting average
(1 for 16), leading many to believe he was distracted by the
free-agent possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   When the Yankees won the American League Championship Series
against Cleveland, Williams skipped the celebration and remained in
the players' lounge. After the Yankees clinched the World Series on
Wednesday, he left the celebration and walked alone with his wife
in deep center field at Qualcomm Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes I let it slip a little bit and in the back of my
mind it's all that uncertainty, the feeling of not knowing what's
going to happen next year,'' Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But then I start thinking about the things that are happening
to me right now and I feel very blessed. I'm just going to worry
about (free agency) when the time comes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
