<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-PETTITT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PETTITTE PERFECT IN PINCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KAREN CROUSE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Andy Pettitte's mind admittedly wasn't on baseball a
week ago. But on Wednesday, in the most monumental start of his
young career, the Yankees pitcher threw his whole soul into the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte pitched 71/3 masterful innings to help power the
Yankees to a 3-0 World Series-sweeping win over the Padres in front
of the largest crowd ever to watch a baseball game here (65,247).
</P>
<P>
   The win capped some kind of weird, worrisome, wonderful season
for the Yankees, who battled more adversity off the field than on
it.
</P>
<P>
   Darryl Strawberry, no small presence among the pinstripes, was
diagnosed with colon cancer early in the postseason and the team
didn't blink. The father of third baseman Scott Brosius also is
fighting colon cancer and Brosius didn't miss a beat, hitting two
home runs to almost singlehandedly win Game 2 on Tuesday to earn
Series' MVP honors.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Pettitte, whose father underwent double-bypass
heart surgery during the American League Championship Series
shortly after his son was shelled in the Yankees' last loss of the
season, as it were, against Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte gave up eight hits, four of them home runs, in 42/3
innings, then traveled to Houston to be at his father's side.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, it had been that kind of year for Pettitte, 26,
whose earned-run average of 4.24 was significantly worse than his
2.88 in 1997. Never had a 16-game winner felt so miserable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of embarrassing to say I won 16 games,'' Pettitte,
who was 16-4 during the regular season, said on the eve of his
stiffest assignment as a professional.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he would have graded his regular season, Pettitte
answered bluntly, ``I'd give myself a B-minus. I felt like it was a
little bit more of a struggle than it has been in the past.
Mechanically, I've had difficulties.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahh, the beauty of midterms; they show you what you need to bone
up on to ace the final exam.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte's 100-pitch performance was first-rate. It was
reminiscent of his effort in Game 5 of the 1996 World Series
against Atlanta when he pitched 8.1 shutout innings to give the
Yankees a 3-2 series lead.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called weak link in the Yankees' rotation allowed five
hits and struck out four.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tend to think about the bad things more than the good so
this was definitely gratifying,'' said Pettitte, who tends to be
harder on himself than any of Yankee Stadium Bleacher Creatures
could ever be.
</P>
<P>
   There was speculation that had he pitched in Game 2 at home, he
would have been booed. Instead, Pettitte will return to New York as
Broadway's newest matinee idol.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
