r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-SERIES-GAME-4-AZR     10-22 0756
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SERIES-GAME-4-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESTINY FULFILLED IN MAGICAL SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ The hype, it turns out, was justified. The New York
Yankees capped as memorable a season as their time-honored
franchise has ever seen by winning their record 24th World Series
championship in stylish fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Just as they had done all season, the Yankees smothered their
opponent in the World Series, sweeping San Diego in four games to
win their second championship in three years.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres, who mostly resembled a club in awe of the Yankees
and their mystique, succumbed, 3-0, on Wednesday night, becoming
the 16th club to fall victim to a World Series sweep.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a doubt they're the best team I've seen in a long
time,'' said Kevin Brown, the losing pitcher in Game 4. ``They're a
super team from top to bottom. They have few holes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees' triumph culminates a season in which they won 114
regular-season games while losing 48 and then breezed through the
postseason with an 11-2 record, giving them an incredible overall
record of 125-50.
</P>
<P>
   It also fulfills Yankees boss George Steinbrenner's promise last
year that his New York club would win the 1998 World Series, a
pledge he made publicly the same night the Yankees lost to
Cleveland in the division playoffs last October.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been a little emotional tonight,'' said Steinbrenner, who
celebrated his fourth Series title in the 25 years since he bought
the club. ``This is as great a Yankee team as there has ever been.
It's wonderful because New York needs this; it boosts the entire
city right up.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end the Yankees simply threw too many weapons at San
Diego, who were National League champions for only the second time
in their 30-year history.
</P>
<P>
   It started snowballing for the Yankees in Game 1 when Chuck
Knoblauch and Tino Martinez slammed key home runs in the seventh
inning, helping erase a three-run deficit, and finished with New
York starter Andy Pettitte putting the Padres to sleep with 7
innings of scoreless ball Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In between, New York tossed its arsenal at overwhelmed San
Diego, including little-known outfielder Ricky Ledee, who was 6 for
10 with four RBIs; perennial All-Star Bernie Williams, who slammed
a key two-run home run in Game 2; and Series Most Valuable Player
Scott Brosius, whose four-RBI game on Tuesday propelled the Yankees
to victory that night.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's heroes for the Yankees were Pettitte and shortstop
Derek Jeter, who made a spectacular defensive play and scored twice
while reaching base three times.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel privileged to have been a part of this team,'' said
Brosius, who arrived from Oakland in exchange Kenny Rogers last
winter. ``No one guy carried the load. It was all 25. It's a
special group of guys filled with great character.''
</P>
<P>
   But this series seemed to be decided well before Wednesday,
like, say, back in Game 1 last Saturday. From the beginning, San
Diego seemed awestruck, especially during the first two games at
venerable Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   No one displayed how intimidated the Padres were more than third
baseman Ken Caminiti, who admitted he was freaked out by the
raucous scene in the Bronx. He may not have been alone: Caminiti,
Wally Joyner and Steve Finley hit a combined .088 with one RBI.
</P>
<P>
   Caminiti, who fell on his rear three times in the last two games
while swinging and missing pitches and has been bothered by a
strained groin almost all season, finished the series with two hits
in 14 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't get anything going,'' said Caminiti, whose seven
strikeouts were the most in a four-game series since Bob Meusel did
the same for the Yankees in the 1927 Series. ``I was good enough to
be out there so I should have been good enough to get the job
done.''
</P>
<P>
   San Diego, whose 1-8 World Series record ranks last in
big-league history, fell one victory shy of becoming the first club
since the 1993 Philadelphia Phillies to go an entire season without
being swept in a series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to use the word magic because I used it in '96,''
said Yankees Manager Joe Torre, who has guided New York to the
title in two of his three years there. ``I will say, I've never
seen a more determined group.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're inundated with so many stats these days and players get
into the `What's in it for me' mentality. There was none of that
here this year. It was a special, special team.''
</P>
<P>
   It's difficult to argue that point. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
