r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN-(SLANG     10-22 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KARIYA IS BACK WITH A FLASH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ He's back.
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 10, 1997, Paul Kariya was in Vancouver waiting for a new
contract offer. The franchise's centerpiece was snipped out of the
opening-night video package and new coach Pierre Page was lustily
booed on one of the strangest evenings in Anaheim Mighty Ducks
history.
</P>
<P>
   And that was before the first puck of the game was even dropped.
The sleep-inducing tie with Ottawa that followed seemed to set the
tone for what would turn out to be the worst season in Anaheim's
short history.
</P>
<P>
   Expectations may not be great heading into the 1998-99 season,
but Kariya was in the highlights, on the program cover, and most
importantly in the lineup Wednesday as the Ducks defeated Boston
3-0 in the home opener before a sellout crowd of 17,174 at the
Pond.
</P>
<P>
   In his first regular-season home game since Feb. 1, Kariya added
another goal to his own personal highlight reel as the Ducks won
their second consecutive game after opening the season with three
losses.
</P>
<P>
   Kariya, who also had an assist, gave the Ducks a 2-0 lead at
14:51 of the second period while Anaheim had a two-man advantage.
Teemu Selanne's cross-ice pass to Kariya at the side of the Boston
net turned into a goal when the Ducks winger swatted the puck past
Boston goalie Byron Dafoe baseball-style after it bounced off his
stick.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks, who had scored only once in their first 21 power-play
chances, then scored their second power-play goal of the game when
Fredrik Olausson's shot from the right point slipped through
Dafoe's pads at 15:42.
</P>
<P>
   That gave the Ducks a 3-0 lead, which was more than enough for a
team whose defense has been surprisingly effective in the first
five games.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim coach Craig Hartsburg doesn't have the luxury of calling
upon Chris Chelios like he did in Chicago, but he insists defense
is more than a one-man effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a team thing, you have to have pride in playing defense
as a team,'' said Hartsburg. ``We've got guys who are capable of
playing well back there. I like the way they compete.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chelios is an unusual player, coaching him you learn to
respect him, but that's over.''
</P>
<P>
   The Anaheim defense did a good job of shutting down the Bruins,
especially in the first two periods when they limited Boston to 15
shots. In particular, the Ducks controlled dangerous winger Sergei
Samsonov, who came into the game with six points in the first six
games.
</P>
<P>
   When the defense did falter, goalie Guy Herbert was up to the
challenge. He made a glove save to stop Ted Danato from close range
midway through the second period. In the third period he foiled a
three-on-two break by the Bruins when he slid across to stop Steve
Heinze.
</P>
<P>
   Hebert got some help from the post on a shot by Ray Bourque
midway through the third, but made some of his own luck by diving
backwards to deny Chris Taylor after his shot bounced off the post.
</P>
<P>
   Hebert stopped 26 shots to record the Ducks' first home shutout
since Nov. 26, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Kariya had three shots in the first period and even dished out a
good body check on Bourque. But it was one of Kariya's newly
acquired bodyguards that opened the scoring.
</P>
<P>
   Jim McKenzie knocked in his own rebound with 46.1 seconds left
in the opening period, this after defenseman Mike Crowley was able
to hold the puck in at the left point thanks to a good forechecking
effort by Tomas Sandstrom.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
