r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-SERIES-BICKLEY-AZ     10-22 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SERIES-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEY'RE GOOD, BUT DON'T SAY GREATEST EVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO - They don't have a nickname. No sure Hall of Fame
candidates. Nothing that separates them in the mythology of
baseball other than a bloated victory total.
</P>
<P>
   No, the '98 Yankees are not the best team of all time.
</P>
<P>
   What they are is a wonderful anomaly. A home-grown outfit. A
team without egos or superstars. A team that is deep, resourceful,
without a weakness.
</P>
<P>
   A team that isn't supposed to exist in the statistic-driven,
me-first era of free agency.
</P>
<P>
   ``We take a back seat to no one in my lifetime,'' Yankees
Manager Joe Torre said. ``This ballclub is like no other club I've
ever been around.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, the Yankees won their 24th world
championship. With a sweep over the Padres, they closed the books
with a record of 125-50, the best winning percentage since the
fabled Yankees of 1927. They started the season with a three-game
losing streak, finished with a seven-game winning streak, and in
between, posted the most victories of any team in American League
history.
</P>
<P>
   And after they celebrated on Padres soil, they walked off the
field, assuming their place under the microscope of history.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got to rank among the greatest ever,'' Yankees' owner
George Steinbrenner said. ``Not just the greatest Yankees, but the
greatest ever. They are warriors. All those great teams of the
past, each year, they would get bigger in people's minds. This team
will do the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Steinbrenner is right about one thing. These Yankees make the
team picture. But they are not Murderer's Row. They are not the
Swingin' A's. They are not the Big Red Machine. And without a
ferocious slugger or something worthy of romantic folklore, they
will not get bigger with age.
</P>
<P>
   The first four batters for the '27 Yankees made the Hall of
Fame. The A's won three straight titles from 1972-74. The Reds were
an offensive juggernaut, one that capped their second straight
title in 1976 without losing a game in the postseason.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees went 11-1 against Tampa Bay.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are now three levels of playoffs,'' Steinbrenner
countered. ``You know how hard it is to get through three levels,
particularly with everybody pointing at you?''
</P>
<P>
   Sure, the road is longer. But with a league seriously diluted by
expansion, a league with an enormous economic disparity between the
big and small markets, the journey is much easier.
</P>
<P>
   When El Duque washed ashore, the Yankees spent the money. When
Hideki Irabu refused to play for the Padres, the Yankees spent the
money. And who else could afford to pay Chili Davis _ a part-time
designated hitter _ a whopping $7 million a year?
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that you're the Yankees and you go out and spend the
money, you're going to have a chance to win,'' Torre said.
</P>
<P>
   In this Series, the Padres never got that chance. They were
badly outclassed. Their manager didn't go a night without a
questionable maneuver. As they paraded around the field afterward,
holding their arms up in triumph, they were clearly content with
second place.
</P>
<P>
   In the other locker room, expectations were met, champagne
swirled, Steinbrenner fought back tears. Like him or not, much of
this accomplishment is a reflection of the owner.
</P>
<P>
   While the system is broken, Steinbrenner will spend anything to
win. From an enormous scouting department to a gigantic payroll,
the man seizes the moment.
</P>
<P>
   And there is something special about his baseball team. While
Scott Brosius was MVP, the Yankees were best symbolized by a
wonderful pitching staff, the professionalism of Paul O'Neill, the
youthful brilliance of Derek Jeter and Bernie Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were 125-50. I don't think many teams can say that, and we
played with an intensity level that I've never seen before,'' Jeter
said. ``I think you can argue for us as being the best of all
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Or you can argue that an air-tight team such as the Yankees were
destined to put up huge numbers in an expansion year. An
organization that enjoyed a great season, but certainly not the
greatest bunch to lace up the cleats.
</P>
<P>
   Celebrate them for what they are. A team in the truest sense of
the word.  &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at 602-444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
