<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 03:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0630 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES-ADAMS-AZR     10-22 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-ADAMS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NHL ROAD PASSES THROUGH FLAGSTAFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Uncertain. Anxious. Altruistic. Vengeful, perhaps.
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes left wing Greg Adams admits his emotions likely will run
the gamut tonight when he and his new teammates meet his old
teammates, the Dallas Stars, at a building appropriately named the
Reunion Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, having played there the past few years, you almost
feel like you want to prove yourself,'' said Adams, a 14-year NHL
veteran who joined the Coyotes this summer as an unrestricted free
agent. ``It's going to be weird. There's a lot of good friends of
mine over there. It's going to be strange to play against them for
the first time. I'm not sure what to expect.''
</P>
<P>
   The 35-year-old Adams felt the same way when he left his family
and home in Nelson, British Columbia, to accept a hockey
scholarship from an obscure little university tucked away in the
pines in a town he'd never heard of before.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where ``did'' he go to college?'' asked Coyotes goalie Jimmy
Waite, a French-Canadian from Quebec.
</P>
<P>
   NAU.
</P>
<P>
   ``NA-what?'' Waite said.
</P>
<P>
   Northern Arizona University. It's up in Flagstaff,Ariz. The
Lumberjacks. They don't have an NCAA hockey program anymore,
though.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yeah. I've heard of that place,'' Waite said. ``I didn't
know they ever had college hockey here.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither did Adams, but it was the only college in North America
that offered him a full scholarship. He took it, closed his eyes
and prayed. After two years of playing Tier II junior hockey near
Vancouver and getting absolutely zero sniffs elsewhere, he figured,
``What the heck?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know what to expect at all,'' Adams said. ``About the
only thing I knew is that it was in Arizona someplace. When I came
down here, I remember flying into Phoenix, and it was something
like 110 degrees, and I'm like, `Oh, my gosh! How are we going to
play hockey here?' But I got a much different feeling driving up to
Flagstaff. It cooled off a lot, and I said, `I can handle this.' ''
</P>
<P>
   During his second and final season at NAU, in 1983-84, Adams
didn't just handle it. He manhandled the rest of the NCAA, leading
the nation in scoring with 44 goals and 73 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a real good team that year,'' he said. ``We had a lot
of guys in the same situation as me, where we didn't get the offers
from the big schools, but we all were good enough to play for one
of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone just had a great year. We ended up something like
21-5, but because we were an independent, we didn't go anywhere. It
was a little disappointing, too, after having such a good season
and not being able to finish it off.''
</P>
<P>
   Not too many years later, the men's ice hockey program at NAU
was finished as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, that was kind of sad,'' Adams said. ``They had a lot of
problems with the arena, and they never had the money to fix it.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams, though, was just beginning. His big season at NAU caught
the eye of the New Jersey Devils, who signed him as a free agent.
Since then, he's scored 30 or more goals four times in his career
and has reached the 20-goal plateau nine times _ five while with
the Vancouver Canucks, where he was a teammate of Cliff Ronning,
Jyrki Lumme and Gerald Didick and went to the Stanley Cup Finals
against the New York Rangers in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to give him a lot of credit for coming out of a
small school like that and making it as big as he has,'' Waite
said. ``It's a pretty cool story.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that it doesn't come with its share of jokes. Adams said he
gets teased about his days at NAU from several players, including
an ex-teammate in New Jersey who once told him, ``A hockey player
coming out of Arizona is like a baseball player coming from
Alaska.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes are glad it worked out the way it did, though. In
Adams, they get a 6-foot-3, hard-working, two-way player who has
tallied 306 career goals and 631 points. They get some desperately
needed scoring help behind captain Keith Tkachuk. And they get a
guy who's been through the playoff wars.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not only a highly skilled player,'' Coyotes Coach Jim
Schoenfeld said, ``but he's a very intelligent player, both with
and without the puck.
</P>
<P>
   ``He makes the right read in the offensive rush. He doesn't
force a play that isn't there. If the thing's shut down, he knows
how to make a good dump-in and establish our forecheck. He's real
good in the neutral zone, he knows all his assignments, and he
battles so hard, he usually wins the one-on-ones.''
</P>
<P>
   It was exactly what he did in Dallas, where he was traded
halfway through the 1994-95 season. He scored 60 goals in 177 games
with the Stars. He was at his best last November, when he had four
goals and four assists, earning NHL player of the week honors. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-98 0300EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
