<HEADER>
A0637 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NASCAR-BUSCH-PIR-     10-22 0560
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-BUSCH-PIR-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
'99 BUSCH SERIES RACE SPEEDING TO WARD PIR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - For nearly 10 years, fans, teams and sponsors have
been hammering Phoenix International Raceway President Buddy Jobe
for a NASCAR Busch Series race.
</P>
<P>
   Well, guess what?
</P>
<P>
   It's here.
</P>
<P>
   Sources on Wednesday told ``The'' ``Arizona Republic'' that
PIR's 1999 schedule will include a Nov. 6 Busch Series race, which
is scheduled the same weekend as the NASCAR Winston Cup event.
</P>
<P>
   PIR officials have scheduled a noon press conference today to
make the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can tell you is we're very close (to an agreement),''
Jobe said. ``It's something we've wanted for a long time. If we get
a Busch race, it will elevate the program we have at PIR.''
</P>
<P>
   NASCAR Operations Director Kevin Triplett wouldn't confirm the
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``We plan on announcing our 1999 Busch schedule in the near
future,'' Triplett said. ``Until certain things are done, we can't
really comment.''
</P>
<P>
   The Busch Series, second in NASCAR importance to the Winston Cup
circuit, has 31 races this season. Many of its races are held in
conjunction with Winston Cup events, giving fans twice the
opportunity to see such stars as Mark Martin, Dale Jarrett and Jeff
Burton, who often compete in both races.
</P>
<P>
   Additionally, Jeff Gordon and Dale Earnhardt Jr. are also going
to compete in several Busch Series races next season, one of which
could be at PIR.
</P>
<P>
   Although sources said there was initial discussion regarding a
Busch Series race at PIR in January, NASCAR officials apparently
never seriously considered the date.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we first got our Winston Cup race in 1988, we started
asking about a Busch race,'' Jobe said. ``But from Day 1, the
response was Busch would never race west of the Mississippi
(River).
</P>
<P>
   ``Now look at the series. There were three races (at Las Vegas,
Fountain, Colo., and Fort Worth) in this region this year. It would
be an immensely great addition for us if we get one. The race fans
want and love this series.''
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally, the NASCAR Craftsman Truck Series schedules two
yearly races at PIR, one of which is Saturday's GM Goodwrench
Service Plus/AC Delco 300 at PIR, which precedes Sunday's
Dura-Lube/Kmart 500.
</P>
<P>
   But the Busch Series addition means the Truck Series will appear
once on PIR's schedule next season. A truck race will be held the
same March 26-28 weekend as an Indy Racing League event.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's Saturday truck race prior to the Dura-Lube 500
attracted a crowd of about 60,000, and it's believed a Busch Series
race will draw even more fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (PIR officials) think 70,000 fans would come to a Busch
race,'' one source said.
</P>
<P>
   Seating capacity at the track is 72,576. However, infield and
hillside attendance swelled last year's Winston Cup crowd to
104,000.
</P>
<P>
   Besides seeking a Busch race, Jobe has lobbied for a coveted
second Winston Cup race. But he's convinced it won't happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's in the cards for us to get another race,''
said Jobe, who sold PIR last year to Daytona Beach, Fla.-based
International Speedway Corp. ``There's too many other areas NASCAR
needs to go like Kansas City and Chicago. I think the chances of
tracks getting a second race are slim and none.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
