r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-ASU-STANFORD-AZR &LR;      10-22 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ASU-STANFORD-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STANFORD'S LOSING, BUT PASSING FANCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - When the game-ending whistle sounds _ sometime
near daybreak Friday is a safe bet _ Arizona State will have a
sense of its immediate future.
</P>
<P>
   Tonight's meeting with Stanford at Sun Devil Stadium could be
the start of a promising era with Chad Elliott at quarterback. Or
it could mean ASU's fifth loss and a season continuing to spin out
of control.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty heavy stuff for a game in which the teams have combined
for three victories.
</P>
<P>
   Both are in a funk. ASU (2-4, 1-2 Pac-10) has lost two straight.
Stanford (1-5, 0-3) is coming off a heartbreaking defeat against
Oregon State.
</P>
<P>
   How does the Cardinal plan to snap out of it?
</P>
<P>
   Pass, pass, pass, pass, pass, pass pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to spread us all over the field,'' ASU Coach
Bruce Snyder said. ``They're going to have shifts, motions and
they're going to try to find a mismatch. And if (quarterback Todd
Husak) has time, he's going to find the open guy. We've got to put
pressure on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanford is expected to play without two backfield starters,
tailback Coy Wire (dislocated thumb) and fullback Maxwell Stevenson
(neck). A team that has attempted more passes than rushes in all
but one game this season is expected to continue its air assault.
</P>
<P>
   It could get interesting. Stanford wants to make better use of
backup quarterbacks Randy Fasani and Joe Borchard _ two of the
team's most athletic players _ and that could manifest itself in
unusual ways.
</P>
<P>
   Offensive coordinator Bill Diedrick told the ``San Francisco
Examiner,'' ``You might see two of them in the backfield at the
same time. There are all sorts of possibilities. . . . I'm still
looking for the ultimate, to get all three in the ballgame at once.
It's not going to happen this week, but it's going to happen. I'm
not going to say when.''
</P>
<P>
   Stanford's strength has been its receivers. DeRonnie Pitts and
Dave Davis likely will surpass 1,000 yards this season. Preseason
All-America Troy Walters is back after playing in just two full
games because of an ankle sprain. Husak has passed for 1,772 yards
and 11 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been excited about his ability to run our offense and
really keep us in the right thing at the right time,'' Cardinal
Coach Tyrone Willingham said. ``His ability to spread the ball
among our receivers has been super this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Said ASU's J'Juan Cherry, ``As a cornerback, you want them to
throw the ball. I ``really'' want them to throw the ball. If
there's a challenge, me and Courtney (Jackson) and the rest of the
defensive backs, we can step up to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sun Devils will be forced into their nickel and dime
packages, which isn't necessarily a good thing because of how thin
they are at defensive back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plan on being there until about midnight,'' Snyder said.
``We're just going to sleep over.''
</P>
<P>
   He was kidding.
</P>
<P>
   Wasn't he?
</P>
<P>
   ``We could see 60, 70 passes from them,'' Snyder said. ``I don't
know, but if you look at the circumstances . . . it could be like a
pass scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just talked to the whole defense: We need to get four-man
pressure where he must throw on time. If he doesn't, we've got to
get him to the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   The bigger story, at least for ASU fans, is Elliott. How will
the redshirt freshman perform in his first start in place of Ryan
Kealy?
</P>
<P>
   Stanford is the right opponent for a debut. Its weaknesses have
been defending the run and giving up big plays. The Sun Devils
offense has the potential to capitalize on both.
</P>
<P>
   Snyder has vowed to get fullback Jeff Paulk in the game more,
and his blocking, in particular, has a significant impact on how
well the Sun Devils run. Having the option to hand off to J.R.
Redmond is the ideal way to keep Elliott focused.
</P>
<P>
   He'll pass, too. Count on it. Elliott loves to throw deep, and
if ASU finds it can capitalize on Stanford's secondary, which is
allowing a conference-high 9.7 yards per reception and 10
touchdowns, he'll go long.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's real confident, and it has a way of rubbing off on other
players,'' center Grey Ruegamer said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
