<HEADER>
A0645 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-GOFCOL-COLUMN-LAD     10-22 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOFCOL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARNIE'S ARMY WILL RE-ENLIST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVE SHELBURNE  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; The King is back, at least for a week, and that's good news for
Los Angeles-area golf fans. Arnold Palmer confirmed Monday he will
play in next week's Pacific Bell Senior Classic at Wilshire Country
Club.
</P>
<P>
   The three-day Senior PGA Tour event (formerly called the Ralphs
Senior Classic) runs Oct. 30-Nov. 1 and also includes two-time
defending champion Gil Morgan, Jim Colbert, Raymond Floyd, Lee
Trevino, hometown hero Dave Stockton from USC and
golfers-turned-broadcasters-returned-golfers Johnny Miller and Gary
McCord.
</P>
<P>
   But the man who will draw the biggest crowds is Palmer, who is
coming off seven weeks of radiation treatment related to his
recovery from prostate cancer that was diagnosed in January of
1997.
</P>
<P>
   This is Palmer's first tournament since August. He has been able
to practice around treatments and has shot several rounds in the
60s, including a 63 on his home course at Latrobe Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good scores happened within two weeks of starting the
treatments,'' said Palmer, who turned 69 on Sept. 29. ``It was
before I had much reaction to it. I was rested from all of the work
I had been doing and started to play some pretty good golf.''
</P>
<P>
   (Palmer played a round with his son-in-law Sunday and shot 68.)
</P>
<P>
   As usual, Palmer won't rule out the chance of one more magical
weekend. His continuing optimism in the face of advancing age and
deteriorating skills is a large part of his appeal to fans. They've
appreciated him for parts of five decades and Palmer says the
feeling is mutual.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans have always been a special part of my career,'' he
said. ``They have inspired me over the years and I hope I have
inspired them, as well.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Names in the game: Alice Cooper, Eddie Van Halen, Hootie and
the Blowfish, and ... Grayson Taylor Eleftheriou? The first three
are rockers turned golfers and Grayson Taylor certainly has that
potential _ but he'll have to wait awhile for both professions.
</P>
<P>
   Six-week-old Eleftheriou, born Sept. 11, is the son of former
heavy metal bandsman and current Scholl Canyon head pro Ted
Eleftheriou, who now combines 60-70 lessons a week with late-night
diaper duty. Mother (Lisa) and baby are doing well, and as for that
predictable wailing and shrieking in the middle of the night,
ex-rocker Ted calls it music to his ears....
</P>
<P>
   __ SCPGA junior stars: Santa Clarita Valley's Brandon
Christiansen, 12, is one of 10 area junior golfers to earn a top-10
placement in the final Southern California PGA junior age-group
rankings for 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Christiansen, a La Mesa Junior High seventh grader who will
compete in the national final of the Golf Skills Challenge Nov. 7
at Ojai, wound up sixth in the age 12-13 SCPGA division. Anthony
Kim of Studio City was second in that division, which was topped by
player of the year Henry Liaw, the 13-year-old Rowland Heights
phenom and two-time Junior World champion.
</P>
<P>
   Other area top-10 finishers included Nick Geyer of Agoura Hills,
Eugene Choi of Granada Hills and Edgar Reyes of Lakeview Terrace
(3-5-7 in boys 11-under); Calabasas High junior Justin Ohye (10th
in boys 14-15); Alemany High junior Krystal Shearer (fifth in girls
15-17); Harvard-Westlake sophomore Ina Kim and Hart freshman Sarah
Jones (2-9 in girls 12-14); and Grace Woo of Burbank (eighth in
girls 11-under).
</P>
<P>
   Kim, who has helped Harvard-Westlake get off to a 15-2 start in
this, the Southern Section's first year of girls' high school golf,
is one of two members of her family to earn top-10 recognition.
Older sister Hanna, a junior at Brentwood, is ranked No.5 in the
girls 15-17 division.
</P>
<P>
   __ Klein honored: Former Notre Dame High star Emilee Klein, who
honed her game at Glendale's Oakmont Country Club and won a
national junior girls championship in 1991 en route to a career on
the LPGA Tour, has been inducted into the SCPGA Junior Golf Hall of
Fame. Klein, 24, who won the 1994 individual NCAA championship
while competing for Arizona State, has won twice on the LPGA Tour,
including the 1996 Women's British Open.
</P>
<P>
   __ Golf in the dark: The Glendale YMCA will hold its annual
night-glow fund-raising tournament Saturday at the 18-hole Verdugo
Hills par-three course in Tujunga, starting at 9:30 p.m. Entry fee
is $30. Information: (818) 240-4130, ext. 24.
</P>
<P>
   __ Teardrop finale: The West Coast championship of the Teardrop
Tour is scheduled for Nov. 10-12 at Cypress GC. Information: (949)
975-8466.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
