<SLUG> BC-FBN-CARDS-KNIGHT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNIGHT UNDERSTANDS DURABILITY QUESTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TEMPE, Ariz. - Tom Knight, the Cardinals' second-year
cornerback, has heard the whispers. He knows there are those
questioning his durability, attempting to attach a hated label to
the ninth pick of the 1997 draft.
</P>
<P>
   Injury prone.
</P>
<P>
   There is little doubt that Knight has the athletic talent to
live up to that first-round draft status. And if he blossoms into
the player the Cardinals envisioned when they selected him out of
Iowa, Knight and Aeneas Williams could be among the NFL's best sets
of cornerbacks.
</P>
<P>
   But injuries have hampered Knight's progress, even during last
season when he started 15 of the team's 16 games. A knee strain,
shoulder injury and concussion slowed his progress and Knight did
not intercept a pass as a rookie.
</P>
<P>
   Another shoulder injury slowed him at training camp, and then a
freakish knee injury during a non-contact practice drill, sidelined
him for the past three games.
</P>
<P>
   Knight had undergone reconstructive knee surgery at Iowa, but
played his last two seasons there relatively injury-free. His
durability never had been questioned.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's extremely frustrating,'' Knight said Wednesday after he
returned to the Cardinals' first team defense in a light workout.
``Obviously, you hear all the things that come up. Maybe you don't
hear it yourself, but you turn on a radio show and a friend or
somebody else is saying, `He's always hurt.'
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing for me is to understand things are going to
happen and realize that they happen for a reason. I can't let it
become a negative thing throughout the course of my career.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals are hopeful that Knight will be ready to return to
the starting lineup Nov. 1 when they visit the Detroit Lions, a
team with one of the NFL's most explosive receiver tandems, Herman
Moore and Johnnie Morton.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals secondary coach Larry Marmie believes the team and its
fans have yet to see Knight's best.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think last year he went through the usual growing pains of a
rookie,'' Marmie said. ``At that position, you're out there
isolated. We felt he was really close to making a lot of plays.
That's the one thing we really talked to Tommy about in the
off-season. He needs to become a playmaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought he had taken a big step forward in training camp
when he hurt the shoulder, and he was really playing well before he
had the setback with his knee injury. He was making plays. That's
the encouraging thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Marmie said he feared the worst when Knight injured the knee,
especially after seeing the play on film. Knight felt the same way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hyperextended it, and the knee was kind of moving all over
the place,'' Knight said. ``After what I had gone through before
(with the knee surgery), it was very frightening. Fortunately,
nothing was torn in there and it remains stable.''
</P>
<P>
   Knight figures to be a target when he gets back into the lineup.
But then he's used to that. It comes with playing opposite a
four-time Pro Bowl selection like Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a target on his chest,'' Marmie said. ``Teams are
going to test him. They know what Aeneas can do, and they're going
to find out what the other guy can do.''
</P>
<P>
   And Knight still believes that he can do a lot more than he's
had a chance to show in his brief NFL career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to go out there this season and really make a
statement,'' Knight said. ``I felt like I was really starting to
get in a groove, play well and get the tempo. I don't think the
best of me has been on the field yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's driving me absolutely nuts sitting out. It's that same
feeling you get when you're a kid. You want to participate. Whether
it's good or bad, you want to feel like you're a part of it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
