<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SERIES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES' DREAM SEASON ENDS WITH SERIES SWEEP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1998 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Many have tried to come up with words to describe
the 1998 New York Yankees, calling them a great team, a complete
team, maybe one of the best teams ever.
</P>
<P>
   But the best way to describe the Yankees' 1998 World Series
championship can be summed up in one word.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees completed a four-game sweep of the San Diego Padres
with a 3-0 victory Wednesday night in front of 65,427 at Qualcomm
Stadium. It was the Yankees' 24th World Series title in 35
appearances. No other major league team has won more than nine
titles.
</P>
<P>
   It was inevitable because the Yankees proved a team which won an
American League record 114 regular-season games and a major league
record 125 games overall was indeed the best team in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitable because the Yankees didn't have to rely on any one
player to carry them, instead getting production from everyone on
the roster.
</P>
<P>
   Inevitable because, well, they're the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees manager Joe Torre said he didn't quite know what he had
in spring training, but he had a good idea after seeing his team
respond after struggling early in the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not until the first week of the season did I know we might
have something special,'' Torre said. ``We started out 1-4 and I
told them, `Do something about it. You've got to get angry.' And
they started playing well.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have this inner conceit. They know they're good but they
don't care about telling other people about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they showed everybody on the field, going 125-50
overall for a winning percentage of .714, the fourth highest in
major league history.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees starter Andy Pettitte, who hadn't pitched since Game 3
of the ALCS on Oct. 9, pitched seven scoreless innings before
tiring in the eighth Wednesday. Relievers Jeff Nelson and Mariano
Rivera worked out of that jam, however, with Rivera getting Jim
Leyritz on a flyout with the bases loaded to end the threat.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees scored the only run they needed in the sixth inning
when Bernie Williams, playing in what was probably his final game
as a Yankee, drove in Derek Jeter from third with a high chopper in
front of the plate.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was thrown out at first, but the Yankees had the lead
to keep. World Series MVP Scott Brosius drove in the Yankees'
second run of the game with a single in the eighth and Ricky
Ledee's sacrifice fly made it 3-0 later the same inning.
</P>
<P>
   In sweeping the series, the Yankees beat the Padres in two games
started by Kevin Brown, the hottest pitcher in baseball going into
the Series.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Pettitte who deserved most of the credit for
Wednesday's victory, pitching for the first time since the Indians
knocked him around for six runs and eight hits in 42/3 innings 12
days earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte responded with 71/3 scoreless innings Wednesday,
allowing five hits while striking out four and walking three. Brown
gave up three runs and eight hits in eight innings.
</P>
<P>
   All that's left for the 1998 Yankees is finding their place in
history. But to those in the champagne-soaked clubhouse, there is
no doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team is as good as any there's ever been, Yankees owner
George Steinbrenner said as he searched for a champagne bottle that
still had champagne in it. ``The game is so much more difficult
today to get to the next level. There are so many more steps along
the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how his team would fare against the '27 Yankees,
Steinbrenner said: ``We'd do very well against them, put it that
way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees players say their record speaks for itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the greatest team ever,'' Yankees pitcher David Wells
said. ``We've got the best record ever, that makes us the best
team. Some day, some team might pass us. But right now, we're the
best ever.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked around the lockerroom when I got here and I said I'm
lucky,'' DH Chili Davis said. ``I knew this was a special ballclub.
I was hurt most of the year, and when I was ready to come back I
walked into a team that was a moving train going full-speed ahead.
I had to run alongside to catch up. And what a ride it was.''
</P>
<P>
   As pitcher Orlando Hernandez passed out Cuban cigars to his
teammates, Steinbrenner summed it up: ``This is one of the best
teams ever in one of the best seasons ever. That's supposed to
happen to the Yankees.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
