<SLUG> BC-BBO-SERIES-PADRES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PADRES TAKE CURTAIN CALL  
 WILL FANS BE SO GENEROUS IN VOTE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ The scene following Wednesday night's final game of
the 1998 baseball season was so incredible that even longtime
baseball watchers could not recall such an outpouring of emotion
for a losing World Series club.
</P>
<P>
   With Qualcomm Stadium still nearly full after the home club had
just suffered a somewhat embarrassing four-game sweep at the hands
of the powerful New York Yankees, the masses forced the Padres
players out for one final curtain call with a steady roar, similar
to what occurs at the end of a concert.
</P>
<P>
   One by one, they players streamed out to thunderous ovations
from what can arguably be called the loudest fans in baseball.
Moments earlier, the Padres had already begun undressing. Suddenly,
they began putting on their pants again and scampering to the
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unbelievable,'' San Diego General Manager Kevin Towers
said. ``It makes you proud to be a San Diegan and be associated
with this city. Most fans would have been out the turnstiles and
headed for the freeway.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was special. With the amount of free agents (six) we have,
maybe their last thought or impression will be what you just saw.
Maybe they'll remember how special it is to play here.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Brown, who figures to be among the most wanted free agents
this winter, however, never saw the scene. Brown remained inside
the Padres clubhouse, sitting alongside reliever Randy Myers, who
was heartily booed when he entered in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Brown insists it was a memorable season for him,
one that culminated in his second consecutive trip to the World
Series. Still, the sense was he probably played his last game for
the Padres.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would have been a fairy tale ride to finish it out,'' said
Brown, who pitched for the Florida Marlins last season. ``I don't
think we have anything to be ashamed of.''
</P>
<P>
   While Brown will wrestle with his decision, nearly everyone
inside the Padres clubhouse was astonished at the fans' wanting to
see the players one more time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to get back in this situation one more time,'' third
baseman Ken Caminiti said. ``We all hugged inside the clubhouse and
felt a lot of emotion. There was a lot of love inside there.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest day in San Diego Padres history will take place in
2{ weeks when voters will be asked to help pay for a new baseball
park for the Padres.
</P>
<P>
   There is little doubt within the club's front office that
reaching the World Series was significant achievement, one that
very well could push the vote over the top for the Padres, who are
talking like they will leave town if the voters deny the new park.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not a threat,'' club President Larry Lucchino said. ``The
reality is that we need this new ballpark to survive in San
Diego.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres probably will not have to worry about the chanting
fans who remained inside the stadium more than an hour after San
Diego lost, 3-0, to the Yankees. They may as well have been
chanting ``Yes on C,'' the referendum's name.
</P>
<P>
   ``You all helped us through the season like you would not
believe,'' Manager Bruce Bochy told the crowd. ``Seeing you all
still here, it gets emotional down here. Thank you''
</P>
<P>
   It was a fitting end to a spectacularly memorable 1998 season.
The lingering memories will be of the juggernaut Yankees club. But
the scene that took place in San Diego after the game should not be
forgotten, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``These fans were great,'' Yankees Manager Joe Torre said. ``I
think they appreciated us for what we did this season. As I like to
say, we don't spike the ball. We just play the game.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
