<HEADLINE>
CATS' FOE WON'T FEAR TUCSON TRIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TUCSON, Ariz. - Northeast Louisiana is just 4{ years removed
from Division II, yet it has a schedule that Nebraska has been
known to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   The obscure school, nicknamed the Indians, plays its third
ranked team Saturday in No. 14 Arizona. It won't be in awe.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians already have played two teams that were No. 3 at the
time. They lost to Florida, 42-10, and Kansas State, 62-7.
</P>
<P>
   They're traveling west, perhaps because Nebraska couldn't fit
them in this year. But there is a payoff. Notheast Louisiana is
guaranteed $350,000, or $200,000 more than the NCAA minimum. In
part, Arizona is paying for not scheduling a home-and-home series
with the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   Northeast Louisiana is also a late stand-in for Virginia.
Orginally, the Wildcats were supposed to play at Charlottesville,
Va., this Saturday. But Arizona Coach  &UR; Dick Tomey didn't like the
idea of having to travel across the country a week after playing at
Oregon State. &QL; 
Crowd count &QL; 
An interesting statistic this Saturday will be the crowd size at
Arizona Stadium. With an obscure opponent, there are questions
about whether the Wildcats are a strong draw in themselves. In
part, the crowd will serve as measure of where the football program
stands in the public eye.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona is fourth in Pac-10 attendance. Over two home games, the
Wildcats have drawn a total of 111,372 fans, or an average of
55,686. UCLA leads with an average of 71,882. Washington is second
at 71,048 and Arizona State third at 66,602. &QL; 
Bowl roll &QL; 
The Wildcats (6-1) will qualify for a bowl with a probable victory
over Northeast Louisiana. The NCAA requires six victories for bowl
qualification. Arizona needs a seventh because it has a 12-game
schedule. But bowl talk sounds premature to quarterback &UR; Keith
Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goals are to go as far as we possibly can,'' he said. ``It
is so hard to look at a bowl game right now. You don't know what is
going to happen.'' &QL; 
Briefly. . .  &QL; 
Running &UR; Leon Callen was one of three nominees for the Pac-10
offensive Player of the Week, which went to UCLA quarterback  &UR; Cade
McNown for the second straight week. Defensive end  &UR; Mike Robertson,
a first-time starter, was nominated for defensive Player of the
Week, which went to UCA linebacker &UR;  &UR; Brendo Ayanbadejo.
</P>
<P>
   Injury report: Robertson started at Oregon State for  &UR; Joe
 &UR; Tafoya, who was suffering from back spasms. Tafoya, probably
Arizona's best defensive lineman, is questionable for Saturday.
Center  &UR; Bruce Wiggins is troubled by a bruised left shoulder.
Cornerback  &UR; LaChaux Rich, sidelined because of an ankle sprain the
past four weeks, probably will miss his fifth game. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
