<HEADER>
A0667 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN-(SLANG     10-22 0730
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGACE CARVES EARLY LEGACY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 c.1998 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SUNRISE, Fla. _ A few years back, Manny Legace was at training
camp with the Hartford Whalers, awed by his surroundings and
wondering who his roommate would be.
</P>
<P>
   He had a Sean Burke hockey card in his wallet, when in walked
his roommate ... Whalers goalie Sean Burke.
</P>
<P>
   ``He walks in,'' Legace said, ``and I said, `Wow.' I feel like a
mouse in a corner.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, with Kings regulars Stephane Fiset and Jamie
Storr sidelined with groin injuries, Legace made his NHL debut
against the Florida Panthers and their goalie, Sean Burke.
</P>
<P>
   By game's end, Legace had stopped all but one of the 50 shots
he'd faced and was the sole reason the Kings (2-1-2) escaped with a
1-1 tie in the first game of a five-game trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my dreams, I never thought I would get 50 shots,'' said
Legace, who received the approval of 17,367 at the National Car
Rental Center. ``I thought I played OK.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, he was the difference in the Kings' third consecutive
overtime game. Burke only faced 19 shots, and he made some big
saves, particularly one where he flung himself across the crease to
block a third-period shot by Yanic Perreault. But the goal he
allowed _ a first-period wraparound by Luc Robitaille in the first
six minutes _ was soft.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the ice, Legace made one save after another,
including stopping Florida rookie Oleg Kvasha from point-blank
range with less than six minutes to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unbelievable,'' Kings goaltending coach Don Edwards said,
shaking his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't like they were 50 shots here and there,'' Kings
coach Larry Robinson added. ``Some of them were point blank,
screened. He won the game for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, he didn't quite win it, but Robinson's point was clear.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson was not nearly as happy with the rest of his team as he
was with his 25-year-old rookie. Not only did the Kings manage just
nine shots in the first two periods, they had to survive eight
Florida power plays, including a 74-second two-man disadvantage in
the first period.
</P>
<P>
   The Kings have killed 28 of 29 short-handed situations in their
first five games. But the Kings' power play was 0 for 8 against
Florida and went without a shot during its final opportunity, which
came in the last minute of regulation and first minute of overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I probably have more faith in young kids than
anything else,'' said Robinson, whose team was without center Jozef
Stumpel (hip-flexor strain), defenseman Steve Duchesne (groin
strain) and winger Josh Green (shoulder strain).
</P>
<P>
   ``At least I know one thing: that they're going to give you 100
percent and they're going to work hard. That's more than I can say
for our team on most nights. And that's the most disheartening
thing for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not playing like we were last year. Last year we were
committed to playing hard for the team and proving everybody wrong
that was saying we're not that good a team. Right now, we're not
getting that commitment.''
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to Legace, however, the Panthers managed just one goal.
Dave Gagner beat him on Florida's 14th shot of the game, a rebound
from the left faceoff circle 43 seconds into the second period
after he'd stopped a shot by Gord Murphy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to give their goaltender a lot of credit,'' Florida
coach Terry Murray said. ``I'll give him a lot of marks.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one Kings teammate, center Nathan LaFayette, said he
was not surprised by Legace's performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been playing against Manny since we were 10 years old,''
LaFayette said. ``He's stood on his head every time. I wouldn't
expect anything different.''
</P>
<P>
   Legace, however, admitted he was nervous through 60 minutes of
regulation, the first 3:39 of overtime, the 20 minutes it took to
sweep up a broken pane of Plexiglas, and the final 81 seconds of
the extra period.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't sleep last night,'' Legace said. ``I got a couple
of hours, not very much. The last couple of nights have been like
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the Kings, he was wide awake Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I'd be exhausted,'' Legace said. ``When the alarm
went off this morning, I was a little tired. But when I got to the
rink, I wasn't. I'll sleep when I'm dead.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
