r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-PGA-MAGEE-AZR &LR;      10-22 0753
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-MAGEE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAPPINESS IS BEING  .  .  .  NO.  30  
 MAGEE ON BUBBLE FOR TOUR CHAMPIONSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL HUFFMAN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If golfers wore numbers on their backs like football or baseball
players _ or maybe even Brahma bulls _ Andrew Magee would be No.
30.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here he comes out of the chute . . . NUMBER 30!'' deadpanned
Magee, who finished 30th on the PGA Tour's money list last year and
is in the same precarious position with $890,702 going into this
week's final regular-season event, the Walt Disney World Classic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm like a second-string quarterback, or a great player off
the bench. I'm always the middle man, and I like it like that. I
don't want to be up there any higher (on the money list). That
would be scary. I'd have to make a lot of public appearances if I
finished better than Number 30.''
</P>
<P>
   Humor always has been Magee's defense mechanism. In the
dog-eat-dog world of professional golf, the Paradise Valley pro
stays alive by staying loose.
</P>
<P>
   But this is an extremely serious weekend of golf for Magee. Any
of the players currently sitting from No. 31 to 50 can knock him
out of next week's $4.5 million Tour Championship if they can grab
one of the top five spots at Disney, and the money adds up in their
favor.
</P>
<P>
   Magee says not finishing among the top 30 money winners ``might
get to someone else, but I'm sleeping fine these days.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps Magee, 36, is at ease because last year's season-ending
event, the Las Vegas Invitational, had such a bizarre twist. Magee
and his wife, Susan, were sitting on the couch at home watching
ESPN when the cable network announced that Magee, who had missed
the cut in Vegas, had been bumped to No. 31 by Billy Andrade. Susan
Magee's math, however, added up to a different result.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, Susan called ESPN, and a half hour later they announced
that I'd beaten Billy by about $5,'' Magee recalled. ``That shows
you how close it is in this business.''
</P>
<P>
   Just two weeks before the 1997 Tour Championship, Magee had made
a $30,000 check with a 10th-place finish at Disney, which this year
switched dates with Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I got up and down on the last hole from some ridiculous
place in the bunker to essentially earn the $5 I needed,'' Magee
said, laughing at the razor's edge that so often defines life on
tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's the story of my whole career. I'm just a
30-kind-of-guy _ the 45th-ranked player in the world. Not bad; but
not great. It's just what I am.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a tag that Magee seems comfortable with. But don't let it
fool you. He has no plans to visit Disney World on this trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year I had won about $665,000 at this point of the
season. This year I've already gone way over that,'' said Magee,
who has several second-place finishes but no victories in '98.
``Regardless of what happens, this is my best season ever
moneywise, so why should I be worry?
</P>
<P>
   ``People are so shortsighted by just looking at the money as
some kind of barometer for success. I'm trying to have a career out
here, not just a good year. I'm concentrating on the long haul.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides, the winner of four tournaments in 15 years on tour is
not the only guy on the Tour Championship bubble.
</P>
<P>
   ``First of all, I never expected that I'd be chasing Tom Watson,
who is in 29th place ($897,385), about $7,000 ahead of me,'' Magee
said. ``Apparently, Tom is not playing this weekend, so that shows
me he's got a lot of money in the bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then there is Stewart Cink, who is No. 31 ($828,835). If he
gets into the top five or six, he could knock me out. And Stewart
has a lot of incentive, because he represents East Lake (Golf Club)
in Atlanta, the site of the Tour Championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I can hope for is that I have my best stuff and pitch like
`El Duque' (New York Yankees pitcher Orlando Hernandez). That's
exactly what I'm planning to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Finishing among the top 30 money winners also has several other
perks, like automatic berths into the major championships for 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, there's that, too. I'd certainly like to pencil Augusta
(National) into my April schedule for next year,'' Magee conceded.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter how the cards fall at Disney, he plans to spend a
couple of extra days in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be the featured guest Monday night on ``Golf Talk
Live'','' said Magee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll either be a happy guy by that time, or I'll be a happy
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   For No. 30, there is no other way.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
