<HEADLINE>
TERRY LABONTE REVVING UP FOR 600TH START IN ROW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK ARMIJO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Move over  &UR; Cal Ripken Jr. and make room for  &UR; Terry
Labonte.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte's NASCAR Winston Cup record for consecutive starts
should grow to 600 on Sunday, when he is expected to take the green
flag in the Dura-Lube/Kmart 500 at Phoenix International Raceway.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte's remarkable streak began nearly 20 years ago on Jan.
14, 1979, when he qualified 25th, but finished last in the Winston
500 at defunct Riverside (Calif.) International Raceway.
</P>
<P>
   Competing in that same race was rookie  &UR; Dale Earnhardt, who
proved to be a similar iron man. Earnhardt is second all-time with
576 straight starts.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Ricky Rudd is third with 537.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really doesn't seem that long ago,'' Labonte said.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte set the record two years ago, breaking the mark held by
 &UR; Richard
 &UR; Petty, who made 513 successive starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few years ago, somebody brought it (Petty's record) to my
attention,'' Labonte said following the historic 514th start in
April 1996. ``When you start out, that's not one of the goals you
set.''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte, known as the ``Iceman'' for his low-key demeanor, was
22 when he began the record run. He'll be 42 next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big weekend for (Terry),'' younger brother  &UR; Bobby
Labonte said. ``He doesn't really get himself into predicaments
where he can get into trouble. I think it goes back to when he
worked on his own race cars.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he tore one up, he knew he'd have to fix it.''
</P>
<P>
   In honor of the expected 600th start, QVC will broadcast a live
three-hour ``For Race Fans Only' show tonight at Phoenix-based
Action Performance, Inc. &QL; 
Tire news &QL; 
Goodyear is supplying Winston Cup teams with 500 sets of tires. The
tires are essentially the same Goodyear Eagle tires used at last
year's race. The only modifications were to the left-side tires,
according to Goodyear lead engineer  &UR; Tony  &UR; Freund.
</P>
<P>
   Green-flag pit stops are expected to occur every 90-100 laps,
depending on fuel consumption. &QL; 
Pit stops &QL; 
Winston Cup rookie  &UR; Kenny Irwin, last year's NASCAR Craftsman Truck
Series rookie of the year, will be pulling double duty. He'll also
drive in Saturday's GM Goodwrench Service Plus/AC Delco 300,
driving a Cintas sponsored truck.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Mike Bliss again will drive the Caterpillar Chevrolet Winston
Cup car, replacing  &UR; Steve Grissom.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Hut Stricklin has been hired as a consultant for Winston Cup
driver  &UR; Gary Bradberry.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Gary Grossenbacher, crew chief for Winston Cup driver  &UR; Jeff
 &UR; Green, is a 1983 graduate of Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Jack Sprague holds a 28-point lead over  &UR; Ron Hornaday with two
remaining Truck Series races, the closest in series history.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, what's so special about  &UR; Jeff Gordon's 11 wins this season,
the most since  &UR; Dale Earnhardt won 11 in 1987? When Earnhardt won
his 11th race, it was the 22nd event of a 29-race season. Gordon
won No. 11 in the 30th race of 33-race season.
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget the ``Park n' Ride'' shuttle offered for Sunday's
race at Blockbuster Desert Sky Pavilion, located north of McDowell
Road on 83rd Avenue. It's $7 to park, but rides to and from the
racetrack are free. Buses begin shuttling at 7 a.m. Save yourself a
headache and ride the bus. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
