<SLUG> BC-OUT-ARIZONA-SCENIC-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GETTING AWAY FROM IT ALL  
 TONTO DRIVE WELL WORTH SOME WORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's probably the fastest way to get into the pines from the
Phoenix area. A careful driver can make it in a car. It offers
awesome views and vegetation to match. There's even a chance to
take a hike or just have a picnic.
</P>
<P>
   That's what Forest Road 201, an eight- or 10-mile stretch in
Tonto National Forest, has to offer those who wish to escape to the
high country.
</P>
<P>
   The turnoff to Forest Road 201 is located north of Sunflower on
State Route 87 (Beeline Highway) to Payson.
</P>
<P>
   The turnoff to the left is at Slate Creek Pass, which no longer
has a highway sign, but the mile marker is 225. There's a large
pull-off area to the left.
</P>
<P>
   Watch for traffic at the turnoff. Vehicles coming on SR 87 from
the north are rather blinded from the intersection.
</P>
<P>
   Once you make the turn, there's a decision to be made. The
unpaved forest road splits. Take the right fork to get on 201. A
sign marks the road.
</P>
<P>
   The road immediately begins a rise into the Mazatzal Mountains
and heads toward the Mazatzal Wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   Take plenty of warm clothes. It was cool in the Valley when we
left last Saturday morning, and it was downright cold in an open
Jeep when we started the climb toward Mount Peeley, which is near
the end of the road.
</P>
<P>
   This narrow road is spectacular. Most of the travel is on ridges
or ledges. In either case, there are steep drop-offs, sometimes on
both sides. Until you reach the pines, the terrain offers
impressive views of the Mogollon Rim, Mount Ord and its
communication towers plus the rugged Mazatzals themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The panorama offers abandoned mines and lush vegetation. It
starts with prickly pear and other desert plants, moves into an
oak-juniper-pinon environment and finally ends up in ponderosa
pines.
</P>
<P>
   The end of the road is nearly 6,000 feet above sea level. And
some of the tree leaves along the way have turned into brilliant
fall colors. Some trees are along the road, some are are in the
distance.
</P>
<P>
   In the final stages of the drive, trees form a canopy over the
road with drop-offs into heavily timbered canyons. It's difficult
to believe that such scenery can be found so close to Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Now, about the road itself. For a Jeep or truck, it is a mere
nothing. It's a little rough in spots and has some steep grades,
but four-wheel drive isn't necessary. Still, the road is so narrow
in stretches that meeting another vehicle requires some
maneuvering.
</P>
<P>
   I wouldn't hesitate to take a car, but those not used to driving
on unpaved and sometimes rough roads should be a little wary.
However, if they take it slowly, I don't believe there would be
trouble except in mud.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the road, there's a parking area cradled among the
mountains that's just made for a picnic. It's shady and beautiful.
It's also a jump-off to a number of hiking trails.
</P>
<P>
   The summit of Mount Peeley, which is more than 7,000 feet high,
is only 1.5 miles away. The first half mile is an easy hike. The
next mile rises 1,000 feet. The trail heads up a steep grade and
apparently stays that way.
</P>
<P>
   There are other, easier trails to be hiked.
</P>
<P>
   This is a tough trip to beat if you want scenery and recreation
in a single day. &QL; 
Barry Burkhart can be reached at 602-444-8454 or at
barry.burkhart(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-98 0303EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981022.0077 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 03:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0687 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-ARIZONAS-TATE-ELL     10-22 1922
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-ARIZONAS-TATE-ELLIOTT-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`TREATED LIKE A TRAITOR'  
 URBAN SCHOOL OFFERED GREENER PASTURES 
 THAN GRASS VALLEY FOR ASU'S ELLIOTT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB COHN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a novel or a movie or just something make-believe, it had it
all. Lies, rage and jealousy. A small town divided. Revenge and
accusations and, eventually, redemption. Peyton Place without the
sex.
</P>
<P>
   But the story was real.
</P>
<P>
   Chad Elliott was the main character.
</P>
<P>
   But the sordid tale has a happy ending. Elliott endured and so
did his mom and dad, who felt everything their son felt, and more.
This, after all, is what parents do. Thursday night, when Elliott
starts at quarterback for Arizona State for the first time, Evon
and Stan Elliott will be in Sun Devil Stadium watching, cheering
and perhaps reflecting on the journey they and their son had to
make to reach this moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had taken one wrong step,'' Stan Elliott said, ``he
wouldn't be there right now.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems straightforward _ a struggling, 2-4 ASU team and a
typical quarterback switch before a game against Stanford. Elliott,
the brash, confident, redshirt freshman in; Ryan Kealy, the
third-year sophomore whose confidence seemingly has vanished, out.
What's going on with Kealy is anything but simple. And so is the
sequence of events that produced his replacement.
</P>
<P>
   The price Elliott paid to position himself to get an ASU
scholarship was high.
</P>
<P>
   On Page 33 of the ASU football media guide, under the picture of
a very serious-looking Chad Elliott, is a description of his high
school career. It says he was a 1997 graduate of Grant High School
in Sacramento and lists his honors and statistics, including the
3,150 yards, the 69 percent completion rate, the 47 touchdowns and
the three interceptions that helped produce a 12-2 record and a
sectional championship.
</P>
<P>
   There is brief mention of what he did his junior year, but
nothing about it being spent at Nevada Union High School, which
serves the twin towns of Grass Valley and Nevada City.
</P>
<P>
   Grass Valley, not Sacramento, is Elliott's hometown, a
postcard-pretty community in the northern California pines about an
hour from Lake Tahoe. Prospectors used to come there for the gold
buried in its mountains. It is where Evon's parents own a grocery
store. Evon Elliott is fourth-generation Grass Valley.
</P>
<P>
   It is also where some considered Chad Elliott to be a turncoat
for switching high schools. His family was ridiculed and scorned.
Tires were slashed, and private investigators looked into the
Elliotts' finances, poked through their garbage, talked to their
neighbors and likely followed them around.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of cruel things that happened,'' Evon Elliott
said.
</P>
<P>
   All because her son wanted to throw the ball, to go deep, to use
his strong right arm and quick wits to the fullest. This, after
all, is what quarterbacks do. And he got to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had my days where I was not very happy, crying,'' Evon
Elliott said. ``I was very upset that high school football could
get this far off the track.''
</P>
<P>
   The story begins during Elliott's junior year at Nevada Union.
The previous season, Elliott led the Miners to a championship, but
then he got hurt and was becoming increasingly frustrated with
Coach Dave Humphers' effective but conservative Wing-T attack.
Elliott knew the only way to attract college recruiters was to show
his stuff, and he couldn't do it there. Besides, Elliott was
somewhat of a rebel and wise guy. He and Humphers were starting to
get on each other's nerves. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Change of scenery &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   About 60 miles away in the Del Paso Heights section of
Sacramento sits Grant High School. It is everything Nevada Union is
not. It is predominantly Black as opposed to all-White. It is
bordered by concrete, not trees and mountains. Its coach, Mike
Alberghini, likes to pass. And he hired as quarterbacks coach a
Grant alum named Aaron Garcia, who was good enough to play
quarterback at Washington State before Drew Bledsoe.
</P>
<P>
   ``My parents knew it would be best for me to go to another
school and hope to get a scholarship out of that,'' Chad Elliott
said. ``At least give me a chance where I can shine, because all I
was doing at the other school was handing off.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant High School's No. 1 rival is Nevada Union, and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   Alberghini, the coach at Grant, knew about Elliott. Knew him? He
defensed him the previous two years. He admired his athletic
ability, respected how he would take a hit and get right back up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put relentless pressure on him,'' Alberghini said, ``and he
never broke down.''
</P>
<P>
   But when he heard from Stan Elliott, ``I thought it was a
joke,'' Alberghini said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look where he grew up,'' he said. ``It was practically
all-White, a mixture of pretty affluent people who had chosen to
move to the hills and get out of the city, and people who had lived
there all their lives. Our school is 83 percent minorities.
Predominantly Black. Samoans. Hispanics. Most of the White kids are
Russian immigrants. It was complete culture shock.''
</P>
<P>
   Alberghini wanted to test the Elliotts' sincerity, so he told
them Chad would have to enroll for the spring semester of his
junior year. He did that. Chad also would have to take a geometry
class in summer school and participate in a summer ``passing
league.'' He did that, too, making the hour-plus daily commute.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when I knew what kind of character he had, what kind of
person we had,'' Alberghini said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Unrest in Grass Valley &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Grass Valley, the reaction was somewhat less than
enthusiastic. Some of the residents, in fact, were irate. It wasn't
enough that Elliott left, but that he went to Grant, of all places.
An undercurrent of racism already tinged the rivalry, and now this.
People wondered aloud why parents would send their son to a school
where he would need a bulletproof vest, why a family would move to
a bad place with gangs.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, many supported the move and understood the
motives. And Evon Elliott wants it made clear she does not want the
people of Grass Valley portrayed as racist. But, she said, ``There
is some backward thinking there.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't long before stories about Elliott surfaced, how he was
uncoachable, a problem. Sure, Elliott said, sometimes he'd irk the
coach by wearing a hat in class or by not wearing a tie when he was
supposed to. But it was all small stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Not so, Humphers said at the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was benched several times for greater offenses than that,''
he told the ``Sacramento Bee'' in October 1996. ``But I'll not drag
a 17-year-old kid through the mud. I just want to leave it alone
and let him play.''
</P>
<P>
   A message left on Humphers' answering machine at Nevada Union on
Tuesday was not returned. &QL; 
Accepted and rejected &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Elliott to be eligible to play for Grant, he and his family
had to establish residency in the school district. So they rented
an 700-square foot apartment from which Stan, a building
contractor, and Evon, who works in her parents' store, commuted to
Grass Valley and back each day. Their other son, Alex, then 11,
stayed in Grass Valley and came down to Sacramento on weekends.
They kept their house.
</P>
<P>
   It was expensive and a little cramped, ``but it was kind of nice
to have a smaller place,'' Evon Elliott said. ``In a bigger house,
sometimes kids find their own sanctuaries.''
</P>
<P>
   At Grant, Elliott was ``fully accepted in a minute,'' Alberghini
said. Throwing to receivers such as Dante Stallworth, who wound up
with a scholarship to Tennessee, Elliott had a huge season. The
Pacers finished 12-2 and won a sectional title.
</P>
<P>
   One of the losses was to Nevada Union, 21-19, in its first
return to Grant's field since a shooting incident caused games to
be moved from Friday nights to Saturday afternoons. Elliott
completed just 8 of 20 passes for 155 yards and was knocked around
quite a bit.
</P>
<P>
   The real pain came after the game when he was ignored by friends
and former teammates, many of whom he played football with since
the age of 8.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was hard for him,'' Evon Elliott said.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was treated as a traitor,'' said Alberghini.
</P>
<P>
   Once, when Elliott went back to watch a Nevada Union game,
somebody slashed his tires. &QL; 
 &QL; 
A wonderful `melting pot' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But Elliott was growing as a football player, and in ways more
substantial than that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how wonderful it was,'' Evon Elliott said of
the family's move to Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it would be a good experience for my son. We lived in a
predominantly White area. Here he was, about to be 17, and he'd
rarely seen any other races in our area. It was beneficial in so
many ways. He made so many lifetime friends. It was good. Football
was good. Relations were made.''
</P>
<P>
   Evon Elliott said her son regularly brought teammates home for
dinner, and even now she sends care packages to Dante Stallworth in
Knoxville.
</P>
<P>
   ``It helped me a lot,'' Chad Elliott said. ``College is a
melting pot, a bunch of different cultures and people, and it
helped me get ready for that.''
</P>
<P>
   After the season, Stan, Evon and Chad returned to Grass Valley,
but Chad finished out the school year, driving up and down the
mountains each day. ASU assistant coach Phil Snow had noticed
Elliott and began recruiting him hard. Quarterbacks coach John
Pettas joined the effort. They were virtually the only ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``People at his old school were disgruntled and were telling bad
stories about him,'' Pettas said. ``So we investigated his
character. We thought he was a good kid.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliott committed to ASU before Christmas. One reason was,
``They stuck by me,'' he said. ``I was getting recruited a lot and
all of a sudden some would drop off. My quarterback coach called
the colleges and asked why. They said the coach of my previous high
school said I was a bad kid and don't recruit me. But ASU stuck by
me.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
Digging up garbage &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, another investigation was taking place. In February
1997, the ``Bee'' reported that the Nevada Joint Union High School
District was checking to see if the Elliotts failed to maintain a
full-time residence in Sacramento. That would strip Grant of its
title and Elliott of his records. The newspaper also reported that
private investigators were hired to follow Elliott and his family.
That was denied. But neighbors were interviewed, credit checks were
made and the Elliott's garbage rummaged through.
</P>
<P>
   It also was a fact that Nevada Union High School sent a letter
of inquiry to Grant. Both principals would not comment, but Nevada
County superintendent of schools Terry McAteer called the whole
thing a ``mess,'' and added, ``It's really sort of sad when a
school district sanctions private eyes going through people's
garbage.''
</P>
<P>
   The investigation produced nothing but harder feelings and a
lawsuit against the school district filed by the Elliotts. No
improprieties were found. Chad Elliott's records stood. Life goes
on, and folks calmed down.
</P>
<P>
   Elliott enrolled at ASU and during his first year, Evon Elliott
moved again, this time to Chandler for six months to help her son's
transition. After Elliott's success at Grant, the same people in
Grass Valley who decried his leaving now looked at him ``like I had
done something special,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If all is forgiven, who knows? If Elliott can lead the Sun
Devils out of the doldrums and becomes the college quarterback he
thinks he can be, they might have a parade for him. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
