<SLUG> BC-FBC-BOIVIN-PAC10NOTES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAC-10 STILL ATTRACTIVE TO OUTSIDERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the temptation of greener (as in money) pastures, the
Pac-10 continues to be courted by universities who want to join.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego State recently invited the conference's athletic
directors and media to tour its state-of-the art facilities. Rumors
of interest from programs including Colorado and Brigham Young have
kept talk of Pac-10 expansion alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're closely monitoring the landscape from a national
perspective,'' Arizona State Athletic Director Kevin White said.
``There are no evident moves on the horizon, but it would be less
than honest to say we weren't paying attention to other
conferences.''
</P>
<P>
   The popular notion is this: When the Big 10 adds a 12th member _
Notre Dame being its No. 1 choice _ other major conferences will
respond accordingly, and the Pac-10 would add two more schools.
</P>
<P>
   The hottest names out there include Colorado, Texas, BYU and
Utah. Although the latter two are moving to a new conference in
1999, Cougars Athletic Director Rondo Fehlberg acknowledged,
``We'll always do what's in our best interest. If's there's a
better alternative, we'll listen.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest argument for expansion is income opportunity.
Greater market size and penetration means bigger dollars.
</P>
<P>
   While the Pac-10's revenues have increased 115.3 percent since
1990, the 12-team Southeastern Conference's revenues are up 261.3
percent during the same period.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents argue that dividing the pie 12 ways would mean less
revenue than expected. Traditionalists wince at the thought of
enlarging the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not something we're pursuing, but, sure, it's often a
topic of discussion,'' said Jim Muldoon, Pac-10 assistant
commissioner
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to understand the lure: tradition and success. Pac-10
teams won 11 NCAA championships last season. Additionally, the
conference grossed $15.8 million in bowl revenue, which was divided
among its schools. The Western Athletic Conference, by comparison,
brought in $2.1 million. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Around the Pac &QL; 
 &QL; 
When Chris Sailer missed a 21-yard field goal at the end of
regulation against Oregon last Saturday, he had a horrible
flashback to a moment at practice two weeks earlier.
</P>
<P>
   He accepted a challenge from a local TV sports anchor to kick
field goals of 25 yards. He won, but tweaked a groin muscle in the
process and didn't kick in practice for the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not the smartest thing I've ever done,'' he told the Los
Angeles Times.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for Sailer, he hit a 24-yarder in overtime to lift
UCLA and keep the Bruins in the national championship picture.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA linebacker Brendon Ayanbadejo said the Bruins remind him of
another Pac-10 team not so long ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, we do look like that Arizona State team,'' he said.
``They pulled it out no matter what. We have the same spark of a
champion, like ASU in '96.''
</P>
<P>
   Southern California Coach Paul Hackett provided some bulletin
board material for UCLA when he called Oregon, the Trojans'
opponent Saturday, ``the best team in the conference.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, he said, ``I don't know if anything can be put on the
bulletin board to affect that rivalry. We're going to play UCLA in
the distant future, so I can't worry about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Quote of the week &QL; 
 &QL; 
``Basically, I think you can pray all you want, but God's not going
to help you make a block or run the ball. If you're not ready to
play, praying's not going to help you.'' _ USC guard Travis
Claridge, on his team's decision to pray before and after each game
in the locker room. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Paola Boivin can be
reached at paola.boivin(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
