<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-TRIAL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MICROSOFT CITES NETSCAPE E-MAIL AT ANTITRUST TRIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
    WASHINGTON _ Microsoft assailed the credibility and motives of
Netscape _ its big Internet software rival and the linchpin of the
government's antitrust case _ by revealing Wednesday a 1994 e-mail
from Netscape co-founder Jim Clark asking Microsoft to buy a stake
in his company.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The e-mail undermines the government's key charge that Microsoft
first approached Netscape, at a controversial meeting in June 1995,
about selling a stake in the company in return for an agreement to
cede the bulk of the browser market to Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   On the third day of the landmark antitrust case, Microsoft used
the e-mail to ridicule the government's argument that the software
giant illegally exploited its dominant Windows computer operating
system and attempted to drive out its competitors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to work with you,'' Clark told top Microsoft
executives in the Dec. 29, 1994, e-mail. ``Working together could
be in your self-interest as well as ours. Depending on the interest
level, you might take an equity position in Netscape with the
ability to expand the position later.''
</P>
<P>
   By owning part of Netscape, Clark implied, Microsoft could
venture into the market for Internet browsers without competition
from the then-industry leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have never planned to compete with you,'' Clark said in the
e-mail. ``We want to make this company a success, but not at
Microsoft's expense.''
</P>
<P>
   Lead Microsoft attorney John Warden asked Netscape chief
executive officer Jim Barksdale, the government's key witness,
whether the message laid the groundwork for the June 1995 meeting.
Barksdale denied that the e-mail had any effect. ``It was not
consistent with my company's strategy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Barksdale, who did not work for Netscape at the time Clark wrote
the e-mail, said he did not learn of the offer until he was
preparing for trial. He also said it was not discussed at the
subsequent meeting with Microsoft, and Barksdale said Clark in
retrospect ``described this (e-mail) as a moment of weakness.''
</P>
<P>
   Clark's message ended with a note that no one else at Netscape
knew about the offer.
</P>
<P>
   At a courtroom break, Netscape lawyer Christine Varney told
reporters that the e-mail ``was in no way related to this June
conversation'' and that Clark wrote the e-mail at 3 a.m. when he
was ``a little nervous'' because startup Netscape was short on
cash.
</P>
<P>
   Lead government attorney David Boies told reporters he will show
that Microsoft rebuffed the offer and never referred to it at the
June meeting. ``This has nothing to do with the case,'' Boies said.
``It's another attempt by Microsoft to change the subject.''
</P>
<P>
   As Warden meticulously picked away at Barksdale's 127 pages of
written testimony, the two parried in testy exchanges. Barksdale
seldom offered information beyond what Warden directly asked, often
adopting a folksy Southern demeanor while appearing painfully
obtuse.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Warden, a thick-set New York attorney with a
booming voice, asked Barksdale whether he had seen certain magazine
reviews of Microsoft's Internet Explorer.
</P>
<P>
   Holding the reviews in his hand, Barksdale asked if he was
supposed to turn the page. Warden barked, ``The first page after
the cover, yes!''
</P>
<P>
   Warden continued to attack the government's claim that Microsoft
used illegal monopoly tactics to gain market share in browsers by
``bundling'' Explorer with Windows.
</P>
<P>
   He suggested that Netscape's own plan all along was to give away
its browser for free, as it is now doing, as a promotional device
to get people to use other high-margin Netscape products, such as
its Internet servers.
</P>
<P>
   Warden cited quotes from Netscape executives in a
soon-to-be-published book saying that Netscape's strategy was to
make the browser ``free but not free,'' a tool to entice new
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Barksdale snapped, ``I have never heard this term, `free but not
free,' '' adding that Netscape ``emphasized market share, but we
were also running a business where we had to meet payroll. . . . We
didn't consider that then, now or ever to be a viable business
strategy.''
</P>
<P>
   Warden also attacked Barks-dale's contention that Microsoft's
free browser distribution hurt consumers and innovation or
precluded anyone from using Netscape's browser.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't it true that any home user of a personal computer
connected to the Internet can freely choose at no cost to use
Netscape's Web browsing software?'' by downloading it from the
Internet, Warden asked.
</P>
<P>
   Barksdale bristled, calling the question biased. ``Most people
don't go to the trouble to do it,'' he replied. ``They are free to
walk down to the store and buy a new Edsel, but they don't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Warden ridiculed Barksdale for complaining about Netscape's
market share slide from 85 percent in 1996 to 54 percent last
month. ``What was GM's market share before Japan started selling
large numbers of automobiles in this country?'' Warden asked,
before Boies objected.
</P>
<P>
   Warden also attacked Barksdale's assertion that Microsoft
hobbled innovation and hurt consumers. ``Would there have been
greater innovation if you had maintained your 85 percent market
share?'' Warden asked.
</P>
<P>
   Barksdale insisted that if Netscape had been able to continue to
charge for its browser, it would have had more money to invest in
research and that other companies, seeing a profit opportunity,
would have invested more as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``So consumers are not better off getting a browser for free
than getting a browser they would have had to pay for in your
hypothetical world?'' Warden asked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
