<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 03:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0722 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GYMNAST-LAWSUIT-SFCHR     10-22 1154
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GYMNAST-LAWSUIT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLYMPIC GYMNAST SAYS PARENTS HAVE SPENT ALL HER MONEY 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOAN RYAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
    Until this week, Dominique Moceanu's life story seemed to
unfold like a script. Her parents, former Romanian gymnasts, had a
plan. ``I made a commitment,'' her father once said, ``that my
first-born, boy or girl, would be a gymnast. It was an unfinished
dream.''
<TEXT>
<P>
   The girl won the U.S. championship at age 13 and an Olympic gold
medal at 14. She smiled through it all, publishing an
autobiography, gracing the cover of Vanity Fair and the pages of
Time and People magazines and leaping across the TV screen in ads
for Kodak.
</P>
<P>
   Now, just weeks after turning 17, U.S. gymnastics' brightest
star has jolted friends and fans with a lawsuit that contends that
her parents have squandered both her fortune and her childhood,
pushing her relentlessly to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   Moceanu ran away from home Sunday, hired a lawyer and petitioned
the District Court of Harris County, Texas, to be declared
independent of her parents. A judge signed a temporary restraining
order Monday saying that Dumitru and Camelia Moceanu must stay away
from their daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It always had to be about the gym,'' the gymnast said of her
parents. ``I would think, `Don't you guys know anything besides
gymnastics? Can't we go out for ice cream? Can't you be my mom and
dad instead of me being your business?' . . . They haven't been
working since 1996. Where does their income come from? Me.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, an upset Dumitru Moceanu held a press conference at
his lawyer's office, saying that he and his wife only wanted the
best for their daughter. He said his wife was so distraught that
she could not leave the house. Dumitru Moceanu declined to say much
about a trust fund that his daughter says is all but depleted, but
he confirmed that it was set up so she would have access at the age
of 35. Dumitru Moceanu pleaded for his daughter to come home and
resume training.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love her very much,'' he said, crying. ``She's just a
child, she's just a minor. I don't believe this comes from her. It
comes from other people.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Dominique Moceanu's lawsuit, her father has wasted
money she earned since turning professional at age 10. But the
teenager told the Houston Chronicle on Tuesday that the problem is
about much more than money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never had a childhood,'' said Dominique Moceanu, who began
training at age 3 and never took a vacation until after the 1996
Olympics. She regularly put in seven- to nine-hour days in the gym,
six days a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always was in fear because I would get yelled at by my
father, and I would say to myself, `I'm 13 years old, come on.'
Instead of talking to me, they're always yelling with me, fighting
with me.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Olympics approached, she stopped going to school because
it interfered with gymnastics. She was home-schooled with
videotapes and books. Her relationship with her parents
deteriorated.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Moceanus opened a $4 million gym in Houston with
some of their daughter's money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things have been getting rough for a while; a lot of people
don't know,'' said the teenager, who won the all-around gold at the
Goodwill Games in New York in July. ``We've been trying to keep
things hidden.'' She admitted that her father has hit her ``a
couple of times.''
</P>
<P>
   Dominique Moceanu has a 9-year-old sister who is also training
in gymnastics. The gymnast told the Houston Chronicle that she does
not want to see her sister go through the same problems.
</P>
<P>
   Dominique Moceanu's unhappiness came to a head over the weekend
when her father reportedly threatened to fire her coach,
26-year-old Luminita Miscenco, a Romanian immigrant who is credited
with reviving Moceanu's career. Miscenco apparently had advised
Moceanu to look more carefully at her finances. With Miscenco by
her side, Moceanu called her attorney from a shopping mall Sunday
and asked to meet with him. She has since been living with friends.
</P>
<P>
   The gymnast and her lawyer, Roy W. Moore of Houston, both
declined to say how much money she has earned or how much has been
lost. But Moore said the trust that had been set up for the gymnast
is all but gone.
</P>
<P>
   Some gymnastics observers were surprised but not shocked by the
young gymnast's revelations. Gymnastics, figure skating and tennis
_ sports in which girls can become the best in the world at very
young ages _ have seen their share of athletes crumble under the
pressure from parents and coaches, from the strain on their
still-growing bodies and from the often unrealistic expectations of
fans and the media.
</P>
<P>
   Several years ago, tennis player Mary Pierce filed a restraining
order against her father, who was also her coach, saying he
physically abused her. Apparently no other athlete, however, has
legally tried to separate from his or her parents, though some
child acting stars, such as Macaulay Culkin, have done so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that on the outside Dominique always looked happy, but
I think she looked happy because she (ital) wanted (ital) to look
happy,'' said former Olympic gymnast Kathy Johnson, now a
television commentator for Turner Broadcasting. When an 11-year-old
Dominique Moceanu was crying during a workout at the U.S. Olympic
Festival, Johnson told her to relax and just have fun. ``She looked
at me like this was some foreign advice,'' Johnson said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   USA Gymnastics, the sport's national governing body, which has
been buffeted by charges in recent years that it was not doing
enough to protect its young athletes, had little to say of
Dominique Moceanu's situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to be as supportive as we can to Dominique,'' said
spokesman Craig Bohnert. ``It's unfortunate when you see any parent
and child resort to legal means (to resolve their problems). . . .
This is such a fresh story we haven't had an opportunity to see if
there's something we could have done, or could do in the future, in
a situation like this.''
</P>
<P>
   Dominique Moceanu has been hiding from her parents for the past
few days, moving from house to house to stay with friends. To gain
legal adult status, her attorney said, she must prove that she is
living away from home and can support herself. Her hearing is set
for Nov. 11. If the status is granted, she will be able to demand
an accounting of her money through legal channels. She does not
turn 18 until Sept. 30, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Some observers say they cannot imagine a court denying her
petition. If she is adult enough to support her family financially
for the past several years and to put in 30- to 50-hour workweeks
since she was a young child, who can tell her she's not adult
enough to begin living her own life?
</P>
<P>
   (Joan Ryan is the author of ``Little Girls in Pretty Boxes: The
Making and Breaking of Elite Female Gymnasts and Figure Skaters.'')
</P>
<P>
   (Chronicle wire services contributed to this report.)
</P>
</TEXT>
