<SLUG> BC-BBO-WORLD-SERIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES TOP OF THE HEAP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ The New York Yankees have put the final touches on
their seasonlong aura of invincibility, leaving absolutely no doubt
who has the best baseball team in the world.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees did so by completing a four-game sweep of the San
Diego Padres with a 3-0 victory in Game 4 of the World Series last
night at Qualcomm Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Pettitte outpitched Padres All-Star Kevin Brown by throwing
four-hit, shutout baseball for 71/3 innings, giving the Yankees
their record-extending 24th World Series championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you could truly win a championship for a city to appreciate
and enjoy, it's there in New York,'' said third baseman Scott
Brosius, who was selected the Series most valuable player.
``There's no better place to win it all. I look forward to the
parade.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the Yankees' 24 World Series winners, this club could go
down with the 1927 Yankees of Babe Ruth and Lou Gehrig and the
Mickey Mantle-Roger Maris edition of 1961 as one of the greatest
teams ever because few teams have been so dominant throughout the
season. The Yankees won an American League-record 114
regular-season games and 11 of 13 playoff games.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is we were 125-50, and not many teams can say
that,'' shortstop Derek Jeter said. ``So I think you can argue that
we're the best team of all time. We came to play every day, and we
played with an intensity level I've never seen before.''
</P>
<P>
   They also put to rest the notion that their regular season would
not be validated if they stumbled in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won 114 games, and it would have been, in its own right, a
wonderful accomplishment,'' Yankees manager Joe Torre said. ``Then
you get into postseason, and you get through the first round and
then the second round, and you think you're going to enjoy the
World Series. But the more you win, the more people expect you to
win. The thing that concerned me the most was not winning the World
Series and having someone look down at their nose at what we
accomplished.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees don't have to worry about that. They really never
did stumble, except perhaps when they lost two of the first three
to Cleveland in the American League Championship Series. They've
won seven in a row since then.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is great,'' first baseman Tino Martinez said. ``People
were picking us to win the World Series by the All-Star break. To
finally fulfill all those high expectations is a great feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Fulfillment finally came when reliever Mariano Rivera, who had
retired Jim Leyritz on a liner to center field with the bases
loaded and two out in the eighth, got pinch hitter Mark Sweeney on
a grounder to Brosius for the final out in the ninth. He
immediately pointed both arms to the sky and was soon buried under
an avalanche of joyous teammates.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees kept up their pitching-mound celebration for about
10 minutes while the vast majority of the crowd remained behind
chanting ``Padres, Padres.'' It was a fitting tribute to a gutsy
team that upset the Houston Astros and Atlanta Braves in the
National League playoffs but couldn't figure out a way to beat the
titans from the other league.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, pitching on three days' rest, matched Pettitte for five
innings before the Yankees broke through in the sixth. Jeter beat
out an infield single, raced to third on Paul O'Neill's double and
scored on Bernie Williams' high chopper to third. They added two
more in the eighth, which was more than enough. Pettitte combined
with Jeff Nelson and Rivera for the Yankees' fourth postseason
shutout.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have no weaknesses out there,'' Padres manager Bruce
Bochy said. ``They have starting pitching, relief pitching, and
everybody in that lineup does a great job. I have to tip my cap to
them; they're one of the best teams ever assembled.''
</P>
</TEXT>
