<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLASS-COLUMN-$ADV25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: TEENS AS ECONOMIC DRAGON SLAYERS
 &HT;    For release Sunday, Oct. 25
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Not long ago, the mother of a daughter about to
turn 16 called National Public Radio's ``Car Talk'' with a query:
Should the $35,000 BMW 328i she and her husband were buying as a
birthday gift come equipped with a 5-speed manual transmission or
with an automatic shift?
</P>
<P>
   ``Car Talk's'' hosts told the caller she was nuts for having
chosen such a machine for a teenager who had just gotten her
driver's license. By turns, Tom and Ray Magliozzi sought to steer
her toward a better choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``She'll be so disappointed,'' the caller finally said. ``She so
had her heart set on that BMW.''
</P>
<P>
   Such big-ticket purchases serve as one of the final bastions of
parental discretion in an era when teenagers increasingly make
their own buying decisions. That fact is evident in the line-up of
programs being aired in the new fall television season: Beleaguered
by a splintering market, the networks are locking onto an
ever-younger audience.
</P>
<P>
   A 30-second commercial on CBS's top-rated ``60 Minutes'' costs
about $250,000 to air. For about the same amount of money, but for
half the audience share, an advertiser can buy a spot on ``Dawson's
Creek,'' a series being aired by WB that features the sex lives of
small-town teens. (The initials stand for Warner Bros., the folks
who run it.)
</P>
<P>
   After three years on the air, WB has yet to earn a profit. But
as a recent report in the Washington Post notes: ``WB has drawn
ratings among young viewers this fall that rival those of ABC, NBC,
CBS and Fox _ quite an achievement, given that WB is carried mostly
on weak UHF stations and still can't reach about 10 percent of
households nationwide.''
</P>
<P>
   Small wonder advertisers are hooked: Marketing studies show that
teens are a highly brand-loyal bunch. More than half purchase the
same brand on two out of their last three shopping trips, across
all brand categories.
</P>
<P>
   Teenage disposable income has also risen steadily through the
golden '90s. These funds currently average $75 a week, gleaned
mostly through part-time jobs and parental allowances. And nearly
all the money is spent rather than saved, mostly on clothing,
health and beauty aids, and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, the nation's 30 million teens deliver some $110
billion a year to retail marketers. They also have what one
marketeer, a firm named ``MarketSource,'' calls ``a persuasive
influence on $150 billion'' in additional family purchases.
</P>
<P>
   The firm's own sales pitch, posted on the Internet, reports:
``Teens are independent, experimental, materialistic, and extremely
difficult to reach through traditional media outlets.''
</P>
<P>
   At this rate, at the next meeting of the Federal Reserve Board,
perhaps Fed chairman Alan Greenspan will praise teenage buying
habits for having averted a recession.
</P>
<P>
   As the father of a 21-year-old who plans to leave the family
``payroll'' next May when he graduates from college, let me voice
my gratitude for having made it through those tough years without a
having bought him a BMW or watching ``Dawson's Creek,'' let alone
``Buffy the Vampire Slayer.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass is a Washington, D.C.-based columnist for Cox
Newspapers. His e-mail address is aglass(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
