<DOCNO> NYT19981022.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 10:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1016 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-GIRLS-NYTSF     10-22 0944
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-GIRLS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG GIRLS DON'T CRY
</HEADLINE>
  By Fay Weldon 
 346 pp. New York: Atlantic Monthly Press. $24 
 ------ 
 THE WOMEN'S ROOM 
 By ELIZABETH GLEICK 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The date is 1971; the place, the middle-class London home of
Stephanie and Hamish and their two children, Rafe and Roland. A
group of women _ ``five furies in the front room'' _ have gathered
for that quaint get-together of the past, a consciousness-raising
session. Upstairs, their consciences distinctly unraised but their
consciousnesses tingling, Stephanie's husband, Hamish, and her
friend Daffy are getting it on. But never mind that: downstairs,
history is being made. As the women plow through bottles of cheap
wine and make boldly original pronouncements along the lines of
``The personal is the political'' and ``Men have art, women have
babies,'' they decide to form their own publishing company, Medusa.
To celebrate this decision, they dance naked around the living
room.
</P>
<P>
   Stephanie, Layla, Alice and Nancy _ the group that eventually
runs Medusa _ are the key ``big girls'' of Fay Weldon's latest
novel, ``Big Girls Don't Cry,'' and given that Medusa sounds
suspiciously like the British publishing house called Virago, their
real-life counterparts may all be out there somewhere. But it isn't
necessary to decode this roman a clef in order to enjoy it. Part
ensemble piece (following the fortunes and misfortunes of its
characters from 1971 to the present) and part feminist primer,
``Big Girls Don't Cry'' cruises through the decades, aided by a
chatty narrator with a well-honed sense of irony and a knack for
telescoping history. Here, for instance, is one of Weldon's sly
then-and-nows: Back in the early 70's, Stephanie and Hamish were
``not very happy living together,'' she writes, ``but the custom of
the times also suggested that this was just the way things were. .
. . The human right to veracity and authenticity in personal
experience was not yet established. To be 'happy' was no one's
quest, simply to get by was enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the novel, Weldon asks _ and attempts to answer _ two
loaded questions: What were the early feminists thinking? And was
the women's movement really worth it? By way of response, she toys
with our preconceived notions, flipping them, then flipping them
again. After Daffy and Stephanie have an argument, the narrator
notes: ``In those days, it was generally accepted that in any
quarrel over a man the women were to blame. The woman who lost him
had 'failed to keep him.' The woman who won him had 'led him on.'
The man stood centrally, smiling, erect, free from accusations.''
How very unfair, the reader thinks _ only to stumble, a few
sentences later, on this: ``Now yet again the gender switch has
operated. If in doubt, blame the man.''
</P>
<P>
   In their decades-long quest for both happiness and political
equality, Weldon's characters trade sexual partners and sexual
preferences with abandon. Stephanie dallies in radical lesbianism;
Layla makes Medusa her life; Alice, after pioneering the whole idea
of ``gender studies,'' gets sucked up by the New Age; and Daffy is
stuck raising Stephanie and Hamish's boys. Weldon's fiction is not
known for its subtlety _ in her last novel, ``Worst Fears,'' a dead
husband turns out to have been not merely unfaithful but
grotesquely unfaithful _ yet we come to care about the fates of
these women and their various offspring both for the ideas they are
meant to represent and for who they are.
</P>
<P>
   And it's a good thing, too, since Weldon never really resolves _
as if anyone possibly could _ the contradictions wrought by
feminism. At times she appears to yearn nostalgically for a simpler
era when the world was more ``erotic, supercharged: composed of
polarities. . . . He, she. Hard, soft. Think, feel.'' At others she
wants to be sure we don't forget the sacrifices made by her
heroines. Toward the end of the novel, Layla, childless and
dissatisfied, considers selling Medusa. ``Feminism, the bloodless
revolution,'' she mutters, lying in the bed of her longtime married
lover. ``The casualty rate was high. Suicides, the collapse of
relationships; so many of us alone, because who would put up with
us, and how could we put up with them? When every casual word is .
. . assessed for correctness, life gets exhausting.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Weldon's satirical breeziness can be infuriating, it's
always entertaining. Those who think that 1971 was not so long ago,
that things haven't changed all that much, have another think
coming. As do those who think the battle is over. ``Well, we're
sorry,'' Weldon writes, in a scene in which a selfish young woman
proves immune to the demands of the sisterhood. ``Every generation
must apologize to the future, and the greater the change that was
brought about, the profounder the apology needs to be. . . . Let
the feminists apologize for the death of love, lost children and
the diminishing of man.'' Whew! Then, just in time, Weldon steps
back from the brink of heresy: ``But what was a girl to do? Someone
has to reform the world. You can't see what you see and do
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   In our passionate and often blinkered debates about the legacy _
even the survival _ of feminism, at least Weldon can be counted on
for one rare quality: in her hands, nothing, truly nothing, is
sacred.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Gleick is a London-based contributor to Time and other
magazines.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
