<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-GOOD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOO GOOD TO BE FORGOTTEN
</HEADLINE>
  Changing America in the '60s and '70s 
 By David Obst 
 282 pp. New York: John Wiley &AMP; Sons. $24.95 
 ------ 
 ZELIG'S BACK 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When it comes to publicity, David Obst ought to know a thing or
two. He's been a literary agent, a writer, the head of a news
service and _ who could forget ``Revenge of the Nerds''? _ a
Hollywood producer. And while this memoir of the 1960's and 1970's
was still in galleys, Obst's name began infiltrating gossip columns
and getting dropped at Georgetown dinner tables. Because Obst, who
acted as literary agent for Bob Woodward and Carl Bernstein when
they sold their book proposal for ``All The President's Men,''
reveals that Deep Throat did not exist.
</P>
<P>
   Or at least he doesn't believe that Deep Throat existed. Obst
emphatically asserts that his clients created a composite character
(Woodward has denied this equally emphatically) in order to sell
more books and befriend Hollywood. In fact, he writes that he was
shocked to hear the Deep Throat character in the film admonish his
reporter to ``Follow the money.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Interestingly enough, that line is not to be found in the book
version,'' Obst writes. You mean _ Gracious me! _ Hollywood isn't
faithful to the letter? (Hasn't he seen ``Up Close and Personal''?
And, heck, who has ever seen a newspaper reporter who looked
anything like Robert Redford?)
</P>
<P>
   But Obst often adopts the tone of the ingenue _ as if to
recapture the wide-eyed idealism of his youth _ in this sometimes
amusing but frequently frustrating personal history. Obst says he
was born in 1946, but he also says his mother was pregnant with him
a month after D-Day, so we can't be sure how accurate a historian
he is to begin with. Nevertheless, he styles himself as a classic
baby boomer. Raised in California, he grew up with school air-raid
sirens, polio and the cold war. He studied at Berkeley, lived in
Southeast Asia, protested the Vietnam War, hung out with Abbie
Hoffman and dropped acid. His book, he writes in the introduction,
is ``about being a baby boomer, about how the emergence of the
youth culture, the Vietnam War and Watergate left their imprint on
our generation. . . . It's the story of how we almost succeeded in
stealing America from the grown-ups, were beaten back, and, by the
inexorable process of aging, became those very adults that we used
to make such great fun of.''
</P>
<P>
   I know, I know. At this point, you're thinking, ``Shouldn't I
just go rent 'The Big Chill' instead?'' But Obst did achieve some
measure of fame as a savvy operator with a good market sense for
the times. In the 1970's, he found himself heading a news service
that, because of his truly creditable and enterprising efforts,
distributed Seymour Hersh's Pulitzer Prize-winning acount of the My
Lai massacre. He met Daniel Ellsberg, who entrusted him with a set
of the Pentagon Papers, and whom he represented for a later book
deal. He began a career as a literary agent in Washington; he is
now a writer and producer, and lives in Santa Barbara, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Because ``Too Good to Be Forgotten'' is so self-adoring, it
probably should have been subtitled ``How I Changed America in the
60's and 70's,'' but Obst does spin a few good yarns. When Abbie
Hoffman doses him with LSD at the 1972 Republican National
Convention in Miami, he describes the surreal scene: thousands of
Republicans are chanting ``Four more years! Four more years!'' but
he is so acid-addled that he hears ``You're in fear! You're in
fear!'' and flees to try to hide on the bottom of a swimming pool.
</P>
<P>
   However, the book is less a rousing portrait of a generation
than a retread. Despite Obst's Zelig-like appearances at some
fascinating historical junctures, he begins each chapter with a
list of that year's most popular movies, record albums and
television shows. Why waste the space? You get the sneaky feeling
that it's because he was a peripheral player and needed some stuff
to fill.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Obst's painfully didactic prose would be better off on
one of those coffee mugs you get for giving money to public
television. At the house _ actually, ``domicile'' _ of a high
school friend, ``minds were like parachutes: They only functioned
when they were open.'' When President Kennedy was murdered, ``it
was like something within us had also been assassinated.'' Obst's
generation was ``inculcated with the idealism of a limitless
future.'' The historian Taylor Branch is ``a true wordsmith.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington is _ of course _ ``the belly of the beast.'' During a
news conference ``expletives were hurled,'' (which begs the
question: when can we start just throwing them, or saying them?).
And, oddly given his P.C. mien, Obst refers to Asia as ``the
Orient.'' And as for his freewheeling California youth, when it
came time to lose his virginity, he didn't want to do it in the car
because that was ``both unsafe and uncomfortable.'' (The beach, by
the way, had ``sand and fleas, and so forth and so on,'' so that
was out, too.)
</P>
<P>
   This all makes for a pretty lackluster tribute to the baby
boomer generation. Perhaps readers should bear in mind that Obst
may have brought up the subject of Deep Throat's identity so that
he'd have a hook upon which to hang an otherwise flimsy piece of
work.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Alex Kuczynski covers the magazine industry for The Times.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
