<HEADLINE>
BOOKS IN BRIEF: UNIVERSITY PRESSES FICTION
</HEADLINE>
  (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 RADIANCE 
 By John J. Clayton 
 Ohio State University, paper, $12.95  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Middle-aged, focused hazily on the middle distance of their
comfortable lives, most of the men in this collection of stories
have their eyes jarred joyously, then painfully, open. In
``Glory,'' Avrom Hirsch, mourning the death of his best friend, is
seized by glimpses of a shimmering connection between the living
and the dead. In ``Open-Heart Surgery,'' an emergency operation
leaves Ned Koenig feeling naked afterward, his heart rawly
vulnerable to the love and hurt around him. And in ``The Man Who
Could See Radiance,'' Peter Weintraub glances into the unguarded
eyes of a stranger on a Boston trolley and loses all sense of a
barrier between himself and others. Back at work, he sidles closer
to a man he loathes just to feel his waves of pulsing life, ``a
humming like when he stood at night outside a Con Edison plant -- a
kid, summertime, doors open and the turbines humming like a giant
chorus in all registers, and it seemed they were producing the
energy that made the earth turn and the trees grow.'' Wives,
children and co-workers think these guys have snapped. But John J.
Clayton sees his reluctant Jewish prophets as wildly lucid, drunk
on spirituality in a secular world that needs each one of them to
be a mensch -- narrowly focused, a pillar of strength for his
family. Writing with compassion, simplicity and power, Clayton
adjusts their visions just enough so they can find the way home. _
PATRICK FARRELL
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A VIEW FROM THE MANGROVE &QL; 
 &UR; By Antonio Benitez-Rojo &QL; 
 &UR; University of Massachusetts, $24.95 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``A View From the Mangrove'' is the final part of a trilogy by
the expatriate Cuban writer Antonio Benitez-Rojo in which he sets
out to investigate the history and culture of the Caribbean using
three different genres. Thus the short stories in this collection
can be read as companion pieces to his novel ``Sea of Lentils'' and
his book of essays ``The Repeating Island.'' Not surprisingly, this
new volume (translated by James Maraniss) covers a wide historical
range, from the 16th century to the mid-20th; some of the material
is based on actual records, some has been fictionalized to resemble
fact. Here Benitez-Rojo chronicles events of unremitting and often
unspeakable horror -- slave trading, invasions, mutinies,
rebellions, murders. His stories are dense with disaster and rich
in description. The characters seem to exist only in extremis,
dying in despondency and despair or in false glory. They are either
mysterious and foreign to one another or brothers in suffering.
Ambition motivates them all -- hypocritical priests, opportunistic
scoundrels, even a few doomed romantics. In Benitez-Rojo's view,
the truth is often more contradictory and confusing than fiction,
and in both it is difficult to tell the defeats from the triumphs,
the pious from the godless, the honorable from the unworthy.
History is what is written down, an orderly procession of events
leading to a specific outcome -- to a duel, to the establishment of
trade, to the political division of an island. These stories
persuasively present the improbable swirl of action out of which
that history is confidently fabricated. _ BARBARA FISHER
</P>
<P>
   &UR; TELL ME EVERYTHING &QL; 
 &UR; And Other Stories &QL; 
 &UR; By Joyce Hinnefeld &QL; 
 &UR; Middlebury/Bread Loaf/University Press of New England, $17.95 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Joyce Hinnefeld's strong debut collection portrays in spare,
haunting prose the lives of women of different ages and
backgrounds, all of whom feel trapped in various female roles.
``What Alma Knows'' is a particularly successful story about a
self-described ``spinster'' aunt, ignored by her relatives;
unhappily, her attempt at revenge during a Christmas party winds up
endangering the one family member she cares about. ``Echo Guilt''
subtly describes a wife who increasingly loses all ambition as her
husband's professional success grows. The yuppie narrator of ``The
Slow and Painful Demise of the American Family'' cannot quite
accept her destiny -- to marry her boyfriend and become a housewife
in the suburbs -- but fears any other possibilities. In ``Speaking
in Tongues,'' a teen-age girl deeply troubled by her sexuality
fantasizes about Jesus and Mary Magdalene. Unfortunately, other
stories -- including the title story and the four brief poetic
sketches that divide the book -- are simply too elusive.
Interestingly enough, the best entry, ``Stories About Miranda,''
has the only male narrator in the collection. He is Rumer Rutledge,
a 21-year-old flasher who is urged by a hospital psychiatrist to
talk about his mother, Miranda, a fat, 45-year-old doll collector
who never brushes her hair or changes out of her baby-doll pajamas.
``The truth is,'' Rumer reluctantly admits, ``Miranda herself is a
pretty interesting story.'' And he turns out to be right. _ JENNY
MCPHEE
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-BRIEFS-FICTION-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: right. _ JENNY MCPHEE)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE SHADE OF BLOSSOMS &QL; 
 &UR; By Shohei Ooka &QL; 
 &UR; Center for Japanese Studies/University of Michigan, cloth, $28.95;
paper, $12.95 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shohei Ooka's novel about a bar hostess in postwar Tokyo is a
bracing alternative to the more familiar geisha stories that have
appealed to romantic American readers. Published in Japan in 1961
but untranslated until now, ``The Shade of Blossoms'' focuses on an
aging woman named Yoko and her various lovers: Matsuzaki, an art
history professor with a wife and child; Takashima, a shady
antiques dealer; Shimizu, a television producer who likes older
women; and Hata, a widower intent on finding a new bride. Yoko has
recently switched bars, with a promotion in rank, but her beauty is
fading and she has few prospects. Unlike many other hostesses, she
won't simply settle for the first man who comes along -- or the
fourth or the fifth. In Dennis Washburn's smooth translation, the
novel displays the subtleties of a sector of Japanese culture ruled
by sexual courtesies. Yoko has a definite sense of self-esteem,
which makes her romantic entanglements and spiritual descent all
the more affecting. _ DAVID GALEF
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE LOSS &QL; 
 &UR; By Vladimir Makanin &QL; 
 &UR; Northwestern University, cloth, $44.95; paper, $14.95 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Russia's writers have always been her most prescient observers.
And now that Communism lies in ruins, it is the writers who are
best at expressing the uneasiness of a new era -- no longer
silenced by ideology but as troubled as ever by the trepidations of
modern life. Byron Lindsey's translation of ``The Loss,'' a novella
and two short stories by Vladimir Makanin, is a revealing
contribution to the literature of the former Eastern bloc. Makanin,
who was banned for many years under Brezhnev, has flourished since
glasnost, winning the first Russian Booker Prize in 1993 and
creating a stir with each new work. (His 1995 story, ``The Prisoner
From the Caucasus,'' included in this volume, is a fine example,
capturing the raw nerves on both sides of the war in Chechnya.)
Distinctive for its layered narrative and existential musings, the
title novella, ``The Loss,'' is a retelling of a centuries-old
legend about a bungling boozer who is determined to dig a tunnel
under the Ural River. With a ragtag cast of helpers, he devotes
himself to this ill-fated pursuit, even as the story's narrator,
lying in a 20th-century hospital bed, tries to dig deeper into his
own childhood memories and connect with this mythic past. Finally,
yet another narrator, intoxicated by the sweet, melancholy wine of
loss, picks up the story -- and, ``searching for a certain
confluence of things,'' gently places it down at the site of his
vanished ancestral village. _ ANDERSON TEPPER
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
