<HEADLINE>
BOOKS IN BRIEF: UNIVERSITY PRESSES NONFICTION
</HEADLINE>
  (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 THE CAT AND THE HUMAN IMAGINATION 
 Feline Images From Bast to Garfield 
 By Katharine M. Rogers 
 University of Michigan, $29.95  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Katharine M. Rogers recognizes the paradox of the cat: though we
may live for years with our beloved pet, we may never truly know
it. Instead, we are led to imagine. Perhaps we see in its searching
stare a ``preternatural knowledge,'' in its stealthy movements a
tendency toward artifice, or in its antiauthoritarian disposition a
rejection of bourgeois values. In ``The Cat and the Human
Imagination,'' Rogers examines the progression of our cultural
understanding of the cat. Her insightful exploration, which begins
with ancient Egypt and ends with the present day, attempts to
explain why and how certain artists and thinkers -- among them
Tintoretto, Poe, Dickens, Jean-Jacques Rousseau, Mark Twain,
Baudelaire, Renoir and (of course) T. S. Eliot -- have embraced the
image of the cat. Rogers charts the historical development of
feline representations as the ``insignificant domestic animal''
becomes ``a treasured and mysterious companion.'' Her book
catalogues not only artistic but also linguistic, folk and
religious perspectives relating to cats. Threaded throughout are
Rogers' arguments about why some people hate cats, why cats are
``successful rivals to dogs'' and why discussions of cats often
``slide automatically into comparisons with women.'' The book --
sheer catnip for the intellectual feline lover -- implies that
whether we consider it a symbol of the home, a paragon of
independence, an agent of evil or a cherished friend, the cat will
remain in our cultural imaginings for centuries to come. _ ZOE
HELENA RICE
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SLAVE IN A BOX &QL; 
 &UR; The Strange Career of Aunt Jemima &QL; 
 &UR; By M. M. Manring &QL; 
 &UR; University Press of Virginia, cloth, $47.50; paper, $14.95 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'se in town honey,'' Aunt Jemima announced in early
advertisements for the pancake mix that has borne her name and
image since the 1890s. This apocryphal figure has always provoked
resentment among black people, and understandably so, as M. M.
Manring points out in ``Slave in a Box.'' Aunt Jemima was
cartoonish at best and demeaning at worst, starting life, Manring
writes, ``as a white man, in drag, wearing blackface, singing on
the minstrel stage.'' The odd twists of Aunt Jemima's career took
her to many advertising pages of women's magazines as well as to
the 1893 World's Fair stage and hundreds of county fairs, where a
former slave and her successors were hired to portray her. She
still adorns the Quaker Oats pancake, waffle and syrup containers,
though today she is thinner and stylish, wearing earrings instead
of a bandanna. ``Who cares?'' Manring asks, and then ably shows why
so many people did and still do, regarding Aunt Jemima not as a
neutral part of the consumer landscape but as a damaging racial
image. From the start, the Aunt Jemima advertising campaign
``traded on themes of racism and sexism, on a relentlessly
sentimental and unrealistic portrait of slave life and Old South
hospitality,'' Manring, an independent scholar in Columbia, Mo.,
writes. Though repetitive, ``Slave in a Box'' is absorbing in its
thickly and thoughtfully layered analysis of the mammy whose
pancake mix, the ads promised, ``made women womanly, men manly and
turned boys into Eagle Scouts.'' _ ANDREA HIGBIE
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ALL-AMERICAN ANARCHIST &QL; 
 &UR; Joseph A. Labadie and the Labor Movement &QL; 
 &UR; By Carlotta R. Anderson &QL; 
 &UR; Wayne State University, $34.95 &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A generation's distance no doubt helped Carlotta R. Anderson
avoid the dangers of settling grudges or idealization in writing an
affectionate portrait of her grandfather, Joseph A. Labadie, a
flamboyant, genial labor organizer and a starry-eyed anarchist.
Labadie (1850-1933) was an American original whose life spanned the
country's transition from agrarian to urban. Growing up in Michigan
and Canada before the Civil War, he absorbed Ojibwa ideas of
community and shared property that shaped his political philosophy.
As a young itinerant printer, he observed the wretched working
conditions of immigrant laborers, and the sight turned him into one
of Detroit's earliest union organizers. In his prime, Labadie
helped organize the Knights of Labor, worked tirelessly on behalf
of the fledgling American Federation of Labor and wrote for
countless short-lived labor papers, his columns generating ``a
predictable surge of apoplectic rebuttal.'' As conservative
personally as he was radical politically, he was a devoted husband,
a loyal friend, a natty dresser and, in time, such a well-known
local icon that he received mail addressed to ``Joseph A. Labadie,
Detroit, Mich.'' A born mischief maker, he once put anarchist
stickers on his outgoing mail and sat back to watch the uproar when
the Post Office refused to deliver it. Labadie, the dogged
anarchist, was married to Sophie, an equally dogged archivist who
saved the voluminous papers that form the core of this biography.
Though her subject is interesting, Anderson's biography is marred
by excessive detail and hampered by irrelevant tangents. Subject,
biographer and labor history would have been well served by an
equally dogged editor. _ LAURA GREEN
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-BRIEFS-NONFICTION-2NDTAKE--NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: editor. _ LAURA GREEN)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BASEBALL AND THE LAW &QL; 
 &UR; By Roger I. Abrams &QL; 
 &UR; Temple University, $27.95 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``The history of organized baseball and the legal process is a
story about people and institutions,'' Roger I. Abrams writes.
``From the outset, the legal process played an important role in
transforming a pastime, a summertime amusement, into a commercial
venture, run not by the talented young men who played the game but
by the entrepreneurs who supplied the capital.'' Starting with John
Montgomery Ward (the Columbia Law School graduate who pitched for
the New York Giants and organized the first players' union in 1885)
and ending with Judge Sonia Sotomayor of Federal District Court in
Manhattan (who forced an end to the baseball strike of 1994-95),
Abrams, the dean of Rutgers Law School, focuses on the checkered
history of the reserve system, which bound a player to a franchise
in perpetuity: how Napoleon Lajoie evaded the system, how Curt
Flood unsuccessfully challenged it, how Andy Messersmith and
Carlton Fisk won arbitration claims that brought it down. On the
management side, Branch Rickey earns notice for developing the farm
system (as well as for bringing Jackie Robinson to Brooklyn) and
Kenesaw Mountain Landis for the despotic, extralegal power he
wielded as commissioner. The Supreme Court, Abrams suggests, has
generally erred by confusing the game and the business of baseball.
In 1922, Justice Oliver Wendell Holmes, writing for a unanimous
Supreme Court, held that baseball, unlike vaudeville, was not
interstate commerce and hence was exempt from antitrust law.
``Legal Bases'' ranges from Honus Wagner to the Wagner Act, names
the four lawyers in Cooperstown's Hall of Fame (Rickey, Ward,
Miller Huggins and Hughie Jennings) and reveals that Chief Justice
William Howard Taft, in his less ponderous days, played third base
for Yale. The book reflects its author's experience as a baseball
salary arbitrator, balancing anecdotes with antitrust analysis and
overviews of the collective bargaining process. Wearing lightly his
notable learning, Abrams writes with verve and intelligence. _
ALLEN D. BOYER
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FORGIVE US OUR PRESS PASSES &QL; 
 &UR; Selected Works by Daniel Schorr, 1972-1998 &QL; 
 &UR; Edited by Matthew Passmore and Chip Robertson &QL; 
 &UR; O'Brien Center for Scholarly Publications/Hastings College of the
Law/University of California, paper, $14.95 &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; More than 50 years in the news business has brought Daniel Schorr
some enviable enemies (the Kremlin, the CIA, the FBI) and some fans
willing to nominate him for journalistic sainthood. In ``Forgive Us
Our Press Passes,'' a collection of 21 homilies on the news media,
Schorr, now a senior news analyst at National Public Radio,
forgives the sins of others, including two former employers, CBS
News and CNN. He forgives even Richard M. Nixon, who put him on the
``enemies list'' and during Watergate ordered an investigation of
Schorr that was cited in the ``Articles of Impeachment'' report
that preceded Nixon's resignation. And yes, Schorr confesses his
own sins -- once he withheld a story that probably would have
prevented thousands of Jews from slipping secretly out of the
Soviet Union; at another time he asked CBS News to pull back a
sensational story about European royalty. He makes clear that
integrity -- not some textbook version of objectivity -- has always
been his primary obligation, and requires that he offer an
uncompromising version of himself as well as the news. _ FORD
BURKHART
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
