<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 10:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1021 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-CASANOVA-NYTS     10-22 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-CASANOVA-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CASANOVA IN LOVE
</HEADLINE>
  By Andrew Miller 
 272 pp. New York: Harcourt Brace &AMP; Company. $23 
 ------ 
 THE RAKE'S PROGRESS 
 By LORNA SAGE 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Death, ``ultima linea rerum,'' wrote Casanova in his ``Histoire
de Ma Vie.'' Which may be roughly translated as ``Death is the
bottom line.'' Going back over his life as a seducer, gamester and
confidence man, he saw his whole career to be a pursuit of the
absorbing freshness of sensation, of the art of living in the
moment. His answer to Descartes was, ``I have lived because I have
felt.'' Writing it out, he relived it a little in his bleak and
bilious old age. (``By recollecting the pleasures I have had . . .
I enjoy them a second time.'') He confessed, but didn't repent a
jot. And if he was making a bid for immortality, he denied it: ``I
have lived without dreaming that I should ever take a fancy to
write the history of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   For Casanova, writing was a bit like death. But Andrew Miller's
second novel, ``Casanova in Love,'' takes the old boaster up on his
declared love of life and yet more life _ his picaresque ethic of
onward, ever onward, let's jump in the coach and gallop off to the
next episode _ to make him a writer manque much earlier in the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Miller does have some clues to go on, some threads to tease out
and unravel from his man's own story. Death caught up with the
historical Casanova 200 years ago, in 1798, when he was 73; but it
was, he said, on his trip to England in 1763 that he began to die.
``What a change was worked on me in London, though I had attained
the age of 38. Here closed the first act of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   England is largely a write-off for Casanova _ he doesn't speak
the language, they use paper money to gamble instead of gold and
his main amorous adventure turns into a humiliating farce when
Marie Charpillon and her mother and aunts and grandmother _ a
household of harpies he'd already come across once in Paris _ trick
him into investing in their fake elixir, the Balm of Life, in
exchange for the never-fulfilled promise of possessing the young
woman he refers to simply as ``the Charpillon.'' She becomes an
object of obsessive pursuit; he buys her many times over without
getting anywhere. In fact, she works a mirror image of his own kind
of sting, gives him pause, reveals an edge to the world that he
just may fall off. He won't adventure farther west. (He travels
next to Moscow.)
</P>
<P>
   Miller treats the ``real'' Casanova of the memoirs as a kind of
moral flat-earther who tried to deny his London revelation. In
Casanova's own account, he turned his back on his obsession, simply
wore it out like an old coat. His final gesture before crossing the
Channel was to buy a parrot, teach it to say (in French, of
course), ``The Charpillon is a bigger whore than her mother,'' and
put it up for sale for 50 guineas on the Exchange. In Miller's
novel, Casanova teaches his bird to say ``Je t'adore.'' Here his
decay (and reconstruction) is far advanced; he is becoming deeper
and more mysterious to himself, a student of pain. He is also
becoming a would-be novelist and playwright _ and a day laborer and
a country dweller _ none of which he was in reality. The apocryphal
English life that Miller gives to his hero alienates Casanova from
his own habits, his language for living, and turns him into a
citizen of a new world where change is serious. This is no land for
libertines; it's an alien, earnest place. For Miller's Casanova, it
is indeed like dying and going to hell, if hell is ennui, the loss
of your appetite for more:
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes he envisaged a hell tailor-made, as all hells should
be, in which he rattled from city to city . . . pursuing women,
pursuing money; never at peace, never still, never able to put his
feet under the table and say 'This is Home.' An eternity of faro
games and lewd outings, of lecherous old ladies, jealous husbands,
of vermin and insatiable sisters.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Casanova in Love'' might well have been called ``Casanova in
England,'' for it records a conversion to the recalcitrant, ambient
real, for all the world as if the country itself were a kind of
pragmatical penance. Miller's Casanova meets Dr. Johnson at Inner
Temple Lane. In the house Casanova rents somewhere in the West
Country, he savors the death-in-life aura of rural existence: ``On
the walls of the corridors were pieces of shot fauna and paintings
of country scenes, of . . . hounds larking woodenly beside their
expressionless young masters. . . . The two sides of the L formed a
kind of courtyard and a walnut tree grew and a sundial stood dumb
under the clouds. . . . Everywhere there was the smell of mice, of
too much weather.'' This is the style of sensation Miller revels in
as a writer _ the frisson of mortality and the sense of being a
stranger in nature.
</P>
<P>
   Miller's much-praised first novel, ``Ingenious Pain,'' also set
in the 18th century, on the dark side of the Enlightenment, had the
same sort of plot: the awakening of sensibility in a temperament
that had previously been immune, untouched, never taking experience
in as experience. In that book, the hero was a freak of nature, a
man who couldn't feel physical pain until it was awakened in him by
a witch. Here the elusive Charpillon performs the same agonizing
operation on Casanova, rescues him from the theatricality of his
world by revealing to him how very threadbare it is.
</P>
<P>
   Miller bends his subject against his own grain by first making
him bored (``nothing now but 20, 30 more years of being Casanova'')
and then taking him out of himself, setting him slumming,
experimenting with these other lives he never had. If you stand
back, it's implausible to a degree. But that's precisely the
confidence trick Miller is so good at, conjuring the phrases that
get sensation onto the page, keeping you in obsessive, close-up
focus, whether you're with Casanova in old age in his ``Bohemian
boneyard, tangling place of the winds'' or London, ``that bruised
honeycomb of a town,'' which becomes a replica of Venice,
Casanova's home, when the streets are flooded in a freak downpour.
It's no accident that this Casanova is reborn as a writer: ``Over
Venice too the sun was rising and a boy would open his eyes and
find himself possessed of a world in which almost anything might
happen, like a writer leaning over a sheet of paper . . . his mind
suspended in the intoxication of the possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Life rolled off the real Casanova like water off a duck's back.
Miller's Casanova, ingeniously translated to our own fin de siecle,
is a New Age narcissist _ so observant, so chastened, that
self-love can save him after all.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Lorna Sage teaches at the University of East Anglia in Norwich,
England.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
</TEXT>
