<HEADER>
A1024 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-BAY-1000&AMP;ADD-     10-22 1659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-BAY-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MY YEAR IN THE NO-MAN'S-BAY
</HEADLINE>
  By Peter Handke 
 Translated by Krishna Winston 
 468 pp. New York: Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux. $30 
 ------ 
 THE PLOT NEVER THICKENS 
 By LEE SIEGEL 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine a cross between Holden Caulfield and Bertolt Brecht, and
you'll have a sense of the Austrian novelist, playwright and
screenwriter Peter Handke, whose alienation from the phony and
harmful adult world is as pure as his esthetic purity is
purposefully alienating.
</P>
<P>
   Handke first attracted attention in 1966 when he ambitiously
denounced Gunter Grass, Heinrich Boll and others for, as Handke saw
it, compromising the novel by pressing it into the service of
social criticism. Like certain French novelists and theorists who
were active at the same time, Handke believed that the novelist had
to enact the radical subjectivity of perception. Novelists should
do this, he argued, by registering, austerely and precisely, the
world of experience as it is grasped by the conscious mind.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of molding character, Handke folded character into
language's fluttering veils; instead of constructing a plot, he
noted life's plotlessness; instead of telling a story, he
(eventually) began to tell a nonstory about how a writer goes about
storing up sense impressions for the telling of a story.
</P>
<P>
   As it happened, Handke ended up writing social criticism with a
vengeance. Throughout the turbulence of the 1960's and 70's, he
composed plays like ``Kaspar,'' which has society brutally
manipulating the protagonist by means of language and convention.
Handke's novels from that period were, however, subtler creations.
``The Left-Handed Woman,'' ``The Goalie's Anxiety at the Penalty
Kick,'' ``Short Letter, Long Farewell,'' though to some degree
time-bound tales of angst, have a pained, mysterious beauty. Their
alluring tension lies in the little war they prosecute between
eloquence of expression and rage at the loss of meaning. (Handke
writes a gorgeous, mesmerizing German, simultaneously winding and
spare.)
</P>
<P>
   Memorable writers always have a countertendency pushing their
dominant tendency into richer realms. In the 1970's, Handke's
unsettling fiction had his narrative powers pushing against his
philosophically grounded self-consciousness. The result on the page
was the spectacle of ordinary life alternately bruised and
entranced by ultimate questions.
</P>
<P>
   But in the 1980's, with ``Slow Homecoming,'' ``Across'' and
``Repetition,'' Handke mostly abandoned his storytelling impulse,
as well as the atmosphere of suspense that thrived uncannily in his
work without the dramatic occasion for suspense. These qualities
gave way to layers of reflection on meaning, on language, on the
act of reflection itself. Such heightened self-consciousness was
partly due to Handke's involvement in filmmaking. In the 1970's,
Wim Wenders directed a screen version of ``The Goalie's Anxiety at
the Penalty Kick,'' and Handke himself filmed ``The Left-Handed
Woman.'' Later, Handke co-wrote the screenplay for Wenders's
``Wings of Desire,'' a stunning movie about angels who descend to
earth. Film's contraction of expansive meaning into an arresting
image and its shuffling of time frames into an eternal present
tense seemed to sharpen Handke's impatience with traditional
literary techniques.
</P>
<P>
   What all this led to was the old post-modern cul-de-sac.
Handke's distrust of storytelling brought him to an exhaustive
scrutiny of his own experience as a storyteller. It was as if, for
Handke, the conventions of fiction had long silenced the writers of
fiction. No longer, in Handke's view, would they be forced to
imagine other people's stories. Novelists, he declared, have their
own stories to tell. They will speak truth to fiction! Thus
Handke's novel ``The Afternoon of a Writer,'' which appeared in
English in 1989, offered the tremendously unexciting account of . .
. the afternoon of a writer.
</P>
<P>
   ``My Year in the No-Man's-Bay,'' first published in German in
1994, is a sequel to ``The Afternoon of a Writer.'' And it takes up
the meditation on writing fiction that Handke also pursues in his
essays.
</P>
<P>
   The novel's structure is as breathtaking as its content is
taxing. Shortly before Easter, a 55-year-old writer sets out to
recall the yearlong artistic and spiritual ``metamorphosis'' he
underwent two decades earlier in the same suburb where he currently
lives. (His name is Gregor Keuschnig _ Gregor K. for short _ meant
as a jab at Kafka, one of Handke's pet aversions.) Gregor,
obviously a stand-in for the author, first came to the suburbs, he
tells us, because he had grown disaffected with the city and with
the country's natural landscape, which have provided the setting
for the traditional novel.
</P>
<P>
   Gregor has chosen to live in a suburb just outside Paris. He
uses the French word for ``suburb'': banlieue, which could mean
``outlaw place.'' Thus the novelistically neglected universe of the
suburb is, for him, the perfect spot to discover a ``New World,'' a
pristine terrain unpolluted by the linguistic and narrative
conventions of traditional fiction. (Apparently, there are no
Updikes or Cheevers in France or Austria.) For this reason, he
considers the suburb more of a ``no-man's-bay'' _ a nameless body
of water _ than inhabited land.
</P>
<P>
   GREGOR writes at length about the writer's quandary. He explains
that he feels most connected to people when he is away from them.
Absence refreshes his imagination the way nameless things replenish
his language. So after recalling his life up to the year of
metamorphosis _ 1999, to be exact _ he imagines the stories of
seven traveling friends and of his peregrinating son, Valentin.
After these brief accounts, Gregor again sets about trying to
describe the year of metamorphosis. But he really can't. He gets
too absorbed by what he calls ``prehistories.'' So he describes the
decade leading up to the special year. When he gets down to the
year itself, he gets sidetracked once more and recounts preceding
events.
</P>
<P>
   By the time he arrives at the novel's last section, ``The Day,''
you realize that Gregor has collapsed all time together. The year
of metamorphosis could be the year he is writing about, or it could
be the year he is writing in. It could, for that matter, be the
year of his friends' and his son's journeys, since they all amount
to pilgrimages that end in metamorphosis.
</P>
<P>
   And because shapeless life itself has constantly intruded on and
become part of Gregor's project of recollection, the act of writing
and the act of living have blended into one. After all,
``no-man's-bay'' in German is Niemandsbucht, and Buch means
``book.'' Thus the boundary between the territory Gregor the writer
lives in and the territory he imagines is of no consequence.
Writing, for Gregor, is the writer's ``synchronized breathing,''
his oneness with the objects he observes. He is convinced that only
a precise description of experience filtered by perception can
outlast the fluidity of time and identity.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-BAY-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: and identity.)
</P>
<P>
   THAT is why ``My Year in the No-Man's-Bay,'' when not taken up
with Gregor's interminable introspections, consists of one
carefully observed image after another expanding into a
cinematically eternal present tense. (Krishna Winston's clumsy and
overliteral translation doesn't help make such tedious cataloguing
more interesting.) In a sense, then, Handke's novel is an argument
for the superiority of film to the novel.
</P>
<P>
   Though at times intellectually bracing, this can make for pretty
arid reading. And Handke's attempts at elevating his epic of
self-regarding banality often make matters worse. Rejecting
character, plot and psychology as mere fictions, he relies on an
ostentatious thematic framework that winds up being more
implausible than any old-fashioned novelistic trick.
</P>
<P>
   To be fair, there are some fanciful touches that work
wonderfully well. Heraclitus, who believed that life is perpetual
flux, is one of the novel's presiding spirits. One illustration of
such flux is Gregor's Catalonian wife, Ana, whose palindromic name
hints at the way she storms in and out of his life on an infinite
wave of passion.
</P>
<P>
   But Handke's organizing allusions are mostly strange,
narcissistic embellishments. His esthetic rebellion has overripened
into spiritual pretension. He likens both Gregor and Valentin to
Christ. He invokes St. Paul and St. John again and again as kindred
spirits, and he identifies Gregor's metamorphosis with Christ's
resurrection. After celebrating the writer's ability to conjure
away time, Handke has a prophetic character make a speech at the
novel's conclusion proclaiming that ``a savior of mankind would be
the great forgetter.'' Having reduced the tale to the teller,
Handke seems to have acquired a messiah complex.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he has taken the deserved success of ``Wings of Desire''
a little too seriously. Throughout the novel, references to angels
and wings abound. When Handke wants to suggest a character's
spiritual breakthrough, he says that he is buoyed up by ``balls''
of air ``rolling in his armpits.'' Such airborne imagery is the
cloying conceit of a still very alienated, though now
much-rewarded, author.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, one realizes that every character in this book
resembles Gregor or refers to a character in Handke's previous work
_ or is so impossibly abstract as to be a figment of Gregor's
imagination. Trying to slay the novel, Handke has almost entirely
killed off the human element in his fiction. His angels need to be
rescued by people.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Lee Siegel is a contributing editor at The New Republic.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
