<HEADER>
A1025 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-BILLINGS-NYTS     10-22 1164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-BILLINGS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACCOMPLISHED IN ALL DEPARTMENTS OF ART
</HEADLINE>
  Hammatt Billings of Boston, 1818-1874 
 By James F. O'Gorman 
 Illustrated. 291 pp. Amherst: University of Massachusetts Press.
$39.95 
 ------ 
 CLASSICS ILLUSTRATED 
 By SUZANNE STEPHENS 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Fame does not guarantee immortality. An artist renowned in his
or her lifetime may be obliterated from history books. That is the
case with Hammatt Billings, a 19th-century artist, architect and
designer. Yet, as James F. O'Gorman points out in ``Accomplished in
All Departments of Art: Hammatt Billings of Boston, 1818-1874,''
this now-forgotten man was once thought a genius.
</P>
<P>
   Billings was impressively versatile. He designed churches,
commercial buildings, colleges and houses in and around Boston. He
also created furniture, organ cases, statuary, monuments (like the
National Monument to the Forefathers at Plymouth) and even
fireworks. He illustrated the first edition of ``Uncle Tom's
Cabin'' in 1852, along with books by Hawthorne, Alcott, Whittier
and others. And he drew historical scenes for magazines, painted
portraits and rendered urban vistas for various publications. Ralph
Waldo Emerson cited ``Billings the architect'' among a group of
Boston notables including Horatio Greenough, Daniel Webster and
Margaret Fuller. James Jackson Jarves, a collector and critic,
extolled Billings for ``the fine taste, imagination, fancy and pure
feeling'' of his illustrations.
</P>
<P>
   So why did this ``jack-of-all-designs'' disappear from public
memory? O'Gorman chooses not to speculate much about the weak link
between fame and immortality but presents a well-documented
argument for Billings's place in the history of culture. He almost
drowns the reader in facts to prove his case, but the exacting
effort is buttressed by his conviction that this range of
accomplishment makes Billings as deserving of our interest as
esthetic triumphs would have.
</P>
<P>
   His goal reflects an increasingly influential orientation in
historical research. It questions the canonization process,
postulating that immortality has been determined too often by the
selective vision of scholars who construct a unified narrative of
development. That narrative generally values those who are first or
foremost in new ideas, forms, materials and techniques. Those whose
work does not ``represent the cutting edge of architectural
innovation and achievement'' are given short shrift. O'Gorman
suggests, ``We owe it to the past and to ourselves to at least
begin our interpretation with what the past thought about itself.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Gorman, who teaches art history at Wellesley College, also has
another mission: his interest in Billings was sparked in the 1970s
by the research of a student in architectural history, Lee Ann
Clements. Her untimely death spurred him to enlarge the
investigation, conducted over the last two decades while he wrote
on other architects like the superfamous H. H. Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Howland Hammatt Billings did not come from the patrician
set of Bostonians. His family had operated a tavern in Milton,
Mass., since the 17th century. The oldest of six children, he
apprenticed himself to a Boston illustrator, Abel Bowen, and by 18
was working for Asher Benjamin, a respected neo-classical
architect.
</P>
<P>
   His success as an illustrator owed something to his just being
in Boston _ in the 1850s the cultural center of America and home to
a great array of book and periodical publishers. In architecture
Billings often collaborated with his younger brother, Joseph, who
evidently had a background in civil engineering. By 1846, when
Billings was only 28, he and his brother had completed the Boston
Museum on Tremont Street. The precisely articulated arch-windowed
granite structure represented a ``fine early example of the
Renaissance Revival in America,'' O'Gorman writes, and contained
one of the ``most dramatic interiors of mid-19th-century Boston.''
Unfortunately, it was demolished in 1903.
</P>
<P>
   Other architectural commissions demonstrated Billings's command
of assorted revival styles from Greek to Gothic, as well as
Picturesque. Yet many of his 52 buildings for which O'Gorman found
records were not built or were destroyed. The ``crowning
achievement'' of his architectural career, College Hall on the
Wellesley campus, burned down in 1914. The eclectic red brick
building contained student and faculty lodgings, plus a dining
room, chapel, gymnasium, science rooms, a hospital, art gallery,
library and a dramatic, skylit central hall surrounded by tiers of
Corinthian columns.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult for architects to remain famous if too much
evidence of their talent disappears. And it helps if the architect
lives long. Billings died at 56. He was treated better in the
histories of illustration, where he does have a small but
reasonably secure place. Nevertheless, even in his lifetime he was
accused of spreading himself too thin. O'Gorman suggests such
diversity is appealing, compared with our obsession with
specialization. But architecture has a better chance than
illustration of remaining visible in the public eye.
</P>
<P>
   Why resuscitate Billings's career and not that of others?
O'Gorman piles on many facts about Billings's accomplishments but
does not address why Billings was considered so good then, and why
he should be venerated now. I want to know. Although O'Gorman
states he is not trying to assess Billings's oeuvre on esthetic
grounds, that is the way architecture was evaluated in his time,
and often still is. O'Gorman gives an enlightening esthetic
analysis of the skylit center hall in College Hall at Wellesley but
not one of the baronial library, an imposing double-height space,
lined with smaller alcoves on both levels and glowing with black
walnut carving and Pompeian red walls. Since scale, proportion,
harmony and rhythm were so important to 19th-century notions of
taste and beauty, the reader could benefit from more explanation of
Billings's compositional flair. Granted, criteria of evaluation
change, but that issue too could be examined.
</P>
<P>
   Still, O'Gorman's thorough ``introductory study'' provides fine
material for the formation of a new and expanded social, cultural
and architectural history. One hopes that future historians will
take up the challenge to integrate his findings into a more
critical framework. What the past thought about itself is
important. So is grappling with what we think about the past
thinking about itself. In that context, the question about ``why
Billings'' might find a clear answer.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne Stephens, who writes frequently on architecture and
design, is writing a doctoral dissertation on American
architectural criticism.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
