<DOCNO> NYT19981022.0103 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 10:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1027 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-DINOSAUR-NYTS     10-22 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-DINOSAUR-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LAST DINOSAUR BOOK
</HEADLINE>
  The Life and Times of a Cultural Icon 
 By W. J. T. Mitchell 
 Illustrated. 321 pp. Chicago: The University of Chicago Press. $35 
 ------ 
 HEAVY SYMBOLISM 
 By MARK C. TAYLOR 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Images of dinosaurs are everywhere; we are in the midst of what
can only be described as ``dinomania.'' But why? In ``The Last
Dinosaur Book,'' W. J. T. Mitchell maintains that dinosaurs are
symptoms of what the literary theorist Fredric Jameson labels ``the
political unconscious.'' Contrary to expectation, the figure of the
dinosaur indirectly discloses the changing economic forces that
have shaped modern society and culture.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell, a professor of English and art at the University of
Chicago, analyzes what he describes as the ``cultural icon'' of the
dinosaur. An icon, he explains, is an ``imagetext'' or
``combination of verbal and visual signs'' that is symptomatic of
psychological, social and economic processes. With Darwin, Freud
and, most important, Marx as his guides, Mitchell unearths the
historical origin and development as well as the psychological and
social functions of icons. The analysis of the dinosaur yields rich
insights because it is ``the totem animal of modernity.''
</P>
<P>
   Drawing on Claude Levi-Strauss's influential account of
totemism, Mitchell insists that the dinosaur is ``a thing to think
with, not of.'' When the totem is an icon, we think with imagetexts
that collapse the distinction between the conceptual and the
visual. The imaginative dimension of all reflection obscures the
supposedly clear lines separating natural sciences, social
sciences, arts and humanities. Mitchell sides with those who reduce
nature to culture: ``Nature is culture; science is art. We don't
ever 'see nature' in the raw, but always cooked in categories and
clothed in the garments of language and representation.'' What
makes the dinosaur a particularly rich resource for thought is its
hybrid character: the dinosaur ``is a figure in constant symbolic
motion, shuttling between science and fantasy, nature and culture,
the image of the other and a mirror of the self.'' The ambiguity of
the dinosaur provokes ambivalent responses.
</P>
<P>
   To support his interpretation of these hybrid creatures,
Mitchell creates a hybrid work. The book consists of 40 brief
chapters, a coda and two superfluous appendixes. It is amply
illustrated with images from popular culture, and its inventive
design gives it the feel of a comic book. The chapters are numbered
sequentially but can be read in any order. Mitchell attempts to
persuade as much by amassing material as constructing arguments.
However, as examples and illustrations proliferate, this dinosaur
threatens to collapse under its own weight. When he finally admits
that this ``shape-shifting, transitional figure . . . can seem to
mean almost anything one minute and almost nothing the next,'' the
point of the analysis appears to vanish.
</P>
<P>
   But shift this apparently arbitrary assemblage of words and
images ever so slightly and another figure takes shape. Like all
good stories, Mitchell's narrative has a clear beginning, middle
and end. Mitchell's deepest sympathies lie with Marx or, more
precisely, the neo-Marxist brand of criticism popularized by
cultural studies. The image of the dinosaur, he says, ``stands for
the fate of the human species within the world system of modern
capitalism.'' Far from monolithic, modern capitalism evolves
through three distinct stages, identified by Fredric Jameson as
market capitalism (1848-1890's), monopoly capitalism
(1890's-1940's) and postindustrial or multinational capitalism
(1940's-present). Without noting his source, Mitchell appropriates
this narrative. There are three chapters in the story of dinosaurs:
early modern (1840-1900), modern (1900-60) and post-modern
(1960-present).
</P>
<P>
   Though ancient creatures, dinosaurs are a modern invention. In
the 1840's the English paleontologist Richard Owen coined the term
``dinosaur.'' For him dinosaurs were antediluvian monsters
resembling ``terrible lizards,'' an image popularized by
iron-and-concrete fabrications displayed in the Crystal Palace in
1854. In the second image, a dinosaur appears as a giant, erect
reptile. Mitchell sees in this familiar icon a ``cultural
allegory'' of monopoly capitalism: ``Giant corporate entities
headed by gigantic individuals'' engage in life-and-death power
struggles. But in a world governed by laws of social and economic
Darwinism, colossal size is not always an advantage. In contrast to
``swamp-bound monsters of sluggish disposition,'' the birdlike
raptors of the film ``Jurassic Park'' represent ``the new stage of
post-modern capitalism, of 'downsizing,' flexibility, rapid strike
forces, teamwork, adaptability.'' Acknowledging the importance of
the information revolution for the third stage of capitalism,
Mitchell labels one chapter ``The Age of Biocybernetic
Reproduction.'' Computer technology and genetic engineering create
a prospect of old monsters in new guises. The difference between
Tyrannosaurus rex and the agile raptor is that between G.M. and
Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   Thus ``The Last Dinosaur Book'' is a disaster story about
imminent extinction of the human race. In the dinosaur we see our
own dark future. The destructive monster out of control is
capitalism, whose voracious appetite is satisfied only by
proliferating instantly obsolete products. At the end of the
millennium, this wasteful process threatens to become an omnivorous
beast that consumes itself. Bound to a neo-Marxist perspective,
Mitchell says biocybernetics ``is not a revolutionary break with
the past like mechanistic modernism was'' but is an extension of
the most pernicious aspects of consumer capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   This one-sided critique fails to do justice to the complexity,
diversity and novelty of the digital revolution. Without
underestimating the destructive potential of new technologies, it
is possible to imagine their constructive deployment. The obsolete
narrative structure of this book is nearing the dinosaur's state --
extinction. That does not imply that Mitchell has not made a
contribution, for, as he writes, dinosaurs are not only good to
think of but are also good to think with. By thinking with ``The
Last Dinosaur Book,'' we are able to see creative possibilities in
our historical moment that Mitchell overlooks.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Mark C. Taylor, the director of the Center for Technology in the
Arts and Humanities at Williams College, is the author of
``Hiding.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
