<HEADER>
A1029 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-PROFESSION-NY     10-22 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-PROFESSION-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DANGEROUS PROFESSION
</HEADLINE>
  A Book About the Writing Life 
 By Frederick Busch 
 245 pp. New York: St. Martin's Press. $23.95 
 ------ 
 ODD JOB 
 By ELIZABETH HANSON 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Quick, name this job: You work by yourself, usually in your own
digs, with no regular salary, no benefits, no paid vacations or
pension, no regular praise or recognition for your efforts; you
might not receive any payment for your product, though it could
have taken years or even a decade to finish; and meanwhile, others
earn fantastic sums as well as public accolades for what you know
is inferior, shoddy work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dollars damn me; and the malicious Devil is forever grinning
in upon me, holding the door ajar. . . . What I feel most moved to
write, that is banned _ it will not pay. Yet, altogether, write the
other way I cannot. So the product is a final hash, and all my
books are botches.''
</P>
<P>
   The quotation is from the young Herman Melville in 1851 _
``Moby-Dick'' was about to be lanced by the critics. A jolly career
indeed, to be a writer of fiction; in his collection of essays ``A
Dangerous Profession,'' Frederick Busch shows us how difficult,
thankless and downright depressing this dangerous profession is.
``There is no satisfaction, because writing does not offer that
emotion,'' Busch, the author of 18 works of fiction, writes. ``The
talent that drives a writer, the ambition to publish, the energy to
continue _ these are why he or she must write. The gift, if it is
that, is also the goad. It is an appetite that feeds itself.''
</P>
<P>
   The first section of the book concerns Busch's own experiences
as a writer, including the requisite poverty and struggle in the
early years, when he wrote perched on the edge of the bathtub,
typewriter on a table in front of him, because there was no other
private space in the tiny apartment he shared with his wife. During
this time he read and reread the list of illustrious publishers who
rejected the manuscript of ``Under the Volcano''; he also kept a
parallel list of publishers who had rejected his first novel, to
remind himself that he and Malcolm Lowry ``were brother sufferers
and therefore brother writers.'' He acknowledges his wife's loyalty
and support in his essay ``The Writer's Wife'': ``You have seen
them, smiling in crowded gatherings at no one because no one talks
to them for very long except to say, 'Oh, you're Mrs. Him? How
wonderful!' '' Busch quotes Dickens, writing as David Copperfield:
he wished ``my wife had been my counselor; had had more character
and purpose, to sustain me and improve me by; had been endowed with
power to fill up the void which somewhere seemed to be about me.''
</P>
<P>
   The second section comprises a series of essays about several
books and their authors. Busch chooses a sad and sometimes suicidal
group of writers (including Melville, Dickens, Graham Greene and
Hemingway) who were driven by their need to make sense of a
darkness that haunted them. Dickens, for example, ``does what all
novelists do: He resists time by rowing backward, against the
current, into his life. Like all serious artists, he takes the
matter of his art as a matter of life and death. The writer, he
believes, must succeed or die.''
</P>
<P>
   Another essay in this section, ``Bad,'' takes on political
correctness. An essential ``bad'' is the phenomenon of black
writers being only black, lesbian writers only homosexual, white
writers only white. Literature professors, Busch rants, tolerate
writers, though they know that if Chaucer were to apply for a job,
he would not be hired ``because he is a dead white European male
and because his degree isn't good enough, and because he doesn't do
theory.''
</P>
<P>
   Nothing in this book suggests that there is any way to be a
fiction writer except with a considerable amount of recurring
anguish. Read this book if you are a beginning writer who wants the
assurance that others, too, have written, submitted and been
rejected over and over again. Read it if you are an established
writer and want to see the continuing doubt and despair of those
who have produced great books. And if you think you'd like to be a
novelist to partake of glamour, fame and fortune, then read on, so
that you can persuade yourself to veer quickly into another line of
work. Busch clearly believes that either you have a call to the
writing vocation or you don't; the only reason to continue to write
is because you can't not do it.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Hanson, an essayist, teaches Japanese at Seattle
University.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
