<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 10:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1030 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-GERMAN-1000&AMP;A     10-22 1576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-GERMAN-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MY GERMAN QUESTION
</HEADLINE>
  Growing Up in Nazi Berlin 
 By Peter Gay 
 206 pp. New Haven: Yale University Press. $22.50 
 ------ 
 DISPLACED PERSON 
 By FRANK KERMODE 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Among the many works of Peter Gay, a prolific cultural
historian, the best known may be the learned five-volume study
called ``The Bourgeois Experience: Victoria to Freud,'' which, like
his new book, is much influenced by his interest in psychoanalysis.
His writing is idiomatically smooth, a sound historian's
instrument, and no one reading it would guess that when he arrived
in the United States as an adolescent named Peter Frohlich he had
only a little English, his native language being German.
</P>
<P>
   Times were hard enough, but the Gays were not complainers and
despised the deracinated German immigrants they called ``Byunskis''
because they so often said ``Bei uns in Deutschland war alles
besser'' (``At home in Germany everything was better''). As a newly
arrived American, Gay, in the time-honored manner, did all sorts of
jobs _ shipping clerk, magazine distributor, stamp dealer _ before
winning a scholarship to the University of Colorado. He was 23 when
he got his B.A., whereupon he began his academic career as a
graduate student at Columbia. There, and later at Yale, he
established his scholarly name and fortune.
</P>
<P>
   It sounds like an arduous ascent, and so it was; but the young
man's qualities were such that it seems to have been relatively
pleasant. Gay has always given thanks for his extraordinary good
fortune, not only in getting out of Germany with his family but in
making it to America, the place he most wanted to be. But nobody
who spent his or her formative years as a Jew in the Berlin of the
1930's could simply forget that past. A new name and a new language
might bury but could not abolish it. Only now, in his still active
retirement, have Gay's memories grown urgent enough to demand
expression. The result is ``My German Question,'' which the author,
who confesses that he normally enjoys writing, calls ``the least
exhilarating assignment I have ever given myself or received from
others.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the public events he describes are all too familiar, but
this is primarily a personal history, and the remembered reactions
of a sensitive boy, as recalled by a writer of keen Freudian
beliefs, give the book its individuality. Why, he wonders, was he
such a well-behaved child? Was his goodness a cover? Was it that he
really wanted to be very bad? He certainly has, to this day, acute
memories of minor infantile delinquencies, and of later sins,
especially the sin of anger. But these seem to have been few and
unalarming, and mostly he just went on being well behaved. However,
he confesses, without reservation, that his hatred for all things
German persisted for years; and it was long before he could be
induced to set foot in Germany. And he remains just as angry with
people, whatever their nationality, who express facile wonder that
German Jews didn't all get out when the Nazi threat was obvious and
while the going was good.
</P>
<P>
   One purpose of this book is to explain the behavior of families
like his own, apparently so imperceptively dilatory. Roughly
speaking, they were unable to believe that oppression of the Jews,
already evident without seeming to be life-threatening, would
quickly grow worse; that the Munich agreement would offer the Nazis
a free hand, and that human beings, fellow Germans, fellow
townsmen, could be so outrageously and unpredictably cruel. Indeed,
they had been deluded into believing that anti-Semitism was waning,
at least in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The Gays were not observant Jews, and apart from one or two
inherited customs, might have been accepted, and seem to have
thought of themselves, as virtually assimilated _ might even, with
their blue eyes and fair hair, have passed for non-Jews. They took
their modest part in the business and cultural life of a city to
which they felt a strong attachment. Jews made a large contribution
to its life: indeed, as Gay remarks, Berlin, with the departure of
the Jews, lost one of the mainstays of its bourgeois culture, and,
as Willy Brandt lamented, their contribution has not been replaced.
Kristallnacht was inconceivable until it happened.
</P>
<P>
   Gay records his memories of daily life in the city and of the
life of the family, in apartments that shrank in size as they came
down in the world. The most disastrous change occurred in 1933,
when, as Gay expresses it, they suddenly became Jews. Yet even this
ultimately catastrophic change seems at first to have made little
difference. There was growing anxiety, but after all one still had
to go on buying groceries, trying for good grades, going to the
dentist; and for a while nobody interfered in these modest
liberties. But eventually the conditions of life grew stricter,
with the boycott on Jewish stores and the law excluding Jews from
public employment.
</P>
<P>
   Gay was relatively lucky, having at his school some teachers who
were not Nazi, and he largely avoided persecution at the hands of
the other boys. And for a while this small-business family (unlike
Jewish actors, lawyers, professors) prospered surprisingly under
the Nazi regime. But the threat did not go away. The young Gay
reacted to it by idealizing America. He came to loathe Germany,
worshiped Jesse Owens and was wildly happy when the German women's
relay team dropped the baton at the Berlin Olympics of 1936, a
disaster he still calls ``one of the great moments in my life. . .
. Schadenfreude can be one of the greatest joys.''
</P>
<P>
   He admits to several eccentric enthusiasms, regarding them as
survival strategies; they included stamp collecting and an
improbable passion for the London soccer team Arsenal, whose
fortunes he follows still, commending Nick Hornby's ``Fever
Pitch,'' a record English best seller, as the best study ever
``about the peculiar symptomatology of being a fan.'' In the long
run these defenses were inadequate. A better defense, not available
to the Frohlich family, was to be proudly Jewish, to be Zionist.
But they were neither, merely ``Jews by Nazi edict.'' In spite of
the Nuremberg Laws they still regarded themselves as German. But
the pressure grew more and more outrageous, and they began, at
first without much urgency, to talk about getting out.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-GERMAN-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: getting out.)
</P>
<P>
   The grim year 1938 climaxed with the Munich Pact and
Kristallnacht, that ``degradation ritual'' that had the effect of
at last making it necessary to leave, and soon. Tentative plans for
departure already existed but were speeded up. Gay's father wrote
to people named Frohlich in England and America, where he had rich
relatives. Application to the British Consulate was refused, a
decision Gay now calls fortunate. The United States had a strict
quota system, and Gay's father was classified as a Pole, which gave
him very little chance. In the end the family made it to America
via Cuba, not without crises, and some virtuous and desperate
trickery. Thereafter, despite early struggles to make a living, all
was about as well as any future, founded on such a past, could be.
</P>
<P>
   Gay's story could hardly be other than interesting, and one is
glad about the happy outcome of his family's afflictions and his
own feeling that his life has been ``an astonishing gift.'' There
are occasional inaccuracies; for example, one doesn't have to be
upper class to watch cricket. But slips like these are of small
importance.
</P>
<P>
   What is odd about the book, given its subject, is the persistent
blandness of Gay's writing. ``Interest'' tends to be ``absorbing
interest,'' and it is difficult to be fortunate without being
``immensely fortunate.'' The prose seems unusually gentle, without
consistent animus, and that is probably a reflection of the
author's temperament. When his anger erupts, and he wishes some
ancient enemy disgraced or dead, the effect is, for a moment,
particularly surprising, as if such sentiments had no place in the
story, though of course they have, and were the main reason for its
being written. And it may be that this, too, is a true reflection
of a quietly remarkable character, civilized, learned, yet
incapable of wholly forgetting or forgiving the hideous cruelties
that threatened his life as a boy.
</P>
<P>
   Remembering those days he also recalls with affection the life
of the family _ his mother, now lodged deep in his superego,
commenting on his errors, his untidinesses, his leaving tasks
incomplete; his agnostic and resourceful father, his various uncles
and neighbors, nearly all pleasant and helpful. He remembers with
admiration the way they went on with their decent lives as the
nightmare descended on them. He is clearly a man capable of a civil
happiness as well as of just anger. And one closes his book with
the agreeable feeling that he has dwelt more upon the welcome and
the opportunities offered him by America than on the foulness of
the country that forced him to flee there, to run, as it turned
out, from terror to contentment.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Frank Kermode's most recent book is the memoir ``Not Entitled.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
