<HEADER>
A1031 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-LIVING-1000&AMP;A     10-22 1429
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-LIVING-1000&AMP;ADD-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE ART OF LIVING
</HEADLINE>
  Socratic Reflections From Plato to Foucault 
 By Alexander Nehamas 
 283 pp. Berkeley: University of California Press. $29.95 
 ------ 
 THE EXAMINED LIFE 
 By JONATHAN LEAR 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the core of Western civilization is emptiness. As Socrates,
the most important figure in Western philosophy, explains at his
trial, when he heard the Delphic oracle say that no one was wiser
than he, he was puzzled, for the one thing he knew was that he knew
nothing. He set out to cross-examine wise men and poets to
determine what in the world the oracle could mean. And everywhere
he looked, he could find only the pretension to knowledge, not
knowledge itself. In the end, Socrates recognized oracular irony:
he was indeed wiser than others precisely because he understood
that he lacked wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   Socrates' famous method of refutation _ the elenchus _ tended to
induce the experience of emptiness in others: an interlocutor would
begin thinking he knew what justice or courage or piety is, and in
the course of the conversation would be reduced to confusion and
self-contradiction. For his own part, Socrates was the ancient
Hellenic version of the Cheshire cat, fading away into his own
smile. Socrates himself had no alternative view to put forward, and
thus he left his interlocutor with an experience of a gap in
understanding where once he felt he had something. In short,
Socrates had an uncanny gift for bringing others to the brink of
anxiety. In the give-and-take of a short exchange, he was able to
lead his conversational partners to a recognition that although
they took their lives to be incredibly important, they did not
really understand what they were doing, or why, or why it was a
good idea for them to be doing that rather than something else.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, the interlocutor would typically rush off,
supposedly called back to the concerns of daily life. Concern about
getting ahead in life _ closing a business deal, winning a court
case, getting into the right school _ would be used to distract one
from the more profound anxiety that one had no idea what a truly
successful life might be, and thus one had no idea what ``getting
ahead'' meant. Socrates is the only figure who is willing to stand
still. He alone can tolerate the anxiety of not knowing. He asks
questions and refuses to move in any direction until he knows where
he is going.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Art of Living'' is Alexander Nehamas's own joyful attempt
to stand still. Philosophy, for him, can be seen as made up of two
very different ways of responding to the figure of Socrates. The
dominant tradition follows the later Plato and tries to provide
answers to Socrates' questions. Philosophy in this mode is made up
of theoretical, impersonal arguments about our obligations to
others, the nature of the good life, what we can know and what
there is. But Nehamas is out to invigorate another neglected mode.
In this Socratic mode, there is an enhanced emphasis on what kind
of life one leads, what kind of self one becomes, when one lives
with the question of how to live. For Nehamas, Socrates' ``major
accomplishment is that he established a new way of life, a new art
of living,'' and in so doing constituted himself as the unique
individual he became. The question for Nehamas is: how can one
possibly follow suit?
</P>
<P>
   There is no easy answer to this question. As Nehamas points out,
one cannot simply ask questions a la Socrates: that is to become a
banal imitator. Rather, if one is truly to follow in this Socratic
mode, one must invent one's own art of living. Nehamas's book is a
study of the struggles of prominent members of this tradition _
Plato himself, Montaigne, Nietzsche and Foucault _ each to become a
philosophical self unlike any other. But this is not simply a
theoretical or historical survey. Nehamas, who is the Edmund N.
Carpenter 2d Professor in the Humanities and a professor of
philosophy and comparative literature at Princeton, wants to create
his own art of living, and this is his stab at it. His writing thus
takes on a compassionate engagement, which is unusual in a
scholarly book. Nehamas suffers from the philosophical variant of
the anxiety of influence, and he deals with it by writing about the
apprehensions of some of the most anxious members of the
philosophical tradition. Author and subjects have it in common that
they turn toward and away from Socrates to grapple with the problem
of their own individuality. If one would like to be introduced to
these thinkers, it is hard to come up with a better organizing
idea.
</P>
<P>
   The chapter on Platonic irony is particularly brilliant. Nehamas
argues that in addition to the much-discussed Socratic irony, there
is a higher level of irony in which Plato both seduces and abandons
his readers. The dialogues are written in a theatrical style, and
thus the reader will naturally, though un-self-consciously, tend to
take up the position of audience. For its part, an audience tends
to assume that it is looking on the dramatized reality from the
perspective of the truth. All the characters on stage may have
partial and distorted perspectives, but the audience, as it were,
has an absolute perspective on all of this.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BC-NYTBOOK-LIVING-2NDTAKE-NYTSF &QL; 
 &UR; UNDATED: all of this.)
</P>
<P>
   So on a first reading we cannot help smiling at, say, the absurd
confidence of Euthyphro, in the dialogue named for him, that he
knows what piety is. Thus Plato lulls us into re-creating in our
own souls the very smug sense of superiority that we (smugly) look
down on in Euthyphro. Should we read the dialogue, close the book
and get on with our lives, we are doing exactly what Euthyphro did
in response to Socratic questioning _ absolutely nothing. For
Nehamas, Plato allows us to think we are viewing the drama from
Plato's perspective, thus inviting an inevitable sense of
superiority to Socrates' interlocutors, only to whip that
assumption away and leave us barefaced and embarrassed at our
vanity. Plato himself disappears beyond the horizon of his
characters. Indeed, Nehamas makes a claim that has come to haunt my
thoughts since I read it: that Plato did not understand his own
literary creature. The Socrates of the dialogues remains opaque to
his author, and this helps to explain the sense of verisimilitude
and realism we feel when we encounter him.
</P>
<P>
   I find myself in strongest disagreement with Nehamas's chapter
on Socratic irony, interesting though it is. Ever since Kierkegaard
published ``The Concept of Irony With Continual Reference to
Socrates,'' it has been more or less required for interpreters to
come to grips with Socrates' irony. Nehamas takes up this
tradition, criticizes it to good effect and then goes on to offer
his own unpersuasive account. Let me simply state, without
argument, that irony is one of Socrates' least important features.
What is important is that others take Socrates to be ironic _ both
figures inside the dialogues, like Alcibiades and Thrasymachus, and
figures outside the dialogues, like Kierkegaard, the renowned
American philosopher Gregory Vlastos and Nehamas himself. Socrates
says at his trial that were he to tell the truth about why he
cannot stop doing philosophy (he would be disobeying God's
command), he would be taken by the court to be speaking ironically.
To be sure, he makes that point with a certain irony, but over all
he warns his audience against the temptation of attributing hidden
layers of meaning to him.
</P>
<P>
   Should one succumb to this temptation, one can then put the
putative irony to various illusory uses: one can see Socrates as
masking a mysterious something (Alcibiades) or as masking a
mysterious nothing (Kierkegaard) or as meaning the opposite of what
he says (Vlastos) or as expressing an essential uncertainty
(Nehamas). What is almost impossible for us to hold on to is the
idea that everything about Socrates is right there on the surface.
It remains a fascinating question about us _ why we cannot help
attributing depth to him.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Lear is the John U. Nef Distinguished Service Professor
at the University of Chicago and a member of the Committee on
Social Thought. His most recent book is ``Open Minded: Working Out
the Logic of the Soul.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
