<HEADER>
A1032 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-LIMAN-NYTSF     10-22 0856
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-LIMAN-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYER
</HEADLINE>
  A Life of Counsel and Controversy 
 By Arthur L. Liman with Peter Israel 
 Illustrated. 386 pp. New York: Public Affairs. $30 
 ------ 
 HIS DAY IN COURT 
 By ADAM LIPTAK 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   If an image of Arthur L. Liman still lingers in the popular
consciousness, it is a caricature: the rumpled New York lawyer
presiding over the Iran-Contra hearings. His very physical presence
_ the shy, crooked grin, the brooding features, the epic comb-over
_ seemed designed to contrast with the pressed and polished
soldiers who appeared before him as witnesses, jaws jutting,
unencumbered by doubt. Liman's role in this piece of political
theater was as straight man, foil. He was earnest, tireless,
skeptical and yet strangely ineffective. In Hollywood, they call
this a fish-out-of-water story.
</P>
<P>
   Liman, who died last year, was far more in his element in
corporate litigation. He was a trial lawyer, rare among the classy
litigators to whom rich men and corporations turn when they are in
trouble. While he proudly called himself a rainmaker for the firm
he helped to build, Paul, Weiss, Rifkind, Wharton &AMP; Garrison, Liman
also did the work: he mastered the documents, interviewed the
witnesses, picked the juries and tried the cases. He ground out
victories and good settlements from this attention to detail and
the incremental concessions he coaxed from hostile witnesses
through methodical cross-examination.
</P>
<P>
   The bulk of his memoir is devoted to these trials. Liman plainly
took pleasure, even decades later, in recollecting the details. The
reader's pleasure is less intense. While the anecdotes are told
crisply and with occasional verve, their cumulative effect is to
convince one, if there existed doubt, that there is no such thing
as an interesting securities fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Liman seems uneasy writing about another aspect of his very full
public life. He was a counselor to many powerful and controversial
executives, an unusual role for a litigator. The things Liman
offered his clients _ absolute loyalty, authentic affection,
discretion _ do not allow him to examine their characters and
escapades in anything but a superficial and one-sided fashion.
Liman gave his clients tough and independent advice, but he
properly keeps their secrets here.
</P>
<P>
   Liman also often found time for public service of the most
demanding sort. He was chief counsel to the McKay Commission, which
investigated the Attica prison riots, and of the Senate Iran-contra
committee. He devotes only a few short chapters to the latter
investigation, which is a pity. He was plainly frustrated by the
perception that the hearings were a failure, and he offers
detailed, if dry, responses to his critics.
</P>
<P>
   The most telling passages about the hearings are brief excerpts
of a diary not discovered until after Liman died. Written in the
heat of battle and with an acid tone absent from the rest of the
book, he sketches nasty portraits of John Nields, his counterpart
in the House of Representatives, and Lawrence Walsh, the
Iran-contra independent counsel. These flashes of another side of
Liman are as illuminating as anything else in ``Lawyer,'' and
publication of the entire diary would be welcome.
</P>
<P>
   Liman does not seem to have been a particularly reflective man.
His legal philosophy is only hinted at, and those hints rarely rise
above bar association platitudes. He did, though, have an almost
religious faith in the courts _ in contrast, he notes, to the
generation of lawyers who preceded him, products of the New Deal
and its commitment to the executive and legislative branches.
</P>
<P>
   At Yale Law School, where he graduated first in his class, he
learned an approach to the law known as legal realism. Skeptical
and pragmatic, legal realism recognizes that judges often rule
first, basing their decisions on ideology or sympathy, and
manufacture reasoning later. Though generally thought to be a
descriptive critique, legal realism was understood by Liman to be a
call to arms, an inspiration to judges to shake off ``archaic rules
that would have prevented them from compensating victims,
nullifying unconscionable contracts, or insuring civil liberties.''
The courts are, he writes, an instrument for social change, and in
his career he looked to them to resolve all manner of social and
political issues.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Liman's Iran-contra experience may ultimately have caused
him to amend his views a little. He ends the book by questioning
the wisdom of unqualified faith in the judicial process to reform
society and by criticizing Congress for shifting ``responsibility
for politically difficult and complex decisions to the courts.''
His greatest public moment may have, ironically, disturbed the
convictions that underlay a lifetime in the law.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Adam Liptak is senior counsel in the legal department of The New
York Times Company.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
