<HEADER>
A1034 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-LEAVING-NYTSF     10-22 1134
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-LEAVING-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEAVING EARTH
</HEADLINE>
  By Helen Humphreys 
 244 pp. New York: Metropolitan Books/Henry Holt &AMP; Company. $22 
 ------ 
 DON'T LOOK DOWN 
 By DAVID WILLIS MCCULLOUGH 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is there a novel in this? Two women take off in an aging blue
biplane on a hot August morning in 1933 intending to fly in
monotonous counterclockwise circles over the Toronto lakefront for
25 days, breaking the world flight endurance record.
</P>
<P>
   By now we should know there can be a novel in anything. And in
the hands of Helen Humphreys, a young Canadian poet, what could be
a minor footnote becomes a novel so beautiful in its reticence and
insight, featuring characters so seemingly fragile and endangered,
that readers may well find themselves becoming curiously protective
about the whole enterprise. They will also feel the tension
building as the final chapters approach, much like the sensation
baseball fans recognize in the eighth inning of what might turn out
to be a perfect game.
</P>
<P>
   Will something go wrong to spoil everything? Something, that is,
in the writing and the storytelling, not in the flying, where a
good deal has already gone wrong. It gives nothing away to say
right now that Helen Humphreys delivers her perfect game.
</P>
<P>
   The two women who fly the tiny Moth called Adventure Girl (the
name is painted on the fuselage in honor of the magazine that's
sponsoring the flight) could not be more unlike _ except for their
love of flying. Grace O'Gorman, known to the public as Air Ace
Grace, is 33 years old, married, the holder of a number of flying
records and famous for her airborne stunts. Willa Briggs is 10
years younger, an inexperienced and unknown flying instructor who
sleeps in a ramshackle cabin behind an airplane hangar. Grace signs
Willa on at the last minute when her original co-pilot breaks her
wrist; she thinks so little of Willa that she forgets to invite her
to the pre-takeoff dinner.
</P>
<P>
   One of the few flying records Grace hasn't broken is the one for
endurance; it is held by her husband, Jack Robson, the man who
first taught her how to fly. If Grace and Willa stay aloft for 25
days, they'll destroy Jack's only claim to fame _ other, that is,
than being Grace's husband. It is Jack's job to fly up every eight
hours in his own plane to rendezvous with the women, deliver food
and messages and, in a tricky midair maneuver, refuel Adventure
Girl.
</P>
<P>
   At first, Willa finds herself filled with wonder, awed by the
ever-changing views below her and the honor of flying with Grace.
They have no radio; because of the noise and the wind in their open
cockpits, they cannot easily speak to each other. Since Willa is
seated behind Grace, they rarely even make eye contact. After their
note pads are ruined in a rainstorm, they are no longer able to
write notes to each other. Partly out of necessity and partly out
of boredom, they develop a private language of signs and gestures,
a means of communication that is all their own.
</P>
<P>
   As the days pass, Grace and Willa's contact with the earth
becomes more and more tenuous. They are too high to recognize
individual human figures on the ground. Jack drops off no messages
with their sandwiches, only copies of the local newspaper featuring
his highly fanciful articles about their adventures, articles in
which Grace always seems terribly vulnerable and plucky Willa
always saves the day. Gradually, the two women stop reading the
papers and spend less and less time looking down. Their only human
contact lies in their unspoken gestures, their occasional touches.
</P>
<P>
   The third woman in the story _ actually, she's a 12-year-old
girl _ is Maddy, the daughter of a Scottish merry-go-round operator
and a Jewish fortuneteller who live in an amusement park over which
Adventure Girl flies its seemingly endless circles. As the sound of
the plane drones on night and day, Maddy, whose bedroom wall is
decorated with a picture of the Air Ace, begins to believe that
Grace is her real mother, that her true identity has been kept a
secret.
</P>
<P>
   Through Maddy, the novel acquires a sense of the times. The
Great Depression is not quite over. Camps for workers have been set
up near the city. Hitler is becoming a disturbingly familiar name.
A gang of pro-Nazi blueshirts roams the amusement park midway.
Maddy's mother's brother is a prizefighter who wears a Star of
David on his trunks. (Willa has taken boxing lessons from him, in
exchange for flying lessons.) After he defeats a German, the
blueshirts take their revenge by beating up Maddy's mother and
burning down her fortune-telling booth.
</P>
<P>
   As 10, 11, 12 days pass, life in Adventure Girl becomes more and
more removed from reality. Willa is not always sure how many days
they have still to go. There's engine trouble. The fabric on a wing
is badly torn (and crudely mended) during an especially difficult
refueling. Willa begins to fear that Jack may be intentionally
sabotaging the flight. Down below, Maddy is collecting bits and
pieces thrown from the plane and saving them as relics: chicken
bones, orange peels, a note Willa wrote to Grace on a scrap of
newspaper and threw away before she dared to pass it on. Maddy
treasures it as a love note from her true mother. It's not long
before Maddy's world and Grace and Willa's become one.
</P>
<P>
   Helen Humphreys writes remarkably spare, uncluttered prose; she
has a great knack for evoking unspoken love and finding stark
beauty in matters as diverse as the sight of a burning ship at
night or the creation of a silent language. The very first image of
the novel illustrates her ingenuity, blending toughness with an
almost housewifely tidiness as the ``masculine'' sport of flying is
hemmed into place with the ``feminine'' art of sewing: ``The plane
slips from a spool of blue, stitches a confident loop in the sky.
Willa stands by the hangar as the Moth roars above her head, growl
of open throttle.''
</P>
<P>
   There are few wasted words or incidents in ``Leaving Earth.'' In
fact, it is a novel that ends just before the most important words
of all are finally spoken. But there is room in it for sly humor
(particularly in Jack Robson's newspaper dispatches) and for some
startlingly lyrical cadenzas, like the scenes of Maddy being given
riding lessons by her father. The horse is her favorite
merry-go-round steed. Its name _ we shouldn't be surprised by this
_ is Amelia.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   David Willis McCullough is the author of a novel, ``Point
No-Point.'' His most recent book is a historical anthology,
``Chronicles of the Barbarians.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
