<HEADER>
A1035 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-HUNGER-NYTSF     10-22 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-HUNGER-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNGER
</HEADLINE>
  A Novella and Stories 
 By Lan Samantha Chang 
 191 pp. New York: W. W. Norton &AMP; Company. $22 
 ------ 
 'A HOLE IN OUR HOUSE' 
 By CLAIRE MESSUD 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The final story in Lan Samantha Chang's elegant debut collection
closes with a resonant image, as a Communist soldier in wartime
Shanghai executes the narrator's wealthy master: ``The soldier
raised his arm again, and the sharp blade sliced all our lives in
two.'' This story is the only one in the book that takes place in
China, but the bifurcation it describes encapsulates the
experiences of all the Chinese-American families who people Chang's
work. Her stories constitute a delicately calculated balance sheet
of the losses and gains of immigrants whose lives are stretched
between two radically different cultures.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The Unforgetting,'' Ming Hwang, his wife, Sansan, and their
young son, Charles, settle in eastern Iowa, where they build a
wholly American life: ``The Hwangs forgot what they no longer
needed. . . . They forgot what they could no longer bear to hope
for. . . . They learned what they needed to know.'' Ming puts aside
his dream of becoming a scientist in order to prosper as a
photocopier repairman, and Sansan learns to cook cream of tomato
soup. Thoroughly Americanized, Charles flourishes academically and
prepares to leave home; only then must his parents confront what
they have lost: ``Nothing remained of the stories and meals and
people they'd known, nothing but what they remembered. Their world
lived in them, and they would be the end of it. They had no solace,
and no burden, but each other.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hwangs, for all the regret that is woven into their lives,
are more fortunate than others, particularly the motherless family
in ``The Eve of the Spirit Festival'' or the fatherless narrator of
``San'' _ or, most notably, the Sung family, whose fierce
disappointments are the subject of the collection's powerful title
novella.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hunger'' is narrated from beyond the grave by Min, the wife of
Tian Sung and the mother of Anna and Ruth. Raised in Taiwan, Min
met Tian when she was working in a Chinese restaurant in New York
and he was a promising violinist. Their union was, according to
Min's mother, yuanfen, ``that apportionment of love which is
destined for you in this world.'' But their lives, distorted by
Tian's private grief and by his failure to secure a permanent
teaching position, are not meant for happiness. Anna, their elder
daughter, turns out to be tone-deaf and is consigned to the role of
mother's helper, while beautiful and rebellious Ruth is brutally
coerced by her father into mastering the violin. Although ``there
was a hole in our house, like a great mouth, filled with love words
and lost objects,'' there is, for a time, some redemption in Ruth's
playing. Her music is ``like a great rope of silk, smooth and
shimmering, shot through with glints and shades of beautiful
light.''
</P>
<P>
   Chang has a fine gift for such evocative concrete descriptions
of the abstract; her prose, while generally as restrained as the
characters to whom it belongs, occasionally bursts into rich blooms
of imagery. Brownstones in late 1960's Brooklyn stand ``in patient
rows, like tablets in a soldiers' graveyard, crumbled and soft
around the edges''; in Iowa, Ming Hwang senses ``the rolling fields
that pressed upon their house. Mutinous seeds opposed the lawn:
tall leaves of pale new wheat, foamy milkweed, Queen Anne's lace.''
</P>
<P>
   Less successful are Chang's explicit renditions of family
altercations, with their blunt, overly familiar dialogue: ``You
will stay in this house!'' storms Tian to Ruth in ``Hunger.'' ``I
am not staying!'' she replies. ``You can't keep me from leaving!''
In ``The Eve of the Spirit Festival,'' the father rails at his
daughter: ``What are you doing that for? You can't go out tonight.
. . . Dressing up in boys' clothes, with paint on your face.'' And
Sansan Hwang, in ``The Unforgetting,'' yells at her husband: ``You
have ruined me! You have trapped me into this life!'' Such
platitudes are perhaps inevitable, since many of Chang's characters
are like Sansan, who ``in English . . . seemed to hide from her
more complicated thoughts.'' Nevertheless, they weaken these
otherwise luminously elegiac stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hunger'' is the melody upon which the rest of the collection
provides graceful variations. Chang offers no easy or reassuring
resolution to the tortures of the immigrant experience: complex and
rueful, her fiction gives voice to internal struggles, withheld
catalogues of loss. As Min notes: ``Some Chinese make their
fortunes in America. Tian and I were not among them. Perhaps we
lacked the forgetfulness that is essential to moving on.''
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Claire Messud is the author of a novel, ``When the World Was
Steady.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
