<HEADER>
A1036 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-SILK-NYTSF     10-22 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-SILK-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SILK AND INSIGHT
</HEADLINE>
  By Yukio Mishima 
 Edited by Frank Gibney 
 Translated by Hiroaki Sato 
 219 pp. Armonk, N.Y.: East Gate/M. E. Sharpe. Cloth, $44.95. Paper,
$19.95 
 ------ 
 RAW MATERIAL 
 By MARK MORRIS 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   By the time Yukio Mishima destroyed himself in 1970, he had
behind him a quarter-century of writing: stories, longer fiction,
plays, critical essays, personal reflections and, especially toward
the end, pamphlets blending ultranationalism and esthetics with
deadly efficacy. Several times during these decades, Mishima turned
away from his luxuriant imagination and tore his gaze from the
mirror long enough to experiment with capturing dramatic aspects of
contemporary society in fiction.
</P>
<P>
   He tried this first in 1950 with the unsuccessful ``Blue
Period,'' the story of a gifted student who turns loan shark amid
the confusion and corruption of the early postwar years. The
protagonist, like his creator, ends up a suicide. Arguably, Mishima
was not so much jumping on the bandwagon of a social scandal as
attempting to extend his range beyond the lyricism of his 1949
masterpiece, ``Confessions of a Mask.''
</P>
<P>
   Another figure taken by Mishima and other contemporaries as
emblematic of their inescapable existential disarray helped Mishima
shape ``The Temple of the Golden Pavilion'' (1956). A deeply
disturbed young Buddhist acolyte had burned down one of Kyoto's
most beautiful temples. But that bit of reality provided only the
framework for this extended meditation on being _ and being part of
the generation that came too late _ and the esthetics of
destruction. The distance Mishima achieved by exteriorizing many of
his own lyrical impulses through a quasi-historical protagonist no
doubt accounts for the control he maintained throughout that book,
his final great work.
</P>
<P>
   ``Silk and Insight'' appeared in 1964, when Mishima's reputation
had begun to slip. It seems clearly to have been an attempt to
repeat the success of an earlier novel, ``After the Banquet,''
which had tackled the unpromising topic of Tokyo politics. In
reconstructing the campaign waged by Noguchi, a veteran politician,
and his new wife, a restaurant proprietor with a colorful past,
Mishima sailed close enough to reality to find himself involved in
Japan's first invasion-of-privacy litigation. Yet the book is
perhaps his most novelistic work, with a degree of earthiness and
warmth rare in his fiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``Silk and Insight'' replaces the world of politics with that of
silk textile manufacturing. Mishima dramatizes a moment in the
labor struggles of the 1950's. The politician of ``After the
Banquet'' is replaced by an old-fashioned factory owner, Komazawa,
and the politician's formidable wife, one of Mishima's few
believable female characters, transmogrifies into a retired geisha,
Kikuno, whose very presence in the plot is, like her eventual
self-abnegation before her boss and lover Komazawa, difficult to
credit.
</P>
<P>
   An even less believable character is Okano, a political operator
who spouts Heidegger and Holderlin. He functions as a mediator
between the different social spheres of the main characters and
manipulates the situation at the factory to the point where
Komazawa loses his paternalistic hold and dies a broken man while
Okano takes over the business.
</P>
<P>
   In his biography of Mishima, John Nathan recalled with bitter
humor his despair in 1964 when, having accepted the job of
translating ``Silk and Insight,'' he finally opened the book. One
reading led him to change his mind. This first English translation
does not suggest that Nathan misjudged. The book conveys certain
aspects of the contradictions of older and newer forms of
capitalist production in that era. But a reader has to pay a steep
price for such peripheral information; this translation of a poor
original is a shambles. Any page may sprout handfuls of problems:
idioms rendered with deadly literalness, tortured syntax trying to
bundle one long Mishima cascade of overripe imagery into a single
English sentence, and more. Equipping it with an editor _ whose
efforts are to my eye invisible _ and a subtitle to plead that
``Silk and Insight'' really is ``a novel'' cannot rescue even this
respected translator of Japanese poetry from a translation too far.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Mark Morris, who teaches Japanese literature at Cambridge
University, is co-editor of Japan Forum.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
</TEXT>
