<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 10:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1039 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-MARCHAND-NYTS     10-22 1614
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-MARCHAND-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAUL MARCHAND, F.M.C.
</HEADLINE>
  By Charles W. Chesnutt 
 144 pp. Jackson: University Press of Mississippi. $20 
 ------ 
 WHITE LIKE ME 
 By ARNOLD RAMPERSAD 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The publication of Charles W. Chesnutt's ``Paul Marchand,
F.M.C.'' (the initials stand for ``Free Man of Color,'' a not
uncommon term in Louisiana before the Civil War) marks another
milestone in the return of Chesnutt's reputation from the grave. At
one time, long ago _ around the turn of the century _ Chesnutt was
not only the most acclaimed of African-American fiction writers but
also the first one to enjoy something like a national reputation.
In 1899, after placing several short stories and articles in
surprisingly prominent magazines, notably The Atlantic Monthly, he
published two collections of short tales: ``The Conjure Woman'' and
``The Wife of His Youth.'' Chesnutt then followed this sparkling
debut with three novels _ ``The House Behind the Cedars'' (1900),
``The Marrow of Tradition'' (1901) and ``The Colonel's Dream''
(1905). All of these books were published by prominent American
publishing houses; Houghton Mifflin brought out the first four;
Doubleday, Page published the last.
</P>
<P>
   By 1905, however, Chesnutt's once-promising literary career, for
which he had given up his practice as a legal stenographer in his
native Cleveland, was in irreversible decline. He continued to
write and to enjoy a degree of prestige as an aging lion in black
literary society, such as it was; but with the hardening of Jim
Crow practices in the new century, most publishers on the whole no
longer wanted his work or that of other black writers. Although he
lived to see the Harlem Renaissance of the 1920's, when the Negro
came briefly into vogue, that movement had little to offer him
beyond patronizing bows. When he died at the age of 74 in 1932,
Chesnutt was virtually unknown except among black American readers.
</P>
<P>
   Six decades later, his work is at last receiving its due. Among
several highly respected scholars of American and African-American
literature, Chesnutt has emerged not only as a pillar of the black
American literary tradition but also, as in the judgment of the
scholar Eric Sundquist, ``among the major American fiction writers
of the 19th century.'' All of the stories he published in his
lifetime are back in print; William L. Andrews, the author of an
important book on Chesnutt, has edited his collected stories;
Richard Brodhead has edited his often fascinating journals. Of the
six unpublished novels Chesnutt left behind, three have been
published recently or are about to be published: ``Mandy
Oxendine,'' from his early years as a writer, and ``The Quarry''
and ``Paul Marchand, F.M.C.,'' which were written after his moment
of fame. The recent proliferation of scholarly articles,
dissertations and books about him suggests that his new prestige is
likely to endure. The American Literature Association now includes
the Charles Chesnutt Society.
</P>
<P>
   This revival is hardly an accident. The melodramatic and
sentimental elements of Chesnutt's craft that once made him seem
second-rate, if interesting, no longer faze scholars and students
who look beyond conventional notions of art in evaluating a text;
and his sometimes glittering insights into the subtleties of racial
consciousness among not only blacks and whites but among those
people who fall between the two groups more than make up, in the
minds of such readers, for his ``faults'' of form. In an
intellectual age that insists on race as primarily a social, not a
biological, construction, and that is freshly fascinated by
theories of hybridity and biracialism, cultural liminality, the
dynamics of postcolonialism and so on, Chesnutt's work seems in
retrospect to have been nothing less than prophetic.
</P>
<P>
   And in his person he indeed embodied many of the most puzzling,
and even vexing and painful, aspects of race in the United States.
Chesnutt was, as he himself put it, a ``voluntary Negro'' _ white
enough to pass across the color line. At 17 he confided in his
journal his determination to do so. ``I believe I'll leave here,''
he wrote about the South, where he had grown up, ``and pass anyhow,
for I am as white as any of them.'' He in fact left the South,
first for New York and then for Cleveland, where he lived the rest
of his life, but he married a black woman and passed only on
occasion.
</P>
<P>
   As an apprentice writer he did not advertise his racial
background but soon discovered that race was his true subject, to
which he brought an artistic vision bordering at times on the
revolutionary. In 1887, when The Atlantic Monthly published ``The
Goophered Grapevine,'' Chesnutt broke new ground with the white
reading public not only by his uncommon use of black folklore
surrounding ``conjuring,'' or the occult, but, more important, by
his cool though quite determined challenge to perhaps the key tenet
of the popular ``plantation'' school of writing _ that the main
fictional voice telling about Southern racial reality, past and
present, had to be white. Chesnutt's hero, Uncle Julius McAdoo, a
former slave (of mixed blood, we are told) and as disarming as he
is shrewd and even devious in his self-interest, took over that
essential task quietly but firmly. In creating this character,
Chesnutt upended other plantation-school tenets, especially one
that held that the years of slavery had been the Golden Age of the
South. To be sure, he was not alone in attacking the plantation
school. His onetime mentor and friend, the accomplished white
writer George Washington Cable, had led the general assault and had
suffered accordingly; but Chesnutt, in an entirely historic way,
carried the flag of black identity in ways even Cable had not
imagined.
</P>
<P>
   In ``The House Behind the Cedars'' and ``The Marrow of
Tradition,'' both set in the Carolinas, Chesnutt left behind the
plantation, and also humor, in order to probe more deeply the lives
of mixed-blood characters living in the middle-class world of W. E
.B. Du Bois's ``Talented Tenth'' of black Americans, from which the
solutions to the endemic racial crisis, and the leaders of the
race, were supposed to come. The heroine of ``The House Behind the
Cedars'' passes for white, entrances a white man, is exposed and
comes to an unhappy end. ``The Marrow of Tradition'' links two
families, one black and the other white, united by blood but almost
hopelessly divided (although not quite) by racism and the obsession
of whites with crushing even the most legitimate ambitions of
blacks in the aftermath of the Civil War. So trenchant was
Chesnutt's analysis of Southern society that many white readers in
the North as well as the South questioned his basic objectivity;
this lack of sympathy translated into weak sales and doomed
Chesnutt's ambition to live by his writings.
</P>
<P>
   The fact that ``Paul Marchand, F.M.C.,'' which Chesnutt finished
in 1921, was rejected by Houghton Mifflin, Harcourt Brace and
Alfred A. Knopf is not hard to understand _ just as it is easy to
see why its publication now, with an excellent introduction by
Matthew Wilson, who teaches the humanities and writing at the
Pennsylvania State University, is a boon not only to Chesnutt
studies but to our understanding of the questions raised by his
art. Still inspired by these questions, Chesnutt had ventured into
another fictional investigation of the tension between nature and
culture that is at the heart of our American understanding and
experience of race.
</P>
<P>
   This novel is, in its essence, about a man, Paul Marchand,
brought up to think of himself as a black _ or, more accurately, as
a man of mixed blood _ who discovers as an adult that he is in fact
white. Suddenly, too, he becomes the wealthy and powerful head of
an extended white family that has little sympathy for mixed-bloods
and blacks. The question _ whether Marchand should discard his
mixed-race wife, whom he loves but who has no legal standing in
Louisiana society _ is piquant but not nearly as important as the
question of whether he can ever hope to overcome the feelings of
inferiority and psychological turmoil conditioned in him. Can such
a man ever become whole, and wholesome?
</P>
<P>
   Such questions concerning race still resonate with us, and
certainly resounded in the 1920's, when racial ``science'' was in
its heyday in the United States; and Chesnutt answers them again,
as in the past, in provocative ways. In 1921 he was still ahead of
his time _ although in other ways his art was outmoded. In
developing his characters, setting and plot, he had reached
arthritically into the past of local-color writing for a too-shiny
Louisiana tale of French Creoles, alabaster maidens, haunted
octoroons, desperate duels, miraculous wills and letters, and the
like. White editors and publishers uneasy with his disquieting
perspective on race (as the liberal Richard Watson Gilder and
William Dean Howells, for example, had been earlier in his career
even as they sought to help and guide Chesnutt) perhaps saw a
relatively easy way out, and took it _ they rejected the book.
Nevertheless, behind the tired literary devices are a vibrant
intelligence and an astute cultural sense on which we can draw as
we continue our own wrestling in the brier patch of race.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Arnold Rampersad is a professor of English at Stanford
University. His most recent book is ``Jackie Robinson: A
Biography.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
