<HEADER>
A1040 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-BREAKING-NYTS     10-22 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-BREAKING-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BREAKING NEWS
</HEADLINE>
  By Robert MacNeil 
 406 pp. New York: Nan A. Talese/Doubleday. $24.95 
 ------ 
 WE TAKE YOU LIVE 
 By ERIC ALTERMAN 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   I did not expect to be charmed by a novel written by a former
PBS news anchor any more than I expected to learn a bit of Yiddish
from someone named Robert MacNeil. But one ought not complain about
life's more pleasant surprises _ particularly when they come from a
man whose program prided itself, in the words of Judy Woodruff, on
its daring willingness ``to be boring.'' ``Breaking News,''
MacNeil's third novel, is not only far from boring, it is also a
provocative cri de coeur aimed at what one character calls
``information/entertainment television.''
</P>
<P>
   MacNeil's hero, Grant Munroe, is facing a life crisis and a
professional crisis simultaneously. He is nearing 60 and musing
over a possible face lift, worried about both his job as network
anchorman and his dignity. Raised on Walter Cronkite, Munroe is a
hard-news man, whereas his producer, Marty Boyle, is younger,
hipper and more in tune with the times. When Grant suggests leading
the evening broadcast with Middle East peace talks, because ``it's
the most important thing that happened today,'' Marty replies:
``Sure, you're right. But we've got pictures of the little girl in
Wyoming who was raped and found dead in the woods; great family
videos of her, cute and poignant as hell. What do you show for the
Mideast? Guys in suits walking in and out of offices. Maybe for
excitement some have no ties on?''
</P>
<P>
   Upon accepting one of those awards anchormen always seem to be
receiving, Munroe delivers a prime time J'accuse to his own
profession. Munroe likens himself and his colleagues to ``Gadarene
swine . . . in our new and insane competitiveness; in our rising
desperation for ratings; our prurient glee in discussing the
President's sex life; in our rush to report unsubstantiated rumor,
leaks and gossip.''
</P>
<P>
   The outburst inspires an editor at Time magazine to assign a
cover profile of Munroe, just as his twin crises are getting into
gear. This plot device gives MacNeil an easy short cut into
Munroe's various depressing thoughts about the state of broadcast
news today. But it also inspires the higher-ups at the network to
wonder whether ``Grant is beginning to lose it.''
</P>
<P>
   The novel tells a grown-up story about a group of privileged
people whose days are dominated by the never-ending news cycle and
whose evenings are spent on the Upper West Side, bordered by Cafe
Des Artistes to the south and Fairway and Citarella to the north.
MacNeil has a Canadian's eye for the many conceits of American
media celebrity, and he uses it to great effect here. If you ever
wondered what it must be like to be rich, handsome, famous and
pampered, to be in late middle age but have beautiful young airline
attendants throw themselves at you just the same, a few hours in
the company of Grant Munroe will tell you, and you will even come
away liking and admiring him.
</P>
<P>
   The plot of ``Breaking News'' is a bit complicated, sometimes
overly so. It's easier to make sense of it if you substitute
real-world identities for each of MacNeil's main characters. For
Grant himself, think Dan Rather (without the weird,
frequency-related questions for ``Kenneth''). For Munroe's network,
whose news ratings are in the toilet, think CBS. For the
celebrity-chasing, prime time star the network is seeking to lure
to goose its ratings, think a younger, more Machiavellian Barbara
Walters. Some of the inventions are distinct improvements over
their real-life counterparts. Instead of the ghoulish Matt Drudge,
for instance, we get a black drag-queen cybergossip who calls
herself ``Hollygo.'' ``Want to know what I look like, honey?'' she
says. ``Think Ru Paul . . . on a bad day.''
</P>
<P>
   By the novel's end, MacNeil has delivered some extremely
disheartening news about the state of our national news media
wrapped neatly in a shiny literary package. Jim Lehrer's loss is
fiction's gain.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Eric Alterman is a columnist for The Nation and MSNBC, and the
author of ``Who Speaks for America?''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
