<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 10:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1041 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-TOURISTS-NYTS     10-22 1163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-TOURISTS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEDUCTIVE JOURNEY
</HEADLINE>
  American Tourists in France From Jefferson to the Jazz Age 
 By Harvey Levenstein 
 Illustrated. 378 pp. Chicago: The University of Chicago Press. $30 
 ------ 
 LIBERTE, EGALITE, INFIDELITE 
 By DEIRDRE BAIR 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Almost everyone who has ever tried to keep a travel diary seeks
the perfect opening statement, one that sets the tone for the
memorable sights and scenes that follow. But who could possibly top
Robert Johnson, a young Connecticut lawyer on a grand tour of
France in 1792-93, who ``on the 21st of January, the second day of
my arrival . . . mixed with the citizens and saw Louis XVI
beheaded''?
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's is one of the many travel diaries culled by Harvey
Levenstein, an emeritus professor of history at McMaster
University, for ``Seductive Journey.'' He has combined the pithy,
amusing and sometimes embarrassing comments of Americans writing
about France with new insights into the cultural history of going
abroad. He explores how our experiences and expectations of foreign
countries and cultures are shaped by who we are and where we come
from, and the result is a thoroughly readable and highly likable
book.
</P>
<P>
   Levenstein separates American tourists in the years 1786-1848
into two groups that could be loosely defined as ``Jefferson''
versus ``Adams.'' Jefferson was ``violently smitten'' with
everything French, whereas Adams did not like ``any Frenchman''
because ``they are not a moral people.'' His wife, Abigail, enjoyed
her friend Jefferson's company on sightseeing jaunts but she shared
her husband's views, especially about sexual matters. To her,
Levenstein says, the easy acceptance of adultery by the French
higher classes was an indication of ``general moral and societal
disintegration.'' Even more distressing was what she saw as a
feeble commitment to family life, exemplified by the French
family's three or four children, whereas Americans often had eight
or nine.
</P>
<P>
   Americans in these years boarded unsafe ships for uncertain
journeys of three to six weeks, enduring violent seasickness and
frequently dying in shipwrecks. Emerson thought it ``strange that
the first man who came to sea did not turn round and go straight
back again,'' but a wealthy New Yorker, Philip Hone, noted
accurately that ``all the world (our world) is going to Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans who traveled to France between 1848 and 1870
represented the shift from ``cultural'' to ``recreational''
tourism, Levenstein writes. Previously, travel had been reserved as
an educational experience for men, but now women crossed the ocean
in ever growing numbers. These nouveaux riches went not only to
experience art and culture but also (and more important) to shop _
when they were not scheming for introductions to the ``dubious
monarch'' Emperor Napoleon III and his ``ersatz aristocrats.''
</P>
<P>
   Harriet Beecher Stowe, the ``archpriestess of middle-class
morality,'' derided her countrymen as the ``parasites of
parasites'' for the way they jostled to become ``hangers-on and
applauders in the train of that tyrant who has overthrown the hopes
of France.'' This led the old rich to ``keeping away from the
Joneses,'' exemplified by elaborate suites on ever larger luxury
liners, private railway cars and private houses or apartments far
from the parvenu crowd. It also resulted in ``the feminization of
American tourism,'' when women became the primary transmitters and
appreciators of high culture and all things artistic. Yet by
holding women responsible for the ``feminization of art
appreciation,'' men had an excuse to enjoy themselves in other
ways, since visiting museums and galleries was no longer considered
``a mark of distinction among cultivated males.'' Mark Twain was
representative when he called da Vinci's ``Last Supper'' ``dark,
dirty and damaged by Napoleon's horses'' and thought that most of
the masterpieces he saw in Europe ``came nowhere near matching''
the reproductions he saw at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leisure'' tourism began around 1870 and ended with World War I
in 1914. Writing of the seemingly aimless and endless wanderings of
rich men dragged across the Continent by their virago wives,
Levenstein describes how these ``prisoners of leisure'' followed
the ``year-round international upper-class tourist circuit'' from
Paris to the Riviera or Biarritz, then back for another season at
Chantilly and Longchamps, then to various Channel resorts.
Seventeen trunks of clothes were considered normal for a woman on
this ``veritable orgy of conspicuous consumption of clothing and
leisure.''
</P>
<P>
   But the middle class also took to traveling in ever increasing
numbers. Unmarried women in search of adventure (and romance) were
soon joined by groups like the ``Masons from Allegheny City,
Penn.,'' who took the first ``Cook's tour'' in 1871. By the Paris
Exposition of 1889, Cook's had solidified its reputation and
financial success by focusing on the middle class, especially
summer tours for teachers, with which the company would be
associated in the public mind for many years to come. Steamship
companies took notice as well, and many ocean liners were fitted
with a preponderance of second- and third-class compartments.
</P>
<P>
   In his concluding section, ``The Invasion of the Lower Orders:
1917-30,'' Levenstein shows how every previous attitude toward
travel in France coalesced in the behavior of the doughboys, some
of it good, but most of it bad. France had come to be seen by
Americans of every social class as ``the pleasure capital of the
world,'' and despite warnings from the military newspaper, Stars
and Stripes, not to treat it as ``a universal pleasure resort,''
many did, in the most appalling ways. The ugly American had been
born.
</P>
<P>
   The writer Kathleen Howard noted that instead of ``women of
exceptional elegance, men of large affairs, with a goodly supply of
lace-collared, flat-heeled schoolteachers,'' a different class of
people was coming to postwar Paris, referring to what Levenstein
lumps together as ``Americans pursuing other kinds of pleasures.''
He discusses these briefly but succinctly, from the artistic (jazz,
modern art, literature) to the sexual (``France's growing
reputation as a center of lesbianism'').
</P>
<P>
   Mme. de Stael called foreign travel ``one of the saddest
pleasures in life''; the inimitable Malcolm Muggeridge abhorred it,
saying, ``Travel narrows.'' But Americans, predominant among the 50
million tourists who each year visit a country whose population
barely surpasses that number, think of France as the ``center of
the American tourist's universe.'' ``Seductive Journey'' does much
to remind us why.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Deirdre Bair is completing a biography of C. G. Jung.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
</TEXT>
