<DOCNO> NYT19981022.0117 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 10:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1042 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-EMOTIONAL-NYT     10-22 1176
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-EMOTIONAL-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKING WITH EMOTIONAL INTELLIGENCE
</HEADLINE>
  By Daniel Goleman 
 383 pp. New York: Bantam Books. $25.95 
 ------ 
 IT AIN'T WHAT YOU KNOW 
 By WARREN BENNIS 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It's beyond me!'' an enraged talk-radio caller screamed into
his car phone recently. ``It's just beyond me that a guy with all
that political savvy, brains and ambition could be so stupid. I
just don't get it.'' He was talking, of course, about Bill Clinton.
Having spent a lifetime studying exemplary and not so exemplary
leaders, I have to confess that I wasn't all that astounded, though
no less angry.
</P>
<P>
   My loss of innocence came a long time ago, when I was asked to
evaluate the No. 2 executive in a large global corporation for the
firm's top post. Let's call him Ed. He seemed ideal: energetic,
ambitious and super-smart. It took me about six months to come to
the conclusion that though Ed looked perfect, he lacked a crucial
ingredient of leadership _ integrity. Nobody trusted him, and I
couldn't help him. The board ignored my advice, and when the
incumbent chief executive officer had a heart attack, in a
collective panic it elevated Ed. He was summarily discharged only
12 months later. A conservative estimate of his cost to the company
was over $5 million.
</P>
<P>
   I included this story in one of my books, and to this day get
letters telling me, ``Ed's my boss.'' If I'd had Daniel Goleman's
``Working With Emotional Intelligence'' back then, I could have
saved that company $5 million for only $25.95. Maybe Ed could have
been saved too.
</P>
<P>
   Goleman is writing about a subject most of us think we know a
great deal about: maturity, emotional health, ``grownupness'' _ and
about how those qualities, which help make up ``emotional
intelligence,'' affect our own and others' careers and job
performance. And he does this with such clarity, convincing data
and literary power that few readers will view the personal and
social undercurrents of organizations in quite the same way again.
</P>
<P>
   Goleman, also the author of the hugely popular ``Emotional
Intelligence,'' among other books, and a former contributor to The
New York Times, is now the chief executive officer of Emotional
Intelligence Services, a consulting company. He has based this new
book on data collected on more than 500 companies worldwide and on
interviews with professionals and employees from all walks of life.
The essence of his findings can be summed up simply: emotional
intelligence, more than any other factor, more than I.Q. or
expertise, accounts for 85 percent to 90 percent of success at
work. In effect, he confirms what we know in our bones.
</P>
<P>
   Goleman argues that I.Q. leaves about 75 percent of job success
unexplained at best, and at worst, 96 percent. He cites a study of
Harvard graduates working in law, medicine, teaching and business
that found that scores on entrance exams, the equivalent to I.Q.,
had zero or negative correlation with their career success. In
those fields, and many others I have studied, emotional
intelligence is much more powerful than I.Q. in determining who
emerges as a leader. I.Q. is a threshold competence. You need it,
but it doesn't make you a star. Emotional intelligence can.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working With Emotional Intelligence'' lays out the framework
Goleman proposed in his earlier book. ``Personal competence''
includes self-awareness (knowing one's internal states),
self-regulation (managing one's internal states) and motivation
(emotional tendencies that help one reach goals). ``Social
competence'' has two major dimensions, empathy (awareness of
others' feelings) and social skills (adeptness at getting desirable
responses from others). For each of the five dimensions of
emotional intelligence, Goleman identifies five key skills. He
refers to these as ``emotional competencies.'' To take just a few
examples, under self-regulation he includes self-control (managing
one's disruptive emotions) and trustworthiness (maintaining
standards of honesty and integrity). Empathy includes understanding
others, leveraging diversity (which Goleman defines as
``cultivating opportunities through diverse people'') and political
awareness.
</P>
<P>
   Goleman's framework is illuminating, but how he applies it is
even more important. In one of his most creative chapters he sets
forth an original model for enhancing emotional competencies,
establishing detailed guidelines for developing each of them.
Goleman understands all too well that most of the dollars spent on
executive training and development are devoted to the cognitive
area of the brain, the neocortex. These courses are very like the
ones we took in college, favoring the ``thinking brain.'' And
indeed, fitting new insights and data into the neural circuitry may
be helpful for many technical jobs. What Goleman calls ``the
billion dollar mistake'' comes in failing to engage the emotional
circuitry. In fact, it's worse than that. It's a $250 billion
mistake, the amount spent annually, according to Linkage Inc., a
management consulting firm, on executive development. I now think
of it as the Great Training Robbery.
</P>
<P>
   I do have one or two problems with the book. Goleman argues that
his five encompassing emotional competencies are hierarchical: that
is, self-awareness is crucial for self-regulation, and empathy and
its four competencies are crucial for social skills. But let's look
at President Clinton's behavior, which so inflamed the talk-show
caller. If emotional competencies are indeed hierarchical, how
could Clinton skip self-regulation (including impulse control and
trustworthiness) without hampering his fabled empathy and social
skills? I also have difficulty believing that the 25 competencies
are of equal value, as Goleman contends. Isn't integrity more
salient for high office than, to take one example, leveraging
diversity?
</P>
<P>
   In making his case, Goleman may also play down the importance of
effective systems or structure in an organization's success. He
tells us about a high-flying executive search firm where everyone
is paid on the basis of overall, not individual, performance. The
average salary of the consultants was $908,000, almost double the
industry average; Goleman attributes the company's outstanding
performance to the collective emotional intelligence of its top
officers. But I can't help wondering if a reward system that
encouraged collaboration wasn't at least as important.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone interested in leadership and the health of human
institutions should get a copy of this book. In fact, I recommend
it to all readers anywhere who want to see their organizations in
the phone book in the year 2001.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Warren Bennis is a professor of business administration at the
University of Southern California and co-author of ``Organizing
Genius.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
