<DOCNO> NYT19981022.0118 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 10:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1043 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-CRIME-NYTSF     10-22 1058
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-CRIME-NYTSF </SLUG>
 
 By MARILYN STASIOx 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Matt Scudder has certainly calmed down since the old days. The
life-scarred New York veteran of 13 city-wise crime novels by
Lawrence Block shows up for action in EVERYBODY DIES (Morrow, $25)
in a contented fog. Wry and ruminative by nature, the aging shamus
hasn't entirely lost his edge, but still: he's happily married,
he's been off the sauce for 16 years, he has his private
investigator's license, he eats mushroom-and-tofu stroganoff
(``with a big green salad''), and he carries an umbrella.
</P>
<P>
   It's all a setup, of course, for the devastating events that
teach him a sobering lesson: people die and he can't do a thing
about it. The first deaths _ the execution of two hired hands who
worked for Scudder's gangster friend Mick (the Butcher) Ballou, the
``bloodthirsty but somehow engaging'' owner of the last great Irish
saloon in Hell's Kitchen _ don't really register. But when mobsters
bomb the saloon, drive Mick underground and mow down Scudder's A.A.
sponsor trying to kill him, he gets the message. Scudder keeps
saying that this is Mick's story, and in the sense that this
colorful and complicated rogue is responsible for all the trouble
(and much of the grand dialogue), it is. But it is Scudder who
ponders the metaphysics, striking the tone of loss, resignation and
acceptance that makes this one of the most harrowing yet most
rewarding chapters in the education of a hero.
</P>
<P>
   The air of dreamlike menace that hovers over TRICK OF LIGHT
(Putnam, $24.95), David Hunt's second thriller (after ``The
Magician's Tale''), transforms San Francisco from a daytime city of
brilliant color and clarity into an eerie nether world ``enveloped
in fog, swaddled in mystery and mist.'' This enigmatic aura comes
filtered through the perspective of the narrator, a profoundly
color-blind photographer named Kay Farrow, who sees subtlety and
shadow and infinite gradations of truth where others see only the
blinding hues of reality. ``Night's my time,'' Kay tells us, the
time when her light-sensitive eyes can focus on the negative images
that absorb her imagination.
</P>
<P>
   The death of Kay's beloved mentor in a fishy hit-and-run
accident takes her to the seedy Mission District, where the older
woman was working in secret on a project involving naked women and
men in suits. Caught by the feeling of ``menace, depravity, even
evil'' in the murky photographs her teacher left behind, Kay
searches for their ``implicate order _ that which is implicit yet
hidden from view.'' Following her own vision (and nudged on by
Hunt's hypnotic prose), Kay conducts an investigation that goes
down some very dark alleys and leads to some very bleak truths. But
in the inverted imagery of this strange world, the blacker it gets,
the lovelier it looks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like it used to be'' _ the nostalgic whine of New
Yorkers fretting over the changes in their old ethnic neighborhoods
_ conveys something more sinister in S. J. Rozan's latest Lydia
Chin mystery, A BITTER FEAST (St. Martin's, $23.95). Although
Chinatown still functions as the patriarchal big-city village that
Lydia knew as a child, the feudal political structure has shifted
in ways that the freelance private eye fails to notice until four
restaurant workers disappear and the office of their upstart labor
union is firebombed. Working undercover as a dim sum waitress,
Lydia learns that the Cantonese elder statesman who hired her (a
godfather figure who reminds her partner, Bill Smith, of the Wizard
of Oz) is engaged in a nasty power struggle with the leader of the
new immigrants from China's Fujian Province.
</P>
<P>
   Rozan, who won the Shamus Award for the best private-eye novel
of 1995 with ``Concourse,'' brings a great deal of freshness to the
formula conventions _ if you can overlook certain corny routines,
like Lydia's girlish skirmishes with her mother and her strained
sexual banter with Bill. The smart, crisp writing makes up for such
lapses, as does the remarkably sharp sense of place. The rich
sights, sounds and textures of daily life in Chinatown are a
sumptuous feast for jaded palates.
</P>
<P>
   Evan Evans, the sweet-tempered constable who keeps watch over
the little Welsh village of Llanfair in a new series of cozy
mysteries by Rhys Bowen, knows little of the world and less of
women. But he proves his bravery twice over in EVAN HELP US (St.
Martin's, $21.95), first by simultaneously fending off the advances
of the local barmaid and a sexy number just arrived from
Manchester, and then by venturing to London in the course of a
murder investigation. ``I grew up in Swansea, which I always
thought of as a big city,'' he tells his sergeant, ``but it's
nothing compared to this.'' Unlike the humor in the tart country
series that M. C. Beaton sets in a quarrelsome village in the
Scottish Highlands (and which Bowen seems to be emulating here),
the jokes don't get any racier than this. The characters don't get
any more complicated either. Indeed, the pleasure of visiting
Llanfair is that nothing, not even murder, can ruffle its placid
composure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Art restoring is a vicious business,'' Iain Pears informs us
in DEATH AND RESTORATION (Scribner, $22), another gleeful excursion
into the cutthroat art world for Pears's esthete-sleuth, Jonathan
Argyll, and his companion, Flavia di Stefano, a senior investigator
for Italy's Art Theft Squad. Most of the legwork falls to Flavia
when an icon is stolen from a rundown monastery in Rome and a
French dealer (``the oldest and canniest icon man in the
business'') is discovered floating in the Tiber. This frees up
Jonathan to sprinkle his acidic wit on art experts and thieves like
Dan Menzies (``the Al Capone of restoration''), who has been
engaged by the monastery to apply his savage artistry to its
dubious Caravaggio. By anchoring his subject in a sturdy plot and
sublime setting, Pears offers more reason to delight in the
articulate characters and erudite art commentary that give his
books _ including the best-selling ``Instance of the Fingerpost'' _
their high style.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
