<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 10:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1044 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-FIRE-NYTSF     10-22 0725
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-FIRE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRIENDLY FIRE
</HEADLINE>
  By Kathryn Chetkovich 
 116 pp. Iowa City: University of Iowa Press. Paper, $15.95 
 ------ 
 DUCK! 
 By ROSS FELD 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kathryn Chetkovich's first collection of stories is knitted with
a very open weave. Based more on situations than plots, it spreads
out lazily rather than trace tortured lines. Chetkovich is a
sharp-eyed observer, which has a lot to do with this open feel; the
world always seems bigger when someone brings along a microscope.
</P>
<P>
   In a typical passage from the title story, a group of women are
at the end of one of their regular eat-and-schmooze evenings. The
hostess's son enters the house with some friends: ``Our hellos
chirp and bob, and Todd's uneven voice slides under them like a
shovel scraping pavement.'' Or consider this, from ``My Real
Life'': ``The song, which I had never heard before, was filled with
disorienting pauses and German lyrics, giving it the quality of an
overseas phone call with a poor connection.'' Chetkovich is
especially good about clothes, describing in ``Magic Acts'' a woman
who often looked as though she had been ``dressed by children, or
birds.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout ``Friendly Fire,'' Chetkovich modestly inserts
herself into her characters' wry, bright realizations. In ``Magic
Acts,'' a character riding in a car and watching the pedestrians
(``a picture of inefficiency somehow _ each person coming from a
place someone else needs to go'') is led to understand that ``being
healed does not always require finding the cure.'' Yet it's odd:
such wise, level-headed characters have a way of draining out some
of the pleasure for the reader. On an excursion with passengers who
make such effortless sense of their experiences, what's left for
you to do? Your own skills rust.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, these stories attempt to be about the decency of not
having the final, be-all-and-end-all word. They forgo brilliance
and spectacular turns. Even their sentences sometimes toggle,
wanting to stay pliable: ``I found myself wondering where he had
been tonight and who the flowers had been for. Whom.''
</P>
<P>
   The title story is illustrative. Fire here doesn't consume; it
warms in an amiable manner in a gentle, plotless evocation of
supportive women friends. The women are friends, however, very much
in the television sit-com mode: they're somehow commodified,
friends as party mix. The more nettling dimensions of their
relationships are left alone: friends who challenge, who have the
bad manners to remind you how much they remember of your failures.
</P>
<P>
   In aggregate, there's a lot of inert not-quiteness to the
situations of the characters in these stories. Friends without
claims; childless couples; grown children beginning to see their
parents fail _ all this can be poignant, but it also suggests
wheels spinning in place. Better are two stories that simply go
one-on-one, with a man and a woman more or less alone.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Damages,'' a married man's tryst is given accidental
meaning when, out with his about-to-be-mistress, he scrapes a
parked car. The woman he's with wants him to own up to the action _
to any action, really. This he's reluctantly prepared to do, but
when he knocks on the door of the house he can hear that he's
interrupting a scene of uncomplicated family happiness. He backs
away.
</P>
<P>
   In the collection's most beguiling story, ``As Needed,'' a
chance meeting on the subway leads to uncertain attraction, maybe
even love. A man flirtatiously rests his briefcase on a woman's lap
as he juggles to hold on to the overhead bar, then accidentally (or
maybe not) leaves the case behind. The woman must figure out a way
to return it.
</P>
<P>
   The story manages to wind itself around the mystery of how much
of life is scripted to desires we broadcast without even realizing
them. In doing so, both it and ``Damages'' satisfyingly edge toward
the shadows, under which they pick up weight. They're a lot more
impressive than Chetkovich's stories of plucky but becalmed social
sandwiching.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Ross Feld's novels include ``Only Shorter'' and ``Shapes
Mistaken.''
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
