<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 10:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1045 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-ADDIE-NYTSF     10-22 1481
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-ADDIE-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADDIE
</HEADLINE>
  By Mary Lee Settle 
 237 pp. Columbia: University of South Carolina Press. $24.95 
 ------ 
 GRANDMA IN A TREE 
 By ANGELINE GOREAU 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Early one West Virginia summer afternoon, on the cusp of the
Great Depression, Mary Lee Settle's grandmother woke her from a
porch nap with the news that ``the Catholic Church is the Whore of
Babylon in the Book of Revelation.''
</P>
<P>
   Having delivered herself of this observation, Miss Addie sat
back in her rocker and proceeded to tell 8-year-old Mary Lee her
version of a hitherto unadmitted family scandal. The story begins
with Addie's first marriage, at 15, to a very ``devil'' of a coal
miner and ends three years later with the young wife up a tree,
terrified of her drunken husband prowling below, and hearing the
voice of Jesus. ``Addie,'' He tells her, ``you are nuthin but a
damn fool. Ain't you ever heard of divorce?''
</P>
<P>
   That Mary Lee Settle, at the age of 79, has chosen to cast her
own autobiography in the form of a memoir of her grandmother seems
entirely appropriate to the writer we have come to know through her
novels. She is, famously, a restless seeker of the larger view: the
Beulah Quintet, her epic fictional investigation into the meaning
of being an American, begins with a single image of a woman lost in
the Endless Mountains and follows the consequences of that scene
first forward, then back in time.
</P>
<P>
   Settle had already published ``O Beulah Land,'' whose events
unfurl in the two decades leading up to the American Revolution,
and ``Know Nothing,'' set in the years before the Civil War, before
deciding that another novel needed to come before them. Layering
and expanding, adding forebears to explain the original characters,
she circled back, more than a decade after writing the first book,
to summon up another beginning, giving us in ``Prisons'' the
17th-century Puritans and Cavaliers whose experiences seem crucial
to an understanding of the pioneers of 18th-century Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   So perhaps it isn't surprising that ``Addie'' should open with
the following words: ``An autobiography that begins with one's
birth begins too late, in the middle of the story, sometimes at the
end.'' The beginning of Settle's story, then, is not necessarily
what simple chronology might suggest. Rather, it is the most
important moment, the moment from which consequences pool out in
ever-widening circles, shaping the choices made by those who come
after. As in her novels, chronology derives from meaning.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the turning point of Settle's life comes well before her
birth, with the divorce Addie finally owns up to on that summer
afternoon in 1927 _ though the facts of the case, unearthed by her
granddaughter from court records, differ substantially from Addie's
recall. She may well have heard Jesus from the top of the tree,
advising her to seek legal redress, but she was in fact 26 years
old, not 18, and already pregnant by the man she would marry only
three years later. The child of that interstice was Mary Lee
Settle's mother. In her turn, Settle's mother would refuse to own
up to the whole story.
</P>
<P>
   The principal focus here is not, as in so much recent
autobiography, revelation or reproach. Rather, Settle is interested
in the way one understands truth by indirection. ``It had been one
of the first divorces in West Virginia, but the facts are misty,
the legends crossed, and I saw more truth if not more fact in the
way Addie told it that day,'' Settle writes. Later on in the book
she remarks that ``the false has to be weighed for its elements of
truth.'' Through all her novels, Settle returns again and again to
the subject of memory's distortions, both personal and collective.
</P>
<P>
   Addie and the grandfather in question, whom she always called
Mr. Tompkins, not only scandalized turn-of-the-century West
Virginia by their out-of-wedlock doings; they also represented an
unwelcome (socially unwelcome) grafting of classes. Mr. Tompkins
was the petted scion of local gentry and Addie the wife of a coal
miner. She had never lived in a house with more than one story.
That he was siphoning off the remains of a once-impressive fortune
into drink and horseflesh mattered little.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Tompkins's relatives _ and neighbors _ conspired to freeze
Addie out, mainly by treating her as an invisible person. Mr.
Tompkins was invited to balls and weddings and dinners as before,
but hosts never made mention of his wife. Addie, with her country
ways, ``rattled their gentility.'' Mr. Tompkins's brother Charlie
even dared to cadge an invitation to freeload at their house when
he was short of cash, but noted in his letter, ``I must have your
assurance that I won't have to speak to that woman.'' According to
her granddaughter, Addie found the letter in Mr. Tompkins's office
and rushed off with it, throwing herself on a pile of laundry and
crying: ``Lord! . . . You promised that you would make my enemies
my footstool. WHEN?''
</P>
<P>
   Without Settle's careful excavation of the Tompkins family
pretensions, we could hardly appreciate the irony of the situation.
Addie's tormentor was the son of a man who began life as an
apprentice gunsmith: ``New rich only 40 years before,'' Settle
tells us, ``by the 1880's the Tompkins family were old rich. They
owned land for literally miles along the narrow valley of the
Kanawha River,'' and they ``saw themselves as gentry.'' Their
gentility, though somewhat tarnished by the defeat of the
Confederacy, was nevertheless defended by eschewing ``lace curtains
and ice water'' as well as the ``city-tacky'' ways of nouveau riche
Yankees who had dinner at night rather than the proper hour of 3
o'clock in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Their most vicious assault on Addie, however, involved removing
the corpses of their hallowed Presbyterian ancestors _ William
Tompkins and his wife _ from their Etruscan-style tomb on the
grounds of the family mansion, presumably to avoid contamination by
the low-class interloper their brother had married.
</P>
<P>
   Addie took her revenge by returning to the Church of God Holy
Rollers and wearing poke bonnets of her own manufacture.
Nevertheless, Settle remarks, ``there was a core of suffering that
Addie had been handed and she handed it on to her children as
surely as if it were part of their genes.'' Some of her suffering
was also caused by her daughter, Rachel, Settle's mother, who
cleaved ferociously to the very society that had cast out Addie.
Rachel became her mother's rival for Mr. Tompkins's affections and
attention, and secretly visited his ``nice'' relatives, religiously
taking up their pretentious ways and mythologizing the family past.
</P>
<P>
   Rachel grew up to be someone whose obsession with propriety
effectively prevented any real connection to her own daughter.
``Touch made her flesh crawl,'' Settle writes. ``I learned it early
when I fell against her by accident, half-asleep in the car when I
was 3, and she recoiled.'' It was Addie who provided real
affection, comfort, a ready ear. She shaped the core of Settle's
inner self _ the self one writes novels out of. ``What informed the
largest work that I have done, the Beulah Quintet, lay so deep
within,'' Settle tells us, ``so early sown, so dependent on Addie,
her voices, her world, that I was unconscious of it.''
</P>
<P>
   In excavating the circumstances that sent Addie up that tree to
talk to Jesus, Settle moves skillfully from the first inhabitants
of the valley to the coming of the railroads and coal mines to the
Civil War and the riots incited by Mother Jones and the Great
Depression, then turns back to herself as a young writer
discovering tea chests of pioneers' scalps in the basement of the
British Museum as she is imagining the Kanawha Valley as a
fictional place she calls Beulah Land.
</P>
<P>
   There is, as in many family stories, plenty of abuse and
betrayal, scandal, failed love, disappointed expectation. There is
even, more exceptionally, murder and suicide. But Settle's wide
empathetic grasp, her layering of context, her persistent search
for meaning put them in perspective _ they are part of the story,
but not the point.
</P>
<P>
   That she has brought her considerable skills and vision as a
novelist to the writing of autobiography is reason enough to feel
grateful. But, in addition, Mary Lee Settle has preserved for us a
moment in the South's history palpable as the trumpet vines and
rocking chairs of a long-departed front-porch afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   Angeline Goreau, the author of ``Reconstructing Aphra: A Social
Biography of Aphra Behn,'' is writing a novel set along the
Mississippi River in the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   ----------
</P>
<P>
   (Nonsubscribers: To publish this article, call a New York Times
Syndicate sales representative, Bob Farnell, Olivia Vasquez or
Connie White, at (888) 2-NYTSYN (888-269-8796).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-98 1020EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981022.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 10:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1046 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NYTBOOK-LERNER-NYTSF     10-22 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYTBOOK-LERNER-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAX LERNER
</HEADLINE>
  Pilgrim in the Promised Land 
 By Sanford Lakoff 
 323 pp. Chicago: The University of Chicago Press. $25 
 ------ 
 TABLOID PHILOSOPHER 
 By DAVID GREENBERG 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Max Lerner, who died in 1992 at 89, was a public intellectual of
the variety whose passing everyone loves to lament these days. ``It
can safely be said,'' Sanford Lakoff safely says in ``Max Lerner:
Pilgrim in the Promised Land,'' ``that no American writer in the
century wrote for as many different audiences.'' Academic and
journalist, teacher and critic, Lerner contributed to both social
science periodicals and Playboy magazine, highbrow opinion journals
and The New York Post. His erudition ranged over law, economics,
history, culture and foreign affairs _ all touched on in his 1957
magnum opus, ``America as a Civilization'' _ and he wrote regularly
into his final year.
</P>
<P>
   Lerner, however, was no boring egghead. Well into his golden
years, he caught people's fancy not just with his political columns
but with his frank embrace of the sexual revolution, frequenting
free-love communes in the early 1970's and befriending Hugh Hefner.
</P>
<P>
   A life as colorful as Lerner's poses a special challenge to a
biographer. Should you focus on the rich story of the man's
intellectual development or explore his psyche? Lakoff, a professor
emeritus of political science at the University of California, San
Diego, and a former student of Lerner's, has gamely attempted both
in his concise and thoughtful new biography. Strong as an analysis
of Lerner's ideas, it is somewhat less so as a portrait of the man.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trajectory of Lerner's change of political views,'' Lakoff
writes, ``is an illuminating index to the shift in thinking among
many public intellectuals in 'the American century.' '' A radical
foe of capitalism in his youth, Lerner became a spokesman for
mainstream liberalism in his middle years and a cranky
neoconservative as he aged. Lakoff doesn't challenge this common
appraisal, but he does complicate it. He argues, for example, that
Lerner, even in his youth, was drawn less to Marx than to the
sociologist Thorstein Veblen, whom he admired as ``a
tongue-in-cheek agitator, more Mencken than Lenin.'' Lakoff also
shows that if, as some have charged, Lerner was slow to acknowledge
the brutality of Stalin's Soviet Union or to see the folly of the
Vietnam War, he was prescient in calling for American entry into
World War II and recognition of Israel. Less adequately explained,
however, is the civil libertarian's embrace of anti-flag-burning
laws.
</P>
<P>
   While the book generally succeeds as intellectual biography, it
disappoints a bit as a character study. To his credit, Lakoff
recognizes the significance of his subject's private life, from the
affairs he had with his students as a young Sarah Lawrence
professor to the goings-on at the Playboy mansion. But he never
really takes us into Lerner's inner life, perhaps because he seems
never to arrive there himself. He sterilizes Lerner's
countercultural escapades by dwelling on their intellectual aspects
_ by explicating, for example, Lerner's opinions about Freud and
Norman O. Brown. Topics such as Lerner's second marriage or his
relationship with his children get only passing attention,
depriving us of seeing critical sides of Lerner's personality.
</P>
<P>
   Still, in the dangerous territory of the links between private
behavior and public persona, Lakoff lays out a plausible
correlation between his subject's intellectual and sexual ardors;
both, he suggests, grew out of the same craving for experience.
``In my own case,'' he quotes Lerner as writing, ``the hunger for
erotic acceptance, still unsated, and the impulse to storm the city
and conquer the domain of ideas and letters . . . were connected in
a circuit.'' For Lerner, as for Freud, eros was a life force. And a
key to understanding this most ambitious and vital of public
intellectuals is appreciating his intense and passionate engagement
with the world.
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   David Greenberg is a Richard Hofstadter Fellow in American
History at Columbia University and a columnist for Slate.
</P>
<P>
