New York: Atlantic Monthly Press. $24. In Fay Weldon's novel, a
group of friends forms a publishing house in the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   NYTBOOK-CASANOVA-NYTSF, CASANOVA IN LOVE, By Andrew Miller, 272
pp. New York: Harcourt Brace &AMP; Company. $23. Andrew Miller's novel
imagines Casanova's obsessive pursuit of a young woman in England.
</P>
<P>
   NYTBOOK-BECH-NYTSF, BECH AT BAY, A Quasi-Novel, By John Updike,
241 pp. New York: Alfred A. Knopf. $23. John Updike's Bech is aging
but will not go without a measure of revenge against his critics.
</P>
<P>
   NYTBOOK-BAY-NYTSF, MY YEAR IN THE NO-MAN'S-BAY, By Peter Handke,
Translated by Krishna Winston, 468 pp. New York: Farrar, Straus &AMP;
Giroux. $30. Peter Handke demonstrates that not every storyteller
tells a story.
</P>
<P>
   NYTBOOK-LEAVING-NYTSF, LEAVING EARTH, By Helen Humphreys, 244
pp. New York: Metropolitan Books/Henry Holt &AMP; Company. $22. In this
novel, the earth below is no longer the real world.
</P>
<P>
   NYTBOOK-HUNGER-NYTSF, HUNGER, A Novella and Stories, By Lan
Samantha Chang, 191 pp. New York: W.W. Norton &AMP; Company. $22. This
debut collection of stories calculates the losses and gains of
Chinese-American immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   NYTBOOK-SILK-NYTSF, SILK AND INSIGHT, By Yukio Mishima, Edited
by Frank Gibney, Translated by Hiroaki Sato,  &UR; 219 pp. Armonk, N.Y.:
East Gate/M. E. Sharpe. Cloth, $44.95. Paper, $19.95. This novel by
Mishima, published in Japan in 1964, deals with the struggle of
textile workers.
</P>
<P>
   NYTBOOK-FISH-NYTSF, BIG FISH, A Novel of Mythic Proportions, By
Daniel Wallace, 180 pp. Chapel Hill, N.C.: Algonquin Books of
Chapel Hill. $17.95. A son tries to get to know his dying father,
who hides behind a facade of jokes.
</P>
<P>
   NYTBOOK-MARCHAND-NYTSF, PAUL MARCHAND, F.M.C., By Charles W.
Chesnutt, 144 pp. Jackson: University Press of Mississippi. $20. In
a 1920s novel, published at last, a black man discovers he isn't.
</P>
<P>
   NYTBOOK-BREAKING-NYTSF, BREAKING NEWS, By Robert MacNeil, 406
pp. New York: Nan A. Talese/Doubleday. $24.95. Robert MacNeil's new
novel offers an insider's view of network television news.
</P>
<P>
   NYTBOOK-FIRE-NYTSF, FRIENDLY FIRE, By Kathryn Chetkovich, 116
pp. Iowa City: University of Iowa Press. Paper, $15.95. The
characters in a story collection find themselves targets from
unlikely sources.
