 NEWS &AMP; FEATURE SUMMARY No 2492 - October 22, 1998   NEWS AND
FEATURE SUMMARY -- No. 2492 -- Oct. 22, 1998 We are offering the
following articles for sale. Please contact us for availability
your country. Best regards, Karl Horwitz
<TEXT>
<P>
   1. LICENSE TO KILL : OSAMA BIN LADEN'S DECLARATION OF JIHAD A
little-noticed declaration of jihad by Osama Bin Laden in an Arabic
newspaper underscores the Islamist's main grievance : infidel U.S.
troops in Arabia. By Bernard Lewis. From Foreign Affairs magazine.
2,500 words. 2. ISRAEL AFTER HEROISM Israel turned 50 with a
midlife crisis. The peace process, though flagging, is still
pushing Israelis closer to a reckoning with the Palestinians, their
original rivals for the land. Americanization is giving a country
built by austere pioneers an identity crisis. Tensions between
religious and secular are increasingly bitter, and even the army no
longer unites Israelis the way it used to. As the myths fade,
Israel is deciding whether a Jewish state can ever truly be normal.
By Eliot A. Cohen. From Foreign Affairs magazine. 1,500 words. 3.
THE TESTING OF AMERICAN FOREIGN POLICY We recommend the following
series, adapted from ``The Testing of American Foreign Policy,'' by
U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright, from Foreign Affairs
magazine : Part I: RULES OF THE ROAD FOR AMERICAN FOREIGN POLICY
Part II: SANCTIONS ARE JUST ONE TOOL Part III: FIVE MAJOR TESTS OF
AMERICAN LEADERSHIP Part IV: FREEDOM IS AMERICA'S PURPOSE Please
contact us for more details. 4. From NEW YORK TIMES BOOK REVIEW A.
BANG THE DRUM SLOWLY : Robert Bly (author of the best-selling
``Iron John'') and Jungian analyst Marion Woodman want men to
explore the feminine and vice versa. Karen Lehrman reviews their
book ``The Maiden King : The Reunion of Masculine and Feminine.''
B. THE PLAGUE THAT CHANGED MINDS : So far, Andrew Sullivan says in
his book ``Love Undetectable: Notes on Friendships, Sex and
Survival,'' AIDS has conferred greater dignity on gay people and
more compassion on others. Review by Andrew Delbanco.
_______________________________________________________________ 5.
ANTI-ANXIETY DRUGS MAY INCREASE DRIVING ACCIDENT RISK Drivers
taking some of the most commonly prescribed anti-anxiety drugs
significantly increase their risk of being in a car crash,
according to a new study. The researchers estimate that drivers who
use some of these drugs increase their risk of being in an accident
by about 50%. They conclude that patients should not drive while
they are using these medications. By Michael McCarthy. The Lancet
News Service. 1,000 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 6.
PLACEBOS PROVE SO POWERFUL EVEN EXPERTS ARE SURPRISED Scientists
are uncovering a host of biological mechanisms that can turn a
thought, belief or desire into an agent of change in cells, tissues
and organs. They are exploring the spooky fact that much of human
perception is based not on information flowing into the brain from
the outside world, but what the brain, based on previous
experience, expects to happen next. By Sandra Blakeslee. New York
Times Science Times. 1,950 words + graphic. 7. SCHOOLDAYS IN THE
COMPUTER ROOM In the Golden Age of ASCII, kids could be king,
writes David S. Bennahum. ``In the school computer room, all the
worries of the real world faded away, replaced by the exhilaration
of the quest, a gleeful sense of discovery, and the joy of being
best at something.'' From Wired magazine. 1,500 words. (N/A Japan.)
8. IS THE PRIORITY PEACE OR RIGID JUSTICE? The instinctive reaction
to word that Chile's Augusto Pinochet has been arrested in London
and faces extradition for crimes against humanity is : good, at
least one bloody dictator can be held to account. But it isn't a
simple issue, and the simple answer can have very bad consequences.
By Flora Lewis. 800 words.
_______________________________________________________________ 9.
FAKING IT Counterfeiting has become easier and cheaper. These days,
anyone willing to invest a few hundred (real) dollars in computer
equipment can print totally counterfeit but believable bank notes.
By Will Hively. From Discover magazine. 1,600 words + photos.
_______________________________________________________________ 10.
VITAL SIGNS: SNOWED ``They came to the hospital emergency room
within days of each other. Each patient was young, well-dressed and
employed. The illness they shared was simple, in a sense, but not
straightforward ... `` Tony Dajer writes about treating abusers of
the drug cocaine. From Discover magazine. 1,200 words + photo.
