<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: There's hope yet for prudes in Congress on sex
policies
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Never mind what its members may do off-camera, you'd be
hard-pressed to find a riper bunch of public prudes than those of
the Congress of the United States. Congress is the home of
hair-trigger moral indignation, with ready rules for how other
people ought to live their sex lives. (Which is hardly at all.
Congress is the anti-Kama Sutra.)
</P>
<P>
   Count it, then, a notable breakthrough that Congress, after
years of pointedly refusing to do so, has ordered that the health
insurance of female federal employees cover contraceptives.
</P>
<P>
   Could this be a long-overdue twitch toward policies that can
accelerate the drop in teen pregnancy and lower the abortion rate?
There is more cause to hope so than to think so, but hope is at
least something.
</P>
<P>
   Even this minor concession required months of backstage
scurrying and had to overcome the efforts of Republican leadership
to quash it. Too, the change prospered in no small part because
gentlemen legislators who were not about to forbid Viagra coverage
found themselves shamed into covering contraceptives for women, but
the double-standard argument isn't elastic enough to stretch over
very many related policy matters.
</P>
<P>
   More encouraging, the House vote found a few anti-abortion
lawmakers trying out a pro-contraceptive stand.
</P>
<P>
   Pro-choice folks have argued for years, to scant effect, that
birth control ought to be common ground for both sides of the
abortion issue. If more anti-abortion legislators can now be
persuaded to decouple abortion and birth control, the way would lie
open for properly treating sex, for policy purposes, as a public
health issue.
</P>
<P>
   That's especially so in the matter of teen pregnancies, where we
appear poised to make dramatic gains if we wish to.
</P>
<P>
   The teen pregnancy rate has dropped to its lowest point since
1975, a decline of 14 percent since 1990. Teens are having sex a
bit later, less often and with fewer partners. And many more are
using birth control. The percentage of teenage girls who use
contraceptives at their first intercourse has jumped from 48 to 78
since the early '80s. New long-lasting injected or implanted
contraceptives are making a big difference for the better,
especially with minority teens.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. teen pregnancy rate is still about five times west
Europe's. That, according to a recent study for Advocates for Youth
by the University of North Carolina, is because west Europe
provides open, unembarrassed access to information and
contraceptives, with explicit instruction on responsible sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its timid gesture on health insurance, Congress
continues funding family planning clinics at levels far below
inflation, directly funds only abstinence programs for teens and
this year for the first time dangerously let legislation escape
from committee that would require parental consent for teen
contraception.
</P>
<P>
   Congress continues to suspect that it alone stands between the
American people and sexual incontinence. Hey, wait a minute. Isn't
narcissism a sin? Or at least a vice?
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
