<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>
  
 Thursday, Oct. 22, 1998      The Hearst News Service will file the following stories for
Friday. If you have questions, call Tim Spence at 202-298-6920.  
    (Slugline includes the ``HNS'' tag.)
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   GULF-SYNDROME (Undated) _ A little-noticed provision in the new
federal budget may give Gulf War veterans the answers to the
mysterious health ailments that have plagued them since the 1991
war. The provision requires the National Academy of Sciences to
detail the dangerous substances soldiers were exposed to in the
gulf region and identify illnesses that can be linked to that
exposure. By KATHLEEN SULLIVAN.
</P>
<P>
   WILDLIFE-RANCH (Kerrville, Texas) _ The buffalo no longer will
roam where the deer and antelope play after Nov. 29 at the
Kerrville Camera Safari. The 230-acre facility will close after
more than six years of operating in what has been called the heart
of the exotic animal industry. By RALPH WININGHAM.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE/FEATURES (``l'' category)
</P>
<P>
   HALLOWEEN-COSTUMES (Undated) _ What's hot in costumery for
Halloween 1998? For adults it's Monica and Bill, but for kids the
styles tend toward Hollywood: Mulan and the Titanic. By CRISTINA
MASUDA.
</P>
<P>
   DRUGS-SINGER (Houston) _ Ashley Millet has been singing country
music tunes since she was 3, performing at baby beauty pageants.
She's long since left the pageant scene, but Ashley, now 15, still
loves to sing and uses her talent to teach other young people about
the dangers of drug abuse, underage drinking and drunken driving
through music. By BARBARA KARKABI.
</P>
<P>
   PARIS-FASHION (Paris) _ Miyake, Paco Rabanne, Guy Laroche,
Stella McCartney and Ungaro are the latest styles to be paraded in
the world or haute couture. By LINDA GILLAN GRIFFIN.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   STREHLI-MUSIC- PROFILE (Houston) _ The B.B. King song title
``Never Make Your Move Too Soon'' pretty much sums up Angela
Strehli's approach to putting out albums. In a blues-singing career
dating back more than 25 years, she has released a grand total of
three solo albums. Strehli's latest album, ``Deja Blue,'' conveys
the kind of soulful credibility that comes only with personal
experience. By RICK MITCHELL.
</P>
<P>
   WILLIAMS-FILM-PROFILE (Toronto) _ When actor and poet Saul
Williams entered the prison where much of ``Slam'' was filmed, he
got a warning: Stick close to the guards. ``The first thing the
warden said when she saw me walking with (director) Marc Levin was,
`You don't need to stray too far from Marc, because you are going
to get mixed up with these prisoners and someone's going to drag
you to their cell. You fit right in.''' By LOUIS B. PARKS.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBO-YANKEES (San Diego) _ So where do these Yankees rank with
the greatest teams of all time? First? Third? Eighth? Twenty-first?
Better yet, how does one make one of these Yankees even address the
question? ``I don't know where we rank, in all honesty,'' pitcher
David Cone said, reeking of champagne and success. By RAY RATTO.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-49ERS (Santa Clara, Calif.) _ In theory, Jerry Rice can
break one NFL record and tie another with a single catch on Sunday
in St. Louis. That catch would have to be for a touchdown, however.
Rice is tied with Art Monk for most consecutive games with at least
one reception, at 183. With 78 touchdown catches as a combination,
Rice and Steve Young are one behind the record of 79 set by Miami's
Dan Marino to Mark Clayton from 1983-92. By JOHN CRUMPACKER.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-RAIDERS (Alameda, Calif.) _ Raiders coach Jon Gruden
apologized after he was officially charged by the Alameda County
District Attorney's Office with driving under the influence of
alcohol. By SAMUEL CHI.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ The president has announced that
it's National Y2K Action Week, and warned us to prepare for the
millennium by making sure our computers are compatible or at least
compliant when they make time together. I'm doing my patriotic best
to prepare for the millennium when computer clocks may launch us
back to 1900. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
