<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHORT-SALES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG BOARD POSTS A 1.4 PERCENT DROP IN ITS UNCOVERED SHORT SALES 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Open positions on the New York Stock Exchange fell by
1.4 percent last month, to 4.15 billion shares, the exchange
reported Wednesday. On the smaller American Stock Exchange,
uncovered short sales decreased by 4 percent, to 195.4 million
shares.
</P>
<P>
   Open positions of short sales are those shares that have been
borrowed and sold, but not yet covered by repurchase. If the share
price falls, an investor can profit by buying shares at a lower
price to replace the borrowed ones.
</P>
<P>
   On the Big Board, the short interest figure for the month ended
Oct. 13 was equal to 1.7 percent of the total shares listed on the
exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Royal Dutch Petroleum shares had the largest increase in short
interest on the Big Board. The number of shares sold short totaled
41.4 million, compared with 6.5 million the previous month.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest decrease in Big Board short interest was for shares
of Tyco International Ltd., which fell to 8.4 million, from 26.7
million the previous month.
</P>
<P>
   An increase in the short position in a company's shares may
indicate a rise in bearish sentiment among investors toward that
company. But a short position could also increase because of
complex trading strategies, especially those related to arbitrage
activity. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-98 1113EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981022.0134 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 11:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1234 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERVIEW-ROSS-COX     10-22 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERVIEW-ROSS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `If my movie could be accused of anything, it's being overly
sentimental'
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A modern fable-maker responsible for ``Big'' and ``Dave,''
screenwriter Gary Ross, 42, turned to directing for his
comedy-drama ``Pleasantville.'' It's the tale of twin 1990s
siblings, played by Tobey Maguire and Reese Witherspoon, who get
zapped into a cardigan-and-warm-milk '50s sitcom called
``Pleasantville,'' where their new ``parents'' are Joan Allen in a
Donna Reed dress and William H. Macy as a father who may not know
best but expects his dinner to be waiting. Introducing '90s
attitude (and a little sex) into the black-and-white landscape, the
youngsters bring color to the town ... and suspicion to those who
don't like for things to change. Ross recently spoke to Cox writer
Steve Murray about his movie.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was the seed for a story about two '90s kids getting
stuck in a '50s TV show?
</P>
<P>
   A: I grew up on this stuff, like a lot of people did. But my dad
(Arthur A. Ross) was a blacklisted screenwriter, so my view of the
'50s was different from other people's. It was this idealized time
that I longed for too, with these perfectly manicured hedges and
white picket fences and everyone was happy.
</P>
<P>
   But it wasn't a utopia by any means. Listen, how many drop
drills did they have in ``Ozzie and Harriet''? You didn't have that
episode where Ozzie and Harriet took Ricky and David to the bomb
shelter and told them how they would live if there was nuclear
fallout. Isn't it wild that we grew up with this specter of
annihilation, and at the same time believed in this happy
patriarchy that underscored this illusion of permanence? There
couldn't be two more disparate messages, really. ...
</P>
<P>
   Then (in the 1980s), when that sort of nostalgia was evoked as a
solution for our problems, ``a kinder, gentler'' time or ``building
a bridge'' to the past _ all those bromides struck me as false or
hollow. At the same time, it was really seductive and appealing.
Memory makes things perfect.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Knowing that your father was blacklisted explains the
witch-hunt elements in the second half of ``Pleasantville.''
</P>
<P>
   A: He wrote ``Creature From the Black Lagoon,'' ``The Creature
Walks Among Us,'' ``Brubaker,'' ``The Great Race,'' and he used to
do a lot of television. Thousands of people were blacklisted in the
'50s and early '60s. He was never a member of the Communist Party,
and felt they were stupid. But he was involved in liberal causes,
which was enough to make you lose work. The blacklist was very
fluid. I learned more about the pain it caused much more
retrospectively. But it's not like I grew up in Nazi Germany. I
lived a very happy life as a kid.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you think ``Pleasantville'' is especially timely now?
</P>
<P>
   A: Sure; don't you? Maybe six months ago, the way it flirts with
issues of tyranny and oppression might have seemed more abstract.
But whatever you think of Bill Clinton's behavior, we're very close
to reversing the constitutional process, albeit through a
constitutional mechanism. And 67 percent of Americans say they
don't want that to happen. I think beneath a lot of the
Clinton-Starr tug of war is a real morals debate. If this had been
littering he'd lied about under oath, I'm not sure any of this
would be going on. It's a puritanical backlash.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Your movie is a Garden of Eden parable, really. Whose
painting is that you use in the movie, of Adam and Eve?
</P>
<P>
   A: Masaccio, ``The Expulsion of Adam and Eve From the Garden,''
from a fresco in the Brancacci Chapel in Florence. It's the first
time anybody painted with a single light source, the first
realistic figures, and the full perspective. Masaccio literally
means ``messy little one,'' and he was a pure consumed artist who
traveled around. He was like Pig Pen in ``Peanuts.'' And he only
lived to 24. I lived in Florence for a while, and that was a
favorite painting of mine, because it was the start of the
Renaissance.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It's interesting how sex plays such a catalyst in the movie,
for better or worse.
</P>
<P>
   A: I tried very hard to not stack the deck. But there are
consequences. Joan (Allen's character) is in turmoil when she turns
into color for the first time. She's not liberated and joyous _
that would have been the postcoital beach montage. There's conflict
and strife and prices to be paid. I think that, beyond a statement
about diversity or tolerance or racism or sexism or fascism, what
the movie says is that real feelings are worth the messy reality
that comes with them. Even if they unlock frightening things, it's
better than living in a bland utopia. These days we avoid feelings
through cynicism.
</P>
<P>
   Q: And irony, too.
</P>
<P>
   A: That's so on-the-nail. People use irony as if being against
something is the same as having a viewpoint. It keeps you totally
safe and doesn't force you to commit. You're defending yourself
against your own hope and disappointment. If we're edgy and cynical
and distant and hip, somehow we're safe. But we're being hurt every
day for what we're missing, for not addressing these longings.
</P>
<P>
   I think culturally what happens is that we pour stuff out into
the culture, we put out a cynical message, and the public reacts
cynically. I think if you make an attempt to break that cycle and
engage people emotionally, their beliefs, desires or idealism, its
funny how fast that cycle can break. If my movie could be accused
of anything, it's being overly sentimental. (He laughs.) But that's
something I'm willing to embrace.
</P>
<P>
   Q: This was J.T. Walsh's last movie. That's a loss.
</P>
<P>
   A: He was phenomenal. He brought something special to every
movie he was in. I'm glad it's a final performance people look at
and notice. J.T. was very hard on himself as an actor, anguished in
some ways. You'd think someone that consummately talented would be
secure. But he gnashed about it. That was sort of his process. He
described the movie better than anybody else. He said these kids
(Tobey Maguire and Reese Witherspoon) were like the sand in the
oyster, because out of the irritation they brought finally came a
pearl.
</P>
<P>
   Q: So what do you do for fun?
</P>
<P>
   A: I haven't had much fun in the past year. My wife is always on
me. It's my mantra: ``When the movie's over, when the movie's
over.'' I have two little kids; they're 3, so they're a huge amount
of fun. I have twins, a boy and a girl.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Just like Tobey and Reese in the movie.
</P>
<P>
   A: Yeah, when I found out I was having twins, I decided to make
the brother and sister in the script be twins. My kids are
literally the same age as the movie.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
