u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERVIEW-SINGER-COX     10-22 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERVIEW-SINGER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Apt Pupil' director Bryan Singer is committed to original ideas
 &HT;    By Chris Garcia
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas -- If anyone has doubted the cultlike fascination
that ``The Usual Suspects'' exerted on a generation of teenage and
twentysomething film dweebs, they need only to have witnessed a
recent scene in the lobby of a local theater after the screening of
Bryan Singer's latest flick, ``Apt Pupil.'' The dweebs _ starry
eyes, goatees, baseballs caps and all _ were out in force, pinning
against a table the lionized director.
</P>
<P>
   This is what happens when you're an impossibly young and hugely
successful director of hip, violent and overly clever crime
thrillers. This is what happened to Quentin Tarantino. And, a
little later, what happened to the 32-year-old Singer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Usual Suspects,'' filmed when Singer was 28, was a solid
box office success and landed its screenwriter, Christopher
McQuarrie, and supporting actor Kevin Spacey Academy Awards in
1995. Its stylish bravado _ testosteronic bloodletting, flashy
visuals, hairpin structure _ marked the arrival of an audacious new
filmmaker. (Singer's first feature was ``Public Access,'' in 1992.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Apt Pupil,'' opening today, is Singer's long-awaited
follow-up. It's a creepy thriller based on a Stephen King novella
about a teenager (Brad Renfro) who blackmails an elderly Nazi war
criminal named Kurt Dussander (Ian McKellen), who has been living
incognito in town. The screenplay is by first-time scripter Brandon
Boyce.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent interview, Singer, a diminutive man who looks no
older than many of his fans, spoke about his work.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What attracted you to ``Apt Pupil''?
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, the idea that this awful thing that happened so long
ago, the way Stephen King viewed it as a collective evil, almost
like a golem, almost like a monster in itself and how it crept
through the decades into contemporary society. That interested me,
and how it manifested itself in this young boy through (the
character) Dussander. I found that fascinating. It was a real
horror film as opposed to a supernatural one, though I do love
supernatural horror films. My favorite horror film is by far ``The
Exorcist.'' This is a horror film to me; a more psychological
horror film. If you had to coin a new phrase, you could perhaps
call it a ``social horror film.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you think it's risky at this point in your career to
continue to work with first-time writers?
</P>
<P>
   A: I have faith in people and my ability to work with writers. I
work very closely with writers from Page One. I think Brandon
exhibited himself well in the prose he had written and his overall
intelligence as a human being, and I had faith that he could write
the script. Ultimately he wrote some scenes and we did some work
together on spec so we could establish that it was possible.
</P>
<P>
   Q: You knew Brandon before this?
</P>
<P>
   A: I've known Brandon since he was 11 years old. He was my
family's paper boy. He was delivering newspapers one day, and we
struck up a friendship when I was very young. We fell out of touch
for about six years when he moved, and then he popped up at USC
while I was attending school there. We ran into each other in a
dining hall and we struck up a more real friendship and have been
friends ever since.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How does your upcoming movie ``The X-Men'' fit into your
vision ?
</P>
<P>
   A: Again, it's a very original idea and original concept and a
very effective and important one. It's all about the
disenfranchised, people who are looking for an identity, a place in
the world, and are trying to find it amidst prejudice. I think it's
an important concept, yet it's presented in a comic book universe,
which allows it to reach so many young people, and that's a key
audience for that kind of ideology.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you have any idea where you're going with your career,
what kind of body of work you're trying to forge?
</P>
<P>
   A: Just original movies, original ideas. When I say ``original''
I don't mean my ideas, I mean things we haven't seen before. Now,
they may incorporate things we have seen before _ we've seen film
noir, we've seen bits and pieces of this movie. But the idea of a
child blackmailing a Nazi to hear of his past, or the idea of five
criminals who end up being the figment of some guy's perpetuation
of his own myth, or X-Men, a group of reluctant superheroes _ you
know, they're all very unique, very special. They're not cast from
molds that we've seen before.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
