<HEADER>
A1236 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-DEVIL-COX     10-22 0745
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-DEVIL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Love story unfolds in full gloom
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The meet-cute tradition of Hollywood love stories has nothing on
the real-life introduction of British painter Francis Bacon (Derek
Jacobi) and George Dyer (Daniel Craig). A part-time burglar, Dyer
plunges through Bacon's skylight into his studio. Instead of
calling the police, Bacon tells the intruder to take off his
clothes.
</P>
<P>
   He does, beginning the affair that is the focus of ``Love Is the
Devil.'' Writer-director John Maybury's dissection of the
sadomasochistic power dynamic between working-class Dyer and
upper-class Bacon offers the thesis that the painter's life was as
violent, dark and haunted as one of his ``Screaming Pope''
canvases.
</P>
<P>
   The film unfolds as a flashback after Dyer's death, as memories
of the relationship hit Bacon ``like a bomb exploding in reverse
... a cruel pastiche of experience.''
</P>
<P>
   We see Bacon having his burglar lover tailored for a proper
wardrobe, then squiring him like a prize into the Colony Club, the
bar where all his art cronies hang out. As Bacon puts it in typical
sardonic fashion, ``Welcome to the concentration of camp.'' In this
den of swinging '60s archness, Dyer the boy-toy lug doesn't stand a
chance. Even in the couple's happier days, one friend cracks, ``If
they're getting on, they're unhappy _ that's what love means.'' And
when Dyer tells Bacon he loves him, the artist snaps, ``Where do
you get your slogans from, George, off the television?''
</P>
<P>
   The relationship is a car crash waiting to happen. It's no
coincidence that Bacon happily recalls ``the beauty of it'' when he
once saw an upturned vehicle on the road, necklaced with bodies,
blood and shattered glass. He also likes to giggle, watching the
bloody Odessa Steps sequence of ``The Battleship Potemkin.''
</P>
<P>
   That Bacon is the submissive partner in bed but the ruthless
dominant in the world is the movie's most compelling paradox. But
``Love Is the Devil'' doesn't bother with easy psychologizing, much
less traditional biographical narrative. Maybury seems to
understand that there's something iconic and inexplicable about the
Bacon-Dyer dynamic. It's something we've seen before in other
doomed-from-the-start couples in which one was famous, the other
not (Joe Orton and Kenneth Halliwell or Tennessee Williams and
Frank Merlo).
</P>
<P>
   Without using any of Bacon's actual work in the film, Maybury
creates claustrophobic tableaux that recall Bacon's diptychs and
triptychs. He shoots through distorting bottles and glasses, or off
warped metallic surfaces. Many of the supporting actors seem chosen
for their asymmetrical or cubist features. Through shock cuts, slow
motion and pixilation, the film creates a fragmented nihilistic
mood that matches the visceral impact of Bacon's work. ``Love'' has
something in common with another new release, ``Pleasantville.''
Both movies are visual wonders (in very different ways) that
compensate for ellipses in the script.
</P>
<P>
   Maybury's movie loses steam after its first hour. After limning
the airless, excessive lives of Bacon and Dyer, it never deepens
into a more complex, probing portrait. The movie lives up to its
subtitle: ``Study for a Portrait of Francis Bacon.'' It's a searing
fragment, but incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   Scrubbing his teeth with bleach and streaking shoe polish into
his hair, Jacobi delivers a daring performance as a queen with
sharp fangs (Bacon is dubbed ``her ladyship'' by his circle). Like
his turn as Claudius in ``Hamlet,'' this is one of Jacobi's key
performances, pitched between monstrosity and guilt. Craig matches
his pyrotechnics with a performance that summons sympathy from
Dyer's inarticulate presence, in Bacon's word ``a combination of
amorality and innocence.'' The supporting characters seem to blur
together in a funhouse haze, which seems to be intentional.
</P>
<P>
   Definitely not for all tastes, ``Love Is the Devil'' works as an
homage to Bacon's world view. It's rivetingly, beautifully
grotesque.
</P>
<P>
   ``Love Is the Devil''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Derek Jacobi and Daniel Craig. Written and directed by
John Maybury. Unrated, but contains violence, frontal nudity,
simulated sex, substance abuse and profanity. Lefont Plaza. 1 hour,
30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: As rivetingly dark, cruel and untidy as one of
Francis Bacon's paintings.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
