<HEADER>
A1238 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERVIEW-WILLIAMS-CO     10-22 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERVIEW-WILLIAMS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Morehouse graduate snares breakout role
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you're looking for some close-to-the-bone reality in a movie,
you can't get much better than Saul Williams' prison-yard scene in
``Slam,'' the breakout film from this year's Sundance Film
Festival.
</P>
<P>
   Playing a poet jailed for drug possession, Williams disarms a
menacing gang of fellow inmates by launching into one of the
high-charged verbal riffs that, in real life, won the Morehouse
College(Ga.) graduate the 1996 Grand Slam Championship at New
York's spoken-word mecca, Nuyorican Poets Cafe.
</P>
<P>
   Director Marc Levin recruited 16 prisoners to work with Williams
on the scene, and got permission to shoot in the jail recreation
yard for two days. On the first day, that meant the other prisoners
weren't allowed to come out of their cells. On Day Two, the warden
allowed everyone out while Levin and Williams shot the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Let's just say some of these guys weren't too happy about having
missed their rec time the day before.
</P>
<P>
   The warden ``didn't tell the other people we were shooting a
film,'' Williams says on a recent visit to Atlanta. ``She just
said, `This camera's out there, and if you don't want to be shot,
stay against the wall.' Pretty soon they figured out the camera was
following me.'' (If you watch this scene in the movie, you can see
a prisoner make a vulgar gesture at the lens.)
</P>
<P>
   When the time came for Williams to be surrounded by the gang,
more than the 16 recruited guys converged on the actor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't really scared, because there was so much adrenalin
already,'' Williams recalls. ``I'd pumped myself up about the power
of the word. I knew they would stop.'' And they did, listening,
awed, as he rattled out his poetry.
</P>
<P>
   A double major in drama and philosophy while at Morehouse
(1990-94), Williams was in town this summer, performing his poetry
at the Variety Playhouse during the National Black Arts Festival.
Theatergoers may remember him in 7 Stages' acclaimed production,
mounted twice, of ``My Children, My Africa!''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was me without any hair,'' Williams quips, now boasting
long dreds.
</P>
<P>
   Raised in upstate New York, he's lived in Manhattan for the past
four years. He went to grad school at NYU, and while there first
became aware of the new spoken-word movement, a legacy of the Beat
generation and '60s poets such as Amiri Baraka, Sonia Sanchez and
Nikki Giovanni. ``You don't just write, you compete,'' he says.
``There's this whole braggadocio element.'' He first started
writing rhymes in the fourth grade, hoping someday to be a rapper.
</P>
<P>
   When he was approached about doing ``Slam,'' he says, ``I was
entering my third year at NYU, and I'd just gotten to the point
where I needed to fuse what was happening with me in the poetry
world with what was happening me in the acting world. I was about
to create this one-man show when I got the call (about `Slam'). It
was the perfect fusion. It was a glass slipper that fit my foot
perfectly.''
</P>
<P>
   Next, Williams will continue his role as a performing chameleon.
He's writing songs for a record with Sony's American Recordings.
His producer is a guy who has produced the Red Hot Chili Peppers,
the Beastie Boys, LL Cool J and Run-DMC. ``He's got a few
credits,'' Williams says with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   The writer-actor-musician gets back to Atlanta at least once a
year to see friends. And he wouldn't mind moving here with his
girlfriend and their child. ``I have a 2-year-old daughter, and I'm
not certain I want to raise her in New York City. I want her to be
able to commune with nature.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
