A1239 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-APTPUPIL-COX     10-22 0562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-APTPUPIL-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Apt Pupil' falls short as study of Nazi evils
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The evil that filmmaker Bryan Singer (``The Usual Suspects'')
tackles in his new movie, ``Apt Pupil,'' makes his Keyser Soze look
like Donnie Osmond.
</P>
<P>
   Working from a Stephen King novella written 16 years ago, Singer
takes us face to face with the hell that Hitler built: the Aryan
grand design of extermination known as the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   High school senior Todd Bowden (Brad Renfro) is a model student
obsessed with the Third Reich in general and the Holocaust in
particular. His fascination helps him recognize that the alcoholic
recluse who calls himself Arthur Denker (Ian McKellen) is actually
Kurt Dussander, an infamous death camp commander who has managed to
keep his past secret for decades. Now Bowden shows up, threatening
to expose Denker/Dussander unless ... unless he relates in
excruciating detail the atrocities he committed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything,'' demands Todd. ``Everything they're afraid to
tell us in school.''
</P>
<P>
   So the old man, between healthy slugs of whiskey, does just
that. How long it took for the poison gas to kill; how the victims
vomited and defecated on themselves; how the children were always
found at the bottom of the heaps of bodies.
</P>
<P>
   These facts provide the movie's most chilling moments,
especially as related by McKellen, whose booze-soaked wariness
reminds us that, old, alcoholic and alone though he may be, he
could still prove a formidable foe. Todd is nibbling at the edges
of an ancient evil that, when provoked, will bite back. Hard.
</P>
<P>
   What evolves is a symbiotic love/hate relationship between the
two in which each tries to maintain the upper hand, through
blackmail, threats, deception, double-crosses, whatever's handy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apt Pupil'' sets out to teach us that evil knows evil, a
lesson it imparts well. The early scenes are the most unsettling,
because we can't quite read what Todd is getting from all this _
aside from lower grades and a low-grade sexual dysfunction. Is he
repulsed, titillated or both? Renfro, who provides a good match for
the peerless McKellen, makes a convincing cipher: the innocent
seduced or the impish seducer.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the plot itself is a bit wheezy. As the stakes
escalate, the movie doesn't know where to take us. We're left with
the feeling of a psychological horror show interrupted by a generic
suspense thriller.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there are some excellent touches. The way Todd's
windshield wipers sound like marching jackboots. Or how easily his
well-meaning guidance counselor (a surprisingly effective David
Schwimmer) can be manipulated into powerlessness when the boy and
Denker double-team him.
</P>
<P>
   ``What did it feel like?'' Todd asks. Later, Denker/Dussander
asks him the same thing. That's what's missing from the core of
this otherwise impressive film. We never quite learn what it feels
like _ for Todd, for Denker, or for the millions just like them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apt Pupil''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Starring Ian McKellen and Brad Renfro. Directed by Bryan Singer.
Rated R for violence, language and disturbing material. At metro
theaters. 1 hour, 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A flawed but chilling lesson about the infectious
nature of evil.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
