<HEADER>
A1240 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-MARIUS-COX     10-22 0545
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-MARIUS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Marius' a tres sentimental bonbon
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Like a Woody Guthrie folk song, ``Marius and Jeannette'' is a
winning bit of populism _ full of sympathy for the working class.
</P>
<P>
   A sleeper hit in France where it was nominated for seven Cesars
(their Oscar), the film was written and directed by Robert
Guediguian, who clearly has the gentle romanticism of '30s
filmmaker Marcel Pagnol in mind. He's even named his male lead
after one of the films in Pagnol's famed Marseilles-set trilogy.
</P>
<P>
   Guediguian's movie is also set in Marseilles, in Estaque, a
charmingly idealized blue-collar neighborhood where the residents
share their feelings while shelling peas or drying dishes. That
they are meant to represent a microcosm of the world is
demonstrated by the enchanting opening shot: a plastic globe
floating downriver until it docks at Estaque.
</P>
<P>
   That's where Jeanette (Ariane Ascaride, the director's wife), a
40-ish single mom with two kids, lives. She's just lost her job as
a checkout clerk at a supermarket for mouthing off to the boss.
</P>
<P>
   Marius (Gerard Meylan) is a taciturn, gimpy-legged, middle-aged
security guard at a semi-demolished cement factory. They meet when
she tries to steal a couple of cans of discarded paint from his
work site. He makes her put them back, but also has to endure a
tongue-lashing about fascist factory owners who barely miss their
former employees, let alone some cans of paint.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, he turns up at her home with the paint. He stays
to help and things proceed from there.
</P>
<P>
   As the title indicates, their slowly-emerging romance is the
film's central relationship. That, in itself, is immediately
appealing _ the opportunity to watch two normal, reasonably
attractive (as opposed to Hollywood airbrushed) adults risk falling
in love.
</P>
<P>
   However, ``Marius and Jeannette'' is more than just a love
story. It's also an engaging study of a community. As Marius gets
to know Jeannette's assorted friends and neighbors, so do we. The
constantly squabbling married couple (she still won't forgive him
for having voted for the Far Right in the last election); the
outspoken Marxist who survived the concentration camps but still
gets riled when Castro puts on a suit to court the capitalists; the
gentle retired schoolteacher who passes along his thoughts on
religious tolerance to Jeannette's Muslim son.
</P>
<P>
   Guediguian's picture of proletarian bliss is perhaps a tad too
rosy. Everyone is so well-intentioned, so good-humored, that you
almost expect them to break into song. But his vision of a mutually
nourishing neighborhood is also immensely appealing. And while some
scenes may be cloying and others clumsily comic, overall, the
community offered in ``Marius and Jeannette'' strikes you as a nice
place to live and an even nicer one to visit on an easygoing
afternoon at the movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marius and Jeannette''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Starring Ariane Ascaride and Gerard Meylan. Directed by Robert
Guediguian. Not rated, but contains sexuality and strong language.
Subtitles. Tara. 1 hour,
</P>
<P>
   42 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A minor delight.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
