<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 11:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1241 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-MONUMENT-COX     10-22 0592
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-MONUMENT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Leary shines in tales of the 'hood
 &HT;    By Eleanor Ringel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Jaws'' and ``Star Wars'' may have set the commercial stakes,
and ``The Godfather'' saga may end up on more all-time-great lists.
But as far as independent filmmaking in the 1990s is concerned, the
most influential movie of the 1970s could well be ``Mean Streets.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Monument Avenue'' is a bleak, gritty Irish variation on Martin
Scorsese's timeless theme of lifelong buddies whose ties to one
another and to the old neighborhood are strangling them.
</P>
<P>
   Set in Charlestown, a working-class section of Boston separated
from encroaching gentrification by the title street, the film
focuses on Bobby O'Grady (Denis Leary), a thirtysomething
small-time hood who still lives at home with his mother. No wonder.
He and his lifelong buddies _ Mouse (Ian Hart), Digger (John Diehl)
and Teddy (Billy Crudup) _ are caught in a kind of extended
adolescence. When they aren't stealing cars or breaking into houses
_ a nice bonus of the ever-nearer yuppies _ they get drunk, snort
cocaine, play street hockey and talk about which movie stars they'd
like to sleep with.
</P>
<P>
   New to the group is Bobby's younger cousin, Seamus (Jason
Barry), fresh off the boat from Dublin. But he soon learns the
ropes: Don't cross the neighborhood's unofficial crime boss, Jackie
O'Hara (Colm Meaney), and keep your mouth shut when the local cop
(Martin Sheen) starts asking questions.
</P>
<P>
   One night, one of Bobby's cronies is shot dead while downing a
few at the neighborhood pub. Everyone knows the hit was ordered by
Jackie. But adhering to their misguided notions of honor and
manhood, they keep the code of silence. When Sheen shows up,
everybody was in the restroom when it happened. As usual.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby provides the movie's moral fulcrum. We see his rage and
pain when Jackie attends the wake to comfort the victim's grieving
mother. We also see how deeply this dead-end existence has claimed
him. Is he truly any better than Jackie? In the picture's most
harrowing scene, he instigates the kidnapping of an
African-American who has committed the unpardonable sin of walking
on his turf.
</P>
<P>
   Director Ted Demme purposely emphasizes the random, episodic
nature of Mike Armstrong's script, which in turn reflects the
random, episodic nature of these men's purposeless lives. It can be
a little wearing, but stick with it. There's a payoff.
</P>
<P>
   The cast is uniformly strong, especially Meaney, who oozes
self-satisfied complacency in a cashmere coat. But the standout is
Leary, who creates an indelible portrait of a guy too smart to be
stuck where he is and too stuck to figure a way out. Leary doesn't
back away from Bobby's ugly side _ the racism, the drugs, the sheer
street-bred meanness _ but he also shows us someone whose
conscience won't shut up.
</P>
<P>
   Demme's use of old photos of Bobby and company when they were
kids is a familiar technique, but it works unusually well in this
case. How, we wonder, did these grinning little boys in cowboy hats
grow up to be these grinning, useless thugs? It's a question the
movie keeps asking and one that, sadly, goes unanswered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monument Avenue''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Starring Denis Leary and Colm Meaney. Directed by Ted Demme. Not
rated, but contains vulgarity, violence and drug use. Tara. 1 hour,
30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: Boy-o's in the 'hood, with a standout performance
by Denis Leary.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
