<HEADER>
A1243 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOVIES-PLEASANTVILLE-     10-22 0696
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOVIES-PLEASANTVILLE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Passion colors town in film fable of the '50s
 &HT;    By Steve Murray
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a sexy tumble with his girlfriend in the back of a jalopy,
high school jock Skip (Paul Walker) comes home and notices a dusky
red rose swaying in the night breeze outside his house. What makes
it so unusual is that it's the only blush of color in the
black-and-white world of ``Pleasantville.''
</P>
<P>
   In his directing debut, Gary Ross, the screenwriter of ``Big''
and ``Dave,'' continues his knack for cinematic fables with a tale
of two 1990s kids zapped into the 1950s TV sitcom of the title.
It's a place of tidy picket fences, kittens trapped in trees, and
mass consumption of milk, malts and mounded breakfast platters
loaded with enough cholesterol to bring down a football team.
</P>
<P>
   David (Tobey Maguire) and twin sister Jennifer (Reese
Witherspoon) are transported there, via a plot device that doesn't
bear much scrutiny. (It involves Don Knotts as a TV repairman with
superpowerful remote control.) Aghast at their suddenly
monochromatic skin and '50s 'dos, they meet their new
Ward-and-June-Cleaver-like parents, Betty (Joan Allen) and George
(William H. Macy), who refer to them as ``Bud'' and ``Mary Sue.''
</P>
<P>
   If the teenagers' culture shock is bad, it's nothing compared to
what the town is in for. David warns his sis to go with the flow
until they figure how to get out. But vampy Jennifer starts
parading around in her angora sweater with the kind of attitude
that makes everyone on the basketball team miss their hoops. Soon,
her girl-power freedom is unleashing, gasp, color into
Pleasantville, as schoolmates and neighbors discover the unknown
pleasures of modern art, controversial literature and, natch, sex.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``The Truman Show,'' the movie teases with our
understanding of the rules of television. But it also pulls in
big-screen references. It plays like a sly revision of the original
``Invasion of the Body Snatchers,'' only in reverse: Instead of
emotionless pod people infiltrating the idyllic town, it's the
passionate people. And the cheerful, bland Pleasantfolk _ led by
the mayor, Big Bob (the late J.T. Walsh) _ want this color seepage
to stop, before it turns them all fully human (flaws and all).
</P>
<P>
   Here's where ``Pleasantville'' starts to lose its light touch.
Ross turns the last act of his movie into a metaphor about the
struggle between safe but deadly conformity and the risky pleasures
of free will. When townsfolk start to talk about the ``coloreds,''
the flick becomes heavy-handed. And the last half-hour could use a
few judicious edits.
</P>
<P>
   Mainly, though, it's a lovely, imaginative work, powered by the
luscious digital blend of color and black and white. Randy Newman's
bittersweet score also helps. Witherspoon, who has few peers in the
sardonic sexpot category, offers sharp work, sitting down with
``mom'' Betty to explain to her the facts of life. Too bad
Witherspoon's role gets smaller as the movie unreels. Maguire
(``The Ice Storm'') is appealing, playing a young man who prefers
to watch things from the sidelines, reserving judgment.
</P>
<P>
   The most powerful relationship in the film is between David/Bud
and his sitcom mom. Ideally cast, Allen raises the stakes
emotionally as her feelings for malt shop owner Mr. Johnson (Jeff
Daniels) turn her, almost literally, into a scarlet woman. And the
indispensable Macy brings bewildered bluster to his role as a man
who can't fathom the notion that his wife may not always be waiting
for him at home. His sputtering wail of ``Where's my dinner?''
becomes the fulcrum of ``Pleasantville,'' where the absence of a
meal becomes the symbol for a world tilting (for better and worse)
into the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pleasantville''
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Starring Tobey Maguire, Joan Allen, Reese Witherspoon, William
H. Macy and Jeff Daniels. Written and directed by Gary Ross. Rated
PG-13 for thematic elements emphasizing sexuality and for language.
2 hours, 4 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: A witty, visually beautiful fable of nonconformity.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-98 1155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
