<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981022.0148 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 12:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1292 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIRST-MAMMOGRAM-COX     10-22 1691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIRST-MAMMOGRAM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Procedure involves lots of pressure but usually little pain
 &HT;    By Sarah Franquet
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Our experts: Dr. Kristine Thayer, a Palm Beach County surgeon
who specializes in breast diseases, and Melanie Nielsen, a
radiologic technologist and manager of the Comprehensive Breast
Center at Good Samaritan Medical Center in West Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What exactly is a mammogram?
</P>
<P>
   A. It is an X-ray of the breast that can detect cancers. There
are two kinds. Screening mammograms are for routine maintenance and
can detect cancers before they can be felt. A diagnostic mammogram
is for a woman who has felt a lump or has other complaints such as
tenderness, dimpling, breast pain, swelling or nipple discharge.
</P>
<P>
   Q. When should I have my first mammogram?
</P>
<P>
   A. The American Cancer Society and others recommend you have a
baseline mammogram (your first one, used for crucial comparisons in
later tests) at age 40 and have one screening mammogram every year
after. These recommendations are controversial; some groups
recommend mammograms every two years for women 40 to 49. But Thayer
says plenty of scientific evidence shows that yearly screening
reduces the number of breast cancer deaths. She also says tumors
grow more quickly in younger women, so early detection is crucial.
(For all women, a monthly self examination is recommended.)
</P>
<P>
   If you have a first-degree relative (mother, sister or daughter)
who has had breast cancer, ask your doctor when you should start
having regular mammograms. el3
</P>
<P>
   Q. How much does it cost?
</P>
<P>
   A. Mammograms usually run from $75 to $125. Unfortunately, many
women won't spend that kind of money on themselves. But Thayer says
they need to keep in mind that it's for the whole family. ``They
are the caregivers, and if something happens to them, it affects
the whole family,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   (Also, during October, National Breast Cancer Awareness Month,
many facilities offer reduced rates.)
</P>
<P>
   Q. How do I choose a facility?
</P>
<P>
   A. Whether you have a mammogram at a hospital, a women's center
or your gynecologist's office, make sure the facility has Food and
Drug Administration and American College of Radiology
certifications. This ensures that basic standards are met.
</P>
<P>
   The American Cancer Society (phone: 616-9370) has a list of
accredited facilities and information on reduced-rate screenings.
</P>
<P>
   Other questions to ask: How does the facility handle your
results? Do you know right away?
</P>
<P>
   Does the facility offer breast examinations along with your
mammogram?
</P>
<P>
   About how long is each patient there? Are they efficient at
getting women in and out?
</P>
<P>
   Who can I talk to if I have questions or need more information?
</P>
<P>
   Q. What exactly is going to happen during my visit?
</P>
<P>
   A. Melanie Nielsen describes a visit to Good Samaritan's center.
As you check in, you'll fill out a patient history form. Questions
include: Do you have any family members with breast cancer? At what
age did you start your menstrual period? Have you ever had breast
surgery?
</P>
<P>
   At this point, a breast examination by a nurse practitioner is
offered. (This is called a Clinical Breast Examination and, along
with self-examination and mammograms, is an important part of a
woman's health care.) You can also watch a video or get private
instruction on how to perform self-exams.
</P>
<P>
   After that, the technologist will perform a screening mammogram,
which gives radiologists two views of each breast. You will undress
from the waist up, and the technologist will place your breast on a
Plexiglas plate, gently pulling the breast tissue away from your
chest walls. Keep in mind that breast tissue extends from your
clavicle to your bra line and from your sternum to your lymph nodes
underneath your arm. That's a lot of chest to cover.
</P>
<P>
   The top Plexiglas paddle will move down to flatten your breast
(the latest machines let the technologist control this with a foot
pedal). She will ask you to hold your breath for a few seconds
while she takes the image. Once the exposure is over, the
compression automatically releases. That's it.
</P>
<P>
   A radiologist will look at the X-rays, interpret them and make a
report. The radiologist is looking for the unusual _ asymmetry,
masses or anything that stands out from normal breast tissue. At
Good Samaritan, they try to give you the report right away. If the
radiologist is unavailable to read the X-rays, the center will
notify you later that day, or the next morning. They will also give
a report to your doctor, and you will receive a letter explaining
what was found.
</P>
<P>
   Q. The big question. Does it hurt?
</P>
<P>
   A. Some women may tell you it hurts. Others say it's a piece of
cake. Most admit it can be a little uncomfortable. It involves
pulling and compressing your breast, but it feels different for
every woman. Nielsen says the majority of women have no problem at
all. A good technologist knows this is high-anxiety time and is
very sensitive to you and your body. So are the newest machines,
which are designed to help eliminate a lot of the discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   If it does becomes painful, tell the technologist. She can work
with you more and try to make adjustments. But the main point here
is to get adequate compression. If that doesn't happen, you will
have gone through this for nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Here is how several women describe the feeling:
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, it didn't actually hurt. It just feels a little weird
because your breast usually isn't squished like that. I didn't know
my breast could be flattened so much. There's pressure, but pain?
No. It's not fun, but it's no huge deal. Look at it this way:
having a PAP smear is a little uncomfortable, too, but you have
those annually, right?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's painless. My breast tissue is fibrous and thick and it
takes a little longer for the X-ray part. I'd describe it as firm
pressure. It did feel a little weird having a woman fondling my
breasts, though!''
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't hurt. It's very uncomfortable though. Pressure is a
good word. Part of the concern is that this huge cold machine is
compressing and you don't know when it's going to stop. And, you're
not used to your breast being handled like that. It's all pretty
impersonal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It just feels like you're being smushed between two cold
plates. But it didn't hurt. You're hugging this big piece of
machinery and being smushed. It's just more awkward than painful.''
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do women ever bruise?
</P>
<P>
   A. It can happen, but not usually. This can depend on any
medication you're taking. Aspirin or certain prescription
medications can cause you to bruise.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Do smaller- or larger-breasted women have more discomfort?
</P>
<P>
   A. No. Nielsen hears comments all the time from small-breasted
women who think large-breasted women will have more pain, and
vice-versa. But size doesn't matter. It all depends on the
sensitivity of your breasts. If you have lumpy breasts, you may
have a little more discomfort. Nielsen says it may help to avoid
caffeine two weeks before your mammogram is scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Q. For very flat-chested women, it seems there's really nothing
there to compress. How does that work?
</P>
<P>
   A. Keep in mind, even men can get mammographies. Everyone has
skin and some amount of breast tissue. ``We just work with the
patient,'' says Nielsen. There is always something to compress.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Is the radiation harmful?
</P>
<P>
   A. Twenty years ago, that was a legitimate concern. Now, you are
exposed to more radiation on a transcontinental flight than during
a mammogram.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I'm really nervous. What can I do to make this whole thing
easier?
</P>
<P>
   A. A few things to keep in mind:
</P>
<P>
   Technologists are trained to give you the maximum privacy and to
treat you with sensitivity. Some techs strike up a conversation and
before you know it, it's all over. So tell her you're nervous and
talk to her about your fears.
</P>
<P>
   The first time is the hardest because it's all a little unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Wear a two-piece outfit. That way, you have to undress only from
the waist up.
</P>
<P>
   Schedule your appointment after your period when your breasts
are not so tender.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have implants. Does that affect my mammogram?
</P>
<P>
   A. Yes. Extra views of the breast are taken and a specialized
technique is used so the entire breast can be imaged. But implants
do not affect your ability to get a good mammogram. Also don't
worry about the process rupturing an implant. There's not enough
pressure involved. In fact, mammograms can be used to detect
abnormalities with your implants.
</P>
<P>
   Q. What if they find something?
</P>
<P>
   A. If an abnormality does show up, the radiologist may recommend
more views be taken or an ultrasound given. It all depends on what
the area in question looks like. The radiologist would call your
doctor, and you would all discuss the next step.
</P>
<P>
   This fear too often keeps women from having a mammogram. But
Thayer emphasizes that finding something is not a bad thing. ``It
used to be that we couldn't do anything,'' she said. ``Now, we
can't prevent breast cancer from happening, but if we catch it
early, you don't have to die from it anymore.'' FACT BOX: Breast
cancer facts 95 percent of breast cancer cases occur in women age
40 and over. In Florida, 27 percent of women over the age of 40
(almost 1 million) have never had a mammogram. Breast cancer is
usually found in the upper, outer part of the breast, but it can
occur anywhere in the breast. Most women _ about 80 percent _ who
get breast cancer do not have a sister or mother who has breast
cancer. Nearly 97 percent of women who are diagnosed with breast
cancer at an early stage survive for more than five years. In 1998,
11,800 women in Florida will be diagnosed with breast cancer and
2,900 women will die. These high numbers can be partly attributed
to demographics _ nearly 1.9 million women are over 60, and more
than 65 percent of all breast cancers occur in women age 60 and
over. 72 percent of the breast cancers diagnosed in Florida are
found in the early stages of the disease. Source: American Cancer
Society
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
