<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 12:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1293 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MAMMOGRAM-SIDE-COX     10-22 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAMMOGRAM-SIDE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PBP-MAMMOGRAM-SIDE
 &HT;    Save the last dance for me
 &HT;    ATTN: COX -- FEATURES EDITORS
 &HT;    For 10/21, WEDNESDAY
 &HT;    By Cara Anna
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service-Palm Beach Post
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOYNTON BEACH, Fla. _ When the photographer asks her to take off
her jacket, Renee Riedl says, ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   But when he is gone, Riedl walks over and lifts the jacket, and
her shirt, and her bra.
</P>
<P>
   And she looks at where her 34C breasts used to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what it looks like,'' she says. ``Nothing. There's
nothing there.''
</P>
<P>
   Riedl found a lump in her left breast on St. Patrick's Day,
1990, and a lump in her right breast on Dec. 17, 1996. Breast
cancer, both times.
</P>
<P>
   Two matching mastectomy scars _ horizontal lines about four
inches long _ have replaced them. Even her nipples are gone.
</P>
<P>
   She drops something from the left cup of her bra and hands it
over. It is a prosthesis, squishy and a too-orange color.
</P>
<P>
   It is also a smaller size, 34B. She could have asked for any
size, Riedl says. ``But I was so thin when I went to get it they
asked, `Why not go down?' Stupid me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Stupid'' because she's no longer 120 pounds and a size 4.
After her second mastectomy and chemotherapy, her body went bonkers
and she gained 34 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   She can list her post-chemo problems without tripping over an
``itis.'' Lupus, autoimmune hepatitis, vasculitis. In short, her
immune system is shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate my body,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   But Mel loves it anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Mel is Riedl's husband. He is 70, she 53. They met in a Pompano
Beach ballroom when Renee, 27, walked into his beginners' rhumba
class. They have been dancing together ever since.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wouldn't let me go,'' Mel says. ``You girls are tough, I
tell you.''
</P>
<P>
   Mel's a talker. While Renee is busy with the photographer, he
offers to show the photos of her that he keeps in the trunk of his
car. ``She's got a body, I swear to God, that could be Miss
America.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Mel, this is embarrassing to me. Tell her why you have
pictures of me in the trunk of your car.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wanted to show people how nice you looked when you were
30.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He goes to the pool room and pulls out those pictures.''
</P>
<P>
   Mel shows a photo of the two of them on the dance floor.
``That's when she had a nice figure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, shut up.''
</P>
<P>
   She says she throws a prosthesis at him when she gets mad at
him.
</P>
<P>
   Renee and Mel, who once made a living dancing and instructing,
have 13 dance routines. They have performed on cruise ships and in
country clubs and ballrooms throughout South Florida. Now Mel goes
to ballrooms alone. He doesn't want Renee catching anything from
other people.
</P>
<P>
   But one night Renee said to hell with it. She and Mel performed
at a charity event in Dade County, doing a whirling, stomping dance
called the paso doble.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't work. Renee got tired. ``Mel just looked up at the DJ
and said, `She has to stop,''' Renee says.
</P>
<P>
   She wants her body back. They are both out of work (he has heart
problems), they traded their house on Lighthouse Point for a
$525-a-month apartment, and they've traded the Chryslers and
Mercedes for one 1995 Chevy.
</P>
<P>
   Because of their old lifestyle, people think they are
millionaires or something, Renee says. They now get $800 a month in
disability payments.
</P>
<P>
   But Renee won't part with her $1,000 ballroom dresses, even if
they don't fit her anymore. She wants to dance again. xo
</P>
<P>
   Her tango dress is her favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Black lace on top. Sleeveless. Fitted to the hips. Ruffled skirt
with a slit up the left leg. Silver sequins along the edges. ``Then
long black gloves, you know, and long red earrings.''
</P>
<P>
   Wearing black stretch pants, curled up in a chair, she watches a
tape of herself and Mel doing the merengue. This was between
mastectomies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Note the legs,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   Thin, graceful on 2 1/2-half-inch heels. ``I can't dance in
anything less.''
</P>
<P>
   When she says she hates her body, Mel says, ``Don't be
ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly don't feel sensual or sexual,'' she says. ``My
husband will love me until the day I die, but this has got to
affect him to some degree.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't dance with her,'' is all he says.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Renee went to get her lymph nodes biopsied. If all
goes well, she will ask to be placed on immunosuppressants, which
should take care of the water weight.
</P>
<P>
   If all goes well, she says, she will get reconstructive surgery.
She says it is covered by Medicare. Mel is impressed. Free surgery?
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they can dance again.
</P>
<P>
   Renee says the last time they danced was April 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then she got all fat and heavy,'' Mel says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mel ... ''
</P>
<P>
   He gets up and walks across the room and hugs her around the
head.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By The PALM BEACH POST, WEST PALM BEACH, FLORIDA
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-10-20-98 1731E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
