<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 12:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1295 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CANCER-LESBIAN23-COX     10-22 1454
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANCER-LESBIAN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    In final months, lesbian made breast cancer fight a public
crusade
 &HT;    By Lillian Lee Kim
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Dennie Doucher was so comfortable as a lesbian, it was
unthinkable that she would feel uneasy about telling others she was
(cq she's deceased) gay.
</P>
<P>
   But many unthinkable things happen when you have cancer.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, when Doucher was diagnosed with breast cancer, the
native Atlantan was thrust into a culture that identifies breast
cancer with heterosexual women.
</P>
<P>
   Support groups, normally nurturing, put Doucher on the
defensive. She felt like an outsider when members spoke of losing
their breasts and how their husbands or boyfriends reacted. She
hated having to explain her sexuality, instead of having her
illness explained to her.
</P>
<P>
   With characteristic verve, Doucher set out to learn as much
possible about her disease. She found that, far from being an
affliction only of straight women, breast cancer is thought to be a
greater problem for lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   She also found that healing would take much more than doctors
and pills.
</P>
<P>
   Cancer doctors have long suspected that lesbian women are at
greater risk for breast cancer, from anecdotal evidence that they
tend to be heavier, undergo cancer screenings only sporadically and
have children late or not at all.
</P>
<P>
   But no one had tested this hypothesis until September, when
researchers completed the first study to compare breast cancer risk
factors of lesbian and heterosexual women. The study, which
involved 1,019 women from 1995 to 1997, concluded that lesbians
indeed have higher weight-height ratios and fewer pregnancies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still too early for us to develop specific mammography
guidelines for lesbians, but our study shows the importance of
encouraging lesbians to seek medical care on a regular basis,''
said Dr. Stephanie Roberts, medical director at Lyon-Martin Women's
Health Services in San Francisco, where the study was conducted.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors recommend a mammogram every year for women after turning
40. Regardless of sexual activity, women 18 and older should have
annual gynecological and clinical breast exams conducted by a
doctor.
</P>
<P>
   But many lesbians visit a gynecologist rarely or never, thinking
the annual exams are for women at risk of getting pregnant or
catching a sexually transmitted disease from a male partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many lesbians report that it's been over three years since
they had their last Pap smear,'' said Dr. Jocelyn White of the Gay
and Lesbian Medical Association, a national organization with 2,000
members.
</P>
<P>
   The Pap smear, which shows cervical abnormalities, and other
regular tests can detect cancer in its earliest stages, when it is
easier to treat. Finding cancer at a later stage generally means a
poorer chance for survival.
</P>
<P>
   Another breast cancer risk factor is not having children, or
having them at a later age, as many lesbians do. Being pregnant has
health benefits: During pregnancy, the body's levels of the female
hormone estrogen drop.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many cancers, specifically breast cancer, are
estrogen-dependent,'' said Linda McGehee, (cq) a close friend of
Doucher's and a faculty member at Georgia State University's
nursing school. ``Lesbians who choose not to have children, or have
them later in life, have more exposure to estrogen.''
</P>
<P>
   Getting lesbians into doctor's offices may take more than
convincing them they should go.
</P>
<P>
   Health care costs are a major barrier. Lesbians generally can't
join spousal health insurance plans, and women typically earn less
money than men. Annual gynecological exams cost $125 to $175, and
mammograms can add $100 or more.
</P>
<P>
   Also, many lesbians fear discrimination and poor treatment if
they reveal their sexual status.
</P>
<P>
   Bev Baker, executive director of the Mary-Helen Mautner Project
for Lesbians With Cancer in Washington, has heard some appalling
tales.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lesbians have been abused in the health care system,'' Baker
bluntly said. ``Once their health care providers find out they're
lesbians, many women have been left flat on their backs, feet in
the stirrups.''
</P>
<P>
   In interviewing lesbians with cancer about their health care
experiences, McGehee found that women felt either very good or very
bad about how their doctors treated them and their partners.
Sometimes the patient's partner was ignored; in other cases, the
doctor made special efforts to talk to the partner and educate her
about her loved one's illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``The medical community needs to address these issues,'' White
said. ``Until physicians can work effectively with lesbians, they
won't be able to work with all patients.''
</P>
<P>
   Physicians also need more information, specifically about the
incidence of breast cancer among lesbians. Only further studies can
determine this statistic, because current tracking methods such as
the National Tumor Registry don't differentiate by sexual
orientation.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco study found that lesbians are more than twice
as likely as heterosexual women to require breast biopsies
performed on lumps, to determine whether they are cancerous.
</P>
<P>
   Surprisingly, the study didn't find that lesbians were more
likely to be diagnosed with breast cancer than straight women _ but
the overall average age of the women in the study was 43. The risk
of breast cancer increases with age, with 77 percent of new
diagnoses occurring among women 50 and older, according to the
American Cancer Society.
</P>
<P>
   The lead researchers themselves say their study had significant
limitations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Future study needs to be done that gets at different economic
groups, different geographic areas,'' Roberts said.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts and her research team will soon begin a three-year study
of 5,000 lesbian and heterosexual women, funded by California's
Breast Cancer Research Program. The study will target women older
than 40.
</P>
<P>
   Lesbian health specialists are anxiously awaiting a report on
lesbian health research priorities by the Institute of Medicine, a
part of the National Academy of Sciences. The report, expected in
November, will address the extent of knowledge of rates of cancer,
STDs, hypertension and substance abuse among lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   ``That report is very likely to shape how we look at lesbians'
health over the next decade or two,'' White said.
</P>
<P>
   Doucher couldn't wait for more research; she needed help and
answers immediately. Luckily, she had extraordinary initiative and
enormous support, from her family and friends.
</P>
<P>
   But she strongly felt that other lesbians with cancer shouldn't
have to struggle to get support and information.
</P>
<P>
   ``She felt she had had to go through it alone at first,'' said
friend Jill Ruhlman. ``She didn't want anyone else to have to go
through that.''
</P>
<P>
   So Doucher conceived a support group for lesbians with cancer
and their partners. Co-founded with McGehee and another friend,
Sherry Hale, the Atlanta Lesbian Cancer Initiative began holding
weekly support groups meetings in October 1996.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Doucher was among five national breast cancer
activists, including entertainer Rosie O'Donnell, who were
recognized for their work by the National Breast Cancer Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Now more than 2 years old, the Atlanta initiative is thriving.
In addition to the support group, it holds a series of monthly
workshops on grief and bereavement.
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks ago, it published the metro area's first lesbian-,
gay- and bisexual-friendly physician list.
</P>
<P>
   ``The physician list goes beyond the scope of AIDS and cancer
and will hopefully help people in our community make choices about
health care providers,'' said McGehee, the organization's executive
director.
</P>
<P>
   The group also recently presented its first community award: the
Dennie Doucher Healing Angel Award, to Dr. Janice Galleshaw, a
metro oncologist.
</P>
<P>
   Despite removal of her right breast in 1992, Doucher's cancer
refused to go away.
</P>
<P>
   The second time it appeared, it attacked her bones. Doucher
underwent chemotherapy and a stem cell transplant. She tried
alternative treatments, including a macrobiotic diet and Chinese
herbs. The third time, cancer struck her brain. She underwent
radiation.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of 1997, cancer reappeared in her brain and spread
to her liver. On Feb. 12, she died, at age 46 _ by all accounts a
soul at rest, a healed spirit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even some lesbians ask me why we need a separate support
group,'' McGehee said, wryly. ``It's because lesbians don't need to
face potential negative reactions when they're going through a
life-threatening illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``All their energy needs to go toward healing.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
