<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Show's storyline about breast-feeding sparks info campaign
 &HT;    By A. Scharnhorst
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ In brilliant color on network television, the
dead baby is rushed into a hospital emergency room _ starved to
death because the infant's breast-feeding mother didn't understand
nutrition.
</P>
<P>
   The horrifying story _ which aired Wednesday night on the CBS
drama ``Chicago Hope'' _ may make gripping television drama, but
national and local breast-feeding advocates are incensed.
</P>
<P>
   The episode, titled ``The Breast and the Brightest,'' has
sparked a national counter-information campaign designed to assure
mothers that breast-feeding is not dangerous for their children.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, a national advocate spotted the storyline on the
``Chicago Hope'' home page on the Internet. The movement was born.
</P>
<P>
   The National Association of WIC Directors _ the group for
administrators of federal Women, Infants and Children programs _
sent out an ``Action Alert,'' warning its members about the
potentially harmful effects of the episode. The national La Leche
League, an organization devoted to educating breast-feeding
mothers, posted a warning on its Web site. Locally, the Palm Beach
County Health Department urged local advocates to call CBS
affiliate WPEC-TV to express their concerns about the plot.
</P>
<P>
   By Wednesday afternoon, the television station had received up
to two dozen calls on the topic, said program manager Donn Colee.
Even before the calls started, the station had decided to produce
and air a segment on breast-feeding for its 11 p.m. news Wednesday,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a good story that's going to run,'' he said Wednesday
afternoon. ``We went with...a lactation consultant on a visit with
the mother of newborn twins.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS encouraged local stations to run such items, as it often
does with Chicago Hope episodes, said a network spokeswoman who
refused to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   And, even if the local station does not do a news piece on the
issue, the Chicago Hope episode should not mislead parents, the
spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The episode is not anti breast-feeding in any way,'' she said.
``It's fictional as is all television, and having viewed it, I'd
say it's pro breast-feeding.''
</P>
<P>
   But local breast-feeding advocates say it isn't as simple as
that. This fictional story could give breast-feeding mothers
unnecessary anxiety that they're harming their children.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public interprets things almost literally _ it is a
concern,'' said Lou Boyes, a board-certified lactation consultant
and WIC breast-feeding coordinator in Palm Beach County. ``Because
of the lack of knowledge out there, it may be misconstrued that
this is a huge danger and it's not a danger at all if the mother is
properly informed.''
</P>
<P>
   Breast-feeding advocates are frustrated by negative publicity
because they have been working for decades to reverse the post
World War II mantra that bottle feeding was best. Only in the last
five years have the percentages of breast-feeding mothers been on
the rise again in the United States, Boyes said. Breast-feeding is
healthier for most babies and mothers in the long term than bottle
feeding, she said.
</P>
<P>
   It's unlikely mothers would watch their infants starve to death
without seeking help, said Boca Raton lactation consultant Marcia
Yolman.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nine times out of 10, these (mothers) will just give up
breast-feeding before they would let it get to that point,'' Yolman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
