<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LETTERS-BOOK23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Girl's letters to `big big world' yield book of intriguing
replies
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If the Coca-Cola Co. had printed menorahs on its soda cans
during the holidays, Naomi Shavin might still be waiting for her 15
minutes of fame.
</P>
<P>
   But Coke didn't, so now the 7-year-old from Sandy Springs is in
the limelight.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Naomi, who is Jewish, was feeling left out by
Coke's Santa Claus imagery. At the urging of her father, Mark, she
wrote the soft drink giant to ask why it didn't put Jewish symbols
on its cans. The company responded with a polite explanation: Coke
avoids religious symbolism, it said, and Santa's not religious.
</P>
<P>
   Naomi, then 5, was pretty impressed. She went on to write other
letters, typed by her dad for clarity, posing questions or making
statements.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 58 letters later, Naomi has published a book called ``Naomi
Wants to Know: Letters From a Little Girl to the Big Big World''
(Fairview Press, $12.95). The book contains Naomi's letters, the
illustrations she drew to accompany them and the responses they
generated.
</P>
<P>
   _ Naomi asked Supreme Court Justice Ruth Bader Ginsburg: ``Are
you in charge of all the people in the United States of America?
Have you ever made a mistake?''
</P>
<P>
   Ginsburg replied: ``I am not in charge of all the people in the
United States, but I work hard to do my judging job well. And yes,
I have made many mistakes, but I try to learn from them so that I
will not make the same mistake twice.''
</P>
<P>
   _ She wrote to the National Labor Relations Board: ``I've got a
lot of problems with me and my little brother Adam. ... He talks
all the time. It keeps me up and I have nightmares that keep me up
and it's enough for me. Will you please try to solve my problems?''
</P>
<P>
   Chairman William B. Gould IV replied: ``I am not sure I can
solve the problems between you and Adam, but here are a few
suggestions. Since you are older than Adam and more grown up you
have a special leadership responsibility to show him the way. Maybe
if you are always willing to share your toys with Adam and never
hit him or pull his hair he will learn by your good example.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Naomi wrote to a homeless person at the Atlanta Union Mission:
``I want to give you a present. ... I'm sending a Barbie. I'd like
to give you toys every weekend, but I don't have that many to
spare.''
</P>
<P>
   A girl, Irece Martin, wrote back: ``I am the one (who) got the
Barbie you sent as a gift. I just like to write you back and thank
you so much for thinking about me.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Naomi met Irece at the mission, and the girls played
happily.
</P>
<P>
   _ She wrote to Sen. John Glenn: ``Here's a joke for you. My
grandmother is 80 years old. I can't imagine her driving a
spaceship because she can't drive a car.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn replied with what appears to be a form letter, telling
Naomi that she too could travel in space. ``As long as you continue
to study and work hard you can achieve anything.''
</P>
<P>
   _ She put a note in a bottle and floated it down the
Chattahoochee: ``What's it like down the river? Do you see any
canoes?''
</P>
<P>
   Six months later, fourth-grader Dale Bailey, who lives 100 miles
downstream, replied: ``I found your letter. ... I was with my Uncle
Glenn and my dad Mike.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Naomi wrote back to Dale, asking him to send her a
picture of him. Which he did.
</P>
<P>
   Naomi's book will hit stores this month, but Naomi seems
unaffected by the attention it's generated among her friends and
family.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not really that excited. My dad doesn't want me to get the
big head,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But it might be kind of hard not to.
</P>
<P>
   She's already pocketed a $3,500 advance from her publisher and
flown to Hollywood to do ``The Roseanne Show.'' (cq) The star
treated Naomi to her first limo ride, her first plane ride, a
computer and a trip to Disneyland.
</P>
<P>
   Naomi will hold her first book signing from 7 to 9 tonight at
Borders Books in the Perimeter Village shopping center in Dunwoody.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Shavin, an executive producer for Fox 5 News, encouraged
his daughter to write letters shortly after she learned the
alphabet. It was a way of bonding; When Dad went home from work, he
would help Naomi practice her writing skills.
</P>
<P>
   Despite her early success in publishing, Naomi said she doesn't
want to be a writer when she grows up.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be a mom,'' she said. ``I'm not sure what else.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
