<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 12:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1305 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PLEASANTVILLE-DANIELS     10-22 1248
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLEASANTVILLE-DANIELS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Pleasantville' star involved for the substance, brilliance of
new film
 &HT;    By Dave Larsen
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO, Ontario _ Jeff Daniels looks right at home behind the
ice cream counter in ``Pleasantville.'' As mild-mannered soda jerk
Mr. Johnson, Daniels discovers spontaneity, creativity and romance
when living color comes to the black-and-white world of a 1950s
television sitcom.
</P>
<P>
   And who better to personify artistic passion in smalltown
America than Daniels? More than 10 years ago, the actor abandoned
Hollywood to return to his hometown of Chelsea, Mich. There he
founded the Purple Rose Theatre Company, dedicated to developing
Midwestern playwrights, directors, designers and actors, while
continuing to expand his stage and screen career.
</P>
<P>
   Daniels calls ``Pleasantville'' the best movie he's ever made.
When your credits include the Oscar-winning ``Terms of
Endearment,'' Woody Allen's ``The Purple Rose of Cairo'' and
Jonathan Demme's ``Something Wild,'' that's quite a statement.
</P>
<P>
   In a hotel suite prior to the film's premiere last month at the
Toronto International Film Festival, Daniels recalled how he passed
on other projects while waiting for first-time director Gary Ross
to roll the cameras amid repeated production delays. ``I'm turning
down work left and right to do this, because I wanted to be a part
of it,'' he explained. ``I loved what it said.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniels' agents were screaming at him all the while, unable to
fathom his devotion to the comic fable by the Academy
Award-nominated screenwriter of ``Big and Dave.'' ``So I said,
`You'll see, you'll see. It's just something I'll be proud to be
in,' '' Daniels said. ``And I am. I really am.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Pleasantville'' is a smart social satire in the guise of a
modern-day fairy tale about two '90s teens transported into a
``Leave It to Beaver'' -like television show. Ross wrote the film,
which opens today, in reaction to Newt Gingrich's Republican
``Contract With America.'' He also drew inspiration from his
father's experience as a blacklisted screenwriter during the
McCarthy era. What starts as an entertaining twist on ``Back to the
Future'' becomes a richly layered allegory about family values,
conformity, censorship and racism.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an intelligent response to the right-wing powers that be
that want to determine what pleasant is and why we should all
strive to achieve that,'' Daniels said. ``Which of course is a room
they're already living in. And Gary's script is going, `No, wait a
minute.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The film's genius is marrying its message to a mainstream
commercial hook instead of shouting it from a soap box, the actor
noted. Tobey Maguire (``The Ice Storm'') and Reese Witherspoon
(``Freeway'') are California twins who, while arguing over a
television remote control left by a mysterious TV repairman played
by Don Knotts, are beamed into the nostalgic sitcom,
``Pleasantville.'' Introducing the denizens of the fictional '50s
suburb to sex, art and ideas, they set off a revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Johnson is the first to be affected, becoming a wildly
expressive painter after being exposed to vibrant works by Picasso
and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're supposed to make everything look like it's happening for
first time in whatever we do as actors, but here's a guy with no
life, no childhood, no background _ no other life other than what
his life is on that show, which is limited in all that he knows,''
Daniels said of his character. ``So here are all these things that
he's exposed to through Tobey Maguire's character, and you get to
realize it and feel it and see it for the first time on camera, all
the time. It was just a thrill.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniels was aware of similarities between ``Pleasantville'' and
``The Purple Rose of Cairo,'' in which he played a movie idol who
steps off the screen and into the real-life world of Mia Farrow,
but was so ``blown away'' by Ross' script that he didn't care about
any possible comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   He said ``Pleasantville's'' conscious symbolism is meant to
recall the McCarthy era, as well as recent attempts to sanitize the
National Endowment for the Arts, in hopes of awakening young
viewers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want you to break rules. We want you to rebel. We want you
dig down and create new work of whatever. I just love that the film
speaks to that, and I hope long after people walk out that young
and old really just walk away with that. Even if it's some Dayton
housewife just going, `You know what, I'm going to start baking
apple pies again, because I was good.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if it goes there!'' he exclaimed, laughing. ``Whatever!''
</P>
<P>
   Daniels, 43, began his career in theater at Central Michigan
University before moving on to New York's famous Circle Repertory
Theatre. He earned a Drama Desk nomination for best supporting
actor as Jed in Lanford Wilson's ``Fifth of July,'' and won and
Obie Award for the Circle Rep production of ``Johnny Got His Gun.''
He most recently appeared in the Broadway production of Wilson's
``Redwood Curtain.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniels made his screen debut in the 1981 film version of E.L.
Doctorow's ``Ragtime.'' His nearly 30 films also include ``Speed,''
``Dumb &AMP; Dumber,'' ``Gettysburg'' and ``Fly Away Home.'' He will
next be seen in Disney's take on the '60s sitcom, ``My Favorite
Martian.''
</P>
<P>
   Seeking stability for his family and thinking his movie career
would never last, Daniels returned to Chelsea, near Ann Arbor,
around the time of 1986's ``Something Wild.'' He founded his
theater company there seven years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our corner of the country, the Midwest, is so often
overlooked,'' he said. In addition to developing regional talent,
Purple Rose commissions plays written by or written about people
from the Midwest. Pulitzer Prize-winner Wilson faced the same
requirement _ plus Daniels' request for ``two jokes'' _ for his
latest play, ``Book of Days,'' whose world premiere was produced by
PRTC last spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Please, write about us,'' Daniels pleaded. ``We're smart
people, too. We're not just something that you fly over on your way
to New York or LA. I mean, the joke is, the reason they invented
nonstops was because nobody wants to see the Midwest, and you start
to feel that way if you live there, which I do. So we created the
theater company to be about and for us.
</P>
<P>
   ``And they're coming,'' he said. ``They're coming in droves.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniels himself has written seven plays for Purple Rose,
including ``Escanaba in Da Moonlight,'' which he has adapted as a
screenplay and plans to direct next year. His latest play, ``Boom
Town,'' which he also directed, premiered last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   When not on a movie set, the actor can be seen around town,
driving his three children _ ages 7, 10 and 13 _ to school, or the
boys to hockey practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love that,'' Daniels said, warmly. ``It takes me out of the
spotlight and puts it on them. But the theater company and the
creativity of being around Gary Ross and (``Pleasantville''
co-stars) Joan Allen and Bill Macy, people like that, it's
inspiring. It's a level, those kind of creative thinkers, I
missed.''
</P>
<P>
   That was part of the reason he created Purple Rose, he
explained, to gather the best creative people he could from around
Michigan, bringing them together in a small town not unlike
``Pleasantville.'' ``It's worked,'' Daniels said. ``It's made the
whole move to Michigan work.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
