<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Antique ivory tusk bought from family for $11,300
 &HT;    By Cathy Mong
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Judy Bailey named it ``Nathan'' and hoped to keep
the antique ivory tusk in the family, but a private buyer paid
$11,300 Wednesday at auction for the rare, 11-pound Narwhal whale
tooth.
</P>
<P>
   The spiral tusk was auctioned by Kramer and Kramer at the Preble
County Fairgrounds in Eaton, along with hundreds of antiques and
remnants from 79-year-old Martha Bailey Horner's days as Brookville
Hardware operator and a homeowner.
</P>
<P>
   Auctioneer John Kramer emphasized that Horton's ownership
predated the Marine Mammal Protection Act of 1972, allowing the
sale of the tooth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't had anything that's taken this much work in my 25
years as an auctioneer,'' Kramer quipped. Interest in the ivory
came from every corner of the United States, Asia and Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Bidding started at $2,000. Horton's son, Robert Bailey, 54, who
used to chase his older brother with the spear in his mom's shop,
flipped his numbered card at Kramer.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruner Arena crowd hushed as the price jumped $1,000 with
each hand signal or nod.
</P>
<P>
   At $10,000 Judy Bailey breathed, ``there goes my car . . . ''
and Horton, seated in a motorized wheelchair next to Bailey,
elbowed her son and shot him an admonishing look.
</P>
<P>
   At $11,300 Bailey shook his head and Barry Harper of Eaton, who
was bidding for someone who wants to remain anonymous, received
pats of congratulations from those around him.
</P>
<P>
   Judy Bailey sighed.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband shrugged, walked off and said, ``I hated to see it
go, but it's gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
