A1308 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONKEYS23-COX     10-22 0774
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONKEYS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MONKEYS , TAUGHT TO COUNT, 'EXTRAPOLATED' TO HIGHER NUMBERS
 &HT;    590&AMP;add. Graphics for this story will be placed in the National
folder on the Cox server.
 &HT;    By JEFF NESMITH
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ One banana, two bananas, three bananas, four.
Monkeys can count.
</P>
<P>
   That discovery, announced Thursday by scientists at Columbia
University, rattles the foundations of some long-held assumptions
on what it means to be human.
</P>
<P>
   For centuries, scientists have believed that the ability to
distinguish between different quantities of things _ two bananas
are fewer than three bananas _ depended on the uniquely human
capacity for language.
</P>
<P>
   Although several different species _ pigeons, rats, parrots and
others, including infant humans _ have been shown to respond
differently to very simple differences in quantities of objects,
the ability to count was believed impossible without having words
like one-two-three-four-five to ``represent'' numerical value.
</P>
<P>
   While they don't do algebra, Rosencrantz and Macduff(cq), a pair
of rhesus monkeys in the university's Primate Cognition Laboratory,
earned passing grades on problems that clearly involved numerical
representation.
</P>
<P>
   In a report in Friday's edition of the journal Science,
researchers Herbert S. Terrace and Elizabeth Brannon describe a
series of training sessions in which the two monkeys were shown
groups of symbols displayed on a touch-sensitive video screen.
</P>
<P>
   Each group had from one to four symbols _ one triangle, two
bananas, three hearts and four apples, for example. Each time one
of the monkeys touched the pictures in ascending order _ such as
one square, then two trees, then three ovals, then four flowers _
he received a banana-flavored food pellet. If he made an error, the
screen turned black for several seconds and a new trial began with
different pictures.
</P>
<P>
   This ``video game,'' which the researchers say the monkeys now
clearly enjoy, trained Rosencrantz and Macduff to perform cognitive
serial tasks without verbal instructions.
</P>
<P>
   Each monkey's ability to correctly select the four quantities
was significantly above random, and improved with added lessons.
</P>
<P>
   But were they thinking _ and counting _ without language, or
simply learning to arrange the groups in four recognizable
categories?
</P>
<P>
   To find out, the psychologist introduced a new set of symbols in
groups of one to nine. Rosencrantz and Macduff never had seen
groups with five or more symbols.
</P>
<P>
   In the new exercises, the monkeys were presented with pairs of
grouped symbols, rather than sets of four.
</P>
<P>
   When each group in a pair had fewer than five symbols _ the
quantities the monkeys had learned to work with _ they picked the
smaller group first more than 90 percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   When one group had four symbols or fewer and the other had five
or more _ such as two apples and seven chess pieces _ the monkeys'
ability to pick the smaller group first was still better than 90
percent.
</P>
<P>
   And when both groups in a pair contained more than five symbols,
the monkeys' scores still were above 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Their scores were significantly higher when the ``distance''
between numbers was greatest _ eight symbols and two symbols,
versus five and four, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Brannon and Terrace believe the experiment is strong evidence
that arithmetic and language evolved separately and that number
skills preceded human speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``Language is a complex social skill, whereas counting can be
learned by the
</P>
<P>
   individual,'' Terrace observed. ``Counting is useful in foraging
for food,
</P>
<P>
   assessing a group of predators or ordering the number of
dominant males in
</P>
<P>
   one's group.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Terrace is director of the Primate Cognition Laboratory, and
Brannon is a graduate student researcher.
</P>
<P>
   The experiment ``elegantly'' showed that even without language,
the animals could ``represent'' numerical meaning, Susan Carey, a
psychologist at New York University, said in a commentary also
published in the scientific journal.
</P>
<P>
   ``This demonstrates that the monkeys were capable not just of
representation of numerical order, but also of the abstraction of a
numerical rule,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At this point, nobody knows how they did it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The process or processes that a monkey uses to detect the
direction of ordinal disparities remains to be determined,'' said
Brannon and Terrace.
</P>
<P>
   Learning that will require further experiments, they added.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
