A1312 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AMERICAN-AIRLINES23-C     10-22 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAN-AIRLINES23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Added flights help American gain edge in Austin departures
 &HT;    By R. Michelle Breyer
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Southwest Airlines, with its cheap fares,
no-frills flights and Dijon-and-orange 737s, has long been the
market leader in Austin skies.
</P>
<P>
   But last month, for the first time in recent history, American
Airlines edged out Southwest in the number of passenger departures
from Robert Mueller Municipal Airport.
</P>
<P>
   It is a feat American accomplished, in large part, by adding new
service to Dallas Love Field and Houston Hobby _ popular business
destinations once the exclusive domain of Southwest on flights from
Austin.
</P>
<P>
   American had 32.3 percent market share for departing passengers
in September, compared with 32 percent for Southwest, according to
city figures. But when it comes to total market share _ service for
both departing and arriving passengers _ Southwest still has a
fractional lead over American, a lead that last month amounted to
about 120 passengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is as close as you get to war in peace time,'' said Ed
Stewart, spokesman for Dallas-based Southwest, which has 41 daily
flights to Austin, including 14 to Love Field.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart said that Southwest is not alarmed by American's
increased strength in the market and its move into Love Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't seen a major drop,'' Stewart said. ``It's a pimple
in the main scheme of things.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are the leader when it comes to (Love Field),'' he said.
``We always have been and we always intend to be.''
</P>
<P>
   But American has become more aggressive in Austin and the result
has landed a bigger chunk of business.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, American's Austin market share was about 22 percent,
compared with Southwest's 39 percent, according to the City of
Austin Department of Aviation. In 1995, American had 24 percent of
the market, while Southwest had 35 percent. Last year, American
jumped to 27 percent, while Southwest had 34 percent.
</P>
<P>
   American considers Austin one of a handful of ``focus cities'' _
non-hub cities where the airline has placed more emphasis. Other
focus cities include Boston, New York City, San Jose, Calif. and
Los Angeles, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   Over the past three years, American has more than doubled its
daily departures from Austin, from 19 to 40. Some of these have
been sought-after nonstop flights to popular destinations such as
San Jose and Miami. Last month, the airline added daily one-stop
service to New York's LaGuardia Airport through Houston Hobby.
Austin business leaders long have sought nonstop service to
LaGuardia.
</P>
<P>
   In late summer, the airline launched its new service between
Austin and Dallas and Houston. Although it initially was more of a
defensive move on American's part to combat efforts by Southwest to
expand its number of interstate flights from Dallas Love Field, the
new flights are proving successful, Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Southwest is still carrying more people than we are into Love
Field,'' said Tim Smith, spokesman for Fort Worth-based American.
``We're the new kids on the block.'' In addition to more flights,
the airline has switched to larger planes on some routes to
accommodate demand. American may be the new kid, but it already is
making its presence known. Earlier this month, American Airlines
snatched away the contract for travel by Texas government employees
from Southwest. The contract is worth well in excess of $1 million.
American expects the contract to generate about 35,000 trips a
year.
</P>
<P>
   And while plans call for American to have five gates at the new
Austin Bergstrom International Airport when it opens next spring _
the same number as it has at Robert Mueller _ it's likely that it
will add others, said Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``Additional gates will be available,'' he said. ``We could go
to six, if there's the opportunity and the need.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
