<SLUG> BC-INTELLIQUEST-EARN23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Intelliquest posts 3rd-quarter profit
 &HT;    By Lori Hawkins
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ IntelliQuest Information Group Inc. said
Wednesday that a year of restructuring allowed it to return to
profitability in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The Austin company reported a profit of $701,000, or 8 cents a
share, on revenues of $13.8 million. During the same quarter a year
ago, the company earned $1.3 million, or 16 cents a share, on
revenues of $12.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``After a year of restructuring, we're beginning to see the
payoff on the bottom line,'' said chief executive Brian Sharples.
``The next thing we need to show is sustained profit growth on an
annual basis, and we expect to do that in 1999.''
</P>
<P>
   IntelliQuest provides marketing services to the high-tech
industry. Its databases and software help companies track product
performance and customer satisfaction. It has 404 employees, 203 of
them in Austin.
</P>
<P>
   The company ran into problems during the fourth quarter of 1997
when it failed to meet revenue expectations. IntelliQuest has lost
$3.26 million in the past three quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Its stock has fallen from a 52-week high of $18.25 on Nov. 5,
1997 to a low of $4.12 1/2 on Oct. 6. Shares were unchanged at
$5.50 on Wednesday in Nasdaq trading.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the restructuring, the company has brought in new
senior management, eliminated unprofitable product lines and is
consolidating operations. For example, the company is in the
process of consolidating three market research centers into one
center in the former Southwood Mall at 1601 W. Ben White Blvd.
</P>
<P>
   An analyst who follows the stock said the company must show
consistent growth before it can win back Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been very inconsistent. They're going to have to build
some momentum before anything's going to happen with the stock
price,'' said Trace Urdan of BT Alex. Brown investment bank in San
Francisco. ``Right now their challenge is to reignite investors'
trust.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharples agreed. ``It's going to take a few quarters of showing
people that when we say we're going to do X, we do X,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In other changes, the company:
</P>
<P>
   Announced that Kit Webster will join the company as chief
financial officer. Webster formerly held the same position at
Austin-based Ross Technologies Inc., which is in the process of
being liquidated.
</P>
<P>
   Adopted a defensive measure, known as a poison pill, to ward off
potential takeovers.
</P>
<P>
   Repriced the company's outstanding stock options, including
options granted to members of the board, at a new grant price of
$5.
</P>
<P>
   Repurchased 270,000 shares in the past two quarters. The
company's board recently voted to buy back 850,000 more.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
