<HEADER>
A1400 &Cx1f; tab-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IVOR-LIFE-IS-BEAUTIFU     10-22 0894
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IVOR-LIFE-IS-BEAUTIFUL-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITALIAN MOVIE BECOMES OSCAR CONTENDER 
</HEADLINE>
  World rights except Great Britain and Australia 
 (This ``separate buy'' article is from this week's Hollywood Stars
feature.) 
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
by fax at 816-822-1444.) 
 (She also has information on how to subscribe to Hollywood Stars, a
weekly column with color art.) 
 &HT;    
 Color slides and black and white photos of Roberto Benigni and
Giorgio Cantarini in scenes from Benigni's film, ``Life Is
Beautiful.''
 By IVOR DAVIS 
 Distributed by New York Times Special Features)  
 &HT;    ``Life Is Beautiful.'' That's not my commentary on the state of
the world, which might seem entirely inappropriate in view of the
stock market, Russia, the Far East and Bill Clinton.
 &HT;    ``Life Is Beautiful'' (``La Vita e Bella'') is a new movie,
modestly budgeted and one of the best films to come along in years.
It opens throughout North America in late October and November but
look for it to be around at Oscar time.
 &HT;    It's Italian with English subtitles and is set in l939 as war
envelopes Europe. The picture stars comic actor Roberto Benigni
(sometimes labeled the Italian Woody Allen) who also wrote and
directed it. He plays the naive Guido who courts and marries the
beautiful teacher Dora (played by his wife of l8 years Nicoletta
Braschi) and dreams of owning his own bookshop. He ignores the
growing incursions of Fascism into his life and the new anti-Jewish
laws until the Nazi occupation sweeps him and his son into a
concentration camp. His gentile wife, refusing to be separated from
her husband and son, is also imprisoned.
 &HT;    It starts off like a Chaplin romance crossed with a Marx
brother's farce and ends up as the spellbinding story of a father's
all encompassing love for his son.
 &HT;    While the conjunction of comedy and Holocaust makes one wince,
Benigni miraculously manages to use humor as an essential element
in the story. For in order to protect his son from the real horrors
of the death camp, Guido pretends to the youngster that the whole
experience is merely a game with bizarre rules. If the boy can hold
out, can stick to the game plan, he and only he will win the grand
prize.
 &HT;    One can only marvel at a movie that makes you laugh when you
know the only sane response is to cry, a movie that makes you come
out of the theater with a smile on your face when you know you
should be in the grip of depression. A man who can do that is not
just an actor and director _ he's a magician.
 &HT;    He could also teach Hollywood a few things. Soon after I saw
``Life Is Beautiful,'' I also saw the Robin Williams extravaganza
``What Dreams May Come,'' which came with a phenomenal price tag of
$85 million and flounders in a sea of computer generated art and
banal dialogue.
 &HT;    Then I viewed Oprah Winfrey in ``Beloved,'' which valiantly
tries to take Toni Morrison's book about a runaway slave who has
killed her own children and translate it into screen material. The
result is ``The Exorcist'' tossed into the middle of a very serious
story. Some novels should simply remain on the page.
 &HT;    Both big commercial films were supposed to be about the infinite
capacity of the human spirit to rise above the miseries of the
world. ``Life Is Beautiful'' actually shows us how to do this.
 &HT;    Made at a fraction of the cost of ``Dreams'' and ``Beloved,'' it
depends entirely on the power of the imagination, on sheer talent,
ingenuity and a simple joy in living.
 &HT;    Benigni admits making this movie was a risky business but he
hoped the early slapstick humor in Guido's romance would make the
camp scenes even more deeply felt. ``I believe laughter saves us,
it forces us to consider the other side of things, the surreal
funny side,'' he says. ``Being able to imagine prevents us from
being reduced to ashes, from being crushed like twigs. It gives us
the sense to survive the endless night.''
 &HT;    Benigni noted his initial reluctance to make a comedy that deals
with the agony of the Holocaust. ``I knew my film would bring up
some very sensitive issues. When the idea first took hold of me, it
was very much like an illumination, a revelation, and my very first
reaction was to retreat. But then I realized the retreat was caused
by fear and in the end my feelings about the story won over the
fear.''
 &HT;    Benigni says he wanted to absorb as deep an understanding as
possible of the real experience of those who lived, loved and
suffered through the camps. He consulted survivor groups and
listened to dozens of personal accounts. ``With Guido I wanted to
create a character who was totally integrated into Italian society,
who lives his life, does his job, isn't the least interested in
politics and then with one blow, his life is suddenly over. That's
the way it happened to many people.''
 &HT;    ``Life Is Beautiful'' won't get the big studio blitz that
``Dreams'' and ``Beloved'' have been given. There won't be huge
billboards all over town, but it has already won top kudos in film
festivals from Cannes to Jerusalem to Montreal. It's an antidote to
the state of affairs around us.
 c.1998 Ivor Davis  (Ivor Davis is a Hollywood-based reporter.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
