<HEADLINE>
Y2CARE ABOUT THE MILLENNIUM BUG? 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The president has announced that it's National
Y2K Action Week, and warned us to prepare for the millennium by
making sure our computers are compatible or at least compliant when
they make time together.
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, it just came out that way. Something about Bill Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, I'm doing my patriotic best to prepare for the
millennium when computer clocks may launch us back to 1900.
</P>
<P>
   I've stocked up on food, water and ammo for my Model 1894
Winchester, and whatever else happens, I'm sure that in six years
I'll be fully prepared for the 1906 earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   In a column a couple of months ago, I knocked all the year 2000
fuss as a soft-core scare tactic by computer consultants to sell
software and services. I made fun of all the television news shows
ominously predicting that our microwaves wouldn't work.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, the hardship. We'd have to time our Swanson's with our
Swatches.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe some two-digit computer clocks would get confused, but
wouldn't it be worth it? So much for a ``Terminator'' vision of the
future. So much for computers running our lives.
</P>
<P>
   So much for arrogant computer geeks, who suddenly turn into
glorified VCR clock-resetters. It's a reassuring vision.
</P>
<P>
   What thanks did I get for trying to stem the Y2K panic? To judge
by e-mail I received after that column, there are thousands of
cultists who almost count on the collapse of civilization when the
clocks strike 2000.
</P>
<P>
   One guy wrote: ``Just wait until your paper's computer crashes
and you don't get a paycheck.''
</P>
<P>
   So what? That paycheck may look good by 1900 standards, but for
what the check is worth now I can wait a while for the bookkeeping
department to find a pen and write a check the old-fashioned way.
</P>
<P>
   One guy called me stupid. Well, maybe, but I can make toast if
the mainframe powering my toaster crashes. First, rub two sticks
together and set fire to your PC. ... If I'm stupid, what about the
geniuses who built computers with only two digits to represent
years?
</P>
<P>
   Sure, they needed all the memory they could get then, but maybe
in the backs of their minds they never believed that their
cobbled-together systems and programs would last into the
millennium of Arthur C. Clarke.
</P>
<P>
   Or else they thought computer-targeted ICBMs would blow up the
world first.
</P>
<P>
   Corporate types, scared by computer consultants, are nervous
about what will happen and are inundating their systems people with
memos and questionnaires.
</P>
<P>
   The systems managers don't really know what they'll be doing on
New Year's Eve of 1999, but they're pretty sure that if they're
watching anything go down, it won't be the ball in Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   What we have here is fill-in-the-blanks sci-fi. A week ago an
episode of ``Millennium'' focused on Y2K cult killers. Don't ask me
the details. ``Millennium'' self-erases after watching. All you had
to know is that a predicted worldwide computer meltdown makes for
good cults.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K is practically a cult already. ``Repent, the end is near''
has been replaced by ``Reboot, 2000 is near.''
</P>
<P>
   Why is it I'm not scared? Is it because I have an iMac that's
Y2K compliant? Yes, downloading dominatrixes, an obedient little
computer is called ``compliant.''
</P>
<P>
   This week the President's Council on Year 2000 Conversion took
out half-page ads in newspapers all over the nation asking
businesses ``Are you Y2K OK?'' The ad listed 159 sponsoring
organizations. They read like a Who's Who of ``What?''
</P>
<P>
   There was the National Turkey Federation. Hey, what turkey ever
lives beyond New Year's?
</P>
<P>
   There was the Internet Society. They would be concerned. The
Internet is filled with Y2K gibberish.
</P>
<P>
   There was the Council on Foundations. Hell, they'll join
anything.
</P>
<P>
   There was the Cellular Telecommunications Industry Association.
Try to imagine a world without people talking to themselves in cars
and restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   There was the Grocery Manufacturers of America. What really
scares me is that groceries are manufactured. Returning to 1900 may
not be so bad.
</P>
<P>
   Why is it that my response to the question ``Y2K OK?'' is still
``Y2Care?''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
