<SLUG> BC-BBO-YANKEES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SEASON FOR THE RECORD BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RAY RATTO  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ So where do these Yankees rank with the greatest
teams of all time? First? Third? Eighth? Twenty-first?
</P>
<P>
   Better yet, how does one make one of these Yankees even address
the question?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where we rank, in all honesty,'' pitcher David
Cone said, reeking of champagne and success. ``How do you compete
with Hall of Famers from years ago? How do you compare with the
ghosts of the past? I don't know if that one has an answer.''
</P>
<P>
   You may be sure, though, that as these Yankees retire and grow
removed from the rough-and-tumble immediacy of their
accomplishment, that they will have an answer for anyone who asks.
They'll sound the way Joe Morgan sounds when he defends the 1975
Reds, or the way Sal Bando sounds when he talks about the A's of
the early '70s.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, they will decide that, yes, they are the best team
of all time, and they'll have some pretty inspiring math to prove
it.
</P>
<P>
   They finished the work Wednesday night in fitting manner _ a 3-0
shutout over the San Diego Padres, with their fourth starter, Andy
Pettitte, beating San Diego's best starter, Kevin Brown. In doing
so, they swept a pretty good team _ not overwhelmingly, and not
because the other team was all thumbs and elbows, but because of
what Tony Gwynn said afterward.
</P>
<P>
   ``This winter is not going to be tough for me, because we got
beat by a better team,'' he said without rancor or hesitation. ``It
would be different if we played lousy. To be honest with you, this
makes it a little easier to take.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the one hard moment for the Padres to take Wednesday
night came in the eighth inning, when Paul O'Neill chopped a ball
to first baseman Jim Leyritz and barely beat Leyritz to the bag.
That play ultimately led to the two final Yankee runs, but for the
moment, it put Brown into a near apoplectic fit. He jumped in the
air, screamed at first-base umpire Tim Tschida, then got into a
chest-to-chest shouting match with second-base umpire Jerry
Crawford, who was trying to lead Brown away from Tschida, and
finally tipped his hat to Tschida in angry sarcasm when he walked
off the field at inning's end.
</P>
<P>
   And, fittingly, given the tone of the series, Tschida had made
the correct call.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be honest with you, at the very moment it happened I'd
have sworn he was out,'' Brown said calmly afterward. ``And yeah, I
carried on about it. But you don't put in a year of work to get to
this point and not be emotional about a call that goes against you.
Now I haven't seen a replay, and if he was safe, then I apologize.
But I don't apologize for my reaction, because you have to allow us
to do that at a time like that. I guess I should thank them for
letting me blow off steam without throwing me out.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the one true turning point in a game the Padres could
never get a grip on, because of Pettitte's brilliant work. He
didn't pitch in New York because his father was ill and because he
was the fourth-best Yankee starter, so some people thought this
might be the Padres' best shot at prolonging the series.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he gave them nothing of value upon which to build their
game. He had only one moment's problem the entire night, loading
the bases in the second, but he drew Brown with two out and retired
him on a bunt. The next time the Padres threatened, in the eighth,
they were down three runs and staring down the barrel of reliever
Mariano Rivera.
</P>
<P>
   It was done, and they knew it. Everybody knew it. This was the
way it had to be.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The postgame celebration was actually kind of muted for a team
that had just finished building a monument. Derek Jeter walked up
to owner George Steinbrenner with a full bottle of Sticky-And-Fizzy
'94, yelled, ``Hold up, there, hold up, there,'' and drenched the
owner, double-breasted coat and all.
</P>
<P>
   They gathered in one corner of the clubhouse and chanted,
``Straw Man!'' for Darryl Strawberry, back home and recovering from
cancer surgery. Then they chanted, ``Scot-ty Brosius!'' for the
series MVP.
</P>
<P>
   And then they considered their place in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I suppose it's fun to argue about, but we won 125 games
and lost 50, so I'd say we have to be up there, don't we?'' Jeter
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had high expectations for ourselves right from the start,''
Chili Davis said. ``The owner had high expectations for us. The
media had high expectations for us. We were hearing about `Greatest
team in history' in the middle of the season. We had nothing to do
but lose, and we didn't. When you have the best record in baseball
ever, you gotta win it all, and we did. We met everybody's
expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   They even met the Padres' expectations of them, which may be the
most remarkable thing of all, since the Padres were the last people
living in denial of what now seems so obvious.
</P>
<P>
   If there was a discouraging word from the Yankee side, it came
inadvertently from general manager Brian Cashman, who leaned
against a wall outside manager Joe Torre's office and said with a
shrug, ``I guess it's all downhill from here, eh fellas?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes, it probably is. But downhill is a very relative term
when you're talking about the greatest, third-greatest,
eighth-greatest or 21st-greatest team of all time. And the
beautiful thing about it is, as time goes by, the '98 Yankees will
only look better. If you don't believe that, ask any of them in
about 15 years. They'll be glad to tell you how much better they'll
be by then.
</P>
</TEXT>
