<HEADLINE>
THIEVES PREY ON SEATTLE MAILBOXES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JANE HADLEY  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Mail is being stolen so frequently from blue street
collection boxes in Seattle that the U.S. Postal Service is
advising customers not to use them.
</P>
<P>
   And it may be years before the Postal Service can make the
city's 1,600 boxes secure again, says Postal Inspector Jim
Bordenet.
</P>
<P>
   Thieves have stolen the master key for the boxes, giving them
access to checks they then take and forge. Often, victims aren't
aware their mail has gone astray until their bank accounts are
drained.
</P>
<P>
   But the Postal Service did not issue a public warning of the
danger until questioned by the Post-Intelligencer. The warning
advises people to avoid putting checks into any blue postal boxes,
including those outside post offices.
</P>
<P>
   A Post-Intelligencer examination of the problem also found that:
</P>
<P>
   _Banks consider the forgery of stolen checks almost routine.
Seattle police estimate that 70 percent of the hundreds of forgery
cases each year are related to mail theft.
</P>
<P>
   _Local police don't consider thefts from the federal mails
within their jurisdiction unless they catch the thief in the act.
</P>
<P>
   _Federal postal inspectors, the first line of defense against
theft of the mail, say they take mail theft seriously. But many
victims say they never respond to complaints.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult to get the feds too interested in this
because there's so much of it,'' King County Sheriff's Office
spokesman John Urquhart said.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly how much mail is stolen is difficult to assess. Seattle
police do not keep statistics on mail theft, considering it a
federal crime. The postal inspection service reported 26,304
arrests nationwide for mail theft between 1993 and 1997. But it
will not release figures for the Seattle area.
</P>
<P>
   In other cities, mail thefts have been brought under control
with the arrest of a gang that has stolen a key. But in Seattle,
master keys appear to be in the hands of many people, making the
problem more difficult to fix, said John Brugger, a spokesman for
the Postal Inspection Service in Washington, D.C. Brugger said
Seattle is the only city having the counterfeit master key problem
at this time.
</P>
<P>
   Theater technician Gail Walls found out the hard way that
mailing her bills at a blue collection box is unsafe. She dropped
payments for her phone and other bills recently into a blue mailbox
in Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   The envelopes were stolen from the mailbox, the ink washed off
the checks with a chemical solution, and the checks were then
forged. Just about all the money in Walls' bank account
disappeared, leaving her with unpaid rent and utility bills and no
money to pay them.
</P>
<P>
   Walls was shocked when a Postal Service employee told her she
should not put her mail into the blue mailboxes on the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like `Excuse me,''' she said. ``Here we have these things
and we think they're safer than (home mail boxes). I know companies
that put everything in them. Nobody's ever said anything to the
general public about this.''
</P>
<P>
   A growing number of citizens are being victimized. And some are
so angry about it they are taking action.
</P>
<P>
   In two Seattle neighborhoods, irate residents have placed their
own warning signs on the postal boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Why have the street boxes at all if they're not safe?
</P>
<P>
   Bordenet says the Postal Service is retrofitting them with new
locks so they will be more secure. However, the retrofitting work
is ``a multiyear project'' and he doesn't know when it will be
completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want the convenience. They want the boxes on the
street,'' Bordenet said. ``We would create a tremendous amount of
public concern if we started removing street collection boxes en
masse. That's not the solution.''
</P>
<P>
   The solution for the moment, he said, lies with citizens,
merchants and banks.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vast majority of our citizens have to change their
behaviors to take account of the threat,'' Bordenet said.
</P>
<P>
   The only safe approach is to do your mailing inside a post
office, Bordenet said. Merchants and banks need to be more careful
about what checks they accept.
</P>
<P>
   But a spokeswoman for the National Federation of Independent
Business in Olympia, Wash., said the Postal Service should be
alerting businesses to the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like if something like this happens, there should be
notice to businesses,'' said Carolyn Logue. ``They may catch the
criminal.''
</P>
<P>
   Walls has not been pleased with the reaction to the theft.
</P>
<P>
   The bank indicated that check washing is ``a pretty normal
occurrence'' and that authorities probably wouldn't do much given
that such a small amount was involved.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't feel like they're ever going to see anybody do
anything,'' she said. ``They laughed and said nothing will ever
happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Seattle police told Walls it wasn't their jurisdiction and that
she needed to call federal postal inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   She did, leaving her name and number. But they never called
back.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Walls is out about $1,000. ``It's everything I had,''
she said. ``My rent check, my car payment, my electricity, my
phone. All those bills that I really, really need to pay. It was a
major blow.''
</P>
<P>
   Walls is particularly upset because the bank branch has
videotape of the woman who tried to cash the washed check, yet
authorities have demonstrated little interest in pursuing the case.
</P>
<P>
   Urquhart, the spokesman for the Sheriff's Office, wasn't
surprised.
</P>
<P>
   Federal postal inspectors have to involve a grand jury and get
in line at the U.S. Attorney's Office to prosecute cases, Urquhart
said. They don't want to bother with small cases.
</P>
<P>
   But postal theft can be frustrating for local authorities to
prosecute, too.
</P>
<P>
   Urquhart said if the thief is caught in the act of stealing the
mail, it's theft. If a person is caught with the mail after the
fact, it's possession of stolen property.
</P>
<P>
   But the local penalties in either case are likely to be minor,
because the value of a stolen letter _ even if it contains a $2,000
mortgage payment _ is 32 cents, Urquhart said. That makes it a
misdemeanor akin to shoplifting.
</P>
<P>
   The value doesn't go up until the thief has actually washed the
check and tried to cash it. That makes it forgery, a felony.
</P>
<P>
   Federal penalties for stealing or possessing stolen mail are
much stiffer: up to five years or a fine of $250,000 for each piece
of stolen mail, Bordenet said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
