<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-FEATURE-SPI </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Seattle Post-Intelligencer plans to move the following
stories for clients of the NYTimes News Service for editions of
Friday, Oct. 23, and thereafter. If you have any questions, please
call Bob Schenet at (206) 448-8037.
</P>
<P>
   FILM-PUPIL (Undated) _ ``Apt Pupil'' is more unpleasant than
thought-provoking, more repulsive than suspenseful or thrilling,
and utterly predictable. But Ian McKellen is undeniably riveting in
it.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-PLEASANTVILLE (Undated) _ The biggest drawback of Gary
Ross' trapped-in-an-inane-TV-show movie, ``Pleasantville,'' is that
it has basically the same premise and theme as ``The Truman Show,''
and it's not half as good. It's visually interesting, but
incredibly flimsy.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-SOLDIER (Undated) _ Kurt Russell's new sci-fi action movie,
``Soldier,'' is nothing to write home about, but it's a bit better
than the chest-pounding, G.I. Space-Joe epic promised by its
publicity _ and better than the dismal track record of its director
Paul Anderson (``Event Horizon'') might indicate.
</P>
<P>
   By William Arnold. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-HAPPINESS (Undated) _ It may seem illogical, but
``Happiness,'' an ultra dark ``comedy'' from Todd Solondz, is oddly
sympathetic in its perversity. Even though it features a pedophile
as a primary character, the film manages to eke out some sense of
compassion for its wayward, lost souls.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-ORGAZMO (Undated) _ ``Orgazmo'' has an outrageous and
irreverent premise that never makes good on its potential, even
though the laughs are fairly constant and a preview audience
appeared to have a good time, guffawing heartily at the silliness
of it all.
</P>
<P>
   By Paula Nechak. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
<P>
   TV-BRIMSTONE (Undated) _ Review of Brimstone, drama series about
a deceased police detective who is dispatched from hell to round up
113 escapees. Premieres Friday on Fox.
</P>
<P>
   By John Levesque. (Story will move in the ``e'' category.)
</P>
</TEXT>
