u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STREHLI-MUSIC-PROFILE     10-22 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREHLI-MUSIC-PROFILE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLONDE AND BLUE, ANGELA STREHLI HAS THE `DEJA BLUES' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By RICK MITCHELL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ The B.B. King song title ``Never Make Your Move Too
Soon'' pretty much sums up Angela Strehli's approach to putting out
albums.
</P>
<P>
   In a blues-singing career dating back more than 25 years, she
has released a grand total of three solo albums, plus the ``Dreams
Come True'' collaboration with fellow Texans Lou Ann Barton and
Marcia Ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't take myself seriously for about 10 years, and then it
took another 10 years to get good at it,'' Strehli says with a
husky laugh.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just been in the last five years or so that I've been
happy with my performances _ my singing. You've got to get some
mileage on you before you have the authority to really put it
across.''
</P>
<P>
   Strehli's latest album, ``Deja Blue,'' conveys the kind of
soulful credibility that comes only with personal experience.
Released this summer on the House of Blues label, the album
features sessions recorded in California _ where Strehli now lives
_ as well as her former home of Austin.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday at Billy Blues in Houston, Strehli will make her
first Houston appearance in several years. She'll share the stage
with West Coast blues veteran Joe Louis Walker, who also has a new
album to promote: ``Preacher and the President.'' Both artists are
bringing their own bands.
</P>
<P>
   A native of Lubbock, Strehli hails from the same musical
generation of West Texans that produced Flatlanders Joe Ely, Jimmie
Dale Gilmore and Butch Hancock. Her brother, Al Strehli,
contributed a couple of tunes to Gilmore's ``Spinning Around the
Sun'' album.
</P>
<P>
   But while she grew up surrounded by folk, country and rock 'n'
roll, Strehli felt pulled toward the black blues and gospel music
she picked up on late-night radio from Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as I heard it, it really grabbed me,'' she says. ``I
had to find out what it was all about. That took a while.''
</P>
<P>
   She moved to Austin in 1966 to attend the University of Texas,
from which she graduated. She also began dabbling in music.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just a big fan,'' she says. ``As far as blues went, I
wanted to play bass and harmonica.''
</P>
<P>
   She eventually fell in with other like-minded musicians,
including Kim Wilson and Jimmie Vaughan, who went on to form the
Fabulous Thunderbirds, and Jimmie's younger brother, Stevie Ray
Vaughan.
</P>
<P>
   ``When all of us started, people thought we were crazy,'' she
says. ``Blues was just real down, period. It was not hip in any
way, and you could hardly make a living at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why Clifford (Antone) built the club, Antone's, to turn
the general population on to the real masters of the blues and to
also allow the rest of us to open and be seen on a proper stage, so
people would realize what we were trying to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The young white blues players had to contend not only with the
indifference of Austin's music-going public, which, at the time,
was far more interested in cosmic cowboys and country outlaws. They
also had to deal with the backlash from so-called blues purists,
who chastised them for trying to rip off black music.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told us, `Either you can't do it, or you shouldn't do it.
Take your pick,' '' says Strehli. ``The only ones who didn't feel
that way were the artists themselves, who saw that we were ready to
devote our lives to the form that they had created, and they were
glad to pass it on.''
</P>
<P>
   Strehli helped manage Antone's Blues Club in the early years.
She also co-founded the Antone's record label.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clifford had all these beautiful live recordings that nobody
else wanted to put out,'' she says, ``so it made sense for us to
start our own label.''
</P>
<P>
   Strehli made her debut for the label in 1987 with ``Soul
Shake.'' This was followed in 1990 by ``Dreams Come True,'' a
rhythm and blues ``girl group'' album with Ball and Barton. She
counts the latter project among the highlights of her career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a miracle for us to be able sing together and have
it sound so good, because our voices are all so different,'' she
says. ``I just loved that. I would still be doing that if anyone
else wanted to.''
</P>
<P>
   In the early '90s, Strehli married rock band manager Bob Brown
(Pablo Cruise, Huey Lewis &AMP; the News) and moved to Novato, 30 miles
north of San Francisco in Marin County.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never expected to leave Austin,'' said the five-time winner
of the Austin Music Awards' poll for best female blues singer. ``It
was love.''
</P>
<P>
   When Strehli started working on ``Deja Blue,'' she didn't have a
record contract. (Her previous album, ``Blonde and Blue,'' came out
in 1993 on Rounder.) She wrote six of the album's 11 tracks,
reflecting her increasing confidence as a composer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that I've had to grow into,'' she says. ``It
would help if I played an instrument well enough to demonstrate
what I want. As it is, I have to eke it out. It helps that I have
great musicians working with me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Deja Blue'' is a tour-de-force of blues styles showcasing
Strehli's powerhouse vocals, from the old-fashioned ballad ``A Man
I Can Love'' to the shuffle ``Hey Miss Tonya'' (which she wrote for
her dog) and the revved-up rocker ``Boogie Like You Wanna.''
</P>
<P>
   She is joined by Barton and Ball (``Still a Fool''); Doug Sahm
(Jimmy Reed's ``Close Together,'' Tarheel Slim &AMP; Little Anne's
``Too Late'') and Steve James (Willie Mae Williams' ``Where the Sun
Never Goes Down'').
</P>
<P>
   Even the blues fan seems satisfied by the album.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do feel that I'm contributing to the genre,'' Strehli says.
``My songs aren't anything earth-shattering, but I think they're
appropriate _ just good blues songs. I feel I'm doing my part.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
