<SLUG> BC-HALLOWEEN-COSTUMES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HALLOWEEN COSTUMES RANGE FROM `BILL AND MONICA' TO TELETUBBIES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By CRISTINA MASUDA 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ After celebrating previous Halloweens dressed as a
devil and belly dancer, Lisa Bates was undecided about her costume
for this year.
</P>
<P>
   Determined to find the best outfit, the 30-year-old went to Just
for Laughs in northwest Houston for a little ``research.''
</P>
<P>
   The inspiration came before she even entered the store. In the
window, a female mannequin with a black wig and beret caught her
attention. It was paired with another male mannequin holding
presidential knee pads and wearing a mask covered with red lipstick
marks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be really funny,'' said Bates, referring to the
Halloween party she will attend as Monica Lewinsky, the former
White House intern. Bates' boyfriend will don a Bill Clinton mask.
</P>
<P>
   But of the approximately $1 billion expected to be spent on
Halloween costumes this year, Monica and Bill won't be alone in the
moonlight.
</P>
<P>
   Both men and boys are clamoring to be Zorro. The dashing hero is
popular once again because of this summer's hit movie, ``The Mask
of Zorro,'' starring Antonio Banderas as the swashbuckler with a
sword.
</P>
<P>
   Stan Damewood, 34, will spend about $80 to rent a Zorro cape,
hat, mask, clothes, boots and a sword from Performing Arts Supply
Co. in the Spring Branch area of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I decided to become Zorro because of his sex appeal,''Damewood
said.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he would be looking for his Elena de la Vega, Zorro's
romantic partner, Damewood said that wouldn't be necessary. ``My
girlfriend, Brandy, will be dressed like a Mexican senorita.''
</P>
<P>
   Mickey Frost, owner of Southern Importers in downtown Houston,
said two things inspire Halloween costumes: current events and
movies.
</P>
<P>
   Just as O.J. Simpson masks were hot a few years back when the
former football star was accused of murder, the Clinton-Lewinsky
scandal is prime for Halloween masquerades.
</P>
<P>
   For the trick-or-treaters, however, the choices are cartoon
characters from the big and small screens, not the characters from
Washington's real-life drama.
</P>
<P>
   Expect to see plenty of little Teletubbies, from the British
children's TV series on PBS, and Mulan, the female Disney hero, at
your door on Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   Teletubbies are the top-selling costume for children at Just for
Laughs. At Party City in northwest Houston, owner Rustom B.
Engineer has tried to get more of the yellow, green, red and blue
bodysuits for his small clients. All four characters quickly sold
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't prepared for such a good sale,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And just as little boys want to be a hero as Zorro, little girls
have the same goal this year.
</P>
<P>
   Mulan, the Chinese heroine from the animated movie, was so
popular that it is already sold out at many stores.
</P>
<P>
   There are two options for the girls who choose Mulan and can
still find it at discount stores: a gown in pink and purple with a
flower hair ornament and a warrior costume, in blue and green, with
pants, scarf and hair tie.
</P>
<P>
   Zorro, Mulan and the Teletubbies are on the Home Sewing
Association's Halloween Top 10 list. Since 1995, the association
has predicted the hottest costumes for Halloween through a survey
of its 2,400 members _ mainly sewing stores and suppliers. Also on
the list: Beanie Babies, toy soldiers/military men, the Spice
Girls, South Park characters, Cinderella, Titanic-era dresses and
Mr. and Mrs. Potato Head.
</P>
<P>
   To store managers' pleasant surprise, the costume from the movie
``Scream'' continues to be a big hit this year. The movie's sequel,
``Scream 2,'' was released on video this summer. The stark mask
costs $9.99 at area stores.
</P>
<P>
   But there are no Monica masks on the market. The New York Times
reported that ``mask companies may have been wise to steer clear.''
An aide to Lewinsky told the Times no one had asked permission to
license a Monica mask, but that if anyone did, she would refuse.
The aide said the former intern's lawyers were looking for ways to
crack down on entrepreneurs who have used her picture on cookies,
T-shirts and postcards.
</P>
<P>
   Lacking a mask, the items needed to create the Monica look
include a black wig, black beret, bright red lipstick and oversized
cigars. The most difficult part will be the blue dress, as most
costume stores aren't stocking it.
</P>
<P>
   Sam McCabe, owner of Wear It Again Sam in Houston, said some
clients are ``staining'' their dresses with white candle wax.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have such a creativity when it's Halloween,'' McCabe
said.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Leva, manager of Texas Theatrical Supply &UR;  &LR; just south of
downtown, agreed. ``Last week I saw a woman with blue dress and a
`DNA tested' tag.''
</P>
<P>
   To make a Lewinsky outfit, Leva sells a traditional beret for $8
and a version with a bow, especially designed for this Halloween,
for $24.50. A Clinton mask with lipstick marks can be purchased for
the same price.
</P>
<P>
   The lipstick-marked mask, named Wild Clinton, is sold out at
Party City, but a lipstick-free presidential mask is still
available for $16.99.
</P>
<P>
   While most stores are selling Lewinsky items individually,
Spirit Halloween Superstores offer a ``President's Intern Kit'' for
$14.99, complete with beret, pearl necklace, plastic lips and a
White House badge.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of our best sellers, especially for women 20 to 30
years old,'' said regional manager Cory Marver, who oversees three
stores in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel's Costume Co. owner Terrie Frankel finds Clinton and
Lewinsky costumes tasteless.
</P>
<P>
   This year, she's betting on romanticism, particularly Zorro and
Elena, as well as Jack and Rose from ``Titanic.'' With ``The Mask
of Zorro'' a success in the theaters, she knew it also would be a
hit this Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   ``I anticipated my clients' request and made many Zorro and
Elena costumes,'' she said. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
