<SLUG> BC-PARIS-FASHION-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESIGNERS PRESENT DISPARATE COLLECTIONS IN PARIS SHOWS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By LINDA GILLAN GRIFFIN 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ Anyone who tries to make sense of the world of fashion
has at one time or another experienced the following sensation: ``I
must be crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   The emphasis in that statement falls not on the word ``crazy''
but on the pronoun ``I.''
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because fashion, like art or music or poetry, is best
understood by its creators _ who sometimes defy understanding. So
observers trying to fit square-hole _ or more often hexagonal _
fashions into some round-hole chart that explains how women can
expect to dress six months in the future should count on feeling
deranged.
</P>
<P>
   Take the following disparate designers' collections.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Issey Miyake &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Inventive Issey Miyake has a new system of tube dressing that
allows the customer to cut out the dress, skirt or swimsuit she
wants. On the runway, his assistants snipped the stretchy fabric
into separate and distinctive pieces, followed by models in bright
green and turquoise examples.
</P>
<P>
   And how many Miyake models can squeeze into one bright red
caterpillar tube of fabric? Twenty-two, of course.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Paco Rabanne &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the Paco Rabanne collection, where one would expect a tour de
force of metallics _ the materials from which this designer's
reputation was forged _ there were indeed dresses of linked metal
plaques or studded with silver. Out of the '60s? Yes, but they once
more looked modern.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Guy Laroche &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Turn the fashion kaleidoscope and factor in the designs of Alber
Elbaz of Guy Laroche, who turned out one of the most cohesive
collections here.
</P>
<P>
   The show began with a reading of Edgar Allen Poe's poem
``Annabelle Lee'' and continued with soft music and a slow _ some
called it mournful _ movement of models through the audience. But
Elbaz's theme was flowers, and he executed it perfectly, sparing
what might have been a heavy hand.
</P>
<P>
   Slim, sleek suits with three-quarter sleeves bore a silk flower
on the lapel or at the neck of a shell blouse. A dress with a
flower at the neckline sported tiny pleats and tucks that appeared
as stems and leaves. Colors were soft or dark grays and pale or
bright flower shades, never garish.
</P>
<P>
   Elbaz begins designing ready-to-wear for the house of Yves Saint
Laurent Nov. 1. Dutch designer Ronald van der Kemp will take over
at Laroche.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Chloe &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Stella McCartney, who stumbled last season with a collection of
tarty, sleazy satins, returned Chloe to pretty, girlish clothes for
spring '99. With cascades of chiffon ruffles, the thinnest knits
and air-brushed nature prints, her clothes were aimed at growing-up
girls who just want to have fun. On a sad note, the show was
dedicated to her late mother, photographer Linda McCartney. Former
Beatle Paul McCartney sat in the front row.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Emanuel Ungaro &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In a radical departure, designer Emanuel Ungaro shifted gears
from his signature jackets and sent a bevy of softly clad models
around a pasture of green grass and weeds.
</P>
<P>
   Attired in flat, gold sandals by Ferragamo _ the company
controls the house of Ungaro _ models wore sweater sets, cardigan
jackets, long suede skirts and chiffons printed with dark floral
and foliage patterns.
</P>
<P>
   These were pretty, light, drapey designs, like lingerie, albeit
for adults. The image certainly tapped into the way Americans
dressed this past summer, in long bias dresses with pointelle
cardigans.
</P>
<P>
   Still, with all the lace edging, hems dragging in the meadow and
sheer fabrics, what does one wear to work? But then, maybe Ungaro
clients don't. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-98 1404EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
