<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 14:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1459 &Cx1f; tad-z
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-FLOOD-$ADV25-CO     10-22 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-FLOOD-$ADV25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    75,000 CHINESE FACE FRIGID WINTER IN 'DUGOUTS'
 &HT;    With photos placed in the International folder on the Cox
Server.
 &HT;    EDs: For purposes of a map, Hujitumo is a small town 65 miles
west of the city of Daqing, China. The dugout camp is a few miles
west of the town center.
 &HT;    For Use Sunday, Oct. 25 And Thereafter.
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL and JOSEPH ALBRIGHT 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUJITUMO, China _ In one of the coldest reaches of China,
twenty-three-year-old mother Bai Ming Xia has been assigned to live
with her new baby through this winter inside a sandbagged shelter
dug into the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Provincial flood-fighting officials in China's northernmost
Heilongjiang Province have decided that the best way to house Mrs.
Bai and 75,000 other victims of this summer's flood is in temporary
camps consisting of brick-lined ``dugouts.''
</P>
<P>
   Each dugout has sandbagged walls that rise a few feet above
ground level and are topped with a roof made of straw and plastic
sheeting. The only heating comes from a single brick hearth that
doubles as a cook stove.
</P>
<P>
   By January, the temperature on the windswept hillside where Mrs.
Bai's dugout sits is expected to slip to 22 below zero. And even
the government worries about finding enough fuel for the dugout
dwellers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our duty is to ensure that no victim of the flood will starve
or freeze to death,'' Ma Shu Jie, the provincial deputy governor,
said in an interview with the Cox News Service.
</P>
<P>
   To Western ears, Ma's pledge may sound minimal. But
accomplishing even that much will be no small feat here in this
hardscrabble frontier region that is worlds apart from the glitz
and bustle of modern China's cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are now working out plans to bring 100,000 cubic meters of
firewood from north of the province,'' Ma explained. ``But we don't
have enough money to pay for it.'' She would also like to transport
coal from province mines to the dugouts, but so far there are not
enough funds for that either.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the destruction of about 300,000 mud- and clay-walled
homes, Ma said, the peasants of Heilongjiang Province lost 186,000
head of livestock as well as crops and grasslands to the floods
that swelled over the banks of three major rivers -- the Heilong,
Songhua and Nen rivers.
</P>
<P>
   But Heilonjiang authorities say that not a single human life was
lost in the province of 36 million because of their insistent,
sometimes forcible, efforts to relocate local farmers in advance of
the cresting waters.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, most dugout dwellers have accepted the government's
determination about their future with the kind of resigned stoicism
that has characterized China's farmers, now 900 million strong, for
most of the last 5,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Bai, however, is an exception. She is hoping to go her own
way with her two-month-old daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``The baby can't live in such cold in the winter. It's dark and
wet here,'' said Mrs. Bai, a round-cheeked young woman. ``I'll go
to my relatives' home. There isn't much room, but it will be better
than here.'' Her husband and his parents will weather the winter in
the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Across China, more than 5.8 million families lost their homes in
August and September floods that killed more than 3,600 people and
caused losses estimated at $30 billion. But outside this northern
province, the hardest-hit areas were in the warmer climes of
central and south-central China, where victims can expect a less
punishing winter.
</P>
<P>
   This is the Siberia of China, a province just south of the
Russian border whose broad farm and grass lands normally surrender
growth to snowfall by the close of October.
</P>
<P>
   It is a region of jolting contrasts, where wealth from the
Daqing oil fields allows even small cities luxurious indoor
swimming arcades and multi-storied department stores, while
hundreds of thousands of poor farmers live in mud houses without
plumbing.
</P>
<P>
   About 10 miles from Mrs. Bai's dugout, some recent visitors were
led to a nearly completed village of 112 solidly built brick duplex
houses. Local leaders said the houses will be assigned to flood
refugees, but probably not until next spring.
</P>
<P>
   Jiao Ming Zhe, head of the Hujitumo town propaganda committee,
said construction crews had not had time to put in the ceilings
meant to go under the roofs. What's more, the planned hook-ups for
water, electricity and cable television have yet to be installed.
</P>
<P>
   And in any case, Deputy Gov. Ma said the roughly 75,000 dugout
dwellers scattered in camps throughout western Heilongjiang do not
have first priority in obtaining the new brick duplexes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The victims in the dugouts are considered to be living in very
good shelters. The new houses should be used for people living in
other people's homes,'' she said, referring to the more than 1.4
million other homeless flood victims in this province, who are now
doubling up in mud farmhouses or tiny city apartments of friends
and relatives.
</P>
<P>
   The deputy governor said the Heilongjiang government has no
thought of moving the rural dugout dwellers into the hundreds of
vacant apartments in modern high-rise cities like Harbin, the
provincial capital of five million people.
</P>
<P>
   ``The victims are farmers,'' Ma explained. ``They have to be
near their land to prepare for farming next year.''
</P>
<P>
   The central feature of the shelters, which measure about 9-by-18
feet, is a plastic-covered brick platform used as a bed. One end
contains a wood-burning oven that not only provides for cooking,
but heats the platform bed and radiates some warmth into the room.
</P>
<P>
   Firewood is the biggest worry of the ``dugout'' refugees. They
know that is what will keep them from freezing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now what we need most is wood to make fires, because the trees
and the grass are all wet,'' said Chen Ling Ji, 52.
</P>
<P>
   Chen is from Jubaoshen, the same village as Bai, and like the
younger woman she was unemotional in telling how her family fled
and lost their home, then had to split up under the pressures of
refugee life.
</P>
<P>
   But finally Chen, too, reached the point when her personal
floodgate ruptured.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly weeping, she broke down and tightly gripped the hand of
a visiting journalist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very lucky to meet you,'' she said through tears. ``It's
the first time I have seen an American. It is very lucky.''
</P>
<P>
   Underneath Chen's courage was a vein of fear and a sense that
she and tens of thousands of other Chinese need a goodly dose of
luck on top of government promises that they will make it through
the winter.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
