<HEADLINE>
RICE EAGER TO GET RECORDS OUT OF THE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN CRUMPACKER  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARA, Calif. _ In theory, Jerry Rice of the San Francisco
49ers can break one NFL record and tie another with a single catch
on Sunday in St. Louis. That catch would have to be for a
touchdown, however.
</P>
<P>
   Rice is tied with Art Monk for most consecutive games with at
least one reception, at 183. With 78 touchdown catches as a
combination, Rice and Steve Young are one behind the record of 79
set by Miami's Dan Marino to Mark Clayton from 1983-92.
</P>
<P>
   Rice began his consecutive-games streak in a big way against the
Rams on Dec. 9, 1985. He had 10 receptions for 241 yards and a
66-yard touchdown. His first touchdown catch from Young, for 46
yards, came on Nov.15, 1987, against New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Of all his 13 NFL records, Rice said breaking Monk's mark is
second in importance to surpassing Jim Brown's career record for
touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm honored to be in that position,'' Rice said. ``I idolized
that guy (Monk). It means a lot to me. I would like to get it over
as quickly as possible. It can work as a distraction.''
</P>
<P>
   Both quarterback and receiver are eager to be done with the
records.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm kind of tired of talking about it,'' Young said of the
combo record. ``We need to get some touchdowns to Jerry. I've
figured out where he wants the ball and when, what he likes and
doesn't like. Through the years we've become great friends and it
shows on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice said, ``I would like to get this one over with. Steve and I
have developed a good working relationship. We're fortunate to be
in a position to break the touchdown record. Hopefully, it will
happen this weekend. It's been awhile since I've been in the end
zone.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been nearly a month, as a matter of fact. Rice had two
touchdown receptions against Atlanta on Sept. 27. Since then, he's
been kept out of the end zone by Buffalo, New Orleans and
Indianapolis. For the 49ers, it's a disturbing trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teams are really determined to double me in the red zone,''
Rice said of the area inside the opponent's 20-yard line. ``I'll
have to score from 50 yards in. That's why Terrell (Owens) and J.J.
(Stokes), if they're singled, they have to make plays, and they
are.''
</P>
<P>
   The statistics bear that out.
</P>
<P>
   Rice is tied for the team lead in receptions with Stokes at 31,
but Stokes has the lead in touchdown catches with five, two more
than Rice. Owens is close behind with 26 and three TDs. However,
Rice's average gain per catch, 16.1 yards, is the highest it's been
since 1991. It reflects the 49ers' greater emphasis on downfield
routes.
</P>
<P>
   Rice said defensive backs are staying in contact with him more
often and farther down the field, beyond the legal 5-yard jam zone.
He usually encounters a safety downfield as well in what is
referred to in football jargon as ``Cover 9,'' not to be confused
with ``Plan 9 From Outer Space.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, only eight receivers in the NFL have more catches than
Rice at this point in the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means he's getting himself open against double- and
triple-teams, everything,'' Young said. ``Look at the generations
of defenses _ whatever a generation is _ and he's still getting
open.''
</P>
<P>
   And when he's not, Rice has struck the classic ``I was wronged''
posture _ hands extended plaintively from his sides, hoping the
officials will throw a penalty flag based on who he is. A smart
ploy, that.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot more going on, but I got to let it go,'' he said.
``I can't turn around every time and look to the officials and
expect to get a flag. The game is a lot more physical. I want to do
more and right now teams are deciding not to let me. I've got to be
patient and the door will open.''
</P>
</TEXT>
