<HEADLINE>
RAIDERS COACH APOLOGIZES FOR DUI CHARGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SAMUEL CHI  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALAMEDA, Calif. _ Coach Jon Gruden of the Oakland Raiders
apologized after he was charged with driving under the influence of
alcohol.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've apologized to the organization, our team and Raiders fans
and anybody who might be offended by it,'' Gruden said. ``This is
now a legal matter and it's being handled by the legal counsel.''
</P>
<P>
   Gruden was charged with misdemeanor drunken driving after the
blood test result taken after his arrest on Oct. 11 showed his
blood-alcohol level to be .10, above California's legal limit of
.08. Gruden was stopped by a California Highway Patrol officer who
spotted him straddling the lanes and traveling 15-20 mph over the
speed limit of 35 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Gruden was charged Wednesday by the Alameda County District
Attorney's Office. He is scheduled to appear in Alameda County
Superior Court in Pleasanton on Nov. 6.
</P>
<P>
   At a minimum, Gruden could lose his driver's license for 90
days, but he could be sentenced to six months in jail and fined
$1,000 if convicted.
</P>
<P>
   The National Football League also could take disciplinary action
against Gruden, said Leslie Hammond, director of media services for
the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's hard to say what action the league will take. We
don't want to speculate and it's too premature,'' Hammond said.
</P>
<P>
   Raiders players said they were not concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gruden's a big boy, he can handle it,'' said wide receiver Tim
Brown. ``We'll let him deal with his own problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Said quarterback Donald Hollas: ``I have no reaction, really.
It's a personal thing and that has no effect on what's happening
here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
