<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GULF-SYNDROME-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPENDING BILL FUNDS GULF WAR ILLNESS STUDY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By KATHLEEN SULLIVAN  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A little-noticed provision in the federal
spending bill President Clinton signed into law may give Gulf War
veterans the answers to the mysterious health ailments that have
plagued them since the 1991 conflict.
</P>
<P>
   The provision requires the National Academy of Sciences to
detail the dangerous substances soldiers were exposed to during the
brief war and identify the illnesses that can be linked to that
exposure.
</P>
<P>
   Veterans organizations hailed the measure, saying the
investigation by the respected panel of scholars might help
separate fact from fiction in the discussion of Gulf War illnesses.
The groups long have criticized Defense Department research of the
ailments.
</P>
<P>
   Under a $520 billion budget package that Clinton signed
Wednesday, the academy will identify biological and chemical
toxins, environmental hazards, preventive medicines and vaccines
connected to the war.
</P>
<P>
   The law includes a list of 33 possible causes, including sandfly
fever, a disease endemic to the Persian Gulf region; sarin, a nerve
agent; smoke from oil-well fires; and depleted uranium, a
radioactive and toxic metal fashioned into ammunition used by
American soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   The new law calls on the academy to review and evaluate existing
research on Gulf War illnesses, and, if needed, recommend further
research to solve the mystery of the ailments reported by
approximately 100,000 veterans.
</P>
<P>
   The National Academy of Science is a private, nonprofit group of
scholars that advises the federal government on scientific and
technical matters.
</P>
<P>
   The academy will give definitive answers to sick veterans, said
Paul Sullivan, executive director of the National Gulf War Resource
Center, a Washington-based coalition fighting for medical care for
veterans and their families.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a year or two, when the research results start to come in
and the National Academy of Sciences issues its findings, we will
finally be able to separate fact from fiction,'' he said. ``We will
finally know whether exposure causes illnesses.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan praised the last-minute maneuvering by Sen. Robert
Byrd, D-W.Va., whose efforts ensured that the legislation included
a means for veterans to get free health care and disability
benefits for illnesses linked to toxic exposures in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the academy looks at the literature and decides that
exposure to depleted uranium causes lung cancer, a Gulf War veteran
with lung cancer can be service connected for that condition,''
Sullivan said. ``If the VA wants to deny the veteran's claim, it
has to prove why the illness is not connected to exposure in the
Gulf.''
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the burden of the proof has been on the sick veteran,
Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan criticized the continuing research sponsored by the
Defense Department and the Department of Veterans Affairs, saying
their studies focused too heavily on stress as the source of Gulf
War illnesses. ``They've avoided the hard questions _ like the
effect of exposing soldiers to the combination of pesticides and
experimental pills,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Office of the Special Assistant on Gulf War Illnesses, which
is overseeing the Pentagon's investigation, did not return phone
calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Byrd said the physical pain suffered by Gulf War veterans had
been compounded by the emotional stress caused by the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``These veterans deserve medical care for the illnesses that
they contracted as a result of their service in the Gulf,'' Byrd
said. ``We should learn from our mistakes in treating Vietnam
veterans, and not delay medical treatment for our veterans for
another 20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Vietnam veterans had to fight for more than 20 years to get
medical care and disability compensation for ailments linked to
wartime exposure to the herbicide Agent Orange.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The new law also:
</P>
<P>
   _ Extends the VA's special authority to provide care for Gulf
War veterans at its hospitals through Dec. 31, 2001.
</P>
<P>
   _ Establishes a public panel, which will include Gulf War
veterans, to advise the VA, the Defense Department and the
Department of Health and Human Services on proposed research
studies, plans and strategies.
</P>
<P>
   _ Requires that the VA, working with the National Academy of
Sciences, establish a mechanism for monitoring and studying the
effectiveness of treatments provided to Gulf War veterans.
</P>
<P>
   _ Extends the authority of the VA to evaluate the health status
of spouses and children of Gulf War veterans through Dec. 31, 1999.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
