<SLUG> BC-FILM-PUPIL-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IAN MCKELLEN SHINES IN GRIM `APT PUPIL' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the past decade, critics have been predicting England's
great Shakespearan actor, Sir Ian McKellen, would eventually escape
his classical typecasting to emerge as one of the movies' top
character leads. This year, the 60-year-old actor may finally be
doing just that.
</P>
<P>
   In November, he stars as horror film director James Whale in
``Gods and Monsters,'' a film that has so impressed pre-release
audiences that Variety has already predicted he will be a likely
Oscar nominee.
</P>
<P>
   He's also the top-billed actor of this weekend's ``Apt Pupil,''
an adaptation of a Stephen King novella directed by Bryan Singer
(``The Usual Suspects''). It's a grim, off-putting affair filled
with Holocaust imagery, but McKellen is undeniably riveting in it.
</P>
<P>
   It's the story of a morbid, Nazi-obsessed high school senior
(Brad Renfro) who _ rather improbably _ recognizes and conclusively
identifies his elderly German-born neighbor (McKellen) as Kurt
Dussander, an infamous Nazi war criminal long on the run.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of turning in the Nazi, the boy more or less blackmails
him, makes him relate all the horrific details of genocide, dress
up as an SS officer and storm around his living room, and otherwise
act as the puppet on his string.
</P>
<P>
   But the crafty fugitive soon turns the tables on the boy, makes
him understand that _ by not turning him in to the authorities _ he
has become his accomplice. The rest of the film chronicles a
cat-and-mouse game that develops between the old Nazi and his apt
pupil.
</P>
<P>
   The point that King and Singer make with not much subtlety is
that our world is full of potential Nazis. And the one thing you
can say about the film is that it definitely has the courage of its
convictions, and doesn't soften its blow with a cop-out ending.
</P>
<P>
   As the Nazi, McKellen _ playing a character considerably older
than he actually is _ gives a shrewd, often mesmerizing performance
of a man who is half Jean Valjean, half hideous monster who just
can't keep himself from such casual evil acts as throwing a
neighbor's cat in his oven, or murdering a passing homeless man.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Renfro is also effective as his adversary and budding
mirror image, though his character might have been more effective
if he had been written or played with a bit more sympathy and
charm. As it is, its hard to stay emotionally connected to a movie
populated with two such bleak, sociopathic characters.
</P>
<P>
   All told, the film makes a less than completely successful
follow-up to Singer's 1995 Indie smash, ``The Usual Suspects.''
Unlike that auspicious debut, ``Apt Pupil'' is more unpleasant than
thought-provoking, more repulsive than suspenseful or thrilling,
and utterly predictable _ a far cry from its predecessor's
irresistible puzzle structure.
</P>
<P>
   Apt Pupil. Directed by Bryan Singer. Screenplay by Brandon
Boyce. Cast: Ian McKellen, Brad Renfro, Bruce Davison, David
Schwimmer. Sony Pictures. 111 minutes. Rated R for scenes of strong
violence, language and brief sexuality.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-98 1431EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
