<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1490 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-PLEASANTVILLE-SP     10-22 0785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PLEASANTVILLE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`PLEASANTIVE' IS TOO MUCH LIKE TRUMAN SHOW, BUT NOT AS GOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The biggest drawback of Gary Ross' trapped-in-an-inane-TV-show
movie, ``Pleasantville,'' is that it has basically the same premise
and theme as ``The Truman Show,'' and it's not half as good. It's
visually interesting, but incredibly flimsy.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Truman,'' director Peter Weir took a one-beat ``Twilight
Zone'' situation, expanded it to feature length and somehow came up
with the year's most strikingly original film: an examination of
man's place in the cosmos that was, at once, witty, moving and
profound.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Pleasantville,'' first-time director Ross (the co-writer of
``Big'' and ``Dave'') takes a similar situation _ two teenagers
trapped in a mindless '50s sit-com _ and unimaginatively exploits
it. It plays like a poor-man's blend of ``The Purple Rose of
Cairo'' and ``Back to the Future.''
</P>
<P>
   The prisoners are David (Toby Maguire) and Jennifer (Reese
Witherspoon), teenage brother-and-sister of a typically
dysfunctional '90s family. He's a terminally shy boy who retreats
into reruns of an insipid '50s TV show called ``Pleasantville'';
she's conniving and promiscuous.
</P>
<P>
   One evening, a mysterious TV repair man (Don Knotts) zaps them
into the alternate universe of the TV show: a black-and-white world
of utopian perfection, without sex, bodily functions or social
strife, where it's impossible to throw a basketball without scoring
a basket.
</P>
<P>
   The script chronicles the impact the two '90s teens have on this
phony world, which comes unglued and even begins to turn to color
as Jennifer spreads her gospel of the joy of sex and David
gradually inspires a '60s-like counterculture revolution.
</P>
<P>
   By far the best thing about the film is its frequent
juxtaposition of color and black-and-white images that fill the
screen as the drab world of Pleasantville gradually comes to life.
Though its been done plenty of times before, its never quite been
tried on such a grand scale.
</P>
<P>
   But it's hardly motivation enough to sit through this
surprisingly uninvolving and humorless comedy, which takes place in
a dimension that Ross's paper-thin script can give no rules or
consistency or sense _ even by the loose standards of a fantasy.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike ``Truman,'' ``Pleasantville'' is filled with annoying and
one-note performances _ Witherspoon is particularly hard on the
nerves. It's also often shockingly tasteless, as when the slutty
teenager teaches her TV mom (Joan Allen) how to masturbate.
</P>
<P>
   It also fails because it simply doesn't make its case _ that
destroying Pleasantville is a worthwhile endeavor. It may be that
the world of the late '90s _ which Ross depicts in his prologue as
a maelstrom of AIDS, angst, famine, overpopulation, broken families
and economic hopelessness _ is preferable to Mayberry R.F.D. But
this movie sure doesn't convince us.
</P>
<P>
   And ``Pleasantville'' fails on an even more profound level. It's
built on a completely false assumption: that '50s-'60s TV shows
were empty-headed lies. If Ross ever spent any time in TV-Land he'd
know that even the more insipid situation comedies of that era _
``Ozzie and Harriet,'' ``Father Knows Best'' _ were loaded with
subtle truths.
</P>
<P>
   Black-and-white TV of the '50s is beloved today not because it
was so false but because it managed to be so truthful within the
context of stylized innocence. Has there ever been, really, a
darker portrait of selfishness and frustration than Lucy Ricardo?
Think of Ernie Bilko, Ralph Kramden or (speaking of Don Knotts) the
tragically self-deluded Barney Fife?
</P>
<P>
   Sexless? Was there ever a more more sex-obsessed teenager in all
of literature than Dobie Gillis? Or a more bitter embodiment of
matronly sexual frustration as ``Our Miss Brooks?'' The audience of
the '90s loves ``Leave It to Beaver'' not because it's mindless pap
but because it so magically catches the vulnerability of childhood
and the hypocrisy of the adult world.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if you read down the list of TV family situation
comedies for the years 1955-63 _ ``My Three Sons, ``The Andy
Griffith Show,'' etc. _ you'll find that none of them is anything
like ``Pleasantville.'' Indeed, they were considerably more
thought-out and better written than Ross' shallow, backhanded
homage to our kinder, gentler cultural past.
</P>
<P>
   Pleasantville. Directed, produced and written by Gary Ross.
Cast: Tobey Maguire, Reese Witherspoon, Jeff Daniels, Joan Allen,
William H. Macy, J.T. Walsh, Don Knotts. New Line Cinema. 122
minutes. Rated PG-13 for numerous sexual references and language.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-98 1432EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981022.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 14:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1491 &Cx1f; tth-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-HAPPINESS-SPI &LR;      10-22 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-HAPPINESS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ULTRA-DARK `HAPPINESS' MANAGES COMPASSION FOR WAYWARD CHARACTERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It may seem illogical, but ``Happiness,'' an ultra dark
``comedy'' from Todd Solondz (his equally relentless first film was
``Welcome to the Dollhouse''), is oddly sympathetic in its
perversity.
</P>
<P>
   Even though it features a pedophile as a primary character, the
film manages to eke out some sense of compassion for its wayward,
lost souls. In this modern day, opines Solondz, the quest for
happiness leads to loneliness, alienation, isolation ... and
extreme behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Whether in the city or its suburbs, happiness is a rarity.
Solondz focuses on three sisters who lead very different lives. Joy
Jordan (Jane Adams) is a do-gooder who wants to make her mark in
the world by helping the poor and huddled masses. She still lives
in her parents' house in New Jersey. But mom and dad (Louise Lasser
and Ben Gazzara) are having their own woes. After 40 years
together, dad wants a divorce so he can be alone and mom is looking
for love in a vial of pills and bottle of scotch.
</P>
<P>
   Joy's two sisters, the glamorous poet Helen (Lara Flynn Boyle)
and pert and perky housewife Trish (Cynthia Stevenson), gloat that
they have it all. But do they?
</P>
<P>
   Helen is relegated to empty one-night stands to prime the pump
to write. She even agrees to meet an obscene phone caller who turns
out to be her lonely neighbor Allen (Philip Seymour Hoffman). Allen
is in therapy for his obsession and is being pursued by his own sad
suitor, Kristina (Camryn Manheim), who may not be as innocent as
she seems. Ironically, his therapist is Trish's husband, Bill
(Dylan Baker), an outwardly respected, stable father and husband
who secretly yearns sexually for his son's schoolboy friends.
</P>
<P>
   This menagerie of characters crosses paths in a myriad of ways _
all in search of happiness.
</P>
<P>
   Solondz has a gift for interweaving his people's lives and the
film flows seamlessly. It's a cross-sectional urban myth where the
perception versus reality of what they have and what they believe
they should have blurs and creates even more misery.
</P>
<P>
   Therapy, valium, scotch, pornography, power ... these are the
instant remedies for all the aches and emptiness. And that's the
subtlety of this comedy, which walks a fine line between morality
and despair, attraction and repulsion. Solondz manages to horrify
us, make us laugh, yet still feel empathetic. There's a real agony
at the marrow of the film and it fulfills the old maxim that
tragedy and comedy are closely related. Most of the credit must go
to Solondz for not shying away from the distastefulness of human
folly or easing the path for any of his characters in the end.
</P>
<P>
   He manages to make a cogent statement about that elusive thing
called happiness, though the formula isn't neat or tidy. He's of
the mindset that is best summed up in one of Joy's mawkish folk
songs, ``Happiness, where are you? I've looked so long for you.
Happiness, what are you? I haven't got a clue.''
</P>
<P>
   Happiness. Directed and written by Todd Solondz. Cast: Jane
Adams, Dylan Baker, Lara Flynn Boyle, Philip Seymour Hoffman,
Camryn Manheim, Cynthia Stevenson. Good Machine Releasing. 135
minutes. Rated R for sexual content, language, abuse of children.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
