<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-ORGAZMO-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`ORGAZMO' BRINGS BAD TASTE TO NEW LEVELS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By PAULA NECHAK  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Trey Parker didn't exactly hit a home run with his last movie,
``BASEketball.'' If anything, he seemed to slide by on the huge
success of his animated TV series ``South Park,'' which is known
for its crude comedy and offensive humor.
</P>
<P>
   It's a relief, then, to report Parker learned a lesson or two
from that shaky outing and has made a more satisfying second movie
_ although he earned an NC-17 rating in the process and reportedly
had a few scenes edited out due to content.
</P>
<P>
   However, the film's outrageous and irreverent premise never
makes good on its potential, even though the laughs are fairly
constant and a preview audience appeared to have a good time,
guffawing heartily at the silliness of it all.
</P>
<P>
   Still, ``Orgazmo'' isn't for everyone. It takes bad taste a step
further than ``There's Something About Mary.'' It's a not so subtle
skewering of the Mormon religion, which it purports to disembowel
with zeal and glee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a superhero, I'm a Latter-day Saint,'' says Joe Young
(Parker), who's been sent to Los Angeles to do his ``recruiting for
Jesus'' mission work. In L.A., the mighty Joe stumbles into the
porno industry after he rings the doorbell of Maxxx Orbison
(Michael Dean Jacobs), king of the ``adult film'' world, who just
happens to be looking for a convert of his own to play Captain
Orgazmo in his latest sex-capade.
</P>
<P>
   Joe dukes it out with Maxxx's thuggish bodyguards, proving
himself an able martial arts Mormon. Maxxx hires Joe, who
reluctantly agrees to swing into action but refuses to go all the
way on camera because he's going to marry his virginal ``cupcake''
back in Utah. Fiancee Lisa (Robyn Lynne Raab) whispers to Joe,
``Jesus and I love you,'' when she signs off from nightly phone
talks and she desperately wants to be wed in the Mormon temple.
</P>
<P>
   Soon Joe is rolling about in front of the camera in order to
earn enough money to make Lisa happy. He cavorts with big-breasted
babes and zaps villains with his orgazmorator, a gun that
incapacitates criminals with an orgasm. With the help of his
sidekick, Choda-Boy (Dian Bachar), who uses sex toys as weapons,
the pair soon become the hottest thing in the industry. But Joe is
caught in a moral dilemma when he's pushed into a dark, underworld
plot. Before long, life imitates art and Joe and Choda-Boy take
their prowess to the streets in order to clean up the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``Orgazmo'' spoofs ``Boogie Nights'' with a vengeance but
doesn't take that aspect far enough. The idea of a Mormon stumbling
into porno is original but much of Parker's film falls flat because
his reach exceeds his grasp. It's never clear if he's making a
satire on religion or a crime caper that never takes off. It feels
like he got cold feet half way through and tried to pull back.
</P>
<P>
   By straddling the fence, he turned the film from what could have
been edgy satire into silly inanity.
</P>
<P>
   Orgazmo. Directed and written by Trey Parker. Cast: Parker, Dian
Bachar, Robyn Lynne Raab, Matt Stone, Michael Dean Jacobs. October
Films. 95 minutes. Rated NC-17 for nudity, language, sexual
content.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C+
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
