<SLUG> BC-FOLM-SOLDIER-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KURT RUSSELL MAKES A FINE `SOLDIER' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kurt Russell's new sci-fi action movie, ``Soldier,'' is nothing
to write home about, but it's a bit better than the chest-pounding,
G.I. Space-Joe epic promised by its publicity _ and better than the
dismal track record of its director Paul Anderson (``Event
Horizon'') might indicate.
</P>
<P>
   Russell plays Todd, a New Millennium mercenary, picked shortly
after his birth (1996) by nefarious government forces and brutally
trained and psychologically programmed to be a highly disciplined,
unfeeling, lean, mean fighting machine.
</P>
<P>
   At age 40 and after many galactic battles, however, Todd and his
colleagues find themselves replaced by a new generation of test
tube mercenaries who have been genetically engineered to be
stronger, and even more disciplined and unfeeling.
</P>
<P>
   After losing a gladiatorial bout with one of these new kids
(Jason Scott Lee), Todd finds himself dumped on a remote
garbage-dump planet and left for dead. But he's nursed back to
fighting trim by an ideal little community of space pioneers
stranded there years before.
</P>
<P>
   When the New Generation of mercenaries and their corrupt leader
(Jason Isaacs) land on the planet and decide to ruthlessly use
Todd's new friends for target practice, he defends them and
``Soldier'' turns into a ``Rambo''-like combat movie.
</P>
<P>
   It definitely has its weaknesses. It's too brutal for mainstream
tastes, its villain is too melodramatically evil to be taken
seriously, and British director Anderson _ who also directed
``Mortal Kombat'' _ just doesn't have the sensibility to raise the
proceedings out of the video-game movie genre.
</P>
<P>
   But it always looks terrific, employing the talents of an A-list
team that includes Oscar-winning visual effects supervisor Ed Jones
(``Who Framed Roger Rabbit?'', production designer David L. Snyder
(``Blade Runner'') and cameraman David Tattersall, who also
photographed the new ``Star Wars'' movie.
</P>
<P>
   The script, by David Webb Peoples (who co-wrote ``Blade Runner''
and won an Oscar for writing Clint Eastwood's ``Unforgiven''), is
also dramatic, character-driven and clever in the way it works in
mythic elements of ``Shane,'' ``Spartacus'' and even ``Beauty and
the Beast.''
</P>
<P>
   And star Russell, who has publicly stated that this will be his
action-movie swan song (too much wear-and-tear on his aging body),
could hardly be more effective. He plays his character without a
hint of tongue-in-cheek, and his transition to human being is
remarkably subtle and completely believable.
</P>
<P>
   Soldier. Directed by Paul Anderson. Written by David Webb
Peoples. Cast: Kurt Russell, Jason Scott Lee, Connie Nielsen, Gary
Busey. Warner Bros. 95 minutes. Rated R for violence.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
