<HEADER>
A1496 &Cx1f; tic-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HERBS-HEALTH-AZR &LR;      10-22 1497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBS-HEALTH-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HERB APPEAL: MEDICINAL PLANTS' POPULARITY GROWING  
 (ADV: SIDEBAR MATERIAL AT END. WITH HERBS-FOOD-ART) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS ROPP  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Doctors still grimace at the mention of them.
</P>
<P>
   However, for the ever-increasing number of people who are
disillusioned with synthetic medicines and their often-harsh side
effects, herbal remedies have become more mainstream as the 20th
century comes to a close.
</P>
<P>
   What's happening in Montana is a prime indication of how
attitudes are changing about herbal medicines. Federal and state
land managers have been stunned over the number of plant hunters or
``diggers'' scouring the countryside in search of the most coveted
medicinal herb in the world right now, echinacea, the purple
coneflower.
</P>
<P>
   The echinacea root, traditionally used by Native Americans to
fight colds and the flu, is more recently believed to bolster the
body's immune system. Public-land managers say tens of thousands of
the plants have been ripped out of the ground illegally in Montana
and sold to pharmaceutical firms for $20 a pound. Botanists warn
that similar plunderings elsewhere across the Northern Plains have
placed echinacea and other slowly growing medicinal herbs at risk
of being wiped out in a few years.
</P>
<P>
   Land managers and botanists are nonplused, but herbalists say
they saw it coming.
</P>
<P>
   Phyllis Hogan, ethnobotanist and owner of Winter Sun Trading Co.
in Flagstaff, Ariz., is not surprised over the mad grab for
medicinal herbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Interest has been phenomenal the past few years,'' Hogan said.
``When I started my business in 1976, almost all my clients were
Native Americans or Mexican-Americans. Now, 80 percent of my
customers are Anglos.''
</P>
<P>
   Hogan believes people have turned to plants because there are
``many different components'' to medicinal herbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taken in their natural state you're getting minerals,
vitamins, alkaloids and nutrients,'' Hogan said. ``With synthetic
remedies, you're getting one main alkaloid, and that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mesa, Ariz., herbalist Mica Steele also has noted the frenetic
interest in herbal medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they've ever been more popular since the advent
of synthetic medicines,'' Steele said.
</P>
<P>
   She believes much of the herbal appeal is the way our bodies
process medicinal herbs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because they're natural, they're gentler on your system,''
Steele said. ``There aren't the side effects you sometimes
experience with synthetic medicines.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the modern medical community, which has viewed herbal
remedies as a kind of gypsy, unproven alternative medicine, is
taking a serious look at the power of medicinal plants.
</P>
<P>
   A survey last year of 128 medical schools found that 43 require
students to take courses in alternative medicine and an additional
43 offer such courses as electives, according to the Association of
American Medical Colleges. Also, medical schools are offering
alternative medicine residency programs _ post-medical school
training programs, according to Columbia University's Rosenthal
Center for Complementary and Alternative Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the University of Arizona in Tucson launched its
Fellowship Program in Integrative Medicine, an innovative two-year
project that examines ways to combine modern and alternative
medical techniques, including herbal medicines.
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Dr. Andrew Weil, a bestselling author and widely
recognized leader of the integrative movement in medicine, four
physicians have been participating fellows.
</P>
<P>
   One is Dr. Roberta Lee, who is a family practitioner and
third-generation Chinese-American who became involved in the
program to learn more about the herbs her grandfather used that
were supposed to hold wondrous healing properties.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy that there are natural remedies, but I'm an
open-minded skeptic,'' Lee said. ``Just because something looks
promising doesn't mean it will really work when you come to the
science of it.''
</P>
<P>
   The medical profession examines medicinal herbs on an individual
basis over a significant amount of time before rendering an
opinion, Lee said. Two herbs that do get a thumbs up from empirical
scientists are echinacea and Saint Johnswort, which is used to
treat depression.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are well-documented,'' Lee said. ``Another one I'm
looking at right now is kava.''
</P>
<P>
   The kava root contains collective active ingredients called kava
lactones, which are purported to help with anxiety and insomnia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, it appears kava is better tolerated than medicines
I use in my practice today, like Valium, that sometimes have side
effects,'' Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   But Hogan said even herbs that have a proven track record are
more or less useless if not taken in the correct form. Fresh herbs,
she said, either consumed directly or brewed in a tea, have the
greatest benefits.
</P>
<P>
   ``People tell me all the time that they're taking herbs, but
they're not helping them,'' Hogan said. ``I then find out they're
taking encapsulated pills. Once it's ground into a powder and put
in a capsule, who knows how long it's been lying around? We don't
sell these inert forms, which are also like synthetic medicines, as
far I'm concerned.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Hogan believes some pill forms are better than others.
She said freshly picked herbs that are freeze-dried before
encapsulating ``provide some benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   Steele agrees fresh herbs are best but understands why people
turn to pill form, especially when it's difficult to pick the herbs
yourself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, modern people don't like the tastes of herbal teas like
chaparral, that tastes pretty nasty,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan believes it's better to just deal with the foul tastes
rather than buy processed pills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bitter tonics are something most people in this country
need,'' Hogan said. ``And once you get used to it, you crave it
like you would a grapefruit.''
</P>
<P>
   If you don't have the time or inclination to prepare your own
herbal remedies, Hogan suggests buying herbal tinctures, which are
very strong liquid concentrations of the herb, that require only a
few drops in a cup of hot water.
</P>
<P>
   Hogan said tinctures are more expensive ($7 to $14 an ounce,
compared with $2 to $4 an ounce for fresh herbs), but they last
longer and have an immediate effect.
</P>
<P>
   Both medical experts and herbalists agree it's a mistake to
believe medicinal herbs alone are a panacea for good health. In
fact, Hogan goes so far as to say that herbal remedies are not for
everyone.
</P>
<P>
   Scottsdale, Ariz., allergist Michael Manning said he sees his
share of patients who are allergic to certain medicinal herbs.
</P>
<P>
   Lee said mixing herbs with modern medicines also can cause
problems. Additionally, Lee said, liver toxicity has been detected
in some people after ingesting herbs such as chaparral. Chaparral,
also known as medicine chest plant because of its purported use by
Native Americans to cure a wide range of maladies, has been touted
as a cancer fighter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Also, you have to keep in mind that herbals generally have a
lower concentration of active ingredients,'' Lee said, ``so they
take a longer time to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Hogan said you shouldn't expect a magic bullet from herbal
medicines. ``What we recommend is that people use nutrition and
herbs in a daily routine to prevent long-term degenerative
illness.''  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
POPULAR MEDICINAL HERBS &QL; 
 &QL; 
Echinacea &QL; 
Part used: root, leaves. &QL; 
Systems affected: lungs, stomach, liver.  &QL; 
Used for: inflammatory conditions, arthritic diseases, colds,
immune system. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Saint Johnswort &QL; 
Part used: entire plant.  &QL; 
Systems affected: liver, nervous system. &QL; 
Used for: depression, neuralgia, nerve pains. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Saw palmetto &QL; 
 &QL; 
Part used: fruit. &QL; 
Systems affected: kidney, spleen, liver. &QL; 
Used for: prostate, impotence, frigidity, underweight conditions,
urinary-tract infections. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Valerian &QL; 
 &QL; 
Part used: rhizome. &QL; 
Systems affected: liver, heart, nervous system. &QL; 
Used for: insomnia, stress and nervousness, menstrual cramps, pain
relief.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
Motherwort  &QL; 
Part used: leaves. &QL; 
Systems affected: pericardium, liver. &QL; 
Used for: suppressed menstruation, blood circulation, heart
problems and arteriosclerosis, nervousness and insomnia. &QL; 
 &QL; 
