<HEADER>
A1515 &Cx1f; tic-z
r d &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HERBS-FOOD-ART-AZR &LR;      10-22 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HERBS-FOOD-ART-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRESH OR DRIED, HERBS ADD ZEST  
 (ART ADV: PHOTO HAS BEEN SEND TO NYTNS CLIENTS)  
 (ADV: WITH HERBS-HEALTH) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY WALKER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Forty years ago, Anne Fischer was served herb butter
on her bread in a restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `My goodness, what is that stuff, and how do I find
out about it?' '' Fischer said.
</P>
<P>
   She went to the library and checked out a book.
</P>
<P>
   A few decades and a lot of herbs later, Fischer is the author of
the Arizona Herb Association's ``The Low Desert Herb Gardening
Handbook,'' which focuses on planting, growing and harvesting herbs
in Arizona. She has learned a lot about cooking with herbs along
the way.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh herbs, everybody agrees, are one of the hottest culinary
trends around. And here's the real secret: You can use lots of
fresh herbs, even if you don't cook. &UR; Herbs are easy.
</P>
<P>
   You live on salads? Specialize in scrambled eggs for dinner?
Fresh herbs give each dish a different dimension.
</P>
<P>
   If you grow your own herbs, pick a couple of leaves or sprigs
from each plant until you have a little handful. Wash them, then
dry in a paper towel. Chop the herbs and sprinkle them on the salad
or into the eggs just before they're done.
</P>
<P>
   If you can make an omelet, sprinkle this little mixture on the
inside with a bit of cheese just before you fold it. Voila! If you
didn't use Velveeta, you have just made genuine gourmet food. Your
``omelette aux herbes'' can be ``la specialite de la maison.''
</P>
<P>
   Reading between the lines here?
</P>
<P>
   Fresh herbs are the ultimate in ease of cooking. You can use
them to jazz up commercial spaghetti sauce or bottled salad
dressing. Fresh herbs add flavor without fat or sodium. All you
need to know are a few tricks.
</P>
<P>
   First, most fresh herbs should be added to dishes just before
they're served. This is the opposite of dried herbs, which need
longer cooking to give off flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Add fresh chopped cilantro to salsa or sprinkle it on a cheese
crisp just before you serve it. Sprinkle chopped parsley or chives
over soup after you put it in bowls.
</P>
<P>
   The exception to the add-it-fresh rule: the handful of parsley
long-simmered in broth or stock. It's strained out with the other
flavoring vegetables. If you add fresh herbs at the beginning of
cooking a dish, you might want to add more at the end to make it
taste fresher.
</P>
<P>
   Another rule to remember is the substitutions formula: Fresh
herbs can be substituted for dried in almost any recipe. Use three
times as much of the fresh herb. If the recipe calls for 1 teaspoon
dried oregano, use 3 teaspoons (or 1 tablespoon) of fresh chopped
oregano.
</P>
<P>
   Heat activates the essential oils in fresh herbs, Fischer
explained. To make teas with fresh herbs, cover them while steeping
to keep essential oils in the container. If you can smell it, the
oils are escaping, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Fischer makes lemongrass tea with fresh ginger almost every day,
using an 18-inch cutting of lemongrass, washed and wrapped and tied
up to fit in a container, along with five slivers of ginger. Pour
boiling water over and let steep 5 to 10 minutes, covered.
</P>
<P>
   She also makes a sun-type tea from Mexican mint marigold just by
cutting a big panful, washing it, and putting it in a gallon jug
with water in the sun. She serves it with no sweetener to guests if
they like licorice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost everyone asks, `What is that?' '' Fischer said. ``It's
so good, so refreshing. It's not strong or overpowering.''
</P>
<P>
   She puts a bit of mint in the water she drinks, just to give it
a little flavor.
</P>
<P>
   Herb vinegars couldn't be easier. Store them in a cool, dry
place away from the sun and they will keep a long time. First, put
washed herbs in a bottle, then add vinegar, then steep in the sun
for two weeks, shaking it daily.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to make vinegar for a salad to use tonight, Fischer
said, pour heated vinegar over the herbs to draw out the essential
oils more quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sage is great with gnocchi,'' or Italian potato dumplings,
Fischer said. (Look for them in freezer cases.) During a cooking
demonstration at a meeting of the Arizona Herb Association, a quick
sauce was made with butter in which two or three leaves of sage
were fried, then poured over cooked gnocchi, which then was
sprinkled with Parmesan.
</P>
<P>
   Nasturtiums, the flowers as well as the leaves, are good in
salads. Or use the whole leaves of herbs in green salads, an
especially good trick if you have unusual-color herbs, such as
purple basil.
</P>
<P>
   Fischer makes low-fat or no-fat dip by blending chopped fresh
herbs with yogurt. To make the yogurt more cheeselike, drain it
overnight in a strainer lined with cheesecloth. For a cup of
yogurt, Fischer recommends adding two cloves of chopped garlic,
maybe a tablespoon of two different herbs you like, plus maybe a
little cayenne pepper. Chives and onions or parsley and oregano
would be good. It's your choice. Serve the yogurt cheese on bread
or crackers.
</P>
<P>
   As for that softened butter that turned Fischer into an
``herbophile,'' she tries to make it early in the day so the
flavors will meld for a dinner party. Merely soften butter at room
temperature and mix in chopped herbs, preferably a couple of hours
before planning to serve.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then again, if it's 10 minutes before 6 and you're doing this,
it's still wonderful,'' Fischer said.
</P>
<P>
   She makes it in a dish that has a lid so that if she has any
left over, she can put it back in the fridge and use it within a
week. It's great with eggs, meat, fish, chicken or on a savory
toast.
</P>
<P>
   You can treat fresh herbs like flowers to keep them longer. Put
the stems in a glass of water, cover loosely with a breathable
produce bag, and stick in the fridge. Or roll washed herbs lightly
in a paper towel, insert the towel in a produce bag, and don't
close tightly. Keep it in the produce bin for several days.
</P>
<P>
   What to do with extra fresh herbs? It's easy to dry them, even
if you don't own a dehydrator. You can tie them up in bunches and
just let them hang. Or dry them in a very low oven, at about 200
degrees, spreading the herbs around on a jellyroll sheet so each
piece can dry. Or just air-dry them on a tray in an airy, light
place, Fischer said.
</P>
<P>
   Herbs are easy. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
