<HEADER>
A1534 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-APTPUPIL-TEX     10-22 0654
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-APTPUPIL-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STUDIED SERIOUSNESS WEIGHS DOWN `PUPIL'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The first time I encountered an excited young dude shouting
``I'm the King of the World'' wasn't in ``Titanic,'' but in Stephen
King's novella, ``Apt Pupil.'' So far, ``Different Seasons,'' four
collected stories by King, has been fertile ground for movies.
``The Shawshank Redemption'' and ``Stand By Me'' both grew out of
``Seasons.'' Each of them benefits from a lack of psychological
examination; King races along, allowing the moviemakers room to add
their own level of emotion (profound in ``Shawshank,'' sentimental
and winning in ``Stand By Me'').
</P>
<P>
   ``Apt Pupil'' director Bryan Singer looked to be the perfect
director for ``Pupil.'' Singer's previous film, ``The Usual
Suspects,'' with its focus on details that turn out to be
meaningless and its cynical ease, has the feel of one of the
stories from ``Seasons.'' The ``Suspects'' movie and the ``Pupil''
novella have the benign flintiness of a parlor trick, the kind of
material that has you asking yourself, in an appreciative manner,
``Wow _ how did I let myself get taken in by this?'' Such mastery
of a shallow craft is wonderful to behold.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Singer and his adapter take ``Apt Pupil'' much
too seriously. King's dissertation on the inevitability of evil has
a swift, ironic tone. The novella's a shaggy-dog story that flirts
with pretensions about a suburban princeling whose interest in
Nazism leads him to the crotchety old man around the corner _ who
turns out to be an escaped Nazi. It's King's turn on an urban
legend; didn't we all whisper that the mean old goat in the
tattered bathrobe was a Nazi/witch? And the kid who busts the Nazi
and picks up on all of the old man's secrets on the sly, all the
while becoming infected by them, was a bright-eyed, freckled-faced
cliche out of a Norman Rockwell painting.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Renfro matches up physically to that archetype. But he's
gulping and sweaty the first time he steps in front of the camera.
He's never allowed a moment of giddy triumph before his opening of
Pandora's box adds the weight of the world to his shoulders; he
already shoulders this burden. The movie ``Apt Pupil'' has a
heaviness of spirit that almost has to come about when the subject
of Nazis is brought to a movie. It can't exult in cheap cynicism
the way King could. The movie works best for Renfro when the
oppressiveness of the old man's evil suffuses his every waking
moment; Renfro looks appropriately haunted.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Ian McKellen gets to walk away with the
picture. His mouth is turned into a perpetual sour twist, as if
he's trying to work that one stubborn sesame seed out from between
his teeth. Because he doesn't have to have a conscience, he
dominates with a showy, cranky turn. He gets to enjoy the
performance, especially after he begins to peel away the civility
he has had to wear.
</P>
<P>
   As ``Apt Pupil'' plays out to its unsatisfying end, McKellen
works the picture like a lounge pianist who has been waiting all
his life for the right crowd to show up. Yeah, sure, they don't
have any taste, but he's gonna give them the best show they've ever
seen. Like King, he knows how to deliver a good time to the rubes.
Sadly, Singer doesn't _ not this time, anyway. It's as if, once he
got knee-deep in the material, he was stuck because he couldn't
play up the humor without making it look as if he condoned the
horrors that Nazism represents.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Apt Pupil''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Bryan Singer
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Brad Renfro, Ian McKellen
</P>
<P>
   Length: 100 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ violence, adult language and adult situations, and
nudity
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
