<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 14:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1537 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-PLEASANTVILLE-TE     10-22 0996
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-PLEASANTVILLE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A NICE PLACE TO VISIT: LET'S TAKE A TRIP TO '50S TV. NOW LET'S ADD
COLOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Pleasantville'' is ... not unpleasant. It starts with a
likable sendup of a Nick at Nite-style cable channel _ TV Time _
that traffics in the relentlessly cheerful irony that makes almost
everything in pop culture feel meaningless because the folks
selling it have to pretend they're smarter than their subject
matter. (And it's easy to make fun of 1950s television, which even
the TV Time actors _ if you want to call them that _ don't seem to
take very seriously.)
</P>
<P>
   The movie gets lost when its writer-director Gary Ross (''Big,''
``Dave'') steps outside of that purview and adds (or tries to add)
real-life weight. Still, he's working at making a liberal fantasy
with some feeling and a heart. That kind of ambition is hard to
find in a movie these days, and my hat goes off to him for the
effort.
</P>
<P>
   Shy, croaky-voiced David (Tobey Maguire) is obsessed with the
syrupy banality of the TV Time '50s series ``Pleasantville,'' which
transports him to a fantasy world where he's far more comfortable.
It's a lot easier to deal with this than his miserable high school
life or coming home to hear his divorced mother (Jane Kaczmarek,
underused, as usual) arguing with his deadbeat dad.
</P>
<P>
   David's twin sister, Jennifer (Reese Witherspoon), is nothing
like him. She's a cool charmer who is obviously using sex as a
substitute for a closeness she's not getting at home. So when David
and Jennifer are sucked into their TV and into the black-and-white
world of Pleasantville via a remote control that a mysterious TV
repairman (Don Knotts) gives them, it's a dream come true for him
and a nightmare for her.
</P>
<P>
   There are elements of ``The Wizard of Oz'' and ``It's a
Wonderful Life'' in the town of Pleasantville, as well as a
make-me-the-center-of-the-universe facet that's reminiscent of
``The Truman Show.'' David is in love with its placid surfaces.
Jennifer digs desperately under the shiny, comfy surfaces only to
find ... more surfaces. They've replaced the happy-go-lucky Bud and
Mary Sue, the teen-agers of the Pleasantville series, and their new
mom (Joan Allen) and dad (William H. Macy) treat them with respect,
confident that their kids will never let them down. So when
Jennifer introduces sex to Pleasantville, pockets of colors _
representing real fulfillment _ begin to erupt all over town.
</P>
<P>
   And when David brings knowledge and curiosity to the town,
something more than color breaks out. Fear over a
no-longer-predictable universe spills into the streets, and the
mayor (the late J.T. Walsh) is unnerved by the disruptions.
</P>
<P>
   What writer-director Ross is out to do is to create a parable
about fascism. He has an abiding interest in innocence, as his
movies ``Dave'' and ``Big'' have shown, as well as a Capra-esque
sensibility in believing that what's right is right. The most
fascinating irony to be found is that Ross' worldview is not much
more complex than Pleasantville's. He's out to bring
three-dimensionality to a world and he barely seems to have two
dimensions himself; there's an intriguing pot-calling-the-kettle
black aspect to ``Pleasantville.'' Jennifer puts aside her
self-proclaimed slutty behavior and turns to books, and she becomes
a real _ in color _ human being; the obvious irony is that the town
Pleasantville, with its structure, is actually good for her.
</P>
<P>
   David learns to stand up for himself, although ``Pleasantville''
misses a point by giving him color a beat too early _ it should
happen when he confronts bullies over his mother's honor. The
patness of Ross' fairy tale is underscored by scenes such as these:
at one point, David enters the soda shop where the shy Mr. Johnson
(Jeff Daniels) works after experience has brought literal color to
the kids' black-and-white cheeks, and the Dave Brubeck Quartet's
``Take Five'' is playing, which is just the kind of generic jazz
you might have heard on some '50s show like ``Father Knows Best''
or ``The Donna Reed Show.'' (For slight redemption, Ross later uses
Miles Davis' ``So What).''
</P>
<P>
   The movie even tries to play on the racism of '50s shows by
creating prejudice over the ``coloreds'' _ that is, black-and-white
characters who gain color. But when Etta James' sexy ``At Last''
comes up on the soundtrack, we wonder how there can be music by ...
well, by someone of color if there's no such person in the city.
And Pleasantville is a little too clean; nobody even smokes there,
which I think even the dogs did on '50s TV. (You may also wonder
what happened to the original Bud and Mary Sue. Are they sitting at
David and Jennifer's, horrified by ``Seinfeld'' reruns?)
</P>
<P>
   There's an amazing level of technical accomplishment to
``Pleasantville,'' as we watch its black-and-white and color
characters co-exist in the same frame. But it's not as exciting as
seeing a director's imagination freed up. Joan Allen, with her
delicate, long neck, brings a resonance that all the technical
excellence of this movie cannot hope to match; she's like a swan
coming into her own. (Randy Newman's score, with its witty,
parodistic lushness, helps, too.)
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the problem is that movies can realize so much visually
nowadays that the storytelling pales by comparison. Under more
modest circumstances, ``Pleasantville'' would have been an almost
subversive idea for a big studio movie. But the overwhelming
capacity of the special effects makes its small idea seem even more
slight.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Pleasantville''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 2 1/2 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Gary Ross
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Tobey Maguire, Reese Witherspoon, Joan Allen
</P>
<P>
   Length: 122 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rating: PG-13 _ adult language and situations
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
