<HEADER>
A1539 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-SLAM-TEX     10-22 0677
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SLAM-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAVED BY POETRY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Director Marc Levin films the urban drama ``Slam'' with such a
casual cinema-verite voyeurism, it's as if he were using
surveillance cameras. He and his actors sometimes seem to have
wandered into the movie's Washington, D.C., locations and just
started filming while the residents went about their business. It's
representative of the movie, which tries to show the real world
while living in a dream one.
</P>
<P>
   At its center is Raymond Joshua (Saul Williams), a two-bit dope
dealer so resigned to his fate that he could be punching a time
clock as he peddles his wares. But Ray's laconic fatalism hides a
bitterness that comes out in his poetry, which spills from his lips
with such furor it's almost as if he were speaking in tongues.
</P>
<P>
   Ray's words can't keep him out of jail, but they do save his
life when he's inside _ this is probably the only cell-block movie
in which poetry rescues an inmate rather than turning him into
someone else's girlfriend. We know Ray is a benevolent criminal
because he deals in marijuana instead of something vicious like
crack (and if that isn't enough easing up for you, he's busted for
possessing only a quarter of a baggie). Lauren (Sonja Sohn), an
English teacher who falls under the spell of Ray's street-preacher
poetry, senses a goodness in him and offers him a ticket out of his
wayward life. But she lets him know that the ticket has a price.
</P>
<P>
   ``Slam'' is an audacious movie, but it's not entirely
successful. Written by and starring real-life slam poets _
including Williams, who, like Ray, has a low-key demeanor that
belies his onstage evangelical furor _ it's a movie about the power
of words that suffers when the words cease rhyming. It tries to
look the harshness of street life dead in the eye, but it blinks;
even though a couple of characters cite the odds against young
inner-city black males as if their dialogue were adapted from a
statistics report, the movie solves its characters' problems with
far too much ease.
</P>
<P>
   It almost seems like it's going to cop out on Ray, giving him an
easy way out, and it still gives us an ambiguous ending that we
could take as an easy out. Naturally, because of its writers, it
comes most alive when the poets are speaking their words _ there's
a mesmerizing scene in which Ray and a jail neighbor improvise a
song-poem that's a cry of pain.
</P>
<P>
   But audacious as it is, the movie is not as unique or original
as some will give it credit for; it merely sets the conventions of
musicals to a different beat.
</P>
<P>
   It benefits from its low budget, which Levin _ whose most recent
movie was 1993's ``The Last Party,'' which followed Robert Downey
Jr. to the 1992 political conventions _ handles with such aplomb,
you almost hope no one ever gives him the money to make something
more expensive. He loses his assurance a little in some of the
dialogue scenes, which he often lets go on too long, but he's
intriguing enough that you wish he'd work more often.
</P>
<P>
   ``Slam'' suffers from a poetic irony _ it's an audience picture
that will have trouble finding an audience, because of its
pocket-change look and its subject matter. It's no wonder that it
has played well at film festivals, where crowds are more likely to
break into applause _ after the poets here show their stuff, you
feel like you should react in some way that's more active than just
sitting in your seat.
</P>
<P>
   Many of its actors also appear in this year's excellent
documentary ``SlamNation,'' which would be a perfect companion
piece. These movies aren't easy to find, but they're worth seeking
out.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Slam''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Marc Levin
</P>
<P>
   Stars: Saul Williams, Sonja Sohn
</P>
<P>
   Length: 100 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Rated: R _ nudity, language, violence and sexual situations
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
