<DOCNO> NYT19981022.0201 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 14:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1541 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-FEINGOLD-BOS     10-22 1399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-FEINGOLD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SENATOR REJECTS SOFT MONEY AND FINDS HIMSELF IN TROUBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MITCHELL ZUCKOFF  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MADISON, Wis. _ Sen. Russell Feingold has been buffeted by
relentless attacks over space monkeys and cow flatulence, flag
burning and late-term abortions.
</P>
<P>
   That's what happens when you put yourself between a rock and a
soft place.
</P>
<P>
   As champion of an unsuccessful effort to overhaul
campaign-finance laws, the Wisconsin Democrat began his race for a
second term facing a dilemma: be branded a hypocrite by taking the
``soft money'' his legislation would have banned, or reject it and
help out his Republican opponent, Representative Mark Neumann.
</P>
<P>
   Feingold chose the latter, while Neumann's campaign has reaped
extensive soft-money support from the National Republican
Senatorial Committee, whose anti-Feingold ads on issues big and
small have recently saturated Wisconsin airwaves.
</P>
<P>
   The senator says it was an easy choice, notwithstanding the
risk. Recent polls suggest this is now an extremely close race
between two very different men with very different visions. But
whoever prevails, the result will surely be viewed as a statement
on how strongly voters feel about the ills of the campaign-finance
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Feingold wins, it proves it's possible to stand up against
these outside issue ads and survive,'' said Don Kettl, director of
the LaFolette Institute of Public Affairs at the University of
Wisconsin. ``If he loses, it proves the playing field is inevitably
not level when outside groups have the ability to bomb away.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The question everyone wants answered is, `Can you maintain
your principles in a real tough battleground, and win with one hand
tied behind your back?''' said Larry Mackinson, executive director
of the nonpartisan Center for Responsive Politics.
</P>
<P>
   Feingold, in fact, has done more than forswear soft money; he
has also moved to erase other advantages incumbents normally cling
to. He and Neumann agreed to limit contributions by political
action committees and non-Wisconsin residents. They also capped
spending at $3.8 million _ about a dollar for each state voter _ or
about half of what a race like this might otherwise cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be darned if I'm going to call up some CEO or some labor
leader to save my neck in a campaign,'' Feingold said last week of
fund-raising calls. ``I'd rather lose my job than play those games,
but I intend to win.''
</P>
<P>
   On the rare occasions anyone looks at this race as something
more than a referendum on campaign finance, the election offers a
compelling matchup of late-1990s political opposites, though with a
twist.
</P>
<P>
   Feingold, 45, is a Rhodes Scholar and Harvard Law School
graduate who nevertheless boasts that he is the Senate's poorest
member, with a net worth around $35,000. He votes with liberals on
most social, environmental and international issues, but has a
decidedly frugal bent on federal spending, particularly when it
comes to using Social Security funds.
</P>
<P>
   He is best known nationally for the campaign-finance legislation
he co-sponsored with Arizona Republican John McCain, and he
describes it as a window into his political philosophy. ``I have
devoted my career trying to prove the average citizen can still
participate in the political process at all levels, and that
includes the US Senate,'' he said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Feingold was elected in 1992 over Republican incumbent Robert W.
Kasten Jr. with help from clever ads (Elvis sightings and tours of
his closets to show they were skeleton-free) and painting three
promises on his garage door (a yearly visit to each of the state's
72 counties; a campaign financed mainly through in-state
contributions; keeping his primary residence in Wisconsin).
</P>
<P>
   Neumann, 44, is a high school teacher-turned-millionaire home
builder who is a member of the restive GOP House class of 1994. He
came to Congress by narrowly beating Democratic incumbent Peter
Barca in a rematch of a 1992 race won by Barca. Since then, Neumann
has nourished a reputation as a hard-nosed advocate for shrinking
the national debt _ he even opposes pork barrel projects in his own
district. In 1995, he wrote a federal budget that would have been
balanced by 1999, in part by cutting corporate welfare; it won 89
votes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think government is too big, takes too much of your money
and has too much control over your life,'' Neumann said.
</P>
<P>
   Neumann is a favorite of the Christian right, which embraces his
no-exceptions antiabortion stand; he pushed an unsuccessful 1997
recall effort against Feingold for voting against a ban on
``partial-birth'' abortions. He's also a darling of conservatives
who want to shrink the government, and Neumann courts veterans with
support for an anti-flag-burning amendment that Feingold opposes as
an assault on the Bill of Rights.
</P>
<P>
   Where both break from the classic mold of liberal Democrat and
conservative Republican is the shared willingness of the two 1975
University of Wisconsin graduates to play the maverick.
</P>
<P>
   Neumann has squared off more than once with House Speaker Newt
Gingrich, and was one of only 11 Republicans to oppose a GOP-backed
tax cut this year because he said it would damage the Social
Security Trust Fund. Feingold was one of just eight senators to
oppose a 1997 tax cut, also to protect Social Security, and he
called for an independent counsel on Clinton administration
fund-raising in early 1997.
</P>
<P>
   At their first debate last week in the state capital, the two
men confined their sharpest attacks to campaign finance, though
Neumann also played into his tough-guy stereotype by making a
college student cry by suggesting her question about an obscure PAC
was a Feingold plant. She denied it and tearfully demanded an
apology, which Neumann granted.
</P>
<P>
   Feingold played up his refusal to allow the national Democratic
Party to run ads on ads on his behalf. He then accused Neumann of
exploiting loopholes in their spending limit by coordinating
television ads with the national GOP.
</P>
<P>
   Neumann countered by accusing Feingold of benefiting from
``issue ads'' by groups such as the AFL-CIO, the Sierra Club and
the League of Conservation Voters, all of which have in fact
entered the fray. In an interview, Neumann said Feingold ``should
just quit whining and get down to the issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the ads that have riled Feingold most is one in which
Neumann accuses him of profligate government spending, citing $11
million for a Russian space monkey research project. Feingold
actually co-sponsored a Senate measure to kill that funding.
Neumann said his real point was to criticize Feingold's 1993
support for a tax increase.
</P>
<P>
   Another unexpected sticking point: gaseous cows. Neumann says
Feingold supported a wasteful program to study bovine flatulence as
a source of methane; Feingold calls that a misrepresentation.
</P>
<P>
   A more recent battleground _ marking a decidedly tougher shift
in Neumann's advertising _ has been late-term abortions. Feingold
says he would vote for a ban only if it included exceptions to
protect the mother's life or health.
</P>
<P>
   Voters interviewed last week said they were focused more on the
issues _ particularly abortion _ than on campaign finance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm with Feingold. I don't want anything to take away a
woman's right to choose,'' said Linda Brunker, a retail manager
from Madison.
</P>
<P>
   But the issue cuts both ways here. Beverly Steiner, a real
estate agent from Mauston, said she voted for Feingold in 1992.
This year she supports Neumann. ``I like his stand on abortion. I'm
strongly pro-life,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Andrea Andrews, spokeswoman for the National Republican
Senatorial Committee, said the race is among the GOP's top five in
terms of priority and financial commitment, though she declined to
elaborate. ``We see this as winnable,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   By most accounts, President Clinton's impeachment troubles have
had little direct impact on the race, though Democrats fear low
turnout from downhearted party members.
</P>
<P>
   Terri Spring, chairwoman of the Wisconsin Democratic Party, was
rueful when asked about how different things might have been had
Feingold used all the advantages of incumbency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really respect him,'' she said. ``But I've got mixed
feelings right now. We'll see on Nov. 3 how it plays out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
