<SLUG> BC-WILDLIFE-RANCH-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXOTIC WILDLIFE RANCH SCHEDULED TO CLOSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RALPH WININGHAM  
 c.1998 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ The buffalo no longer will roam where the deer and
antelope play after Nov. 29 at the Kerrville Camera Safari.
</P>
<P>
   The 230-acre ranch will close after more than six years of
operating in what has been called the heart of the exotic animal
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got an offer to buy the entire ranch that we couldn't
refuse,'' Ken Wilson, ranch manager and co-owner of the safari,
said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   About 30,000 people a year drove through the canyons and draws
of the ranch in the Hill Country northwest of San Antonio _ an area
that once concealed whiskey stills _ to observe the collection of
more than 300 animals ranging from giraffe to American bison.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was more than just a tourist attraction. It was a
showcase for the exotic ranching industry in an area where hundreds
of ranches specialize in raising various species,'' Wilson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most game ranches are closed to the public, so this offered
people an opportunity to see something that was normally not
available,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the purchase were being withheld by agreement between
the two parties, Wilson said, adding that the deal was finalized
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a commercial master plan being developed for the
entire 230 acres,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sherry Cunningham, president of the Kerrville Area Chamber of
Commerce, said the operation would be missed as an attraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was my grandchildren's favorite place,'' she said. ``It
has been such a special place for families who just want to go out
and picnic or drive around and see the animals.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a real loss for Kerrville,'' Cunningham said.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said the animals will sold to other exotic animal
operations.
</P>
<P>
   The ranch is part of an original 4,400-acre property called
Whiskey Creek Ranch, named for the illegal whiskey stills once
operated there.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson and his partner, Roger Haley, both from California, spent
more than $250,000 to improve the property before its opening on
Sept. 4, 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Animals that have been displayed at one of the largest drive-
through parks of its kind include aoudad, axis deer, bison,
blackbuck antelope, eland, giraffe, Hawaiian black sheep, llama,
Texas dall sheep, timberwolf, water buffalo and zebra.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
