<HEADER>
A1554 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOMELESS-KIDS-ART-AZR     10-22 1562
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMELESS-KIDS-ART-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARIZONA STREET KIDS GET LIFELINE  
 (ART ADV: PHOTO HAS BEEN SENT TO NYTNS CLIENTS) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By KARINA BLAND  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Three nights a week, Steven Serrano and Linda Silva go
out in a white van and drive slowly through the worst parts of
Phoenix and neighboring Tempe, looking for homeless kids.
</P>
<P>
   Concealed by day, the teenagers emerge from the dark shadows of
the street with their hands outstretched when they see the van.
</P>
<P>
   They know it is stocked with food, cold drinks and clothes _ in
particular the thick white socks that help ward off the foot fungus
that breeds from too much time in the same pair of shoes and socks.
</P>
<P>
   Every kid out here has a different story, but there are similar
plot lines.
</P>
<P>
   Some lived in expensive homes, others in crack houses. Most were
physically or sexually abused. And many of them have given up the
lives they once dreamed of, sleeping now on sidewalks and masking
their pain with alcohol and drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd rather sell their body for sex than go home, so home
has to be pretty bad,'' Serrano said.
</P>
<P>
   The Children's Action Alliance, a non-profit advocacy agency,
estimated in 1990 that there were 5,000 runaway and homeless youths
in Arizona. Now, estimates run as high as 10,000.
</P>
<P>
   And since 1983, the number of homeless girls has about doubled.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one really knows how many kids are out there,'' said Karny
Stefan, development director for HomeBase Youth Services, a
non-profit agency that helps homeless young people with food,
shelter, clothing, counseling and other services.
</P>
<P>
   They rarely stay in one place long enough to be counted.
</P>
<P>
   Within two days of landing on the streets, 72 percent of girls
will turn to prostitution to make money, Serrano says. Half of the
boys will do the same within three days.
</P>
<P>
   Homeless kids are scattered throughout the metro Phoenix area,
although there are higher concentrations of them in downtown
Phoenix and Tempe, where Serrano and Silva make regular runs.
</P>
<P>
   Besides HomeBase, only two other non-profit agencies _
Tumbleweed Center for Youth Development and Stand Up for Kids _
comb the streets in search of these kids. Serrano says they could
use double that force.
</P>
<P>
   Serrano has been making these runs into the night for HomeBase
for four years, Silva since March.
</P>
<P>
   They take the van but often canvass parks and nearly empty
streets on foot with packs on their backs, peering into public
restrooms and alleys and behind fences and trash cans.
</P>
<P>
   Serrano and Silva hand out bags of non-perishable food _
pull-top cans of tuna, canned fruit, granola bars. And they
distribute hygiene products _ toothbrushes, toothpaste, disposable
razors, soap, shampoo and combs.
</P>
<P>
   In the van, they keep blankets, bandages, remedies for lice
infestation and other medicine. &UR; Everything is donated. They can
empty the van in a single night.
</P>
<P>
   Silva asks the kids if they are thirsty, hungry or if they need
a place to stay. The goal is to find the young people a safe place
to stay, such as HomeBase's shelter near Seventh Street and Indian
School Road, which is for people ages 18 to 21.
</P>
<P>
   There, they get counseling, go to school or find jobs. They're
well fed, living in apartments around a small swimming pool. They
can live there for as long as two years.
</P>
<P>
   They are either homeless children, runaways or foster kids who
had no place to go once they turned 18. Of those who have lived
there, about 85 percent never go back to the streets, the best rate
in the nation among homeless programs for children, director Pat
Leach says.
</P>
<P>
   On the street, the kids are hesitant when they meet Serrano and
Silva, scared to trust someone they don't know.
</P>
<P>
   ``The minute they wake up out here, someone wants something from
them,'' Serrano said. ``They want them to do a drug run or they
want them for sex. It's hard for them to believe that we don't want
anything from them.''
</P>
<P>
   He drives first through an area in downtown Phoenix known on the
streets as ``Boys Town,'' a place where male prostitutes
congregate, and shiny Infinitis and BMWs _ one with a child
restraint seat in the back _ cruise by slowly.
</P>
<P>
   In the alleys, addicts shoot up. A police officer walks the
area.
</P>
<P>
   It is quiet tonight, and they see no kids. Yet the men working
the area _ some dressed as women _ wave. Serrano and Silva wave
back.
</P>
<P>
   They befriend drug dealers and pimps because they know where the
children are. A pimp once called Serrano to tell where to find a
missing teenage boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We talk to everyone,'' Serrano said. ``We make sure we know
what's going on that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Silva and Serrano move on. Their next stop is in a dark
industrial area in downtown Phoenix that is known as a haven for
drug users and dealers.
</P>
<P>
   There, a 19-year-old girl named Angie waves down the van.
Serrano parks under the single street light on the block.
</P>
<P>
   Silva asks Angie if she is hungry, and Serrano hands her a cold
drink.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you have any socks?'' Angie asked. ``I need a blanket, too.
Can I have the blue one?''
</P>
<P>
   Another boy walks over to the van, his lip burned and split from
smoking cocaine from a hot pipe.
</P>
<P>
   ``How old are you?'' Serrano asked.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen, the boy tells him. His name is Juan.
</P>
<P>
   Serrano gives him a sandwich for now and a bag of food for
later. He also gives Juan a card with the telephone number of the
HomeBase shelter. The boy puts it in his bag.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll call,'' he said. ``I'm tired of sleeping on the
sidewalk.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is, Serrano says, there are few shelters for people
younger than 18, so they often are full. Even HomeBase's shelter
has a waiting list, although two beds are kept open for emergencies
_ kids who are sick or have been beaten or raped.
</P>
<P>
   On the street, the kids are polite, saying ``please'' and
``thank you.''
</P>
<P>
   But, as Serrano talks to Juan, 20 men and women gather around
the van _ homeless, prostitutes, drug users and dealers. Mostly,
they are haggard; some wear thick gold chains.
</P>
<P>
   They, too, ask for handouts, and Serrano explains that HomeBase
serves only people ages 14 to 21. Other services are available for
the adult homeless.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 21!'' shouted a man with gray hair who clearly was at
least twice that.
</P>
<P>
   Serrano and Silva shut the van's doors, but the crowd presses
in, hands reaching for the box of doughnuts in Serrano's hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back up. Back up,'' Silva said.
</P>
<P>
   But the crowd moves closer, pushing Serrano and Silva against
the van. Someone shouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's gonna be a fight,'' a woman yells.
</P>
<P>
   Serrano hands the box of doughnuts to the man nearest him, and
he and Silva hurriedly get into the van.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whew!'' Serrano said. ``My heart is pounding.''
</P>
<P>
   This has happened before, Serrano says, sometimes twice a week.
Serrano and Silva carry cellular phones and whistles but no
weapons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had anything happen to me out here,'' Serrano said.
``The day might come, but it's important that we saw people _
Angie, Juan, Justin.''
</P>
<P>
   Justin was a skinny kid about 18. Serrano gave him a bag of
food, though chances are good that one of those adults _ older and
stronger _ would take it from him.
</P>
<P>
   Serrano and Silva stop next at Central Arizona Shelter Services.
t Craig, 20, who has lived here for a few months, moved to Arizona
to live with his parents only to find that his parents had moved
away three weeks earlier.
</P>
<P>
   He and other young men gather around the van.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thank you, sir,'' Craig said, taking a bag of food and
toiletries from Serrano.
</P>
<P>
   Nathaniel, 20, went to high school with Serrano near the
exclusive enclave of Paradise Valley. In the last year and a half,
Serrano says, he has run into a dozen youths on the street with
whom he went to school. Some of them are in bad shape, mostly
because of drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we see kids who are really, really bad, we don't know if
we'll ever see them again,'' Serrano said.
</P>
<P>
   Their shift is over, but Serrano and Silva don't want to go back
until they find Luke, an 18-year-old who has been homeless for a
year and a half.
</P>
<P>
   He has been coming to HomeBase's drop-in center for food and
counseling, but they are worried because Luke's arms are lined with
slash marks. He cuts himself.
</P>
<P>
   Serrano pulls himself up on a concrete block fence behind a
Phoenix restaurant and calls, ``Luke! Hey, Luke!''
</P>
<P>
   Luke's blond head pops up.
</P>
<P>
   He's eating a can of tuna that Silva gave him earlier in the day
at the drop-in center and reading a book, borrowed from the
center's library.
</P>
<P>
   His parents kicked him out of his Phoenix home, although he
didn't say why. He has talked to them twice on the phone since.
</P>
<P>
   ``They ask me how I'm doing, but they don't ask me to come
home,'' Luke said. ``You learn how to live with it. You try not to
get angry at anyone. I'm just angry at myself.''
</P>
<P>
   He's a good-looking kid and well spoken. He promises Silva he
will come to the drop-in center the next day to talk about moving
into the shelter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need some help. It's been hard this year and a half, and I
obviously can't do it on my own,'' Luke said.
</P>
<P>
   No matter how many kids Serrano and Silva find each night, they
never forget a name _ Angie, Joshua, Craig, Nathaniel, Noel, Luke,
and the hundreds more like them.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could you forget?'' Serrano asked. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
