<HEADER>
A1558 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-22 0889
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANY IN GOP ANGRY AT CONGRESS'S DEAL WITH CLINTON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLIS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last week's budget agreement left many Republicans and
conservative commentators in a foul mood. They were aghast at the
extraordinary spending levels agreed to by the congressional
Republican leadership. They were angered by their party's
capitulation on tax cuts. They were amazed that President Clinton
was so successful in rewarding Democratic members of the House
Judiciary Committee. Privately, they wondered whether their
leadership had become the hacks they once abhorred.
</P>
<P>
   Former vice presidential nominee Jack Kemp spoke for many when
he said: ``Today, the Republican Party is adrift, without an agenda
and without purpose beyond its seeming preoccupation with saving
the congressional seats of its incumbents.''
</P>
<P>
   George Will was even tougher, calling the Republican Congress
``disgraceful,'' ``corrupt'' and ``the Boston Red Sox of politics,
forever muttering, `Wait till next year.''' Will concluded by
saying, ``Republicans can no longer say it is important to elect
them because they represent something dramatically different.
Democrats can no longer say it is important to defeat Republicans
lest there be risky assaults on ... anything.''
</P>
<P>
   That last sentence was the reason Gingrich agreed to the deal;
he ``lost'' the budget battle to ``win'' the electoral war. This
may explain the speaker's irritation Tuesday with conservative
critics, whom he denounced as ``perfectionists'' and ``petty
dictators,'' out of touch with political reality.
</P>
<P>
   From Gingrich's point of view, the 1998 budget negotiations were
all about 1998 midterm and year 2000 election strategy. Gingrich
feared that if the Republicans did not give President Clinton some
measure of what he wanted, then Clinton would force the issue (by
veto) and shut down the government, blaming Republicans as he did
so. Gingrich wanted no part of a replay of the budget battle of
1995. He learned that lesson the hard way.
</P>
<P>
   The whole point of Gingrich's strategy was to take the ``risky''
out of Republican and leave Clinton issueless going into the last
two weeks of the campaign. By caving in to key Clinton demands,
Gingrich ensured that the president would be unable to campaign
against a Republican Congress that had just given him more than a
fair shake. Taking away the GOP Congress as a campaign issue leaves
Clinton without a -``national'' issue to discuss.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich's bet is that by ``denationalizing'' the midterm
elections, they will revert to form. The form works to Republican
advantage at almost every turn. Historically, the party out of
power in the White House makes significant gains in congressional
elections in the sixth year of the incumbent's reign.
</P>
<P>
   Currently, the GOP's financial advantage is made much more
significant if the mid-term elections are denationalized. This is
especially true this year because the Democratic Party is pouring a
huge percentage of its funds into California to try to capture the
governorship and keep control of the state Legislature. Democrats
hope that by doing both they will be able to redraw the
congressional districts in 2001 to their advantage. But by devoting
such a high percentage of their resources to one state (and an
expensive state at that), they are substantially increasing the
GOP's money advantage in every other state.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Democratic turnout will likely be lethargic given
that key Democratic constituencies (such as teachers unions) did
well in the budget negotiations. Anger is the key to high turnout,
and Democrats can hardly be irritable about this year's budget
deal.
</P>
<P>
   Psychologically, Gingrich understands that Clinton can't stand
taking himself off the playing field. Clinton will feel compelled
to campaign, even if few in his party would like him to come to
their states or districts. Once he is out on the trail, Clinton
will be perceived as the lying politician that he is (as opposed to
the chief executive working hard to keep the government
operational). His campaigning _ and the coverage of it on
television _ will remind every Republican constituency why it is
that they loathe him with such intensity. Which will likely drive
Republican turnout up.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Gingrich is preparing his party for the year 2000
election. Truth be told, he likes the fact that the more
conservative elements of the party have been publicly critical of
the budget deal. That moderates the party's image and makes it more
difficult for Clinton and Gore to portray the GOP as obstreperous
or dangerous. Which in turn might make it easier for Americans to
elect both a Republican president and a Republican Congress in
2000.
</P>
<P>
   If Republicans make substantial gains in this year's midterm
elections, then the recent spate of conservative criticism will be
forgiven and forgotten in the victory celebration of enhanced
majority status. If Gingrich's strategy fails to produce
significant gains, then the party's right wing will become much
more assertive immediately, opening up the possibility of another
challenge to Gingrich's leadership. The stakes in these elections
are as high for Gingrich as they are for Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(John Ellis is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
