<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LADYBUGS MAKE THEMSELVES AT HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CAROL STOCKER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When thousands of ladybugs swarmed Teri Christoferson's windows
Sunday trying to find a way in, her 12-year-old son, Robert,
defended the Westwoodm Mass., homestead by blowing the ladybugs off
the screens with a vacuum set on reverse. But as soon as the
machine was off, the ladybugs were back.
</P>
<P>
   By Tuesday, however, the beetles had vanished just as suddenly
and mysteriously as they had appeared.
</P>
<P>
   Nicknamed ``Halloween ladybugs'' for their colors and timing,
the black-spotted orange creatures are a newly arrived species that
has been infiltrating houses on warm October days ever since they
came to Boston about five years ago.
</P>
<P>
   In their native Asia, they hibernate in limestone crevices, so
when winter approaches, they look for someplace white to climb
into. Like the Christofersons' white windows.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Cocca, a natural history information coordinator for the
Massachusetts Audubon Society, was herself swarmed with calls about
the insects Monday, all from people who lived in white houses or
houses with white shutters. Most also lived near wooded areas. Some
of the calls were from offices that assigned an employee to
telephone after trading Monday-morning anecdotes about rampaging
ladybugs.
</P>
<P>
   So where did these ladybugs come from, where did they go, and
what should you do about it?
</P>
<P>
   Most experts agree that the Asian ladybugs (Harmonia axyridis)
hitched a ride here, as they were first recorded in large numbers
near a port in Louisiana 10 years ago. They spread from there and
now they're in all the New England states.
</P>
<P>
   Asian ladybugs spent the warm season outdoors eating insect
pests (they've been a boon to orchardists), but when a warm spell
hit last week, they started swarming. When the weather turned cold
again this week, most settled back down under leaf litter. Those
that got into houses soon disappeared into walls and attics to
hibernate. These ladybugs probably won't be seen again until next
spring, when they'll gather at windows waiting for you to let them
out, which is a good idea.
</P>
<P>
   There are several things you can do to thwart Asian ladybugs.
Put screens on attic air vents and keep window screens secure till
November. Consider painting your white house or window trim another
color.
</P>
<P>
   What you should never do is crush ladybugs indoors, because
their fluids stain and have a noxious odor. Insect sprays indoors
are a bad idea, too, as the ladybugs themselves are harmless.
</P>
<P>
   If you're housing uninvited ladybugs, you can vacuum them up
live and dump them outside or stash the bag in a cool basement or
garage and release the beetles in early April. If they do spend the
winter indoors, they won't eat or reproduce, which makes them easy
house guests, so you could also adopt the attitude of the Japanese.
They consider it good luck to house hibernating ladybugs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
