<HEADLINE>
SUBTERRANEAN HUBBY'S-AT-HOME-SICK BLUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LAURI NOTARO  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - It wasn't the first sneeze that scared me.
</P>
<P>
   When I heard my husband sneeze a third, fourth and fifth time
from the living room, I still had no fear. It's a common occurrence
in our house; if you touch anything, move anything, or sit on
anything, a sneeze is imminent.
</P>
<P>
   Our little dog, who I believe sustained minor brain damage from
spending too much time out in the sun when she was a puppy, refuses
to come back indoors unless she has completely coated herself with
a thick layer of dirt and dead grass. If you try to brush her or
pat the dirt off her, it will just make more. As a result, I have
enough dust on some bookshelves to plant seeds in.
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't scared until my husband woke up the next morning and
shook me awake.
</P>
<P>
   ``Honey, I don't feel so good,'' he squeaked out. ``My throat
feels scratchy.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten minutes later, he came back into the bedroom and leaned over
me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I coughed up my colon,'' he begged. ``What does it
look like to you?''
</P>
<P>
   Then he stared at me and muttered the most horrendous words a
husband could ever say to his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' he said, ``I think I'm going to stay home today.''
</P>
<P>
   I will say right now that my husband is the nicest guy on the
planet. I knew when I married him that I got the best deal on the
market, although I never thought a guy like him would ever settle
for a big bag of trouble like me. We had had a lot to drink the
night he first told me he loved me as we sat in a Denny's parking
lot, and then he bought me a Grand Slam breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   The next day he mentioned that he remembered what he had said
and didn't even take it back. I was amazed. I had a Good Guy, an
endangered species. The only thing that would make my husband more
valuable is if he were an albino.
</P>
<P>
   But when he gets sick, King Cranky is born, and a wave of panic
washes over me when he mentions staying home. I know all about the
vows I took when we got married _ for richer, for poorer, in
sickness and in health _ but the man I married changes just as soon
as he's unable to breathe out of one nostril. He becomes a walking
testament to misery, shuffling around the house with two little
wads of tissue compacted in his nose, poking his congested head in
my office every couple minutes and asking me questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard the phone ring. Is it for me?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Is it time for my pill yet?''
</P>
<P>
   ``How much longer do you have to work?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Where's the dictionary? I want to look up `tuberculosis.' ''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm lonely.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Boy, you type loud. Every time you press a key, it's like a
dagger going into my brain.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What are the symptoms for the hantavirus again?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm bored.''
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you make soup from scratch?''
</P>
<P>
   ``If the instructions on the box of oatmeal say it should cook
for one minute, how long is that in the microwave?''
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, and the fact that I had a deadline that day,
I jumped out of bed, rushed to the bathroom and dug like an animal
through our medicine chest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here's some stuff to make you feel better,'' I offered to his
droopy eyes, his pink nose, his chapped upper lip.
</P>
<P>
   He unscrewed the top of the bottle and popped a pill into his
mouth. ``What are . . . Derma Caps?'' he asked weakly, reading the
label as he turned the bottle around.
</P>
<P>
   I gasped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Spit it out!'' I snapped, holding my hand out. ``Spit it out!
That's medicine for the dog's dandruff!''
</P>
<P>
   I ran back to the bathroom and dug some more. In a box I still
haven't unpacked from our move two years ago, I hit gold. There, at
the bottom, I found a whole box of a cold remedy you mix with water
and then drink. I remember taking that stuff the last time I was
sick, and how I passed out and flew into potent hallucinations
before the last mouthful went down.
</P>
<P>
   ``This medicine,'' I told my husband, plopping the two fizzling
tablets in a mug of water, ``is better than drinking a whole fifth
by yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   He downed it in one swallow. Within fifteen minutes, he was
asleep on the couch, twitching and batting at things. It was magic.
</P>
<P>
   I went back to work, but I checked on him every now and then,
and was even privy to some of his hallucinations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Merv Griffin won't give me back my pillow!'' he shouted from
the couch. ``Give it back! But I'm the Hooner!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey all of you sailors, get out of my house! Put your pants
back on! Where's my wife?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I told you, Mister, I'm Nick Barkley and I'm the head of this
ranch!''
</P>
<P>
   As soon as I even suspected that he was beginning to regain
consciousness, I mixed up another batch of cold stuff and poured it
down his throat. I had drugged him so heavily he could have written
``The White Album'' all by himself. By nightfall, I had made my
deadline successfully, and I went into the living room to see how
many things I could put up my husband's nose before he woke up.
</P>
<P>
   I had a nickel in my hand when he shuddered awake, rubbed his
eyes and then said, ``Honey, you don't look so good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Those sailors wear me out!'' I replied. (begin ital) ``Choo!''
(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, no,'' my husband gasped. ``You're getting sick!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not!'' I protested. (begin ital) ``Choo! Choo! Choo!''
(end ital)
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't handle this,'' he replied, handing me a tissue. ``You
get so cranky when you're sick! You turn into Mrs. Mean!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not!'' I said angrily, patting my nose with the Kleenex.
``Will you quit looking at me? Move over, hog! I want to lie down
there!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Can I get you anything?'' he asked kindly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shut your pie hole!'' I screeched. (begin ital) ````Choo!''
(end ital) Your voice goes through me like daggers! Get me some
soup! But I want it from scratch!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got something a little better,'' he said, getting up from
the couch, and in no less than five seconds, I heard the familiar
sounds of Plop! Plop! Fizz! Fizz! coming from the kitchen. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Write to Lauri Notaro in care of the ``Rep,'' P.O. Box 2245 NF-19,
Phoenix, AZ 85002. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
