<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WADING ONTO THE WEB 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LINDA WELTNER 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ When my dad was in his 70s, I gave him a tape recorder.
He'd once said he wished he could save certain radio talk-show
conversations and I thought he'd like being able to record his
favorite parts. He turned the tape recorder over in his hand before
giving it back to me.
</P>
<P>
   ``What, Dad?'' I said. ``Look, it's easy. You just press the red
button and the one beside it. That's all there is to it.'' He shook
his head. It was clear he felt the machine was too complicated for
him to master.
</P>
<P>
   It was upsetting to see my dad intimidated by technology. I
vowed that would never happen to me. I didn't want growing older to
mean getting befuddled by every newfangled invention. So I figured
out how to hook up a fax, how to get on the Internet, and how to
send an e-mail. I should have known I wouldn't have time to rest on
my laurels.
</P>
<P>
   The next obstacle was my own Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Over the years I've personally answered letters from readers
without too much difficulty, but I was overwhelmed by how many of
my readers requested a spirituality inventory last May. The first
batch of letters covered the dining-room table, and every time I
caught a glimpse of oak, the mailman delivered hundreds more. I had
to open every letter and respond to questions, fold and fit three
sheets of paper into such a variety of envelopes that at times I
felt I was in the middle of an origami project. Some people forgot
to enclose an envelope. Others forgot the stamp. I added my return
address. It took all my leisure time for one solid month.
</P>
<P>
   This is not something I want to ever do again.
</P>
<P>
   Yet time and again, I think of things I'd like to share with my
readers. For example, after hearing Dr. Susan Love speak in Boston
about the importance of adding soy to a healthy diet, the steering
committee of the Marblehead Cancer Prevention Project decided to
have a soy potluck dinner. I collected all the recipes, plus our
evaluations, and wanted to share them with my readers, but I didn't
want to do the self-addressed stamped-envelope dance again. It
occurred to me that if I had a Web site on which to post them,
those recipes could be downloaded far more easily than I could ever
mail them.
</P>
<P>
   All of a sudden, I thought of a million uses for a Web site. I
have photos of my family I thought folks might enjoy comparing to
the images they've carried in their heads for the past 17 years.
Since my schedule includes numerous speaking engagements that are
open to the public, a Web site would give me a chance to invite
readers to attend. I could include information about the subjects
of my talks in case anyone wanted to invite me to address their
organization.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are reviews of my books, which most folks have never
seen. Although ``No Place Like Home'' is out of print, I have 600
copies in the garage for sale to those who'd like to read
selections from my earliest columns. I envisioned including a
reading group guide for my new book, ``Family Puzzles,'' which
would bring up provocative issues for discussion. It also occurred
to me that I could stay in touch with readers who've left Boston by
posting my ``Ever So Humble'' column on my Web site every week so
that they could visit me on the Internet from anywhere in the
world.
</P>
<P>
   I had no problem imagining the content. It was implementation
that stopped me cold.
</P>
<P>
   How do you get a Web site? How much does it cost? Does it matter
how many screens you fill? Does a Web site end up being another
monthly charge or does your e-mail account cover it? How do you
update it? How do you get your Web site listed on search engines?
All I knew was the depth of my ignorance. I toyed with the idea of
taking a Web-site workshop, but the task seemed overwhelming. For
months I did nothing.
</P>
<P>
   I was actually eating a mushroom stuffed with tofu and bread
crumbs at our soy dinner when I gave vent to my confusion. What
happened next always happens in my life. The minute I'm clear
enough to express a need, the perfect person to help me appears as
if by magic.
</P>
<P>
   It just so happened that the woman I was speaking to was married
to a man who'd just decided to create Web sites for a living. I'd
known Jane for a year yet I hadn't had even a inkling of that. It
felt like fate to me. And so, with a folder full of papers and
photos, I met with her husband and placed my Web site in Nelson's
hands. The depth of my ignorance hasn't changed, but my Web site is
now on line.
</P>
<P>
   Come visit me at www.shore.net/weltner. I'm at home there 24
hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Linda Weltner is a freelance writer. Her column appears each week
in the Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
