</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-ADD-NYT-BUDGET  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Add N.Y. Times News Service budget for papers of FRIDAY, Oct.
23.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT &LR;  (Moving in ``e'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   PERSIAN-ART-EXHIBIT (New York) _ In every culture, objects of
beauty bring delight. They also push ideologies, advertise
interests, secure alliance and pump up reputations. So it has
always been; so it is likely always to be. It was certainly true
two centuries ago in Iran. By Holland Cotter.
</P>
<P>
   VAUTIER-ART-EXHIBIT (New York) _ Ben Vautier is appearing in
three shows in New York: ``Ben Vautier: Statements with Clocks,''
at the John Gibson Gallery in SoHo; with one large piece, ``Gallery
One,'' in ``Premises: Invested Spaces'' at the Guggenheim Museum
SoHo, and ``Ben Vautier: Photo Rejects,'' at the Zabriskie Gallery
on East 57th Street. Lots of Ben: joy to the world. By Vicki
Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   FAIRIES-ART-EXHIBIT (New York) _ It's about sex. I am, of
course, referring to the peculiar and heretofore obscure Victorian
phenomenon known as fairy painting, the subject of a show at the
Frick that is a scaled-back version of a hugely popular exhibition
in London a year ago. By Michael Kimmelman.
</P>
<P>
   THEATER-PROGRAM-EXHIBIT (New York) _ More than 100 theater
programs of the avant-garde theater in Paris are on view at the
National Academy Museum in Manhattan. By John Russell.
</P>
<P>
   APPLE'S-LOUISVILLE (Louisville, Ky.) _ The city began with the
river. As the broad and occasionally unruly Ohio flows southwest
from Pittsburgh toward its rendezvous with the Mississippi, it is
interrupted here by rapids. In 1778, that barrier prompted George
Rogers Clark, a young frontiersman from Virginia, to pause on his
trip west and establish a settlement that eventually grew into
this, the first metropolis west of the Alleghenies. By R.W. Apple
Jr. (With a map.)
</P>
<P>
   LEWINSKY-THEATER (New York) _ In the rehearsal hall, the
dialogue was sliced tart and true from the life and times of Monica
Lewinsky, with no less than three actresses taking a crack at the
ultimate ingenue's role in the inescapable national melodrama that
has no copyright, perchance no ending. By Francis X. Clines
</P>
