<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WHITE-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE HARD READ CAFE COULD DO A LOT OF GOOD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DIANE WHITE 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Hard Read Cafe, another brilliant concept brought to you by
the same column that brought you the Soft Rock Cafe. And whatever
happened to that idea? Could it be that its time has finally come?
What with the Burt Bacharach revival and all? Or isn't he soft
rock? He's soft, definitely. But rock?
</P>
<P>
   Back to the Hard Read Cafe, where the great books are always
accessible, and the not-so-great books are too. Where there's a
trained staff, many with advanced degrees, to explain the difficult
bits, to describe how a particular work fits into the grand scheme
of literature.
</P>
<P>
   How many times have you put down a book, maybe even flung it
across the room, shouting, ``What the hell is this supposed to be
about?''
</P>
<P>
   The Hard Read Cafe would could provide the answer.
</P>
<P>
   People are turning back to books. Some are turning to them for
the very first time. Oprah's television book groups are a huge
success. National Public Radio has a monthly
reading-group-of-the-air. Don Imus is handing out big-money
literary prizes. On the Internet, amazon.com is thriving. People
actually debate the merits of the Modern Library list of the 100
best English-language novels of the 20th century. And while smaller
bookstores are being driven out of business by the big chains,
those big chains are getting bigger.
</P>
<P>
   Reading is back. But if reading is going to flourish in the
information-overload age it has to be glamorous, trendy, now, hot,
or cool, or whatever the current word may be.
</P>
<P>
   The idea for the Hard Read Cafe occurred to me last weekend in
Baltimore, where there's a new waterfront attraction, the Power
Plant, a huge building that used to be what its name implies. Now
the east wing houses a Hard Rock Cafe, the west wing the new ESPN
Zone, the prototype for a planned chain of sports bars on steroids.
In the middle there's a Barnes &AMP; Noble bookstore.
</P>
<P>
   The lines were long outside the Hard Rock, and outside the ESPN
Zone too. Inside Barnes &AMP; Noble people browsed the shelves, but
outside there were no lines of people waiting to be granted
admittance. Why not? Now that reading is back, shouldn't there be
eager throngs clamoring to get into bookstores?
</P>
<P>
   Hence the Hard Read. It's really only a step or two beyond what
some bookstores are doing now. They sponsor book groups, readings,
and signings by authors. Staff members post lists of personal
recommendations. And many bookstores have cafes. In some instances
it almost seems that the cafe is the big draw, the books merely
incidental.
</P>
<P>
   Books will never take a back seat at the Hard Read Cafe. Reading
will always be the main event. Not that we'll stint on amenities.
At the Hard Read Cafe you'll be able to sit down with a scholar,
maybe even a PhD, who'll help you understand those difficult
passages in, say, ``Ulysses,'' or ``Darkness at Noon,'' over a cup
of coffee or a glass of wine and an authentic literary delicacy
from our cafe menu. Bread pudding James Joyce. Mansfield Park
gooseberry tart. Chlodnik a la Alice B. Toklas. Pinhead oatmeal
porridge in the style of George Bernard Shaw. And the inevitable
Remembrance of Things Past madeleines.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Hard Rock Cafes display collections of rock n' roll
artifacts, the Hard Read Cafe will be adorned with select literary
memorabilia. Pop music pilgrims travel great distances to Hard Rock
Cafes to eat cheeseburgers and stare at Mick Jagger's codpiece, or
whatever. Imagine the appeal to avid readers of items with literary
associations. Edith Wharton's corset stays. An empty bottle of
Wildroot Creme Oil thought to have been used by F. Scott
Fitzgerald. An Ernest Hemingway wineskin, signed by the author.
Really, the possibilities are endless.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Diane White is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
