<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEDIA-NOTES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWSPAPERS LAG ON HIRING MINORITY JOURNALISTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK JURKOWITZ  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Twenty years ago, the American Society of Newspaper Editors set
a goal of having newsrooms match the nation's racial makeup by the
year 2000. With the millennium around the corner, minorities
constitute just over a quarter of the American population, but
minority journalists still fill only 11.46 percent of the newsroom
desks. At its board meeting in Miami this week, ASNE emerged with a
mission statement declaring that ``the nation's newsrooms must
reflect the racial diversity of American society by 2025 or
sooner.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, we will be measured as much for our efforts as our
aspirations,'' declared ASNE president Edward Seaton. Included in
those efforts are a series of upcoming round-tables to encourage
minority journalists, journalism teachers, and media foundation
officials to brainstorm about the elusive goal of stronger minority
recruitment and retention. In addition, ASNE will establish
``measurable benchmarks'' to gauge its progress _ in areas from
increasing minority internships to reducing minority turnover _
every three years.
</P>
<P>
   But ASNE's new diversity declarations provoked a mixed reaction
in some quarters. ``We're encouraged that the society thinks
diversity is a goal worth striving for,'' says Vanessa Williams,
president of the National Association of Black Journalists. But
``we're troubled that they've put the goal (of diversity by 2025)
so far away.'' Asserting that ``lack of commitment'' has been the
single biggest obstacle to journalistic diversity, Williams worries
that the 2025 deadline creates ``no sense of urgency.'' By ASNE's
own count, 42 percent of American daily papers have no minority
staff.
</P>
<P>
   ASNE's mission statement is ``not sufficient,'' agrees Kara
Briggs, president of the Native American Journalists Association
and of UNITY: Journalists of Color Inc. ``Is it a step in the right
direction? Sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Although she says ASNE has ``done some very serious talking and
engaged in some very respectful dialogue'' on the topic of
diversity, Briggs still worries that newsroom diversity is still a
``numbers game'' that does not recognize the inherent value of
minority journalists and often creates ``hostile environments'' for
those journalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that this has to be a two-fold challenge,'' she adds.
``Certainly it is a newsrooom policy issue. But it is also an
in-your-heart issue. ... Are you willing to have a change of heart
about the value of these journalists?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
What's next for Newsweek? &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As Newsweek staffers gather in New York today for a memorial
service for editor Maynard Parker, thoughts turn to a successor.
Parker, whose legacy is his magazine's out-hustling of rival Time
on the cultural Zeitgeist beat, died last week of complications
from pneumonia after battling leukemia. He leaves an ostensible
heir apparent in managing editor Mark Whitaker. But his ascension
may not yet be a done deal. Other reported contenders include
international editions editor Michael Elliott and assistant
managing editors Evan Thomas and Ann McDaniel. The selection of
either Whitaker, an African-American, or McDaniel would strike a
blow for diversity atop the masthead. But word is that McDaniel,
based in Washington, is not eager to relocate to New York.
</P>
<P>
   Parker was known for a hard-driving style, what Time managing
editor Walter Isaacson called ``his legendary intensity'' in a
tribute he penned in Time. But his final resting place is far
removed from New York's grinding journalistic rat race. Parker's
ashes will be scattered near a favored Oregon vacation spot.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
