<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 15:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1613 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GAGNON-COMIC-AZR &LR;      10-22 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAGNON-COMIC-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUNNYMAN LAUGHS OFF LACK OF RECOGNITION IN U.S.  
 (ADV: WITH CELINE-DION-MUSIC) 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDY CORDOVA  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - More than 16,000 tickets to Celine Dion's concert in
Phoenix went on sale on a Sunday back in April. In only two days,
all were sold.
</P>
<P>
   You have to figure that at some point, about 15,999 of those
buyers were looking at their tickets and wondering, ``Who the hell
is Andre-Philippe Gagnon?''
</P>
<P>
   The man with the big moniker is the fortunate soul who landed
the opening spot on the Canadian chanteuse's ``Love in the Round''
tour. And while his name may be as common as Sleaman's Cream Ale
north of the border, the Quebec-born funnyman knows it's a
different story down here.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Americans hear that Andre-Philippe Gagnon is on the show,
they get confused,'' says the comedian, calling from a Calgary,
Alberta, hotel. ``There's this element of surprise the first five
minutes: `Who is this French-Canadian with the thick accent?' But
the accent disappears when I sing, and the mood starts to build up.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end, I have people on their feet, applauding, so I've
warmed them up. They're ready to welcome Celine and to party.''
</P>
<P>
   Judging from his mammoth press kit, the whole Gagnon story seems
to be a veritable phenomenon. A shy kid in French-speaking Canada
watches Tweety Bird cartoons on a daily basis. He doesn't
understand the words, but he learns to do a pretty fine imitation
of the lippy canary.
</P>
<P>
   Pretty soon, the kid is imitating teachers, friends,
celebrities. He grows up, hits the Canadian comedy circuit. A 1985
gig on ``The Tonight Show'' launches him into the front ranks north
of the border and in France, although U.S. fame has yet to
materialize.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've done shows at the Comedy Store and in Vegas,'' says
Gagnon, a genuinely friendly type. ``The shows in America don't
give you the same exposure. In Canada, I sell out 4,000-seat
theaters. Then you play to 30 people at the Comedy Store, so it's
different.''
</P>
<P>
   He's hoping that the current tour will raise his American
profile. Plus, the U.S. tour works out well for him. When he was
focusing on the French-speaking world, he was a young guy with no
commitments. Now he's 37, a married man with two small kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've neglected the States for some time,'' he admits. ``Things
were going so well in France, and I was traveling a lot. But now,
the traveling is easier if we stay in North America because I can
see my family more.''
</P>
<P>
   His repertoire has grown to include more than 400 voices. It's
tempting to call him a Canadian Rich Little, until you remember
that Rich Little was born in Ottawa. Still, Gagnon probably is the
most famous impressionist of his generation working in his homeland
today.
</P>
<P>
   Gagnon doesn't offer up many impressions on the phone _ he's
resting his voice before a gig. But the concepts sound funny. His
big number is a re-creation of ``We Are the World,'' in which he
handles all the different celebrity voices. He does
``Unforgettable,'' a la Natalie and Nat King Cole. There's Roger
Whittaker singing heavy metal and Metallica performing nursery
rhymes.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, there is the whole different-culture thing to deal
with. Gino Vannelli and Gordon Lightfoot impressions probably won't
inspire big belly laughs at the Purple Palace. And no matter how
good a Pierre Trudeau joke is, it's still a Pierre Trudeau joke.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm in front of Canadians, it's a little different,'' he
says. ``When I'm in front of Americans, I do their Top 40. I tell
stories about the parallels in the culture. It all works out. If
something doesn't work, I've taken it out of the show by now.''
</P>
<P>
   And no, he won't do any Celine impersonations in the show. He
used to do her back in her child-star days, before she crossed over
to English-speaking audiences. But now he offers only kind words
for the titanic-voiced singer.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's so talented and so generous,'' he says. ``She works so
hard. It's no wonder why she's such a success. We're all like a big
family to her _ she takes the time to say hi to everybody on the
tour. It's a two-way situation _ she loves them and we love her.''
</P>
<P>
   OK, he's talking about his boss. Still, the sentiment sounds
sincere. And for a guy who has been in the limelight for more than
a decade, he sounds remarkably grounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I found out that someone in Arizona wanted to talk to
me,'' Gagnon confesses, ``I thought it had to be some kind of
joke.''
</P>
<P>
   Nope. After the concert Sunday, (Oct. 25) the joke will be on
those Celine Dion fans still wondering, ``Who the hell is
Andre-Philippe Gagnon?'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
