<HEADER>
A1623 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-MAURENSIG-BOS &LR;      10-22 0877
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-MAURENSIG-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUSIC AS A METAPHOR MAKES FOR COMPELLING FICTION
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD DYER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CANONE INVERSO &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By Paolo Maurensig &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Translated from Italian by Jenny McPhee &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Holt, 202 pp. $21 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Paolo Maurensig was past 50 when he wrote his first novel, ``The
Lueneberg Variation,'' which enthralled an international literary
audience a couple of years ago. His second, ``Canone Inverso,'' is
another fable or metafiction at least as compelling as its
predecessor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lueneberg Variation'' used chess as subject and metaphor
for history; for ``Canone Inverso'' Maurensig uses music for the
same purpose. This is a subject Maurensig can write about from
within, because he plays Baroque flute, viola da gamba, and cello,
and one of his earlier careers was as a restorer of old
instruments.
</P>
<P>
   On one level, ``Canone Inverso'' is a story about two young men
and a violin. Jeno Varga is a musician of promise, maybe of genius,
the illegitimate son of a Hungarian peasant woman; his only
connection to the father he never knew is a violin, an unusual
instrument with ``a tiny anthropomorphic head carved into the top
of the pegbox, where one usually finds the traditional scroll. ...
This (head) was a very precise reproduction of a man's face,
perhaps a Mameluke, with a drooping mustache, a ferocious
expression, and a wide-open mouth, as if he were screaming in pain
or anguish.''
</P>
<P>
   We follow Jeno through his early affinity for the violin, to the
beginning of serious studies, to his infatuation with the great
violinist Sophie Hirschbaum. Then he arrives at an isolated and
prestigious Austrian musical school, the Schola Cantorum, which is
a cross between a monastery and a labor camp. There Jeno meets
another young violinist, Kuno Blau, a young aristocrat who is
everything he is not. The two, for a time, find common ground in
music, and Jeno goes to visit Kuno in the Tyrolean family castle,
Hofstain. There the friendship of the two young men both reaches
its apex and begins to unravel _ Jeno is a better musician and
violinist than Kuno, and the differences in their backgrounds seem
obscurely hostile, not complementary. ``Without my being aware, our
friendship, which had risen to its supreme fulfillment in an
original burst of mutual genius, had already, and for some time,
begun its descent, its countdown, or, to use a musical term, its
canone inverso.'' (A canone inverso is one in which the second
voice is the first one played upside down; Maurensig's canon seems
to be both upside down and moving backward, in retrograde).
</P>
<P>
   There is much thoughtful discussion among the residents of
Hofstain, and the discussions are repeatedly interrupted by ugly
incidents of rivalry and betrayal that unfold in an atmosphere of
strange family secrets. Nothing is uglier, however, than a concert
Jeno later attends in Vienna, when Hirschbaum is booed for daring
to play the Violin Concerto by Mendelssohn. ``It was an anonymous
crowd, attracted, in its stupidity, to a sign of power, to
something that promised to satisfy its repressed base instincts, a
crowd that had come, in a sort of sleepwalker's stupor, to take
part in a lynching, a public execution. It was a crowd that
rumbled, and came together in order to see what was going on, a
bobbing crowd that was moving ... toward perdition, turning their
backs on salvation, blindly aiming toward the place of their own
annihilation. I extracted myself from those bodies and went to the
front of the theater. Scraps of paper were scattered over the steps
leading up to the entrance. Posters and notices had been ripped
from the walls and covered with offensive graffiti and swastikas.''
</P>
<P>
   Maurensig unfolds this tale with an elegant, beguiling, and
meaningful complexity: There are stories within stories, and
everything reverberates. The book opens in the 1980s, when the
first narrator has just been reunited with a strange and familiar
violin he has bought at auction at Christie's. A second narrator, a
writer, arrives too late for the auction, and tries to buy the
violin because he has heard something of its story from an old
itinerant fiddler named Jeno; for the writer, the existence of the
violin affirms the truth of the ``terrible story'' he has heard,
which he repeats to the violin's new owner, mostly in Jeno's words.
By the end, we have learned who the violin's new owner is, and in
the last couple of pages, in a document that has come into his
possession, we learn a fact about Jeno and Kuno that makes it
necessary to reexamine the whole book, and its meaning.
</P>
<P>
   Until the end approaches, that single word ``swastikas'' is the
only direct reference to the history that surrounds Jeno and Kuno
and that is about to engulf them, but just about everything in the
story of the two men is a probe into that history, its causes, its
meaning, and its consequences. The writer says he wants to ``get to
the end'' of the story he is investigating; there is no way to get
to the end of history, but you can encompass it, illuminate it,
wrestle it into a kind of order, even if the order is as complex as
a canone inverso, and that's what Paolo Maurensig has accomplished.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
