<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1628 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROCK-MORISSETTE-BOS &LR;      10-22 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCK-MORISSETTE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINGER REVEALS A QUIETER SIDE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Following a blockbuster album is an almost impossible task.
Whether you're Michael Jackson, U2, Madonna _ or Alanis Morissette
_ it can be a thankless job, though no one is going to shed any
tears for you. It's now Morissette's turn to give it a go, as she
prepares to follow up her 28-million-selling ``Jagged Little Pill''
album with the strangely titled ``Supposed Former Infatuation
Junkie,'' which hits record store shelves Nov. 3.
</P>
<P>
   She's previewing it with a club tour that drew a sold-out crowd
of 1,500 fanatics to Avalon Thursday night. They may have come to
hear Morissette pick up from the ``angry young woman'' image that
suffused her last album, but what they got was a more mature, more
inwardly calm, but still terrific, performer.
</P>
<P>
   Morissette crammed nine new songs into her 90-minute set _ many
of them still hard to fathom because the audience and this critic
had not yet digested them _ but the most significant moment was
actually on an older song, ``You Oughta Know,'' a once-angry anthem
that had been defused dramatically. It was obvious that Morissette
no longer had the heart to sing it venomously, which tells a lot
about where she is today.
</P>
<P>
   Having taken a long time off, during which she traveled to and
meditated in India, Morissette is clearly a different, more evolved
person. She said nothing to the crowd other than ``thank you''
after every number, but she didn't have to. It was apparent in her
manner and in many of her new songs, which have a slower, more
pensive air, and ride a rhythm of grooves, rather than the
guitar-steeped, rock 'n' roll intensity of the aptly named ``Jagged
Little Pill.''
</P>
<P>
   Dressed in a black and silver T-shirt, a maroon, India-print
skirt, with her hair in a pigtail dangling to her waist, Morissette
performed in front of a curtain that contained the bold-printed
words: ``We ask you to abide by the following moral code upon the
premises: Please refrain from killing.'' The same saying was on her
T-shirts for sale at the gig, which had the further embellishment
of asking that you refrain from ``lying, stealing, sexual
misconduct, and taking intoxicants.''
</P>
<P>
   Morissette opened with new track ``Baba,'' which questions the
pursuit of gurus. ``How soon will I be holy? How much does this
cost, guru?'' she asked in the song, as she built to an
open-throated wail and let her band (now five pieces with the
addition of a groove-stoking keyboardist) take over.
</P>
<P>
   She switched to acoustic guitar for the new ``Can't Not'' (which
asked gently, ``Would I be whining if I asked for a hug?'') and the
new, more rocking ``Would Not Come,'' in which she wondered, ``If
I'm masculine, I will be taken more seriously.'' And in the new
``Sympathetic Character,'' she sang, ``I was afraid of your
testosterone.'' These underscored a new vulnernability, rather than
the armored attack of her last disc.
</P>
<P>
   Morissette, who was in great voice and was setting the table for
an arena tour to follow this winter, reached back for oldies ``Hand
in My Pocket'' and ``All I Really Want,'' but the focus was
definitely on the new. In yet another new tune, ``Joining You,''
she concluded, ``We need reflection.'' And that's as good a summary
of her new path as any.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-98 1517EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
