<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 15:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1631 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CELINEDION-MUSIC-AZR &LR;      10-22 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELINE </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DIVINE MISS DION?  
 (ADV: WITH GAGNON-COMIC) 
</HEADLINE>
 DION-MUSIC-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDY CORDOVA  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The gushing tone was undeniable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Celine Dion is just incredible,'' the woman on the phone said.
``She is such a (begin ital) diva. (end ital)''
</P>
<P>
   It made me pause. Celine Dion is a lot of things. Wildly
successful, sure. Canadian, of course. Multilingual, (begin ital)
oui. (end ital) But a diva? I think not.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's because VH1 recently included her in its ``Divas
Live'' special. Maybe it's just that she's a woman who sings with
all the subtlety of a bulldozer.
</P>
<P>
   But a classic, true-blue diva? Pardon me, but the sparkly gown
of divadom simply does not fit on the 30-year-old singer's petite
frame. In a few years, who knows? Right now, though, she's simply a
nice woman with a great set of pipes and a cute accent.
</P>
<P>
   To attain true divaness, a few requirements must be met. It's
like passing a driving test. It separates the women from the girls.
It's the difference between a Madonna and a Sheena Easton.
</P>
<P>
   Here's a quick rundown on the holy triumvirate of divadom. A
woman can achieve diva status without all three, but a minimum of
two is absolutely essential.
</P>
<P>
   - Attitude: Divas have it down pat, baby. They take no bull.
They pull no punches. It's two snaps up and then they're out.
</P>
<P>
   Divas can be nice women, but there's that snappish edge that
comes out at the oddest times. A classic diva moment: Diana Ross
grabbing the microphone away from Mary Wilson during the ``Motown
25'' anniversary special. ``Reach Out and Touch Somebody's Hand''?
I'll reach out, honey.
</P>
<P>
   Other examples: Barbra Streisand, Courtney Love, Claudine
Longet, Kathleen Battle, Patti LaBelle.
</P>
<P>
   - Survival instinct: Nothing stops true divas. There is no
obstacle they cannot overcome. They will endure anything and come
out singing. That's one reason Judy Garland is the mother of all
divas: She went through almost every conceivable hell and still
performed ``Over the Rainbow'' with a touching believability. Plus,
it gives divas a good reason to shed actual tears on a concert
stage.
</P>
<P>
   Other examples: Gloria Estefan, Connie Francis, Rosemary
Clooney, Billie Holiday, Edith Piaf, Liza Minnelli, Tina Turner.
</P>
<P>
   - Sheer fabulosity: You've heard the expression ``Miss Thang?''
Divas not only know it _ they live it. They think they (begin ital)
are (end ital) it. There is nothing more pleasing than hearing the
sound of their own voice, which is one reason they love to indulge
in vocal acrobatics even if it has nothing to do with the song they
are singing.
</P>
<P>
   That's why insecurity doesn't work with this aspect of divadom.
She must be big and brash. She's so over-the-top she should play
only in open-air arenas. A shy diva is an oxymoron. A diva is not a
fly on the wall; she's the life of the party. Bette Midler is a
one-woman amusement park, while Paula Cole could have a lampshade
on her head and you still wouldn't notice her.
</P>
<P>
   Other examples: Whitney Houston, Mariah Carey, Minnie Riperton,
Vikki Carr, Shirley Bassey, Cher.
</P>
<P>
   See? It's simply a little too early for Celine to come to the
party. It doesn't have to do with age _ Brandy has already made it
and she's not out of her teens yet. It has more to do with
experience, with style, with pure ``it''-ness.
</P>
<P>
   Celine may be on her way, but she's not there yet. Give her time
_ and some lessons from RuPaul _ and who knows? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
