<HEADLINE>
THERE ARE WAYS TO GET BETTER MATCHES IN BONE MARROW TRANSPLANTS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JUDY FOREMAN 
c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two new studies published in the recent New England Journal of
Medicine show that bone marrow transplantion can be refined to get
better matches between unrelated donors and recipients, and better
outcomes between partially mismatched, related donors.
</P>
<P>
   The studies, one by Japanese researchers and one by an
Israeli-Italian team, ``are milestones in our quest to find bone
marrow donors for all our patients,'' Dutch researchers noted in an
editorial. ``It is equally clear,'' they added, ``that many other
milestones will have to be passed before not only all patients have
donors, but also all are cured.''
</P>
<P>
   In bone marrow transplantation, marrow cells or so-called stem
cells from another person or stored cells from the patient himself
are used to reconstitute the patient's own bone marrow after it is
destroyed by chemotherapy or radiation. About 30,000 such
transplants are performed a year worldwide, and in many the patient
acts as his own donor.
</P>
<P>
   When it is necessary to use cells from another person, the best
matches are between identical twins, although matches involving
other family members, or even strangers whose blood is similar to
the patient's, are sometimes close enough.
</P>
<P>
   In the Japanese study, 440 patients, most of whom had leukemia,
received transplants from unrelated donors. The team showed that
even when standard antibody tests showed donors and recipients
carried identical markers called HLA-A, HLA-B, and HLA-DR, more
precise tests of DNA revealed small but important differences.
``Genomic typing'' of HLA ``adds substantially to the success of
transplantation,'' the researchers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a deeper way of identifying'' matches and ``should
become state of the art,'' says Dr. Jerome Groopman, chief of
experimental medicine at Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   In the Italian-Israeli study, 43 leukemia patients received
transplants from related donors. In each case, half of the donor's
HLA markers were a good match with the recipient's and half were
not. Often, this degree of mismatch causes the donated cells to
attack the recipient (graft versus host disease, or GVHD) or leads
to failure of the graft to ``take.''
</P>
<P>
   In this study, the researchers boosted production of stem cells
in the donors with a drug called G-CSF, then removed ``T cells''
before transplantation to reduce the chance of GVHD. Despite the
mismatches, the transplants took and did not cause GVHD.
</P>
<P>
   The mortality rate was high _ 40 percent _ and the researchers
tracked survivors for only 18 months. That all the grafts took is a
``tremendous achievement,'' said Dr. Claudio Anasetti, director of
the unrelated donor transplant program at the Fred Hutchinson
Cancer Research Center in Seattle. But the fact that recipients end
up with no T-cells is a ``major drawback.'' T-cells are crucial for
immune defense, and the body's ability to make new ones is limited
after age 15.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Prostate patients fare well off drug &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Men with metastatic prostate cancer who have been surgically
castrated are sometimes given the drug flutamide to block a hormone
that can drive the cancer. But a new study published this week in
the Journal of the National Cancer Institute shows that they're
better off without it.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers from the Southwest Oncology Group Statistical Center
in Seattle found that men given a placebo had a better quality of
life _ less diarrhea and better emotional functioning _ than those
who got flutamide. There were nearly 400 men in each group. Data
from the study also showed that combining the drug with surgical
castration had no significant survival benefit.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Boxers or briefs, sperm don't know &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Remember those old wives' tales that tight underwear could raise
the temperature of the testes enough to lower sperm counts and
ultimately, fertility? Well, forget it, say two urologists writing
in the October issue of the Journal of Urology.
</P>
<P>
   With a colleague, Dr. Bruce Gilbert, a urologist at the State
University of New York at Stonybrook, examined 100 men and measured
core body temperature as well as the temperature of scrotum and
forearm skin. They compared these temperatures to the type of
underwear the men wore _ boxers or briefs.
</P>
<P>
   The conclusion? While heat does affect sperm production, the
type of underwear does not influence scrotal temperature. ``So it
doesn't matter whether you wear boxers or briefs,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Judy Foreman writes about health and medicine for the Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
