<HEADLINE>
A COUPLE OF TOOLS MAKE USING THE INTERNET FASTER, SOMETIMES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HIAWATHA BRAY  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Like everyone else, I often wait in frustrated
anticipation for a Web page to appear on my computer screen. But I
don't waste empty minutes playing electronic solitaire. I prefer
the game called Figuring It Out. Why is my Internet connection so
slow? Why is this particular Web site so sluggish?
</P>
<P>
   These aren't simple questions. The Internet actually is
thousands of networks woven together; there are so many possible
points of failure, it's a wonder the thing works at all. But if you
can figure out why you're having trouble getting through to a Web
site or receiving e-mail, you may be able to sidestep the problem,
and get some work done.
</P>
<P>
   Which is why I don't go surfing without those basic tools of the
network engineer: a couple of programs called Ping and Traceroute.
These are pieces of software that'll tell you how quickly your
machine is communicating with some other computer on the network.
</P>
<P>
   Ping and Traceroute were developed years ago for use with Unix,
an operating system designed from the ground up for use in
networks. Now that we're all hopping onto the Internet, every
serious PC or Mac user should also have Ping and Traceroute in his
toolkit.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of you already do, without knowing it. In a rare act of
modesty, Microsoft Corp. added Ping and Traceroute to Windows 95
and 98, without advertising the fact. I stumbled across them by
accident three years ago. Mac users aren't quite as lucky, but Ping
and Traceroute software for the Mac can be downloaded off the 'Net
at no charge.
</P>
<P>
   What do they do? Consider their names. Ping sounds like the
sonar in a submarine warfare movie, right? That's the idea. Ping
sends out a special data packet to any Internet server computer you
choose. All Internet servers are programmed to echo this type of
packet back to its source, like sonar bouncing off a ship. The
sending computer calculates the packet's travel time, measured in
milliseconds.
</P>
<P>
   Anything under 400 milliseconds is fine, but you can get one- or
two-second times when the network is really running slow, and if
the server is down, you'll get no response at all. Can't get
through to yourfavoritesite.com? ``Pinging'' the site is a quick
and dirty way to see whether it's up and running. On a Windows PC,
just open up a DOS window and type ``ping'' and the address of the
site.
</P>
<P>
   Say your site pings you back, but very slowly. What's causing
the slowdown? Traceroute can help you figure it out. Every Internet
packet passes through a number of router computers on its way to
its destination. Often a slow router will delay your message.
Traceroute can pinpoint the problem by pinging each router along
the path, and timing its response. Again, your wait should be less
than 400 milliseconds. To try this on a Windows PC, type
``tracert'' and the site address.
</P>
<P>
   If you're not satisfied with the Windows versions of these
tools, there are a bunch of programs on the Web that do the same
thing. The coolest of the PC offerings is NeoTrace, a $19.50
Traceroute program that actually draws you a map of your Internet
connections. For a free trial, go to http://www.neoworx.com.
Macintosh users can try WhatRoute, a free Ping and Traceroute
program available for download at
http://mac.org/internet/whatroute. And if you don't feel like
loading up new software, there are Web sites that provide on-line
Traceroute services at no charge. Just type in the server name, and
let somebody else's machine do the work. To find these sites, go to
http://www.yahoo.com and search under ``traceroute.''
</P>
<P>
   What good is all this information? Even if you find that you're
getting hung up on a router in San Francisco, there's not a lot you
can do about it _ unless you've got more than one Internet
provider. But at least you know.
</P>
<P>
   And if your work requires you to have Internet access, you ought
to have at least two ways of getting on-line. I maintain America
Online and CompuServe accounts, and a Web hosting account with
Concentric Network in California, because this gives me access to
several different Internet backbones. When one is crawling, another
is screaming. And with the help of Ping and Traceroute, anybody can
figure out which is which. It beats the heck out of playing
solitaire.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   You can send electronic mail to Hiawatha Bray at
bray(at)globe.com
</P>
</TEXT>
