<SLUG> BC-CONNIEFRANCI-MUSIC-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TO KNOW SINGER CONNIE FRANCIS IS TO FEEL HER PAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By RANDY CORDOVA  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - Rock-and-roll stardom, drug addiction, mental illness,
violent crime _ it was just a matter of time before someone made a
documentary about Connie Francis.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, the Arts and Entertainment channel took up the task of
telling the singer's story, so ``Connie Francis: America's
Sweetheart ofSong'' (airing Sunday) manages to be revealing without
being too sordid. Lord knows how the E! channel would have handled
it.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the life of the biggest-selling female singer in
history unravels rather politely. An unflappable Shelley Fabares
serves as narrator, coating even the disturbing aspects of Francis'
life with a sensible ``niceness.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the frankness of the project is surprising, especially
considering that the hourlong show was made with the assistance of
the 59-year-old vocalist and members of her family. If this is the
``approved'' version, an unauthorized take could be positively
hellish.
</P>
<P>
   Francis' immigrant father is described as a controlling tyrant
who never wanted kids and torpedoed her romance with Bobby Darin.
The singer's four failed marriages are carefully documented, as is
her longtime battle with pill addiction.
</P>
<P>
   It grows even darker. The mob-related killing of her brother is
rehashed, with home movies showing the young man relaxing in his
pool. It gives a sad face to the tragic crime.
</P>
<P>
   The singer's aunt recalls Francis' headline-making 1974 rape in
harrowing detail. When she talks about the vocalist coming home
from the police station, tearfully crouching in the back seat of
her father's car, it's almost too intimate, a secret that should
have stayed in the family.
</P>
<P>
   With all the dark moments in Francis' life, the show winds up
giving short shrift to the music, the thing that made her so
appealing in the first place. She was the dominant female singer in
the late '50s and early '60s, racking up 16 Top 10 hits in a
spectacular reign.
</P>
<P>
   She had a big, confident voice that could sing anything. She
could belt out a rock-and-roll song (``Lipstick on Your Collar'')
or weepily handle a heartbreak ballad (``Among My Souvenirs''). She
had hits in 16 different languages, and her repertoire ranged from
1920s standards (``Who's Sorry Now'') to Neil Sedaka bubblegum
(``Stupid Cupid'').
</P>
<P>
   It was both a blessing and a curse for Francis to be a superstar
in her day. She was exactly what America needed: optimistic,
clean-cut and personable, someone both kids and their parents could
like.
</P>
<P>
   But she was huge during a time that most people forget when
looking back at pop music. She came after Elvis but before the
Beatles, an era usually dismissed with an indifferent shrug.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, a friend says that Francis became known as ``the
woman who was raped rather than the No. 1 female vocalist in the
world.'' Unfortunately, this show doesn't shift the attention back
to where it rightly belongs. Maybe the producers needed another
hour to do that.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most poignant aspect of the entire program is seeing
how Francis has been affected by the pitfalls in her life. Grainy
black-and-white footage reveals a striking woman with
girl-next-door good looks and a sunny, confident personality.
</P>
<P>
   The mature Francis seems distant and uneasy, speaking in a
scratchy monotone that sounds nothing like the starlet who
frolicked on the beach in ``Where the Boys Are.'' With her hair a
deep red and her appearance modified by plastic surgery, it's hard
to connect the two images.
</P>
<P>
   Even the singing voice is different. It's not only because of
age, but due to a botched nose job that permanently marred her
vocal range.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there's a moment in ``Connie Francis: America's
Sweetheart of Song'' that shows the contemporary Francis grabbing a
microphone and endearingly singing ``You Made Me Love You.'' It may
not be the voice we remember, but it is the voice of a survivor. &QL; 
 &QL; 
Randy Cordova can be reached at randy.cordova(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
