<HEADLINE>
CHINESE SPEAKERS CAN RECAST BALLOTS IN SAN FRANCISCO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DIANA WALSH  
 c.1998 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Thousands of Chinese-speaking voters who
received ballots for the November election that did not list the
Chinese names of seven San Francisco candidates will have a chance
to recast their ballots.
</P>
<P>
   Under a compromise ordered by a Superior Court judge, the city
agreed Wednesday to mail letters to 3,000 Chinese-speaking voters
telling them that they could vote over if they had difficulty
finding their preferred candidates on their ballots.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the mass mailing, acting Registrar of Voters
Naomi Nishioka will take out ads in four Chinese-language daily
newspapers alerting voters of the offer to recast their ballots.
</P>
<P>
   The deal was made after three candidates for the Board of
Supervisors _ Mabel Teng, Carlota del Portillo and Victor Marquez _
filed suit against the city for not putting their
Chinese-translated names off the absentee ballots.
</P>
<P>
   Although Judge Ronald Evan Quidachay denied their original
request to have a correction letter sent to all 52,000 voters in
the city who requested an absentee ballot, the plaintiffs declared
the compromise an overwhelming victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a landmark decision ... that ensures a fair and
constitutional election,'' Teng said. ``This is about the right for
Chinese-speaking voters to be able to participate in an election
with full information. It is defending bilingual voting.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Teng and her attorneys called the omission an error,
Nishioka placed the blame with the candidates and their campaigns.
The registrar's office is required only to offer Chinese and
Spanish translations of occupations and other designations on the
ballot. The translation of names, which has been used during only
one other city election, in 1995, is an optional courtesy provided
by the registrar.
</P>
<P>
   Nishioka said her office had twice called Teng's campaign to see
whether the supervisor wanted her name printed in Chinese on the
ballot and been told no both times. Nonetheless, Nishioka, who
maintained that her office did not have the time or staffing to
complete the more extensive mailing to all absentee voters, said
she hoped that the compromise would have positive results.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe it was necessary, but since we have agreed to
it, we will abide by it,'' Nishioka said. ``If it helps bring
additional voters, we will be pleased.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the compromise, Chinese-speaking absentee voters can
recast a ballot if they take the registrar's letter to Nishioka's
office. Once there, they must sign a declaration stating that they
were unable to vote for the candidate of their choice because their
ballot lacked the proper transliteration.
</P>
<P>
   The election is Nov. 3.
</P>
</TEXT>
