<P>
   The New York Times News Service calls your attention to the
following automotive features moved during the last week.
</P>
<P>
   For retransmission of these stories, call 888-346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   ABOUT-CARS-ODYSSEY-NYT (Detroit) _ Honda has arrived at the
minivan party with a new model, the 1999 Odyssey, which is even
more magical than Chrysler's offerings, and Chrysler faces its
toughest competition yet. By Michelle Krebs. With Photo.
</P>
<P>
   CAR-PRICE-COMPETITION-BLOOM (Los Angeles) _ Car shoppers are
finding that U.S. prices for 1999-model cars and trucks are holding
mostly steady as automakers grapple with excess supply, the growing
popularity of used models and more overseas competition. By
Joyzelle Davis.
</P>
<P>
   LUXURY-CARS (Undated) _ How did Lexus, even with designs that
are often called bland, become one of the top-selling American
luxury cars, behind only Lincoln, Cadillac and Mercedes? By Sharon
R. King.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-FUELS-NYT (Detroit) _ Struggling to comply with federal
fuel-economy and emissions regulations even as Americans buy ever
bigger family vehicles, automakers have quietly begun experiments
with oil companies to develop new and potentially cleaner fuels. By
Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-US-AUTOS-BLOOM (Washington) _ South Korea has agreed to
scrap barriers that have made the world's fifth-largest car market
inhospitable to U.S. automakers, U.S. trade officials said. By Todd
R. Eastham and Emily Schwartz.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-FOREIGN-AUTOMAKERS-BLOOM (Detroit) _ International
automakers said they've doubled their investment to $21 billion in
U.S. plants and equipment since 1992, a major reason they now
account for 34 percent of U.S. passenger car production.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-REVIEW-BOS (Hershey, Pa.) _ To the regulars in the old-car
hobby who flock here every October, the event is simply known as
``Hershey.'' It is difficult to comprehend the immensity of this
rite of autumn where Hershey Park, a vast complex of stadium,
amusement park, factory store, and even vaster grassy fields
separated by roads is turned into a tent city of 28,000 souls
overnight. Suddenly this pretty little company town is home to a
sprawling refugee camp cum junkyard wherein you may find parts for
obscure autos, whole vehicles, automobilia, and such diverse
offerings as musical instruments, boats, pedal cars, cameras,
lamps, gas pumps, an occasional boat _ once an airplane. By John R.
White.
</P>
<P>
   AUTOS-COLUMN-BOS (Undated) _ Toyota, dropping the kid gloves in
the truck market, unveiled a new weapon for a fresh assault on
full-size pickup market share for the New England Motor Press
Association this week. The truck, dubbed Tundra, is to be a
no-nonsense competitor with a 245-horsepower (315 ft/lb torque),
32-valve, double overhead cam low-emissions V-8 under the hood, a
one-ton load capacity, and the ability to tow 7,200 pounds. By John
R. White.
</P>
<P>
   CARS-WILLIAMS-COLUMN-TEX (Undated) _ When Toyota needed a
sport-utility vehicle to supplement its line of Lexus luxury cars,
it didn't have to look further than its own Toyota Land Cruiser to
come up with the full-size Lexus LX 450. By G. Chambers Williams
III.
</P>
