<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-HAPPINESS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN PURSUIT OF `HAPPINESS'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There probably isn't another director working who has made a
style of ambivalence in the way Todd Solondz has. With ``Welcome to
the Dollhouse,'' which followed an outcast Jersey preteen girl at a
difficult time in her life, his deadpan direction kept people
off-guard. His newest film, ``Happiness,'' is sure to provoke even
more conversation. He clearly wants to subvert, and cheat, the
expectation that a movie should make audiences feel one thing at a
time _ laughter, sadness, outrage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Happiness'' follows a group of people whose connection to each
other is revealed as the film plays out. We see a gentle, smiling
young woman (Jane Adams) trying to let down a suitor (Jon Lovitz),
and the moment, with all of its good intentions, goes horribly
wrong. He goes from blubbering to acid hostility in a heartbeat,
and she doesn't know which way to look. It's a scene that sums up
the contradictory ideas of ``Happiness'' instantly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Happiness'' _ an ironic title if ever there was one _ then
examines this group connected by sticky threads of suburban
gossamer. Philip Seymour Hoffman is a sweaty pervert seeing a bored
psychiatrist (Dylan Baker). The object of Hoffman's deviant
fantasies is his next-door neighbor (Lara Flynn Boyle), a glam poet
who brings new men into her life so often you'd swear they had
expiration dates stamped on some part of their anatomy. Boyle also
happens to be Baker's sister-in-law. Boyle's married sister
(Cynthia Stevenson) is a chirpy suburban mom who goes on about
having it all _ a comfy home, three kids and a loving husband. She
doesn't quite have her husband; when Baker's not confessing
homicidal fantasies to his own shrink, he's confecting drugged
treats to give to neighborhood boys so that he can molest them.
</P>
<P>
   Adams is sister to Boyle and Stevenson, and the three of them
are trying to comfort their mother (Louise Lasser), because her
husband (Ben Gazzara) is walking out on her after a 40-year,
loveless marriage. Like Adams in that very first scene, you may not
know where to look or how to react. Solondz is out to create a
world filled with people whose existences are so fogged by
self-absorption they can't recognize happiness.
</P>
<P>
   It doesn't matter if the characters are right-minded people or
not; they end up walking into a wall. All except Boyle, whose
movie-star slinkiness seems to guarantee her the least amount of
hurt. Although Solondz does fill his films with regular-looking
people, and he pokes at the tyranny of a looks-obsessed culture, he
seems as much a slave to it as anyone else. There are scenes with
Hoffman and Camryn Manheim, as his other neighbor, who's needy and
overeager, that play just like scenes from ``Marty,'' except the
audience chortles at these two pathetic people who are lonely even
when they dance together _ the joke is underscored by Air Supply's
middlebrow lilt, ``All Out of Love.''
</P>
<P>
   Solondz isn't out to extort a reaction. Instead, he practices a
remote touch that can add a grayness to the proceedings, even
though he's not being judgmental. So the scenes with Adams bouncing
from one kind of suffering to another are treated with the same
lack of affect that he gives to Baker's weird, patient explanations
of sexual function with his 12-year-old son. Or later, to Baker's
final confessions of his behavior to his son, which leave the boy
crushed and confused. Because Solondz doesn't lead you to a
conclusion, you may find yourself angered by the implicit
compassion he shows Baker, who emerges as a sympathetic figure
because of his performance. Or you may find Solondz's lack of
insistence refreshing. Then again, you may find yourself just as
ambivalent about these characters as Solondz seems to be, which may
strike you as a cheat, because lack of perspective can often betray
a lack of interest in developing insight. It felt like a cop-out to
me.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Film: ``Happiness''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 3 on a scale of 5
</P>
<P>
   Director: Todd Solondz
</P>
<P>
   Featuring: Lara Flynn Boyle, Dylan Baker, Philip Seymour Hoffman
</P>
<P>
   Unrated _ scenes of aberrant sexual behavior that makes it
suitable for adults only
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
