<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-BOOKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGH-TECH HISTORIES MAY OFFER INSPIRATION FOR BUSINESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TERESA MCUSIC 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   To grow the economy, the government has to continue to think
big.
</P>
<P>
   That's the history lesson to be drawn from Thomas Hughes'
``Rescuing Prometheus'' (Pantheon Books, $28.50, 372 pages). The
book chronicles the development, execution and long-term impact of
four massive post-World War II projects with the size and scale to
spark creative thinking that could affect the way the commercial
sector does business for decades to come.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes, a Pulitzer Prize finalist for his book, ``American
Genesis: A Century of Invention and Technological Enthusiasm,''
extends his efforts at chronicling the history of technology
development with his new title.
</P>
<P>
   The book provides an in-depth look at the creation of the
pioneering Semiautomatic Ground Environment, or SAGE, defense
system; the first intercontiental ballistic missile, called Atlas;
a major highway construction project that is burrowing a tunnel
under the city of Boston; and the computer network that laid the
foundation for today's Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The common thread tying those projects together is their
complexity. By solving problems on a grand scale, managers and
engineers have had to come up with new approaches that created
solutions that could be applied in the business world.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the whole notion of systems engineering _ the
practice of designing different pieces of a complex machine at the
same time _ made significant strides because of the SAGE project.
Likewise, the Atlas project _ carried out in the 1950s at the
height of the Cold War _ provided a glimpse at how project leaders
can cut through red tape to speed the development of a crucial
defense system.
</P>
<P>
   ``The billions of dollars expended on SAGE and Atlas provided
the engineers, scientists, and managers physical and personnel
resources of quantity and quality unprecedented in the long history
of technology,'' Hughes writes. ``Such support emboldened them to
tackle enormously complicated problems. The creative problem
solving they did for SAGE and Atlas proved an exhilarating
experience for many of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately for the reader, much of that exhilaration does not
transfer to the pages of ``Rescuing Prometheus.'' The sheer size of
the projects described practically dictates that decisions are made
by committees, a setting that hardly sets the stage for gripping
narrative.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Hughes describes a series of committee decisions and
how they came to be made. As it turns out, reading about a
committee is probably about just as interesting as sitting on one.
Hughes' authoritative work provides telling detail about the
individual projects he describes, but they are stories more likely
to be useful to students writing a historical summary of the
efforts rather than a casual reader seeking smooth-reading insight.
</P>
<P>
   Hughes does as well as he can in describing the context that
propels the projects to their historical significance, but the
description of the process behind the projects is probably reading
that only a historian, engineer or bureaucrat would love.
</P>
<P>
   For a more lively look at the internal workings of a big
government project of the modern era, try ``Managing Martians,'' by
Donna Shirley with Danelle Morton (Broadway Books, $25, 276 pages).
</P>
<P>
   Shirley headed the team that designed and built the 25-pound
robot Sojourner rover that sent those incredible pictures of Mars
back to Earth in July 1997.
</P>
<P>
   The book describes that historic space mission, Pathfinder, with
a riveting first-person account from the landing of the spacecraft
on Independence Day back to when the ideas were first being
bantered about.
</P>
<P>
   The book is also quite autobiographical, following Shirley's
life from a small town in Oklahoma to her experience as one of the
first female aeronautical engineers at the University of Oklahoma
and then in the work world beyond.
</P>
<P>
   BLURBS
</P>
<P>
   ``The Cost of Caring: Money Skills for Caregivers''
</P>
<P>
   By Anne M. Johnson and Ruth Rejnis
</P>
<P>
   John Wiley &AMP; Sons, $14.95
</P>
<P>
   It's estimated that there are 50 million caregivers in the
United States, people working full or part time to take care of
someone else, generally a family member. Of that group, around 38
million are also in the work force. Caregivers need a lot of help,
and this book shows you there is a lot of help out there. Caregiver
associations have been formed on the local, regional and a national
levels, and more than 3,000 sites on the Internet are devoted to
caregivers. The book focuses on topics from tax deductions to wills
for those caring for others.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``How to Start, Run and Stay in Business: The Nuts-and-Bolts
Guide to Turning Your Business into a Reality''
</P>
<P>
   By Gregory and Patricia Kishel
</P>
<P>
   John Wiley &AMP; Sons, $14.95
</P>
<P>
   Now in its third edition, this is one of the bibles for
entrepreneurs. The book analyzes the upsides and downsides of
running your own business, then asks a number of pointed questions
to determine whether readers have what it takes. Then the authors,
who are business consultants in Orange County, Calif., take readers
through a thorough checklist of business basics to get readers up
and running.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   ``The Millionaire Kit: Surprisingly Simple Strategies for
Building Real Wealth''
</P>
<P>
   By Stephen L. Nelson
</P>
<P>
   Times Books, $29.95
</P>
<P>
   Complete with computer software, this book offers a step-by-step
strategy to accumulating wealth with computer-based financial
modeling. Author Stephen Nelson is a certified public accountant
and author of a bestselling book on the financial software Quicken.
The books covers real estate investment trusts and other
investments, as well as simple budgeting and spending habits.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Teresa McUsic reviews business books for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the
World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-98 1546EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
