<HEADER>
A1698 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-SOLONDZ-TEX     10-22 0949
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SOLONDZ-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOLONDZ FOLLOWS TWISTED ROAD TO `HAPPINESS'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ELVIS MITCHELL 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``There's Something About Mary'' seemed to upset almost
everyone, except Todd Solondz, the writer-director of a new movie,
``Happiness,'' that has a high outrage quotient of its own. So it's
interesting that ``Happiness'' seemed to disturb the Farrelly
brothers, writers-directors of ``Mary.'' A recent New York Times
Sunday Magazine article was supposed to feature a dialogue between
these creators. But instead, it became a profile of only Solondz.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, initially the writer had pitched a story which she
described as high art/low art,'' says the slender, reflective
Solondz, whose first film, ``Welcome to the Dollhouse,'' was a
twisted, hilariously dark look at junior high. ``I don't think I
would consider myself high art exactly. ... I'd seen `Mary' and had
quite enjoyed it. I thought it was very funny and very liberating
in a way, and also a very personal film at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' he continues, ``when they saw my movie, I'm not sure
there was a mutual appreciation going on.'' According to the Times
article, in fact, the Farrellys thought ``Happiness'' was ``sick.''
</P>
<P>
   It may not just be the Farrellys. ``Happiness'' has received
laudatory reviews and last spring won the critics' prize at Cannes.
But it has also drawn controversy for its plot and characters,
including a sexually predatory poet, a phone-call pervert and a
child molester. October Films, an art-house film-releasing arm of
Universal, dropped ``Happiness''; Solondz got a new distributor and
chose to release the movie unrated rather than accept an NC-17.
</P>
<P>
   No one could look less threatening than Solondz. With his
glasses, high forehead and shock of hair perched atop it, he looks
like the smartest kid in the class. But his easygoing manner hides
a will of iron.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to the Dollhouse,'' about a pushy, unsympathetic
12-year-old girl may not have made it abundantly clear that Solondz
gets what he wants, but Happiness does. And there's no
sentimentality in his work.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's true. One moderator, when introducing me, said I don't
invite easy sympathy for my characters,'' Solondz says. ``It's easy
to make a character sympathetic. You just give them cancer, and, of
course, your heart will go out. You'll feel sorry for that person.
It's a knee-jerk response. ... But for me _ to be able to accept
and acknowledge, if not, embrace people with their flaws, that, for
me is a much greater challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   But Solondz's characters are victims, although not just that. He
often introduces them in a humorous context, and then works
backward to show the person underneath.
</P>
<P>
   ``I prefer not to use the word jokes when describing my movies,
because as much as many people may find them funny, to me it is
never a joke,'' he says. ``There is a certain kind of humor at
play, but I think if the audience is laughing out of a sense of
superiority ... well, it's not cruel, but rather exposing a kind of
cruelty. An unwitting cruelty which some find funny, and others
find incredibly sad. And a cruelty that doesn't just disappear
after the seventh grade. It's only the best of us who are able to
suppress, rechannel, sublimate, these baser instincts _ but they
are present.''
</P>
<P>
   His characters certainly suffer. In ``Happiness,'' the wife
(Cynthia Stevenson) is denied sex by her child-molester
psychiatrist husband (Dylan Baker); in ``Dollhouse,'' Dawn the
ridiculed kid is ignored by her parents while her adorable younger
sister is prized. So Solondz seems cruel.
</P>
<P>
   ``People do call me misanthropic as well,'' he says. ``But
that's not the case. It's funny, because people will say, `Why do
you make movies about such ugly people?' I don't think they're
ugly. I think it's more telling about the viewer than the film,
because these characters are not glamorized. They are not softened.
They are not beautiful, and audiences want to identify with the
beautiful and the alluring. I feel very emotionally connected to
all of these characters, although I must retain some degree of
detachment from them. Without that, it would be unbearable to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet, there has to be a need to provoke in Solondz, as surely
evidenced by not making his child-molester character a monster.
</P>
<P>
   ``Y'know, it's a funny thing,'' he says. ``It's not the (child
molestation) subject that makes people run away, or else the Oprah
book and the Roseanne book wouldn't be bestsellers.''
</P>
<P>
   Those projects, however, focus on people who've been victimized,
not aggressors who prey on children.
</P>
<P>
   ``To actually try to humanize, put a face, a heart and a mind,
attach that to someone who perpetrates such a crime ... when people
say the movie is shocking, that I think is what is most shocking to
them,'' he says. ``What makes this man tragic is not merely that he
has this horrible affliction but rather that he is, in fact, a
great father who loves his wife and (son).''
</P>
<P>
   That element of the film has been rendered in the most
sensationalistic terms, as if it's the only story that
``Happiness'' deals with. Was such a one-dimensional depiction a
concern of Solondz's?
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that would happen and it has happened. People, in
describing the movie, do reduce it to its basest elements
sometimes. You can't stop that.
</P>
<P>
   ``But ultimately,'' he muses, ``you hope the movie will get seen
for what it is, that it will speak for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   (Elvis Mitchell is film critic for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7614. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
