<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service calls your attention to the
following religion features moved during the last week.
</P>
<P>
   For retransmission of these stories, call 888-346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   MISSION-AZR (Mesa, Ariz.) _ Bradley Borden, a Mormon missionary
from Mesa, is recovering from the knife wounds to his upper
intestines, liver and pancreas, inflicted by a drunk in Russia who
murdered his friend, officials say. But when the 20-year-old
recovers from the stabbing, his mother said, ``I know he'll want to
go back to Russia.'' ``Being a missionary is the best thing a young
man can do,'' Myrna Borden said. ``It's what the prophet of our
church has asked our young men to do.'' By William Hermann.
</P>
<P>
   SACRILEGE-REVIEW-NYT (Undated) _ The play ``Corpus Christi'' has
refueled debate over a purported double standard: is offending
Christians not as bad as offending other religious or ethnic
groups? But the deeper and more complicated issue is what is fair
and what goes over the line in dealing with religious themes. By
Peter Applebome.
</P>
<P>
   CORPUS-CHRISTI-HNS (New York) _ Hate the sin, love the sinner.
It's the official Roman Catholic position on homosexuality, and it
would also seem to be the lesson of Terrence McNally's new play
about Jesus, ``Corpus Christi.'' By Joan Smith.
</P>
<P>
   GAYS-CONTROVERSY-TEX (Undated) _ The killing of a Wyoming
homosexual brings new attention to an ongoing controversy: Gay
advocates say you are what you are, and Christian activists say you
don't have to be. By Barry Schlacter.
</P>
<P>
   BLACKCHURCHES-COX _ An alarming number of Black churches are
experiencing financial difficulties, younger church members are
more critical of church management, and African Americans belonging
to the Church of God in Christ, Pentecostal and Baptist
denominations tend to give more money than those of other
denominations. These are a few of the findings released Wednesday,
part of a two-year study by the Interdenominational Theological
Center. By John Blake.
</P>
<P>
   BAPTISTS-SEMINARY-TEX (Fort Worth, Texas) _ Board members of
Southwestern Baptist Theological Seminary have changed a bylaw to
require faculty members to sign the updated version of the
denomination's statement of faith that includes a passage stating
that women must ``submit graciously'' to their husbands. By Tara
Dooley.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX (Undated) _ Sister Helen Prejean, the
author of ``Dead Man Walking,'' is full of life. The spirited Roman
Catholic nun's smiles and hugs won her audience long before she
began speaking. ``I'm taking my case to the American people,'' said
Prejean, who munched a sandwich as she greeted old and new
acquaintances and signed autographs before speaking out against the
death penalty last week in Fort Worth. Since actress Susan Sarandon
won an Academy Award for her portrayal of Prejean in the acclaimed
movie version of ``Dead Man Walking,'' the nun has been much in
demand and her audiences are larger. By Jim Jones.
</P>
