<SLUG> BC-BASEBALL-YANKEES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BY COMPARISON, 1927 TEAM STILL LOOKS MURDEROUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; SAN DIEGO _ Who's the best? The 1927 Yankees featuring Babe
Ruth and Lou Gehrig? Or the 1998 Yankees, a collection of lesser
talent molded into an unstoppable unit by manager Joe Torre? The
arguments have already started.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the debate has been raging since the regular season.
The 1998 Yankees set an American League record with 114 wins in 162
games. But the 1927 club, which won 110 games in a 154-game season,
had a better winning percentage (.714-.704).
</P>
<P>
   Wins weren't the only credentials of the club that featured the
so-called Murderers' Row _ Ruth, Gehrig, Tony Lazzeri, Bob Meusel,
and Earle Combs. Six members of that club _ Ruth, Gehrig, Lazzeri,
Combs, and pitchers Waite Hoyt and Herb Pennock _ were elected to
the Baseball Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   How many potential Hall of Famers does the 1998 team have? Maybe
Derek Jeter, but it's far too early in his career to project him
for Cooperstown. The same goes for batting champion Bernie
Williams. Maybe Chuck Knoblauch, but if he gets inducted, it will
be in a Twins cap. Among the pitchers, Andy Pettitte has 67
victories in four seasons but would need to maintain that level for
another decade at least. Mariano Rivera would have to remain a
dominant closer for years to merit consideration. David Cone is
winding down a fine career, but it won't get him to Cooperstown.
Right fielder Paul O'Neill is a consistent, productive hitter and
excellent defensively, but he's no Hall of Famer. Ditto first
baseman Tino Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are expectations when you wear a Yankee uniform,'' said
manager Joe Torre. ``You work for George Steinbrenner. He is a
perfectionist and he's always trying to improve on perfection. I
don't remember the 1927 Yankees. But you hear a lot about them.
Coming to New York, you understand that getting to the World Series
is what it's all about. They had a winning club in 1994, 1995. We
won finally in 1996 and made the playoffs again last year. It's
just something that has happened here over the years.''
</P>
<P>
   But the benchmark remains manager Miller Huggins's world
champions of 61 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   The offense batted .307 and pitchers had a combined 3.20 earned
run average; six of them won in double figures. Gehrig batted a
team-high .373 with 47 homers and 175 RBIs. Ruth batted .356 and
hit 60 homers, a record that stood for 34 years. Lazzeri (102) and
Meusel (103) knocked in more than 100 runs. Combs had a league-high
231 hits, including 23 triples, and batted .356.
</P>
<P>
   Hoyt (22-7), Wilcy Moore (19-7, league-leading 2.28 ERA),
Pennock (19-8), and Urban Shocker (18-6) formed a redoubtable
rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Can the 1998 club match up? Not statistically. But for pure
athleticism, the choice isn't so obvious. Defensively, the infield
of Jeter, Knoblauch, Scott Brosius, and Martinez would be hard to
match. But the 1927 quartet of Gehrig, Lazzeri, Mark Koenig, and
Joe Dugan was considered the best of its day. Whom would you want
in your outfield? Chili Davis, Bernie Williams, and O'Neill? Or
Ruth, Combs, and Meusel? Get your encyclopedias out and prepare for
a long debate.
</P>
<P>
   The clubs of 1927 and 1998 have one thing in common: Both knew
how to win. Both capped their seasons with World Series
championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to go back to the old Boston Celtics to find a team
that compares to the one we have now,'' said Torre. ``Those guys
averaged 16, 18, 19 points a game, but they were always able to win
games as a team. With this ball club, they're going to take MVP
votes away from each other. It's a great feeling for a manager to
know that when these guys come to the field, the only thing they
are interested in is winning the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're driven. This is a club that even surprised me. They
don't care who gets the game-winning hit. They all want to get the
game-winning hit, but they don't want to talk about it. It's the
most unusual club that I've seen in all my years in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing the 1927 club had going for it was longevity. The
nucleus stayed together to win World Series titles in 1928 under
Huggins and again in 1932 for Joe McCarthy. That would be unheard
of in today's baseball climate.
</P>
<P>
   The 1996 Yankees had two major defections after winning the
World Series _ pitchers John Wetteland and Jimmy Key _ because of
free agency. The '98 club faces a similar loss _ namely, Williams.
As close as the Yankees have become, they fully understand that the
marketplace and budget considerations could do more to break them
up than the San Diego Padres ever could.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew when we won in 1996 we weren't going to be able to keep
all those guys together,'' said Torre. ``With free agency the way
it is today, it's tough. It was difficult saying goodbye to the
Jimmy Keys and John Wettelands after 1996. But we understand it.
That's why players want to come here and take advantage of
something special like we have going on now. We were fortunate to
just be able to keep this club together all year. The last couple
of years, we added people here and there and subtracted people
during the course of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't do that this year. The players who did come in
seized the opportunity. It's nice that we had a nucleus. It was a
lot easier for those guys to blend in and get caught up in the same
things we do.''
</P>
<P>
   How well they did that compared to their '27 forefathers is a
matter for the historians to settle.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-98 1553EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
