<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 15:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1729 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-SETTLERS-1023-     10-22 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-SETTLERS-1023-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SETTLERS' ACTIVISM AIMED AT KEEPING LAND THEY SEE AS GOD-GIVEN
 &HT;    EDs: Optional add begins at 650 words.
 &HT;    With MIDEAST-TALKS-1023.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW 
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIT EL, West Bank _ Founded in biblical zeal, this hilltop
hamlet is where suburban pleasantries meet the uncompromising
frontline of the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   Kids in kindergarten amble down the sidewalks past tidy
landscaping and red-roofed stone villas. The grocery store is
friendly, and a community club board announces a music and lecture
program for seniors week.
</P>
<P>
   Men and women cover their heads with skullcaps or hats in
accordance with Orthodox Jewish tradition. On the edge of town,
mobile homes house the newcomers eager to join in the community
spirit.
</P>
<P>
   But people in this West Bank settlement are worried and angry
about the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks, in their eighth day
Thursday, at the Wye Plantation on Maryland's Eastern Shore.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike much of the world, they do not want any deal to come out
of the Wye talks and are concerned that their choice of prime
minister, right-winger Benjamin Netanyahu, is caving in to
pressure.
</P>
<P>
   They say God gave this mountain to them -- not to the Arabs.
They are fearful that the Wye talks could make them an island among
Palestinians, neighbors who hurl large stones at them through their
windshields and, they say, cannot be trusted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel that giving up any part of the land of Israel is
something we cannot accept,'' said Judith Missel, a 39-year-old
Beit El municipal worker and mother of five. ``There is no place
else in the world a Jew can live and not be expelled or persecuted.
Why should that happen in the land of Israel?''
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen-year Beit El resident Becky Pinsky, originally from
Brooklyn, N.Y., knows a compromise may be necessary, but not
without trust.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody says peace has to come now. Maybe it will take another
20 years,'' said the 47-year-old kindergarten supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   This is the West Bank, land captured by Israel in the 1967 war.
Palestinians say it is theirs, and even American officials have
asked in vain for a halt to Israeli settlement construction because
of the bitterness it inspires.
</P>
<P>
   Today, there are 144 West Bank settlements with about 170,000
residents in the West Bank. They are easy to spot on hilltops,
usually surrounded by fences.
</P>
<P>
   Most have biblical names -- Beit El residents say the story of
Jacob's ladder took place here and God promised the Jews this land.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the settlements there are more than 1.5 million
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   The Oslo peace process is built around the hand-over of
Israeli-occupied lands to the Palestinians. Most settlements will
remain, but they could be encircled by Palestinian lands. No maps
have come from Wye yet, but Beit El residents could see the circle
close around them soon.
</P>
<P>
   That is hard to face in Beit El, a 21-year-old community of 750
families about a half-hour from Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
   About two years ago a mother and son were shot to death in their
car, and a 17-year-old boy was shot to death outside the town's
gate.
</P>
<P>
   For several days, settlers have blocked roads in the West Bank
and threaten to do likewise in the heart of Israel in protest
against any agreement that would come out of the Wye talks turning
over land.
</P>
<P>
   It was the start of a peace talks backlash similar to others
Netanyahu has faced and survived.
</P>
<P>
   Right-wing members of the Israeli parliament, or Knesset, have
already filed a no-confidence motion to greet Netanyahu upon his
return.
</P>
<P>
   Most settlers supported Netanyahu's election. Now, though, their
leaders are considering candidates to oppose him in case early
elections are called in the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   Demonstrations are planned and, girding for the worst, police
intend to increase Netanyahu's personal security when he returns
home.
</P>
<P>
   Settler leaders are not without influence in Washington, where
they traveled last week to meet friends and visit with American
supporters. In fact, in Beit El and other settlements here, the
larger buildings bear the names of American benefactors.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Settlers claim their presence buffers Israel from its hostile
neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   But, many left-wing Israelis argue that, in the age of missile
warfare, settlements do little for the country's security and may
do more harm by the anger they inspire.
</P>
<P>
   Mosi Raz, secretary general of Israel's Peace Now group,
disputes the idea that turning over land endangers settlements. He
said settlements in the Gaza Strip are more peaceful now,
surrounded by Palestinian lands, than they were during the
turbulent Israeli occupation there.
</P>
<P>
   David Newman, Israeli political scientist, said the settlers'
organized tactics have been effective at toughening Israel's
position in the Oslo process. But, most Israelis do not identify
with them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Increasing numbers of people see them just as (American)
Indian reserves in the West Bank,'' he said, noting that two-thirds
of Israelis have never been to the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
