<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 15:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1735 &Cx1f; tic-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PLEASANTVILL-MOVIE-AZ     10-22 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLEASANTVILL-MOVIE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEVER `PLEASANTVILLE' PICKS UP WHERE `TRUMAN SHOW' LEFT OFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - If average Americans spend a quarter of their lives
watching TV, why not go all the way and live inside a TV world?
They do in ``Pleasantville,'' a mostly comic fantasy that takes
``The Truman Show'' idea and turns it inside out.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone in the happy town of ``Pleasantville'' is not an actor
but a character existing in the unchanging world of TV reruns.
</P>
<P>
   The movie starts in what we unhappily call the real world, with
its full range of dangers.
</P>
<P>
   David (Tobey Maguire) and his sister Jen (Reese Witherspoon) are
suburban high schoolers stumbling awkwardly through a world that
has little to offer but sex, humiliation and despair.
</P>
<P>
   David escapes through nostalgia TV. He's a devoted rerun fan of
a show from the '50s called ``Pleasantville,'' one of those sitcoms
that encompasses ``Father Knows Best,'' ``The Donna Reed Show'' and
``Ozzie and Harriet'' rolled into one happy, black-and-white world.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, David and Jen are transported into that world, where
everyone thinks the kids are the stars of the show, Bud and Mary
Sue.
</P>
<P>
   Now they're living in a black-and-white world where everything
is pleasant and meaningless, where the weather report is the same
every day: ``a high of 72 and a low of 72.''
</P>
<P>
   But Jen threatens the perfection of that Pleasantville world
when she introduces desire into their sealed-off existence.
</P>
<P>
   Comparisons between ``The Truman Show'' and ``Pleasantville''
are obvious. Happily, ``Pleasantville'' is more original, funnier
and more thoughtful.
</P>
<P>
   Unhappily, writer/director Gary Ross pushes his metaphor too
far, and the film loses its sense of fun and becomes preachy.
</P>
<P>
   Ross starts with a clever notion: a TV world where desire brings
color out of black and white, where sex leads to rock and roll, and
art liberates.
</P>
<P>
   But when Ross starts hammering home the idea that ``family
values'' is a thin cover for fascism and that you can be put on
trial for illegal use of magenta, he stretches his vision and his
metaphor until it pops like an overinflated balloon.
</P>
<P>
   He also loses grip on what makes the movie work: the amusing
contrasts between real life and TV life.
</P>
<P>
   Why the irksome problems with a visionary film like
``Pleasantville?'' Probably one man doing too much.
</P>
<P>
   Ross is a talented, successful screenwriter (``Big,'' ``Dave'')
moving up to direct his first film, which he also wrote and
produced. That means the top three voices for guiding the vision
all came from the same man.
</P>
<P>
   An accomplished filmmaker might succeed flying solo. But
first-time directors often need someone else telling them when
they've gone off-base.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its shortfall, ``Pleasantville'' is such an original
that you have to see it. Like ``Back to the Future'' or ``Who
Framed Roger Rabbit'' ``Pleasantville'' gives us a new way to look
at pop culture.
</P>
<P>
   Visually, the film makes such clever use of black and white that
it puts color in a new light. Stylistically, the movie zips, full
of surprises, especially in the first half when the kids arrive in
Pleasantville.
</P>
<P>
   As a nation whose culture is dominated by television, we are
watching a generation of filmmakers who have learned more about
life from the tube than from the more confusing world off the
living-room couch.
</P>
<P>
   Now ``Pleasantville'' and ``The Truman Show'' are telling
stories to people trapped by TV about people trapped inside TV.
Wonder what's coming next?
</P>
<P>
   ``Pleasantville'' is misrated at PG-13. It has enough profanity,
sex and nudity for an R. 3 stars. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-98 1559EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
