<HEADLINE>
`APT PUPIL' MAKES SUBTLE STUDY OF FAS CISM'S EVILS 
</HEADLINE>
 PUPIL-MOVIE-AZR   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB FENSTER  
 c.1998 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNDATED - In a pleasant suburban town, could your good neighbor
actually be a Nazi war criminal? He definitely can in a movie based
on a Stephen King story.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Apt Pupil'' is not the kind of slasher/horror thriller
that will please fans of ``Scream'' or ``Blade.'' Instead, director
Bryan Singer turns King's tale into a tense psychological study of
evil.
</P>
<P>
   Curious about the nature of extreme evil, a bright high school
student, Todd (Brad Renfro), becomes absorbed in a study of Nazi
Germany and the Holocaust.
</P>
<P>
   Todd's research unearths the fact that an old man in the town,
Kurt (Ian McKellen), is actually a former Nazi officer, responsible
for exterminating thousands of people in the gas chambers during
World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Threatening Kurt with exposure, Todd blackmails the old man into
telling him the truth about what it was like to slaughter innocent
people.
</P>
<P>
   But as the months pass, the old man and the boy subtly begin to
shift positions of power until Kurt threatens to control Todd's
life.
</P>
<P>
   Singer turns King's novella about a boy who learns his lessons
too well into a suspense movie that is more psychologically
disturbing than frightening in traditional Hollywood terms.
</P>
<P>
   Singer had a surprise hit with the unusual crime tale ``The
Usual Suspects.'' His work in ``Apt Pupil'' is more subtle and
sophisticated, as he must build suspense out of thin plot elements
and practically no action.
</P>
<P>
   The director succeeds in convincing us that the monster inside
all men doesn't lie far beneath the surface.
</P>
<P>
   However, the film's dynamics slump badly in the middle once we
know what Todd's up to and before we find out how Kurt will deal
with him. That leaves us with too much time waiting to see if the
story will pick up steam again. It does, but perhaps not enough to
satisfy thriller fans.
</P>
<P>
   Singer is greatly aided by two taut, constrained performances by
the stars. Renfro (``The Client,'' ``The Cure'') remains one of the
most talented serious young actors in Hollywood. He keeps us on the
edge, wondering about Todd's motives and exactly what he is capable
of doing.
</P>
<P>
   McKellen, the English actor, is becoming particularly creepy
with his fascist portrayals. Last year, he reinterpreted
Shakespeare's Richard III as a modern dictator. In ``Apt Pupil,''
he gives us a broken old man who hasn't entirely lost the goose
step in his soul.
</P>
<P>
   The previews are somewhat misleading about the level of
excitement in the movie, but ``Apt Pupil'' has a lingering,
depressing psychological effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apt Pupil'' is rated R for profanity, violence and nudity. 3
stars. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-98 1602EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
