<SLUG> BC-DRUGS-SINGER-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SINGER `HOOKED ON LIFE' 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BARBARA KARKABI 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Ashley Millet has been singing country music tunes
since she was 3, performing at baby beauty pageants.
</P>
<P>
   She's long since left the pageant scene, but Ashley, 15, still
loves to sing and is now trying to teach other young people through
music about the dangers of drug abuse, underage drinking and drunk
driving.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston teen just returned from a country western tour of
Georgia and recently performed ``Hooked on Life,'' a song she
co-wrote, at Miller Outdoor Theater in Houston as part of the Red
Ribbon Campaign, sponsored by the Texas Federation of Parents for a
Drug Free Youth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a really good response to the song. There were about 200
kids,'' said Ashley, who is the group's teen advocate. ``I co-wrote
the drug-free song because so many kids do listen to the words as
well as the music. We were hoping to get the idea through with
music.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashley wrote ``Hooked on Life'' with Clifton Smith, who produced
the song. It encourages teens to stay drug-free, to resist peer
pressure and to stay focused on life.
</P>
<P>
   The song goes:
</P>
<P>
   ``Hooked on life and live for tomorrow and don't give up the
fight ...''
</P>
<P>
   ``What we are trying to do is reach younger kids so that when
they get to high school they won`t do drugs,'' Ashley said. ``Kids
today are often portrayed as being on drugs, but they're not. It's
just a few who do, and they give the rest a bad name.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Ashley has always been anti-drugs, it was only recently
that she got involved musically. About 1 1/2 years ago, she was
approached to sing a song called ``Little White Crosses'', about
drunk driving.
</P>
<P>
   Through that song she was connected with an organization in
Florida called Alcohol Free Kids, which decided to use ``Little
White Crosses'' as its theme song and Ashley as the group's
national student spokeswoman. Ashley is also involved with Houston
Crackdown.
</P>
<P>
   Besides her appearance at Miller Outdoor Theater, Ashley sang
``Hooked on Life'' over the weekend in Del Rio and on Tuesday in
Austin _ all for the Red Ribbon Campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Ashley used to attend Faith West Academy, but these days she is
so busy with her career that she is home-schooled. She's also given
up guitar and horseback-riding lessons, so she has more time for
performing and voice lessons.
</P>
<P>
   These days her songs are being played on a Bay City country
station, KMKS 102.5, which is also the sponsor of her Web site.
Ashley sometimes thinks about studying law and being an
entertainment lawyer. But right now her No. 1 goal is to be a
successful entertainer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be a famous country western singer, and by being
famous I want to reach kids by being drug-free,'' Ashley said. ``I
will always be drug-free.''
</P>
<P>
   Ashley's Web site is www.kmks.com/ashley.html &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
