<HEADER>
A1840 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REX-FILM-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      10-22 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REX-FILM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`T-REX: BACK TO THE CRETACEOUS': MONSTERS ON THE MARCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Production notes are at end of review.) 
(mk) 
 By LAWRENCE VAN GELDER    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Passions for the prehistoric that remain unsated after the two
``Jurassic Park'' films are likely to be requited by the latest
IMAX 3-D film, ``T-Rex: Back to the Cretaceous.''
</P>
<P>
   Drooling and menacing, the monsters of the Mesozoic are on the
march again in this brief, enjoyable dip into paleontology,
teen-age adventure and parent-child relationships.
</P>
<P>
   Outdoing ``Jurassic Park'' and its sequel, ``The Lost World:
Jurassic Park,'' ``T-Rex'' puts its dinosaurs visually in your face
_ close up and personal, as the television networks like to say.
Set against the lush ferns, moss and ancient trees of the Olympic
rain forest in the state of Washington, these creatures seem
marvelously lifelike.
</P>
<P>
   Better yet, ``T-Rex,'' directed by Brett Leonard and written by
Andrew Gellis and Jeanne Rosenberg, doesn't rest on its
technological splendors. Its plot takes the viewer to a
paleontological dig, raises unanswered scientific questions and
introduces some of the major figures in the history of the subject.
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, seeing ``T-Rex'' won't qualify anyone for a
doctorate in paleontology, and an intriguing subplot that hints at
a troubled family background for its teen-age heroine is left
unresolved; but the film is the sort likely to whet active young
minds to know more about the past.
</P>
<P>
   ``T-Rex'' is built around Ally Hayden (Liz Stauber), the
daughter of an eminent paleontologist, Dr. Donald Hayden (Peter
Horton). While he is busy uncovering new specimens at a dig in
Dinosaur Provincial Park in Alberta, Canada, she is spending her
summer wishing he would allow her to join him. Sharing his passion
for the subject, she is leading tours at the natural-history museum
where he works and completing a paper embodying her theories about
parental instinct among dinosaurs.
</P>
<P>
   When Donald returns with his latest find, Ally speculates that
it might be a dinosaur egg, although her busy father reminds her
that no one has ever found one.
</P>
<P>
   Toward nightfall, after Donald is summoned to a meeting
elsewhere in the cavernous museum, the find is knocked to the
floor, and moments later, Ally begins a journey in and out of the
past. Dinosaurs in the museum appear to come to life; she meets
Charles Knight, the prescient artist of dinosaurs, and in the early
part of the century encounters Barnum Brown on one of the digs that
earned him renown. And from time to time, she finds herself in that
forest primeval, among the creatures that fascinate her and seem
equally likely to fascinate and stimulate young audiences.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `T-REX: BACK TO THE CRETACEOUS'
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Brett Leonard; written by Andrew Gellis and Jeanne
Rosenberg, based on a story by Gellis and David Young; director of
photography, Andrew Kitzanuk; edited by Jonathan Shaw; music by
William Ross; produced by Antoine Compin and Charis Horton;
released by Imax Corp. At Sony Theaters Lincoln Square, 1998
Broadway at 68th Street. Running time: 45 minutes. This film is not
rated.
</P>
<P>
   With: Peter Horton (Dr. Donald Hayden), Liz Stauber (Ally
Hayden), Kari Coleman (Elizabeth Sample), Laurie Murdoch (Barnum
Brown) and Tuck Milligan (Charles Knight).
</P>
</TEXT>
