<HEADLINE>
FOX'S `BRIMSTONE' GOES THROUGH HELL AND BACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Check local listings for time and channel.)  
 By JOHN CARMAN  
 c.1998, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You might have guessed that ``Touched by an Angel'' would mother
some strange puppies, but this beats all.
</P>
<P>
   Fox's ``Brimstone,'' premiering Friday, is a kind of ``Touched
by the Devil,'' in which our hero does Satan's work on earth.
</P>
<P>
   Not that that's a bad thing.
</P>
<P>
   (Some television guides might tell you that ``Brimstone'' isn't
on Friday night. But in a late move, Fox pulled two struggling
comedies and subbed ``Brimstone.'' Its regular time slot is 9 p.m.
Tuesdays.)
</P>
<P>
   Ezekiel Stone (series star Peter Horton, who used to be more up
to earth in ``thirtysomething'') is good-looking, courageous and,
darn the luck, dead.
</P>
<P>
   He was a New York City cop who avenged his wife's rape by
murdering the assailant, died himself 15 years ago, and was
condemned to hell.
</P>
<P>
   Satan (John Glover, in the role he's surely been searching for
all these years) can always use a good man. He sends Stone back up
top to hunt down 113 escapees from hell.
</P>
<P>
   And a truly bad lot they are. Stone's hunt begins Friday night
with a pedophilic priest.
</P>
<P>
   Do we have this straight? The priest is the bad guy. The devil,
in his incorrigible way, is doing the right thing. This is not a
comedy.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, brother, is it ever (set ital)not(end ital) a comedy.
``Brimstone'' is dark, and earnest, and a bit too smitten with its
own ornate premise.
</P>
<P>
   As the last scheduled fall series to debut, ``Brimstone'' is
also right in line with so many of the year's new shows _ hard to
hate, hard to adore. It fills space with neither dishonor nor
distinction.
</P>
<P>
   I'll give it this, though: ``Brimstone'' manages one of the best
lines of the season in a scene where a young woman hits on Stone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very flattered,'' he tells her, ``but I'm married. Not to
mention dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Take it. The line is yours, a gift from Fox. Halloween's coming;
the situation might arise.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
    &UR; (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL ADD FOLLOWS) &LR;  &QC; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   _ If you've seen Oprah Winfrey's ``Beloved,'' watched ``Africans
in America'' this week on PBS and can handle more, it's here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Masterpiece Theatre'' has a two-part, four-hour British drama
called ``A Respectable Trade,'' airing Sunday and Monday.
</P>
<P>
   It's a different take on a dirty business, though the
fictionalized treatment _ Philippa Gregory wrote the script, based
on her own novel _ ultimately buttresses the ``Africans in
America'' documentary series.
</P>
<P>
   Here, the story is in England. In 1788, Frances Scott (Emma
Fielding), a parson's daughter and lord's penniless niece, marries
Bristol businessman Josiah Cole (Warren Clarke).
</P>
<P>
   His business, the ``respectable trade'' of the title, is
shipping and selling African slaves to Jamaica plantation owners.
He also imports several to Bristol, with the idea of polishing them
and selling them at a profit.
</P>
<P>
   Horrified and then reluctantly agreeing to tutor the slaves,
Frances eventually falls in love with one of them, Mehuru (Ariyon
Bakare). Though he's forced to wear a silver slave's collar, he has
the intelligence and sensitivity that Frances' husband, Josiah,
lacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``A Respectable Trade'' slumps badly in Monday's installment,
when the production turns so sudsy that, but for English restraint,
it might become a British ``Mandingo.'' It's a close call.
</P>
<P>
   The best thing about ``A Respectable Trade'' is Clarke as Josiah
the slave trader. He's an oafish man with hopes that his ill-gotten
fortune and refined wife will pave his way into polite society.
</P>
<P>
   Yes and no. If Josiah had any wits, he'd be smart enough to
recognize who is and isn't a ``savage'' in 18th century Bristol.
</P>
<P>
   _ And finally, no confirmation from Fox, but I hear that Rob
Schneider (``Saturday Night Live,'' ``Men Behaving Badly'') has
signed to guest star as Ally's boyfriend on ``Ally McBeal.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
