<P>
   BASEBALL
</P>
<P>
   BBO-CHIPPER-ADULTERY _ Atlanta Braves third baseman Chipper
Jones acknowledges that he fathered an illegitimate child born
seven months ago. ``I've messed up royally,'' Jones said. ``I've
messed up just about as bad as a man can mess up without killing
somebody. I've committed adultery and I'll pay for that the rest of
my life. (Stinson, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   BBO-CHIPPER-IMAGE _ Chipper Jones and his wife, Karin, came to
Atlanta in 1993 as the all-American baseball family. Jones, a
minimum salary ballplayer, soon developed into a superstar. Along
the way, he became arguably the most popular Braves player since
Dale Murphy. So it's no surprise that he is the talk of Atlanta
today after admitting that he had fathered a child out of wedlock.
(Wilkinson, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 35-40.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-CHIPPER-FALLEN _Atlanta is full of young children who adore
Chipper Jones. So as parents, how do you explain this to your kids,
who are wearing his No. 10 jerseys. (Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
10-12.
</P>
<P>
   BBO-CHIPPER-JONES _ Chipper Jones talks about his ``mistake''
under his own byline. (Tentative)
</P>
<P>
   BBO-WORLDSERIES-FOLO _ Folo on World Series. (IJRosenberg,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   BBO-SERIES _ Follow story. (McCoy, Dayton Daily News). 22.
</P>
<P>
   FOOTBALL
</P>
<P>
   NFL
</P>
<P>
   FBN-FALCONS-NOTES _ Falcons notebook. (Winkeljohn, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 22.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-NFLPREVIEW _ Here are highlights for the upcoming NFL
weekend. (Pasquarelli, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 13-15.
</P>
<P>
   COLLEGES
</P>
<P>
   FBC-GATECH-KEYS _ Six weeks ago, it appeared Georgia Tech was
headed for another dismal season after a shocking 41-31 loss at
home to Boston College. Now, the Jackets have won five straight,
lead the ACC and have a chance to move closer to their first
conference title in eight years with a victory at home Saturday
against Florida State. How were the Jackets able to turn the course
of their season? We will look at three critical areas - the
emergence of receiver Dez White, outstanding special teams play and
an opportunistic defense, which has produced an NCAA record five
touchdowns. (Rogers, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 22.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   FBC-FSU-WEINKE _ After just two games as Florida State's
starting quarterback, Chris Weinke had nine turnovers. In the loss
to N.C. State, he threw six interceptions. Now he's thrown 149
straight passes without an interception and he has thrown for more
than 300 yards in two straight games. It now appears that Weinke,
the 26-year-old sophomore, is finally rounding into form just in
time for Saturday's visit to Georgia Tech. Bobby Bowden said
earlier this year that if Weinke got his act together, Florida
State would be good enough to compete for the national
championship. His dream may be coming true. (Barnhart, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 18. WITH GAME-BY-GAME STATS.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-OSUFB _ Feature on Northwestern tight end, Jay Tant, an
Alter High School graduate. Three years into his college football
career and with the Wildcats 2-5, how does the former state
swimming champion feel about his decision to play football instead
of swim? How's it going for him this year? (Vinella, Dayton Daily
News). 15.
</P>
<P>
   FBC-AGGIES _ Protect the ball. And, apparently, the Aggies are
practicing what their coaches are preaching. Through seven games,
A&AMP;M's defense has forced 17 turnovers, while the offense has
coughed it up only six times, the fewest in the Big 12. The 1.57
margin-per-game ratio ranks second in the league to Kansas State's
1.67 ratio, and is 10th nationally. To the Aggies, that stat is a
crucial component of their 6-1 record and No. 8 spot in the
Associated Press poll going into Saturday's Big 12 game at Kyle
Field against No. 25 Texas Tech. (Riggs, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
