<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GOOD MORNING AMERICA' IS JUST TOO SMART FOR ITS OWN GOOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eulogies for ``Good Morning America'' have been piling up for
months now, and they only seem to become more grave in tone. Once
considered unbeatable, ``GMA'' has fallen badly and can't get up.
Why? Because it's breaking the cardinal rule of morning television:
It's failing to give its audience what it wants.
</P>
<P>
   Now it must pay the price of catch-up in a genre in which
ratings turnarounds are often painfully slow in coming.
</P>
<P>
   Judging from what I've read so far of this mess, fingers are
pointing within the ABC family about who broke this once-proud
program and how it should be fixed. Some say the fall began when
``GMA'' was placed under the network news division and those stiff
shirts tried to ``make it matter.''
</P>
<P>
   I am struck, however, that this is a production that has flown
against the established standards of morning TV by selecting
co-hosts (Fort Worth's Lisa McRee and Kevin Newman), for their
brains and not beauty; by pushing substance over sizzle; and by
assuming that journalism experience is the first and foremost
qualification.
</P>
<P>
   Is this where ``GMA'' stumbled and ``Today'' thrived? Morning
television watchers often flick on the TV without much thought as
to what awaits them, following a morning routine that is exact,
comfortable, gloriously familiar.
</P>
<P>
   Most ordinary viewers who tune in to weekday infotainment
programs like ``GMA,'' ``Today,'' ``CBS Morning News,'' or even
``Good Morning Texas'' on the Dallas-Fort Worth ABC affiliate,
catch these shows in the chunks in which they're shrewdly designed.
</P>
<P>
   They consume news nuggets, lightweight interviews, entertainment
and lots of chatter while doing something else, like eating,
getting the kids dressed, cleaning. In most instances, it's
background noise. A companion with whom you never feel guilty for
being less than attentive.
</P>
<P>
   The hosts of these programs must be attractive and warm, but not
forceful or opinionated, and shouldn't probe or drill someone even
when they leap into well-rehearsed legalese doublespeak.
</P>
<P>
   And that's fine. Let's face it: We don't look to these people
for journalistic scoops or investigative reportage.
</P>
<P>
   ``GMA'' wanted to tweak the format, and hired the people to do
it. Unfortunately, it succeeded, and ``GMA'' now trails ``Today''
by nearly 3 million viewers.
</P>
<P>
   Having watched McRee's career, from her days at the local ABC
affiliate to overnight news anchor, cable magazine host and anchor
in Los Angeles, I often watch her on ``GMA'' and wonder why she's
bothering to interview some movie star on publicity autopilot.
</P>
<P>
   Much was made of her news background and how she's more prepared
to handle a breaking news story, better equipped to improvise and
summarize, and able to make a seamless transition between the news
and cooking segments.
</P>
<P>
   But is that what we want? I remember the flak recently over
former U.S. Rep. Susan Molinari co-anchoring the Saturday version
of ``CBS Morning News,'' that she wasn't a ``journalist.'' How soon
we'd forgotten that David Hartman, the original ``GMA'' host, was
an actor, or that former ``GMA'' co-host Joan Lunden couldn't
breathe without a TelePrompTer telling her how.
</P>
<P>
   Newman, for instance, is able to balance serious reporting with
breezy banter, but I can't count the number of female friends and
colleagues who have questioned his hunk quotient and noted how it
doesn't compare with that talking model over on ``Today.''
</P>
<P>
   Thing is, you can't have it both ways, at least not in the
sizzle-over-substance climate in which we've created.
</P>
<P>
   I say ``GMA'' will succumb to the tastes of the waking-up TV
watchers, returning to a world of triteness and banality. In fact,
plans are already under way to mimic ``Today's'' viewer-friendly
``window to the world'' of flag-waving tourists who gather weekday
mornings outside 49th Street and Rockefeller Plaza in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, we can say that ``GMA'' went down the tubes shortly
after it changed hands to the ABC News division. I say it's that
darn window at NBC. What a shrewd ``journalistic'' move.
</P>
<P>
   (Ken Parish Perkins is television critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7862, or e-mail:
kpp(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
