<HEADER>
A1937 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-CORN-MAZE-ART-NYT &LR;      10-22 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-CORN-MAZE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.Y.)  
 LOST IN THE LABYRINTH: SO WHAT IF IT'S CORN? 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By TAMAR LEWIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forget about England and the groomed green hedges that line the
maze at Hampton Court Palace, with its quiet bench in the center.
</P>
<P>
   Forget about Crete and the maze where Daedalus confined the
Minotaur. Drop any vestige of hope for the religious and meditative
features of labyrinths.
</P>
<P>
   And then, with a couple of kids in tow, you can have a really
good time at the raggedy corn maze in back of a farmstand on the
North Fork of Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   It's nothing fancy, just a set of paths cut through an acre of
unusually tall corn (a red strain called Butcher Block) with tacky
Halloween-theme props to mark your way. But the maze and, a few
miles down the road, a farmstand and petting zoo called Punkinville
USA, have become our family's ritual markers of fall.
</P>
<P>
   This year, after a beautiful ride past the North Fork vineyards
and pumpkin fields, my husband and I, our enthusiastic 9-year-old
daughter, our slightly blase 13-year-old son and his politely
interested 13-year-old friend arrived at the Greenland Family Farm
maze in Cutchogue in midafternoon on the day it opened in
September.
</P>
<P>
   Corn mazes, by their nature, are not built to last; the ones on
Long Island open in September or October and close soon after
Halloween. By this time the cornstalks have become dried out and
ratty, and there is a heavy infusion of yellow tape to block off
paths that have been stomped into confusion by weeks of heavy
traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the season goes by,'' said Adam Samolewski, a member of the
family that runs the farm, ``there get to be more and more trails,
and we have to try to mark off the path and stop people from making
their own.''
</P>
<P>
   But when we visited, the corn was ripening, the paths were clear
and the maze was very inviting. After fortifying ourselves with
raspberries, peaches and honey sticks from the farmstand, paying
the $2-a-person entrance fee and getting a copy of the map, to be
opened only in case of panic, we plunged in, boys first, dad
second, mom and daughter last.
</P>
<P>
   The boys were off on their own in an instant. The dad, too.
There was the initial thrill of adventure, traipsing around
corners, finding dead ends, pushing through a set of black plastic
streamers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ooh, this is really fun,'' said the daughter, four minutes in,
as we encountered the cutout of the witch feeding a cat out of a
kettle.
</P>
<P>
   Ooh, this is really frustrating, thought the mom, nine minutes
in, coming on the kitty peeking out of the pumpkin for the fourth
time in as many minutes, and having absolutely no idea how to do it
any differently.
</P>
<P>
   There was no panic to my disorientation, since cornstalks,
unlike hedges, are not impenetrable barriers, and I knew I could
push my way out the side at any time. But after 12 minutes, the fun
was wearing off. And when my husband reappeared _ having made it to
the end, congratulated the triumphal boys and then come back in _
my daughter was ready to abandon my aimless meandering and go with
him.
</P>
<P>
   I stayed behind. But as soon as they were out of sight, I
sneaked a peek at the map, only to discover that it showed a blank
maze with no markings _ completely useless unless you'd tracked
every turn you made since entering and could figure out where you
were. So when my husband came back to get me, I was perfectly
content to be guided out.
</P>
<P>
   The boys, meanwhile, had gone back in, memorized the way and
could now, according to my daughter's stopwatch, navigate the whole
route in one minute and 22 seconds. Not to be outdone, she went
back with the map and followed the most direct path, straight to
the exit.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brother designed it, on graph paper,'' Samolewski said.
``We just plant the rows and then take out the plants where the
paths are going to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Corn mazes have become ubiquitous in the Northeast in the last
five years, the most visible feature of a push into agri-tourism by
family farms looking to expand their income with attractions like
hayrides and harvest festivals. This is the third maze the
Samolewskis have planted; they also have pick-your-own pumpkins, a
nursery and a series of tiny backyard ``ponds'' guaranteed to
please the under-6 group.
</P>
<P>
   We looked at the fish in the ponds and then, carefully avoiding
the vineyard tastings that are the upscale North Fork attraction,
drove east on Route 48 to Peconic, site of our other landmark of
hokey fall fun _ Punkinville USA, a farmstand and petting zoo
decorated with an almost unbelievable number of garishly painted
pumpkins, ghosts and witches.
</P>
<P>
   Here the $3 entrance fee buys a look at, and a chance to feed, a
huge collection of birds _ macaws, ostriches, rheas, pheasants of
all kinds _ as well as Vietnamese potbellied pigs, Jacob sheep with
six horns, Nibbles the pygmy goat, iguanas, a menagerie of bunnies
and more.
</P>
<P>
   When the children were younger, we would spend many, many
dollars buying corn kernels from gum-ball dispensers to feed the
animals. In those days, the high points were the pony ride, the
bales of hay to romp in, the enclosure for mingling with a herd of
goats and, one year, the prairie dog that would grab corn from
between fingers.
</P>
<P>
   This year though, the stars were the wild boar; the coati, a
raccoonlike South American creature, and Frankie, the imposing
white llama who stood nine feet tall or more as he put his front
legs up on the fence and stared at us.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't fancy, but it's fun.
</P>
<P>
   GREENLAND FAMILY FARM, 17155 County Rd. 48, Cutchogue, N.Y.
11935, (516) 734-5791. Open daily, 8:30 a.m. to 5:30 p.m. The maze
is expected to last through Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   PUNKINVILLE USA, a petting zoo and farm stand, 26085 County Rd.
48, Peconic, N.Y. 11958, (516) 734-5530. Open daily, 10 a.m. to 5
p.m.
</P>
</TEXT>
