<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHERS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    '100,000 TEACHERS' BILL MAY HAVE LITTLE IMPACT
 &HT;    By JULIA MALONE
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton claimed victory this week as the
Republican-led Congress approved $1.2 billion as the first step
toward hiring 100,000 new teachers.
</P>
<P>
   But the legislation's fine print _ and doubts among some
education experts about the benefits of smaller classes _ could
throw cold water on public expectations that the influx of teachers
will quickly improve the nation's lagging academic skills.
</P>
<P>
   Among the facts that have been clarified since the plan was
rushed into law as part of an end-of-session budget agreement:
</P>
<P>
   _ While Clinton promised 100,000 new teachers to reduce class
size to 18 in grades 1-3, the Education Department says that it
will take up to seven years to fulfill that pledge _ and then only
if Congress decides to go along each year with additional funding,
totaling $12 billion over the period.
</P>
<P>
   _ The first teachers under the program won't be hired until next
July, and the total number will be no more than 30,000 for the
first year.
</P>
<P>
   _ Finding qualified teachers for the new slots could be
difficult, since many areas of the country have a critical shortage
of teachers now.
</P>
<P>
   _ And if good teachers can be recruited, where will the schools
find the new classrooms to put them in? Congress rejected a Clinton
proposal to subsidize school repairs and new construction to
relieve overcrowding.
</P>
<P>
   _ Finally, education experts are sharply divided on whether
shrinking class size will translate into significant academic
gains. Some researchers suggest it could be a waste of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most studies give no reason to expect a change in student
performance as a result of smaller class sizes,'' said University
of Rochester professor Eric A. Hanushek, considered one of the
foremost researchers in the field.
</P>
<P>
   In the largest study yet, the state of Tennessee commissioned an
experiment to compare varying class sizes in kindergarten through
grade 3. The U.S. Education Department uses the study as evidence
of gains in math and reading for the smallest classes, which
averaged 13-17 pupils. However, Hanushek studied the same data and
concluded that ``small classes at best make a discernible
difference in kindergarten, but not at later primary grades.''
</P>
<P>
   Such contradictory conclusions have hardly dissuaded of
advocates of Clinton's plan to hire new teachers. ``It's a giant
step in the right direction,'' said Mary Elizabeth Teasley,
director of government relations for the National Education
Association, the nation's largest teachers union.
</P>
<P>
   But Teasley conceded that the growing teacher shortage in many
regions will complicate the effort to find 100,000 qualified new
teachers in the coming years. In fact, a major concern is retaining
new teachers already in the schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very concerned about support for new teachers for the
first three years,'' she said, adding that up to 50 percent of the
newcomers now leave the profession within the first few years.
</P>
<P>
   Nina Chokraii Rees, education policy analyst at the Heritage
Foundation, a conservative research group in Washington, seconded
that observation. Especially in the inner cities where conditions
are the toughest, she said, schools have difficulty keeping their
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new ones won't stay long enough to make a difference,''
Rees said, adding that the government should have begun with the
shortage of quality teachers first.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real problem with teachers is that the teacher training
schools are not attracting the best and the brightest,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The new teacher funds will be divvied up to the states according
to a formula that takes into consideration poverty and population
numbers. The Education Department released estimates Thursday
indicating that California will receive the greatest amount , $129
million, to hire an estimated 3,322 teachers, followed by New York
($140 million and 2,688 teachers) and Texas ($97 million and 2,500
teachers).
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
