<SLUG> BC-TV-BRIMSTONE-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DARK AND MOODY `BRIMSTONE' DEBUTS FRIDAY ON FOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hell hath no fury like a network ignored.
</P>
<P>
   So it is that Fox's gloomy back-from-the-dead adventure
thriller, ``Brimstone,'' makes its debut Friday night at 8 instead
of next Tuesday at 9. The thinking is that ``Brimstone,'' a dark
and moody drama, is a better fit with the dark and moody
``Millennium'' than two underwatched comedies _ ``Living in
Captivity'' and ``Getting Personal'' _ ever were. The programming
executive who scheduled those comedies in front of ``Millennium''
this season has probably been relegated to the network equivalent
of hell, which at Fox would be devising new and creative strategies
for ``World's Wildest Police Videos.''
</P>
<P>
   To make room for ``Brimstone,'' Fox placed ``Living in
Captivity'' on the shelf and canceled ``Getting Personal.'' It also
decided to keep ``Guinness World Records: Primetime,'' an
extravaganza of stupid human tricks originally intended as summer
filler, in the Tuesday slot that was supposed to have gone to
``Brimstone.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a lot of maneuvering to accommodate one new show. But Fox
could use some good news right about now. Three of its new fall
comedies, ``Costello,'' ``Holding the Baby'' and ``Living in
Captivity,'' are already off the schedule, the moving of ``King of
the Hill'' from Sunday to Tuesday has cut its audience almost by
half, and ratings for the just-concluded World Series were weak.
</P>
<P>
   So, who you gonna call?
</P>
<P>
   How about somebody who can take a few bullets to the chest
without wincing? Or can fall off a building and walk away, albeit
stiffly, without having to visit the emergency room?
</P>
<P>
   Ezekiel Stone is your man, especially if you need to round up
escapees from hell.
</P>
<P>
   Stone is a New York police detective who went to hell when he
died because of the vigilante-style justice he administered to the
man who raped his wife. Conventional law enforcement was unable to
bring the criminal to justice, so Stone killed him in cold blood,
then died shortly afterward in the line of duty.
</P>
<P>
   That would be the end of the story, except Fox needs a hit show
and hell seems to have a serious security problem. One hundred
thirteen vile souls have managed to return to Earth, and Satan
wants them back. Stone is picked to handle this last roundup
because he was New York's best detective once upon a time, and he
would very much like to see his wife again. The devil, in fact, has
promised him redemption if he successfully corrals each escapee.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Horton plays Stone as the antithesis of Gary Shepherd, the
fun-loving guy he created on ``thirtysomething.'' Then again, 15
years in hell might dull anyone's sense of fun. So what we get is a
tormented soul, still suffering despite his work-release reprieve,
still wondering about his qualifications for sending people back to
hell.
</P>
<P>
   In the show's third episode, for instance, Stone's
escapee-of-the-week is a rape victim from medieval times who got
revenge by killing her attackers and their families. Stone must
send her back, but, having been deeply affected by the same crime,
he's not sure the woman deserves any more time in hell.
</P>
<P>
   Horton shows a tad more emotion in that episode than he displays
in Friday's premiere, but he's no grim weeper. It seems he and
Michael Madsen of ABC's ``Vengeance Unlimited'' prepared for their
roles with the same minimalist acting coach. They have achieved the
same soto voce murmur, the same sarcastic asides, the same
mysterious, brooding presence.
</P>
<P>
   Though detective Stone occasionally has amusing run-ins with the
devil, played impishly by John Glover, the overall effect of
``Brimstone,'' as any preacher will tell you, is not salubrious.
Reasonably well written, it is nevertheless sullen and moderately
violent _ a real downer that's hard to embrace at the end of a long
week.
</P>
<P>
   Borrowing liberally from ``X-Files''-style themes of fighting
evil supernatural forces, ``Brimstone'' ends up doing it with style
but not a lot of grace: Stone must subdue his targets by destroying
their eyes.
</P>
<P>
   That may change as Ezekiel Stone gets used to tracking down
hell's fugitives. But if one of them shows up on ``Guinness World
Records: Primetime'' trying to cram the Anaheim Angels onto the
head of a pin, you'll know the show's in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Brimstone. Hourlong drama series about a deceased police
detective who is dispatched from hell to round up 113 escapees.
Starring Peter Horton and John Glover. Premieres Friday night on
Fox. Parental guideline rating: TV-14.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B-
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
