<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THREE WOMEN JOURNALISTS WHO ARE HANGING TOUGH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c. 1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Three foreign female journalists stood behind a
podium in the Waldolf Astoria on Wednesday and, one after another
calmly recited the horrors they have endured _ death and rape
threats, kidnapping, acid thrown in a face, years of imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   All for merely doing their job, which is to honestly report what
goes on in their countries.
</P>
<P>
   The women were brought to this country by the International
Women's Media Foundation, which encourages the work of female
journalists abroad and each year highlights the bravery of a few
who literally put their lives on the line every day. There was
scarcely a dry eye in the place as the courageous trio told a
banquet crowd their tales of survival and sacrifice.
</P>
<P>
   American journalists take freedom of the press for granted. As
CBS correspondent Rita Braver observed, ``In our country, if
somebody comes after us, it's usually with a lawsuit.''
</P>
<P>
   But many reporters and editors in corrupt and authoritarian
countries operate under outrageously repressive conditions imposed
by governments that fear public exposure of the truth.
</P>
<P>
   We Americans feel courageous if we defend our reporting against
the criticism of a powerful politician or editor. But the worst
that can happen is that we might be fired. Our foreign colleagues
must sometimes risk their health, their sanity, their very freedom.
Now that calls for true grit.
</P>
<P>
   Anna Zarkova, a veteran reporter at Trud Daily in the Bulgarian
capital of Sofia, writes investigative articles about police
violence, drug trafficking, corruption and the burgeoning criminal
clans in her country. In May, an attacker threw sulfuric acid on
her, severely burning the left side of her face, neck and arm and
potentially blinding her in one eye.
</P>
<P>
   After a long hospitalization, she went back to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us there is no other way,'' she says. ``If they do not
splash acid in your face as a journalist, they will kill you in the
street as a civilian.''
</P>
<P>
   Blanca Rosales Valencia is the editor of La Republica, a
newspaper in Lima, Peru. She says she constantly receives death
threats. Last year she was kidnapped, held at gunpoint and
threatened with rape and death by her captors before finally being
freed in a distant field.
</P>
<P>
   She admits she was terrified, but she continues to go to work
every day. ``Our everyday reality'' she says, is ``the lack of
press freedom.'' She cites the example of a covertly recorded
conversation at a local television station between the producer of
a top-rated program and a government official. The official not
only dictated which information was to be reported that day and
which facts ignored, but the order in which the information should
appear.
</P>
<P>
   The third honoree, Chris Anyanwu, former editor of Zest News
Limited's Sunday Magazine in Lagos, Nigeria, won the International
Women's Media Foundation's Courage in Journalism award three years
ago. She was unable to accept in person because she was behind bars
in a primitive prison, convicted in a secret military court as a
traitor for publishing a story unflattering to Gen. Sani Abacha,
who ruled Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   After Abacha died in June, his successor released her and she
was allowed to come here to tell her story. She says imprisonment
was ``a nightmare.'' But she told herself, ``Don't give in, don't
be an insult to women. Women have not come into this world to fool
around.''
</P>
<P>
   To keep her sanity, she knitted 120 berets in her solitary cell.
She isn't going to give up her chosen profession, either.
</P>
<P>
   Why do these women remain in journalism? Is it really worth the
pain and fear?
</P>
<P>
   They all say that they feel an obligation to help their
countries move toward democracy. ``It is my deliberate choice not
to join the conspiracy of silence,'' Anyanwu says. ``We are in a
frontal fight against corruption,'' Valencia says.
</P>
<P>
   ``After 45 years of being ruled by communist dictators,
Bulgarians are making the first steps as citizens ... if we lose
the battle against the criminals, we might lose everything we have
gained,'' Zarkova says.
</P>
<P>
   It makes covering Washington politics seem very tame.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-98 1720EDT &QL; 
