<HEADER>
A2017 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAIRIES-ART-EXHIBIT-7     10-22 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAIRIES-ART-EXHIBIT-780(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICTORIAN ESCAPISM AND DENIAL WITH THE FASCINATING FAIRIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MICHAEL KIMMELMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It's about sex.
</P>
<P>
   I am, of course, referring to the peculiar and heretofore
obscure Victorian phenomenon known as fairy painting, the subject
of a show at the Frick that is a scaled-back version of a hugely
popular exhibition in London a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   It's not only about sex, because it's also about drugs, some of
the pictures having possibly been painted under the influence of
cocaine, morphine, absinthe or chloroform, all of which were
readily available in Victorian Britain. Narcotics seem to be ``the
stuff,'' for example, in ``The Stuff That Dreams Are Made Of,'' a
picture by John Anster Fitzgerald, who is said to have sustained
his imagination with a steady diet of laudanum, a preparation of
opium, and who, so as to leave no doubt in this case, included
tell-tale medicine bottles in a watercolor version of the painting,
which shows a peaches-and-cream Victorian heroine in a flimsy white
dress conjuring up goblins, satyrs and other Boschian creatures at
her bedside.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis Carroll once counted 165 fairies in ``The Quarrel of
Oberon and Titania'' by a Scottish artist named Joseph Noel Paton,
much admired by Queen Victoria. That's 165 naked women in a single
painting.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, we are told, the British never acknowledged the erotic
content of their fairy paintings, thereby demonstrating a form of
collective sexual denial that is a root of the phrase there'll
always be an England. For the Victorians, it seems, the
un-Disneylike images were sufficiently couched in mythological
terms to allow critics and the public to see the pictures as
respectable, even ennobling variants of history paintings, the
highest endeavors for painters at the time.
</P>
<P>
   For contemporary sensibilities, the pictures are more simply
about sex and drugs, and death, too. (Fitzgerald painted a fairy
funeral, for example.) No wonder the exhibition has been so
popular.
</P>
<P>
   The show's cachet in London had partly to do, I think, with the
current vogue for surrealism. The exhibition was on view there at
the same time as ``Sensation,'' the much-talked-about survey of the
new British shock art, and it made a useful point of comparison:
the gap is very wide between young artists like Matthew Barney, an
American, or the British Chapman brothers, and a fairy painter
like, say, Daniel Maclise, whose ``The Faun and the Fairies'' shows
a particularly malevolent faun among dozens of frisky, frolicking
nymphs. But the divide isn't infinite, and some of the fairy
paintings therefore look oddly up-to-date.
</P>
<P>
   Up-to-date though not precisely a revelation. There are some
very good pictures in the exhibition but only one great one, ``The
Fairy Feller's Master Stroke'' by Richard Dadd. The paintings,
roughly spanning the 1840s through the early 20th century, are
mostly amusing, and above all they are instructive as byproducts,
or symptoms, of a mix of 19th-century cultural phenomena, each of
which is ultimately more significant than the art.
</P>
<P>
   I am talking, for example, about what Charlotte Gere describes
in the exhibition catalog: ``As modern industrial progress engulfed
the English countryside,'' she writes, ``the Victorians embraced
belief in fairies as a reaction to the disenchantment of the
world.'' Fairies provided an escape from a new Darwinian existence
into an occult and magical kingdom that existed apart from urban
society. Fairy paintings show a half-seen, pixie realm in nature.
</P>
<P>
   Akin to that feeling of unease and the desire for escape in the
mid-19th century was a taste for the paranormal, sparked by various
spirit sightings, which made table-turning and seances popular
British pastimes. The new spiritualism, as it was called, cut
across society to include the educated classes, the most famous
example being Arthur Conan Doyle, who, besides writing the Sherlock
Holmes stories, was the son of a fairy painter named Charles Doyle.
</P>
<P>
   From his father, he inherited a belief in the paranormal and
became so convinced of the authenticity of several fairy or spirit
photographs concocted by a pair of English girls in Cottingley,
West Yorkshire, in 1917 that he even wrote a book defending them,
``The Coming of the Fairies.''
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the photographs now look patently fake. Fairy
painting, overlapping with photography and eventually the early
stages of cinema, provided visual evidence of an unseen universe to
a British public (of which Doyle was a late representative) that
longed to believe what it saw. Their faith in make-believe was
probably less a matter of gullibility or collective delusion than
simple nostalgic wishfulness or desire, which the undeniable
brutality of World War I finally brought to an end.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   There was also a good deal of discussion in the middle of the
19th century about the empire's importation of (read: dilution by)
foreign cultures. Fairies, although they came partly from the
German Grimm Brothers, derived from native folklore. The term
folklore is itself Victorian.
</P>
<P>
   What we see at the Frick exemplifies a kind of oblique jingoism,
which can be described as another manifestation of social
insecurity and longing. Fairies derived from Scottish, Celtic,
Irish and Welsh stories and legends and from Shakespeare, whose
fairy plays, ``A Midsummer Night's Dream'' and ``The Tempest,'' had
revivals in 19th-century English theaters where the public also saw
Gilbert and Sullivan's ``Iolanthe'' and ``La Sylphide.''
</P>
<P>
   In an essay in the show's catalog, Jeremy Maas, an expert in
fairy paintings who died recently, stresses the special impact of
ballet and theater: Marie Taglioni in ``La Sylphide,'' he points
out, provided fairy painters with an image of a figure dancing on
the tips of her toes, and a general revolution in stagecraft and
set design increased the public appetite for spectacle and
illusion, blurring the line between what was real and what wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   A few of Thomas Grieve's fantastical watercolors for extravagant
set designs are at the Frick, along with paintings like Robert
Huskisson's ``Come Unto These Yellow Sands,'' based on Ariel's song
in ``The Tempest,'' the image set within a proscenium arch and the
figures spotlighted. Fairy painting became an extension and
reflection of the new forms of theater and thrived as they did.
</P>
<P>
   It was a French painter at the time, Gustave Moreau, who said,
``I believe only in what I do not see,'' which is what the British
fairy painters contended. Besides Moreau, there were artists like
Puvis de Chavannes and Anselm Feuerbach in France and Germany
painting classical images of a strange, dreamy sort that is not
altogether unrelated to fairy painting. My point is that fairy
paintings were just one British manifestation of an escapist ethos
throughout Europe, you might call it the flip side of 19th-century
Realism, which in the singular case of Dadd rose to an exceptional
level because his imagination was stronger and his technique more
exact than any other British fairy painter's.
</P>
<P>
   Dadd's story is familiar by now. Born in 1817, a follower of
Maclise, he was regarded as one of the most promising artists of
his generation, universally liked for his cheerful good nature.
Then he went mad, believing he was persecuted by devils and under
the power of the Egyptian god Osiris. He murdered his father, fled
to France was caught and then was committed in 1844 to the British
lunatic asylum known as Bedlam. He spent 20 years there until
transferring to the new asylum at Broadmoor, where he died of
consumption in 1886.
</P>
<P>
   During his 42 years of confinement he painted, according to an
observer, ``amidst the most revolting conversation and the most
brutal behavior,'' and although once he had a few works exhibited
publicly, basically he was cut off from the world.
</P>
<P>
   His madness inevitably colors how people see the work, but what
makes it remarkable is in part its connection, despite his
isolation, to what was going on in British art. Dadd offers the
prime example of a hyper-precise, narrative style that reached its
apogee in ``The Fairy Feller,'' his insect's-eye view of
Lilliputian figures seen through a scrim of timothy grass.
</P>
<P>
   The image is dense, like woven tapestry, its surface as smooth
and hard as enamel. Dadd spent years on it. Dozens of figures, the
fairy populace of his mind, surround a woodchopper, the fairy
feller, about to split a hazelnut.
</P>
<P>
   Dadd always declined to explain the scene, which has about it a
particular hallucinatory and vaguely menacing quality. I noticed
the other day that the blade of the woodchopper's ax is
conspicuously left unpainted.
</P>
<P>
   Dadd killed his father by stabbing him to death.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
