<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2022 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILMS4KIDS-NYT &LR;      10-22 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILMS4KIDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLAMOROUS WITCHES VS. THE WALKING DEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRACTICAL MAGIC &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Bullock, Nicole Kidman, Dianne Wiest, Stockard Channing,
Aidan Quinn, Goran Visnjic &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by Griffin Dunne &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PG-13 05 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Being from a family of witches, the gorgeous Owens sisters,
Sally (Ms. Bullock) and Gillian (Ms. Kidman), have a problem with
men. By pronouncing a curse on the entire male gender, an Owens
woman of long ago sentenced mates of future generations to a
premature end.
</P>
<P>
   Sally marries a cheery fish merchant, only to have him hit by a
truck. Gillian, though, puts the destructive force to good use and
brings about the demise of her vile boyfriend, a bad idea named
Jimmy (Visnjic).
</P>
<P>
   But Jimmy, now dead and with eyes looking as if they've been
borrowed from a striped bass, won't stay put in the hole the
sisters have dug for him in the back yard of the strikingly
photogenic Owens seaside homestead.
</P>
<P>
   With Gillian possessed by Jimmy's body and soul, the plucky
Sally rallies the neighbors, who swallow their distaste for witches
and pitch in to wield broomsticks and prepare the potions required
to exorcise the evil among them. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE Jimmy cuffs Gillian around and tries to brand her with
his heated-up signet ring. Later there is much seething and
thrashing about as the women battle the dead. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX No action but Gillian vamps about. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY Now and then the obscenities fly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-5 Yes, there are witches, but they look like major movie
stars and come with relationship troubles and other baggage.
Besides, the film is too scary and too confusing. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 6-9 They'll like the idea of witches, but this just isn't a
movie for small children. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 10-12 Ms. Bullock and Ms. Kidman aren't teen-agers, but
they seem to be at times as they bounce about a glossy-magazine
setting. The glamour will appeal, but parents have profanity and
domestic violence to consider. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 13 AND UP By this age, the film could be too tame and a
trifle silly. Teen-agers generally crave stronger stuff. Jimmy is a
creep, but he'd never make it in ``Scream'' or ``Scream 2,'' huge
hits with older adolescents, whose bad boys take no prisoners. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HOLY MAN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Murphy, Jeff Goldblum, Kelly Preston, Robert Loggia &QL; 
Directed by Stephen Herek &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PG 113 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Ricky (Goldblum) and Kate (Ms. Preston) work at a television
shopping channel where they attract and repel each other while
honing pitches for glue guns and love scents.
</P>
<P>
   One day as they are changing a tire on an expressway, they
encounter a smiling, beatific fellow called G (Murphy), who
materializes amid the whizzing traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Kate and Ricky (though he has misgivings) sponsor G and soon the
mysterious visitor _ some kind of holy man? _ proves himself
overpoweringly wise and calming. Put on the shopping channel, he
eschews materialism and becomes a kind of guru to the masses, who
to everybody's delight buy more junk than ever.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the world's leading religions take a crack at
explaining G's views, but only he knows for sure. Now, can he help
Kate and Ricky overcome their differences? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX One fleeting encounter and some smutty references tied to
home shopping. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY Other than the above, none. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-5 Even if they understood, they'd die of boredom. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 6-9 Ditto, especially the boredom. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 10-12 They may be enthused at the prospect of an Eddie
Murphy movie, but be warned that this one is slow and preachy with
no action or payoff that would be of the slightest interest to
children this age. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 13 AND UP Some teen-agers might sit through this film, but
again Murphy is not a particularly lively presence and they'll be
mighty itchy by the time Ricky and Kate get to the last half-hour
with the entire boy-loses-girl-boy-regains-girl sequence still to
go.
</P>
<P>
   Or in this case sales manager loses efficiency expert, which is
another drawback for an audience that doesn't exactly relate to the
travails of 30-something business people. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RUDOLPH THE RED-NOSED REINDEER: THE MOVIE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An animated film with the voices of John Goodman, Debbie
Reynolds, Eric Idle, Bob Newhart and Whoopi Goldberg. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Directed by William R. Kowalchuk &QL;
</P>
<P>
   G 90 minutes &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Trot through the song lyrics and you have the spine of this tale
about gentle Santa (Goodman), the truculent ice queen Stormella
(Ms. Goldberg) and the much-maligned little reindeer called on to
lead the team through socked-in flying conditions. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   VIOLENCE None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SEX None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   PROFANITY None. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Which Children? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   AGES 3-8 The animation certainly isn't of Disney rank, but the
story will divert very little ones. One should also note that films
of this kind often reach the video racks sooner rather than later.
</P>
</TEXT>
