<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SPECIALEFFECTS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIMINISHING EFFECTS: VISUAL GEMS LIKE `PLEASANTVILLE' HARDLY RAISE
AN EYEBROW
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROBERT PHILPOT 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back in 1988, when Bob Hoskins throttled the animated title
character of ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit,'' audiences were stunned.
When we saw this movie, our eyes bugged out as if we were cartoon
characters ourselves.
</P>
<P>
   We'd seen live action and animation mixed before, but it never
looked like this _ you actually believed that Hoskins' hands were
around the neck of a character you knew wasn't real. You couldn't
read about the movie without reading about its effects; you
couldn't see it without being amazed.
</P>
<P>
   Flash forward to Friday, when Gary Ross' fantasy
``Pleasantville'' opens in theaters. The movie centers on a couple
of '90s teens who somehow get sucked into a black-and-white 1950s
sitcom _ and start coloring the world of its characters. The
effects should startle viewers _ in one scene, Jeff Daniels wipes
the black and white off Joan Allen's tear-stained face to reveal
flesh-toned skin _ and yet, the film has received very little
pre-release buzz.
</P>
<P>
   So are we becoming too jaded about what movies can do? If one of
the reasons we see movies is to escape, to visit worlds that we
could never otherwise visit, our increasing sophistication about
how movies are made creates a problem. It's like knowing how a
magic trick is done; once you've been educated, the spell is
broken.
</P>
<P>
   We know, for instance, that ``Pleasantville'' involves a lot of
computer enhancement and digital trickery. And we've grown used to
the movies doing these things. We see such effects not only in
movies, but also in commercials, in music videos, in TV shows such
as ``The X-Files.'' We've come perilously close to taking them for
granted, egged on by the number of effects used just for effects'
sake.
</P>
<P>
   Computer trickery has given filmmakers a lot more visual
freedom, but something has been lost in trade. It's like the
complaint that record collectors make when debating CDs vs. vinyl;
sure, the newer technology is cleaner, but that cleanliness lacks
the warmth of the old style.
</P>
<P>
   That's not to say that moviemakers should turn Amish on us. Tom
Rainone, the Arlington, Texas-bred effects wiz whose work has been
seen on such recent movies as ``Wishmaster'' and ``Star Kid,'' says
that the digital enhancement isn't evil if that's what you use it
for _ enhancement.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you use it as a control device, to clean up some of the
stop-motion effects, it's fine,'' Rainone says. He credits the
influence of such effects pioneers as Willis O'Brien, who set the
standard for stop-motion effects with 1933's still-amazing ``King
Kong,'' and O'Brien's protege Ray Harryhausen, who dazzled with a
series of myth-inspired fantasies such as ``Jason and the
Argonauts'' in the '50s, '60s and '70s.
</P>
<P>
   These older movies look primitive by today's standards, and
that's exactly what's so charming about them. In stop-motion work,
someone had to painstakingly move an 18-inch Kong by hand for frame
after frame to provide the illusion that he's a real, moving, giant
ape.
</P>
<P>
   We marveled at tricks like this for decades. During the
pre-''Star Wars'' '70s, film buffs still gaped at the effects in
1956's ``Ten Commandments'' when it first appeared on TV. The
parting of the Red Sea, achieved through reverse photography, looks
almost hokey now, but it's fun to watch.
</P>
<P>
   Movies such as 1972's ``The Poseidon Adventure'' and 1973's
``The Exorcist'' also had people babbling about their effects.
``Poseidon's'' upside-down luxury liner now looks like it was
filmed in a bathtub, but the knowledge of what it achieved at the
time gives the movie a much-needed boost. Even as recently as 1994,
we were astonished to see Tom Hanks interacting with dead
presidents in ``Forrest Gump'' _ directed, not coincidentally, by
``Rabbit's'' Robert Zemeckis.
</P>
<P>
   But lately, we're becoming spoiled. The past month has brought
us three visually amazing movies: the aforementioned
``Pleasantville,'' DreamWorks' computer-animated ``Antz'' and the
Robin Williams new-age reverie ``What Dreams May Come.'' Yet we've
heard more about ``Antz's'' subversive humor and ``Dreams'''
Kodak-commercial sentimentality than we have about how great the
movies look.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were to play `Antz' to an audience of 8-year-olds and
then play (Harryhausen's) the `Seventh Voyage of Sinbad,' I think
they'd enjoy `Sinbad' more,'' Rainone says. ``For a lot of reasons,
but mostly because it's neater.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, every now and then, people still do things the
old-fashioned way _ and that's when we're most astounded. The best
recent example is ``Titanic.'' Although James Cameron used
computers, his movie was so expensive and took so long to make
partly because he insisted on using a realistic ship, built 70
percent to scale. When the boat starts going down, it looks so real
that it's staggering, and the movie transcends its hoary love story
and clunky dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   But although the old-fashioned way looks better, we're going to
see more and more of the computerized stuff and digital trickery
because of the freedom it allows filmmakers and the time it saves _
and it's just not that impressive anymore.
</P>
<P>
   It'll take a true visionary to stun us again, the type of person
who comes along every 20 years or so. In 1977, it was George Lucas,
whose first ``Star Wars'' still looked incredible in its 1997
reissue. Place your bets on him again: He's under so much pressure
to deliver on his next ``Star Wars'' movie in 1999, he's likely to
pull every trick out of his bag to make our eyes pop out again. But
after he takes us to that next level, where will we go from there?
</P>
<P>
   (Robert Philpot is a film critic for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7872. Visit the
Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
