<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 17:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2040 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LASSO-BOOK-REVIEW-685     10-22 1080
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LASSO-BOOK-REVIEW-685&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`LASSO THE WIND': HOW THE WEST WAS WON, THEN LOST 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Publication notes at end of review.) 
(lb) 
Ed Sylvester is a professor of journalism at Arizona State
University and author of ``The Healing Blade: A Tale of
Neurosurgery.'' 
 By ED SYLVESTER   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hollywood provided the American education about the ``Wild
West'' through most of this century, and two story lines
predominated. Good settlers would be rescued from hostile Indians
by heroic cavalry, and good settlers would be rescued from bullying
big ranchers or outlaw gangs by rambunctious but hard-working and
honorable cowboy heroes.
</P>
<P>
   The cowboy, in particular, had to be all that and more to match
land that was and is rock-hard, prickly and mostly bone dry. Gold
was a fever that drove men crazy, but water drove them to wars
throughout the West.
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly news. The ongoing struggles in courtrooms and at
ballot boxes over water and land use have been well documented in
books, television specials and newspaper articles.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Timothy Egan, a third-generation Westerner who is a
national correspondent of The New York Times, with ``Lasso the
Wind,'' a book that is terse in length and sprawling in scope. In
chapters ranging from Arizona and New Mexico to the Northwest and
California, he covers every hot topic of the New West: Water.
Cattle. Mining. Logging. Sprawl. The clash of cultures. The good
feel of wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   Such sweeping reportage, part travelogue but more essay, is a
time-tested way to cover a huge topic, and the form has been used
successfully since de Toqueville. Here it is only partly
successful, and most of its failings owe something to Egan's
method.
</P>
<P>
   He sets off from a conference on the future of the West at Grand
Teton National Park in Wyoming, with this mission: ``It may be
easier to lasso the wind than to find a sustaining story for the
American West. Still, as storytellers it is our obligation to keep
trying.''
</P>
<P>
   In the best chapters, Egan uses the past powerfully, to explain
and give dimension to the present. We visit the Oregon frontier,
where whites destroyed the Nez Perce led by Chief Joseph. We move
to the present, where that cruelty haunts the town named for
Joseph. The Nez Perce got treaty rights to their land in 1863.
Fourteen years later they were given a week to leave it.
</P>
<P>
   Now, impoverished white settlers whose land is played out by
logging and grazing are enraged that the government is trying to
curtail those activities. They reach back into that past for a most
sovereign right to defend their property from seizure.
</P>
<P>
   We view the ruin of Butte, Mont., a huge chunk of which is now
an open-pit mine; and we stop in agricultural Washington, reluctant
to accept Hispanic mestizo culture where it was born, while relying
on the cheap labor that only Mexicans will provide.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout ``Lasso the Wind,'' Egan develops two themes. First,
by embracing cattle-grazing, logging and mining as the true West,
ordinary working people wind up destroying the beauty and majesty
that drew them there. Second, in claiming their historical rights
to the land and its customs, the descendants of settlers are taking
exactly the same stand as the original Hispanic and Indian
residents did against the settlers.
</P>
<P>
   The book's most powerful scene concludes the chapter on Butte.
Egan depicts a miner who, as his father had, worked for the company
that chewed up city, mountain and countryside. He is telling his
children not to become miners. But he will move on to a new mine
job paying $15 an hour.
</P>
<P>
   ```What good is the money when this place will kill you?'' his
wife asks. ```But look how damn beautiful it is,' the miner says,
dragging on a cigarette and motioning to the mountains all
around.''
</P>
<P>
   The family is sitting at a memorial to 168 miners killed in the
worst mining disaster in U.S. history. In the cemetery, those not
killed in mine accidents usually died of lung diseases. On many
miners' graves are etchings of their beloved mountains. The setting
of such observations side by side is Egan's strong point.
</P>
<P>
   But in between there is too much lassoing of wind, and in
between are most of the words. Using a journey to underlie a book
makes the writer a prisoner of the itinerary. There is a lot of
territory to fill, and a lot of old stories are retold for no new
purpose.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The book's most serious shortcoming is its portrayal of Mormon
history. The problem is not one of historical accuracy, but of tone
and attitude. The chapter on Utah details the infamous Mountain
Meadows massacre of 1857. At least 120 adults and children in a
wagon train were murdered by a band of Mormons fearful that
settlement was a prelude to invasion by the U.S. government.
</P>
<P>
   An account of that awful day belongs in a book about the
past-haunted West, and overall it is well told, though derivative
of the work of Juanita Leavitt Brooks, a courageous Mormon who
first dug the story from families' records and oral histories. But
Egan tells too much of this important chapter with a sneer and
sarcastic asides that are especially inappropriate in a book
exhorting the many cultures of the West to share their common
ground.
</P>
<P>
   He opens the Mountain Meadows episode at the site, quoting the
granite memorial in full. He questions the lack of completeness in
what's there, hinting that some conspiracy of church fathers
prevented including details of who killed whom. He says, ``No stone
commemoration was more fought over.''
</P>
<P>
   But a news-database search on the term ``Mountain Meadows
massacre'' turns up a story on the laying of the memorial in 1990
by descendants of the survivors and descendants of the killers.
</P>
<P>
   The man who organized the reunion, a descendant on the victim
side, said both groups had chosen the words to honor the dead
without punishing the living. The man said, ``Do we want to pass on
to the next generation the animosity and hate that's been passed on
for the last 133 years, or do we want to stop it now?''
</P>
<P>
   Those are good words for the West, and words Egan himself echoes
a dozen times through this adventurous, often powerful, but flawed
look at the American West grappling with its past on the frontier
of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `LASSO THE WIND'
</P>
<P>
   Away to the New West
</P>
<P>
   By Timothy Egan
</P>
<P>
   266 pages. Alfred A. Knopf. $25.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
