Search: (miller and risen)AND(19981015 
(EQ)pdate Your search found 2 articles. This is article 1 
 
October 18, 1998, Sunday Late Edition - FinalSection: 1 Page: 6
Column: 1 Desk: Foreign Desk Length: 1205 words  
 
Backed by U.S., Saudis Seek Afghan Ouster of Bin Laden 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   By JUDITH MILLER and JAMES RISEN  &QL; 
 &QL; 
WASHINGTON, Oct. 17 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Urged on by the Clinton Administration, Saudi Arabia's top
intelligence official met privately with the leader of the Taliban
in late September to try to persuade Afghanistan to deport Osama
bin Laden, the Saudi exile suspected of masterminding the August
bombings of two American embassies in East Africa, according to
United States and Arab officials.
</P>
<P>
   Just weeks after the United States launched a cruise-missile
strike against Mr. bin Laden's terrorist training camps in
Afghanistan, Prince Turki bin Faisal, chief of Saudi intelligence,
sat down with Mullah Mohammed Omar, leader of the Taliban's Supreme
Council, and asked him to end his protection for Mr. bin Laden and
hand him over, Arab officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The Taliban, the Islamic movement that controls most of
Afghanistan, refused. Their recalcitrance in the face of Prince
Turki's personal request finally prompted Saudi Arabia, one of the
Taliban's most important financial sponsors and allies, to
downgrade its diplomatic ties with the group.
</P>
<P>
   American officials say they are supporting diplomatic efforts to
persuade the Taliban to deport Mr. bin Laden. ''Achieving the
expulsion of bin Laden and bringing him to justice is something we
are actively pursuing,'' said a State Department official.
</P>
<P>
   In their effort to persuade Afghanistan to deport Mr. bin Laden,
State Department officials also have spoken to Taliban
representatives themselves and have sought the intercession of
Pakistan, the only other major ally of Afghanistan in the region.
</P>
<P>
   They have also, said an Arab official, talked to members of Mr.
bin Laden's family in Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   If Afghanistan does turn over Mr. bin Laden to Saudi Arabia, it
is possible that Mr. bin Laden might be tried there, rather than in
the United States. If he were to be handed over to the Saudis and
brought back to Saudi Arabia, one Arab official said, he could face
swift execution.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials say they want him to face trial in the
United States. They say they asked the Saudis to urge the Taliban
only to deport Mr. bin Laden. Senior United States officials said
they were not negotiating with the Taliban, but simply repeating
the message that they should get rid of Mr. bin Laden.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've certainly urged, in public and private, all those who
have influence with the Taliban, that it is our strong view Mr. bin
Laden should be expelled and brought to justice,'' a White House
spokesman said. ''We will certainly continue our multi-pronged
strategy of combating Mr. bin Laden's network.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton Administration officials said that the new diplomatic
effort did not preclude further military action against Mr. bin
Laden and his terrorist network. Officials said the Aug. 20
cruise-missile attack was intended to break up the network and
perhaps kill Mr. bin Laden. Since then, the Federal Bureau of
Investigation and other law-enforcement and intelligence agencies
say they are continuing to work with other nations to arrest as
many of Mr. bin Laden's operatives as possible. Mr. bin Laden
already faces criminal charges in the United States under a sealed
indictment handed up by a Federal grand jury in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Pressing the Taliban is part of a broad effort to damage the bin
Laden network, officials say. ''Our tactics may have changed, but
our strategy of putting him out of action remains the same,'' said
a senior American official. ''This is another way of trying to deal
with the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   But critics outside of Government say it also suggests
ambivalence among Administration officials over how best to deal
with the radical Islamic group that now controls most of
Afghanistan.
</P>
<P>
   ''There has been a gap between our interests in Afghanistan and
the level of our attention to the need for a strategy,' said Zalmay
Khalilzad, an Afghan expert at the Rand Corporation. ''A rogue
state could emerge there, so we either need to pay attention now,
or later.''
</P>
<P>
   The Saudi role in trying to extricate Mr. bin Laden from
Afghanistan has been a murky one, complicated by Islamic politics
and the longstanding alliance between the Saudis and the Taliban.
But the Saudi request to the Taliban for Mr. bin Laden represents a
significant shift.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, the Saudis had made it clear that they did not want
Mr. bin Laden brought back to Saudi Arabia, for fear that he could
be a martyr figure to Saudi dissidents. More broadly, United States
officials say they have been frustrated by the Saudis' refusal to
cooperate fully on terrorism investigations in the past, especially
in the case of the 1996 bombing of the American military barracks
at Khobar Towers in Dhahran, Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
   But now, what Administration officials say is the clear evidence
of his involvement in the East African bombings, as well as a
growing belief among Saudi officials that Mr. bin Laden poses a
threat to their Government, seems to have prompted a change in
their strategy.
</P>
<P>
   And, while he is not currently under indictment for any crimes
in Saudi Arabia, Arab and United States officials now say they have
evidence linking him to the 1995 car bombing of a military
installation in Riyadh in which American servicemen were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. bin Laden, who was stripped of his Saudi citizenship in
1994, would face ''swift'' action if he were brought back to Saudi
Arabia, said one Arab official.
</P>
<P>
   Now, even Mr. bin Laden's wealthy Saudi family is cooperating
with the United States and Saudi Arabia on how to bring him to
heel, the Arab official said. The bin Laden family made a fortune
in the construction industry. ''U.S. officials, after Saudi Arabia
blessed it, have talked to members of the bin Laden family,'' the
Arab official said.
</P>
<P>
   After Taliban officials repeatedly said they would consider
turning over Mr. bin Laden if they were presented with evidence
against him, Arab officials familiar with the matter say that
Prince Turki presented evidence to the Taliban of Mr. bin Laden's
involvement in terrorism, but it made no difference. Evidence was
also presented by Bill Richardson, former chief delegate to the
United Nations, when he visited Afghanistan earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton Administration officials, fearing that his return to
Saudi Arabia could lead to trouble for the Saudi Government, stress
that they do not want the Saudis to have Mr. bin Laden brought back
to their country. And they note that the United States does not
have an extradition treaty with Saudi Arabia. The Clinton
Administration is still determined to have Mr. bin Laden put on
trial in the United States, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't have a policy on whether we would accept bin Laden
being brought to justice in a third country, we haven't crossed
that bridge yet,'' one Administration official said. ''But Saudi
Arabia would not be the place where we would want him to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Abdul Hakeem Mujahid, the Taliban's ambassador designate to the
United Nations, confirmed in an interview that his Government's
discussions with Prince Turki over Mr. bin Laden had been
''disappointing.'' but argued that Afghanistan's unwillingness to
oust its ''guest'' would not damage long-term relations between
Afghanistan and Saudi Arabia. He added that his Government would be
willing to try Mr. bin Laden in Islamic court in Afghanistan if
there were ''solid'' evidence against him.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
Copyright 1998 The New York Times Company &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
