u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APPLE'S-LOUISVILLE-AR     10-22 1350
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE'S-LOUISVILLE-ART-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOUISVILLE: FOOT IN THE NORTH, HEART IN THE SOUTH 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
(JT) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ The city began with the river.
</P>
<P>
   As the broad and occasionally unruly Ohio flows southwest from
Pittsburgh toward its rendezvous with the Mississippi, it is
interrupted here by rapids. In 1778, that barrier prompted George
Rogers Clark, a young frontiersman from Virginia, to pause on his
trip west and establish a settlement that eventually grew into
this, the first metropolis west of the Alleghenies.
</P>
<P>
   Clark himself, a brother of Meriwether Lewis' partner, William
Clark, pushed on into the wilderness with a meager little force of
175 men. Marching through primeval forest and across flooded
prairies in a campaign of audacious brilliance, he fought and
defeated the better equipped, more numerous British at isolated
villages in the Northwest Territory _ Vincennes, Cahokia and
Kaskaskia _ securing that vast domain for the fledgling United
States.
</P>
<P>
   In 1809, long retired, Clark returned to Louisville to live out
his final years at his sister's house, Locust Grove. Built in 1790,
meticulously restored in 1962, it stands today as a monument to
Clark's exploits, which are detailed in a nearby visitors center.
But with its Flemish bond brickwork, shellacked ash floors and
original walnut paneling, its gardens and dependencies, Locust
Grove also bears witness to the highly refined tastes of some of
Kentucky's pioneer settlers.
</P>
<P>
   Louisville has preserved other handsome mementos of its early
years. Farmington, an exceptional little federal-style plantation
house with delicate fan lights and a pair of octagonal rooms, was
built to plans by Thomas Jefferson in 1820. Depressed because he
feared that his courtship of Mary Todd had failed, Kentucky-born
Abraham Lincoln took refuge there for six weeks with his friend
Joshua Speed, scion of the family that owned the plantation.
</P>
<P>
   Downtown, the Jefferson County Courthouse, whose pediment is
supported by monumental fluted Doric columns, was built just a
little later, from 1835 to 1860. With a grand cast-iron stairway
and balustrade inside a 68-foot rotunda, it is by Gideon Shryock, a
student of the Philadelphia architect William Strickland, who
designed the Second Bank of the United States. Shryock introduced
the Greek Revival style to the states beyond the Alleghenies.
</P>
<P>
   The county was named, of course, for Thomas Jefferson, whose
statue stands in front of the courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   The city, whose inhabitants call it LOO-uh-vul, all but
swallowing the final two syllables, was named for Louis XVI, the
French king who aided the colonies in their war for independence.
(The Almanac of American Politics, Michael Barone's invaluable
compendium, points out that only one other American city, St. Paul,
Minn., was named for a man who was executed.) Other place names in
Kentucky, including Bourbon County and the towns of Paris and
Versailles, also reflect the new nation's gratitude to France in
the postwar years.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Whisky, Women and Horses &LR;
</P>
<P>
   But ask a native about Louisville and you are likely to hear
about things other than history and architecture. The Kentucky
writers who put together the city's entry in the Depression-era WPA
Guide said it was ``noted for fine whisky, beautiful women and the
Kentucky Derby,'' and it still is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Louisville is too busy making and selling things to have the
languor of a town in the Deep South, but it does have its special
graces,'' the guide adds. ``Its people are friendly and hospitable.
Bourbon and water or a cocktail after work is popular; amusement
and relaxation are as important as work.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost 60 years, three wars and several economic upheavals
later, that description rings as true as ever, down to the last
semicolon.
</P>
<P>
   The city proper has a population of only about 275,000, but its
suburbs spread into three Kentucky counties and four across the
river in Indiana. The metropolitan area has more than a million
people and a big-city feel, with Interstates and freeways circling
and bisecting it. Yet drivers gallantly yield to people in
crosswalks and cars waiting to turn left.
</P>
<P>
   Officially, this is a border city in a border state. Kentucky
stayed in the Union during the Civil War, with Kentuckians fighting
on both sides. But Louisville long ago lost its heart to the South.
Before the war, explained James Holmberg, a curator at the Filson
Club, a Louisville historical society, ``we were a Western city,
but Confederate veterans took over the city and state after the
war. Kentucky was the only state to secede after Appomattox.''
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Maye, a Georgian who came to Louisville by way of
Chicago, says it ``combines Southern rural charm with Northern
urban tolerance.'' It produced not only Louis Brandeis, the first
Jewish Supreme Court justice, but also Muhammad Ali, in whose honor
the city plans a 50,000-square-foot museum, and it was one of the
first cities anywhere to comply with the 1954 desegregation ruling.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Those Exciting Two Minutes &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Come here during Derby Week, the seven days leading up to the
annual Run for the Roses on the first Saturday in May, or the week
before that, and the traffic might make you think you're in
Manhattan or Los Angeles, even if the nonstop Southern belles and
the lawn parties, with lethal mint juleps served in silver stirrup
cups, might remind you rather more of Biloxi or New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   The city plays host to the world with costume balls, the Pegasus
Parade down Broadway, the Great Balloon Race out at the Fairgrounds
and the Great Steamboat Race on the Ohio, punctuated by calliope
toots, between the local stern-wheeler, the Belle of Louisville,
and the larger Delta Queen from New Orleans. Race day itself might
come as an anticlimax if it were not so stirring: the sentimental
strains of Stephen Foster's ``My Old Kentucky Home,'' the clang of
the starting bell and the hell-for-leather charge down the stretch,
jockeys' silks flashing, crowd cheering, steeds straining.
</P>
<P>
   It is indeed ``the most exciting two minutes in sports'' (except
in 1973, when the great Secretariat won in one minute 59 and
two-fifths seconds). It is a parimutuel money-spinner, with $8.3
million bet at the track on the 1998 Derby. It is the only horse
race most Americans pay the slightest attention to.
</P>
<P>
   It is also a hell of a party. A Kentucky judge once said of the
julep that ``he who has not tasted one has lived in vain.'' Not
many of the 130,000 or so people at the Derby in a typical year are
in danger of that.
</P>
<P>
   Churchill Downs, where the race has been run since 1875, is open
almost every day of the year. Tucked beneath the twin octagonal
Edwardian cupolas, the track's trademark, is a museum celebrating
the race, the owners, the trainers, the jockeys and the horses
themselves, from Man O' War, Whirlaway and Citation to the present.
An exciting audiovisual presentation of the most recent race is
projected onto an oval overhead screen. Or maybe you'd like to gawk
at doll houses depicting C.V. Whitney's estate near Lexington,
Maple Hill, or collect trivia like this tidbit: women used to bet
candy or gloves on the race.
</P>
<P>
   Louisville has another sporting claim to fame: it is the home of
the Hillerich &AMP; Bradsby Co., the maker of Louisville Slugger
baseball bats. Lately the company has opened a museum, identified
by a bat 120 feet tall leaning against the building. Here, too,
there is a film, featuring Johnny Bench and Tony Gwynn talking
about hitting in such a lively, understandable way that my wife,
Betsey, a non-fan, was entranced. You can watch bats being made
from ash blanks taken from 50-year-old trees in Pennsylvania and
New York, and view Sluggers used by Babe Ruth and Roger Maris (but
not Mark McGwire, who swings a Rawlings bat).
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
