<HEADER>
A2074 &Cx1f; tab-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WALLSTREET-FAIRYTALE-     10-22 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WALLSTREET-FAIRYTALE-ECONOMIST-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREENSPAN'S MAGIC WAND WON'T ALTER ECONOMIC REALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   From the Economist magazine  
  
 (This ``separate buy'' article is from the current (week beginning
October 24, 1998) Economist magazine.)  
  
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada except to The Toronto Globe &AMP; Mail.)  
  
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndicate sales representative
CONNIE WHITE in Kansas City at 1-800-444-0267 or 816-822-8448, or
fax her at 816-822-1444.)  
  
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
  
 c.1998 Economist Newspaper Ltd.  
 (Distributed by the New York Times Special Features)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stockmarket investors are fond of fairy tales. Until this
summer, their favorite was Goldilocks: the American economy, they
claimed, was neither too hot, nor too cold, but just right. Their
belief in perpetual growth seemed to justify ever-rising share
prices. Pity they forgot that, in the story, Goldilocks was
eventually chased away by the bears.
</P>
<P>
   After the markets fell back in July, the favorite tales changed:
the recent talk has been of something nasty in the woodshed. But as
in all good stories, a fairy godmother has arrived in the nick of
time.
</P>
<P>
   With a flick of his magic wand, and two swift cuts in interest
rates, Alan Greenspan has saved the day. Stockmarkets have rallied;
America's economy will, after all, continue to boom.
</P>
<P>
   Or so ever-optimistic investors hope.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-week, the Dow Jones Industrial Average had gained 13
percent from its low at the end of August, leaving it only 9
percent below its July peak. Share prices have also bounced back in
Asia and Europe. Hong Kong and Bangkok have risen by half since
August.
</P>
<P>
   As well as lower American interest rates, there have been other
bits of (apparently) good news to cheer. The Japanese parliament
has, at long last, approved a plan to make 60 trillion yen ($500
billion) available to help the ailing banking system. America's
Congress has agreed to top up the IMF's coffers by $18 billion,
which should bring in over $70 billion more from other countries
and make it easier to arrange a rescue package for Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   There are glimmers of hope in East Asia, where interest rates
have fallen sharply. And a weaker dollar has eased fears about a
devaluation of the Chinese yuan. All in all, investors might
conclude, the world is no longer coming to an end -- so goodbye,
bears.
</P>
<P>
   But take off the rose-tinted spectacles and the monsters still
loom large. One bank has now said it will apply for Japan's bank
bailout, but it is unclear whether others will follow. Financial
panic may be over in East Asia, but the region's economic troubles
remain daunting. And now a credit crunch threatens in the United
States, and perhaps in Europe, as firms have found raising new
money far harder in securities markets that have all but dried up.
Even a few more quarter-point cuts would not solve these problems.
</P>
<P>
   More pertinently, American share prices remain substantially
overvalued by historic measures. Some bullish analysts have argued
that recent falls in bond yields and the expectation of further
falls in interest rates justify higher share valuations. They have
even been advising investors to put more money into shares.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the main reason that bond yields and interest rates have
come down is concern about financial turmoil and a growing risk of
recession. That points to shrinking profits -- which can hardly be
good for share prices.
</P>
<P>
   It is striking that, even as equity strategists talk up share
prices, economists, often employed in the same firms, are becoming
gloomier about world growth. Many forecasters now expect the world
economy to expand by less than 1.5 percent next year, which by past
standards counts as a recession.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that financial bubbles, unlike fairy tales, never
have happy endings. Greenspan cannot prevent a bear market with a
mere wave of his wand. From the 17th-century Dutch tulip mania
through to emerging-market madness and today's Wall Street, bubbles
always burst eventually -- and the result is always painful.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street's tumble since the summer has been widely blamed on
financial troubles in emerging markets. If so, goes the argument,
brighter prospects in Asia and an IMF package to rescue Brazil
should push share prices back up where they were.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in truth, America's bubble was inflated at home. For over
two years the Fed all but ignored the explosion in share prices and
lax credit conditions. And to the extent that America's rapid
economic growth in recent years has been fuelled by a splurge of
credit and by large capital gains, both its economic and its
financial boom remain unsustainable. A sharp slowdown is
inevitable; a recession is distinctly possible.
</P>
<P>
   Some commentators now seem to view Wall Street as a gauge of
whether the Fed has got things right. A rise in share prices is
taken to mean that Greenspan has understood what needs to be done
to avoid troubles ahead.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a bad test. Central banks cannot and should not try
to prevent an overdue correction in share prices. They should only
cushion the economy from the worst consequences.
</P>
<P>
   The zeal with which Wall Street has cheered Greenspan's latest
rate cut shows that investors still miss the point: even in fairy
tales, what goes up does eventually come down.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-98 1742EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981022.0290 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2075 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APPLE'S-LOUISVILLE-AR     10-22 1259
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE'S-LOUISVILLE-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 LOUISVILLE: Rawlings bat.)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; A Museum's Holdings &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Down Third Street at the far end of the neighborhood known as
Old Louisville stands the J.B. Speed Art Museum, one of the premier
cultural institutions in a city that has a lot of them for its
size.
</P>
<P>
   Recently remodeled, the Speed has a tureen by Paul Storr, a
beautiful second century A.D. Roman altar supported by two lions, a
fine early Rembrandt portrait of a woman (the mate of a male
portrait in the Norton Simon Museum in Pasadena, Calif.), a set of
folding screens painted in 1911 by Everett Shinn for the interior
designer Elsie de Wolfe, and the wooden paneling of an entire
reception room, complete with spectacular carving, from a manor
house in Broadhembury, Devon, England. Dating from 1619, it was
removed when the house was pulled down, sold to William Randolph
Hearst at the peak of his collecting mania, then resold to a
Louisville patron who gave it to the museum.
</P>
<P>
   Odd, the way places catch up to you: the manor house, called the
Grange, belonged to a family named Drewe. For years, Betsey and I
have been stopping for lunch at a pub in that same speck of a
village, on our way from London to visit friends in Devon. The pub
is called the Drewe Arms. Snap.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the city's best sculpture, including pieces by Calder,
Dubuffet, Tony Smith, Louise Nevelson and John Chamberlain, is
gathered in and around the Kentucky Center for the Arts, a big,
glistening glass box. Its three stages provide homes for
Louisville's resident opera, ballet and symphony orchestra, plus
touring Broadway musicals and concerts from bop to bluegrass.
</P>
<P>
   The Louisville Orchestra, which celebrated its 60th anniversary
last year, has a reputation extending well beyond the region.
Beginning in 1953, under its founding conductor, Robert Whitney, it
has recorded several hundred previously unavailable works by more
than 250 composers, including Ginastera, Ives, Villa-Lobos, Piston
and Britten. Battered like many similar groups by drastic
reductions in funds in the 1980s, the orchestra finally returned to
the black in 1996 and named a new principal conductor, the Israeli
Uriel Siegel, for this season. It opened in mid-September with
Pinchas Zuckerman as violin soloist.
</P>
<P>
   A Tony Award-winning regional theater company, the Actors
Theater, occupies a Greek Revival bank building on Main Street,
built in 1837 (and erroneously thought for a long time to have been
designed by Gideon Shryock). Each winter the Actors Theater stages
a highly regarded Festival of New American Plays.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Innovative Leaders &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The city's civic and artistic life has been blessed by a
succession of innovative and capable mayors, including Wilson
Wyatt, a founder of Americans for Democratic Action; Harvey Sloane,
and the present incumbent, Jerry Abramson.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Louisville's cultural life was underwritten for years by
the Bingham family, as was the Falls Fountain, built in 1988. Best
seen from the Riverfront Belvedere or the Riverwalk, it spews water
to a height of 375 feet from the midst of the Ohio River. In
theory, it forms a fleur-de-lis, the city's official symbol, but to
be honest, you'd have to have a Rorshachian imagination to see much
of anything except a lot of splashing water.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Worth Bingham bought The Louisville Courier-Journal in
1917 from Henry Watterson, one of the greatest of 19th-century
American editors. In 1933, he went to London to serve as U.S.
ambassador, and his son, Barry, took over the paper. Barry Bingham
and his wife, Mary, rapidly became a dominant force in Louisville
political, cultural and philanthropic circles; he and Wilson Wyatt,
boyhood chums, worked in close partnership.
</P>
<P>
   But the Bingham children squabbled over their inheritance, and
the paper was sold in 1986. It has lost much of its zest under its
less open-handed new owner, the Gannett chain, and many Louisville
charities have felt the loss of the Binghams' leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Happily for the city, however, others have stepped in, notably
the family of David Jones, founder of Humana Inc., the health-care
company. Humana's headquarters, a salmon-pink skyscraper, is one of
Louisville's most distinctive buildings; its entrance is flanked by
Busby Berkeley waterfalls refashioned in Michael Graves'
post-modern idiom. Almost next door stands the American office of
the Aegon Insurance Group, a good-looking 1992 tower by John Burgee
and Philip Johnson whose openwork cap has led irreverent locals to
christen it ``the Ban roll-on building.'' The two contrast sharply
with other contemporary structures downtown, a thoroughly mediocre
group. Worst are the Waterfront Plaza Towers, with gaudy
scarlet-and-white ``lighthouses'' on their roofs.
</P>
<P>
   The waterfront itself has been redeveloped to great effect,
making it possible to walk for miles along the Ohio. You can also
follow the river upstream along River Road to some of Louisville's
prettiest suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Fried Chicken and Bourbon  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Humana and other companies in its field are among Louisville's
biggest employers; there are no fewer than 15 hospitals in the
city. The city is also the global hub for United Parcel Service,
which provides 14,500 local jobs, more than any other single
company. General Electric makes appliances here, Philip Morris and
Brown &AMP; Williamson make tobacco products and Brown Forman and
United Distillers make bourbon. Tricon Global, the new corporate
tent for Taco Bell, Kentucky Fried Chicken and Pizza Hut, has its
headquarters here, too.
</P>
<P>
   But if you want to experience the definitive Kentucky fried
chicken , and explore the bourbon belt, the best thing is to head
south to Bardstown, one of the state's oldest communities. It was
founded in 1775, the year of Paul Revere's ride in far-off
Massachusetts, and its streets are lined with 18th- and early
19th-century houses. More to the point, it has Kurtz's, where
Marilyn (Toogie) Dick serves her glorious fried chicken to hordes
of hungry people each weekend, some of whom come all the way from
Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   Suitably fortified, you can use Bardstown as a base to learn
more about bourbon, the corn-based whisky that made Kentucky famous
(along with Daniel Boone and racehorses). This is the state, it has
been said, ``where the corn is full of kernels and the colonels are
full of corn.'' So visit the Oscar Getz Museum of Whiskey History
in Bardstown to soak up distilling lore.
</P>
<P>
   Then move on to Maker's Mark in Loretto, a charming old
distillery. Its whisky is much loved by Kentuckians, for its red
wax seal and its distinctively mellow flavor. That results in part
from using winter wheat, instead of rye, along with corn and malted
barley. Near Versailles is Labrot &AMP; Graham, perhaps the most
picturesque of the distilleries; Woodford Reserve, the company's
small-batch bourbon, has the savor of a French Armagnac, with a
typical ``hot'' finish.
</P>
<P>
   If you have more time, spend a morning in the more abstemious
atmosphere of the restored Shaker Village of Pleasant Hill, near
Harrodsburg. The triumph of the place is not the 33 brick, frame
and stone buildings, or the clever, handsome furniture or even the
wonderful twin spiral staircases at the Trustees' House. The
triumph is the sense of serenity _ or is it spirituality? _ that
visitors feel, far from the roar of the interstate and the clamor
of the city, surrounded by ponds and meadows where sheep may safely
graze.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
