<HEADER>
A2081 &Cx1f; taf-z
u t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-APPLE'S-LOUISVILLE-AR     10-22 1653
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-APPLE'S-LOUISVILLE-ART-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 LOUISVILLE: safely graze.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; From a Shaker Village To Whisky and Racetracks &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Here is information about visiting Louisville, Ky.: &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Where to Stay
</P>
<P>
   THE CAMBERLEY BROWN, 335 West Broadway, (502) 583-1234. Echoes
of Derby frolics past resound through the magnificent marble halls
of the 75-year-old Brown, Louisville's old-money hotel. Ornate
chandeliers, collections of equine paintings and sculptures and a
registration desk concealed behind gilded screens enrich the lobby.
Guest rooms, some a trifle small, are nicely appointed. Double
room: $189; special rates may be available.
</P>
<P>
   SEELBACH HILTON, 500 Fourth St., (502) 585-3200. Opened in 1905,
the Seelbach served as a model for a scene in ``The Great Gatsby.''
It was restored in the early 1980's, but some rooms and bathrooms
have grown shabby since; another facelift is needed and planned
soon, to the tune of $3.2 million. The lobby, with murals
illustrating Kentucky history, begs for better lighting. Double
rooms: $159 to $209; based on availability, special rates of $99 on
weekends and $129 on weekdays, including Continental breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   HYATT REGENCY, 320 West Jefferson St., (502) 587-3434, offers
the usual amenities of the chain hotels, but it, too, is starting
to look a little tired. Nonetheless, the Hyatt's downtown location
is convenient, and the tennis court, indoor pool and 18-story
atrium are strong selling points. A revolving rooftop restaurant
overlooks the river, if you like that sort of thing. Double rooms:
$99 to $120 on weekends; $169 to $210 on weekdays.
</P>
<P>
   OLD LOUISVILLE INN, 1359 South Third St., (502) 635-1574. Third
Street is lined with Gilded Age houses of every description from
Richardsonian Romanesque to Eastlake Victorian, many of them
carefully restored. One such is the Old Louisville Inn, a well-run,
10-room bed-and-breakfast with 12-foot ceilings, which was built in
1901 as the baronial residence of a telephone tycoon. Double rooms:
$95 to $135.
</P>
<P>
   Where to Eat
</P>
<P>
   CLUB GROTTO, 2116 Bardstown Rd., (502) 459-5275. Big Jim
McKinney says he knows 90 percent of the customers who visit his
animated, red-walled, low-ceilinged bistro. The menu reflects an
aversion to shortcuts: mozzarella is made in the house, barbecued
shrimp are served in a sauce based on lobster stock. Try
cornmeal-breaded fried walleye or the 11-vegetable ``orgy.''
</P>
<P>
   J. GRAHAM'S CAFE, in the Camberley Brown (see above), is a
glorified coffee shop that serves an authentic Hot Brown sandwich,
an old Louisville favorite invented at the hotel. Toast triangles
in an ovenproof dish are covered with shaved turkey breast, Mornay
sauce, smoky Kentucky bacon, Parmesan and tomato wedges and
finished under the broiler. Result: a cheese dream with a Ph.D.
Open for breakfast and lunch only: Mondays through Saturdays, 6:30
a.m. to 3 p.m.; Sundays, 7 a.m. to 3 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   KURTZ'S, 418 East Stephen Foster Avenue, Bardstown, (502)
348-8964. Don't look for furbelows in this old stone house. Kurtz's
has been there since 1937, serving chewy, salty Kentucky ham;
crisp, greaseless chicken fried in deep cast-iron skillets;
blini-shaped fried cornbread, soufflelike corn pudding,
home-pickled beets and mashed potatoes better than your
grandmother's. Oh, my.
</P>
<P>
   LILLY'S, 1147 Bardstown Rd., (502) 451-0447. Lilly's served us
the best meal of a recent visit to Louisville. ``God bless our
local farmers!'' the menu said; I understood why after eating a
stack of phyllo rounds and ripe tomato slices topped with warm goat
cheese. Even better: juicy roast pork tenderloin with a spicy
red-brown sauce, gossamer cornbread and wasabi slaw.
</P>
<P>
   LYNN'S PARADISE CAFE, 984 Barret Avenue, (502) 583-3447. Who
needs a barrel of monkeys? Nothing could be more fun than Lynn
Winter's place, with an eight-foot-tall coffee pot out front,
corncob murals and a zany array of hideous lamps. Four thousand
people a week come for gotta-try-'em grits or French toast at
breakfast, meatloaf at lunch and Lynn's warming smile all day long.
</P>
<P>
   THE OAKROOM, in the Seelbach Hilton (see above), features
Kentucky products, from smoked spoonfish and Newsom's hams to
mangolike papaws, gathered by foragers in Appalachia. The gifted
chef, Jim Gerhardt, also marinates pork, the local meat of choice,
in bourbon and molasses and pairs it with a fruit compote. Fine
wines and cheeses are chosen by Adam Seger, the maitre d'hotel.
Open daily 5:30 to 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   VINCE STATEN'S, 9219 U.S. Highway 42, Prospect, (502) 228-7427.
A co-author of the standard guide to the nation's barbecue
restaurants, Vince Staten runs a joint of his own in the suburbs.
The decor is plastic, but not the food. Ribs and pulled pork
sandwiches are succulent, as are the beans and coleslaw; Staten's
offers six sauces, culminating in Legal Limit hot. Attractions
</P>
<P>
   LOCUST GROVE, 561 Blankenbaker Lane, (502) 897-9845. A 1790
Georgian mansion on 55 acres six miles up river from downtown,
restored and furnished to its original appearance. Hours: Mondays
through Saturdays, 10:00 a.m. to 4:30 p.m.; Sundays, 1:30 p.m. to
4:30 p.m.; last tour at 3:30 p.m. Admission: $4; $3 for the
elderly; $2 for children 6 to 12; children 5 and under free.
</P>
<P>
   FARMINGTON, 3033 Bardstown Rd., (502) 452-9920. Built in 1810
after a plan designed by Thomas Jefferson and furnished with
19th-century pieces. Hours: Mondays through Saturdays, 10 a.m. to
4:30 p.m.; Sundays, 1:30 to 5 P.M; last guided tour at 3:45 p.m.
Free parking. Admission: $4; $3 for visitors 60 and over; $2 for
students 18 and under; children under 6 free.
</P>
<P>
   CHURCHILL DOWNS AND THE KENTUCKY DERBY MUSEUM, 700 and 704
Central Avenue, (800) 273-3729. The three-floor museum has
exhibitions, racing artifacts and memorabilia about thoroughbred
racing and the Kentucky Derby. Off-season, a walking tour of the
racetrack takes visitors to the paddock, under the grandstand via
the same tunnel the horses use, and to trackside to see the finish
line, the winners circle and the famous twin spires. Weather
permitting, 30-minute tours are given hourly, with the first at
9:45 a.m. and the last at 3:45 p.m. Admission: $6; $5 for ages 55
and older; $2 for ages 5 to 12; children 4 and under, free.
</P>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE SLUGGER MUSEUM, 800 West Main St., (502) 588-7228.
Look for what may be the world's tallest bat perched outside the
door. After a short film, visitors walk through the full-size
dugout and onto the museum's playing field. There are exhibitions,
interactive displays (the sensation of a 90 m.p.h. pitch coming at
you), baseball equipment and memorabilia. ``Baseball's
Revolutionary Louisville Slugger Remembers Babe Ruth,'' featuring
original photographs, artifacts and memorabilia, is on view through
October. Hours: Mondays through Saturdays, 9 a.m. to 5 p.m. Tours
every 20 minutes, lasting about 90 minutes. Admission: $5; $4.50
for the elderly; $3 for children 6 to 12; under 6, free.
</P>
<P>
   J.B. SPEED ART MUSEUM, 2035 South Third St., (502) 634-2700.
``Ansel Adams, a Legacy: Masterpieces From the Friends of
Photography Collection'' is on view through Nov. 15. Tickets: $7;
$6 for the elderly; $4 for children. Hours: Tuesdays, Wednesdays
and Fridays, 10:30 a.m. to 4 p.m.; Thursdays, to 8 p.m.; Saturdays,
to 5 p.m.; Sundays, noon to 5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   KENTUCKY CENTER FOR THE ARTS, 501 Main St., (502) 584-7777 or
(800) 775-7777. Saturday at 8 p.m., the Louisville Orchestra, with
the cellist Gustav Rivinius, plays Elgar's Cello Concerto; Uriel
Segal, conductor. Tickets: $11 to $52. From Thursday to Nov. 1:
``Bachiana,'' a premiere by David Parsons, with the Louisville
Ballet. Tickets: $16 to $46.
</P>
<P>
   THE ACTORS THEATER, 316 West Main St., (502) 584-1205. In the
Pamela Brown Auditorium, the musical ``Peter Pan,'' with music by
Jule Styne and lyrics by Carolyn Leigh. Through Sunday. Friday
night at 8; Saturday at 2:30 and 7:30 p.m. Tickets: $16 to $40. In
the Bingham Theater, ``Dracula,'' adapted from Bram Stoker by
Hamilton Deane and John L. Balderston. Through Oct. 31. Friday
night at 7:30; Saturday at 2 and 8 p.m.; Sunday at 2 and 7 p.m.
Tickets: $10 to $22. Michael Frayn's ``Noises Off'' begins
Wednesday and runs through Nov. 22. Tickets $16 to $40. ``A Tuna
Christmas'' begins Nov. 5 and runs through Dec. 27. Tickets: $10 to
$22.
</P>
<P>
   OSCAR GETZ MUSEUM OF WHISKY HISTORY, Bardstown Historical
Museum, Spalding Hall, 114 North Fifth St., Bardstown, (502)
348-2999. The museum focuses on the history of Kentucky and whisky.
Hours: Mondays through Saturdays, 9 a.m. to 5 p.m.; Sundays, 1 to 5
p.m. Free.
</P>
<P>
   SHAKER VILLAGE, 3501 Lexington Rd., Pleasant Hill, (800)
734-5611. A self-guided walking tour includes 15 restored buildings
with original and reproduced 19th-century Shaker furniture and
household items. Artisans in costume work at 19th-century trades.
Shaker music is performed four times daily from April through
October. Hours through October: Daily, 9:30 a.m. to 5:30 p.m.
Admission: $9.50; $5 for children 12 to 17; $3 for children 6 to
11; under 6, free; family package, $25. A riverboat excursion along
the Kentucky River Palisades is held daily through October at 10
a.m., noon, 2, 4 and 6 p.m.; tickets: $6; $4 for those 12 to 17; $3
for children 6 to 11; under 6, free.
</P>
<P>
   Getting There
</P>
<P>
   CONTINENTAL AIRLINES has two nonstop flights from Newark
International Airport on weekdays. The unrestricted round-trip fare
is $854; $533 if purchased one week in advance; $230 if purchased
two weeks in advance and travel includes a Tuesday or Wednesday
trip; $261 if purchased two weeks in advance, with a Saturday
overnight stay. Information: (800) 525-0280.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. AIRWAYS has a daily nonstop flight from La Guardia Airport.
The cheapest fare, $244, requires a 21-day advance reservation and
a Saturday overnight stay and has other restrictions. The fare with
no restrictions is $867.90. Information: (800) 428-4322.
</P>
