<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2085 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT &LR;      10-22 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT THE MOVIES: COLD WAR MOOSE ON THE LOOSE; NEFARIOUSNESS WITH A
TWIST; A LEAP FOR TOMLIN  
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JAMES STERNGOLD   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ The Cold War produced plenty of victims, but the
ending of the Cold War has had its victims, too. The
military-industrial complex is a shadow of its former size, the
backyard bomb-shelter business has died, and Rocky and Bullwinkle
have become forgotten heroes without a Boris Badenov or Natasha
Fatale to pursue.
</P>
<P>
   Or so we thought. Evil has a way of adapting itself to every
generation, and Boris and Natasha and their fearless leader,
Fearless Leader, have emerged from the '60s and reinvented
themselves as villains for the millennium; now they have a scheme
to take over the world by taking over television. Only a flying
squirrel and a 7-foot-tall moose can stop them.
</P>
<P>
   Universal Studios and TriBeCa Pictures, Robert De Niro's film
company, are preparing to make a big-budget movie based on the old
Rocky and Bullwinkle cartoon show, with filming set to begin in
January. The director will be Des McAnuff, who won a Tony in 1993
for directing on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   The movie intends to be more than just another retread for
nostalgic baby boomers. Like the original show, noteworthy for its
mocking, satirical edge and wordplay, the picture will be
self-mocking with an edge of tart political satire as it takes on
the media in the latter years of the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   ``The whole premise is, `Gee, the world has changed,''' said
Jane Rosenthal, the movie's producer. ``They sort of drop in and
the Cold War is over and they wonder what evil spies do now. Well,
they seek world domination through TV.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie will be shot in live action, with only Rocky and
Bullwinkle done in an old-fashioned cartoon style. None of the
casting has been formalized, but De Niro is expected to play the
Fearless Leader.
</P>
<P>
   Stacey Snider, president of production at Universal Pictures,
said that as part of the plot the two cartoon characters,
subsisting on tiny syndication checks from the show's diminishing
reruns, contemplate making a Rocky and Bullwinkle movie. They go to
a studio executive, Mini Mogul, to pitch their idea. Her boss
rejects the notion, insisting he does not do moose movies. And Jim
Carrey rejects the lead role because he does not want to walk
around in a heavy, hot moose suit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We admit throughout that we're in a movie,'' McAnuff said.
``And we'll have that narrator's voice coming in explaining things.
It's like breaking through the fourth wall of the theater.''
</P>
<P>
   The duo find redemption by frustrating the plot of Boris and
Natasha, but only after a string of misadventures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sort of parachute these Cold War icons into our own day and
age, and what it does is remind us how cynical we've become,''
McAnuff said. ``They bring a kind of clarity to the age of
information through their bumbling. This great big stupid moose
comes up with these gems of truth.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``It gets farcical and there's lots of satire, but the
art is to not overdo it. It's like extracting the essence of
reality.''
</P>
<P>
   Bad Guys Who Are Hip
</P>
<P>
   You know that cool guy, the insouciant character who rejects the
establishment, as demonstrated by his yellow-tinted glasses and
unkempt short hair dyed dark red or defiantly spiky hair pushed
straight up. Now imagine that that guy is working for the
government and out to destroy you, using every bit of computer
technology that exists.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the post-Cold War nightmare of Tony Scott. The new
thriller he has directed, ``Enemy of the State,'' due out on Nov.
20, is a relatively standard film of paranoia about a battle of the
little man against overwhelming forces. But there is a twist. In
this bleak view, the hipsters we learned to trust because they
fought the accepted order and pushed creativity ahead of conformity
are now the ones tracking the individualists down, ruthlessly.
</P>
<P>
   Scott's view is not too bleak because the good guys _ one,
played by Will Smith, in a Brooks Brothers suit, and the other,
Gene Hackman, a nondescript everyman in a flannel shirt and
horn-rimmed glasses _ win. But, the movie asks, what kind of
victory is it?
</P>
<P>
   In the film, Smith is a Washington labor lawyer fighting with
some mobsters when a chance encounter with an old classmate turns
his life upside down and he suddenly finds himself struggling
against the awesome resources of the National Security Agency. The
mastermind of the plot against him is a rogue spymaster, played by
Jon Voight, made up as a carbon copy of former Defense Secretary
Robert McNamara. The malevolent force behind all this intrigue is
the telecommunications industry. The old communists look like
pushovers by contrast.
</P>
<P>
   Scott said the point of the movie, which cost roughly $85
million, was to reverse expectations by making the characters
usually presented as nefarious government geeks into hipsters
rather than warped super-patriots. The conservative characters with
the brush cuts are now the good guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was more spooky that way,'' Scott said. ``The
world's changed. The tables have turned. That's what I was aiming
to show here.''
</P>
<P>
   But Scott said the movie is not off the mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't make a commitment to a film until I check it out, and
I was able to toy around at the CIA and NSA,'' he said. ``I was
amazed. It was like the campus of UCLA. They were all kids and they
looked like these guys in the movies, sitting with their laptop
computers. I took a leaf out of the reality book when I made it
this way.''
</P>
<P>
   The young agents are meant to be particularly intimidating to
aging baby boomers, Scott said. But he said that at age 54, he does
not regard members of Generation X as rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm around kids like that all the time, but I'm a leech,''
said Scott, who has legions of young people working for him at his
commercial film company. ``I steal from them all the time. I steal
their ideas. I steal their energy. I respect those guys. But a
little fear is probably not a bad thing.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
