u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2NDTAKE     10-22 0487
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AT-THE-MOVIES-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 HOLLYWOOD: bad thing.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Nurturing Tomlin
</P>
<P>
   Lily Tomlin has proved her versatility many times over, with
everything from a well-received one-woman show on Broadway to movie
roles like the recent part of an aging producer of LSD in
``Flirting With Disaster,'' and characters like her famed telephone
operator from her television days. But making the leap to play an
American lesbian archeologist in Italy during World War II was
something new.
</P>
<P>
   In ``Tea With Mussolini,'' which will open in late November, Ms.
Tomlin takes on an unusual dramatic role that not only gave her a
chance to try something different, but also took her to Italy for
three months and put her in company that, she said, left her awed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tea With Mussolini,'' directed by Franco Zeffirelli, is based
on a chapter in his autobiography that tells the story of his
boyhood. Zeffirelli was illegitimate, and his father took little
responsibility for his upbringing. After his mother died, he was
taken under the wing of a group of odd English women in Florence,
who cared for him during the war.
</P>
<P>
   The women are played by some of the grande dames of the British
theater _ Joan Plowright, Maggie Smith and Judi Dench. But
Zeffirelli added two characters for the film.
</P>
<P>
   Cher plays Elsa, an amorous American art dealer who is part of
their circle, and Ms. Tomlin is Georgie, the archeologist, who is
aggressive and protective of this unlikely band of eccentrics who
are struggling to get by as the clouds of war gather. Georgie
teaches the Zeffirelli boy, Luca in the film, to play soccer.
</P>
<P>
   The British women embrace the idea that Mussolini is not such a
bad dictator until Elsa, who is exposed as a Jew, is threatened.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first heard about the part, it was actually pretty
negligible, but I just didn't want to pass this up,'' Ms. Tomlin
said from Los Angeles, where she was filming an episode of one of
her favorite television shows, ``The X-Files.''
</P>
<P>
   And then, she added: ``Franco rewrote it. Making this was
hilarious, scary, exhilarating, insecure-making. It was everything.
Frustrating. I felt like a bobby-soxer around these people.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Tomlin said that half the fun was swapping stories and
hanging out with the distinguished cast in between takes, but that
the work could get intense because of Zeffirelli's famous
perfectionism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Franco is completely, um, unique,'' she said, fighting for the
diplomatic phrase. ``He's inspiring. He's spoiled. He's
infuriating. He's endearing, all in one day. You would see him do
the most impassioned things.''
</P>
<P>
   Some modifications had to be made for Ms. Tomlin's character.
</P>
<P>
   ``In one scene she has to swing up these big suitcases,'' Ms.
Tomlin recalled, ``and I just said, `I can't do that physically.'
We had to change it a bit, but she still came through, even with
all those great ladies around. What a trip.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
