<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-BUDDY-1023-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DIPLOMATIC TAILS: CLINTON EVEN USES BEST 'BUDDY' AT WYE TALKS
 &HT;    With MIDEAST-TALKS-1023.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WYE MILLS, Md. _ U.S. officials have used dogs to sniff out
drugs, hunt down bombs and hold would-be attackers at bay.
</P>
<P>
   But can man's best friend help make peace?
</P>
<P>
   The answer's a bit fuzzy, but here's a tail that's on point.
</P>
<P>
   When President Clinton journeyed to the sprawling Wye River
Conference Center earlier this week to try to press forward the
Israeli-Palestinian peace summit, he took a break with U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright. Strolling around a nearby
farm, they came upon a litter of young golden retrievers for sale.
</P>
<P>
   Not even the president and his top diplomat, it turns out, could
resist puppies. And so, before returning to the tough business of
bargaining for peace with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, they toyed with the
retrievers for some time.
</P>
<P>
   That gave Clinton an idea.
</P>
<P>
   When he returned to Wye on Thursday to try to hammer eight days
of talks to a conclusion, Clinton brought along Buddy, his year-old
Chocolate Labrador.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after Clinton and the First Dog disembarked from the
presidential helicopter, Marine One, White House spokesman Joe
Lockhart told reporters that Buddy had ''met'' one of the Middle
East leaders. In the spirit of fairness, he declined to reveal
which one -- clearly not wanting to risk tipping the balance of
access at a critical moment in the peace talks.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what Buddy brought to the talks, all Lockhart could say
was a ''canine perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   After eight inconclusive days here, that might have been about
the only point of view not yet fully aired.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
