<HEADER>
A2094 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VAUTIER-ART-EXHIBIT-7     10-22 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VAUTIER-ART-EXHIBIT-710(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THIS CLOWN PRINCE, ART HERE, ART THERE, ART EVERYWHERE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By VICKI GOLDBERG   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Sometimes, these days, it can be awfully hard to
distinguish a work of art from the objects that stray into the rest
of life. Artists like it that way. They have been trying to widen
the boundaries of art land since the second decade of this century
and began really strenuously hacking at the borders in the 1960s.
The ultimate grand, inclusive, generous gesture made by the French
artist Ben Vautier was the declaration that ``Everything is art,''
which rather mitigated the importance of distinctions. (On the
other hand, maybe this was the ultimate cop-out.)
</P>
<P>
   Ben, as he usually styles himself, is appearing in three shows
in New York: ``Ben Vautier: Statements with Clocks,'' at the John
Gibson Gallery in SoHo; with one large piece, ``Gallery One,'' in
``Premises: Invested Spaces'' at the Guggenheim Museum SoHo; and
``Ben Vautier: Photo Rejects,'' at the Zabriskie Gallery on East
57th Street. Lots of Ben: joy to the world.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, Ben's manifesto of total inclusion perfectly
suited the Fluxus group, who believed that art and life should
cohabit whether legally married or not. The utopian idea that art
was everywhere, for everyone, that indeed everyone was an artist
and everything art, certainly changed the course of art making. It
also stirred a certain sense of puzzlement in the hinterlands and
prompted the creation of an entire literature in an arcane language
called artspeak. As for photography, it made answering that
persistent question ``But is it art?'' a whole lot easier.
</P>
<P>
   One of the nicest aspects of the notion that anything could be
art was that some of its adherents (more so in the early days)
considered it a license to have a good time and chaff just about
anything they could think of, especially the holy writs of art.
George Maciunas, who thought up the name Fluxus, once pronounced
the movement ``the fusion of Spike Jones, vaudeville, gag,
children's games and Duchamp.''
</P>
<P>
   Ben Vautier is one of the devoted, amusing, thoughtful and silly
members of the old Fluxus group. His show at the John Gibson
Gallery is a glancing discourse on time, consisting of various
clocks and brief apercus that he wrote beneath them on a recent
trip when he whizzed into the gallery. The show has moments of
sweet appeal and off-balance wisdom like ``Time is too short to
spend it on your knees,'' or, in Ben's typically unpunctuated,
run-on, ardently ambiguous prose, ``to stop time suicide.'' But
he's not La Rochefoucauld, and the charm here is a little slight at
times.
</P>
<P>
   The Guggenheim's ``Gallery One'' is a re-creation in the spirit
of ``Ben's Window,'' a store window that he lived in publicly for
15 days in London in 1962. Ben and his life were the display. Ben
and his life were art. On a table in the window at the Guggenheim,
a small frame that might be expected to hold his wife's or
daughter's photograph or perhaps a mirror says, ``Don't look at
me,'' highlighting the private-public nature of this art and the
observer's precarious position between an invitation to voyeurism
and Mum's preachments about not staring. Ben wrote on the window
and furniture, too, things like ``beauty is awful'' and the
portentous ``everything is art.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, he took his personal theater into the street as
part of the effort to bring art to everyone. In France, he sat on a
chair on a busy street with a sign that, in translation, said
``Look at me that suffices I am art,'' sat at a table outside a
gallery with a sign that announced ``I sign other people's
paintings'' and was actively engaged in signing things that had not
previously been considered art, like dirty water, plants, the pope,
God, death, the universe.
</P>
<P>
   Some of these little happenings can be seen on tapes at the
Zabriskie Gallery, where the Fluxus spirit reigns again. For
example, Ben takes a razor to a self-portrait that he has slathered
with shaving cream, et voila! The portrait comes out cleanshaven.
Ben has plastered the walls up to the ceiling with photographs and
deadpan philosophical questions (making some things a bit hard to
see) and has thrown himself a gleeful party with, and at the
expense of, photography. Any visitor whose mouth hasn't been sewn
shut will be summarily forced to smile.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Ben's photographs are often pretty dumb, poorly exposed, even
tattered; your photographs are probably more presentable. He was in
the gallery a few hours before the opening, cobbling together a new
piece with artistic items he had brought from France: a plastic leg
and a reproduction of a painting of Martin Luther that he arranged
as if the great reformer were staring at a female nude. ``I am not
a good photographer,'' he confidently announced. That's fair. No
one will ever confuse Ben with Ansel Adams.
</P>
<P>
   But whether in English or French, he poses more philosophical
questions about the medium than Adams had time for, in a dry and
even ridiculously naive manner, as if he were explaining Roland
Barthes on ``Sesame Street.'' Under a pair of so-so pictures of
Nice covered with snow, he wrote, ``Snow is exceptional in Nice so
this is an exceptional photo,'' raising the issue of the importance
of subject matter in photography. Under two Polaroids that are
nothing but blank color, he writes ``2 polaroids failed or
successful?,'' in effect asking what makes a photograph a work of
art.
</P>
<P>
   In a group of photographs of himself, his face is hidden by
signs saying things like ``No copyright for this photo'' (clearly
not a unique work of art); ``blind photo'' (Ben and the photograph
itself are incapable of ``seeing''); and ``Forget that this is a
photo'' (because you might think differently about it if you cast
off preconceptions _ or whatever; you are after all free to
interpret these pronouncements any way you choose).
</P>
<P>
   Long before the computer got into the art act, some artists
wanted the audience to interact with works of art. One of the walls
full of photographs at Zabriskie is a partial re-creation of a
piece Ben did in France. There it included a bathtub and a bed that
visitors could pose in or on for Polaroids they took and then
tacked onto the wall along with Ben's.
</P>
<P>
   The piece also had ``a lot of decor,'' as the artist put it, and
a transvestite who was there ``animating the place.'' Another piece
at the Zabriskie show, called ``Taking the Family Out to See a
Photo Show,'' consists of an old picture of a wedding lying atop a
flat wheeled cart that is meant to be taken for a walk on a leash.
</P>
<P>
   There's more. It's alternately zany, canny, dumb, wise. There
are lots of lessons to be learned here, but not to worry: if this
were a textbook, it would have been written by Groucho Marx. As it
is, photography will probably never be the same. But then, it never
is. Already.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ben Vautier: Statements with Clocks'' is at the John Gibson
Gallery, 568 Broadway, at Prince Street, SoHo, through Nov. 14.
``Gallery One'' is at the Guggenheim Museum SoHo, 575 Broadway, at
Prince Street, through Jan. 10. ``Ben Vautier: Photo Rejects'' is
at the Zabriskie Gallery, 41 East 57th Street, Manhattan, through
Dec. 5.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
