<HEADLINE>
.
</HEADLINE>
  
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following stories
today for use by NYTimes News Service clients. They will move in
the ``e'' entertainment news file. For questions, contact Bob
McCarthy at the Daily News, (818) 713-3665. 
. 
APT-PUPIL _ Stephen King's ``Apt Pupil'' may not be his scariest
story, but it's likely his most disturbing. No ghosts. No
werewolves. No uplifting themes like those other stories from
King's ``Different Seasons'' collection that were turned into the
beloved movies ``Stand by Me'' and ``The Shawshank Redemption.''
Just two thoroughly evil guys talking, mostly, then finally acting
on their dreadful impulses. How do you make a Hollywood movie out
of that? For Bryan Singer, the 32-year-old director who made a big
splash last time around with the intricate crime puzzler ``The
Usual Suspects,'' it's been a warped dream ever since he first read
the story. By Bob Strauss. 
. 
CONTROVERSY-FILMS _ An avalanche of films with disturbing themes,
unsavory characters and creepy situations are making their way into
theaters, and audiences, if they're brave enough, are going to have
an unprecedented amount of opportunities to squirm in their seats.
By Glenn Whipp. 
. 
PUPIL-REVIEW _ ``Apt Pupil'' is creepy in ways you almost can't
imagine. That's the source of its mesmerizing power; we know the
unimaginable did happen, and this film shows us how easily it might
again. By Bob Strauss. 4 stars 
. 
LIFE-REVIEW _ ``Life Is Beautiful'' has been labeled in some
publications as a ``concentration camp comedy.'' It's a shorthand
description that's accurate up to a point, but one that ultimately
trivializes this movie's tremendous power and beauty. Italian
filmmaker Roberto Benigni has created a masterpiece that delicately
mixes laughter and tragedy in a way that you'd never think
possible. By Glenn Whipp. 4 stars
<TEXT>
<P>
   . &QL; 
PLEASANTVILLE-REVIEW _ Gary Ross' wonderful new film,
``Pleasantville,'' taps into our collective nostalgia for the
simplicity of the good old days and then forces us to examine
whether that bygone era was really as swell as we remember. In
fact, the movie prompts us to ask ourselves whether Father really
did know best or if everything we now remember about the Eisenhower
era comes courtesy of Nick at Nite. By Glenn Whipp. 3 1/2 stars
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
ORGASMO-REVIEW _ This satire of the porno film industry is so
inept, in fact, it makes your basic amateur X-rated production look
like ``Gone With the Wind.'' By Bob Strauss. 1 star
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
DISC-REVIEWS _ Record reviews. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
VIDEO-COLUMN _ After a promising beginning, ``Hope Floats'' becomes
one of those heartwarming and life-affirming films that never sinks
to the level of total schmaltz but never has enough edge to make it
compelling. What elevates it, though, is the irrepressible Gena
Rowlands. By Rob Lowman.  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
CELINE-DION-CONCERT (Los Angeles) _ Adult-contemporary goddess
Celine Dion did Wednesday what so many before her were never able
to manage _ make the yawning cavern of the Forum seem intimate. By
Fred Shuster.
</P>
</TEXT>
