<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS _ QUEENSTOWN, Md. _ President Clinton returns to
Wye Plantation on Thursday to make a final push on an interim
Israeli-Palestinian agreement. Developing. (Deans, Cox News
Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-SETTLERS _ BET EL, West Bank _ This hardly looks like a
hotbed of activism. Kindergarten children with backpacks make their
way down the sidewalks past tidy landscaping and red-roofed stone
villas. The grocery store is busy and a community club is having a
music and lecture program for Seniors Week. But, this is the place
where they do not want a deal in the Wye Plantation talks and where
many are so to the right of right wing Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu that they want to oust him. They are religious
Jews fearful of being surrounded by Palestinian land and who
believe that God gave this mountain to them, not the Arabs,
forever. It's settlers like these who are spearheading the
opposition to Netanyahu and this phase of the Oslo peace process.
(Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-PEACE _ JERUSALEM _ No matter what happens at the Middle
East peace summit at Maryland's Wye Plantation, the bulk of what
needs to be done to settle the issues between Israelis and
Palestinians is still ahead. We take a look at the heavy-lifting
that's left to be done, because once the summit is over, now the
real work begins. (Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-BOX _ A box listing the steps that have been taken to
complete the Oslo peace process, and those that remain. (Kaplow,
Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-QA _ Where Wye meets Oslo: The Peace process in
midstream. (Kaplow, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   TEACHERS _ WASHINGTON _ A bill to begin funding 100,000 new
public school teachers has been billed by both Democrats and
Republicans as one of the great accomplishments of the closing days
of the last Congress. But the program's promise is open to
question. The bill pays for only 30,000 teachers _ the rest will
have to be funded later _ and even the first batch won't be hired
until next July. Some educators, already warning that school boards
are hiring unqualified teachers to fill shortages, wonder where the
new contingent will come from. And once they are hired, school
officials say, where are the 30,000 classrooms to put them in?
(Malone, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT _ WASHINGTON _ Microsoft attorneys continue
questioning Netscape chief executive James Barksdale, the main
government witness in the federal antitrust suit against Microsoft.
(Glass, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   MONKEYS _ WASHINGTON _ One banana, two banana, three banana,
four: Monkeys can count. That discovery, announced Thursday in
Science Magazine by researchers at Columbia University in New York,
rattles one of the fundamental assumptions about what distinguishes
human beings from all of Earth's other creatures. (Nesmith, Cox
News Service 400).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   FLOOD _ Main news story. (developing). (Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   w/FLOOD-FEMA-TOURS _ AUSTIN _FEMA chief James Lee Witt flys into
Austin for a tour of the flood-davastated areas, and promises quick
assistance to those whose homes and businesses have been destroyed.
With details. Developing. (Ward, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL-GUARD _ By 2000, Austin will have one of the nation's
10 special National Guard response teams to terrorist acts. The
team of 22 will be trained to help local police and EMS respond to
incidents where biological or chemical weapons are used.
(Tanamachi, Austin American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CAMPAIGN _ AUSTIN _ Gov. George W. Bush says on the road
Thursday that unless he runs for president, this will be his last
campaign. He has no interest in running for a third term and no
interest in any other elective office. Herman, Austin
American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   PHIL-GRAMM _ AUSTIN, Texas _ Congress appeared poised this year
to dismantle a Depression-era law that has prohibited consumers
from one-stop shopping for banking, insurance, stocks and bonds.
But Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, with his objection to a tiny piece of
the overhaul, stalled a reform that had been 20 years in the
making. We explain Gramm's problem with the CRA and the future of
banking reform. (Harlan, Austin American-Statesman)
</P>
<P>
   SIERRA-BLANCA _ Thursday's decision day in the Sierra Blanca
case. Three environmental commissioners will hear evidence on all
sides, then decide whether to grant an operating license to a
radioactive waste site in Sierra Blanca. (Haurwitz/Harmon, Austin
American-Statesman).
</P>
<P>
   GOPSTRATEGY _ It's the last two weeks of an unpredictable
election season. You would expect to find Newt Gingrich campaigning
for vulnerable Republican incumbents and promising GOP challengers.
He is doing some of that, but the speaker also is spending a lot of
time in places like Michigan, where a controversial Democratic
nominee for governor may offer Republicans the chance to upset
Democrats up and down the ballot. Gingrich speaks Thursday in two
Democratic-held districts where the odds favor the incumbents. The
Republican hope is that Democrats will stay home in droves on Nov.
3 out of disgust with Geoffrey Feiger, Dr. Kevorkian's lawyer and
the Democratic nominee for governor, and that appearances like
those of Gingrich will help rally the faithful. (Sherman, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   TRIPLE _ News of the day in the triple homicide in the Atlanta
Hilton &AMP; Towers. Attending board meeting of Atlanta Convention and
Visitor's Bureau in morning (Charles), funeral of Phillip Dover in
Gainesville in evening (Croft) and talking about Saturday funeral
of Gerrold Shropshire (Bixler, Atlanta Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   NRA _ The National Rifle Association is beginning campaigns
against all nine proposed revisions to Florida's Constitution,
including one proposing waiting period on buying guns at gun shows.
(Staletovich, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   IVORY-TUSK _ DAYTON, Ohio _ Judy Bailey named it ``Nathan'' and
hoped to keep the antique ivory tusk in the family, but a private
buyer paid $11,300 Wednesday at auction for the rare, 11-pound
Narwhal whale tooth. (Mong, Dayton Daily News). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   BREAST-FEEDING-CAMPAIGN _ AUSTIN, Texas _ In brilliant color on
network television, the dead baby is rushed into a hospital
emergency room _ starved to death because the infant's
breast-feeding mother didn't understand nutrition. The horrifying
story _ which aired Wednesday night on the CBS drama ``Chicago
Hope'' _ may make gripping television drama, but national and local
breast-feeding advocates are incensed. The episode has sparked a
national counter-information campaign designed to assure mothers
that breast-feeding is not dangerous for their children.
(Scharnhorst, Palm Beach Post). MOVED
</P>
