   HEADSETS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ It all started with that dorky icon of customer
service, the Time Life operator. In 1990 it surfaced on stage,
clamped to Madonna's noggin like some high-tech orthodontic
headgear. Now, it's infiltrated the very core of cool-dom: the
Hollywood prop house. It's ... the headset. Why does everyone now
seem to be wired? By LIZ STEVENS. Story has moved in ``l''
lifestyle category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   E N T E R T A I N M E N T &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-SOLONDZ &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Todd Solondz's black comedy ``Happiness'' has received
much critical acclaim _ and a great deal of outrage about its
subplots, including one focusing on a pedophile. But the filmmaker
thinks it's more interesting to portray characters with all their
flaws than just try to wring sympathy from an audience. By ELVIS
MITCHELL. Story has moved in ``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-HAPPINESS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ There probably isn't another director working who has
made a style of ambivalence in the way Todd Solondz has. With
``Welcome to the Dollhouse,'' which followed an outcast Jersey
preteen girl at a difficult time in her life, his deadpan direction
kept people off-guard. His newest film, ``Happiness,'' is sure to
provoke even more conversation. He clearly wants to subvert, and
cheat, the expectation that a movie should make audiences feel one
thing at a time _ laughter, sadness, outrage. By ELVIS MITCHELL.
Story has moved in ``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-SLAM &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Director Marc Levin films the urban drama ``Slam''
with such a casual cinema-verite voyeurism, it's as if he were
using surveillance cameras. He and his actors sometimes seem to
have wandered into the movie's Washington, D.C., locations and just
started filming while the residents went about their business. It's
representative of the movie, which tries to show the real world
while living in a dream one. By ROBERT PHILPOT. Story has moved in
``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-APT PUPIL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ The first time I encountered an excited young dude
shouting ``I'm the King of the World'' wasn't in ``Titanic,'' but
in Stephen King's novella, ``Apt Pupil,'' now a film under the
direction of Bryan Singer. By ELVIS MITCHELL. Story has moved in
``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-PLEASANTVILLE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ ``Pleasantville'' is ... not unpleasant. It starts
with a likable sendup of a Nick at Nite-style cable channel _ TV
Time _ that traffics in the relentlessly cheerful irony that makes
almost everything in pop culture feel meaningless because the folks
selling it have to pretend they're smarter than their subject
matter. (And it's easy to make fun of 1950s television, which even
the TV Time actors _ if you want to call them that _ don't seem to
take very seriously.) By ELVIS MITCHELL. Story has moved in ``e''
entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-ORGAZMO &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ In spite of its much-ballyhooed NC-17 rating, ``South
Park'' co-creator Trey Parker's ``Orgazmo'' succeeds on two levels:
as a clever spoof of pornography, action films and the '60s
``Batman'' TV series; and as a surprisingly hilarious piece of
``adult'' humor. By TODD CAMP. Story has moved in ``e''
entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FILM-SPECIAL EFFECTS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ Are special effects becoming so ubiquitous in movies
that we're becoming jaded about them? The new movie
``Pleasantville'' deftly mixes black-and-white with color images _
often in the same frame _ but nobody's acting like this is a big
deal. By ROBERT PHILPOT. Story has moved in ``e'' entertainment
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TV-PERKINS-COLUMN &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ ``Good Morning America'' is dying because it broke the
cardinal rule of morning television: It tried to give the audience
something that flew against the established standards of fluffy,
style-over-substance morning programs. By KEN PARISH PERKINS. Story
has moved in ``e'' entertainment category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   F I N A N C I A L &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-BOOKS &QL;
</P>
<P>
   UNDATED _ To grow the economy, the government has to continue to
think big. That's the history lesson to be drawn from Thomas
Hughes' Rescuing Prometheus'' (Pantheon Books, $28.50, 372 pages).
The book chronicles the development, execution and long-term impact
of four massive post-World War II projects with the size and scale
to spark creative thinking that could affect the way the commercial
sector does business for decades to come. By TERESA McUSIC. Story
has moved in ``f'' financial category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
