<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 17:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2145 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDEAST-BOX23-COX     10-22 0636
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-BOX23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    THE ROAD TO WYE, THE LONG ROAD AHEAD
 &HT;    With MIDEAST-PEACE-1023.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The summit talks at the Wye River Plantation are one step in
restarting a peace process that was born in hope in 1993 but has
been mired in violence and intransigence.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 13, 1993: Palestinian Liberation Organization Chairman
Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin come to the
White House to sign the Oslo accords (negotiated in Norway).
</P>
<P>
   The accords lay out a largely unspecified schedule for Israel to
turn over occupied areas to the Palestinians in return for the
Palestinians dropping their resistance to the Jewish state.
</P>
<P>
   May 4, 1994: Israeli and Palestinian leaders, in Cairo, sign the
Gaza-Jericho agreement, clearing the way for those areas to be the
first areas where Israeli troops withdraw.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 26, 1994: Culminating years of secret relations and months
of formal talks, in part a result of the Oslo process, Israel and
Jordan sign a peace treaty.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 28, 1995: Arafat and Rabin come to Washington to sign the
detailed agreement filling in many of the gaps in the first
accords.
</P>
<P>
   Nov. 4, 1995: An extreme right-wing Israeli kills Rabin at a
peace rally in Tel Aviv.
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 20, 1996: As laid out in the previous accords, elections
are held in the Palestinian areas, electing a legislature and
Arafat as president of the new Palestinian National Authority.
</P>
<P>
   February and March, 1996: Four Palestinian terrorist attacks
kill 54 Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   May 29, 1996: Shocked by terrorism, Israelis narrowly elect
right-wing Benjamin Netanyahu prime minister over incumbent Shimon
Peres. He had opposed Oslo, but says he will fulfill its
commitments.
</P>
<P>
   September, 1996: Scores of Palestinians and several Israelis die
when Palestinian police and Israeli troops engage in firefights.
Palestinians were protesting Netanyahu's expansion of a tunnel near
a Muslim holy site.
</P>
<P>
   Jan. 17, 1997: Israel and the Palestinians sign the Hebron
Accords, pulling Israeli troops out of 80 percent of the holy city
and laying out a rough schedule for further withdrawals. Israel has
now pulled out of most of Gaza and pockets in the West Bank
containing most of the Palestinian population.
</P>
<P>
   March, 1997: Deadline for the first of the three next troop
withdrawals is missed when Israel's offer is rejected as too small.
</P>
<P>
   July-September, 1997: Efforts to restart the peace talks are
derailed when Palestinian suicide bombers kill 24 Israelis in two
attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Sept. 10, 1997: U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
visits the region and leaves with little progress, stressing that
the local leaders are not ready to make hard choices needed for
peace and that she will not come back again to ``tread water.''
</P>
<P>
   September, 1998: Deadline for second in series of Israeli troop
withdrawals missed.
</P>
<P>
   Oct. 15, 1998: President Bill Clinton hosts summit at Wye River
Plantation, aiming to get Israel to carry out the delayed troop
withdrawals and get the Palestinians to improve their fight on
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   In the future:
</P>
<P>
   Early 1999: Negotiations could begin on the toughest issues
under Oslo:
</P>
<P>
   Whether Israel will share Jerusalem;
</P>
<P>
   whether Palestinian refugees can return to their homeland or be
</P>
<P>
   compensated;
</P>
<P>
   whether the Palestinians can have a state;
</P>
<P>
   and what the two final borders will be.
</P>
<P>
   May 4, 1998: Oslo accords expire. Arafat says he might declare
statehood whether or not he has Israeli approval. Israel hints that
could prompt it to retake land.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
