<HEADER>
A2147 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDEAST-PEACE23-COX     10-22 0799
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-PEACE23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;    
 &HT;    ATTN EDS: PLEASE NOTE, STORY PRESUMES AN AGREEMENT AT WYE. DO
NOT RUN IN THE ABSENCE OF AN AGREEMENT.
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    ISSUES IN MIDEAST PEACE PROCESS JUST AS TOUGH AFTER WYE SUMMIT
 &HT;    EDs: Optional add begins at 600 words.
 &HT;    With MIDEAST-QA-1023; MIDEAST-BOX-1023; MIDEAST-TALKS-1023.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ As hard as it was to get Israelis and Palestinians
to agree in this week's American-hosted summit meeting, the future
of the Middle East peace process looks even tougher.
</P>
<P>
   Consider: The Oslo peace accords signed five years ago were not
a finished product. They simply set a schedule for settling the
disputes between the Israelis and Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   The parties are now more than a year behind that schedule.
</P>
<P>
   This week's agreement at the secluded Wye River Plantation in
Maryland certainly moved the process forward. Even so, Ron Pundik,
one of the Israeli authors of the Oslo Accords, warned, ``The
post-Wye Plantation era could be tragic.''
</P>
<P>
   Under Oslo, the Palestinians are supposed to recognize Israel's
right to exist. Israel is supposed to make phased troop withdrawals
from some of the Palestinian lands it captured in wars. The idea is
to build trust, allowing the adversaries to resolve the most
important and contentious issues in the so-called ``permanent
status talks'' at the end of the process.
</P>
<P>
   The permanent status issues include whether the 3.4 million
Palestinian refugees, and descendants of refugees, can return to
land that is now part of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The fate of the holy city of Jerusalem, including whether Israel
will let Palestinians rule part of it, must be decided. And
negotiators must decide whether to dismantle or protect the 144
Jewish settlements in the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the final boundaries of Israel to discuss.
</P>
<P>
   Israel has already withdrawn from most of the Gaza Strip and
from lots of little pockets in the West Bank. The Palestinians have
made partial progress in dropping their resistance to Israel's
existence.
</P>
<P>
   But, as Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and Israeli leader
Benjamin Netanyahu journeyed to the woods of Maryland's Eastern
Shore to work out this week's deal, they were already 19 months
behind schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The main topic of the summit: a land transfer that was supposed
to start in March, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Ominously, the whole process is set to expire May 4, 1999 -- and
the two sides have not even started negotiating the final issues.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat has vowed to declare Palestinian statehood in May. That
would put nations around the world on the spot as they decide
whether to recognize the new nation. And Israeli leaders hint they
could respond by retaking the land they gave back under Oslo.
</P>
<P>
   That could lead to war.
</P>
<P>
   Another danger is that the Wye agreement could unravel before
negotiators can even get to the final issues. Terrorist blasts
could derail it all. So could threats from Netanyahu's right wing
supporters to topple his government.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to take into account the extremes on both sides,''
said Palestinian political analyst Mahdi Abdul Hadi. ``It is a test
all the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Wye agreement holds, the two sides are approaching
negotiations over the permanent issues with totally incompatible
positions. Netanyahu says he will never share even an inch of
Jerusalem. About a third of the city's population is Palestinian,
but it is ruled by the Israelis.
</P>
<P>
   Israelis say they will not allow the return of the more than
three million Arab refugees, something that would change the very
nature of the Jewish state. And settlers threaten political
upheaval in Israel -- and even civil war -- if many of Israel's 144
West Bank Jewish neighborhoods are dismantled.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Arafat says there can be no real peace without a
Palestinian capital in a shared Jerusalem. The refugees insist on
returning to the land they say was stolen from them. The
settlements are indeed situated in occupied territory, and are
often surrounded by bitter Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   However, Hadi, the Palestinian political analyst, said
negotiators might be able achieve a permanent status agreement that
will be based on support from both sides and security commitments
from around the region. That, Hadi said, is one of the reasons
Jordan's King Hussein, an influential figure in the region, was
brought into the Wye talks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything is pending,'' Hadi said. ``Once there is a regional
package for cooperation, I can see the Israelis and the
Palestinians meeting halfway.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
