<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WHERE WYE MEETS OSLO: THE PEACE PROCESS IN THE MID-STREAM
 &HT;    With MIDEAST-PEACE-1023.
 &HT;    By LARRY KAPLOW
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Question: How do the talks at Wye River Plantation Conference
Center fit into the Oslo peace process?
</P>
<P>
   Answer: The Oslo Accords, agreed to in 1993, set out a series of
negotiations aimed at settling the dispute between the Israelis and
Palestinians. The understanding was based in part on Israel making
phased troop withdrawals from captured Palestinian lands in
exchange for the Palestinians dropping their resistance to the
existence of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The process was supposed to include a series of troop
withdrawals while leaving the toughest issues to be dealt with at
the end.
</P>
<P>
   The Wye talks are meant to end a 19-month stall in the process
and continue the troop withdrawals and security work.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How far along is the process?
</P>
<P>
   A: Israel has withdrawn from most of the Gaza Strip and the
parts of the West Bank areas that are populated by Palestinians.
But, in the West Bank, the Palestinians are left in more than 150
little pockets that are surrounded, and can be cut off, by Israeli
troops.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Palestinians, having dropped their Intifada
uprising, made commitments to recognize Israel. Their security
forces often work with Israeli forces, but their fight against
terrorist extremists within their own ranks has been inconsistent.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Is the process on schedule?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. The troop withdrawal negotiators are discussing at Wye
was supposed to have started in March 1997. And Israelis contend
the Palestinians have not kept their promises to fight terrorism.
The Palestinian Liberation Organization (PLO) started, but never
completed, the process of amending its charter to drop resistance
to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Q. Why are the negotiations so tough?
</P>
<P>
   A. Right now, leaders on both sides have incentives to resist
compromise. Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu is backed by
a right-wing coalition that largely opposed the Oslo process when
it was signed by then-Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin.
</P>
<P>
   PLO Chairman Yasser Arafat has threatened to declare Palestinian
statehood on May 4, 1999, when Oslo expires, and he may feel that
deadline will scare Israelis into making concessions.
</P>
<P>
   Q: If they get an agreement at Wye, what comes next?
</P>
<P>
   A: First, it will have to be implemented. If Israeli troops are
to be pulled out, the withdrawal could be phased over time along
with Palestinian anti-terrorism steps. Then, another phased
withdrawal might be negotiated.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, and most important, come the permanent status talks.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What are the issues in the permanent status talks?
</P>
<P>
   A: Will part of Jerusalem, a city run by Israel with about
450,000 Jews and almost 200,000 Arabs, be ceded by Israel for use
as a Palestinian capital? Will the 3.4 million Palestinian
refugees, and the descendants of refugees, be allowed to return to
Israel? Will Jewish settlements in occupied territories be
preserved? What are Israel's, and the Palestinians', final borders?
</P>
<P>
   And the parties will have to negotiate what kind of powers the
Palestinian government will have, such as whether it will be
empowered to form an army, or negotiate with other countries. And
they will have to resolve whether Palestine will, in fact, be a new
nation.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   AP-NY-10-22-98 1600E
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
