<HEADLINE>
PROSTATE CANCER RESEARCH GETS A BOOST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Oct. 25)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After a week of chaotic horse-trading on Capitol
Hill, advocates for more spending on prostate cancer research
emerged with $184 million to study the No. 2 cancer-killer of men,
more than the previous year but significantly less money than they
had sought.
</P>
<P>
   The budget package that President Clinton signed into law
Wednesday boosts prostate cancer research funded through the
National Institutes of Health (NIH) _ which includes the National
Cancer Institute _ and the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   The military's commitment rose from $40 million to about $62
million. The effort was a victory for research advocates given that
this summer House and Senate negotiators considered funding as
little as $10 million through the Pentagon budget.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon is a major contributor to cancer research in part
because the military operates numerous hospitals across the country
and treats active-duty and retired service members for cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The NIH will spend about $122 million for research on prostate
cancer this year, an increase of $8 million.
</P>
<P>
   The NIH funding was a setback for advocates. In closed-door
sessions before a sweeping $520 billion spending package was
approved last week, House and Senate budget negotiators dropped a
controversial measure by Sen. Ted Stevens, the chairman of the
Senate Appropriations Committee, that would have earmarked $175
million for NIH-funded prostate cancer research.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, R-Alaska, is a survivor of prostate cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The provision was eliminated because it directed NIH scientists
to spend funds for a specific purpose. Congress typically grants
scientists the leeway to spend cancer funds as they see fit.
</P>
<P>
   House Speaker Newt Gingrich, R-Ga., has been a staunch critic of
designating spending on specific ailments, preferring to leave that
to the discretion of scientists and researchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am opposed to getting into political health research, where
every group shows up with their banner, and their slogan, and their
calculations,'' Gingrich told research advocates this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The very politics that led AIDS to become a politically
desirable thing to do research in is wrong. It distorts the
research process,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The National Prostate Cancer Coalition, a Washington-based
patient advocacy group, had pressed for a total commitment of $418
million from lawmakers in the new fiscal year, asserting that
prostate cancer research is underfunded compared with other killers
such as breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   The group sought a major spike in funds from the NIH and the
Pentagon. The latter was met with stiff resistance from lawmakers
who felt the armed forces needed every available dollar for
military readiness.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Hedlund, the coalition's president, said that while the
group didn't achieve its target, ``we've made a lot of progress.''
He said the organization would lobby NIH throughout the year to
spend as much as possible on prostate cancer research.
</P>
<P>
   Some 184,500 men will be diagnosed with carcinoma of the
prostate this year, making it the most diagnosed cancer in the
United States next to highly curable forms of skin cancer. Nearly
40,000 American men will die from the cancer; only lung cancer will
kill more American men, according to the American Cancer Society.
</P>
<P>
   Prostate cancer research receives comparatively little from the
federal government.
</P>
<P>
   ``Despite nearly 20 percent of all cancers diagnosed each year
being prostate cancer, until now less than four percent of total
federal funds for cancer research have been devoted to prostate
cancer,'' Hedlund said. ``Prostate cancer research money has been
left behind.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, breast cancer and prostate cancer killed about the
same number of Americans in 1997 _ 43,900 women and 41,800 men,
respectively _ while about 14,000 people died from AIDs-related
illnesses last year.
</P>
<P>
   The NIH spent about $107,214 in AIDS research for every
AIDS-related death that year; $9,362 in breast cancer research for
every breast cancer death; and $2,512 in prostate cancer research
for every death from that disease.
</P>
<P>
   From 1990 through 1997, the National Cancer Institute spent $371
million on prostate cancer research. By comparison, institute spent
nearly $1.67 billion for breast cancer research.
</P>
<P>
   ``We absolutely must do more to fight this dreadful disease,''
said John Kelly, vice chairman of the American Cancer Society's
board of directors. ``We need a nationwide commitment to expand
prostate cancer research efforts in order to better understand and
prevent this disease.''
</P>
</TEXT>
