<HEADLINE>
THE `100,000 NEW TEACHERS' AREN'T FOR EVERYONE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Oct. 25)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton and his Democratic allies in
Congress hope they've created an election year vote-getter with a
new federal program to pay for 100,000 new teachers to help cut the
size of elementary school classes.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton program is designed to hire 100,000 new teachers
over seven years to help cut class size in overcrowded schools to
an average of 18 students per teacher in first, second and third
grade.
</P>
<P>
   If funding is approved by Congress each year, the program could
eventually provide $12.4 billion over the next seven years to many
of the nation's 48,000 public elementary schools.
</P>
<P>
   But the details behind the alluring headline of ``100,000 new
teachers'' show a more fragmented picture.
</P>
<P>
   For example:
</P>
<P>
   _ Although Clinton has showcased the program as a benefit to all
Americans, with visits to suburban schools with overcrowded
classrooms, the actual formula for selecting schools for the money
targets schools serving low-income families rather than more
affluent suburban schools where overcrowding is just as common.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Clinton initiative could expose state and local
governments to billions of dollars in unplanned spending for
benefits and pensions for the new teachers.
</P>
<P>
   _ U.S. Education Department studies forecast that the
teacher-student ratios in elementary schools will decline from 18.9
in 1996 to 17.3 by 2008 even without Clinton's initiative.
</P>
<P>
   _ Money from Clinton's teacher initiative won't reach schools
for months; the initial $1.2 billion for the first 30,703 teachers
will not enable schools to hire teachers until next July 1.
</P>
<P>
   Public public opinion polls show that voters rank education
second only to the global economic crisis as their top concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing more important to America's future prosperity
than giving our children a world &QC; class education,'' Vice President
Al Gore declared during a campaign swing to California last week.
``We must ensure that every child can master the basics and meet
high standards to succeed in today's knowledge-based economy _ and
this initiative will help reach that goal.''
</P>
<P>
   But Scott A. Hodge, a senior fellow in tax and budget policy at
the Citizens for a Sound Economy, in Washington, D.C., says the
White House is exaggerating the federal role in public education
for political gain.
</P>
<P>
   Federal spending accounts for only 7 percent of the nearly $300
billion a year that the nation spends on public and private
elementary and secondary schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very clear that education spending plays well with the
Democratic base _ whether its women or teachers' unions or
residents of inner cities,'' Hodge says. He claimed that Democrats
were using education as a ``wedge issue'' against Republicans to
gain political advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Education Secretary Richard W. Riley downplays political
motives.
</P>
<P>
   ``All across America, we will begin to lower class size by
hiring teachers to give more personalized attention to students,''
Riley says.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of politically active teachers' unions hail the
venture. Bob Chase, president of the 2.4 million member National
Education Association, applauded Clinton's ``aggressive leadership
in keeping the class size proposal as a priority.'' Sandra Feldman,
president of the 1 million member American Federation of Teachers,
says Congress ``did the right thing'' underwriting new teachers
because ``students do better in smaller classes.''
</P>
<P>
   Julie Green, Riley's spokeswoman at the Department of Education,
said the Clinton administration remains committed to winning
congressional funding for the program each year in the future.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have to go through the annual appropriations
process,'' Green says. ``But it will still be our commitment to
provide these resources to the school districts to pay for these
teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   Harry Zeeve, national field director of the deficit-fighting
Concord Coalition, predicted that the White House and the
Republican Congress will have trouble finding the money in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE -- OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The White House modeled its election-year initiative after an
effort launched in 1994 to use federal funds to hire 100,000 new
police officers. So far, the White House and Congress have agreed
to fund 88,473 police officers but only 46,544 police officers are
actually on the beat. The remainder are either being recruited or
trained.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Clinton's teachers' initiative, the 100,000 new police
program requires local communities to take over the salaries and
benefits of the new officers after three years.
</P>
<P>
   Justice Department officials say that 98 percent of the police
departments that have received federal funds to hire police
officers for the first three years have advised the Clinton
administration that they will keep the officers on the payroll with
local funds after the federal grant expires.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
