u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELECTION-HMO-HNS &LR;      10-22 1198
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELECTION-HMO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HMO CONCERNS FAIL TO ELECTRIFY VOTERS IN THIS ELECTION 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ Addressing a group of local officials this
week, John Edwards, the Democrat challenging incumbent GOP Sen.
Lauch Faircloth, ticked off the critical issues he believed faced
the nation.
</P>
<P>
   When the candidate finished, he was peppered with questions
about his proposals to pump more money into the public schools,
protect Social Security, and revamp campaign finance laws.
</P>
<P>
   No one asked him about his plan to reduce the power of health
insurance bureaucrats and give people more choice of doctors in
their managed care plans.
</P>
<P>
   Concerns over health maintenance organizations do not appear to
be electrifying voters this election season contrary to the
predictions of many Democrats who had hoped that growing voter
disgust with their health plans would be a key campaign issue
across the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Last winter, reports of audiences cheering when a character
played by Helen Hunt in the movie ``As Good as it Gets'' lashes out
at the lousy service she received from an HMO, had stoked
Democrats' hopes that the issue was golden.
</P>
<P>
   With the support of the White House, they crafted a Patients
Bill of Rights that gave consumers more choice of doctors, the
ability to appeal managed care decisions and the right to sue their
plans for malpractice.
</P>
<P>
   Reluctant Republicans, prodded by their own polls showing rising
concern about HMOs, countered with their own watered-down versions
of managed care reform.
</P>
<P>
   But observers say that by late August the intense media focus on
the White House scandal made it harder for congressional Democrats
to showcase their health care agenda.
</P>
<P>
   Legislative efforts fizzled as lawmakers became increasingly
distracted by the prospect of impeachment hearings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a cyclone hit and people stopped thinking about
any issue except the president,'' said Bob Blendon, a professor of
the Harvard School of Public Health, who has overseen a number of
polls about health care.
</P>
<P>
   Blendon said surveys continue to show that voters favor some
restrictions on managed care policies. But he said, they place
higher priorities on other issues such as education and the decline
of moral values.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards disagreed that the scandal has drowned out health care,
Social Security and education, the marquee issues Democratic
candidates are highlighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think exactly the opposite is true. I think that as a result
of what people perceive to be highly politicized process in
Washington regarding the president they are more hungry than ever
to hear people talk about issues that really matter in their
lives,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats had looked to North Carolina as a test case on the
managed-care issue, because Edwards had stressed it successfully in
his primary campaign last spring. In the race against Faircloth he
has continued to mention the issue in stump speeches and aired one
health-care television spot earlier this fall. He is also running
an ad accusing Faircloth of voting to cut Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   But political experts say that health care is only one of
several factors that has helped Edwards bring the race to a dead
heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not debating health care everyday. You would have to
stretch it some to say this is a referendum on health care or
HMOs,'' said Ferrel Gailoory, director of Southern Politics, Media
and Public Life at the University of North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Edwards seems to place a higher priority on education
and visits a public school every week.
</P>
<P>
   Although his campaign spokesman denies health care is an issue,
Faircloth has felt the need to respond to Edwards' attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, he was one of a handful of Republicans who
joined Democrats in their unsuccessful effort to keep managed care
legislation alive when it was hastily brought up on the Senate
floor.
</P>
<P>
   And to shore up support among women, for whom health care issues
particularly resonate, Faircloth tells voters he supports breast
cancer research. This week the senator was scheduled to appear at a
breast cancer event on the courthouse steps in his hometown of
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he is inoculated if the issue comes up,'' said Charles
Black, a Washington-based Republican consultant who is advising the
Faircloth campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the health-care issue is no longer on the
front-burner politically, the business interests involved in the
matter have not forgotten it.
</P>
<P>
   The managed care industry, fearful of losing allies in Congress,
blitzed North Carolina and other states in September with ads
claiming that Democratic health care legislation was intended to
enrich trial lawyers, such as Edwards, because it would have
allowed consumers to sue their HMOs for malpractice.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Merritt, a spokesman for the American Association of Health
Plans -the major HMO lobbying association _ said the group was
confident that ``80 percent'' of candidates plugging anti-managed
care messages will lose this year.
</P>
<P>
   But knowing the issue could be revived, the HMO group plans to
continue advertising next year in New Hampshire and Iowa, the first
presidential primary states.
</P>
<P>
   And interests on both sides of the issue are still opening their
wallets to candidates this season.
</P>
<P>
   According to a new report by the Center for Responsive Politics,
health care interests have contributed $35 million in the 1997-98
election cycle, with 58 percent of those contributions going to
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   A number of Democratic candidates around the country have taken
the health-care fight to the airwaves. Their ads often feature the
candidates against the backdrop of a hospital or emergency room
pledging to give people more choices of doctors. Others feature
victims of managed-care abuses.
</P>
<P>
   In one spot, Pat Casey, a Democrat in a tight race for an open
Pennsylvania House seat stands in front of a scene of a doctor
examining children.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're sick, they should check out your pulse, not your
wallet,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   In Nevada, Democratic House candidate Shelley Berkley has taken
a more humorous approach to underscore the impersonal nature of
managed care plans, Her televisions ads depicts doctors, in Groucho
Marx poses, shoving thermometers, assembly line fashion, into long
lines of patients.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans consultants said that Democrats are not likely
to gain much traction, because most GOP lawmakers have backed some
variation of managed care reform and voters are not that excited
about the issue.
</P>
<P>
   The experience of Texas Democratic gubernatorial candidate Garry
Mauro helps prove their point. He tried to use the managed care
issue last spring against incumbent Republican Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro ran ads attacking Bush for vetoing a bill that would have
given consumers more doctor and hospital choice.
</P>
<P>
   ``To choose your own doctor, you need to choose a new
governor,'' was the tag line of the ad.
</P>
<P>
   But even after the ads ran, Mauro continued to trail badly in
the polls. He rarely mentions it on the campaign trail anymore. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
