<HEADLINE>
FASHION DESIGNER READIES STARS FOR VH1 FASHION AWARDS SHOW 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By PAMELA MITCHELL 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Inge Fonteyne knows clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Celebs like Mariah Carey and Jennifer Aniston often consult her
before stepping out. For the second year in a row, VH1 has hired
her to dress the host of its annual Fashion Awards Show. When Ellen
DeGeneres arrives at Madison Square Garden Friday night to emcee,
she'll have Fonteyne to thank for her look.
</P>
<P>
   And, what exactly will that look be? The New York-based stylist
won't share her glamour plans but she did recently take a break
from her hectic, pre-show schedule to dish about last year's
celebrity presenters and their various fashion emergencies. The
most memorable _ presenter Jim Carrey's now-famous fig leaf.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim Carrey came up with this idea, to wear a fig leaf. He
faxed over a sketch, drawn to scale, and I had to search high and
low for just the right G-string. It had to be nude but I couldn't
find one that was perfectly nude so I ended up dying one with
coffee and tea. It was so last minute, I sent it off to him still
wet,'' Fonteyne remembered. ``The next day, the G-string came back
to me. It was too small. He had undermeasured himself by about 10
inches.''
</P>
<P>
   Thankfully, Fonteyne got Carey in a fig leaf that fit before the
big night. But more dressing dilemmas soon followed. Fonteyne put
Ashley Judd, who co-hosted with Harry Connick Jr., in a collection
of vintage evening gowns. One of the dresses came back from the
cleaners damaged.
</P>
<P>
   ``They absolutely ruined a strap that was covered in little
diamonds. So, hours before the show, I'm running to the fashion
district to find new diamond studs.''
</P>
<P>
   She fixed the dress, and the fashion world buzzed about Judd and
Carrey's show-stealing styles.
</P>
<P>
   Fonteyne doesn't expect this year's show to be any calmer. In
addition to DeGeneres and Heche, she'll be responsible for Janet
Jackson and her dancers, plus any other celebrity presenters who
need her talent and taste. Like Andy Dick, who called on her to
dress the actors in a short film he created for the awards show.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andy was fun to work with. We can push his boundaries,'' said
Fonteyne, who won't reveal the film's plot but did offer the
following hint: ``It has to do with live clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   Before rushing off to meet another celebrity, Fonteyne weighed
in on whom she thought should take home statues Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   For most fashionable artist, she picks Madonna over Marilyn
Manson, Sarah McLachlan, Sheryl Crow and Steve Nicks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Madonna always pushes the limit, pushes the envelope.''
</P>
<P>
   For best female personal style, Fonteyne likes Cameron Diaz more
than Jenna Elfman, Jennifer Lopez, Liv Tyler and Oprah Winfrey.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just love Cameron. I've worked with her.''
</P>
<P>
   For best male Personal Style, Ben Stiller beats out Chris Rock,
Dylan McDermott, Nicolas Cage and Vince Vaughn in Fonteyne's book.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ben Stiller is awesome. He loves Prada.''
</P>
<P>
   The VH1 Fashion Awards happen Friday but don't air until 8 p.m.
Tuesday on the cable channel. Tyra Banks, Minnie Driver, Jennifer
Lopez and Michael Stipe are just a few of the celebrities scheduled
to present. Look for performances by the Smashing Pumpkins, Lenny
Kravitz and Iggy Pop.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
