<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 18:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2192 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAELI-MUSIC-BENEFIT     10-22 0630
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAELI-MUSIC-BENEFIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FROM DARKNESS TO LIGHT': HISTORY AND FAITH 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ALLAN KOZINN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Having revived the American Symphony Orchestra with
programs in which works and composers are linked by overarching
themes, Leon Botstein showed on Monday evening that his programming
approach can enliven fund-raising concerts as well.
</P>
<P>
   The occasion was a concert at Avery Fisher Hall for the
Jerusalem Foundation, a philanthropic organization that was founded
by Teddy Kollek, at the time the mayor of Jerusalem, with the goal
of improving the city for all its residents, Jewish, Muslim and
Christian, and making it more attractive to visitors as well. The
foundation has underwritten some 1,600 projects, including gardens,
museums, hospitals, cultural and sports centers and archeological
restorations.
</P>
<P>
   The 50th anniversary of the establishment of Israel was the
ostensible focus of the program, but its title, ``From Darkness to
Light,'' as well as the opening comments by Liv Ullmann, the
actress, and the intermission remarks by Martin Peretz, editor of
The New Republic, suggested a broader historical panorama.
Botstein's repertory selections widened the scope further, touching
on the complex balance between the forces of history and the power
of sustained faith.
</P>
<P>
   Lamentation, in the form of the mourner's prayer, ``Kaddish,''
as set by Ravel, and Jeremiah's reflections on Jerusalem's
destruction, as set by Bernstein, were offset by Jacob Weinberg's
beautifully modal setting of ``Kol Dodi,'' a section of ``The Song
of Songs,'' and ``Lord God of Abraham, Isaac and Israel,'' Elijah's
proclamation of his readiness to serve God, from the Mendelssohn
oratorio about him.
</P>
<P>
   Allusions to Israel's liberation from Egypt were laced through
the program by way of a quartet from Rossini's ``Mose in Egitto,''
the final trio and chorus from Handel's ``Israel in Egypt,'' and a
spiritual, ``Go Down Moses.'' And Verdi's ``Va pensiero,'' from
``Nabucco,'' offered near the end of the program, revisited the
same sense of hope and longing embodied in the Israeli national
anthem, ``Hatikva,'' heard in Kurt Weill's peculiarly expansive
arrangement at the start of the evening. (``The Star-Spangled
Banner'' was given a Jewish connection too: Botstein conducted the
arrangement by Morton Gould.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobles seigneurs, salut,'' from Meyerbeer's ``Huguenots,'' may
have seemed off the topic at a glance, but the opera's look at the
dangers of religious intolerance is universal. The aria, sung with
exquisite suppleness by the mezzo-soprano Olga Borodina, was far
and away the most delightful performance of the evening. Less clear
was why the Mendelssohn Violin Concerto was included, but it
offered an opportunity to hear an energetic, sweet-toned
performance by Sarah Chang.
</P>
<P>
   Kelley Nassief's lovely, dark-timbred soprano suited the Ravel
``Kaddish'' nicely, and John Cheek used his rich bass effectively
in the selections from ``Elijah'' and ``Nabucco.'' Also among the
highlights were Harolyn Blackwell's graceful, light-textured
reading of Weinberg's ``Kol Dodi,'' Kristine Jepson's assured
singing in the finale of Bernstein's ``Jeremiah'' Symphony, and
Kathleen Battle's virtuosic renderings of three spirituals, ``I
Hear Music,'' ``Li'l David Play Your Harp'' and ``Go Down Moses.''
</P>
<P>
   A work commissioned from Philip Glass for the occasion, ``Psalm
126,'' seemed halfhearted: Not quite a setting of the psalm, the
piece was five minutes of choral and orchestral noodling in Glass'
trademark style, against which an English translation of the psalm
was read by Paul Sorvino.
</P>
<P>
   The American Symphony Orchestra and the New York Choral Artists
contributed polished, supportive performances.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
