<SLUG> BC-WOMEN-STATES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NORTHEAST AND WEST BEST FOR WOMEN, WHILE SOUTH LAGS, REPORT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JUDY HOLLAND  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Areas in the Northeast and West rank among the top
places for women to live based on factors such as wages,
reproductive rights and opportunities to gain political posts,
according to a study released Thursday by a Washington think tank.
</P>
<P>
   The organization, the Institute for Women's Policy Research,
said the lowest-ranking states are mostly in the South.
</P>
<P>
   The 10 best are the District of Columbia, Connecticut, Maryland,
New Hampshire, Vermont, Washington state, California, Oregon,
Hawaii and Alaska, the institute said.
</P>
<P>
   The 10 worst, from the bottom up, as Mississippi, Tennessee,
Kentucky, Arkansas, West Virginia, South Carolina, Alabama,
Oklahoma, Louisiana and South Dakota, according to the institute's
report.
</P>
<P>
   ``All too often, women's well-being is determined about what
states they live in,'' said Linda Tarr-Whelan, U.S. ambassador to
the United Nations Commission on the Status of Women, at a news
conference here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state of your residence sets up the odds of whether you
will be at the table where political decisions are made, economic
decisions are made,'' she added. ``It determines whether there is
going to be capital or education for you as a woman.''
</P>
<P>
   The nonpartisan group analyzed indicators of women's well-being
and ranked the states according to how well women fared on all of
them.
</P>
<P>
   Besides wages and the ability to win political offices, the
indicators included the percentage of women registered to vote and
of those who actually voted and the proportions of females in the
work force, of those who are managers and professionals and of
those below the poverty line.
</P>
<P>
   The indicators also included the share of women with health
insurance, college degrees and their own businesses. Additionally,
they included reproductive rights such as access to abortion,
public funding for infertility services, insurance coverage for
contraceptives and whether gay or lesbian couples can adopt
children.
</P>
<P>
   Heidi Hartmann, the institute's president, said the status of
females has improved in many states, ``but women will pay a penalty
in their paychecks even in the best states. In the worst states,
(they get) really socked ... every pay day.''
</P>
<P>
   In Oklahoma and Alabama, considered the bottom of the heap for
women's wages, females earn slightly more than 63 cents for every
dollar men are paid.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the District of Columbia, which has the highest
percentage of women in professional and managerial jobs and the
biggest percentage of female-owned businesses, women earn 87 cents
for every dollar men are paid, the study said.
</P>
<P>
   Hartmann said the poverty rate for females is 50 percent higher
than it is for men.
</P>
<P>
   ``Poverty is a woman's epidemic in states like New Mexico,
Mississippi and Louisiana, where one out of five women are
scrambling to survive below the poverty line,'' Hartmann said.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire, Alaska, Utah and New Jersey have the fewest women
living in poverty, with rates ranging between 7.6 percent and 9
percent.
</P>
<P>
   While 64 percent of females are registered to vote compared with
61 percent of men, relatively few women hold elective office.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety-four percent of state governors are men and 91 percent of
U.S. senators are male. Only 15 women have been state governors. In
terms of electing women to public office, Washington, California
and Maine have the best records while Mississippi, Kentucky and
Alabama have the worst, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Betty Friedan, a founder of modern feminism who helped launch
the National Organization for Women, said at the news conference
that research shows adding just two women to a state legislature
begins to change the agenda, ``not just in the direction of women's
rights, but in issues having to do with life, health, welfare,
older people, children, the environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Friedan said if women can win about half of elective offices,
``you might see all sorts of wonderful changes in national public
priorities, such as child care.''
</P>
<P>
   On the score card for women's reproductive rights, Hawaii ranks
highest, trailed by New York, Connecticut, Vermont, Oregon, New
Hampshire, New Jersey, Washington, Maryland and the District of
Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Reproductive rights are most curtailed in North Dakota, followed
by Nebraska, Mississippi, Kansas, Tennessee, Wisconsin, Ohio, South
Dakota, Utah and Michigan, the report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
