<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANTIQUES-COLUMN-465&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN WALLS TALKED TO YOU 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID W. DUNLAP   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Are you sorry you tossed that Bob Dylan poster? You
know, the one with his face in silhouette and his hair a tangle of
psychedelic spaghetti; the one that came folded up in the ``Best
of'' album, which you tacked to your wall and then threw out after
senior year?
</P>
<P>
   It was designed by Milton Glaser. It is quite scarce. In good
condition, it would be worth $500.
</P>
<P>
   Now, are you sorry?
</P>
<P>
   Contemporary posters are nowhere close to rivaling the classics
in price or popularity. But they are, nonetheless, being admitted
for the first time in large numbers to the International Vintage
Poster Fair, which begins at 5 p.m. Friday at the Metropolitan
Pavilion at 110 West 19th St.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of my goal is to broaden people's perception of what's
desirable,'' said Louis Bixenman, the organizer of the fair and
proprietor of the Poster America gallery at 138 West 18th St. ``The
reason there are Toulouse-Lautrecs and Cassandres today is that
people saved them when they were contemporary posters.''
</P>
<P>
   Already a collector's item is Paul Bruehwiler's 1983 poster for
a Fritz Lang retrospective at the Filmpodium-Kino in Zurich,
Switzerland. The director stares grimly from the center, encircled
by radiant black and white spokes that slash through the bold type
and through the small movie stills that are peppered across the
background.
</P>
<P>
   Bixenman estimated that 300 of these posters were printed, half
of which were posted and thus effectively destroyed. But quality as
well as scarcity dictates the $1,200 price, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you imagine this hanging on the street?'' Bixenman asked,
as he slid the poster into view on a broad tabletop piled high with
bright images. ``You'd almost have to stop to look at it. That's
what a good poster does.''
</P>
<P>
   One of four dealers who will be showing contemporary posters at
the fair is Jack Rennert, president of Posters Please and Poster
Auctions International, both run from a corner loft in the
Starrett-Lehigh Building at 601 West 26th St., with panoramas of
the Hudson River so sweeping that one can almost overlook the
posters.
</P>
<P>
   And that is just what many collectors do _ overlook contemporary
posters.
</P>
<P>
   ``You walk by a poster gallery and see that it's charging $500
for a poster that you had in your dorm room,'' Rennert said.
``People are not prepared to make the jump from $5 to $500.
</P>
<P>
   ``These things take time,'' he said. ``Toulouse-Lautrec did all
his posters in the 1890s. Up until the 1950s, you could go to any
Madison Avenue gallery and get one for $50.''
</P>
<P>
   Not today. Toulouse-Lautrec's 1893 poster of Aristide Bruant,
his gaze averted from the viewer, red scarf draped rakishly over
his black cape, is expected to command $40,000 to $50,000 at a Nov.
8 auction organized by Poster Auctions International in Manhattan.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At the auction, in the auditorium of the Armenian Diocese,
Second Avenue and 34th Street, A.M. Cassandre's dynamically
mechanistic hymns to modern transportation _ the Nord Express
railroad poster of 1927 and the Normandie ocean-liner poster of
1935 _ are each expected to sell for $7,000 to $9,000.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Shargel, Rennert's associate, does not expect much
disruption at the high end from the turmoil on Wall Street. ``We
always sell the best items,'' she said. ``People who have $50,000
or $100,000 to spend still have it.''
</P>
<P>
   For those with a little less, $200 will buy one of Tomoko Miho's
elegant 1968 posters saluting New York City, sponsored by Container
Corp. of America. These images recall the suavity and confidence _
however illusory _ of the era of Mayor John Lindsay.
</P>
<P>
   The Verrazano-Narrows Bridge, which was then quite new,
dominates one poster as a high-contrast black image against a
ruby-red sky, compressed by a telephoto lens into abstract
intersecting arcs and angles. Aligned vertically with the bridge
tower is the caption ``65 bridges to new york,'' all in lower-case
Helvetica type.
</P>
<P>
   Less legible but even more evocative of the period are the
posters produced in San Francisco for rock concerts at the Fillmore
West and Avalon Ballroom.
</P>
<P>
   A three-box set of 300 small posters, from 1966 to 1971, will be
offered at the Nov. 8 auction. Rennert estimated the price at
$10,000 to $12,000 and expects that a museum will buy the set.
</P>
<P>
   While it is said that anyone who can remember the '60s probably
wasn't there, it is difficult not to feel transported by the sheer
infuriating exuberance and urgency of these posters.
</P>
<P>
   They almost defy the viewer to decipher them, and certainly
suggest that the task would be best done in an altered state of
consciousness. Letter forms are fattened into thick slabs or loopy
balloons, looking less like Roman type than Sanskrit characters
that have been inflated with a tire pump.
</P>
<P>
   For a February 1967 concert by Moby Grape, the artist Victor
Moscoso created a Neptune figure in neon-bright raspberry,
shimmering in high contrast against an electric blue sea. Wrapped
around him is a great fish, as orange as Tang, whose scales spell
out ``Neptune's Nation'' and whose mouth encircles a nymph.
</P>
<P>
   One month later, for a dance concert called the Eye Ball,
Moscoso devised a multilayered diamond framing an eyeball. After a
few moments' study, the layers of the diamond reveal themselves as
letters: ``Big Brother and the Holding Company / The Charlatans /
Blue Cheer.''
</P>
<P>
   It was also in 1967 that Glaser's poster of Bob Dylan could be
bought for the price of an LP album. ``When I was in college, we
all had this pinned up,'' Bixenman said. ``At the end of the term,
we all threw it away.''
</P>
<P>
   A year or two ago, seeing the poster for sale at Poster America,
Glaser stopped, introduced himself and asked the price. He was
amazed to hear the figure. ``You would think that this would not be
one of the world's scarcest posters,'' he said. ``I mean, they
printed 6 or 7 million of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Then again, the poster was scarce enough that even its designer
was bereft of a copy in good condition. ``I really didn't have any
left except for one very beat-up, torn version,'' Glaser said.
</P>
<P>
   Several months later, he received a Dylan poster from Poster
America _ at no charge. ``I gave it to him,'' Bixenman said. ``I
thought if anyone should have it, he should have it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bixenman expects 35 American and European dealers at the fair,
which runs through Sunday. Admission is $30 for three days, $15 for
two days or $10 for one day. More information on the fair is
available at www.posterfair.com or (212) 206-0499, and on the
auction at www.posterauction.com or (212) 787-4000.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
