<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-PERKS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUDGET HOLDS PERKS FOR MISSOURI, KANSAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID GOLSTEIN  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star   WASHINGTON _ Smaller than a set of
encyclopedias, but larger than the New York City telephone
directory, the budget passed by Congress this week is also a
textbook of parochial concerns.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Kansas got $6 million, for instance, to help build a new public
policy center at the University of Kansas and name it after former
Sen. Bob Dole. Missouri, meanwhile, got $7 million to pay for a
new, state-of-the-art juvenile records system.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas also received $4 million to renovate the Topeka
elementary school that figured in the landmark Brown vs. Board of
Education Supreme Court case. And Missouri also got $2.5 million
that will help restore Kansas City's Union Station.
</P>
<P>
   So it goes.
</P>
<P>
   Littered among the big-ticket, national spending priorities,
such as money for Bosnian peacekeeping and aid to farmers, is a
host of earmarks for local projects. The roughly $500 billion
measure was crafted in a headlong rush to avoid a government
shutdown and allow Congress to leave town to campaign. Many
members, even as they voted for the bill, were disgusted with the
process.
</P>
<P>
   While he was happy to get money for farmers, Sen. Sam Brownback,
a Kansas Republican, said, ``A half trillion dollars in spending
was put together at the last minute with five people in the room,
and then we get less than 24 hours to look at the bill. This is
just not the way to run a democracy...and I really had to think
long and hard on whether or not to support the bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Most Democrats united behind President Clinton and presented a
unified front on the budget. They trumpeted priorities such as
education spending, and blasted the Republicans, who control
Congress, for causing the last-minute, breakneck pace of
negotiations needed to keep the government open .
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks to the Republican leadership, we've worked the fewest
days and passed the fewest bills in decades,'' said Democratic Rep.
Richard Gephardt of Missouri, the House minority leader. ``We
didn't even pass a budget resolution in the House.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the biggest howls came from within the Republican
Party's own ranks. Many members were critical of their own
leadership for giving away too much to the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John Ashcroft, a Missouri Republican and one of several
senators from both parties to vote against the spending bill, said
in a statement that the bill was ``a win for liberal
tax-and-spend.''
</P>
<P>
   But in a press release from the National Republican
Congressional Committee, Rep. John Linder of Georgia, who is
chairman of the group, said, ``The Republican Congress once again
won a victory for the American taxpayer.''
</P>
<P>
   In Missouri, the projects that got money in the measure
included:
</P>
<P>
   $4.5 million _ Statewide purchase of buses, vans and equipment.
</P>
<P>
   $2.5 million _ Buses, vans and equipment for the Older Adults
Transportation Service, which serves seniors and rural areas.
</P>
<P>
   $2 million _ Guadalupe Center, Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   $1.9 million _ Air-traffic control tower improvements at Lambert
Field in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   $1 million _ Intelligent Transportation System, which monitors
highways and gets information to drivers about problems. Half goes
to the Kansas City area, half goes to the state.
</P>
<P>
   $1 million _ Commuter rail study, half for a planning along
Interstate 35 in the Kansas City area, half for planning in St.
Louis, Jefferson City and Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   $750,000 _ Improvements to Thornberry Center for Youth and
Families in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   $500,000 _ Missouri Department of Conservation's Discovery
Center planned for Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas, the projects that got money include:
</P>
<P>
   $2 million _ Construction of Johnson County bus garage and
maintenance facility.
</P>
<P>
   $1 million _ YouthFriends project, a regional YMCA mentoring
project for at-risk children.
</P>
<P>
   $1 million _ Commuter rail study in Johnson County.
</P>
<P>
   $500,000 _ Hays Airport emergency landing system.
</P>
</TEXT>
