<HEADLINE>
AFRICA DESERVES BETTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1998 Kansas City Star   _ The woes of Africa can be surreal in
their horror.
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are droughts that turn whole regions to ash, and
visitations by locust swarms so immense they block the sun and
leave crop fields as bare as slate.
</P>
<P>
   There are flies whose larva, deposited through a bite, migrate
to the eyes and destroy sight. And a worm, the Guinea worm, that
enters a wound on the foot and grows as long as the leg of its
human host.
</P>
<P>
   There are eruptions of genocidal fury so ugly and so often that,
for the most part, the world can only look away in sorrow and
revulsion.
</P>
<P>
   There is the ancient torment, malaria, present now in strains
resistant to the commonly used drugs. And there's the new plague,
AIDS, whose virus infects such appalling numbers in some parts of
Africa that it's impossible to imagine how the spread can be
halted, or even slowed.
</P>
<P>
   Not many years ago there was that wretched Central African
Republic, ruled by a self-proclaimed emperor, a cannibal who
literally ate his subjects.
</P>
<P>
   Now there is Nigeria, Africa's most populous country and
potentially one of its richest _ so wrecked by the succession of
generals who've brutalized and looted it that much of its
population, especially in rural areas, has been reduced to hopeless
poverty.
</P>
<P>
   And poverty explains the hellish catastrophe of recent days, in
which gasoline flowing from a pipeline valve opened by thieves
ignited, incinerating at least 500 villagers, possibly many more.
</P>
<P>
   The dead, it was reported, were using cups and cooking vessels
to dip from a lake of spilled gas when a spark touched off the
inferno. Nigeria produces 2 million barrels of crude oil a day, but
because its refineries are broken and derelict it must import
gasoline, which common people cannot afford.
</P>
<P>
   The top police official of the region dismissed the victims as
people who ``came digging for free gold'' and ``got buried.''
Compassion like that is typical of thugs with a little power.
</P>
<P>
   I've been three times to Nigeria as a journalist. Except for a
few friends there _ decent people, who deserve better _ there's
nothing else about the place I find appealing.
</P>
<P>
   My last visit, nine years ago, was like a Hadean dream. The poor
were building their cooking fires in the unfinished concrete
cubicles of high-rise office buildings _ projects abandoned when
corruption had emptied the public treasury.
</P>
<P>
   Huge bridges vaulted partway out over brackish lagoons, then
stopped where the money ran out.
</P>
<P>
   The army at night rented its weapons to highway bandits. The day
I left, the air of the capital stank with burning rubber from tires
in roadblocks thrown up in some futile protest.
</P>
<P>
   At the airport, an old woman ticketed on our flight was found to
be carrying an infant that had been eviscerated and sewn full of
heroin. And the last sounds I heard before boarding the plane were
the falsetto whinnies and screeches of a man who'd been dragged
from the waiting area to be beaten by police for no evident reason.
</P>
<P>
   The fire that consumed those unfortunate villagers, awful as it
was, was but a small part of the greater fire of failure that has
devoured their country and wrecked its hopes.
</P>
<P>
   For more than half my lifetime I've loved Africa with a passion.
But if I never go back to Nigeria again it will be soon enough.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
