<DOCNO> NYT19981022.0335 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2231 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANDREBAUGHER-COX     10-22 1704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANDREBAUGHER-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Andre Braugher one complex character
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL OCTOBER 25: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Drew Jubera
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   He's Pembleton-ish. Not that many people would notice. Until
Andre Braugher won a dramatic actor Emmy this year for his role as
Detective Frank Pembleton on NBC's critically acclaimed,
little-watched ``Homicide: Life on the Street,'' he was TV's best,
littlest-known actor.
</P>
<P>
   Even winning the Emmy hasn't raised his public profile that much
yet _ he jumped the show at the end of last season and won't appear
on TV again until early next year, when he stars in movies on TNT
and Showtime. He also co-stars with Alec Baldwin in the independent
feature ``Thick as Thieves,'' due out this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm racing from project to project. Trying to strike while the
iron is hot,'' he says of his post-Emmy career.
</P>
<P>
   How hot is it?
</P>
<P>
   ``Hotter than it used to be.''
</P>
<P>
   For six years, Braugher, 36, created in the prickly, principled
Pembleton TV's most compelling male character _ not its sexiest
(George Clooney, Jimmy Smits and Noah Wyle are the ranking body
heat), not its grittiest (Dennis Franz drunk, Dennis Franz shot,
Dennis Franz naked), not its coolest (David Duchovny).
</P>
<P>
   Braugher inhabited a character so complex he almost couldn't be
categorized: a detective who went by the book, except when he threw
the book out; who could make an innocent man confess as deftly as
he could shake the truth from a guilty one; whose religious
conviction ran so deep he tested it far more than he trusted it.
</P>
<P>
   TV has produced few characters as dense and enigmatic as Frank
Pembleton. His scenes in ``the Box'' _ the ``Homicide''
interrogation room _ were TV's gold standard.
</P>
<P>
   ``What you will be privileged to witness is not an
interrogation, but an act of salesmanship,'' Pembleton advised a
rookie partner in the series pilot, ``as silver-tongued and
thieving as ever moved used cars, Florida swampland or Bibles. But
what I am selling is a long prison term _ for a client who has no
genuine use for the product.''
</P>
<P>
   Pembleton sold his ``client'' a prison term in that episode and
did the same in many memorable others. But because the show has
been a long-running ratings cripple, more people could tell you the
make of Don Johnson's car in ``Nash Bridges'' (yellow '71 Barracuda
convertible) than could tell you anything at all about Braugher in
``Homicide.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Very few people say, `Yo, Pembleton,''' Braugher says of his
off-screen life.
</P>
<P>
   He smiles. Braugher exists beyond Pembleton, of course, even if
it takes a minute to convince yourself of that when you first meet
him.
</P>
<P>
   He's in priest robes on this humid
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, standing in the parking lot outside a Stone Mountain,
Georgia basketball gym, where he's filming the TNT movie ``Passing
Glory.'' It's the true story of Father Paul Verrett (played by
Braugher), who in 1965 organized the first basketball game in New
Orleans between two undefeated Catholic high schools, one all-black
and one all-white. Co-starring Rip Torn and directed by Steve James
(``Hoop Dreams''), ``Passing Glory'' is scheduled to air in
January.
</P>
<P>
   Braugher's face is big and round and dark as a new moon (``You
could stare at his face forever and keep asking questions,'' series
co-star Michelle Forbes once said), and his easy smile is what his
wife, actress Ami Brabson (also his on-screen ``Homicide'' wife),
has called ``the most winning smile.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to our show. Can I get you a drink of water?''
Braugher greets a visitor, smiling. His tone is welcoming and
at-ease-putting, but also a kind of sly test of how far you'll let
this friendliness go. It's how Pembleton might greet a visitor if
he was playing Braugher.
</P>
<P>
   The two are not unalike. Both have an intense kind of smarts and
ooze an uncommon integrity. Neither is the easiest cat to get a
bead on. Braugher has been called ``regal,'' ``naturally
commanding,'' a guy who ``disdains false intimacies'' _ flattering,
but at-arm's-length descriptions that could just as easily apply to
Pembleton.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not intimidating to me, but some people are put off by
the sheer force of his intelligence,'' Richard Belzer allowed of
Braugher during their ``Homicide'' days.
</P>
<P>
   ``The essence of the man comes through, and in Andre it was the
perfect role,'' adds David Rosemont, co-executive producer of
``Passing Glory.''
</P>
<P>
   The youngest of four kids raised in a blue-collar household in
Chicago, Braugher attended Stanford University as a pre-med
student, with a second major in mechanical engineering. He got
onstage by accident: A friend asked him to be a last-minute fill-in
as Claudius in a student production of ``Hamlet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried out, got the part, learned all my lines in days and
did it. And it was terrible. But I felt alive for the first time. I
switched my major (to drama) right then and there.''
</P>
<P>
   He went on to get a master's degree from the Juilliard School in
1988. His career started immediately: stage (various Shakespeare
productions), TV (Telly Savalas' sidekick on ``Kojak''), film
(1989's ``Glory'').
</P>
<P>
   He moved to Los Angeles from New York to cash in on his small
but visible role in ``Glory'' as Thomas Searles, an idealistic
young soldier from Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came out (to Los Angeles) and sat by the phone, waiting for
something to happen. And nothing did.''
</P>
<P>
   He returned East to audition in 1991 for ``Homicide,'' a gritty
detective series put together by Oscar-winning director Barry
Levinson and Tom Fontana. Levinson said Braugher had the part after
reading four lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Andre is one of those actors who makes me think I'm a better
writer than I am,'' Fontana has said.
</P>
<P>
   The part had everything Braugher wants in a role: complexity,
keen language, lots of untidy drama.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to play complex, contradictory men,'' Braugher says.
``(Pembleton) was a family man who liked standing over dead bodies
(talking) with cops on a cold March night. He was a devout Catholic
who rejects the church. A con man and manipulator who was loyal and
loving. His life was ebb and flow and tug _ like in our lives. He
wasn't jumping over walls with a shiny Magnum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen a lot of heroes (on TV): They spot the oil on the
crankcase, which leads to the warehouse where the bad guys are. I
don't understand them. It's impossible to play something that
pure.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite critical raves (he received two previous Emmy
nominations, and TV Guide once gushed, ``If there's anyone doing
better dramatic acting on TV these days, we haven't seen it''),
Braugher says his ``Homicide'' work didn't accelerate his career.
He got supporting roles in such features as ``Primal Fear,'' ``Get
on the Bus'' and ``City of Angels'' and continued working on the
stage, where he won an Obie (best off-Broadway) for the title role
in Shakespeare's ``Henry V.''
</P>
<P>
   But Braugher left ``Homicide'' at the end of the series' sixth
season, before he received his overdue Emmy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I need to grow up and expand. It's easy to ossify as an
actor,'' he says. ``I loved working on (`Homicide'). But in 2015,
if you don't watch out, you can be like Peter Falk or Telly
Savalas, trapped in a character.''
</P>
<P>
   The Emmy finally has Braugher's phone ringing (he was so dazed
by his Emmy win he recalls thinking ``all these people are staring,
I better walk up. And then this beautiful, oddly familiar woman
handed me (a statue). I later realized it was Halle Berry''). Two
days after ``Homicide'' wrapped production last spring, he began
filming on ``Thick as Thieves.'' He then went to work on Showtime's
``Love Stories,'' a trilogy in which he directs one episode and
stars with Lynn Whitfield in another.
</P>
<P>
   This month he's been in Atlanta filming TNT's ``Passing Glory,''
co-written by acclaimed screenwriter John Sayles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just like manna from heaven,'' says Andre Carey, TNT's
vice president of original programming, of landing Braugher. ``It's
no great leap to know what a great actor he is, and now he's
getting the attention he deserves. Makes us look like geniuses.''
</P>
<P>
   But Braugher's notions of success are unconventional in an
industry famous for ego and excess. He once told an interviewer he
hadn't seen the blockbusters ``Independence Day'' or ``The Rock''
because he didn't believe either was ``an honest movie.'' He's fine
with being a star _ but on his own terms. It can't take him away
from his wife and two sons.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's probably a cool place to be in,'' says actor Bill Nunn
(``Do the Right Thing''), also in ``Passing Glory,'' of Braugher's
respected place just below stardom's real heat. ``He doesn't have
to work on going out. He can do what he wants.''
</P>
<P>
   He does. Braugher moved his family during his ``Homicide'' stint
from New York to Baltimore, where the series was filmed. He says
his was the only first marriage on the set. He has since moved the
family back to suburban New Jersey. He won't live in Los Angeles,
where he'd likely have more TV and film opportunities, unless
Brabson has to move there for her own career. She moved to
Baltimore for him; he'll move anywhere for her. He'd like to return
to TV next season, in a New York-based show, so he can go home
every night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a family man _ I like to tuck the kids into bed, make the
PTA meetings,'' he says. ``(The Emmy) was a lovely token of my
peers' esteem and validation for the hard work I've put into my
craft. But it taught me to realize all the simple and beautiful
things I have in my life. If I was a miserable man with an Emmy, it
wouldn't make up for having an Emmy. I never want the profession to
overburden the more important aspects of my life. If I reach the
pinnacle and go home to an empty house, I've failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking out for 2015, when we (Braugher and Brabson) can
look back when we're 50, when the boys are grown, and say we spent
positive time with them, taught them the lessons that needed to be
taught. If I can look back and say that, we've been successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm done,'' he then says suddenly and walks away across the
parking lot. Very ... Pembleton-ish.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
