<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 18:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2232 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOKS-MSKUBE25-COX     10-22 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-MSKUBE25-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COLUMN: Book review isn't poetry, but it is rhyme and reason
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL OCTOBER 25: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Edmund Wilson, as usual, said it with magisterial finality. For
114 days, beginning in the fall of 1962, a printers' strike left
New Yorkers without a daily newspaper _ and there were more dailies
then than now. It meant no sports pages, no stock market pages, no
crossword puzzles and, among other deprivations, no New York Times
Book Review. It no sooner was gone than Wilson said its
disappearance ``only made us realize it had never existed.''
</P>
<P>
   Into the breach came a fledgling biweekly calling itself The New
York Review of Books. It has been there 35 years this month, with
the same editors (Robert B. Silvers and Barbara Epstein), the same
distinctive covers and long blocks of type, the same brilliant
caricatures by David Levine.
</P>
<P>
   The strike was settled, the delivery trucks sent back out on
their routes and the Times Book Review returned to its role as
stolid bellwether of the book world. But the New York Review had
created a forum of its own, one in which books were the vehicle for
discussion of the full range of American intellectual life _ poetry
and science, art and politics, fiction and history. The New
Statesman, a good magazine gone to its grave, called its founding
``of more cultural import than the opening of the Lincoln Center.''
</P>
<P>
   The first issue sold out immediately. Here was a new kind of
magazine, one that took itself seriously but took its readers
seriously as well. It assumed they in fact were readers _ that they
were comfortable with ideas and had come to its pages with an
active intelligence, not the blank passivity that daily journalism
insists on assuming.
</P>
<P>
   And its editors and writers brought to those pages something
else: a political stance that started well to the left and has
never wavered. During the Vietnam War years, there was no more
committed opponent of American involvement than the New York
Review. The most famous cover in its history must be the one of
Aug. 24, 1967. During the midst of urban rioting, the New York
Review was showing its readers how to make a Molotov cocktail.
</P>
<P>
   The New Left and Old Left had already parted ways, but the
cocktail cover ended all hope of reconciliation. It moved Tom
Wolfe, who earlier called it ``The New York Review of Bores,'' to
declare it ``the chief theoretical organ of Radical Chic.''
</P>
<P>
   Home to nation's best writers
</P>
<P>
   But no one has ever doubted its standing as the leading
intellectual journal in the country. From the outset, it attracted
many of the country's best writers and thinkers and gave them acres
of space. The 35th anniversary issue finds Joan Didion reviewing
the Kenneth Starr report (accompanied by a Levine drawing of a
cigar-chomping Monica Lewinsky). In the same issue J.M. Coetzee
writes on ``Collected Fictions'' by Jorge Luis Borges; Louis Menand
reviews Norman Mailer's new novel, ``The Time of Our Time''; Alma
Guillermoprieto reviews three memoirs of Fidel Castro (one of them
out of print) and the Cuban revolution; and Luc Sante considers the
Walker Evans photography exhibition ``New York.'' Those five pieces
alone, most of them several thousand words in length, make up
barely a quarter of an issue that is vintage NYRB.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't a magazine in which the reviewer gives a quick thumbs
up or thumbs down. Rather, as James Wolcott wrote recently in The
New York Times, its purpose is to have ``issues and authors
settled, sentenced and roped in a bag.''
</P>
<P>
   But the trials are not swift. The review may be the only
publication left (with the possible exception of Hungry Mind
Review) that doesn't recognize attention-deficit disorder. In the
35th anniversary issue, the legal scholar Ronald Dworkin wrote what
must be 6,000 words on ``The Shape of the River,'' William Bowen
and Derek Bok's densely statistical defense of affirmative action
in American colleges. (At least Dworkin _ unlike the Magi of many
editorial pages _ actually read the thing.) It is tough sledding,
and then, at the bottom of the last column of type, one comes upon
these words: ``This is the first of two articles.''
</P>
<P>
   A loyal following after 35 years
</P>
<P>
   If you wonder what market there could still be for a magazine so
chockablock with type, consider this: Thirty-five years after its
first issue, paid circulation is 124,538 and the average length of
subscription is eight years. More telling, the typical subscriber
reports spending an average of two hours reading each issue.
Amazing.
</P>
<P>
   No one could deny that the salutes accorded the New York Review
are well earned, and yet it is the third cheer that is given
halfheartedly. Five years ago, on the occasion of its 30th
birthday, I wrote:
</P>
<P>
   ``For all its brilliance, its intelligence, its willingness to
ignore convention, The New York Review is a magazine that never
charms. To say so is to express more regret than dissatisfaction.
You can ask for too much, I suppose. It avoids all the sins of
everyday journalism _ the schmaltziness, the glibness, the numbing
idiocy _ but the words never quite rise off the page. They lie
there inert. They never shout, but neither do they sing.''
</P>
<P>
   Those words may not sing either. They are only a plea for an
occasional melody in a magazine that, once gone, will be missed
indeed. For now, one must say it's aging magnificently.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
