<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REM-QUOTES-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    From Berry to aging, the band speaks out
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL OCTOBER 25: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   THE NEW ALBUM ``UP''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think of this record as psychedelic. It's a good record to
listen to by yourself when you're hiding. You want to try to expand
your horizons without being a dilettante. This is not supposed to
be a record of great technical proficiency and dexterity. It's a
record of not trying to get it down perfectly, but having great
sounds and ideas come out. I just hope people give it a chance.
This is a record that takes two to three listens.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Mike Mills
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't always provide these easy, hummable songs. I read an
article that said 99 percent of hit singles are midtempo ballads
about universal love. I thought, `Hey, we're fresh out of those
this time around.' It would take a complete revolution in the way
music is marketed to make a record like this be as big as a Celine
Dion record. And that's OK. I like to sell a lot of records, but
it's more important that we do something that's challenging to us,
and that will bring people along with us. As much as people seem to
want the same thing over and over _ like with Pink Floyd they want
`Dark Side of the Moon' every time _ if you give them that, then
after about three times they don't want that anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Peter Buck
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about the saddest and most romantic record I've ever
made.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Michael Stipe
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   THE SINGLE, ``DAYSLEEPER''
</P>
<P>
   ``I worked the 11 to 7 shift when I was a teenager, cooking at a
Waffle House. It's a song about someone who is a soldier ant in
this huge structure, working at night, isolated. They're working
this kind of very small but significant job in this much larger
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Michael Stipe
</P>
<P>
   ``The label picked it. I think they picked it because it's the
one song that might sound a little bit like R.E.M.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Peter Buck
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always been really involved in picking out the singles,
but ever since we picked `E-bow the Letter' (the commercially
disappointing single from `New Adventures in Hi-Fi') well. ... The
singles we pick aren't necessarily predicated on the best
commercial use. We thought on this one, well, let's let the record
company do it.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Mike Mills
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   GROWING OLDER
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels pretty great. I'm on top of the world. Twenty-two is
its own thing, 38 is its own thing. You can't really say that
you're happier now than you were at any other time in your life. Is
it easy to compare you at 22 with you now? I like now a lot, but I
like now then, too. I think I may have been a little more embracing
of the darker things when I was in my early 20s, but that's just
something you go through. I don't think you can put an age on
music. I don't feel that way. If other people do, well, they can.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Michael Stipe
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone that I went to high school with, when I see them, one
out of 10 of them buys new records. The rest of them still have the
same record collection, but now it's on CD. I'm an anomaly. I go
out and see lots of shows. I probably buy 10 records a week. I read
reviews and get excited about stuff. But generally, if I go to a
club, I am one of the older people there. And I'm not that old.
There might be one guy older than me. And you always wonder what
he's doing there.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Peter Buck
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   THE RETIREMENT OF BILL BERRY
</P>
<P>
   ``It just made a difficult process even more so. We had never
been a three-piece before. The dynamic shifts. Everything that was
comfortable, none of that was there.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Michael Stipe
</P>
<P>
   ``If he had quit at the end of a record or the end of a tour, we
probably wouldn't have gotten back together. But he quit the first
day we were starting this record, basically. Between Mike (Mills)
and myself, we probably had 40 to 45 songs, really great demos, and
we were excited about getting into the process of it.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Peter Buck
</P>
<P>
   ``He (Berry) actually said, `If you're gonna break up, then I'm
gonna stay in because I don't want to be the one to break up the
band.' Like Peter said, if it had happened at the end of a project,
I'm sure we might not have broken up, but we certainly would have
taken some time off and thought about things and said, `Well, let's
take a little break and see if we still want to do this.' We were
all geared up and excited about all this new stuff, and this new
approach to recording, so why quit? We had the songs written. Why
quit just because Bill doesn't want to do it anymore?''
</P>
<P>
   _ Mike Mills
</P>
<P>
   --
</P>
<P>
   ON THE DECISION NOT TO TOUR
</P>
<P>
   ``We just didn't want to. We have a really good internal
barometer. Our instinct is really good on when to do stuff, and it
just didn't seem right. We really didn't want to dedicate the next
year to traveling around.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Michael Stipe
</P>
<P>
   ``We kind of felt that at this time in our careers and at the
age we are, we didn't think it made a whole lot of sense to go out
for seven months and play songs because that's what everybody
thought we should do. I think we want to concentrate more on
writing new songs and doing another record.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Peter Buck
</P>
<P>
   ``The two biggest records we ever had, we didn't tour on them.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Mike Mills
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-98 1840EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981022.0340 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2236 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REM-UPREVIEW-COX     10-22 0378
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REM-UPREVIEW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Quiet and cohesive, R.E.M. in love on `Up'
 &HT;    (EMBARGOED UNTIL OCTOBER 25: DO NOT USE BEFORE THEN)
 &HT;    By Steve Dollar
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Look at it this way. Now that R.E.M.'s stylistic legacy has been
recycled for the umpteenth time (check out that hopeful jangle
buoying the collegiate whimpering of current alterna-faves Sister
Hazel), why shouldn't R.E.M. recycle someone else's legacy?
</P>
<P>
   Replacing retired drummer Bill Berry with a fun house panoply of
vintage analog keyboards, percussive knickknacks and metronomic
synths, the newly defined trio has made an album that sounds like
an offhanded Kraftwerk tribute _ or electronic visionary Brian Eno,
or poppy British knob twiddlers Stereolab, or American indie-rock
stalwarts Yo La Tengo pretending to be Stereolab.
</P>
<P>
   It'll bore the pants off you the first time through, but slap on
some headphones _ as bassist/keyboardist Mike Mills suggests _ and
the music becomes progressively more involving: a core of intimate
revelation submerged in drones and pulses and waves and tweaky
smears of reverb, a harpsichord here, a stunted guitar solo there,
all paced at a stately tempo.
</P>
<P>
   At an extremely cohesive 64 minutes, ``Up'' bogs down in the
final stretch. The jauntiest tune is front-loaded: ``Lotus,'' with
its ``hey, hey!'' refrain and Three Dog Night keyboards layered
over vocalist Michael Stipe's bongo-cafe improv poetry (``ocean
flower aquarium''). Mostly though, Stipe is surprisingly direct and
uncontrived, much in the manner of ``Be Mine,'' from the previous
``New Adventures in Hi-Fi'' or the still, quiet moments of
``Automatic for the People,'' still R.E.M.'s finest hour. These are
love songs he's singing: ``Give me that smile/Just turn it on and
I'm lost again'' (``You're in the Air''); ``Someone has to take the
fall/Why not me?'' (``Falls to Climb''); ``I save your messages/
</P>
<P>
   Just to hear your voice'' (``At My Most Beautiful''). Underneath
its blatantly noncommercial slant, ``Up'' is as unabashed a display
of pop song romance as Mariah Carey's next lushly swathed trill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Up''
</P>
<P>
   R.E.M. Warner Bros. 14 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
