<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2237 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SINATRA-BOOK-COX     10-22 0771
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SINATRA-BOOK-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Private moments with Sinatra
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You've got to hand it to Pete Hamill. Here it is, barely five
months since Frank Sinatra died, and already the colorful New York
newspaperman and best-selling author (``A Drinking Life,'' ``Snow
in August'') has churned out a book that purports to tell us ``Why
Sinatra Matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Consider the chutzpah. Judging from the book's dated anecdotes,
the last time Hamill and Sinatra actually were together was in the
mid-1970s (although Hamill does tell us exactly where he was _ at
the Miami airport, watching CNN _ when he heard that Sinatra had
died May 14).
</P>
<P>
   At 185 pages, the book initially seems as slim and insignificant
as a certain bony-kneed, bow tie-wearing teenager who sang for
cigarettes and sandwiches in Hoboken, N.J. But appearances can be
deceiving. For just as young Frank Sinatra (``Francis Albert'' was
the stuff of legend, never his birth certificate, Hamill tells us)
attained larger-than-life status, there's also a surprising heft
and depth to Hamill's work.
</P>
<P>
   ``In their work all great artists help transcend the solitude of
individuals. ... They supply a partial response to the urging of
writer E.M. Forster: `Only connect,''' Hamill writes in the book's
too-cute-by-half ``Overture.'' ``In their ultimate triumph over the
banality of death, such artists continue to matter. So will Frank
Sinatra.''
</P>
<P>
   Forster? What, no Jilly Rizzo?!
</P>
<P>
   Not to worry. The perfectly named sidekick/New York club owner
shows up early, part of a group drinking at P.J. Clarke's saloon in
1970. Legendary sportswriter Jimmy Cannon's there, too, along with
Sinatra (who makes them stop playing Sinatra on the jukebox) and
Hamill.
</P>
<P>
   But such name-dropping proves the exception in ``Why Sinatra
Matters.'' As for dropping himself into the narrative, well, after
a scary start, Hamill does that just frequently enough to gain some
essential storytelling ``cred'' _ he grew up in a Brooklyn, N.Y.,
tenement, looking over the water at Hoboken and listening to adults
listening to him on tabletop radios; later, the two became
``friendly'' and Hamill even toyed with the idea of writing
Sinatra's autobiography.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why Sinatra Matters'' may not be autobiography, but it's a
very personal story nonetheless. It's the story less frequently
heard over the din of all those ``Rat Pack'' drinking tales, the
very public lovers' quarrels with Ava Gardner and Mia Farrow, the
accusations of mob ties and all the other high-pitched talk that
swirled around Sinatra for so many years.
</P>
<P>
   It's largely the story of one man's music _ how it initially
helped him rise up and out of obscure surroundings as the lonely,
only child. And then much later, after numerous personal and
professional failures, how it helped him find his place in the
world again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that ever permanently worked was the music,''
Hamill writes.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, one of the most intriguing aspects of ``Why Sinatra
Matters'' is Hamill's thesis that Sinatra's development as a
performer paralleled developments in 20th-century American society:
As the first-generation offspring of immigrants, Sinatra produced
music that resonated with that unique combination of disillusioned
world-weariness and unbridled optimism familiar to all those who'd
gambled everything on gaining a better life. As the fellow who
stayed home and sang romantic songs during World War II (his draft
classification was 4-F), Sinatra really came into his own only
around the time of the Korean War, when the more hardened,
questioning quality of his music spoke to many Americans.
</P>
<P>
   But forget sociological commentary. It's a prerequisite that
Sinatra books be stuffed with colorful anecdotes and quotes, and
Hamill doesn't disappoint. (Sinatra on New Jersey: ``We thought
everybody was on the take. ... We thought if God came to New
Jersey, he'd get on line to get his envelope.'') But from the
Kennedys and Marilyn Monroe to Farrow and the Rat Pack, it's also
surprising what he chooses to leave out of a book that prefers to
bulk up the man, not the myth.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had made many of us wiser about love and human
loneliness,'' Hamill concludes. ``And he was still trying to
understand what it was all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Or as Sinatra himself told Hamill while gliding through New York
on a snowy, early-'70s night: ``Maybe that's what it's all about.
Maybe all that happens is, you get older and you know less.''
</P>
<P>
   You've really got to hand it to Hamill.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
