<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURFER23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fox's `Brimstone' lacks fire, but plenty get iced
 &HT;    By Lyle V. Harris
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Television is going to heck in a handbasket, and Fox proves it
again with its new devil-made-me-do-it comic book drama,
``Brimstone'' (8 EDT tonight).
</P>
<P>
   Former ``thirtysomething'' hunk Peter Horton stars as Ezekiel
Stone, a highly decorated New York cop with a nagging health
problem _ he's dead.
</P>
<P>
   As we learn in the exposition-laden pilot, Stone was offed by a
two-bit punk (as opposed to the more expensive kind) and winds up
spending the last 15 years of his afterlife in hell.
</P>
<P>
   Although a goody-goody for most of his career, God is punishing
Stone for a vigilante rage during which he murdered his wife's
rapist.
</P>
<P>
   Despite what you've heard, ``Brimstone's'' devil (skull-faced
character actor John Glover) turns out to be a decent guy after
all. Ol' Scratch gives Stone a chance to redeem his sins by
returning to Earth and tracking down 113 of the world's wickedest
souls on the lam from Hades after ``a jailbreak.''
</P>
<P>
   Why hell needs jail is anyone's guess.
</P>
<P>
   All whispery and grungy-looking, Stone first must track down a
child killer who has come back disguised as a priest to fulfill his
apocalyptic visions by slaughtering innocent altar boys.
</P>
<P>
   Since Stone's from-hell prey are already dead, the only way he
can destroy them is by shooting out their eyes, a running plot
point that guarantees a gory denouement every week made more
``artsy'' by the show's quick-cutting camera work.
</P>
<P>
   As undead fantasy hero, Stone is reminiscent of ``Spawn,'' the
cult comic book hero who's also an animated feature on HBO. But
``Brimstone'' is not as much fun as WB's kicky ``Buffy the Vampire
Slayer'' or as morbidly mysterious as Fox's other spookfest,
``Millennium.''
</P>
<P>
   At best, ``Brimstone'' is barely passable entertainment for
Horton fans, who get to watch him shrug off speeding bullets and
bound from tall buildings while looking all tortured and testy.
</P>
<P>
   At worst, it may appeal to viewers who are tired of ``Touched by
an Angel'' and are happy that Satan is finally getting equal time.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: C
</P>
<P>
   SEEN AND HEARD
</P>
<P>
   Honeymoon hulk
</P>
<P>
   There's nobody bigger in the big, big world of televised
wrestling than Bill Goldberg. He's not just big, he's huge.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg doesn't lose. The ex-Georgia Bulldog and ex-Atlanta
Falcon wipes the mat with all comers. All the time.
</P>
<P>
   So, pardon us if it feels just a little bit strange to hear him
crooning a duet with fellow wrestler Kevin Nash. And that they're
singing Bette Midler's ``Wind Beneath My Wings.'' To each other.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg and Nash visit tonight's ``Love Boat: The Next Wave''
(9 o'clock EDT on UPN), playing tag-team partners who ... well,
what does it really matter? They're here, aren't they?
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Goldberg and Nash do wrestle on the boat. They act, too _
probably as well as anybody else on the show.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg's character is freshly married and he's a puppy around
his new bride. But it's clear Goldberg is having fun. Sometimes he
grunts his lines. Sometimes he just smashes the scenery.
</P>
<P>
   This ``Love Boat'' is all dolled up not only with Goldberg and
Nash but also with Robin Leach. Now there's somebody we'd like to
see Goldberg spear and jackhammer.
</P>
<P>
   Grades: A (for Goldberg _ we'd rather have him on our side)
</P>
<P>
   C- (for the ``Boat'' and all those namby-pamby cast regulars)
</P>
<P>
   _Bob Longino, c. 1998 Cox News Service
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: channelsurfer(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
