<SLUG> BC-PLEASANTVILLE-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S NOT A BLACK-AND-WHITE WORLD IN `PLEASANTVILLE'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING: 3 1/2 Stars 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ Gary Ross' wonderful new film, ``Pleasantville,''
taps into our collective nostalgia for the simplicity of the good
old days and then forces us to examine whether that bygone era was
really as swell as we remember. In fact, the movie prompts us to
ask ourselves whether Father really did know best or if everything
we now remember about the Eisenhower era comes courtesy of Nick at
Nite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pleasantville'' has plenty of other ideas, too _ the film
delves into the hows and whys of censorship, intolerance, emotional
repression as well as the enormous shaping power of television.
Coming on the heels of ``What Dreams May Come,'' it's also a
shining example of the thoughtful ways digital effects can be used
to further storytelling instead of, say, destroying the Eiffel
Tower by meteor storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pleasantville'' is the name of a 1950s ``Ozzie and
Harriet''-style sitcom where no problem lasts longer than 22
minutes. It's the favorite program of the teen-age David (Tobey
Maguire), who uses the show's steady brand of blandness to
counteract the stark realities of his own broken home.
</P>
<P>
   David's sexpot sister, Jennifer (Reese Witherspoon), would
rather watch a test pattern than another episode of
``Pleasantville.'' One night while they're fighting over a remote
control left by a mysterious TV repairman (the perfectly cast Don
Knotts), the two teens are zapped through the television screen to
the black-and-white world of the show.
</P>
<P>
   And what a world it is. In Pleasantville, the temperature is
always 72 degrees, it never rains, and the bathrooms don't have
toilets. (Think back: When did you ever see Wally or the Beav
actually inside a bathroom?)
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there's a flip side to this sterile perfection. Every
day follows the same routine; there are no surprises, no emotions,
no new ideas. The books inside the library are blank. Mom and Dad
(Joan Allen and William Macy) have two children, but they never
have sex or even sleep together. (Twin beds, you know.)
</P>
<P>
   After a few days, the presence of the two '90s kids begins to
upset the delicate balance of Pleasantville's world. Once Jennifer
takes her boyfriend up to Lovers Lane (Him: I wonder if we're going
too fast, what with us holding hands. Her: Maybe I should just
 &UR; !ital! &LR; pin &UR; !off! &LR;  you) and introduces sex into this Eden, the
daily routine takes an unexpected turn. The basketball team
actually loses a game. Kids don't know all the answers at school.
And the local soda shop, run by the mild-mannered, would-be painter
Mr. Johnson (Jeff Daniels), turns into a den of iniquity.
</P>
<P>
   Something else begins to happen, too. Dashes of color _ a red
rose here, a pair of blue eyes there _ begin to creep into
Pleasantville's black-and-white landscape. Citizens begin to feel
love, joy, fear and anger. Mom's wholesome facade begins to crack
when Jennifer gives her the talk about the birds and the bees. Soon
enough, Dad arrives home from work to a darkened house and no
dinner on the table. The words ``Honey, I'm home'' have never
sounded so forlorn as when Macy repeatedly delivers them and, not
hearing the cued response, wonders if he has done something wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, ``Pleasantville's'' mix of worlds and colors is a
remarkable achievement, but the movie has a lot more to offer than
digital wizardry. Ross, who wrote ``Big'' and ``Dave,'' makes an
impressive directorial debut with another fable, this one a modern
 &UR; !ital! &LR; Alice in Wonderland. &UR; !off! &LR;  The story cleverly shows the
importance of opposites and extremes in a fully formed life, and
how you can't truly know love unless you've experienced hurt and
disappointment as well.
</P>
<P>
   Or as David eloquently puts it during a town meeting: ``I know
you want things to stay `pleasant' around here, but there are so
many other things that are so much better, like silly ... or sexy
... or dangerous ... or wild.''
</P>
<P>
   The film's cast is uniformly excellent. Particularly noteworthy
are Macy and Allen, Pleasantville's Adam and Eve, two innocents who
respond to their awakening desires with a mixture of wonder and
fear. It's easy to underestimate how difficult a job these two had
since basically they're playing characters who are acting in their
own lives. But once their routines are upset and they're forced to
become real people, both characters are confronted with the great
unknown. And Macy and Allen deliver performances of sublime
complexity, worthy of attention around Oscar time.
</P>
<P>
   Because of their work and everything else in this outstanding
gem of a film, you'll never be able to watch those ``classic''
reruns the same way again. &UR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-98 1845EDT &QL; 
