<HEADER>
A2252 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONTROVERSY-FILMS-LAD     10-22 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONTROVERSY-FILMS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD ROLLING OUT FILMS WITH A DISTURBING TREND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If you flinched when Ben Stiller got his privates
caught in the teeth of his zipper in ``There's Something About
Mary'' or covered your eyes while Tom Hanks and company took Omaha
Beach during ``Saving Private Ryan,'' then you might want to avoid
going to the movies for the next few weeks. An avalanche of films
with disturbing themes, unsavory characters and creepy situations
are making their way into theaters, and audiences, if they're brave
enough, are going to have an unprecedented number of opportunities
to squirm in their seats.
</P>
<P>
   Already in theaters in Todd Solondz's ``Happiness,'' a look at
suburban loneliness and alienation that features a sympathetic
family man who sexually preys on his son's school chums. Then
there's the trio of movies featuring Nazis _ ``Apt Pupil''
(teen-ager finds Nazi war criminal in neighborhood and adopts him
as a role model), ``American History X'' (neo-Nazi skinhead repents
and tries to save his kid brother from adopting him as a role
model), and Roberto Benigni's ``Life Is Beautiful'' (a heartrending
tale of a father's love for his son while living in a Nazi death
camp).
</P>
<P>
   ``Life Is Beautiful'' actually doubles as a comedy, a rare
attempt to use humor to shed light on human depravity and a telling
illustration of how far filmmakers are willing to push the
boundaries of convention and taste these days. What's even more
interesting is that audiences seem to be responding.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people are crying for a departure from the
formulaic,'' says actor Edward Norton, star of ``American History
X,'' and no stranger to controversy from his work in the
much-debated ``The People vs. Larry Flynt.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And I think it's great,'' Norton continues. ``There are lots
of completely valid goals of film and art. There's entertainment,
which is a very worthwhile goal and, sort of, escape, and then
there's also provocation, even agitation, which is sometimes very
healthy.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the confluence of controversial films is just a
reflection of the times. Last month at the Telluride Film Festival,
the moderator of a panel discussion picked up on an increased
cultural willingness to deal with bodily fluids when he said, ``Ten
years from now, we will look back on 1998 as the year of
`Happiness,' `There's Something About Mary'' and Monica Lewinsky's
dress.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe. Or maybe people will look back on this year as the time
when films _ mainstream and independent alike _ finally began to
mirror America's tabloid culture, in which no subject, however
unseemly, is regarded as taboo. (Exhibit A: daytime talk. Exhibit
B: the evening news.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I suppose with what the president is doing ... these really
are perfect movies for the times,'' says Brad Renfro, co-star of
``Apt Pupil.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
UGLY BEHAVIOR
</P>
<P>
   Consider some of the other films that are either playing now or
will be in theaters soon: the black comedy ``Very Bad Things,''
which follows the ramifications of a drunken bachelor party where
the good-looking swinging buddies murder the prostitute they hired;
``Pleasantville,'' a lighthearted, if pointed, jab at (among other
things) conformity in the suburbs; and ``The Celebration,'' a raw
look at a family tearing itself apart at the 60th birthday of its
father (the eldest son toasts his dad by accusing him of molesting
his sister and himself).
</P>
<P>
   There's also ``Your Friends and Neighbors,'' Neil LaBute's
withering follow-up to ``In the Company of Men''; the marshal law
drama, ``The Siege,'' which already has Arab-American and Muslim
groups up in arms; the NC-17 rated ``Orgazmo,'' Trey Parker's
(``South Park'') story about a Mormon porn star; and ``Beloved,''
which features everyone's favorite talk-show host and role model,
Oprah Winfrey, confronting one family's nightmare with slavery in
graphic, unsparing detail.
</P>
<P>
   After all this, the Thanksgiving trio of ``A Bug's Life,''
``Babe: Pig in the City'' and ``The Rugrats Movie'' will be
welcomed by audiences as nothing short of an emotional catharsis.
Arriving as they do after this wave of films, though, people might
expect to see Babe roasting on a spit at a skinhead rally instead
of cavorting with his animal friends.
</P>
<P>
   Says ``Chicago Hope'' star and ``Very Bad Things'' director
Peter Berg: ``I think what many of these movies are trying to do is
take the monster and bring it in the house so you couldn't stay in
the house and look at it out the window. The monster is in the
house with you.''
</P>
<P>
   What's disappointing to some moviegoers is that while all these
monsters are on the loose now, studios, for the most part, keep
them caged up for the rest of the year. Indeed, once Thanksgiving
draws near, all these films will be shunted aside for big studio
fare like ```Meet Joe Black,'' ``Psycho,'' ``Star Trek:
Insurrection'' and the Julia Roberts tearjerker ``Stepmom.'' It
will be well into next year before we see this kind of challenging
fare again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, there's just a slew of these things, really good
movies in many cases, which are going to be competing, regrettably,
for a relatively small portion of the audience,'' says horror
writer and film director Clive Barker, one of the producers of the
upcoming gay-themed film ``Gods and Monsters,'' which is about the
later life of ``Frankenstein'' director James Whale.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be nice if we could come to the place where these
kinds of pictures would have more of a chance year round. As it is,
it feels like feast or famine.''
</P>
<P>
   And at the moment, it's feast, which means that studios are
doing everything they can to separate their movies from the
competition. Since most of these films don't feature A-list (or, in
many cases, Z-list) stars, the advertising campaigns often
highlight their perversity as a selling point.
</P>
<P>
   It's almost surprising that Good Machine, the production company
that picked up ``Happiness'' after Universal Pictures CEO Ron Meyer
ordered subsidiary October Films to drop it, isn't using a quote
from Meyer himself. He did reportedly say that he would throw
himself in front of a truck rather than let October release
``Happiness.''
</P>
<P>
   Says Solondz: ``I kind of liked that. It's almost a badge of
honor.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, it certainly is.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
