<HEADLINE>
FILE TREY PARKER'S `ORGAZMO' UNDER STINKY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
OUR RATING:   1 star 
 
 
BY BOB STRAUSS 
c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; LOS ANGELES _ ``Orgazmo'' aims for sophomoric but barely hits
moronic. This satire of the porno film industry is so inept, in
fact, it makes your basic amateur X-rated production look like
``Gone With the Wind.''
</P>
<P>
   The humor attempted here comes strictly from the breaking-wind
school, except most schoolyard jokes are funnier than anything this
movie has to offer.
</P>
<P>
   Judging by ``BASEketball'' and now this thing, Trey Parker, one
of the creators of ``South Park,'' should stick to scatological
cable cartoons. He wrote, directed and stars in ``Orgazmo.'' None
of these tasks were performed well.
</P>
<P>
   Parker's creative partner, Matt Stone, co-produced and has a
small role as a semi-consciously gay lighting guy. He gets three of
the film's five laughs.
</P>
<P>
   The idea here is that Parker's Joe Young, a naive Mormon
missionary, becomes a sex movie superstar in order to pay for the
temple wedding that Lisa, his fiancee back in Utah (Robin Lynne
Raab), has her heart set on. His film character Captain Orgazmo, a
kind of sexual superhero, becomes a cultural phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   When the guilt-ridden Joe tries to leave the trade, mob
pornmeister Maxxx Orbison (Michael Dean Jacobs in the worst movie
performance of the year), kidnaps Lisa. Captain O and his runty,
sex toy-bedecked sidekick (Dian Bachar, the runty sidekick in
``BASEketball'') then have to become real heroes. Some of this _ a
lot of this _ is played with unaccountable, if strained
seriousness, as if a plot like this was important or something.
</P>
<P>
   But it's the bad jokes that hurt more than the witless drama.
Consider the filmmaker's favorite running visual gag: Every time a
porn actress prepares to strip for action, some nude guy with a
hairy behind steps in front of the camera. Now that's satire of a
high order.
</P>
<P>
   Parker could probably argue that ``Orgazmo'' is only making fun
of what passes for humor in the adult video universe. He could,
also, reasonably contend that his film looks so consistently ugly
because porn often does, too. He might even put forth the
proposition that making fun of Mormons is an unenlightened thing to
do, so that's why the film's many gags at their expense are
uniformly stupid.
</P>
<P>
   What I'd doubt Parker could explain, though, is why anyone would
spend a few weeks and what was apparently a month's worth of lunch
money on a project as thoroughly unrewarding as ``Orgazmo.'' Or,
for that matter, on a ticket and the time it takes to sit through
this. &UR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
