<DOCNO> NYT19981022.0360 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2260 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      10-22 1216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES EARNED PLACE AMONG BEST EVER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   You know about the 114 victories, the staggering 22 games they
finished ahead of the second-place Red Sox in the American League
East, and their steady march through the playoffs en route to the
inevitable triumph in the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   But it was even more of a Yankees year than you might think.
</P>
<P>
   They even won their Old-Timers Day game against the Dodgers when
_ get this _ Willie Randolph hit a home run over the left-field
fence.
</P>
<P>
   That's the final proof of just how much the year 1998 belonged
to the New York Yankees, and now the irresolvable debate begins.
</P>
<P>
   Were we looking at the Greatest of All? The natural defensive
tendency of anyone historically minded enough to be aware of the
1902 Pirates, 1927 Yankees, 1936 Yankees, 1939 Yankees, 1955
Dodgers, 1961 Yankees, 1972-73-74 A's, and 1975-76 Reds is to say
no, of course not. Baseball has changed. Expansion has dispersed
the talent too widely. And yeah, whom did they beat, anyway?
</P>
<P>
   Don't buy it. The Yankees have earned a seat at the head table
with the best teams of all time, and their claim to being the
greatest is a lot better than traditionalist hardheads will ever
concede.
</P>
<P>
   The other teams come at you with Hall of Famers and arguable
Hall of Famers, and this Yankee team can't do that. The only
projected Hall of Famer on the 1998 Yankees is 24-year-old
shortstop Derek Jeter, and he is another 8-10 good years from
having anything concrete to talk about in terms of Cooperstown
enshrinement.
</P>
<P>
   There is no Honus Wagner, no Babe Ruth, no Lou Gehrig, no Joe
DiMaggio, no Roy Campanella, no Mickey Mantle, no Reggie Jackson,
no Johnny Bench, Pete Rose, or Joe Morgan _ in other words, not a
single, obvious, no-questions-asked, first-ballot Hall of Famer _
on this entire club. (Without getting into the Sargasso Sea of a
Pete Rose debate, you know what I mean by including him.)
</P>
<P>
   So?
</P>
<P>
   With the 1998 New York Yankees, it's all about team. That's it _
T-E-A-M. If we assume that the obvious goal of any general manager
is to assemble a 25-man unit that has a high level of expertise in
every conceivable phase of the game, then the new world champions
will serve as the model for generations to come.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees were 61-20 at the All-Star break, and they had zero
position player starters in the game, nor did they deserve any. The
Yankees have no members of the Silver Slugger club, the players
selected as the best hitters at their position. Their only Gold
Glove winner is Bernie Williams. It is highly unlikely that a
Yankee will be named MVP, although Jeter will finish high. All this
underscores the reality of their phenomenal team play.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, they did have the best pitching staff in baseball.
Let's not forget that.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the assets of the 1998 New York Yankees: 1. Great
starting pitching. 2. Excellent middle relief. 3. Outstanding short
relief. 4. People who know how to get on base. 4. People who know
how to drive in other people. 5. Astonishing top-to-bottom
offensive balance in the batting order. 6. People who can catch the
ball. 7. People who can steal bases and take the extra base. 8.
People who know how to check their egos at the clubhouse door and
channel their energies toward one thing _ winning that day's game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a terrific ball club when it comes to self-motivation and
determination,'' salutes manager Joe Torre. ``This ball club is
like no other club I've ever been around.''
</P>
<P>
   There, by the way, is another extremely important New York
Yankee asset. In the Bronx, as in no other place in the baseball
world, it is vitally important to have the proper man running the
ball club. For there are but two types of major league managing
jobs _ the 29 on teams not run by George Steinbrenner and the one
working for George Steinbrenner.
</P>
<P>
   Torre was handed the most complete baseball team he has ever
seen, and he knew exactly what to do with it. Baseball is the
longest season of all. It begins in February and it can last, if
you're lucky, until the last week of October. Keeping people
physically and mentally sharp is not easy, but Torre was able to do
it. He can praise the players for their self-motivation all he
wants, but those on the inside know how valuable his approach to
leadership was for this team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe has been a great manager, a great leader for us,'' lauds
Williams. ``He has really taken the trouble to know what makes
everyone tick and how he can get the best out of everybody to play
up to the best of their ability.''
</P>
<P>
   Sounds easy, right? It isn't.
</P>
<P>
   There should be credit enough for everybody. Start with Gene
``Stick'' Michael, a superb baseball man who has worn many hats
during his distinguished Yankee career. He is currently director of
scouting, but in a previous incarnation as general manager, he made
some great moves, the best of which was trading Roberto Kelly to
Cincinnati for a strong-willed right fielder named Paul O'Neill.
The latter is entrenched as the Yankees' No. 3 hitter. He is a
rock-steady .300 hitter, run producer, and defender. The former has
now been moved eight (8) times since 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Credit is due 31-year-old rookie GM Brian Cashman, who looks
like _ bear with me _ a young, non-mustachioed Groucho Marx. Tabbed
as a future GM by Steinbrenner when he was in his early 20s, he has
been a superb liaison between The Boss and The Skipper (``He's
tough. He gives his opinion. He does a good job for me'' _ Torre).
Cashman also made the Deal of the Year, sending Kenny Rogers and
``cash considerations'' to Oakland for Scott Brosius, a k a Mr.
Series MVP.
</P>
<P>
   There is credit available for all the players. There is credit
available for Arthur Richman, a special assistant to Steinbrenner
who first suggested Torre as a possible manager to his Boss. There
is credit available for an amazingly credentialed coaching staff
(Jose Cardenal, Chris Chambliss, Tony Cloninger, Mel Stottlemyre,
Randolph, and Don Zimmer), which, almost without question, boasts
of the greatest playing accomplishments of any staff in baseball
history.
</P>
<P>
   And there is even credit available for Steinbrenner, who,
recognizing the greatness before him, stayed as quiet as he
possibly could (by Steinbrennerian standards, anyway).
</P>
<P>
   It all came down to this: The 1998 New York Yankees had as many
ways to beat you, with as many talented people on their 25-man
roster, as any team in baseball history. And with a final record of
125-50, they usually did.
</P>
<P>
   The Greatest of All? In knock-your-socks-off individual talent?
No. But in the combination of all-around skill and the desire to
get it done? Yes.
</P>
<P>
   Torre, bless his middle-aged heart, has compared his team to the
Old Celtics. ``Nobody really cared if they scored 30 points. They
worked together, and it was fun to watch them,'' Torre points out.
``They only really cared about the end result, which was winning.''
</P>
<P>
   And now we have the 1998 New York Yankees. ``The one thing I
would love to have people think about is there's no one name that
comes to mind but the team itself,'' Torre says.
</P>
<P>
   The team. What a refreshing thought.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
