<HEADLINE>
GOV. WILSON SAYS HE WILL RUN FOR PRESIDENT IF HE GETS FUNDING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ California Gov. Pete Wilson said Thursday that
he'll run for White House in 2000 if he can garner enough money to
mount a serious challenge for the Republican nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be very interested in running again if, realistically,
the money is there,'' Wilson told reporters. ``But that remains to
be seen.''
</P>
<P>
   Wilson said he would need about $15 million in his election
coffers in time for the first presidential primary held in New
Hampshire on February 22, 2000. Building such a treasury won't be
easy, Wilson conceded, adding that it would require an ``awesome
amount of fund raising.''
</P>
<P>
   The more money in the bank, the better equipped a candidate is
to buy advertising in local markets and get his message to voters.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson ran for the Republican nomination in 1996 but his bid
quickly fizzled in part because the GOP faithful were not
enthusiastic for his politically moderate views on such hot-button
issues as abortion and gay rights. He also suffered a throat
ailment that affected his speaking ability.
</P>
<P>
   This time around, however, the political landscape is different.
For starters, there is no incumbent in the White House to unseat.
And Wilson wants to move up California's primary to March 7, 2000,
so that it coincides with primaries in New York and at least eight
other states.
</P>
<P>
   The action would contract the presidential nomination process
and favor better-financed candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Wilson, who is leaving office this year under the state's term
limits, said that he will wait until leaving office in January
before investigating a presidential bid. He said he thought that
running for the White House as an ex-governor, as Ronald Reagan
successfully did in 1980, would be easier than trying to campaign
while still being governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found that I was campaigning on the weekends because I was
doing a job during the week,'' Wilson said. ``If you are from a
large state, it is challenging to do both.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-98 1852EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
