<HEADLINE>
TODD COLLINS FOLLOWS INSTINCTS, AND DOES HIS HOMEWORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Last Dec. 28, in the second quarter of the
AFC wild-card playoff game against Miami, Todd Collins made a play.
A very good play. He picked up Dan Marino's check-off, knew the
Dolphins quarterback was calling a slant play and anticipated the
throw, made the interception, and ran 40 yards for a touchdown to
give the Patriots a 14-0 lead which turned into a 17-3 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Collins's great anticipation was a source of mystery. How did he
know what was coming? Did the Patriots know the Dolphins' plays?
</P>
<P>
   ``It turned into some big espionage thing,'' said Collins. ``We
didn't know their plays. When you play a team three times, you file
away certain numbers they use on their check-offs, and when you
hear it, you react. I do that in almost every game. There are
things you hear that you anticipate what's going to happen and get
them right. And there are other things you hear that you think you
know that you're wrong on.
</P>
<P>
   ``That turned out to be a big play in that game. But to say we
knew what was coming all the time _ that's just not true.''
</P>
<P>
   Dolphins coach Jimmy Johnson reportedly changed his audibles and
did change his offensive coordinator and the entire offense after
that game.
</P>
<P>
   Marino still believes the Patriots knew a lot of what was
coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they had an idea about some of them,'' he said during
his conference call this week. ``We had some of the stuff for quite
awhile. I'm sure they had a pretty good idea. I figured they were
game-planning pretty well against us.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins said a smart player will listen and learn and try to
gain every advantage possible against a savvy veteran quarterback
like Marino. He knows it's unlikely he'll hear the same signals
Sunday at Pro Player Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, they probably do some things differently now, but
it doesn't mean we can't study them and try to figure it out all
over again,'' said Collins. ``I know they do things differently now
where they emphasize the run more, but they still have to throw the
ball, and sometimes they like to go with their short passing game.
I think as a defense, you always have to anticipate things. And
we'll probably anticipate things again. That's not cheating or
knowing their plays. That's just trying to guess right.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins said the Patriots had the Dolphins' number last year,
but he's also aware how rapidly the situation can change. He
believes the Patriots will be particularly wary after suffering an
embarrassing 24-14 defeat to the Jets on national television.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just didn't play well and we got beat,'' said Collins. ``On
that night, they did all of the right things and we didn't play the
way we're capable of playing. But we have pride. We know this is a
divisional game and that this is a team we have to beat. We knew
that last year and we beat them in some big games. This is for
first place, and everybody wants it.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins, a quiet, humble country boy from Tennessee, said he's
not upset that fellow linebackers Chris Slade and Ted Johnson seem
to get all the attention. Every year, it seems Collins, faces a
challenge from Tedy Bruschi, and every year he goes to camp and
proves why he belongs as a starter in the regular defense.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Jets, he didn't play that much because the Patriots
constantly were in the nickel package, which calls for Bruschi to
step in as a pass rusher in Collins's spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing wrong with being in the background,'' Collins
said. ``Don't get me wrong _ getting praise isn't bad, either. I've
gone through a growing process here. I don't worry about things
that I can't control. People are always going to have opinions
about you, good or bad. People are going to pick you apart and
people are going to praise you. One thing I learned from Coach
(Bill) Parcells is you can't get too high and you can't get too
low.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Parcells made him low. So low that Collins decided to
retire in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, it was probably best for him. Parcells
persuaded him to come back, and he did so with a new verve that
helped the 1996 Patriots to the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   His contract is up at the end of the year, and he feels he's
having one of his best seasons, a continuation from last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a process,'' said Collins. ``When you're a young kid,
you're not quite sure of yourself and where you're supposed to be.
You don't have that confidence. That slowly builds, and I think
from last year to this year, I have that now. I have an idea of
what's going on out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins won't be looking to break the bank in the offseason, but
he does want to finish his career here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I enjoy this system and this team and the people in it,'' he
said. ``I think this is a very good team that can go far if we put
our minds to it. The big thing is that I have fun playing
football.''
</P>
<P>
   Never so much fun as last Dec. 28.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
