<HEADLINE>
MIAMI'S APPROACH: A STINGY DEFENSE, A DULL BUT STRONG OFFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVIE, Fla. _ One fascinating statistic stands out from the
Miami Dolphins' first six games. Miami has scored 6 points _ total
_ in the first quarter, while its opponents have scored 7.
</P>
<P>
   So if you're worried about forgetting to turn back your clocks
this weekend and missing the first quarter of the Patriots' game in
Miami, fret not. Not much happens early in Dolphins games.
</P>
<P>
   There is a pronounced lack of production even though the
Dolphins script every play of their early drives. Only Woody Hayes
might want to know what would happen if the Dolphins didn't script
their early plays.
</P>
<P>
   This is what Jimmy Johnson has wrought in Miami _ a quick,
aggressive, stingy defense that already has two shutouts, and a
dull, conservative offense with a journeyman at running back (Karim
Abdul-Jabbar), one journeyman wide receiver (O.J. McDuffie), and
one of the greatest passers of all time (Dan Marino) handing the
ball off play after play.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can establish some sort of physical game, a game like
the Patriots like to play,'' said McDuffie, ``then it will be a
long, hard battle.''
</P>
<P>
   For sure, the Dolphins will try. Though team after team has
exploited the Patriots' pass defense, especially New England's
nickel and dime packages, the Dolphins likely won't be looking to
Marino to do the same, unless they fall behind. Johnson has told
his offensive players to look extra long at New England game tapes
to discern the Patriots' blitzes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've learned their blitzes,'' McDuffie said
yesterday. ``We've simplified our offense enough now that we can
pick up their blitzes and not be confused again. We've been
confused more than anything (against the Patriots). It hasn't been
anything difficult that the Patriots did, but they just confused us
a lot. Now, with the simplification of our offense, we'll be more
ready to pick up the different things they bring at us.''
</P>
<P>
   Coaches, as well as players, win games in the NFL. Bill Parcells
and the Jets coaches took away the Patriots' strengths on both
offense and defense Monday night. Conversely, Johnson may have been
at his worst last January when New England beat Miami in a playoff
game at Foxborough. Johnson's Dolphins seemed unprepared for New
England 10 months ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We felt helpless in that playoff game last year,'' said tight
end Troy Drayton. ``But last year we were more a passing team,
while this year we've been establishing the run.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only did the defensive game plan drawn up by the Patriots
coaches leave Miami totally confused, but the Patriots also knew
Marino's audibles, leading directly to a Todd Collins interception
and touchdown. Johnson reportedly knew that New England knew his
audibles but could not or would not change them; Johnson's decision
to sign troubled running back Lawrence Phillips a month earlier
looked savvy in comparison.
</P>
<P>
   Phillips is gone and so are the audibles. Marino's option now
when he sees a defense he doesn't like is a ``check-with-me''
system in which he can change to another set play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel we're more ready for them this time around,'' said
McDuffie. ``Our offense is a lot less complicated than it was in
terms of picking up blitzes and the different things they try to do
up front to confuse us. I think we're much better prepared for them
than we were.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dolphins will go to great lengths to say this year's offense
is much different from last year's weak outfit, even though it
seems Miami once again looks to pass only when necessary.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, if there is a difference, it is that Miami is sometimes
more conservative in its formations, often going to only two wide
receivers and lining up with two tight ends, a true running
formation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing this year is we're trying to balance the running
game with the passing game,'' said Drayton. ``The balance is the
key to everything. Last year we didn't dictate the tempo of the
game on offense. We sat back and had four wide receivers and we
didn't get much out of that but a lot of pressure (on Marino). But
this year we have an attacking-style running game and an
attacking-style passing game, and that's the way to beat the other
team ... mano a mano.''
</P>
<P>
   Explanations aside, this appears to be the same side of beef,
only sliced differently. The Dolphins tried to run the ball last
year but often couldn't, just as they are intent on running the
ball this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having two tight ends not only helps us get out on pass
patterns but also helps out in protection,'' explained Drayton.
``When the defenses bring their linebackers or their strong safety
(on blitzes), we're more ready for that than last season. It brings
an extra dimension to our offense.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
