<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLOBAL-WARMING-$ADV25-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GLOBAL WARMING NEGOTIATIONS CONTINUE DESPITE SENATE OPPOSITION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, Oct. 25) (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1998 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Last December world leaders, exhausted but
exhilarated, emerged from marathon negotiations in Kyoto, Japan,
with an agreement to cut emissions of greenhouse gases that many
scientists say are dangerously warming the earth's atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton immediately hailed the agreement, known as the
Kyoto Protocol, as ``environmentally strong and economically
sound.''
</P>
<P>
   But while it called for deep slashes in emissions by industrial
nations, it exempted developing countries from similar cuts. That
angered the U.S. Senate, which earlier in the year had voted 95-0
to reject any treaty that did not impose the same requirements on
the developing countries.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with the Senate objections, the Clinton administration
planned to mount a year-long public relations campaign led by Vice
President Al Gore, a fervent supporter of environmental causes.
</P>
<P>
   The administration and its allies in the environmental movement
believed that such a campaign would keep the issue before the
public until negotiators met again on Nov. 2 in Buenos Aires.
There, they hoped, U.S. negotiators could persuade some of the
major developing countries, particularly China and India, to agree
to emission cuts.
</P>
<P>
   With some major developing countries on board and the American
public behind the agreement, the administration assumed it could
then persuade the Senate to ratify the accord.
</P>
<P>
   But that scenario blew up on Jan. 21, when the Monica Lewinsky
scandal broke. With Clinton fighting for his political life, the
Kyoto agreement, along with many other issues, was pushed aside as
the White House marshaled most of its energy on saving the
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard for people to focus on the melting icecaps in the
Antarctic when they're being titillated by Monica,'' said William
Bumper, an environmental lawyer here who is an expert on global
warming.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's troubles didn't stop opponents of the Kyoto agreement,
particularly industry groups, from waging their own PR campaign.
</P>
<P>
   With no counter-attacks from the administration, the campaign
succeeded to such an extent that even environmental groups have
acknowledged it has hurt their cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew we were in trouble when my 13-year-old son was swayed
by a commercial that shows a pair of scissors cutting out
developing countries on a world map with a voice in the background
saying that these countries will be let off the hook,'' said Nancy
Kete, director of the global climate change program at the World
Resources Institute, an environmental group here.
</P>
<P>
   The administration's failure to rally public support for the
Kyoto accord also has allowed opposition to the treaty to harden in
the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is almost no support for the agreement as it stands in
the Senate,'' said Deb Fiddelke, press secretary for Sen. Chuck
Hagel, R-Neb., a leading opponent of the accord.
</P>
<P>
   And without Senate support, environmentalists concede that the
agreement has virtually no chance of being accepted by the world's
other industrial countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States is like the 800-pound gorilla in the living
room,'' said Alden Meyer, director of government relations for the
environmental group Union of Concerned Scientists. ``You just can't
ignore it.''
</P>
<P>
   But nations backing the agreement are pressing ahead. When
diplomats from 160 nations meet on Nov. 2 in Buenos Aires, they
hope to hammer out details on methods to monitor and enforce the
agreement.
</P>
<P>
   American negotiators _ led by Stuart Eizenstat, undersecretary
of state for economic, business and agricultural affairs _ will try
to entice some developing countries to agree to emission cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States has made clear that developing countries
must be a part of any treaty,'' said David Sandalow, associate
director for International Environmental Policy for the White House
Council on Environmental Quality.
</P>
<P>
   As it now stands, the accord would require the world's
industrial nations to reduce their emissions of carbon dioxide and
five other heat-trapping greenhouse gases to 5.2 percent, on
average, below their 1990 levels. The United States would be
required to cut emissions 7 percent below 1990 levels by 2012.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the difficulties, Kete and other environmentalists
believe the Senate eventually will ratify the accord. They cite
polls from environmental groups showing that a majority of
Americans, while not favoring the Kyoto agreement, nonetheless
consider global warming a major environmental threat.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, environmentalists argue, governments will be unable
to ignore the growing impact of global warming on the earth over
the next 10 or 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the country and the world begin to see more floods and
more droughts and higher temperatures, there will be no choice but
to act,'' said Daniel Lashof, senior scientist at the environmental
group Natural Resources Defense Council.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
