<HEADER>
A2297 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT &LR;      10-22 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THEATER-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEATER NOTES: SMALL BUDGETS, BIG SUCCESSES; ON THE DOTTED LINE; A
PERSONAL DRAMA; MAKING LIGHT OF `MEDEA'; RIGG IN `PHEDRE' 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JESSE McKINLEY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Three weeks into October, and three new productions
look like bona-fide hits. But unlike in years past, the early
winners are neither new Broadway musicals nor expensive revivals
but small-budget shows in unlikely off-Broadway venues.
</P>
<P>
   The best buzz is emanating from the MCC Theater, a 99-seat black
box on West 28th Street, where Margaret Edson's ``Wit'' has the
management scrambling to find seats for celebrities and for
producers dreaming of a run at a larger house.
</P>
<P>
   The play stars Kathleen Chalfant as a cancer-stricken literature
professor and was originally set for a four-week run. But the show,
co-produced by the Long Wharf Theater in New Haven, Conn., has been
extended twice on the strength of glowing reviews, and this week
was extended again, to Jan. 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're already getting people who are dying for tickets for
Christmas,'' said Bernard Telsey, an executive director. ``My
8-year-old son, Danny, and his friends were called in here on
Sunday to answer phones.''
</P>
<P>
   The extension may be part of a waiting game. Producers say they
are mulling over several offers to move the show, and visited the
Eugene O'Neill Theater on Wednesday, days after ``More to Love''
belly-flopped. Broadway insiders say other possibilities may arise
at the Helen Hayes, where ``Getting and Spending'' opens on Sunday,
and at the Booth, where Sandra Bernhard opens a limited run on Nov.
5.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, at the musty SoHo Playhouse, the producer Darren Lee
Cole was hiring extra staff to handle the crush of ticket requests
for ``Killer Joe,'' Tracy Letts' potboiler about a murder scheme,
which opened to strong reviews this week and was extended until
mid-December. ``It's going like gangbusters,'' Cole said, adding
that in three days the production sold more than $125,000 worth of
tickets for the 199-seat theater.
</P>
<P>
   Things are also good for ``The Mystery of Irma Vep,'' the
revived Charles Ludlam quick-change comedy at the 250-seat Westside
Theater. Total advance sales topped $350,000 this week, with
producers planning a run at least through January.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the heart of the Broadway audience coming,'' said
Richard Frankel, one of the producers. ``We knew we would get young
people, and knew we would get a gay audience, but people are
bringing their children. It's just fantastic.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, none of the shows have recouped their initial investment
yet. ``Wit,'' in fact, is just breaking even, because of a large
cast and small house. And while talk of a Broadway move may
continue, some feel the play's true home is off-Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the subject matter, I think it's going to be an uphill
battle,'' said Rocco Landesman, president of the Jujamycn Theaters,
``regardless of the quality of the work.''
</P>
<P>
   On the Dotted Line
</P>
<P>
   Actors Equity decided late this week to allow the Tony-winning
Irish actress Anna Manahan to remain in the cast of ``The Beauty
Queen of Leenane'' through March. (She plays Mag Folan, the
overbearing mother.) Under the play's current Equity agreement, the
whole Irish cast was to leave on Jan. 3 to make way for American
actors.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the producers, Steven M. Levy and Leonard Soloway, said
Thursday that the remaining three roles _ played by Marie Mullen,
Tom Murphy and Brian F. O'Byrne _ would be taken over by Americans
in 1999. Kate Burton is considered likely to take Miss Mullen's
role.
</P>
<P>
   And at the Public Theater, the role that had been filled by
Blythe Danner in Arthur Miller's ``Ride Down Mount Morgan'' has
been taken by Frances Conroy. Ms. Danner left the cast on Oct. 13
because of a family matter. Despite the quick replacement, the
change has delayed the play's opening until Nov. 3.
</P>
<P>
   A Personal Drama
</P>
<P>
   It was quite a weekend for the Chilean playwright Ariel Dorfman.
First, he unveiled two new plays: ``Mascara,'' which opened Friday
at the Julia Morgan Theater in Berkeley, Calif., and ``Who's Who,''
which began Sunday at the Frankfurter Schauspiel in Frankfurt,
Germany. Both were written with his son, Rodrigo, 31.
</P>
<P>
   Then on Saturday came news that the former Chilean dictator Gen.
Augusto Pinochet, who had forced Dorfman into exile in the 1970s,
had been arrested in London. ``I've been dreaming of this for 25
years,'' Dorfman said. ``He's under arrest and I'm free.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everything was ideal. ``Mascara'' was smeared by the San
Francisco critics. ``Pinochet tried to destroy me,'' Dorfman said.
``I'm not so worried about critics.''
</P>
<P>
   Making Light of `Medea'
</P>
<P>
   Zoe Wanamaker has a secret: ``Medea'' makes her giggle.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first line of the script is something like `Ay-ay-ay,'''
Ms. Wanamaker said recently from her home in London, sounding
perfectly bubbly. ``I think I would crack up.''
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, Ms. Wanamaker plays the unfortunate Electra, not the
murderous Medea, in the play coming to the Barrymore Theater next
month. But it is telling that Ms. Wanamaker sees humor, and
humanity, in classic roles that are usually approached with grim
faces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the deepest gesture in her is not violence, but
love,'' she said. ``The most important question is not why she must
avenge her father's death but what makes the grief so unbearable in
the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   The role is a departure from Ms. Wanamaker's last appearance on
Broadway, in Joe Orton's farce ``Loot'' in 1986. That performance
resulted in a Tony nomination for her, as did her turn in 1981 in
``Piaf.''
</P>
<P>
   What does she make of her chances this time around?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, I don't know,'' she said. ``Nominations are nice, but
they're really just icing on the cake.''
</P>
<P>
   Rigg in `Phedre'
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Medea, it looks as if Diana Rigg is headed to New
York in ``Phedre,'' from London's Almeida Theater. A deal is nearly
complete to bring the show, along with another Racine play,
``Britannicus,'' to the Brooklyn Academy of Music for a two-week
run in January. Both are directed by Jonathan Kent, who directed
Ms. Rigg in ``Medea'' on Broadway in 1994.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
