A2302 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-USC-LADN     10-22 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUGH PART OF USC'S SEASON BEGINS 
</HEADLINE>
  &HT;     (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &LR;  LOS ANGELES _ Southern California wide receiver R. Jay Soward
thought for a minute, trying to remember the last time the Trojans
played for stakes as high as this week's game with Oregon.
<P>
   It didn't take long to come up with an answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't been in a game like this before. I've never been a
contender for anything since I've been at USC,'' Soward said. ``We
haven't been in a big game.''
</P>
<P>
   For all but a handful of seniors who were members of USC's 1996
Rose Bowl championship team, this week's game is a new experience:
An important game that has bowl implicatons.
</P>
<P>
   There have been big games against Notre Dame and UCLA, but
nothing the past few years compares to this week's contest in
Eugene. The Trojans (5-2, 3-1) and the 12th-ranked Ducks (5-1, 2-1)
are basically playing a Rose Bowl elimination game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be interesting to see how we respond,'' Soward
said. ``I know the game means a lot more. We need a big win.''
</P>
<P>
   The loser can forget about a trip to Pasadena, while the winner
at least keeps its hopes alive. Each team's bowl possibilities
could also hinge on this contest.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans have Washington, Stanford, UCLA and Notre Dame left
on the schedule after Oregon. Every team but Stanford has a winning
record, so a loss to the Ducks could be disastrous.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rest of the season is make it or break it,'' linebacker
David Gibson said. ``I had gone into this thinking we would beat
Cal and Washington State. We're on our heels. We're in a bind. We
can still go to a bowl game if we lose, but our goal is not to just
go to a bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   As much as the Trojans would enjoy a trip to the Rose Bowl, it's
probably more realistic to say they need to win at least two of
their final five games to become eligible for a bowl.
</P>
<P>
   A small accomplishment? Not when you consider USC hasn't played
in a bowl in three years.
</P>
<P>
   It might be hard for the players to focus on that, however, when
they consider how close they are to being undefeated in the
Pacific-10 Conference.
</P>
<P>
   If the Trojans had not blown a 21-point lead against Cal two
weeks ago, this week's game would not be quite as crucial. Even as
USC focuses on Oregon, it's still difficult not to look back and
ponder that loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely on my mind still,'' linebacker Chris Claiborne
said. ``I just take it to each game with me.''
</P>
<P>
   As disappointing as the Cal game turned out for the Trojans,
they are still grasping with a new role: being Pac-10 contenders in
late October. The past two seasons, the Trojans have been busier
figuring out what went wrong with the first part of the season,
content to try and salvage some respect while most attention
focused on the status of the head coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been crazy the past couple years,'' Soward said. ``This
is a great opportunity for the football team. We're not pointing
fingers this year. The only thing going on is a slight quarterback
controversy.'
</P>
<P>
   By winning five of their first seven games, USC's on-field
performance finally remains the No. 1 priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting,'' Gibson said. ``It hasn't been like this since
high school where we were in a playoff-type situation and you can
make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Even chronic problem issues of the recent past like team
leadership have been put aside.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're starting to become a team and gain an identity,''
Claiborne said. ``This is the first year we've come together and
had a good record. When you win, all the complaints go away.''
</P>
<P>
   But winning in Eugene remains a formidable task. USC hasn't
exactly demonstrated the ability to win conference road games,
going 3-5 the previous two seasons. Last week's 42-14 victory at
Washington State was a start, although the Cougars are 0-2 at home
against Pac-10 foes.
</P>
<P>
   A far bigger task, with major ramifications, awaits Saturday
against the Ducks. At least the Trojans are not lacking confidence
_ something that couldn't be said the past two seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can beat this team,'' receiver Mike Bastianelli said.
``They're not supermen. Is this a make or break game? Yeah.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
