<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    MICROSOFT: NETSCAPE SET US UP FOR ANTITRUST CHARGE
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In 1995, the young designer of the first browsing
tool for the World Wide Web, tried to snare Microsoft Corp. in an
antitrust trap, the lead lawyer for the software giant charged in
federal court Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft said that when Marc Andreessen, co-founder of Netscape
Communications Corp., was questioned about why he had taken such
detailed notes on his laptop of a June 21, 1995, Silicon Valley
meeting between key Netscape and Microsoft executives, he replied:
``I thought it might be a topic of discussion with the U.S.
government on antitrust issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Andreessen made the comment in a deposition taken in August 1997
by the Texas attorney general's office in Austin. Twenty states
(but not Texas) have joined the Justice Department in alleging that
Microsoft has abused its Windows monopoly to squash Netscape after
the browser maker spurned an offer to divide the market,
purportedly made at the June 21 meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the courtroom, a Netscape lawyer minimized Andreessen's
comments. ``He has this incredibly sarcastic temperament,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Andreessen's served as Netscape's 23-year-old chief
technology officer. His holdings in the Netscape later came to be
worth about $80 million, the fruits of his having led a team that
created Mosaic, the first graphical tool to surf the Internet,
while still a student at the University of Illinois.
</P>
<P>
   On the fourth day of the landmark antitrust trial, James
Barksdale, who was recruited in January 1995 to run Netscape while
the fledgling firm suffered from a deep cash crunch, described
Microsoft's alleged market-splitting bid.
</P>
<P>
   With his soft Southern voice rising in anger, Barksdale said
when ``the manufacturer of an operating system that controls 90
percent-plus of the world's (personal computer) platforms pulls the
browser into the operating system, (it) has stepped across the
line.''
</P>
<P>
   Under cross-examination, Barksdale testified that a Microsoft
official ``proposed that a line be drawn between the area'' where
Netscape would compete against Microsoft, turning the potentially
lucrative Windows 95 market entirely over to Microsoft. In return,
Barksdale said, cash-laden Microsoft offered to make an investment
in Netscape and take a seat on its board.
</P>
<P>
   During a day of tough questioning by John Warden, Microsoft's
lead lawyer in the case, Barksdale said the bid prompted him to
ask, ``where is this line going to end, and what keeps the line
from moving?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Is this anything more than just a difference of opinion going
on between you and Microsoft about where the line is?'' Warden
wanted to know.
</P>
<P>
   ``You were going to put the browser in your (new Windows 95)
operating system and give it away for free on all (computing)
platforms,'' he replied. ``In the June meeting, that's the first I
knew about that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Here we are a little company and you're a big company with
unlimited resources. You're going to move the line any time you
want against our economic interests,'' Barksdale said.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft countered Barksdale's comments about monopoly
leveraging by introducing Netscape's own sales figures. They showed
that use of Netscape Navigator Web browser rose by more than 60
percent during a year-long period that government antitrust
investigators say Microsoft was engaged in a systematic campaign to
crush its Internet market rival.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only fair conclusion that can be reached is that Marc
Andreessen invented or imagined a proposal to divide markets and
that you and your company have signed on to this invention or
imaginary concoction in order to assist the Justice Department in
the prosecution of this lawsuit,'' Warden thundered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a witness to it, and you weren't,'' Barksdale shot back.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
