<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-SETTLERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JEWISH SETTLERS FEEL BETRAYED BY PEACE EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Jewish settlers, some with prayer shawls over their
shoulders and some with machine guns, took to the streets Thursday
for a second day of protests against a peace deal being hammered
out by Israeli and Palestinian leaders in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   As the likelihood of a deal grew, the settlers' protests
intensified. They gathered for early morning prayer vigils, blocked
roads that could soon come under Palestinian control, and waved
Israeli flags. At least five were arrested in confrontations with
police.
</P>
<P>
   For these ultranationalist settlers, the possible peace deal is
a betrayal of the promises that led them to vote for Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu over Simon Peres, who helped negotiate
the 1993 Oslo Accords.
</P>
<P>
   They pray for divine intervention to stop the deal. If that
fails, they vow to topple Netanyahu's fragile coalition through a
vote of no-confidence in the Knesset, the Israeli parliament. And
they appear to have the votes to do it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is criminal treachery,'' said Elyakim Haetzni, a leader of
the settler community in Kiryat Arba who had demonstrated along the
road in Bet El Thursday. ``A Jewish leader, one we voted for, is
signing over Jewish land to the enemy. It is a betrayal to those
who voted for him.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 160,000 Israelis live in an archipelago of 144 Jewish
settlements scattered among the 1.5 million Palestinians in the
West Bank, which was captured by Israel from Jordan in the 1967 Six
Day War. They feel threatened by the current compromise, which
calls for a 13 percent further Israeli troop withdrawal from the
West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   They believe they are biblically ordained to control the land of
Judea and Samaria, as they refer to the West Bank. And they fear
for their lives if the Palestinians take control of the areas along
the roads they use every day to go to and from Jerusalem and Tel
Aviv.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not only 13 percent,'' added Haetzni. ``This is the
end of the land of Israel, the severing of our link to the promise
land. We wil pay for this with our blood if we do not stop it. We
will punish Netanyahu. He will die a political death.''
</P>
<P>
   Their words and their banners can be apocalyptic. Some of the
violent rhetoric seems chilling three years after Prime Minister
Yitzhak Rabin was gunned down by Yigal Amir, a right-wing extremist
with deep ties to the settler movement.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Kleiner, a hard-line settler, warned Netanyahu in the
Israeli newspaper Ma'ariv, ``We have a sword to your throat, and
when I am talking about a sword I am not merely philosophizing. ...
You can stop this.''
</P>
<P>
   But as some observers point out the protests are subdued
compared to the large crowds and deeper vitriol found in similar
demonstrations from 1994 through 1996, when Rabin's government
began the initial troop withdrawls from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts believe that Netanyahu has marginalized the
ultra-nationalist movement by aligning himself with more
established members of the right, such as former general Ariel
Sharon, his new foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
   Take Oren Amit, a 22-year-old resident of the Dolev settlement
in the West Bank. He feels ``betrayed'' by Netanyahu's efforts in
Maryland, but he also realizes there is no real political
alternative to him. ``The truth is we don't know what other choices
we have,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Herb Keinon, a Jerusalem Post reporter who covers the
settlements, said: ``Rabin slapped the settlers. Netanyahu has
stroked them. He permitted construction in the settlements, brought
them into the inner political circle. So the streets are relatively
quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardliners have, to some extent, been coopted despite
their strong words,'' he added. ``There is no way for them to
muster real anger against an agreement made by Netanyahu and
Sharon. Now is Netanyahu just politically smart or truly empathetic
to the settlers' cause? I think it is both.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
