<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAVENLY HERB ON MISSION STREET
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: This story also moved in the ``a'' national news file)  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle
<TEXT>
<P>
   A three-man team from Burning Alive Designs signed, sealed and
pronounced complete their 20-by-70-foot homage to the late
columnist  &UR; Herb Caen &LR;  on Columbus Day. Their new mural, on the side
of Big O Tires on Mission between Sixth and Seventh s &LR; treets,
pictures Caen's face beaming down at a San Francisco skyline as
angels flutter nearby. The line ``San Francisco is heaven on
earth'' is a sentiment that was often expressed by Caen.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Alex Eremian &LR; , &UR; Sandro Tchikovani  &LR; and  &UR; Richard Richey &LR; , who
worked on the mural for six weeks, were born and raised in San
Francisco. ``I read Caen's column a lot,'' said Eremian. ``He's a
San Francisco icon. ... We wanted to do something that is a
celebration of our home town.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HOT ITEMS FROM THE RENAISSANCE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   _ At a Manhattan luncheon for the debut of the magazine Madison,
guests were buzzing about the magazine's logo, in a font that was
developed from the handwriting of  &UR; Leonardo &LR; .  &UR; Baird &LR; 
 &UR; Jones &LR; , who was among them, said the buzz fizzed out when the
guests realized it was  &UR; da Vinci &LR;  and not  &UR; DiCaprio &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   _  &UR; Richard Kibsgaard &LR;  notes that the two 1521 drawings by
 &UR; Albrecht Durer &LR;  that, according to the PBS series ``Africans in
America,'' depict the Johnsons (a free black planter and his wife)
were made long before the Johnsons were born. ``This may set a
record for creative history on PBS,'' says Kibsgaard.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; _ Henry Kissinger  &LR; and  &UR; Jim Carrey  &LR; dined with  &UR; Milos Forman &LR; 
and others at Spago recently, reports People. Kissinger ``has
always admired Carrey's work,'' a spokeswoman told the magazine.
</P>
<P>
   _ Aspirations: &UR; Julia Roberts  &LR; told W she's hoping to play
 &UR; Lucille Ball &LR;  in a movie ``loosely based'' on the life of the
comedian. And  &UR; Christopher Darden &LR; , whose work as a prosecutor
failed to convict  &UR; O.J. Simpson &LR; , tried out for a part in a sitcom
this week, reports Variety.
</P>
<P>
   _ Superintendent of Schools  &UR; Bill Rojas &LR;  won a night at the San
Francisco Marriott hotel in a silent auction, and sent it to
Supervisor  &UR; Tom Ammiano &LR;  with a note about using it to commemorate
an important moment in his life. The memorable event was Ammiano's
arrest on October 1 while picketing the Marriott with hotel
workers. He says he'll use the coupon after labor issues are
settled.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WHO SAID WHAT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw him for lunch. I said to the waitress, `What's your
name?' and she said `Monica,' so that took care of the first
half-hour of the lunch. Johnny and I don't see each other as much,
but when we see each other, we're right back where we were.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Ed McMahon telling the New York Observer about his
relationship with Johnny Carson nowadays. McMahon's new book is
``For Laughing Out Loud: My Life and Good Times.''
</P>
