The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Friday, Oct. 23. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
KPTY-RADIO (Phoenix) - A Phoenix area radio station, struggling in
the ratings, turns to drugs and sex as a way of building an
audience. By MICHAEL CLANCY. Story will move in the ``E''
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
PORK-ARIZONA (Washington) - Looking for example of egregious
Arizona pork in the new federal budget. By ADRIANNE FLYNN and JEFF
BARKER. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
HOMELESS-KIDS-ART (Phoenix) - Three nights a week, Steven Serrano
and Linda Silva go out in a white van and drive slowly through the
worst areas in Phoenix and Tempe, looking for young homeless kids.
Invisible by day, the teenagers emerge from the dark shadows of the
street with their hands outstretched when they see the van. Every
kid out here has a different story, but there are similar plot
lines. The Children's Action Alliance, a nonprofit advocacy agency,
estimated in 1990 that there were 5,000 runaway and homeless youth
in Arizona. Now, estimates run as high as 10,000. With PHOTO. By
KARINA BLAND. Story moved in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
GAGNON-COMIC (Phoenix) - More than 16,000 tickets to Celine Dion's
concert went on sale on a Sunday back in April. In only two days,
all were sold. You have to figure that at some point, about 15,999
of those buyers were looking at their tickets and wondering, ``Who
the hell is Andre-Philippe Gagnon?'' With CELINE DION-MUSIC. By
RANDY CORDOVA. Story moved in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CELINE DION-MUSIC (Phoenix) - The gushing tone was undeniable.
``Celine Dion is just incredible,'' the woman on the phone said.
``She is such a diva.'' It made me pause. Celine Dion is a lot of
things. Wildly successful, sure. Canadian, of course. Multilingual,
oui. But a diva? I think not. With GAGNON-COMIC. By RANDY CORDOVA.
Story moved in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CONNIE FRANICIS-MUSIC (Undated) - Rock-and-roll stardom, drug
addiction, mental illness, violent crime _ it was just a matter of
time before someone made a documentary about Connie Francis.
Luckily, the Arts and Entertainment channel took up the task of
telling the singer's story, so ``Connie Francis: America's
Sweetheart of Song'' manages to be revealing without being too
sordid. Lord knows how the E! channel would have handled it. By
RANDY CORDOVA. Story moved in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
HERBS-FOOD (Undated) - Forty years ago, Anne Fischer was served
herb butter on her bread in a restaurant. ``I thought, `My
goodness, what is that stuff, and how do I find out about it?' ''
Fischer said. She went to the library and checked out a book. A few
decades and a lot of herbs later, Fischer is the author of the
Arizona Herb Association's ``The Low Desert Herb Gardening
Handbook,'' which focuses on planting, growing and harvesting herbs
in Arizona. She has learned a lot about cooking with herbs along
the way. With PHOTO and HERBS-HEALTH. By JUDY WALKER. Story moved
in the ``F'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
HERBS-HEALTH (Undated) - Doctors still grimace at the mention of
them. However, for the ever-increasing number of people who are
disillusioned with synthetic medicines and their often-harsh side
effects, herbal remedies have become more mainstream as the 20th
century comes to a close. With HERBS-FOOD. By THOMAS ROPP. Story
moved in the ``L'' catgory. &QL; 
 &QL; 
NOTARO-COLUMN (Undated) - It wasn't the first sneeze that scared
me. When I heard my husband sneeze a third, fourth and fifth time
from the living room, I still had no fear. I wasn't scared until my
husband woke up the next morning and shook me awake. ``Honey, I
don't feel so good,'' he squeaked out. ``My throat feels
scratchy.'' By LAURI NOTARO. Story moved in the ``L'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
PLEASANT-MOVIE (Undated) - If average Americans spend a quarter of
their lives watching TV, why not go all the way and live inside a
TV world? They do in ``Pleasantville,'' a mostly comic fantasy that
takes ``The Truman Show'' idea and turns it inside out. Unhappily,
writer/director Gary Ross pushes his metaphor too far, and the film
loses its sense of fun and becomes preachy. 3 stars. By BOB
FENSTER. Story moved in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
APT PUPIL-MOVIE (Undated) - The attempt to bring Stephen King's
novella about the deadly friendship between a former Nazi war
criminal and a white-bread teen to the screen. It's had as many
headaches as it has camera shots. 3 stars. By BOB FENSTER. Story
moved in the ``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
ORGAZMO-MOVIE (Undated) - When a movie is rated NC-17, it usually
means that anyone younger than 17 can't get into the theater. In
the case of ``Orgazmo,'' it should mean that anyone with an IQ over
17 doesn't qualify. 1 star. By BOB FENSTER. Story moved in the
``E'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
AUTO-REVIEW (Undated) - And now, ``A Tale of Two Grand Ams'': ``It
was the best of cars, it was the worst of cars.'' No kidding. Truth
be told, the two Grand Ams in question _ the sportier GT model and
the standard-issue SE _ were like Cain and Abel, Yin and Yang. One
that's hot, one that's not. By BOB GOLFEN. EMBARGOED FOR SATURDAY,
OCT. 24. &QL; 
 &QL;
