<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOSTON TRIES TO GET BACK TO BASICS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Coach Pat Burns put his players through a
grueling 75-minute skate Thursday with the objective of getting
back to basics.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins have lost two games in a row to superior teams _ the
Phoenix Coyotes and the Anaheim Mighty Ducks _ and in both, they
looked as if they had shown up for a knife fight armed only with a
wooden spoon.
</P>
<P>
   They're missing two-thirds of their top defensive line _ Tim
Taylor is sidelined with an ankle injury and Rob DiMaio is serving
a two-game suspension for an elbowing incident in Phoenix. Also
missing are forward Anson Carter, who signed with the Utah
Grizzlies of the IHL, and defenseman Kyle McLaren, who is about to
sign with an IHL team.
</P>
<P>
   Already thin in terms of talent, the Bruins had their weaknesses
glaringly exposed in their last two games.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got lucky with Paul Kariya whacking the puck out of the
air,'' said Burns, referring to a Ducks power-play goal in the
second period of Wednesday's 3-0 loss when Kariya showed amazing
hand-eye coordination to bunt the puck past goalie Byron Dafoe.
``But that first goal (by Jim McKenzie late in the first period)
was criminal. It was a sin. You've got a giveaway from a
defenseman, you've got a winger who doesn't get the puck on the
boards, you've got another defenseman standing in front of the net
looking for the puck ... that's probably the only goal McKenzie's
going to score. That's criminal. It should never happen. It
shouldn't happen against us, that's for sure.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins are now 2-3-0 on the trip, which wraps up in New
Jersey tomorrow night. The power play has been abysmal the last two
games (0 for 11), a big reason the team hasn't generated any
offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're being pressured and we're not reacting very good yet,''
said Ray Bourque. ``The passes we are making, we don't have that
much time and it takes one good pass to kind of settle everything
down. Sometimes we're just dishing off one problem to the other
guy. He's being checked and doesn't have much time. We've got to
spread it out and find the right guy to settle it down and get them
running around instead of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Burns said his players just haven't worked hard enough during
the man advantage to earn a goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're passing it around, but when we do get a shot from the
point, there's nobody there,'' the coach said. ``We want an easy
power play. We don't want a hard power play. We have to pay the
price a little bit more. We didn't pass the puck well, that's for
sure. When we did make a pass, we didn't help anybody out. We let
everybody go by themselves. You have to come over and support a
little more and help each other out. When you've got an opportunity
to shoot the puck, you've got to shoot it. You can't turn away from
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Club morale has been down the last couple of days. Early in the
last two games, the Bruins' opponents have been all over them,
overwhelming them and forcing them to play catch-up. They can't be
successful that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``There weren't a whole lot of positive things to look at,''
said Burns of the effort against the Ducks. ``We came out and
played hard in the third period, but ... there weren't a whole lot
of positive things. I'm disappointed about the game. We have to go
back to the way we win hockey games. We're looking for an easy way
to win. There's no easy way. You've got to work and work hard for
60 minutes. We're not good enough to go out and think we're going
to win because we won last year. It doesn't make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Bourque said it hasn't helped that so many people are missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Robbie DiMaio and Tim Taylor are a couple of big pieces to the
team and they're not here right now,'' he said. ``To go along with
Kyle and A.C., that's four guys who aren't there for us. That
certainly has something to do with it, but we could play a lot
better. We've got to go out and play harder. The effort is there,
but we're not playing very disciplined or doing the things we need
to do to win. Look at the amount of shots we had (an average of
just 20 over the last two games). We're not creating all that
much.''
</P>
</TEXT>
