<P>
   CHEFS-CAREER (Undated) _ Food preparation is one of the fastest
growing occupations in America, but making it as a chef is
incredibly tough slogging. The training is expensive, the return on
investment slow in coming, the work tedious and the competition
cutthroat. We go behind the scenes at Le Cirque 2000 to see how
ambitious cooks get ahead. By Amanda Hesser.
</P>
<P>
   With Graphic.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-UTILITIES (Undated) _ Californians will vote next month on
whether to halt one of the nation's most aggressive moves toward
utility deregulation. The campaign pits underfunded consumer groups
against every imaginable business group, and labor as well. The
politics reflect the economic realities of utility deregulation:
Unlike the advent of long-distance telephone competition, there is
little savings for the average consumer in the deregulation of gas
and electric power. Almost all the benefits go to industry. It's
not just in California where residents are beginning to wake up to
this reality. Across the country, there are signs that utility
deregulation is being second-guessed. By Agis Salpukas.
</P>
