<P>
   For Friday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-TALKS (Washington) _ President Clinton moves in to
jump-start the Middle East peace talks between the Israelis and
Palestinians. Negotiators report some progress on territorial and
security issues, but other points remain to be worked out. By NANCY
MATHIS.
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-STATES (Washington) _ The Institute for Women's Policy
Research, a nonpartisan think tank, ranks the 10 best and 10 worst
states for women based on factors including wages, reproductive
rights, health insurance coverage and the number of females in
business and elected office. By JUDY HOLLAND. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   WILSON-2000 (Washington) _ California Gov. Pete Wilson, who will
leave office in January, tells reporters he will run again for
president in 2000 ``if the money is there.'' Wilson, a Republican,
says he would need at least $15 million. He also says gay rights
advocate James Hormel ``would not be the best choice'' for the post
of U.S. ambassador to Luxembourg. By ERIC ROSENBERG. (Already
filed.)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NUKE-DUMP (Austin, Texas) _ In a politically charged case that
has rallied Mexican officials and environmental protesters, a state
regulatory board denies a license to a storage site for hazardous
trash near the Mexican border. The site at Sierra Blanca would have
stored low-level radioactive waste. By JOHN GONZALEZ.
</P>
<P>
   ELECTION-HMOs (Charlotte, N.C.) _ Addressing officials this
week, John Edwards, the Democrat challenging incumbent Sen. Lauch
Faircloth, ticked off the critical issues he believed faced the
nation. No one asked him about his plan to give people more choice
of doctors in their managed care plans. Concerns over HMOs do not
appear to be electrifying voters this election, contrary to the
predictions of many Democrats who had hoped to make it an issue. By
BENNETT ROTH. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   BALLOT-LAWSUIT (San Francisco) _ Thousands of Chinese-speaking
voters who received ballots for the November election that did not
list the Chinese names of seven San Francisco candidates will have
a chance to recast their ballots under a compromise ordered by a
Superior Court judge. By DIANA WALSH. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   TX-FLOODS-CUERO (Cuero, Texas) _ Half of this South Texas town
of 6,000 people is under water and few, if any, have flood
insurance. On Wednesday, the community was cut off by land with
every road leading into town under water. By ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA.
</P>
<P>
   DEAD-PROTESTER (San Francisco) _ The mother of David Chain, a
Texas native killed while protesting logging on California
timberland, plans to hold a news conference here to question the
objectivity of the police investigation into her son's death. By
BILL DAWSON.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-PRESSURE (Jerusalem) _ Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu faced a tough task going into peace talks with the
Palestinians at a rural Maryland conference center: He was under
pressure from the United States to pursue the peace process begun
by his predecessors, yet not appear to loosen his tough stance. A
look at what he faces when he returns home. By DEBORAH HORAN.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ American journalists often take
freedom of the press for granted. But in many foreign countries
journalists literally put their lives on the line to get the news;
I review some horror stories from female journalists who have
demonstrated true grit. By MARIANNE MEANS. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SERIES-YANKEES (San Diego) _ Forget the 1927 Yankees with their
infamous Murderer's Row. Disregard the M&AMP;M Boys of the `61 Yankees.
The Big Red Machine doesn't even come close. The record speaks for
itself. This year's New York Yankees team ranks as the greatest
team in the history of baseball. By JOSEPH DUARTE.
</P>
<P>
   FBN-BRONCOS (Denver) _ Suddenly, the Super Bowl champion Denver
Broncos have emerged as the latest team to beat in the NFL. Proving
last year's world championship was no one-year wonder, the Broncos
have stormed out to a 6-0 start this season in impressive fashion.
But they face one of their toughest challenges of the season this
weekend when they host the Jacksonville Jaguars in the NFL's
featured game of the Week. By JOHN McCLAIN.
</P>
<P>
   For Sunday:
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-TEACHERS (Washington) _ President Clinton and
congressional Democrats hoped to create an election year
vote-getter with their new federal program to pay for 100,000
teachers to help cut the size of elementary school classes. But if
voters take a closer look, they will see that the program has
funding for only three months and will cut class size in poor city
neighborhoods rather than the suburbs. By STEWART M. POWELL.
(Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   PROSTATE-RESEARCH (Washington) _ Federal research spending on
prostate cancer will top $182 million in the new fiscal year, $28
million more than last year but significantly less than advocates
sought. By ERIC ROSENBERG. (Already filed.)
</P>
<P>
   GLOBAL-WARMING (Washington) _ Diplomats from the United States
and 159 other countries are preparing for a new round of talks next
month in Buenos Aires on a global warming accord. But prospects are
bleak for U.S. Senate acceptance of the pact, and failure to win
ratification is likely to scuttle it. By MARK HELM. (Already
filed.)
</P>
</TEXT>
