<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 19:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2345 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-     10-22 1148
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS MANAGE TO LAND DAVEY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   At least I can sleep better now knowing that Kevin Malone, whose
frantic high-profile search for a manager was perhaps unprecedented
in baseball history for sheer high camp, finally has found someone
to manage the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   The new Dodger GM had scoured the planet looking for the right
person to revitalize the team, consulting with everyone except
Monica Lewinsky.
</P>
<P>
   Why, he even flew down to the Dominican Republic to beg Felipe
Alou to accept his seven-figure offerings, perhaps even
island-hopping over to Cuba to see if that venerable baseball
aficionado, Fidel Castro, was available to impart his vast
knowledge to the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   Natch, after all his well-publicized tomfoolery, Mr. Malone was
able to only come up with the well-traveled Davey Johnson, whose
success in previous managerial jobs with the New York Mets and
Cincinnati Reds and Baltimore Orioles was exceeded only by his
inability to get along with the management of those teams.
</P>
<P>
   In his first major move with the Dodgers, Malone has at least
showed the courage to hire someone unafraid to express his feelings
to those who sign his paychecks.
</P>
<P>
   There is no doubt Davey Johnson is a top-flight manager with a
strong personality who figures to inject some much-needed fire into
an underachieving Dodger team that desperately needs it.
</P>
<P>
   But one of my most hallowed theories in life is that people
don't change.
</P>
<P>
   How long will it be before Davey Johnson sasses Kevin Malone, a
guy whose hysterically funny handling of the Dodger managerial
search would give one the impression that he's just the type of
fellow that Davey Johnson will wind up sassing? ...
</P>
<P>
   I've consulted the Las Vegas bookmakers, and the under/overs on
Davey Johnson's stay in Los Angeles is a mere two years. I'm taking
the unders. ...
</P>
<P>
   I have nothing against Davey Johnson, but I'd have preferred to
see Kevin Kennedy, a San Fernando Valley native who lives in
Tarzana, get the job. I'm sure Kennedy's past ties to the Dodger
organizaHSg'5,'tion went against him with Malone, who's instituted
a wide-spread internal purge and brought in his own replacements.
...
</P>
<P>
   I'm sure Bobby Bonilla is turning joyful somersaults at the
thought of being managed again by Davey Johnson, as he was in
Baltimore. To say the two men didn't get along is like saying Tommy
Lasorda's favorite sports columnist is me. ...
</P>
<P>
   Incidentally, I spotted Lasorda at Qualcomm Stadium before Game
3 of the World Series, and waved to him. He looked at me, and
turned his back.
</P>
<P>
   Why did Lasorda wind up sitting in box seats down the
right-field line while Malone and Charley McCarthy oops, I mean Bob
Graziano were ensconced in better seats between the bases behind
the Padres' dugout? ...
</P>
<P>
   Well, David Wells' indeed would never make it as a clairvoyant.
He predicted before the series the Yankees would win it in five
games. ...
</P>
<P>
   Only those who live in the past and, unfortunately, there are
too many people who do would demean these New York Yankees, who
statistically wound up having the greatest season in baseball
history.
</P>
<P>
   Artistically, they rank with any team that has ever played their
sport. ...
</P>
<P>
   Is there a luckier man in baseball than Joe Torre? He had been
fired from three previous managerial jobs when George Steinbrenner
tabbed him to take over the Yankees in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Torre figured to last a season or two before being detached by
the hair-triggered Steinbrenner, but darned if he hasn't won two
world titles during his bright Yankee incumbency. ...
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Bochy came under severe criticism for moves that
constantly backfired during the World Series, but the Padres didn't
blow four straight because of Bochy. Moves tend to backfire when
you're managing a team not nearly as good as the one you're facing.
...
</P>
<P>
   If the Yankees remain intact, doubtful because Steinbrenner
reportedly won't meet Scott Boras' absurd $15 million a year salary
demand for soon-to-be free agent center fielder Bernie Williams,
they'll probably return to the Fall Classic next October.
</P>
<P>
   They might, anyway, but the team won't have the same chemistry
without Williams, a well-liked figure in the Yankee clubhouse. ...
</P>
<P>
   I think those pundits saying the Yankees don't have a future
Hall of Fame player are wrong. Twenty-four-year-old Derek Jeter,
who covers as much ground as any shortstop in the major leagues and
is a dangerous hitter, will one day make it if he continues to play
as exceptionally as he has in his first three seasons in the big
leagues. ...
</P>
<P>
   The Padres might have sagged, but their redoubtable right
fielder, Tony Gwynn, certainly didn't. The 1977 Poly High graduate
wound up batting .500, and also played exceptionally in the field.
...
</P>
<P>
   San Diego is a wonderful metropolitan area, but its residents
and some members of its media still retain a small-town
provincialism. ...
</P>
<P>
   I thought my old friend Charlie Steiner and Kevin Kennedy did
exceptional work during the playoffs on ESPN radio. ...
</P>
<P>
   The NBA is doing what I've long been advocating getting rid of
its tiresome, tedious yawn of a regular season. The playoffs are
the only time anyone pays serious attention to the NBA, anyway. I
just wonder how long all those millionaire NBA players will remain
tolerant of their union leadership's tough negotiating stance with
the owners when the reality sets in that they're blowing hundreds
of thousands of dollars that never will be retrieved.
</P>
<P>
   Still, if the players stay firm, I have a feeling the owners
eventually will lift the lockout because they stand to lose far
more money than do any of the players. ...
</P>
<P>
   I don't sympathize with either side in this labor dispute. To
me, it's a silly pillow fight among multi-millionaires, although
the players shouldn't give in to the owners' demands to institute a
hard salary cap. ...
</P>
<P>
   Long Beach tough guy cop and bon vivant bachelor Two-Fisted Ted
Husley informs me celebrity restaurateur Phil Trani is donating
$4,000, the proceeds from his annual golf tournament, to the Police
Athletic League. ...
</P>
<P>
   What a heart of gold Magic Johnson has in wanting to play a
pivotal role in Mike Tyson's career. I wonder if he'd show such
interest if Tyson wasn't boxing's greatest gate attraction? ...
</P>
<P>
   I never realized how dramatically my life would change with
Tommy Lasorda no longer a part of it. I've not only lost a close
friend for my Benedict Arnold betrayals but also my chief culinary
adviser, a bitter piece of linguini to swallow.
</P>
<P>
   I wonder if ol' Tommy would forgive me for my journalistic sins
of printing those unflattering anti-Lasorda quotes from Bill
Russell if I wrote a fable that told of the great affection Russell
has for his former manager. ...
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
