<SLUG> BC-NUKE-DUMP-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS REJECTS PLAN TO BUILD NUCLEAR WASTE DUMP IN SIERRA BLANCA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN _ To the glee of environmentalists from West Texas and
Mexico, state officials on Thursday delivered a fatal blow to the
17-year-old plan to build a radioactive waste dump amid the
tumbleweeds and sagebrush near Sierra Blanca.
</P>
<P>
   Citing a lack of information about whether the Hudspeth County
site could withstand an earthquake, along with unanswered questions
about the project's socioeconomic impact, the Texas Natural
Resource Conservation Commission unanimously rejected the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Despite legal avenues to keep the Sierra Blanca option alive,
Gov. George W. Bush immediately pronounced it dead. And while
advocates have never called it a ``dump,'' Bush issued a terse
statement referring to it as just that.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state's environmental officials have determined the site
is not safe. Therefore, the dump will not be built at Sierra
Blanca, period,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   With a portrait of Bush looking over their shoulders, the
three-member commission, all Bush appointees, turned down a license
application from a state agency with a legislative mandate to find
a place to store low-level radioactive waste. The material would
come from nuclear power plants in Texas, Maine and Vermont, as well
as contaminated items from Texas businesses, universities and
research facilities.
</P>
<P>
   The quest began in 1981, long before the term ``environmental
racism'' was part of the legislative jargon. The Sierra Blanca
debate has included allegations that the site was picked because
its largely Hispanic population was relatively powerless to stop
it. The proposed site, less than 20 miles from the Rio Grande, also
has caused an outpouring of diplomatic and informal protests from
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Despite predictions that the commission vote will force the
state Legislature to study other sites in 1999, the agency seeking
the license, the Texas Low-Level Radioactive Waste Disposal
Authority, said it will try to keep the Sierra Blanca option
viable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed,'' said authority director Rick Jacobi, who
said he would seek a rehearing. But the unanimous vote and Bush's
reaction were being construed as the kiss of death for the
long-embattled proposal.
</P>
<P>
   A coalition of utilities, businesses, research institutions and
other generators of radioactive waste, including Houston Lighting &AMP;
Power and Texas Utilities, said it isn't abandoning efforts to help
the state find an economic disposal site in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is still too early to assess the full ramifications of the
decision, but we will continue to support the authority in its
efforts to receive a license at an appropriate site,'' said Edward
Selig, who heads up the coalition.
</P>
<P>
   Until then, Texas' low-level waste will remain at more than 600
temporary storage locations, including several in Harris County,
Selig said.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Addington of Sierra Blanca, a leader of the opposition, was
pleased by the decision but reluctant to declare the battle won.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still politics. If it had been politically feasible for
the commissioners to approve this site, they would have done it,''
he said. A year ago, he was calling approval ``a done deal.''
</P>
<P>
   He and other opponents grew more pessimistic in the summer when
Congress approved a pact allowing Maine and Vermont to ship
contaminated materials from decommissioned nuclear power plants to
Texas, if a site were were approved.
</P>
<P>
   With the interstate pact still valid, Addington predicted his
worry will soon be someone else's.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem of what to do with this waste could be forced on
somebody else, putting their natural resources at risk. The
struggle must go on, and until I die, I will do what I can to stop
this insane, kitty litter-box technique of dealing with radioactive
waste,'' Addington said.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican congressman Carlos Camacho of Chihuahua, the state lying
across the Rio Grande from Hudspeth County, rejoiced at the
``unbelievable'' outcome, and theorized that a series of Mexican
diplomatic protests, hunger strikes, international bridge
blockades, picketing and demonstrations must have had an impact on
the decision-makers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if they never manage to say it, it was in their minds,''
Camacho said.
</P>
<P>
   ``One guy said it would be too expensive to look for another
place, but it would be more expensive to look at the same place,''
Camacho said.
</P>
<P>
   In their ruling, TNRCC Chairman Barry McBee of Austin and
Commissioners R.B. ``Ralph'' Marquez of Texas City and John M.
Baker Jr. of Temple adopted the negative finding of a panel of two
administrative law judges. The judges spent months analyzing
scientific, socioeconomic and other analyses of the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   McBee, calling it a ``heart-wrenching decision,'' said the vote
was made harder by the fact that Hudspeth County is clamoring for
economic development. Besides ranching, rock-crushing and a new
sludge disposal site, jobs are scarce in the community.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a part of Texas that is in great need, and this
facility could have helped that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The commissioners stated they were ``disappointed'' that the
authority didn't do a better job conducting geological and
socio-economic studies for the site.
</P>
<P>
   Plans called for digging trenches in the desert, lining them
with concrete, storing wastes in concrete canisters and burying
them as they were filled. The main unanswered scientific question,
the commissioners said, was whether a fault lying under the site _
which hasn't changed for 780,000 years _ and a second fault 20
miles away were capable of causing problems. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-98 2003EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
