<SLUG> BC-BB0-CHIPPER-FALLEN-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Explaining Chipper case can help kids
 &HT;    By Alma E. Hill
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Parents can use the news about Atlanta Braves third
baseman Chipper Jones to emphasize responsibility to their children
and make it ``a learning experience,'' experts said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Many parents will find themselves dealing with the issue in some
way, after Jones, perhaps the most popular Atlanta sports figure
among kids, disclosed this week that he had fathered an
illegitimate child.
</P>
<P>
   The news of his affair followed a recent revelation by Evander
Holyfield that the boxer had fathered two illegitimate kids soon
after marrying his second wife.
</P>
<P>
   But ``Dr. Laura'' Schlessinger, the radio talk-show host and
newspaper columnist, characterized both men as ``bums'' and
advocated that parents encourage children to rip down posters of
Jones or Holyfield ``instantaneously.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's some more advice for parents :
</P>
<P>
   _ Parents should help children put the news in perspective, said
Dr. Tom Cummins, assistant professor of child and adolescent
psychiatry at Emory Medical School.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would try to make it a learning opportunity,'' he said. ``If
people do things that are wrong, it does not necessarily mean they
are bad people. They've made a mistake. The important thing is, you
realized it was wrong and you tried to do better in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Cummins said it's important to stress to children that there are
a lot of people who can be admired in everyday life.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the potential drawbacks of hero worship of public
figures is you don't really know who they are,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Parents can underscore to children the importance of being
responsible, says Peter Elkon, a licensed professional counselor
with Families First, a nonprofit agency in metro Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teach them (that) if they receive something, if they have a
lot of success, they have to handle the gifts that come with it
responsibly,'' he said. ``It takes a lot of power and
responsibility, if you get rich and famous, to resist temptation.''
</P>
<P>
   Elkon warns parents not to get too ``preachy,'' however.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to go in and get out quickly,'' he said. ``If you try
to branch out in too many directions at once, the kid's going to
turn off.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Schlessinger, however, says that being a hero has nothing to
do with hitting home runs or throwing hard punches in the ring _
and that Jones and Holyfield need not apply.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes both these men ... bums is that little children
were brought into the world without a family. They are not
heroes,'' she said in a telephone interview Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Heroes are men and women of character who have sacrificed for
a greater ideal,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Paulette Holyfield, Evander's first wife, has had to deal with
the subject of infidelity and illegitimate children on several
occasions.
</P>
<P>
   ``With my Christian background, I let them know nobody's
perfect,'' she said. ``And that he's not less of a man, nor is he
more of a man, because he has a lot of kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also let them know it's always best for them to keep their
virginity until they're married. Sex is such an important
responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
