<SLUG> BC-DIESEL-POLLUTION-560&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK ATTORNEY GENERAL CHALLENGES DIESEL DEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., N.Y.)  (dl) 
 By JOHN H. CUSHMAN Jr.   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ New York State Attorney General Dennis Vacco took
preliminary steps Thursday to challenge a huge national settlement
between federal authorities and diesel truck engine manufacturers,
saying it would do too little to prevent smog and acid rain in the
state.
</P>
<P>
   He acted shortly after the Justice Department and the
Environmental Protection Agency announced a billion-dollar
settlement with the seven leading manufacturers of heavy duty
diesel engines for evading pollution control standards. The federal
authorities called it the most significant environmental
enforcement action ever taken, whether measured by the $83.4
million in civil penalties or by the 75 million tons of air
pollution that they said would be avoided during the next 27 years.
</P>
<P>
   But Vacco signaled that New York state, which is not bound by
the settlement, might seek tougher remedies. He issued subpoenas to
the engine manufacturers late Thursday, a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This settlement appears to have serious deficiencies,'' Vacco
said in a statement. ``I am stepping up my own investigation to
ensure that New York state's interests are protected.''
</P>
<P>
   Fumes from diesel trucks are important contributors to smog,
which plagues New York City, and acid rain, which damages lakes and
forests in the Adirondacks.
</P>
<P>
   The federal authorities had charged that the engine makers
designed their engines with computerized controls that enabled the
engines to meet air pollution standards during certification tests
in the laboratories even though they violated the standards in
normal operations, such as when cruising on highways. As they
settled the cases, the companies asserted Thursday that the
allegations were untrue and that their engines meet applicable
standards, a claim that the EPA said was proven false by its
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of us believe that we violated the law, and we were
prepared to litigate that,'' said John Farmer, general counsel of
Detroit Diesel Corp., who called the settlement a fair compromise
and urged third parties like New York State to accept it. ``They
have a big burden to overcome what I think is a rational result,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the settlement, the companies agreed to pay tens of
millions of dollars each in fines, to spend an additional $109.5
million on clean-air research and demonstration projects, to
accelerate the introduction of cleaner engines by two years, to
redesign new engines immediately and to pay for changes to about 1
million engines already on the road when they are returned for
routine rebuilding after several years of use. Altogether, the
companies are expected to spend $1 billion.
</P>
<P>
   But the agency said it would not demand that the engines be
immediately recalled, which is the remedy specified in such cases
by the Clean Air Act. Instead, the dirtier engines will be cleaned
up at the manufacturers' expense when they are rebuilt, typically
after several years or a few hundred thousand miles of operation.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups that are already suing engine makers
separately under California state law said they would challenge the
federal settlement and demand a recall, and now it appears that
Vacco has taken their side. California, which alone among the
states has independent legal authority to regulate the truck
emissions, joined the federal settlement on Thursday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Vacco's spokesman, Mark Carey, said that the lack of a recall
meant that some trucks would remain on the road for years to come.
</P>
<P>
   But Carol Browner, the EPA administrator, disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, we are doing something that's much, much better than
a recall,'' she said. ``We chose a rebuild because we wanted to get
the best possible environmental result quickly, and that's what it
gave us.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Kassel, senior attorney with the Natural Resources
Defense Council, an environmental advocacy group based in New York,
said that New York did not come out as well as California in the
settlement. California, as a party, was promised a big share of the
penalties and of the environmental projects that the companies will
undertake.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the key pieces of this settlement had to be
supplemental programs that are really targeted to the cities that
are suffering the most,'' he said. ``Cities like New York are
crying out for relief from the millions of pounds of diesel exhaust
that millions of New Yorkers breathe every day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
