<HEADLINE>
SEARCHERS RAISE CAR FROM CREEK, RECOVER FOUR BODIES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By THADDEUS HERRICK 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   KIRBY, Texas _ Firefighter Stan Irwin saw the headlights of the
car dim in the high water and then disappear.
</P>
<P>
   It was Sunday morning, about 1 a.m., and the car slipped
downstream into Salado Creek. ``Help'' was all he heard.
</P>
<P>
   ``It floated for about two minutes,'' said Irwin. ``I tried to
swim out to them, but I couldn't make it.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, six days after the torrential rains socked San
Antonio with up to 20 inches of rain, the car was pulled from the
still-swollen creek. It was a white Lincoln Town Car, and in it
were four people, including a young mother and her infant baby, who
had been the focus of an intense San Antonio-area search.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was frustrating not to be able to do something for those
folks,'' said Irwin. ``We tried.''
</P>
<P>
   Dead are Donna O'Bar, 65, a mother of four, her son, Richard
Hartman, 47, Jennifer Allensworth, 20, the fiance of Hartman's
nephew, and their 2-month-old daughter, Mallory.
</P>
<P>
   They are among 27 people to perish in the severe weather that
struck Texas over the weekend. Seven others were swept away in
low-water crossings in the San Antonio area. But none of those
incidents involved as great a loss of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst feeling was when they found it,'' said Mark Hartman,
O'Bar's youngest son and brother to Richard. ``That's when it hit.
That's when you realize your worst fears have come true.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Bar and her family were returning to this suburb east of San
Antonio from a family wedding Saturday night about 35 miles south
of the city. At a gas station on the city's outer loop they were
told the inner loop was closed. So they sought another route home.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody is quite sure how they ended up on Rigsby Avenue where
they encountered high water. Nor is it clear whether the low-water
crossing was barricaded. Irwin only saw flares posted by local
residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to tell what led them there,'' said Carl Wedige, a
district chief for the San Antonio Fire Department, who did not
know if the road had been closed. ``People think they can cross.
Then they stall.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday friends, neighbors and family milled about O'Bar's
low-slung house on Ackerman Road. Their search, which involved
dozens of authorities and volunteers, was agonizing.
</P>
<P>
   Though they reported the four family members missing Sunday
afternoon, they had no firm leads until Wednesday when Irwin told
them during the ongoing search that he had seen a white car
disappear in high water.
</P>
<P>
   A firefighter with the nearby Leon Springs department, Irwin
said he reported the car to the San Antonio Fire Department, but
the Hartmans never learned of the possible connection. They sought
help from a missing persons group called the Heidi Search Center.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities suspected the car had been swept far down the creek.
But Wednesday they refocused their search closer to where the car
went off the road and, using inflatable boats, poles and a metal
detector, located the car Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   So devastated was Justin Hartman, Richard's son and
Allensworth's fiance, he fainted as the car was pulled from the
creek.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Hartman described his mother as ``his best friend,'' a
straight-talking, domino-playing woman who raised kids and became
so successful selling appliances that she eventually bought an
appliance company.
</P>
<P>
   ``She'd tell you how everything went,'' he said. ``But she'd
give you the shirt off her back. She'd give you her last dime.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Hartman hauled trucks out of College Station. That's
where his nephew, Justin, also lived with Allensworth and their
baby Mallory.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was happy about being a momma,'' said Hartman.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, authorities in Caldwell County Thursday recovered the
body of 7-year-old Devon McCoy, who had been missing since
Saturday, when the vehicle his mother had been driving was washed
into Brushy Creek near Uhland.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Department of Public Safety Trooper Keith Conley said the
boy was found near the water's edge along a dam on private
property. Rescuers had searched that site Wednesday, Conley said,
but Devon`s body was not there then.
</P>
<P>
   A 10-year-old friend of the McCoy family, Heather Cottle, also
had been in the McCoy's car and drowned. Her body was found
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Still missing are Leandro Acevedo, 71, and his wife, Melva, 60,
who left their son's Galena Park home about 11 p.m. Saturday headed
toward Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't heard anything from them,'' said Robert Pruett, an
assistant police chief in Galena Park. ``I'm just afraid they may
be in a gully somewhere since so much time has passed.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
