u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-YANKS-ANDERSON-CO     10-22 0708
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-YANKS-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WHY WAS GEORGE BLUBBERING ON TV?  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Who was that silver-haired man in the white
turtleneck and blue blazer blubbering over the World Series trophy
on television Wednesday night?
</P>
<P>
   It couldn't possibly have been George Steinbrenner, not grumpy
George, not the Bronx bully. It had to be somebody else, maybe the
actor on ``Seinfeld'' who played the Yankees' principal owner.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, it had to be the genuine George because the genuine
George's ego would not have allowed anybody else, certainly not an
actor, to accept the World Series trophy, much less blubber.
</P>
<P>
   But that only prompts two questions: what is the genuine George
really like now, and why was he blubbering?
</P>
<P>
   For all his bluster, George Steinbrenner is really a
sentimentalist, at least when the Yankees are winning. And with a
World Series sweep for 125 victories, these Yankees, his Yankees,
not only won more games in one year than any other Yankee team ever
had, they also won more games than any other team ever had.
</P>
<P>
   The genuine George was blubbering because these were his
Yankees, but the sentimentalist in him was blubbering because maybe
he knew it was the last time they would really be his Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   If all the talk about his selling the Yankees to Cablevision is
to develop into a real deal, the genuine George, who is 68, knows
now is the time. The value of America's most famous sports
franchise has never been higher. If an expansion pro football
franchise in Cleveland goes for $530 million, who's to say the
Yankees aren't worth $1 billion?
</P>
<P>
   Quite a tidy profit, considering that Steinbrenner and his
silent partners put up $10 million in 1973 to buy the Yankees from
the Columbia Broadcasting System.
</P>
<P>
   Not that a sale would necessarily evict the genuine George from
his Stadium office. Part of the deal might be for him to remain in
control of the team. In the hours before Wednesday night's 3-0
Series clincher in San Diego, he growled, ``I will tell you this:
I'm never going to be in a situation where I have a token role.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Cablevision is the primary owner, the Yankees won't
really be his Yankees the way they have been all these years.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his image as a big spender with big money, the genuine
George's cash flow is whispered not to be as strong as it once was.
</P>
<P>
   According to someone familiar with Cablevision's negotiations
with the genuine George, ``He needs the money.'' His shipbuilding
business is a memory. His baseball team is his primary source of
income. And if he's going to sell the Yankees eventually anyway,
strike while the franchise is hot.
</P>
<P>
   Keep in mind that, more than anything else, the genuine George
is a promoter and a businessman.
</P>
<P>
   If he had blubbered over the World Series trophy because he's a
sentimentalist, it's because his Yankees won, not because he has
really changed that much, although maybe he has softened a little.
After the recent American League Championship Series, he told Brian
Cashman, his 31-year-old general manager, ``Good job.''
</P>
<P>
   The genuine George has yet to say ``good job'' to Bob Watson,
the general manager when the Yankees won the 1996 World Series;
Watson resigned early this year, citing health reasons.
</P>
<P>
   And if these Yankees, with their $65 million payroll, had
stumbled through the season, the genuine George would have been as
obnoxious and as obvious as ever. If he's a sentimentalist when the
Yankees win, he can still be a tyrant when they lose.
</P>
<P>
   Around the Yankees, the feeling has always been that the genuine
George would never bequeath his principal owner's power to his
29-year-old son, Hal, and his 43-year-old son-in-law, Steve
Swindal.
</P>
<P>
   Now the genuine George is saying: ``If Steve and Hal told me
they like running this thing, I can walk away. If my family wants
it, I should be willing to give it to them. I'm convinced that they
do want it.''
</P>
<P>
   So maybe the sale would include roles that would put Steve and
Hal in control eventually.
</P>
<P>
   But one way or another, if the genuine George sells the Yankees,
they won't be his Yankees anymore. Maybe that's why he was
blubbering.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
