<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-CHURCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON ASKS HIS HOME CHURCH FOR FORGIVENESS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By LAURIE GOODSTEIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton has sent a letter to the members of his home
church in Little Rock, Ark., expressing his repentance and asking
their forgiveness for his sins.
</P>
<P>
   The two-page, handwritten letter was read aloud to the
congregation of the church, Immanuel Baptist, at the close of
morning services on Sunday by the pastor, the Rev. Rex Horne. A
church staff member said Horne did not plan to release the contents
of the letter because it was a private message about spiritual, not
political, matters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president expressed repentance for his actions, sadness
for the consequence of his sin on his family, friends and church
family, and asked forgiveness from Immanuel,'' Horne said in a
one-sentence statement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the right thing for the president to do,'' Horne told
the Arkansas Baptist Newsmagazine after the services. He said he
sensed that a majority of the congregation was responsive to
Clinton's request for forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton joined Immanuel Baptist Church in 1980 and has retained
his formal membership there while living in Washington. The church
is a member of the Southern Baptist Convention, the nation's
largest Protestant denomination and one whose leadership has turned
increasingly conservative in the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks since the president admitted to having lied about
his relationship with Monica Lewinsky last August, top officials of
the Southern Baptist Convention have called on Immanuel Baptist to
discipline Clinton by revoking his church membership.
</P>
<P>
   ```How can President Clinton claim to be Southern Baptist and
persist in this display of serial sin?'' said R. Albert Mohler Jr.,
president of Southern Baptist Theological Seminary, in a commentary
for Religion News Service. ``Only because the congregation which
holds his membership has failed to exercise any semblance of church
discipline.''
</P>
<P>
   Paige Patterson, president of the Southern Baptist Convention,
said at a news conference in Louisville, Ky., in September that he
agreed with Mohler's call for Immanuel Baptist to discipline the
president. Both Mohler and Patterson have also called on Clinton to
resign as president. Referring to a biblical passage, Patterson
added, ``It is said that the church is to deal with them in public
so that all may learn to fear.''
</P>
<P>
   Southern Baptist leaders have no power to force Immanuel Baptist
Church to discipline Clinton or any church member, however; each
local church is considered autonomous, and therefore has the
authority to decide who is eligible for membership.
</P>
<P>
   Horne has declined to respond to the calls to discipline the
president, but has emphasized Immanuel Baptist's autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Michael Seabaugh, chairman of the Arkansas Baptist
State Convention resolutions committee, said of disciplining
Clinton: ``I don't see what would be gained. He has confessed, he
has asked forgiveness, and forgiveness has been extended.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-98 2020EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981022.0414 </DOCNO>
