A2368 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TXFLOOD-RESCUE-HNS &LR;      10-22 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TXFLOOD-RESCUE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMAN, 94, WHO REFUSED RESCUE ATTEMPTS DURING FLOODING, FINALLY
COAXED TO LEAVE 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEPHEN JOHNSON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHARTON, Texas _ Fetid flood waters lapping at her doorstep
couldn't budge 94-year-old Ira Mae Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Neither could game wardens, police, the Wharton Fire Department,
a city councilman and other emergency personnel.
</P>
<P>
   For two-days _ until the councilman brought Anderson's home
health care aide to the house Thursday _ the adamant woman waved
away would-be rescuers. She just didn't want to evacuate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sick,'' Anderson had explained to those sloshing through
the waters to talk to her through a window. ``I``m nervous and when
I get nervous, I can't move and I'm gettin' more nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got high blood pressure and I don't feel like moving,''
she said. ``Sure, the water could come into my house, but it's just
better if I stay here and stay quiet.''
</P>
<P>
   A procession of Wharton police and fire personnel waded to her
house, begging her to leave. Texas National Guard trucks, air boats
and skiffs carrying emergency personnel came and went as the
ever-rising floodwaters threatened her neatly kept home.
</P>
<P>
   Since state law does not allow officials to forcibly evacuate
residents, persuasion was the name of the game.
</P>
<P>
   With flooding here expected to reach its apex Friday with the
cresting of the Colorado River at Wharton, about 70 miles southwest
of Houston, rescuers were feeling thwarted, but determined,
Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm worried about her like I would be for any person cut off
by high water,'' explained Wharton Fire Chief David Copeland. ``She
runs the risk of losing her power, and being surrounded by this
contaminated water is a real health hazard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Besides,'' said Copeland, ``she's 94!''
</P>
<P>
   Emergency personnel had ferried 30 residents from Anderson's
neighborhood to safety Wednesday night. Like Anderson, the 30 had
initially refused to leave their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Game Wardens John Feist and Bobby Jobes accompanied by
Wharton Fireman Brian Van Horn roared down Anderson's submerged
street in an air boat to plead with her to leave Thursday.
``Thanks, but no thanks,'' Anderson politely told them.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, City Councilman Leroy Barnes arrived aboard the
V-8-powered air boat _ which is usually used in the pursuit of
poachers _ and made his own pitch for her to leave. She was
unimpressed.
</P>
<P>
   However, Anderson admitted that she missed being visited by a
home health care aide who spent four hours with her each day.
</P>
<P>
   ``She stays with me and takes care of me,'' said Anderson. ``She
hadn't been here because she says there's just too much water.''
</P>
<P>
   In no time at all, officials located the aide Bessie Mae Pine.
She agreed to board the air boat for the trip to Anderson's home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll use city councilmen, nurses or whatever it takes to talk
her out of that house,'' said Copeland, the fire chief.
</P>
<P>
   While the pistol-toting game wardens sat on the prow of the air
boat moored in Anderson's submerged yard, Barnes and Pine entered
Anderson's home. After nearly 15 minutes of negotiations, she
agreed to go home with Pine.
</P>
<P>
   Reassured by her aide and the good-natured Barnes, Anderson
changed clothes (after curtly ordering the city councilman
outside).
</P>
<P>
   After being carefully helped into the boat, she pulled on a hat
to protect herself from the wind and sat on the boat's prow.
</P>
<P>
   Why did she finally agree to leave, she was asked.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson gestured at her aide: ``I just didn't want to listen to
Bessie's mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   Pine's just smiled as she sat across from Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   The boat's engine jumped to life with an ear-splitting roar and
a smiling Anderson thanked everyone around her for their help
before heading for higher ground. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
