<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROSENTHAL-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: PRISONER OF BAGHDAD  
(JT)
</HEADLINE>
   By A.M. ROSENTHAL    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Goal by goal and strength by strength, the U.N. inspection teams
searching out Saddam Hussein's weapons are being diminished in
purpose, effectiveness and dignity by Secretary-General Kofi Annan,
to the point of public insult.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In case Saddam Hussein and the world have any doubt about where
the secretary-general stands, Annan announces that U.N. members do
not have the will to use force to reopen Iraq to the hunt for
chemical, nuclear and biological weapons.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He also says the 100 percent removal of these weapons, as
ordered by the United Nations is impossible. A ``political''
decision, says he, is needed on whether Iraq is disarmed enough or
has any of those weapons left. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Political. For seven years, inspectors have been sent out by the
United Nations, specifically assigned to find, examine and destroy
nuclear, chemical and biological weapons until all, not some, were
destroyed, to make scientific and technical accountings, not
political judgment.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And he said that the inspection teams should avoid
confrontational inspections, which means any that Iraqis don't
want, and be more flexible, more conciliatory. No other
secretary-general has humiliated his own people in the field.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The downgrading of U.N. inspection automatically affects its
chief, Richard Butler, one of the more admired U.N. servants in
decades. It has gone on quietly for a year. Russia, France and
other courters of Saddam do their part behind the closed doors of
the Security Council. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In my last column, I wrote again about the campaign within the
United Nations against U.N. inspection. The purpose is to draw down
inspection, lift or wither the economic sanctions imposed by the
United Nations for years of Iraqi refusal to cooperate with
inspection, and get back to the tasty days of oil and weaponry
contracts between Saddam and favored countries. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The next day Annan met with editors and reporters of The
Washington Post and told them his thoughts and wishes, for
publication.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   His comments undercut the United States and Security Council
demand for total destruction of Saddam's hidden mass-death
weaponry. And by announcing that U.N. members are against military
action to save U.N. inspection, Annan wipes out the critical power
of Chapter VII. That chapter gives the United Nations the right to
take military action to put down aggression or breach of the peace.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Chapter VII was the pillar of U.N. action against Saddam after
Iraq's invasion of Kuwait, the prod for his promises to disclose
his weapons within 15 days after he made them _ seven years ago. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Now, all Saddam has to do is to make his hilarious
open-inspection promise again and under the Annan doctrine the
United Nations will review what it can do to make him happy, such
as minimal sanctions and ineffective inspection. Then, happy,
Saddam can proceed to make weapons of mass destruction again from
the material and technology the inspectors have not yet found. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scott Ritter, who resigned from the inspectorate to talk out
against its throttling, says Iraq will need three years to produce
nuclear weapons, six months for biological weapons.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ehud Barak, former Israeli military chief of staff and now
leader of the Labor Party, agrees about nuclear estimates, and
thinks chemical weapons will take two years.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   How did Annan get so brave as to cut across American policy?
Why, because the Clinton administration has inspired neither
respect, fear nor sense that its policy was more than to wait for
Iraq to go away. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In February 1998, with U.S. approval, he went to Baghdad and
made a deal with Saddam. Promise not to bar inspectors again, and
we will welcome you back penalty-free _ and speed economic things
along for you.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He got real carried away with Saddam. He called him wise,
courageous and flexible. He announced he ``could do business'' with
him. He created a layer of U.N. bureaucracy to shelter him from the
inspectors.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Along comes Aug. 5. Saddam orders another blockade, which is
still going on, of almost all inspection. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Annan could have liberated himself by saying that he had been
wrong to trust Saddam _ and would not again until Iraq surrendered
all its weapons of mass destruction.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But he did not have the courage to say that. So there he
remains, on the 38th floor of U.N. headquarters in New York, the
prisoner of Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
