<SLUG> BC-VAIL-FIRES-480&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VAIL FIRES WERE ARSON, FEDERAL EXPERTS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (dl) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Federal arson experts in Colorado have concluded
that the fires atop Vail Mountain were almost certainly set
deliberately, law enforcement officials said Thursday, a finding
that means the case will be investigated as an act of environmental
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   The preliminary arson findings came as investigators said they
found empty plastic jugs that contained gasoline used to ignite the
fires on Monday at several buildings and chair lifts at the
11,200-foot level on the mountain, the officials said. The fires
started at multiple sources at several buildings, strongly
suggesting the blazes were set on purpose.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the fires emerged following a claim of
responsibility on Monday by a shadowy group, the Earth Liberation
Front, which said in e-mail communiques to news organizations that
it set the fires _ just weeks before the start of the ski season _
to stop a ski operator from expanding onto a ridge overlooking a
national forest that was a potential habitat.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said they regarded the Earth Liberation Front
claim as legitimate, although they appeared to have no suspects.
The fires are being investigated by the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco
and Firearms, along with state and local authorities, and caused an
estimated $12 million in damages.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, it seemed evident that although no one was hurt in
the blaze, federal law enforcement agencies regarded the Colorado
incident as a major case. The ATF dispatched two National Response
Teams comprised of arson investigators, chemists and other forensic
experts. At the FBI, agents in the domestic terrorism section of
the agency's national security division began organizing the search
of suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators have brought in a mobile laboratory. Evidence
collected at the sites, which officials described as two crime
scenes situated more than a mile apart, will be sent to ATF labs in
California and Maryland. It remained unclear what agency would take
the lead in the case, although terrorist inquiries fall under the
FBI's jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   The fires occurred at a site where Vail Resorts has planned an
885-acre expansion into a mountainous back-country area where the
company had begun clearing trees on Friday in a hotly contested
development plan opposed by environmentalists and many local
residents of Eagle County where the ski operation is located.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putting profits ahead of Colorado's wildlife will not be
tolerated,'' said the statement by the Earth Liberation Front,
referring to the the ski area as a habitat for the lynx. ``This
action is just a warning. We will be back if this greedy
corporation continues to trespass into wild and unroaded areas.''
</P>
<P>
   The officials said that arson has sometimes been used as a
weapon by environmental and animal rights extremists, two somewhat
independent movements whose activities have been on the rise in
recent years.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In June, fires were set at government buildings here that had
been used to conduct animal research experiments. Environmental
militants in the West have destroyed fences, set fires to livestock
buildings and driven spikes into trees to prevent logging in
fragile areas.
</P>
<P>
   One law enforcement official said Thursday that little was known
about the membership and operations of such groups, although they
are believed to have a handful of active supporters. They are
organized in a manner similar to right-wing extremists adopting
formless structures of small leaderless cells which have proven
difficult for the authorities to penetrate.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-98 2032EDT &QL; 
