<SLUG> BC-MA-HEALTH-INSURER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TUFTS HEALTH PLAN WILL LIMIT DRUG BENEFITS FOR SENIORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX PHAM  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tufts Health Plan, which offers the state's biggest health
maintenance organization for seniors, said Thursday that it will
limit prescription drug benefits for the elderly to $125 a quarter,
starting Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   The decision is the latest industry challenge to a popular
Massachusetts law requiring insurers to offer unlimited drug
benefits to seniors.
</P>
<P>
   Seniors and patient advocates decried Tufts' new limit, saying
it will leave many low-income elderly without any means to pay for
medications. ``This is going to devastate many seniors,'' said Phil
Mamber, a member of Massachusetts Senior Action Council, an
advocacy group for seniors.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Tufts, which has 83,900 seniors in its Secure Horizons HMO,
said that the limit will actually benefit 89 percent of its current
membership, while leaving 11 percent _ roughly 9,000 seniors _
financially worse off than under the current terms.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Tufts is not the first insurer to cap drug benefits. Harvard
Pilgrim Health Care last month said it will limit drug benefits to
$800 a year for each senior enrolled in First Seniority, beginning
Jan. 1. Harvard's limit would be based on the retail value of the
drugs, while the Tufts limit would be based on a discounted price,
or the cost to the HMO to reimburse pharmacies.
</P>
<P>
   State Attorney General Scott Harshbarger, in a lawsuit filed
last month, alleges Harvard is violating a 1994 state law requiring
unlimited drug benefits. Harvard and the managed care industry have
argued that a 1997 federal law exempts HMOs from state laws
governing benefits. The suit, which is being closely watched by
other states as a test case on the ability of states to regulate
Medicare HMOs, is scheduled for a hearing Oct. 30 in federal
district court.
</P>
<P>
   If the court decides in favor of HMOs, seniors could face a
gradual erosion of their drug coverage, advocates said. Since
Medicare does not offer any drug benefits, HMOs are not required by
federal law to cover drugs.
</P>
<P>
   ``There would be nothing to stop HMOs from eliminating drug
benefits altogether,'' said Michael Miller of Health Care For All,
a consumer advocate group in Boston. In fact, HMOs would have an
incentive to be stingy with their drug benefits, Miller said. Since
sicker seniors with high medical costs are more likely to pick
plans with drug coverage, HMOs wishing to avoid these seniors and
to ``cherry pick'' healthy seniors could eliminate drug coverage by
relying on a federal exemption, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Tufts argued that some seniors will be better off under the new
limit. All Secure Horizons members will automatically get the
$125-per-quarter drug benefit without having to pay a premium,
Davis said. Se-niors currently pay $74 a month for unlimited
prescription drug benefits. In addition, seniors will not have to
make copayments, now $8 for a 90-day supply of a generic drug, $15
for a brand-name drug. So a senior must take more than $1,500 worth
of drugs &UR;  &LR; a year to be financially worse off under the new limit,
said Michelle Davis, a spokeswoman for the Waltham health plan.
</P>
<P>
   Tufts estimates that 9,000 seniors in Secure Horizons use more
than $1,500 worth of medications a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-98 2033EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981022.0423 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
