<HEADER>
A2384 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-BOS &LR;      10-22 1221
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-SUMMIT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON PRESSES MIDEAST PEACE EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and i coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID L. MARCUS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WYE MILLS, Md. _ Continuing the most intensive foreign diplomacy
of his career, President Clinton yesterday shuttled between
clusters of Israeli and Palestinian officials to try to resolve
knotty disputes, including the final stage of a West Bank pullout,
the fate of Palestinian prisoners in Israel, and a Palestinian
charter that calls for Israel's destruction.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Palestinians stepped up their demands for
an end to Jewish settlements on disputed lands, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   US officials said they reached a breakthrough during bleary-eyed
talks early Thursday, as Israelis and Palestinians tentatively
agreed to American proposals for increasing security in Israel. The
measures included using CIA officers as intermediaries to decide
which Palestinians charged with terrorist acts should be extradited
to Israel, according to those familiar with the heated discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Another sticking point, the plans for a Palestinian airport in
Gaza, was basically resolved, the officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In the latest of more than 60 hours of face-to-face involvement,
Clinton spent the day discussing and debating fine points of the
agreeement as he alternated between Netanyahu and Arafat and their
aides, officials said. The president turned on the charm, and his
hard sell, as he arrived for his sixth day at the talks on
Maryland's Eastern Shore. ``The hardest decisions now at last are
on the table,'' he told reporters before going to the secluded Wye
Plantation.
</P>
<P>
   Prodding and cajoling Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, Clinton asked the two sides
to reach an agreement by late last night or early this morning, and
then attend a ceremony at the White House. As the sun went down
over the marshland surrounding the Wye Plantation, State Department
spokesman James P. Rubin said the talks had entered a ``fairly
high-intensity'' stage. But ``there's definitely no deal yet,'' he
added.
</P>
<P>
   The White House sees added urgency for a deal because Netanyahu
has talked about flying to Jerusalem or New York before the
Sabbath, which starts at sundown today. In addition, Americans said
they were jolted up by a grenade-throwing terrorist in Israel on
Monday and wanted Netanyahu and Arafat to make a commitment, shake
hands and sign a document before something else disrupts the talks.
</P>
<P>
   Complicating matters, Israeli hard-liners said they would tie up
a new surrender of the West Bank with political chaos if Netanyahu
made concessions to the Palestinians. Hanan Porat, a legislator and
member of the National Religious Party, said the right wing would
bring down Netanyahu's government and force early elections.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to restore an atmosphere of congeniality after a tense
day of brinksmanship Wednesday, Clinton, Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright and US envoy Dennis Ross took walks through the
woods of the Wye Plantation throughout the day with Israeli and
Palestinian officials in the brisk fall breezes. Adding to the
sense of familiarity, Clinton brought his dog, Buddy.
</P>
<P>
   Details of the security agreement were sketchy, but one official
said it includes concessions by Palestinians to cooperate with the
CIA and turn over terrorists to Israeli authorities. In exchange
for the cooperation, Israel will hand over 13 percent more of the
West Bank in several stages during three months.
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with his national security team in the morning,
Clinton spoke with Netanyahu while Albright spoke with Arafat.
Clinton talked to Arafat, and then the two Mideast leaders sat on a
couch and held a rare talk _ which Americans called an encouraging
sign.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli and Palestinian delegations sat at different sides of a
cavernous dining room during a buffet lunch, but Rubin said
officials of the two groups mixed for talks.
</P>
<P>
   US officials said they are not interested in a partial agreement
that leaves major issues to be decided. But they indicated that
some less-important topics had been scuttled for now, including
talks about a seaport that the Palestinians hope to build.
</P>
<P>
   Delegations and lawyers were meeting to decide when Palestinians
will build an airport and seaport and whether Israel will free a
group of Palestinians convicted and accused of terrorism from
prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president wouldn't have rolled up his sleeves today and
urged the leaders to get down to business if significant gaps did
not remain,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of US Jewish groups urged said they were in touch with
Netanyahu and his staff throughout the day, recommending a peace
pact that included a surrender of 13 percent of the West Bank so
long as Israel feels it will not be exposed to more terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overwhelmingly, the American Jewish community wants the peace
talks to succeed, just as Israelis do, but we know that Israelis
are the ones who pay the price if there isn't security,'' said
Malcolm Hoenlein, executive vice chairman of the Conference of
Presidents of Major American Jewish Organizations.
</P>
<P>
   Hoenlein was one of about 150 leaders who spoke with Netanyahu
on a conference call Wednesday evening after the Israelis packed
their bags and threatened to leave the talks. Netanyahu said the
Palestinians were backtracking on agreements and showing bad faith
by keeping a charter that calls for destroying Israel.
</P>
<P>
   US officials spoke about Netanyahu's threat with a mix of
bemusement and trepidation Thursday. One official noted that as
Albright approached the Israelis' cottage Wednesday, members of the
delegation were placing suitcases on the grass, then removing them
and putting them back _ as if rehearsing the scene of a play.
</P>
<P>
   The peace summit, finishing its eighth day, has lasted twice as
long as planned. Asked how much the US government was paying for
food and lodging for approximately 50 Palestinian and Israeli
guests, Rubin said there was no figure yet. ``I think whatever the
tab is, it will be a small price to pay if we can advance the cause
of peace.''
</P>
<P>
   The day started with Israelis and Palestinians reviewing a
20-page document put together by the Americans that outlined the
terms of the deal, especially the Israelis' withdrawal from 13
percent more of the West Bank, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   By nightfall, Clinton was nearing his 70th hour at the talks. He
has already postponed a two-day trip to California to campaign for
Democratic candidates for Congress, and the White House said the
president will stick to his new plan to depart Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan's King Hussein arrived at the estate for a second day,
but by the evening he was still confined to a guest cottage, where
he was phoning Arab and Israeli leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Palestinians said they were demanding the release of thousands
of prisoners as part of this peace deal. They also asked the
Israelis to make a commitment to a further withdrawal from the West
Bank, which is called for in a 1995 peace pact.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu has resisted talking about further withdrawals,
according to Americans who have spoken with him. ``The number of
issues has been reduced but the issues remaining are substantially
complex,'' Rubin said.
</P>
</TEXT>
