<DOCNO> NYT19981022.0431 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 20:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2390 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-1023-CO     10-22 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-1023-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    WITH CLINTON URGING THEM ON, MIDDLE EAST LEADERS TRY TO MAINTAIN
'MOMENTUM OF PEACE'
 &HT;    With ISRAEL-SETTLERS-1023; MIDEAST-BUDDY-1023.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WYE MILLS, Md. _ President Clinton pressed Israeli and
Palestinian leaders to ''capture the momentum of peace'' on
Thursday and embrace a high stakes land-for-security deal, but
talks among the parties ground to a ninth-inning snag over life and
death concerns on both sides.
</P>
<P>
   As an eighth excruciating day of Mideast summitry stretched into
the night, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat continued to meet around a roaring
fireplace here in rural Maryland, but they remained far apart on
half a dozen issues that frame the heart and soul of a peace
accord.
</P>
<P>
   Among the sticking points were questions over Israeli troop
withdrawals, the treatment of suspected terrorists by Palestinians
and the status of a Palestinian covenant calling for the
destruction of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty of the issues and the severity of the remaining
gaps, after eight days and nights of negotiations, left the talks
suspended in a stomach-wrenching netherworld between culmination
and collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ''What will happen is very much an open question,'' U.S. State
Department spokesman James Rubin told reporters late Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''The issues remaining are sufficiently complex and emotionally
laden and difficult for the parties involved for us to be unable to
know whether this will come out with an agreement or not,'' Rubin
said. ''The critical gaps in some of these areas have not been
closed.''
</P>
<P>
   Journeying to the secluded Wye River Conference Center on
Maryland's Eastern Shore for the sixth time in eight days, Clinton
lent the prestige of his office and the force of his will to the
talks, while U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright shuttled
back and forth between the Israeli and Palestinian leaders,
prodding, encouraging and offering her own suggestions on how to
move beyond impasse and toward peace.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope the parties will seize this opportunity and not retreat
from the clear moment to capture the momentum of peace,'' Clinton
said at the White House, before journeying by helicopter to the
summit, where he has spent more than 65 working hours since talks
began a week ago Thursday. ''The hardest decisions now, at last,
are on the table.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of bargaining at its most earnest, Netanyahu and
Arafat held a rare one-on-one meeting for two hours in the
afternoon, as their aides huddled in side meetings trying to come
to terms with various aspects of an overall deal.
</P>
<P>
   By day's end, though, they had yet to reach agreement on a host
of important issues.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're getting there, on some of them,'' said Rubin, who
compared the atmosphere to that of a last-minute political
horsetrading session on the eve of a critical legislative vote.
</P>
<P>
   ''It had a little bit of the flavor of a legislative session,
drawing toward the close, where people were working very hard,''
Rubin told reporters gathered near the conference center, where the
talks are unfolding at a 1,000-acre riverside retreat.
</P>
<P>
   ''But that doesn't mean that they will draw to a close,'' Rubin
cautioned.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are still obstacles,'' he said. ''I would say it's in
the half-dozen category.''
</P>
<P>
   At the core of the talks is a proposal for Israeli troops to
withdraw from an additional 13 percent of the occupied West Bank,
in exchange for a Palestinian commitment to combat anti-Israeli
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement would leave some 40 percent of the West Bank
under full, or partial, control of Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Under a U.S. proposal, agents of the Central Intelligence Agency
would assist Palestinians in handling difficult terrorist problems.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu is seeking additional promises from the Palestinians,
specifically over the issue of how to handle suspected terrorists
in territory under Palestinian control.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu is also insisting on the specific rescinscion of a
provision in the Palestinians' charter that calls for the
destruction of Israel. Arafat counters that the policy-making arm
of the Palestinian Authority has rescinded the provision -- even
though it is yet to be officially excised by a broader, 700-member
legislative body.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, for his part, is pressing for promises of additional
Israeli troop withdrawals from the West Bank, as called for in the
1993 Oslo accords that spawned the current peace process.
</P>
<P>
   That process has been stalemated for 19 months.
</P>
<P>
   The Wye talks are an attempt to advance the process toward
so-called final, or permanent, status talks, which, under the Oslo
accords, are to be completed by May 4.
</P>
<P>
   Permanent status talks would be aimed at resolving the most
difficult issues remaining in a conflict that has endured for half
a century, including the future of Jerusalem, which both Israelis
and Palestinians claim, and a host of economic, territorial and
security issues.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
