<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOP-CONSERVATIVES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPROMISE ON BUDGET MAY HURT REPUBLICANS   IN CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The strategy was simple: Hit the pause button on
the Republican revolution, strike a budget deal with the White
House, and avert a high-stakes government shutdown before the
November elections.
</P>
<P>
   But the price of bargaining away key elements of the GOP
conservative agenda in the compromise may be steep for House
Speaker Newt Gingrich and other congressional leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after President Clinton signed the controversial, $520
billion spending package into law, several GOP conservatives
predicted Thursday that Republican congressional leaders could face
serious divisions within their party's ranks as a result of their
election-year gamble to appease the White House by abandoning tax
cuts and other budget initiatives dear to the conservative
movement.
</P>
<P>
   But the most severe fallout is expected to occur when the next
Congress convenes in January. Gingrich, in particular, could suffer
as he tries to retain his speakership and position himself for a
possible presidential candidacy in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has created a huge problem for himself going into the next
Congress,'' said David A. Keene, chairman of the American
Conservative Union. ``He has coasted on the goodwill and the debts
owed him by many members who realize they couldn't have gained a
majority in 1994 without him. That has allowed many sins to be
forgiven. But the outrage over this deal is very serious.''
</P>
<P>
   Before lawmakers scrambled away from Capitol Hill this week for
their reelection races, many Republican members foreshadowed the
potential strife by firing parting shots at Gingrich and Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott, the chief congressional architects of
the spending deal.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative critics said the 4,000-page, 40-pound package
represents a massive capitulation by Republican leaders who were
more concerned about preserving pre-election stability than
standing by their principles.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to forgoing a tax cut, GOP leaders agreed to
spending proposals that exceeded last year's budget cap by more
than $20 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Steve Largent of Oklahoma, who entered the House
with the ``Republican revolution'' class of 1994, was quoted in the
Capitol Hill newspaper, Roll Call, Thursday as saying of the budget
deal: ``How we can call ourselves conservatives after that, I can't
imagine.''
</P>
<P>
   Largent, a member of the National Football League Hall of Fame,
added, ``I wish I could have negotiated my NFL contracts with this
leaderhsip.''
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich, who barely survived a coup attempt last year by GOP
conservatives, faces the likelihood of similar threats in the
future from Largent and other Republicans in the class of 1994.
They have formed a New Conservative Leadership Fund aimed at
electing enough conservatives to wrest control of the leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich, in a meeting Wednesday with reporters, appeared to be
positioning himself for a possible backlash, indicating he would
pursue the conservative agenda more vigorously next year. ``I think
you can be much bolder in the year immediately after an election,''
Gingrich said.
</P>
<P>
   Several Republican strategists said the budget compromise has
enabled GOP leaders to stave off potentially devastating attacks
against them as overseers of a ``do-nothing'' Congress. By agreeing
to fund many of Clinton's top priorities, including $1.1 billion to
hire as many as 100,000 new teachers, Republican leaders also may
have muted criticism that they have blocked efforts by Democrats to
improve public education and address other social problems.
</P>
<P>
   And very few Republican incumbents, if any, are likely to be
turned out of office by conservative voters, particularly when the
opponents are Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   The budget package passed the House, 333 to 95, and the Senate,
65 to 29.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're mad at Clinton for pushing the spending and mad at
Gingrich for allowing it, you're going to vote for the candidate
who is saying, `Damn, this budget is too big,' '' said Grover
Norvquist, the head of Americans for Tax Reform. ``And that
candidate is probably going to be one of the Republicans who voted
against the budget.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert D. Reischauer, a senior fellow at the Brookings
Institution and former director of the Congressional Budget Office,
predicted a ``significant backlash'' against Gingrich and the
current budget process in Congress next year because of the
spending deal.
</P>
<P>
   But how much the dynamics change, he said, will depend largely
on whether Republicans expand their slim, 11-seat majority in the
House. ``Unless the Republicans pick up more than 10 seats,''
Reischauer said, ``the House majority is going to remain very
fragile, which will continue to make it difficult for the leaders
to move forward without risking defeat on the floor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
