<SLUG> BC-TXFLOOD-CUERO-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUERO, TEXAS, FLASH FLOOD VICTIMS RETURNING TO LIVES CHANGED
FOREVER 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ARMANDO VILLAFRANCA 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CUERO, Texas _ When William B. Smolik, 78, returned Thursday to
his meat market after being rescued by boat from the family
business Tuesday morning, he peered at the debris as if searching
desperately for something he already knew was gone forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm kinda numb right now. I don't know,'' said Smolik, whose
family immigrated to Texas from Moravia after the Civil War. ``It's
pitiful. I don't know where to start.''
</P>
<P>
   He then dropped the brim of his cowboy hat and raised his right
thumb and forefinger to his eyes to catch the tears.
</P>
<P>
   Families returned to homes wrenched from their foundations by
floodwaters that rose more than 10 feet in four hours and swept
through Cuero like a tidal wave.
</P>
<P>
   Statewide, the death toll from the devastating floods rose to 27
Thursday as the bodies of five more victims were discovered.
</P>
<P>
   The Guadalupe River crested here at 49.78 feet early Monday and
sent water surging over its banks and through portions of the city
at 138,974 cubic feet per second.
</P>
<P>
   The force of the water left homes standing in the middle of
streets, boats balancing precariously on the hoods of pickup trucks
and debris hanging from fencelines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had two-thirds of our city affected, probably of that
two-thirds, half of that is what I call a war zone. I mean it's
totally devastated,'' said Cuero Mayor Michael Thamm.
</P>
<P>
   Areas expected to withstand 100-year and 500-year storms were
submerged when floodwater swept through the western and southern
parts of this community of 6,700.
</P>
<P>
   Officials estimate that 160 homes were destroyed by the water
surge and that hundreds more suffered substantial flood damage.
Luther Boysen, DeWitt County emergency management coordinator,
estimated that the toll will rise to more than 300 homes destroyed
once crews can inspect flooded areas.
</P>
<P>
   Thamm said miraculously no one was killed or injured. He said
damage cost estimates had not been determined.
</P>
<P>
   ``My main concern is the public safety right now, trying to do
as much as a I can for these people; 3,000 of the 7,000 people here
have been affected,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Red Cross officials fed 1,700 people displaced by the flood
Tuesday and had sheltered more than 1,000 the night before.
</P>
<P>
   The flood surge cut through Cuero just before noon Tuesday,
without warning. With no local radio station to broadcast an alert,
no one was aware the rising water was coming so quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Melissa Vavrusa said residents were told the crest would not
occur until Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem here,'' Thamm said, ``this time the river rose so
fast we had no time to prepare.''
</P>
<P>
   Residents with permits began returning to their homes Thursday
on Cuero's west side as floodwaters began to recede. The areas
worst hit by floodwaters, in southern Cuero, were not opened until
Thursday afternoon, after utility crews plugged natural gas leaks
and shut down electrical power.
</P>
<P>
   David Smolik, 43, was dumbfounded when he first saw the damage
Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm speechless right now,'' said the younger Smolik as his
eyes misted and he looked into the distance.
</P>
<P>
   Several blocks behind Smolik Quality Meats, Alfred Anzaldua, 59,
and a friend loaded the two barber chairs found on the side of a
road two blocks from where his barber shop had stood. Behind him, a
dirty yellow pulpit bearing a plaque with the word ``Peace'' stood
in the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my open and closed sign, but today I'm closed,'' said
Anzaldua, grinning as he slapped the mud from the sign on his
thigh.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of his barber shop, the roof and front wall with a
barber's pole still attached, rested on top of Mark Vavrusa's
tractor in his front yard, another block away.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seventeen acres, and I believe I caught just about everybody's
belongings,'' said Vavrusa as he surveyed the junkyard his property
had become.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my neighbors, what's theirs is theirs,'' he said. ``I
ain't fighting nobody over nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, the Colorado River rose to record levels and
continued to force evacuations in much of Wharton while other
swollen waterways in South and Central Texas receded, leaving
behind hundreds of millions of dollars in destruction across 60
counties.
</P>
<P>
   Among the victims of the unprecedented flooding were four
members of a San Antonio-area family whose bodies were found inside
their car in a creek. They had been missing for five days. Also
recovered Thursday was the body of a 7-year-old boy missing since
the weekend in Caldwell County, south of Austin. A Lockhart area
couple is still missing.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton earlier declared 20 Texas counties federal
disaster areas, making them eligible for federal aid, as state
officials put preliminary damage estimates at $400 million. Gov.
George W. Bush asked the Federal Emergency Management Agency to add
to the declaration five more counties in Southeast Texas _ Austin,
Fort Bend, Harris, Montgomery and Waller.
</P>
<P>
   In Wharton, 55 miles southwest of Houston, authorities tried to
prevent any more loss of life by taking airboats and Army trucks
into the Colorado River floodwaters to urge people to leave. The
city's west end was under water Thursday night and about 300 people
had taken refuge in shelters.
</P>
<P>
   ``This area's continuing to take on water and it probably will
all day long,'' Fire Chief David Copeland said earlier Thursday as
he stood across from one neighborhood swallowed by the river.
</P>
<P>
   And ranchers whose herds graze near the Guadalupe and San Marcos
rivers were trying to round up as many as 50,000 cattle and calves
that moved downstream when the swift waters knocked down fences.
The cattle were dodging floating logs, snakes, fire ants and other
animals.,
</P>
<P>
   ``The fire ants float on top of the water in big balls, and they
get around the cow's eyes and nose,'' said Trey Hamlett, manager of
the Luling Foundation farm where hundreds of strays have been
corralled by volunteers. ``The cow's hide is thick, but the ants
are still a problem to them.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
