<SLUG> BC-GOPSTRATEGY23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gingrich stumps for Michigan candidates
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WESTLAND, Mich. _ Wherever Speaker Newt Gingrich campaigned
Thursday in Michigan, he leveled criticism at pairs of Democrats,
the local Democratic member of Congress and Geoffrey Fieger.
</P>
<P>
   The former lawyer for Dr. Jack Kevorkian, Fieger won his party's
nomination for governor against popular Republican Gov. John
Engler.
</P>
<P>
   Polls say Fieger is hopelessly behind.
</P>
<P>
   But on his way to a near-certain defeat in November, he has
offended nearly every major religious group, made insulting
references to Engler and, perhaps most important, given Republicans
the notion that his antics will keep Democrats from voting in
November and result in Republican gains in Michigan's congressional
delegation.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich (R-Ga.) spoke and raised money in four Democratic-held
districts in which the incumbents normally would be expected to win
rather easily in a year that appears friendly to elected officials.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich's day began at the northern end of Lake Michigan, where
he appeared at a fund-raising breakfast for state Rep. Michelle
McManus, who is trying to oust three-term Democratic Rep. Bart
Stupak.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker repeatedly tried to tie Stupak to Fieger, even
though Stupak, who won 71 percent of the vote in 1996, has publicly
refused to endorse his party's nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the Fieger-Stupak team, no matter what Stupak tries to
say,'' Gingrich said.
</P>
<P>
   Later, in this western Detroit suburb, the speaker told a small
audience that to Rep. Lynn Rivers, ``party means everything, no
matter how unusual the nominee.''
</P>
<P>
   Rivers, who won election amid the Republican revolution of 1994,
also has chosen not to endorse Fieger. In an interview, she called
the governor's race ``crazy'' and referred to Fieger as ``a sort of
wild candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Michigan Republicans have kept up a steady drumbeat about
Fieger, predicting that he will demoralize Democratic voters and
keep them at home, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And for those not offended by Fieger, Clinton's problems will
be a turnoff. And not a single Democrat will vote in Michigan,''
Rivers said.
</P>
<P>
   Is it overdone? ``Just a tad,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Tom Hickey, the small-business owner who hopes to take
Rivers' place in Congress could muster a crowd of only 50 or so
adults at an afternoon rally that Gingrich headlined. A marching
band and a few dozen high school students _ one of whom yelled,
``You rule, Newt'' _ provided the event with some enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   University of Michigan political science professor Gregory
Markus said he has been struck by the lack of excitement over
political campaigns this year and he doubted whether Fieger's
candidacy would be much of a factor in the election results.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he acknowledged, if people choose not to vote, ``Low
turnout makes for quirky outcomes.''
</P>
<P>
   That prospect is motivating Republicans to send party leaders to
Michigan to boost the troops. House Majority Leader Dick Armey and
Rep. John Linder, chairman of the House Republican campaign
committee, will campaign for McManus next week.
</P>
<P>
   Gingrich, who is expected to visit 20 states in a pre-election
blitz, criss-crossed the state, also attending closed-door
fund-raising events for the Republicans challenging two senior
Democrats, House Minority Whip David Bonior and Rep. Sander Levin.
</P>
<P>
   The speaker mainly stayed away from the House's impeachment
inquiry, other than to criticize the media for overemphasizing
scandal.
</P>
<P>
   In Acme, Mich., where Gingrich spoke in the morning, Linda
Wiseley, an official with the Associated Builders and Contractors,
said she believes voters will allow their opinions of Clinton and
Fieger to influence their choices in other races.
</P>
<P>
   But in the next breath, she conceded that challengers from both
parties would have trouble gaining traction this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overall, things are pretty good,'' Wiseley said. ``People are
working.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
