<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GRIFFITH-JOYNER-DEATH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTOPSY ATTRIBUTES TRACK STAR'S DEATH TO ASPHYXIATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (a and s coding)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BARBARA HUEBNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Florence Griffith Joyner, the glamorous Olympic gold-medal
sprinter who died unexpectedly last month, asphyxiated during an
epileptic seizure in her sleep, authorities said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   An autopsy showed no evidence of either drug use or heart
problems, they added.
</P>
<P>
   ``In layman's terms, she suffocated,'' said Dr. Richard
Fukumoto, chief of forensics for the Orange County, Calif., sheriff
and coroner. Apparently, he said, she had been lying on her stomach
when the seizure caused her limbs to stiffen and turn her head to
the right, where her breathing was constricted by covers and
pillows.
</P>
<P>
   The autopsy discovered that Griffith Joyner, 38, had a
congenital blood vessel abnormality called a ``cavernous angioma''
on the front left part of her brain. It is found in 1 in 400
Americans, according to Dr. Marc Nuwer, a neurologist and
co-director of the adult epilepsy program at UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's sufficient explanation for a seizure,'' said Dr. Steven
Schachter, an associate professor of neurology at Harvard Medical
School and an epileptologist at Beth Israel Deaconess Medical
Center in Boston. ``Had she lived and this had been discovered, she
probably would have been put on seizure medication.''
</P>
<P>
   The abnormality has never been associated in medical research
with steroids or any other drugs, Fukumoto said. It may have been
present at birth.
</P>
<P>
   Griffith Joyner died at her Mission Viejo, Calif., home Sept.
21, and investigators had been trying since to determine the cause.
Her husband, 1984 Olympic triple jump champion Al Joyner, called
paramedics that morning after awakening to discover that his wife
wasn't breathing.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Griffith Joyner was hospitalized overnight after
suffering a seizure on a flight from St. Louis to California, but
apparently, she had no further incidents until the seizure that led
to her death.
</P>
<P>
   ``Epilepsy is usually defined as two or more seizures,'' said
Schachter, who is on the professional advisory board of the
Epilepsy Foundation. ``Usually, people are not treated after their
first seizure, especially if there is no reason to believe they are
at tremendous risk. Presumably, she was evaluated and there was no
reason to believe she was at risk for a second seizure.''
</P>
<P>
   During the news conference Thursday in Santa Ana, Calif.,
sheriff's spokesman Lt. Hector Rivera cut off questions about
Griffith Joyner's medical history and whether the condition had
been diagnosed.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Griffith Joyner had been shadowed by rumors, which
she vigorously denied, that she was using banned substances when
she won her three gold medals and set world records at 100 and 200
meters in 1988. But she never failed a drug test, and toxicology
tests after her death ``showed there was nothing unusual in terms
of drugs,'' said Lt. Frank Fitzpatrick, head of forensic sciences
for the Orange County Sheriff's Office. Tests showed only that she
had recently taken about one tablet each of the over-the-counter
painkiller Tylenol and antihistamine Benadryl.
</P>
<P>
   ``We now hope that this great Olympic champion, wife, and mother
can rest in peace,'' said Bill Hybl, president of the US Olympic
Committee. ``It is time for the whispers and dark allegations to
cease and for us to move on with the dream she shared for young
girls and women in sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Dwight Stones, former world record-holder in the high jump,
called Griffith Joyner ``the most tested athlete'' of the 1988
Olympics. ``I think this is fabulous and phenomenal vindication for
her and her family,'' he said Thursday. ``Now they should just
leave her alone.''
</P>
<P>
   Epilepsy is a neurological condition that from time to time
produces brief disturbances in the normal electrical functions of
the brain. When someone has epilepsy, normal brain activity is
interrupted by intermittent bursts of electrical energy that are
much more intense than usual. About 1 in 200 people has some form
of epilepsy, with an unknown number untreated and undiagnosed.
Although it primarily affects children and young adults, it can
occur at any age.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
