<SLUG> BC-FLOJO-AUTOPSY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIFFITH JOYNER DIED OF SUFFOCATION, AUTHORITIES SAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Olympic sprint champion Florence Griffith Joyner died of
suffocation a month ago after suffering a seizure while she slept,
medical authorities said Thursday in southern California.
</P>
<P>
   The seizure was caused by a congenital abnormality of blood
vessels in her brain called cavernous angioma, said Dr. Richard
Fukumoto, the chief forensic pathologist for the Orange County,
Calif., coroner's office.
</P>
<P>
   Toxicology tests showed that Griffith Joyner, 38, had taken a
tablet of the painkiller Tylenol and the antihistimine Benadryl,
but tests for evidence of alcohol, recreational drugs and
performance-enhancing drugs were negative, authorities said at a
news conference in Santa Ana, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Fukumoto said that he did not find any abnormality of Griffith
Joyner's heart during an autopsy, saying that she had a ``normal
athlete's heart'' that was in ``good form.'' At the time of her
death on Sept. 21, a family spokesman had said that a heart seizure
was believed to have been the cause of death.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Barbara Zaias, a neuropathologist with the coroner's office,
said that the blood vessel abnormality is found in about 25 percent
of the population and many people live their whole lives without
knowing it. Others suffer from headaches or seizures, brought on by
microscopic bleeding, she said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Fukumoto, Griffith Joyner had been sleeping face
down when the seizure apparently caused her to turn her head into
her pillow, restricting the flow of oxygen into her lungs and
causing her to asphyxiate. Not all such seizures are grand mal
seizures that would be noticed by another person, doctors said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In layman's terms, she suffocated to death,'' Fukomoto said.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors did not release any information from Griffith Joyner's
medical files and declined to say whether she was aware that she
had a blood vessel abnormality or whether she had suffered previous
seizures.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, her family said that she had suffered a seizure
while on a flight two years ago, and had been hospitalized
overnight, but that no cause of the incident had been determined.
</P>
<P>
   Fukomoto said that he knew of no connection between the use of
performance-enhancing drugs and cavernous angioma. ``I don't see
how you can tie it in at all,'' Dr. Gary Wadler, an internist and
sports medicine expert from the New York University School of
Medicine, said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Griffith Joyner, the winner of three gold medals at the 1988
Summer Olympics in Seoul, South Korea, died while she slept at her
home in Mission Viejo, Calif. Her husband, Al Joyner, the 1984
Olympic triple jump champion, called paramedics, saying that she
was unresponsive and not breathing.
</P>
<P>
   Griffith Joyner was a spectacular presence on the world track
circuit with her long fingernails, her flamboyant racing suits and
her searing speed. But because she shattered previous world records
at 100 and 200 meters and retired soon after the Seoul Olympics,
she also faced rumors and accusations from competitors that she had
used such performance-enhancing drugs as steroids or human-growth
hormone.
</P>
<P>
   In the days after she died, however, doctors cautioned against
trying to link her death to the use of illicit substances and
pointed out that the science was murky in that area.
</P>
<P>
   Griffith Joyner denied taking any banned substances and passed
every drug test that she took, although no test exists to detect
the presence of human growth hormone in a urine sample.
</P>
<P>
   Her family took Thursday's announcements as affirmation that she
had been a clean performer and as a chance to assert her legacy as
a great champion, devoted wife and mother, author of children's
books and ebullient worker with underprivileged children.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coroner's investigation was very thorough,'' Al Joyner
told reporters Thursday. ``My wife passed the ultimate drug test.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Meyer, the Joyners' attorney, said: ``The results of the
investigation confirm the fact that Florence Griffith Joyner passed
away from a congenital vascular malformation in her brain. There
were no heart problems and there was no indication of any drug or
steroid use, past or present. Her remarkable achievements remain
unspoiled.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Hybl, president of the U.S. Olympic Committee, said in a
statement that he hoped Griffith Joyner's admirers would now be
allowed to celebrate her legacy to sport and her work with children
and that it was ``time for the whispers and dark allegations to
cease.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Flo-Jo is deeply missed, but her gifts to sport, and to
children, will outlast all of us who were fortunate to see her in
moments of triumph and greatness,'' Hybl said.
</P>
<P>
   Craig Maback, chief executive officer of the U.S. track and
field federation, said that news of the cause of Griffith Joyner's
death ``reaffirms our belief that our focus should be on supporting
her husband, Al, and daughter, Mary Ruth, in their time of need,
and on celebrating what she gave the world in her grace, style and
speed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
