<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-VAUGHN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MO VAUGHN TAKES STEP TOWARD FREE AGENCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In a procedural move clearing the way for him to file
for free agency, Red Sox first baseman Mo Vaughn informed the team
Thursday that he is not exercising the option in his contract for a
1999 salary of $6.75 million, slightly more than the $6.6 million
he was paid this past season.
</P>
<P>
   It actually was a dual option, meaning either the club or the
player could refuse to exercise it. The Red Sox offered him the
option, but there was never a question that Vaughn would refuse it,
and in past negotiations, the Red Sox already had offered Vaughn a
contract extension for far more than the previous option would have
paid.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn was not among the eight players who filed for free agency
Thursday, the first day on which potential free agents could
declare their intentions, but he is expected to do so in the next
few days.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox also are expected to meet with Vaughn's agents
sometime in the next 15 days, the period when players who have
filed for free agency can talk only with their present teams. Sox
officials have been in contact with Vaughn's agents in the
postseason, and GM Dan Duquette, who was in San Diego during the
World Series, broached the possibility of meeting then, but
Vaughn's agent, Tom Reich, was in Pittsburgh on business for his
hockey client, Mario Lemieux.
</P>
<P>
   While it is assumed the Red Sox are preparing another offer for
Vaughn, it appears that the Sox first baseman will not sign until
after he has entertained offers from other clubs. He has said that
since a deal was not struck by now, he intends to see what his
value will be on the open market.
</P>
<P>
   Despite speculation that Vaughn will be pursued vigorously by a
group of teams that may include the Yankees, Dodgers, Angels,
Orioles and perhaps the Rangers, the Red Sox will have their shot,
though at a price nuch higher than the deal they could have had
done last spring, when they insisted Vaughn undergo an alcohol
evaluation.
</P>
<P>
   With such top stars as catcher Mike Piazza, American League
batting champion Bernie Williams and pitchers Kevin Brown and Randy
Johnson eligible for free agency, it seems likely that the $12.5
million average annual value of Pedro Martinez's precedent-setting
contract last winter will be eclipsed.
</P>
<P>
   Other star players eligible to file by the Nov. 5 deadline
include World Series MVP Scott Brosius, Baltimore second baseman
Roberto Alomar and Chicago White Sox third baseman Robin Ventura.
</P>
<P>
   Red Sox pitcher Butch Henry, who missed almost the entire 1998
season after undergoing knee surgery, was one of eight players who
filed for free agency Thursday. That list included former Sox DH
Jose Canseco, who hit 47 homers and drove in 107 runs for Toronto;
Rangers pitcher Todd Stottlemyre; Brewers outfielder Darrin
Jackson; Cardinals outfielder Brian Jordan; Dodgers catcher Tom
Prince; Twins right-hander Bob Tewksbury; and Mariners right-hander
Mike Timlin.
</P>
<P>
   Henry was paid $1.367 million last season after making an
apparently successful comeback from tendon-transfer elbow surgery.
He began the season in the Sox rotation, but made just three starts
before undergoing surgery for a torn ACL, an injury to which he may
have become vulnerable when he pulled a hamstring while running the
bases in a game late in spring training.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox also exercised the $750,000 club option for 1999
they were holding on reliever Jim Corsi, who was the team's most
dependable setup man last season. Corsi, 37, held lefthanded
batters to a .211 average last season and made a career-high 59
appearances. The Red Sox may decide to offer a contract extension
to the Newton native, especially with Dennis Eckersley likely to
retire.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox already offered a two-year deal for around $2.8 million
to lefthanded reliever Greg Swindell, but he turned it down and is
eligible to file for free agency.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
