<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2436 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-YANKS-PARADE-ART-     10-22 0960
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-YANKS-PARADE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR ONE DAY AT LEAST, PEACE WILL PREVAIL AS POLITICIANS PRAISE
YANKEES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(JT) 
 By DAN BARRY    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In his exuberance over the remarkable New York
Yankees season that ended with a World Series championship on
Wednesday night, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has momentarily set aside
his many differences with various politicians - and there are many
_ to invite them all to Friday's Yankees parade that begins at
Battery Park and ends with a reception in front of City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   The most notable beneficiary of the mayor's good cheer is Peter
Vallone. As speaker of the City Council, Vallone might well expect
to be invited to a citywide, apolitical celebration _ but not
necessarily one thrown by the mayor, and particularly not one
centering on the Yankees organization.
</P>
<P>
   Vallone, the Democratic candidate for governor, irked both the
mayor and the Yankees' principal owner, George Steinbrenner, by
promoting _ unsuccessfully, it seems _ a referendum on whether to
use public financing for a new stadium in Manhattan. The mayor
wanted to preserve that option in negotiating to keep the team in
New York, if not in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   One reflection of the mayor's anger over Vallone's maneuver was
to not invite him to a rally at City Hall this summer that honored
David Wells, a Yankees pitcher, for pitching a perfect game.
</P>
<P>
   But victory has a way of breeding generosity. Not only did the
Giuliani administration invite Vallone to Friday's celebration, but
it has included him on the reception's dais, along with various
dignitaries, ballplayers and Yankees officials. A more delicate
matter, perhaps, will be where to seat Vallone in relation to where
Steinbrenner sits, and to where the speaker's opponent, Gov. George
Pataki, sits.
</P>
<P>
   Many other Giuliani adversaries have been invited as well, all
of whom might argue that decorum would require their attendance,
notwithstanding the mayor's mood of the moment. Among others, they
include H. Carl McCall, the state comptroller; Sheldon Silver, the
speaker of the State Assembly; and Mark Green, the city's public
advocate. C. Virginia Fields, the Manhattan borough president, and
Fernando Ferrer, the Bronx borough president _ both of whom have
differed with the mayor over the Yankee Stadium issue _ have also
been invited, along with the city's three other borough presidents.
</P>
<P>
   Many other political leaders that the mayor does get along with,
more or less, have also been invited, including U.S. Sens. Daniel
Patrick Moynihan and Alfonse D'Amato. Moynihan will not be
attending; D'Amato will.
</P>
<P>
   Colleen Roche, Giuliani's press secretary, said that no one
should be surprised by the relatively open invitations, which are
roughly following the etiquette of the city's World Series parade
and reception for the Yankees in 1996. ``This is a time to
celebrate the New York Yankees, arguably the best team in the
history of the game,'' she said. Referring to the mayor's various
political disagreements, she added, ``It's time to put aside those
differences and celebrate.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're my best friends,'' marveled Bruce Bender, Speaker
Vallone's chief of staff, who admitted to expecting some tension
over the Yankees celebration. Instead, he said, the mayor's office
is providing a double-decker bus for Council members who want to
participate in the parade, as well as seats for the reception at
City Hall. ``It worked out well.''
</P>
<P>
   Some suspicious types on the City Council side even speculated,
rather uncharitably, that by being so magnanimous, the mayor was
effectively denying Vallone the sympathetic press coverage that a
mayoral snub might create. But the mayor's aides scoffed at such
speculation, and said, simply, it's a celebration of the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, City Hall looked more like a catering hall before
an elaborate wedding Thursday than a building for the business of
government. City workers set out some 5,000 chairs in the parking
lot, draped red-white-and-blue bunting onto the 1812 building's
facade, and hung a sign thanking the Yankees for their season of
125 victories. The mayor's name appears on the sign, but only on
the bottom, and in significantly smaller type than the rest of the
lettering.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Thursday _ in which reporters watched as
Giuliani promoted flu shots by receiving a shot himself _ the mayor
talked excitedly, and at great length, about the Yankees and the
parade. Among other observations, he said that the Yankees'
manager, Joe Torre, is the best he has ever seen, that this season
exceeded the city's Subway Series of the 1950s in excitement, and
that _ when asked about students cutting classes to attend the
parade _ he probably learned more by playing baseball than by going
to school. ``About life,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why City Hall was being opened to invited guests for the
Yankees event when recent concerns about terrorism have prevented
it from being used for more mundane rallies, Giuliani said that
access will require a ticket, and that security will be extremely
tight. ``The front of the Capitol of the United States is used for
the inauguration of the president, but they do not allow
demonstrations that create insecure problems and issues for the
members,'' he said. ``So this is a common-sense distinction that's
made all over the country.''
</P>
<P>
   By equating a baseball celebration to a presidential
inauguration, Giuliani revealed the giddiness that the Yankees have
been known to bring out in him. He made no apologies: ``I mean,
this is baseball history.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
