<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2437 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHIPPER-IMAGE-COX     10-22 1484
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHIPPER-IMAGE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tarnished golden boy
 &HT;    Many saw him as a role model, but Jones acknowledges `a
hypocritical life'
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   March 4, 1997. A Tuesday evening in Palm Beach. Already an hour
late, a man drives another 15 minutes lost in the dark, winding
through the streets of PGA National before finally finding the
spring-training rental home of one of baseball's most glamorous
young couples. The doorbell rings. The front door opens. And there
are Chipper and Karin Jones, asking, ``Where ya been? We were
worried about you.''
</P>
<P>
   For the next three hours, catching up with the Joneses was a
pleasure. Karin fixed a salad and pasta. Chipper relaxed on the
sofa. Over _ what else? _ a Coke. He recalled his baseball
upbringing in Pierson, Fla., and meteoric rise in the major
leagues; she spoke of their courtship and marriage. Despite the
lingering disappointment of the 1996 World Series, they seemed to
have the world at their bare feet.
</P>
<P>
   In reality, their world was just starting to unravel. That
month, as Jones revealed Wednesday, he began an affair with a
waitress at a Hooter's restaurant in West Palm Beach. The woman
became pregnant and gave birth in March to a son. For Jones, who
has acknowledged paternity and vowed to support the child, it was
one of several extramarital affairs he had after the '96 World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   It has cast Jones, now apologetic and repentant, in a far
different light from his public image. Home and away, he's by far
the most admired, envied and popular Brave. He does more local
endorsements and commercials _ Wendy's, Coca-Cola, a Volvo
dealership, the ``Ask Chipper'' question-and-answer segments on WSB
radio _ than any of his teammates. Teenage girls shriek his name
the way their mothers once shrieked for Paul, John or any of the
Beatles. Until Bobby Cox reprimanded him for outspokeness in a team
meeting before Game 3 of the NLCS, Jones' was the most vocal and
oft-quoted voice in the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   That public voice was stilled until right after Atlanta lost
Game 6. The next time Jones spoke for public consumption was
Wednesday, when he admitted to the Morris News Service that he had
committed adultery and fathered an illegitimate child. He publicly
apologized to his wife, fans and the Braves organization.
</P>
<P>
   Chipper and Karin both said their marriage nearly ended but is
stronger now. Still, that union has been much like the cover photo
shot of a September 1996 Sports Illustrated profile of Chipper: A
roller-coaster ride of emotions from '91, when they first met, to
the giddy heights of celebrity and the '95 World Series title in
his rookie year, to the personal trauma of the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Atlantans were stunned by the news of Jones'
infidelity. It is different from Andruw Jones, a single man
involved in a paternity suit over a child born out of wedlock to an
unmarried woman. Different even from Evander Holyfield, who
admitted after his heavyweight title defense last month that he'd
had two more illegitimate children with two separate women. This is
the golden couple, Chipper and Karin Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Theirs are scenes from a marriage that has been both highly
public and privately painful:
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of '91, Karin Fulford was between her junior and
senior years at Wesleyan College in Macon. Born in Atlanta and
raised in DeKalb County, the daughter of a now-retired DeKalb
juvenile-court judge, she graduated from Tucker High School, class
of '88. Karin was majoring in early childhood education at Wesleyan
and dating Tyler Houston, a catcher for the Macon Braves, Atlanta's
Class A affiliate in the South Atlantic League. She was waiting for
Houston at a Macon sports bar one night in '91 when she met Jones,
the Braves' No. 1 draft pick in 1990 and Macon's new shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I first saw him, he was not my type at all,'' Karin told
The Atlanta Journal-Constitution during the '95 World Series. ``I
was into preppie guys. And he was sitting there wearing a lot of
gold chains and driving a Corvette.''
</P>
<P>
   A shiny black Corvette, with a vanity license tag: CHIP10. To
this day, Chipper Jones signs his autograph by writing his number,
10, in the lower loop of the script J.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there was an immediate attraction,'' Karin recalled. ``We
joked around all night.''
</P>
<P>
   She sensed Jones was too shy to ask her out. So she asked him
for his phone number. He wrote it down on a scrap of paper _ which
Karin still has _ and, eventually, they went out.
</P>
<P>
   Both were blond, good-looking and quickly smitten. When Chipper,
then 19, told his father about the young woman _ two years his
elder _ he'd fallen in love with, Larry Jones was hesitant. But
Chipper said, ``Dad, she's just like Mom.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 12, 1992, Chipper and Karin were married at Mountain
West Church of God in Stone Mountain. After his spectacular 1993
season at Class AAA Richmond, Jones was set to start the '94 season
in left field in Atlanta but tore the anterior cruciate ligament in
his left knee in the last week of spring training and missed that
entire strike-shortened season. The young couple nearly had to sell
their house in Marietta; Karin took a job as a substitute teacher
at Smitha Middle School in Cobb County.
</P>
<P>
   For the Joneses, the world was never better than in 1995. One
night, before Chipper hit a dramatic home run, Karin was captured
on TV spilling a drink while walking up an aisle in Atlanta-Fulton
County Stadium. Both the homer, and the spill, were shown later
that night on ESPN's ``SportsCenter.'' The Joneses saw that and
laughed. The next night, a fan held up a sign in the ballpark: ``If
I Was Married to Chipper Jones, I'd Spill My Drink, Too.''
</P>
<P>
   At season's end, Chipper, the Braves new third baseman, was
runner-up to Hideo Nomo as the NL Rookie of the Year. More
importantly, the Braves won the World Series in six games over
Cleveland. And America came to know both Chipper and Karin.
Sportswriters from around the country likened him to a young Mickey
Mantle. When he caught a popup for the final out of Atlanta's Game
1 win, NBC's TV cameras showed Karin in the stands, wearing her
good-luck white cowboy hat and cheering for Chipper.
</P>
<P>
   The next year, Chipper Jones was an All-Star, hitting .309 with
30 homers and 110 RBIs. His fans were legion. One afternoon during
the '96 season, a Fernandina Beach, Fla., woman named Dot Williams
was in her home when she heard a sing-song coming from the next
room. Quietly, she peeked around the corner to find her daughter,
Anna, 8, singing a parody of Billy Paul's ``Me and Mrs. Jones.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Me-ee-ee-ee and CHIP-per, Chipper Jones, we got a thing going
on. ...'' It seemed everybody, from big-league general managers to
little girls with a crush, was enamored of Mr. Jones. Later that
summer, the Joneses invited the Journal-Constitution into their
home, for an ``At Home With...'' photo shoot and story. The
four-bedroom Marietta house was casual and comfortable. Hoping for
more space and privacy, however, they were considering a move to a
larger house, and have since moved to Country Club of the South.
One with a nursery.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had really hoped to be pregnant by now,'' Karin said then.
``I'm, like, the only Braves wife without kids.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got lots of time,'' Chipper replied.
</P>
<P>
   When the 1996 World Series ended in Yankee Stadium, Chipper
Jones was in the on-deck circle as Mark Lemke popped out to
complete an Atlanta collapse. After taking the first two games in
the Bronx, the Braves lost four in a row. Sometime after that
crushing ending, Jones told Morris on Wednesday, his extra-marital
activity began. ``I was going through a rebellious period where it
didn't matter what Karin said,'' he said. ``I was going to do the
opposite.''
</P>
<P>
   During the second half of the '97 season, rumors of Jones'
extra-marital activity cropped up in the Braves clubhouse. That
August, the club was slumping badly and playing terribly, and Jones
had committed several uncharacteristic base-running blunders and
mental errors. Some players and people in the organization wondered
privately if Jones was distracted by personal problems.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors persisted this season. There were at least two instances
when Jones was heckled at Turner Field. Once was when he was
stepping into the batter's box; after the at-bat, Jones walked to
the stands and confronted the heckler.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the extent of Wednesday's disclosure stunned many. The
Joneses underwent marriage counseling earlier this year. That
alone, Karin said, wasn't enough to convince her the marriage was
worth saving. She nearly left, but has since seen fundamental
changes in her husband. He, too, hopes to atone for ``leading kind
of a hypocritical life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I ask,'' Chipper Jones said, ``for forgiveness.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
