<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 21:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2439 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SMITHKLINE-MARKETPLAC     10-22 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SMITHKLINE-MARKETPLACE-860&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKET PLACE: A TALE OF EXECUTIVES AND EGOS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By DAVID J. MORROW   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jan Leschly, the chief executive of the London-based SmithKline
Beecham, has never been short for words. He's more than willing to
tell you about Paxil, his company's popular anti-depressant, and
how its sales increased 21 percent in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not what Leschly has on his mind these days. He wants
the world to know that he has no intention of retiring early,
regardless of what investors say privately, and of how high his
company's stock has risen _ partly on speculation that he may
leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lots of rumors that I may retire early,'' Leschly
said. ``It is absolutely not true. This is entirely a UK issue,
started by the UK press. People just write too much here in the
UK.''
</P>
<P>
   Leschly's troubles have become a popular topic throughout the
pharmaceutical industry, as well. After watching the falling apart
of three huge drug mergers this year _ attributed largely to a
clash of the chief executives' egos _ investors are scrambling to
find ways to defuse the next boardroom brawl before it can spoil
the deal.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of this controversy are Leschly and John Stafford,
chairman of American Home Products, who have each had two failed
mergers this year. Analysts have attributed the casualties to the
refusal of both executives, in separate deals, to share power.
</P>
<P>
   ``After the merger between American Home Products and Monsanto
fell apart last week, there has been increasing speculation about
what decisions the top-level executives should be allowed to
make,'' said Viren Mehta, a partner at Mehta Partners, a
biopharmaceutical investment firm. ``We may never know the number
of mergers that have gone sour because of people issues, because
most of the deals die before they become public.''
</P>
<P>
   Investors and analysts have been toying with ways to prod a
chief executive to forget his ego and complete whatever deal is
pending. While some analysts think Stafford and Leschly have acted
responsibly in aborting their merger, others are far from
convinced.
</P>
<P>
   Several big institutional investors in Britain seem suspicious
of Leschly's intentions. According to analysts, investors including
Mercury Asset Management are so annoyed by Leschly's aborted merger
with Glaxo Wellcome that they have asked SmithKline's board to buy
him out.
</P>
<P>
   Mercury, along with two other large British investors _
Prudential Portfolio Management and Scottish Widows Investment
Management _ declined to comment. A spokesman for SmithKline denied
that Leschly was about to be asked to leave.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for American Home Products said its aborted merger
with Monsanto had nothing to do with Stafford personally but was a
mutual decision by both boards.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the talk of removing Leschly has touched off an
interesting debate. By allowing a chief executive to block a merger
for personal reasons, the company's directors are putting the
bosses' interests over those of the shareholders. Yet jettisoning a
chief executive who refuses to share power could rob the company of
a savvy leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``The board members have to think if the strategy they choose is
going to help the company,'' said James Westphal, an assistant
professor of management at the University of Texas. ``You don't
want to throw out a chief executive just because of a failed
merger. That's only one part of his job.''
</P>
<P>
   So how does a board know when it's time for the boss to leave?
Management consultants say the ideal test is to see what happens to
the company's shares when news of that likelihood hits the market.
</P>
<P>
   The reaction could be startling. In the late 1980s, the
departure of Occidental Petroleum's chairman, Armand Hammer, had
been so much anticipated that the company's stock went up after
Hammer once slipped in the shower.
</P>
<P>
   If the stock price is a gauge for dismissal, Stafford won't be
leaving any time soon. Shares of American Home Products are up 26.8
percent this year, even after investors took profits earlier this
week. Leschly may not be so fortunate. A person who snapped up
SmithKline shares in London two weeks ago would be 20 percent
richer on speculation about Leschly's imminent departure and a
resulting merger with Glaxo Wellcome.
</P>
<P>
   Still, fans of Leschly and Stafford think that the two are well
worth the headaches their botched mergers have caused. Analysts
point out that Stafford has expanded American Home Products _ the
company bought American Cyanamid, the maker of Centrum vitamins,
four years ago _ and has introduced several promising new drugs
including Rota Shield, a vaccine against rotavirus, the most common
cause of severe diarrhea in children.
</P>
<P>
   Leschly has stocked SmithKline's pharmaceuticals pipeline. The
company has several potential blockbusters under development,
including Avandia for diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Leschly may have lost some credibility with the unsuccessful
mergers, but no one wants to see him leave,'' said Nigel Barnes of
Merrill Lynch in London. ``It wasn't just Leschly with the aborted
merger to Glaxo; it was the entire management team. And who could
think SmithKline and Glaxo will merge now? There's no way they
would trust each other.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   When SmithKline reported its third-quarter earnings on Tuesday,
Leschly said he would not retire early or be forced out. But
analysts say that the hatchet is far more likely to hit Leschly
than Stafford, mainly because of where their companies are based.
</P>
<P>
   British institutional investors generally have more influence
over domestic companies than their American counterparts do. They
often take larger positions in their home companies and are vocal
about getting the greatest return possible.
</P>
<P>
   Management experts were split on what path SmithKline's board
would ultimately take. Some thought it would allow Leschly to make
his own decision, virtually ensuring his tenure, while others said
he could go, given the positive reaction the stock price has had to
such an outcome.
</P>
<P>
   But there is room for compromise. Leschly could reopen merger
discussions with Glaxo Wellcome, a move that would give investors
substantial short-term gains. When Glaxo announced its intention to
merge with SmithKline at the end of January, the company's American
depository receipts rose 16.6 percent in one day.
</P>
<P>
   Not even rumors of Leschly's leaving have been able to produce
that kind of gain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
