<HEADLINE>
AT LEAST 100 BOEING PLANES IN PRODUCTION NEED REPLACEMENT PARTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ At least 100 airplanes now in various stages of
production at Boeing's Renton and Everett plants have suspect
electrical connectors that must be replaced, and the time-consuming
work has only just started, the company said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   It was an acknowledgment of the seriousness of its latest
assembly-line problem.
</P>
<P>
   Planes on the flight lines at both locations that are in
pre-delivery testing have been grounded until they can be inspected
and, if necessary, the suspect parts replaced.
</P>
<P>
   So far, however, no planes have been delivered late to customers
because of the parts problem, a Boeing spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   President Harry Stonecipher, in a conference call with reporters
to discuss the company's third quarter results, said airplane
warranty reserves will be used to cover the unexpected costs and
earnings will not be affected. He declined to estimate those costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have very little idea how big this is,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Post-Intelligencer disclosed Wednesday that wire shop
testing had found a high failure rate in a batch of 18,000
electrical connectors known as ``Burndy blocks'' that Boeing
received from one of its suppliers. The problem involved a cracked
conductive plate inside the blocks.
</P>
<P>
   Connectors from the suspect shipment were installed on planes in
Everett and in Renton, though none were delivered to customers,
Boeing said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Federal Aviation Administration, which has
quality control inspectors at Boeing's plants, said the agency is
aware of the problem, but because no planes with the suspect parts
are believed to be in service it does not consider the matter a
serious safety issue.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is serious for Boeing, though, as it struggles to
recover from a series of production woes that caused profits to
tumble and planes to be delivered late to customers. The company is
under the gun to to deliver 550 planes by the end of the year, but
it is running behind schedule and anything that disrupts or
threatens production is cause for concern.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing does not know precisely which planes have the potentially
faulty parts, so every 747, 777 and 767 jet in production in
Everett must be inspected, as well as all next generation 737s in
production in Renton.
</P>
<P>
   Those inspections can take take upwards of 5 hours per plane,
depending on the model.
</P>
<P>
   The part in question provides a connection for the miles of
electrical wiring in an airplane. The small connector, about 1 inch
by 3/4 inch, is used to transmit power voltage or as a ground.
</P>
<P>
   The number of these connectors in a Boeing plane varies widely,
depending on the model. A 777, for example, has 380 Burndy blocks.
A 747 has only 10 and a 767 has six. The next generation 737, the
plane most effected by Boeing's previous production difficulties,
has 570 Burndy blocks.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview with the Post-Intelligencer Tuesday night, Wolf
Glende, Boeing's chief engineer for 777 systems, said most planes
in Renton and in Everett had been inspected and the suspect parts
replaced.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not the case, the company acknowledged Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing spokeswoman Yvonne Leach said all planes in Everett have
been inspected and about 35 were found to have the suspect
connectors. But only five have actually had the parts removed and
replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Workers are first removing suspect parts in planes on the flight
line, then they will work their way down the assembly lines, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not flying any planes with these defective parts,'' she
said. ``But so far, we have not had any late deliveries because of
this problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Inspections in Renton are only about 30 percent complete, she
said. It's believed about 60 to 65 planes there have the suspect
parts. But as of Thursday, workers had replaced the suspect Burndy
blocks in fewer than 5 planes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a lot of people working this issue,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   A Boeing source who is familiar with the parts problem said the
company's estimate that only about 100 planes are effected ``is
very low.'' The final tally will be significantly more, this person
said.
</P>
<P>
   And even though no planes have been delivered late to customers
because of the parts problem, this person said workers had to
scramble Thursday to yank defective Burndy blocks from a 777 on the
flight line in Everett so it could be turned over to the customer
later in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Leach said Boeing has enough non-defective Burndy blocks on hand
to avoid delays in getting more connectors from the sole-source
supplier.
</P>
<P>
   About 700 of the connectors are used each day on Boeing's
production lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are working closely with our supplier and they can supply
us with about 800 connectors a day,'' she said. That will increase
to about 1,300 a day by next week, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Mulally, who replaced Ron Woodard as head of Boeing's Commercial
Airplane Group Sept. 1 in a management shakeup, said the parts
problem is not expected to throw the company's current production
schedule off track.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have assured ourselves that the next month's plan looks
good,'' he said. ``We have enough parts in the production line to
support production. These things happen and they are always hard,
but we feel like this is a manageable situation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
