<HEADER>
A2443 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-CHIPPER1ADULTERY-     10-22 0569
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-CHIPPER1ADULTERY-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves' Jones tells of affair, illigitimate child
 &HT;    WITH PHOTO; BBO-CHIPPER-IMAGE; BBO-CHIPPER-FALLEN
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Braves third baseman Chipper Jones shocked the state
Wednesday with the revelation that he fathered an illegitimate
child during a binge of extra-marital activity that began two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The affair nearly ended his six-year marriage with his wife,
Karin, and left Jones living a duplicitous life as wholesome
baseball personality on the outside and fretting philanderer on the
inside. Although Jones has pledged to support the child, born seven
months ago, and has patched up his relationship with his wife
through counseling, the shock waves rippled through the same town
that only last month was stunned by another paternity confession
from heavyweight boxing champion Evander Holyfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, I had to make a decision on what the most important
thing in my life was,'' Jones told Morris News Service reporter
Bill Zack. ``The most important thing was Karin. So, in order to
keep Karin around, I had to make changes.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who is on a hunting trip in central Georgia, did not
return repeated telephone messages Thursday, and his Alpharetta
home was dark and locked Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The news was hardly welcomed at the Braves' front offices, where
another front-line player, Andruw Jones, who is single, already has
been subject to a paternity suit this year. The public clamor over
the team's early elimination from the postseason, fanned by some
flippant comments from Chipper Jones, had begun to subside, only to
be replaced by a larger public-relations concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever those concerns may be, they are insignificant next to
my concerns for Chipper and Karin,'' club President Stan Kasten
said. ``That's all I really care about.''
</P>
<P>
   It already was an important offseason for Jones, whose four-year
contract with the Braves expires after next season. Jones, who made
$2.5 million last season, is one year short of free-agent
eligibility and is seeking a long-term deal that could more than
triple his salary.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the revelations could jeopardize contract discussions,
Kasten replied, ``I just don't think it's appropriate to connect
the two issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones told Morris he had several sexual flings after the Braves'
1996 World Series and that he befriended a waitress in West Palm
Beach during 1997 spring training. The waitress later became
pregnant. The woman and the child are living in Michigan with her
parents. Details on legal support have not been completed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going through a pretty rebellious period where, it
didn't matter what Karin said, I was going to do the opposite,''
Jones said. ``I was really self-absorbed. I was going to go out and
do what I wanted to do. I was so self-absorbed there for a while,
the only thing that mattered was self-satisfaction.''
</P>
<P>
   He informed Karin of the situation last winter, and the couple
has worked since to reconcile the marriage. But the
public-relations hit is not so easily repaired, given Jones' image
and vast following among school-age fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be a better role model,'' Jones told Morris. ``I
don't want to be what I've been the first four or five years of my
major-league career.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
