<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIH-FUNDING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NIH BUDGET GETS $2 BILLION BOOST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By AARON ZITNER  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a sharply partisan year that saw tobacco and
health insurance legislation falter, Congress and President Clinton
united with little fanfare behind another major health initiative:
the biggest boost ever in research funding for the National
Institutes of Health.
</P>
<P>
   That is good news for Massachusetts, which gets more in NIH
grants than any state but California. If past trends hold, about 10
percent of the $15.6 billion NIH budget that Clinton signed into
law Wednesday will find its way to Massachusetts laboratories.
Money sent to other states could wind up paying for equipment and
biotechnology products purchased from Boston's large cluster of
high-tech firms.
</P>
<P>
   The money may also help pay overhead costs for several Boston
research hopsitals that are planning new laboratory buildings.
Boston University and the Boston Medical Center are developing as
much as 16 acres of research space off Albany Street, and Tufts
University has proposed 180,000 square feet on Harrison Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a period of grant growth, we &UR;  &LR; know we'll be able to pay the
mortgage,'' said Dr. Jeffrey Gelfand, dean for research at Tufts
University School of Medicine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't remember a time when people have been as optimistic
about the future of biomedical research,'' said Dr. Deborah Cotton,
clinical research director at BU Medical Center. ``For many years,
we've had more ideas and more investigators than could be funded.
We think that will change now because of this new money.''
</P>
<P>
   Lobbyists for the new NIH money included an unusual mix of
characters, including Fidelity Investments guru Peter Lynch,
political columnist Morton Kondracke, and Boston attorney Arthur
Ullian, a spinal cord injury patient who has become a leading
advocate of research on the nervous system.
</P>
<P>
   But many lawmakers were ready to spend more on research even
before the lobbyists launched their campaign. From Senator Edward
Kennedy to House Speaker Newt Gingrich, lawmakers say this year's
increase is only a down payment on a plan to double the nation's
research spending within eight years.
</P>
<P>
   The $2 billion boost in the NIH budget, which amounts to a 15
percent increase, was part of a broad commitment by Congress to
scientific research in fiscal year 1999, which began Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   At the Defense Department, basic research spending has fallen
for five years when inflation is considered. This year, it will
rise 6 percent, a potential boon for math and computer science
programs at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. The
Department of Energy, another major sponsor of MIT programs, will
spend 8 percent more on research. Research funding at the National
Science Foundation will rise 8.8 percent, compared to 3 and 4
percent gains in the prior two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the year of NIH,'' said Christopher Jennings, health
policy adviser to Clinton. ``In this year of partisanship, this was
one of the few issues that was nonpartisan.''
</P>
<P>
   Advocates argue for more scientific research every year, but a
variety of factors made the sale easy this time.
</P>
<P>
   To begin with, the federal government enjoyed a $71 billion
surplus in the fiscal year that ended Sept. 30, allowing Congress
more latitude in funding new programs without stripping money from
other parts of the government.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, NIH grants go to a variety of congressional
districts, giving a large number of lawmakers a reason to support
the agency. ``I don't think this is as strategic as some of the
Department of Defense funding has been,'' said Jennings, referring
to the practice of making components for a weapons system in
various states to win greater political support. ``But I'm not
naive enough to suggest this has no relevance.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, new research funding gave Republicans an opportunity
to support a health program in a year when Democrats chastised them
for opposing the ``Patients Bill of Rights.'' That bill would have
given patients new powers when fighting insurers to cover medical
treatment. Pollsters said the bill was popular with voters, but
Republicans said it would raise costs and impose unreasonable
requirements on insurers, who are also major campaign contributors.
</P>
<P>
   By supporting health research, lawmakers of both parties were
able to tell voters they were working to improve health care.
``Talk about being able to connect with peoples' concerns: There is
not a family in American that you can't touch when you talk about
cancer, Parkinson's disease, Alzheimer's,'' said Senator Connie
Mack, a Florida Republican who wants to double NIH funding within
five years. ``It's just a natural thing for us to be doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The campaign for a substantial increase in NIH funding began at
least as early as 1994, the year Republicans took control of
Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Reliable supporters of medical research, such as Senator Mark
Hatfield, Republican of Oregon, were about to retire, and lobbyists
were hearing that budgets were becoming tighter. ``We were afraid
we had lost our champions, and the Contract with America might be
cause for deep budget cuts,'' said Kevin Casey, director of federal
and state relations for Harvard University.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard and other universities had already formed a group called
The Science Coalition to lobby for research funding, and fear of
budget cuts swelled the group from 15 members to about 40.
</P>
<P>
   The coalition was not the only group to call for a new
commitment to research. Another organization called ``NIH x 2''
began arguing that the NIH budget should be doubled. Kondracke,
whose wife has Parkinson's disease, helped promote the group and
wrote about the campaign for medical research funding several times
in the political newspaper Roll Call. In his columns, Kondracke
disclosed his personal interest in the issue.
</P>
<P>
   From Boston, Ullian and his colleagues arranged a meeting with
Jennings, the White House health adviser, to lobby for more money.
They also helped organize a Capitol Hill event last summer where
Lynch, the Fidelity stock-picking ace, argued that medical research
benefits the broader economy.
</P>
<P>
   But many lawmakers, such as Kennedy, were already on board. Mack
says the Republican Senate conference backed new research money as
early as January 1997. And according to Casey of Harvard, when
Ullian, Kondracke, Lynch and others met with Gingrich last summer,
the House speaker said he supported new funding, though he wanted
the federal commitment to include math, physics and other fields,
not just medical research.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone, however, is pleased with the idea of doubling the
NIH budget over five years. ``There's no way they could spend that
money responsibly,'' said Stephen Moore of the Cato Institute, a
Libertarian think tank. ``It would be like the Department of
Defense in the early 1980s. They'd be spending $500 for a single
hammer.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
