<SLUG> BC-CRIME-VOTER-REPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
1.4 MILLION BLACK MEN DISENFRANCHISED, REPORT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Maine, Mass., Utah, Vt., Ala., Fla., Iowa, Miss., N.M., Va.,
Wash., Wyo.) (mk) 
 By TAMAR LEWIN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nationwide, 1.4 million African-American men _ 13 percent of all
black men _ cannot vote because of their criminal records,
according to a report made public Thursday by Human Rights Watch
and the Sentencing Project, two nonprofit research and advocacy
groups.
</P>
<P>
   Every state except Maine, Massachusetts, Utah and Vermont denies
prisoners the right to vote. And 15 states bar former felons from
voting even after they have served their sentences; 10 of them
impose lifetime disenfranchisement on anyone convicted of a felony.
</P>
<P>
   In Alabama and Florida, nearly one in every three black men is
permanently disenfranchised, and in Iowa, Mississippi, New Mexico,
Virginia, Washington and Wyoming, the ratio is about one in four.
</P>
<P>
   ``The proportions in some black communities are so large now
that we've reached the point where this is an issue that can
potentially affect some elections,'' said Marc Mauer, assistant
director of The Sentencing Project, and co-author of the report.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a basic question of democratic rights and societal
inclusion,'' Mauer added. ``Given our low rate of voter
participation, we should be looking for ways to encourage people to
vote, not locking them out.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the country, 3.9 million men and women of all races are
disenfranchised, according to the report, the first state-by-state
analysis of criminal disenfranchisement. Of those, nearly 1.4
million are former offenders who have completed their criminal
sentence, another 1.4 million are on probation or parole, and more
than a million are in prison.
</P>
<P>
   But the report cautioned that all numbers should be considered
estimates, since necessary data at the state level were often
incomplete or available only for selected years.
</P>
<P>
   In theory, former offenders can regain the right to vote in
states where reinstatement is not automatic, usually by order of
the governor or action of the parole or pardons board. But in
practice, the report said, that rarely happens: In Virginia, for
example, where every felon loses the right to vote for life, and
only the governor can restore it, only 404 of the state's 200,000
ex-convicts have had their voting rights restored in the last two
years.
</P>
<P>
   According to the report, no other democracy denies as many
people, either in absolute or proportionate terms, the right to
vote because of their criminal records.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the very least, it seems to me that the states that
permanently disenfranchise ex-offenders should reconsider those
policies,'' Mauer said, ``not only because they are so racially
discriminatory, but because they fly in the face of the idea that
once you've paid your debt to society, you should be able to take
your place back in the community.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-98 2132EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
