<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATL-GLENNCLASS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia students earn stake in shuttle mission
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook and Diane R. Stepp
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARIETTA, Ga. _ Does your chewing gum lose its flavor on the
Shuttle overnight? Does your popcorn pop or crayons melt when they
fly into outer space?
</P>
<P>
   These are things inquisitive second-grade students at Dowell
Elementary School in Marietta want to know, and NASA is going to
help them get the answers.
</P>
<P>
   As part of the space agency's student education program, the
class is among eight others in the nation whose experiments were
chosen to fly aboard next week's nine-day shuttle mission, the one
that will carry former astronaut John Glenn back into space.
</P>
<P>
   For the past several days, an NBC film crew has been at the
Marietta school taping the students as they prepare for their
high-flying experiment.
</P>
<P>
   The network will be broadcasting live from the school next
Thursday when the shuttle lifts off. (cq ds) The student's
experiment, which NASA has dubbed ``Effects of Microgravity on an
Object's Physical Characteristics,'' will fly in a container in the
shuttle's cargo bay. Inside the container will be 20 vials
containing a variety of everyday items: chewing gum, popcorn,
bread, stickers, paper clips, chalk, crayons and bubble wrap.
</P>
<P>
   ``The objects will be examined by the students after the vials
fly in the shuttle to see if there are any changes,'' said
assistant principal Denise Feezor.
</P>
<P>
   Dowell's experiment was selected by NASA after first-grade
teacher Andrea Apple submitted her class' proposal over the
Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Preparations for the experiment began last year, when the
students were in the first grade. In science class, they had been
chewing gum and doing taste tests to see how quickly the gum runs
out of flavor. Chewed gum and some unchewed gum will fly on board
the shuttle, and the students will check the unused gum to see if
its flavor is depleted after flying in space.
</P>
<P>
   The students will also send popped popcorn and unpopped popcorn
on the shuttle to see if the unpopped corn loses any of its
explosive properties. They also want to see if microgravity and
being closer to the sun has any effect on crayons and chalk.
</P>
<P>
   Dowell third-graders have also built a replica of the Friendship
7 space capsule in which Glenn became the first American to orbit
the earth in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   Stepping back for a critical view of the nearly life-sized
model, third-grader Kimberlee Chauncey, 8, announced her assessment
of Glenn's first ride into space: ``He must have been really
squished and scared, but happy that he was going.''
</P>
<P>
   ``These kids are used to seeing (the movie) `Apollo 13' and
don't realize how little room there was on the early space
capsules,'' said third-grade teacher Dorrie Harrell, who was
herself a third-grader in Texas when she and her classmates watched
Glenn lift off.
</P>
<P>
   Alexia Holdiman, 8, thought it noteworthy that Glenn had lights
on the tips of his gloves to help him see the instrument panel on
his first ride and that the early spacecraft had no computers.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Hord, 8, has a word of advice for Glenn. ``I hope you have
a safe trip. Just be careful not to run out of fuel or oxygen.''
</P>
<P>
   The kids are hoping to meet their hero in person. He's been
invited to visit Dowell in March, said Feezor.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
