<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-2ap1023a </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cops compare hotel slayings
 &HT;    By Lyda Longa and Mark Bixler
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A motel slaying in College Park that occurred just two days
before the weekend triple murder at an upscale downtown Atlanta
hotel has investigators from both agencies comparing notes to
determine whether they are related.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Police Maj. Mickey Lloyd said Thursday Atlanta
investigators contacted College Park this week to discuss the Oct.
15 fatal shooting at a Days Inn on Old National Highway and the
Oct. 18 triple, execution-style murders at the Atlanta Hilton &AMP;
Towers on Courtland Street.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've talked to them and we've met with them to talk about the
cases,'' Lloyd said. ``We haven't ruled anything out.''
</P>
<P>
   Gerrold Shropshire of Altamonte Springs, Fla., Ronnie Gutkowski
of Leesburg, Fla., and Phillip Dover of Gainesville, were found
shot in the back of the head in room 2414 of the Hilton early
Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Deputy Chief C.B. Jackson has said the men probably were
shot sometime after midnight on Sunday in a hotel that was only
half-occupied.
</P>
<P>
   There was no forced entry to the cramped, cream-colored room,
which overlooks two tennis courts and the city's skyline.
</P>
<P>
   College Park Detective David O'Neal said his case bears some
similarities to Atlanta's.
</P>
<P>
   In that case, 19-year-old Ladaris Hawkins was shot in the face
with a handgun after he either let someone into his motel room or
perhaps gave someone a key. O'Neal said Hawkins, who lived at the
hotel, was found on his bed, but did not die until he arrived at
the hospital. Crack cocaine also was found in Hawkins' underwear,
O'Neal said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was a robbery-homicide,'' O'Neal said. ``The victim
didn't have a wallet on him. We believe he may have been awoken by
this person.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal would not discuss other similarities between the two
incidents. The victims' bodies also have been released to the
families for funerals, the Fulton County Medical Examiner's Office
said. Blood samples to determine whether the victims had drugs and
alcohol in their systems have been sent to the GBI.
</P>
<P>
   Dover's funeral was Thursday. Mourners in Central Florida plan
to say goodbye to Gutkowski, 51, and Shropshire, 50, in services
this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators in Atlanta asked their counterparts in Central
Florida this week to look into the background of Gutkowski and
Shropshire, and a search turned up no evidence that Florida police
have had dealings with either man.
</P>
<P>
   Capt. Don Gregory of the Lake County Sheriff's Department said
their search for any police contact yielded results that jibe with
descriptions from friends and relatives that Gutkowski and
Shropshire were family men who went to church and steered clear of
trouble. ``We have no indication of these gentlemen being involved
in anything,'' Gregory said Wednesday. ``We've done a complete
history.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
