<SLUG> BC-BOEING-EARNS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOEING EARNINGS BEAT EXPECTATIONS, BUT COMPANY WARNS OF TROUBLE
AHEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.1998 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ The Boeing Co. Thursday announced third-quarter
earnings that were better than Wall Street had expected, but
company executives warned that the unsettled financial crisis in
Asia will mean fewer orders and lower production rates by the year
2000, and possibly sooner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our biggest concern going forward is that the economic crisis
in Asia is more severe and more prolonged than previously
anticipated,'' Alan Mulally, who replaced Ron Woodard as head of
the Commercial Airplane Group on Sept. 1, said in a conference call
with industry analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Scheduled production rates are being assessed, and downward
revisions are expected to be made based on customer requirements,''
he added.
</P>
<P>
   Mulally also said that Boeing still has 34 planes in desert
storage. Many of those were intended for Asian customers who can no
longer afford to buy them, or no longer want them as fleets are
reduced. But most will have to find homes if the company is to meet
its year-end goal of delivering 550 planes.
</P>
<P>
   To reach that number, Boeing must deliver 182 planes in the
fourth quarter. The company has never before delivered that many
airplanes in one quarter, Mulally said. Boeing delivered 374 planes
last year.
</P>
<P>
   Getting planes delivered between now and the end of the year is
so critical that Boeing said Thursday it has delayed from Nov. 2
until March 1998 the next phase of implementing its billion-dollar
production overhaul initiative known as DCAC/MRM. It is intended to
improve efficiencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason is simple,'' Mulally said of the delay in a
management information bulletin sent to Boeing workers. ``Each time
we implement a phase of DCAC/MRM, we disrupt factory operations
because people must learn new processes and we must transition to
new computing systems. We can't afford that during this busy
time.''
</P>
<P>
   In the conference call with analysts, followed by one with
reporters, Boeing executives said they remain convinced they can
reach their 550-plane forecast.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Nisbet, an analyst with JSA Research, said even if Boeing
does not make its 550-plane goal, it probably will not hurt
earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe they will give it the old college try and make
it,'' he said. ``But it's not critical unless they miss it by a
large amount. ... Regardless of whether they make it to the last
plane, they are still going to be up around $1 a share profit, and
maybe better.''
</P>
<P>
   For the third quarter, Boeing reported a net profit of $347
million, or 36 cents a share. The earnings reflected a tax credit
of 6 cents a share. Analysts surveyed by First Call Corp. had
estimated operating earnings at 27 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues rose 12 percent to $12.72 billion from $11.37 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Commercial airplanes accounted for 61 percent of revenues but
just $77 million in operating income in the latest quarter. Defense
and space operations accounted for 38 percent of revenues and $362
million in operating income.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing's shares closed Thursday at $36 7/16 on the New York
Stock Exchange, up 7/16.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Boeing lost $696 million in the third quarter after
taking a $1 billion charge to offset production problems.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing Chairman Phil Condit said the company forecasts $56
billion in revenue and just over $1 billion in net earnings for
1998. Revenues should be about the same in 1999, but profits should
be about $2 billion, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing is now reviewing the impact Asia will have on future
airplane orders and current production rates, and will announce the
results later in the quarter, Mulally said.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Boeing estimated it and other manufacturers would lose
up to 150 airplane orders over the next three years because of
Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think it's going to be much higher than the 150,'' Mulallay
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing recently increased production of its next generation 737
from 14 to 21 planes per month. That will go to 24 per month in the
second quarter next year, Mulally said.
</P>
<P>
   But Boeing plans to cut production of its 747 from 5 per month
to 3.5 per month in the second quarter, and slash 777 production
from 7 a month to 5 in the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Any change in those previously announced rates are unlikely
until well into next year, Condit said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we will see significant changes to the 1999
numbers,'' he said, but added. ``There will be a significant effect
on the year 2000.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
