<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUKE-DUMP-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERMIT DENIED FOR LOW-LEVEL NUCLEAR WASTE DUMP NEAR MEXICAN BORDER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BARRY SHLACHTER 
c.1998 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ A state commission unanimously denied a license
for a proposed radioactive waste dump near the West Texas village
of Sierra Blanca on Thursday, eliciting whoops from grassroots
activists who had fought the proposal for more than five years.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately, promoters of a site in Andrews County, near New
Mexico's jutting corner into West Texas, began handling out flyers
extolling their location as a site for the dump that would handle
low-level radioactive waste from nuclear plants, hospitals and
other industries. The Andrews County site is owned by Dallas
millionaire Harold Simmons and ex-Railroad Commissioner Kent Hance.
</P>
<P>
   The three Texas Natural Resource Conservation Commission
members, all appointees of Gov. George W. Bush, cited insufficient
analyses of a geological fault under the 250-acre Sierra Blanca
site and of the project's social and economic impact as reasons for
denying the license.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the weightiest matter we've dealt with in three
years,'' said commission chairman Barry R. McBee, explaining that
his vote was based on a recommendation by two administrative
judges.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to know enough, scientifically, to have a reasonable
assurance'' that the site would be safe, McBee said.
</P>
<P>
   Stunned officials of the Texas Low-Level Radioactive Waste
Disposal Authority reacted by publicly weighing their options.
These include appealing to a state district court, asking the
Legislature to allow it to re-address the geological and
socioeconomic complaints, or seeking another site.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real issue is, what are we going to do with our
radioactive waste?'' said Doug Caroom, lawyer for the authority.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas Legislature created the waste disposal authority in
1981 to develop and operate a waste facility. The authority looked
at several sites in West Texas before settling on the Sierra Blanca
location in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   An agreement with Maine and Vermont would have allowed those
states to ship radioactive waste to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   During Thursday's final arguments on the Sierra Blanca site, the
administrative judges said basic questions about the geological
fault's length and whether it extended to faults in
earthquake-prone areas were not fully answered.
</P>
<P>
   Backers of the proposed dump responded by saying the geological
fault hadn't shifted in at least 750,000 years. Even in a worst
case scenario in which the 5-inch-thick, concrete canisters of
radioactive waste somehow ``crumbled into dust,'' no contamination
would leave the site, they asserted.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout most of the session, McBee maintained courtroom-like
decorum by cautioning the 250 spectators not to cheer or make any
noise. When he announced that the license was denied, dump
opponents burst into whoops and shouts.
</P>
<P>
   Anti-nuke activists who had devoted years to the struggle
against the site loosened their neckties and pony tails and hugged.
Pro-dump Sierra Blancans quickly slipped away.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a victory for the people _ but we'll still be wary of
what they do next,'' said Erin Rogers, director of the Sierra
Blanca Legal Defense Fund which spearheaded the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so excited I can hardly talk. Now I feel I can live a
normal life,'' said Gloria Addington, who owns a store in Sierra
Blanca.
</P>
<P>
   To win over the impoverished, predominantly Hispanic community
90 miles east of El Paso, project promoters spent millions planting
sod for the first time on the high school football field for the
six-man ``Vaqueros'' squad, providing a clinic and a library, and
delivering a new ambulance and fire truck.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sierra Blancans can keep them _ things that they should have
had in the first place,'' Rogers said.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, a score of Mexican children from a Chihuahuan dance
troupe twirled joyfully to thunderous drums. Ten visiting members
from Mexico's federal Congress gave non-stop interviews via
cellular phones. The Congress had publicly opposed the dump site,
which is only 20 miles from the Rio Grande, although Mexico's
executive branch had sent mixed signals.
</P>
<P>
   Political pressure was never hinted at during the hearing, but
Dr. Milton Guiberteau, the waste disposal authority chairman,
conceded that it hovered, invisibly, throughout.
</P>
<P>
   Sierra Blanca became an issue in the state's most heated
political race _ for lieutenant governor _ when Democrat John Sharp
voiced opposition to the proposal during a campaign swing. During
the gubernatorial debate in El Paso, Democrat Garry Mauro came out
flatly against the site and Bush said it wouldn't be built if the
site was unsafe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was politics which put it there and it was politics that
took it away,'' said state Sen. Eliot Shapleigh, an El Paso
Democrat. ``The emotional, heart-felt campaign shows that the issue
of siting it in West Texas was what caused the decision by this
commission.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
