<DOCNO> NYT19981022.0506 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 22:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2497 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NRA23-COX     10-22 0496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NRA23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NRA opposition to gun law grows
 &HT;    By Jenny Staletovich
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ The National Rifle Association has
expanded its opposition from the state's proposed gun law to the
entire list of revisions on the November ballot.
</P>
<P>
   In a flier urging Florida voters to reject a revision giving
counties control over gun shows, the NRA also opposed eight other
changes they dub ``Tricks and Deceptions in Revisions 5-13.''
</P>
<P>
   The group sent 5,000 fliers to its Palm Beach County affiliate
this week, president George Russum said.
</P>
<P>
   The flier is a meager campaign compared to the intense lobbying
waged by former NRA president Marion Hammer earlier this year when
the revision commission first began considering the gun law change.
Some expected the group to spend as much as $10 million, but in
recent weeks, speculation put the amount at as little as $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   National NRA officials did not return phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   In major television markets, station sales representatives said
they still had not heard from the group and time is running out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's beyond booked up. The boat's sinking. They can preempt
someone else, but it's crazy,'' said Jay Burmer, a sales rep at
WFLA in Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   The flier attacks the 37-member commission, which started
studying the Constitution in 1997 and drafted the revisions after a
series of public hearings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way they've got them grouped together and the way you'll
see them on the ballot, you don't have any idea what you're voting
on,'' Russum said. ``We're just recommending they shoot down the
entire thing,''
</P>
<P>
   Russum plans to mail the fliers to local members and hand them
out ``wherever we can buttonhole people.''
</P>
<P>
   But Dexter Douglass, chairman of the commission and former
general counsel to Gov. Lawton Chiles, said the flier
``irresponsible'' and inaccurate.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least they're consistent. They're against everything that's
good,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Douglass pointed out that the commission, made up of both
Republicans and Democrats, devised the groupings in an attempt to
make the ballot understandable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just not the case that anybody wants the public to go in
blindly and vote yes,'' he said. ``Our job on the commission was to
inform people about what's in it and not just to vote. We haven't
run campaigns to tell people to vote yes or no.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters say the NRA is attacking all the revisions because
the gun law has received overwhelming support, with some polls
showing 80 percent favor it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's apparent to us they can't defeat the amendment on its own
merits, so they're just going for the general scare,'' said Don
Ungurait, assistant to Miami Dade State Attorney Katherine
Fernandez Rundle, who sponsored the gun revision. ``We expected
exactly that attack. We expected that kind of tactic and they have
not disappointed us.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
