<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   RALLY IN BLUE-CHIP STOCKS EXTENDS TO SEVENTH DAY
</P>
<P>
   Blue-chip stocks rallied late in the day, pushing the Dow Jones
industrial average higher for a seventh consecutive session. The
Dow rose 13.91 points, to 8,533.14. The broader Standard &AMP; Poor's
500-stock index rose 8.56 points, to 1,078.48.
</P>
<P>
   The technology-heavy Nasdaq composite index continued its climb,
jumping 1.67 percent, or 27.89 points, to 1,702.64. It has
increased nearly 20 percent since Oct. 8.
</P>
<P>
   BOEING BEATS ANALYSTS' ESTIMATES
</P>
<P>
   Boeing reported higher-than-expected third-quarter earnings, but
warned that the turmoil in Asia would cause it to lose more
airplane orders than it had previously estimated.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA EXPECTED TO CLOSE TRUSTS
</P>
<P>
   As signs of financial trouble in China's trust and investment
companies come to light, bankers and economists say they expect the
Chinese authorities to close dozens more debt-ridden financial
houses.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT IS BEST FOR THE COMPANY?
</P>
<P>
   Three huge drug mergers have fallen apart this year largely
because of a clash in the chief executives' egos. Should a board
dismiss the executive and merge?
</P>
<P>
   TELEGROUP CONSIDERING A TAKEOVER
</P>
<P>
   Telegroup, a small international telephone carrier that was
flying high six months ago, is on the verge of running out of cash
and is weighing takeover offers.
</P>
<P>
   LUCENT NET BETTER THAN EXPECTED
</P>
<P>
   Profit before charges at Lucent Technologies rose a
better-than-expected 48.5 percent in its fiscal fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   VICE CHAIRMAN OF GOLDMAN TO RETIRE
</P>
<P>
   Roy Zuckerberg, vice chairman of Goldman, Sachs &AMP; Co. and the
longest-serving partner at the private Wall Street firm, will
retire next month, potentially missing a chance to perhaps triple
the value of his stake if the firm goes public. Zuckerberg, who has
been with Goldman for 31 years, is the largest single shareholder
in the firm.
</P>
<P>
   FCC WIRETAPPING RULES
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Communications Commission has proposed rules
intended to settle a bitter dispute over high-technology
wiretapping that has pitted the FBI against the telecommunications
industry and privacy advocates.
</P>
<P>
   NEW CHIEF FEDERAL AUDITOR
</P>
<P>
   Just before adjourning this week, the Senate approved David M.
Walker, a 47-year-old accountant, as comptroller general, the chief
auditor of all federal programs, contracts and operations.
</P>
<P>
   NEW WAY TO ACCOUNT FOR MERGERS
</P>
<P>
   The Financial Accounting Standards Board has tentatively decided
on new rules that may make companies think twice about future
mergers and acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   TWO INTERNET MUSIC SELLERS TO MERGE
</P>
<P>
   After weeks of negotiation, CD Now and N2K, the two biggest
Internet music sellers, agreed to merge.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA'S STEALTH PRIME MINISTER
</P>
<P>
   Now that Yevgeny Primakov, the prime minister of Russia, has
spent six weeks leading one of the biggest nations through its
worst fiscal crisis, one thing is becoming increasingly clear:
Nobody outside the Kremlin knows what the prime minister is doing.
</P>
</TEXT>
