<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD'S HEGEMONY OVERSEAS MEANS BUCKS AT HOME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Hollywood's salvation is coming from Britain,
Brazil, Bulgaria and nearly every other nation on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   That trend was underscored last weekend when ``City of Angels,''
which generated a modest $78 million in the U.S., became the 12th
movie this year to top the $100 million mark in foreign grosses.
The Warner Bros. remake of ``Wings of Desire'' has grossed $15.8
million in Japan, $15.4 million in Germany and $8.4 million in the
United Kingdom.
</P>
<P>
   The foreign performance is particularly impressive since it came
from a slow-paced spiritually themed movie starring Nicolas Cage
and Meg Ryan. It clearly lacked the three key elements -- slam-bang
action, special effects and major international stars -- that
usually lead to big audiences in overseas theaters.
</P>
<P>
   But ``City of Angels'' was also an American film, a big plus
overseas. Even though moviemaking is a worldwide art, Hollywood's
films are the ones that are allocated most of the screens, often
well over 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``American movies are the coin of the realm in foreign
markets,'' observed analyst Tim Baskerville recently. ``Although
it's usually the big action movies that we tend to associate with
doing well overseas, the other thing to keep in mind is that those
markets tend to be dominated by U.S. product.''
</P>
<P>
   The top foreign performers list is led by ``Titanic'' with an
astounding $1.2 billion in overseas box office receipts, or double
the U.S. total. ``The Man in the Iron Mask,'' released at the peak
of Leonardo DiCaprio's popularity, was a major beneficiary of the
frenzy over ``Titanic'' in overseas markets and cleared well over
$100 million.
</P>
<P>
   The $100 million-overseas list will be augmented by ``Mulan''
and ``The X-Files'' by the end of the year, with ``Mulan'' expected
to reach $200 million by the end of its run. The surprise U.S. hit,
``There's Something About Mary,'' which has just started its run in
many markets, could also join the club.
</P>
<P>
   Baskerville recently released a forecast showing foreign markets
will increase their influence during the next decade, rising from
60.8 percent of worldwide revenues this year ($10.96 billion) to
65.6 percent in 2007 ($15.37 billion), representing a gain of 40
percent. North American box office grosses will rise 24 percent
from $7.07 billion to $8.81 billion in the same period.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas business will boom in large part because of the growing
popularity of new multiplexes, often in towns where traditional
cinemas had either become outmoded or were closed. Baskerville said
that trend will lead to 22 percent more screens by 2007 with the
average admission ticket rising 34 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at the total revenue and profit picture for a
significant-budget American release, the majority of the money is
often going to come from outside the United States,'' Baskerville
said. ``If you're a major studio, a very high percentage of your
movies will get released in foreign markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Top U.S. movies move into foreign markets a few weeks to a few
months after opening domestically. North American theatrical
grosses -- generally split 50-50 with exhibitors -- were once the
dominant factor in the success of a film; that area now accounts
for 35 percent of a movie's revenues and that figure will fall
because of growth in foreign theaters, video markets and television
rebroadcast rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Studios have more opportunities than ever to recoup their
investments,'' Baskerville said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
