<HEADLINE>
MOTHER OF DEAD LOGGING PROTESTER SAYS INVESTIGATOR TO RECOMMEND
MANSLAUGHTER CHARGES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BILL DAWSON 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The mother of the Pasadena, Texas, man killed while protesting
Houston-based Maxxam's redwood-logging practices says the lead
investigator in California has told her he would recommend
manslaughter charges be filed against her son's fellow activists.
</P>
<P>
   Members of a small band of Earth First! protesters who were with
David Chain when a falling tree struck him on Sept. 17 have said a
logger for Maxxam's Pacific Lumber subsidiary had threatened them
and should be charged in his death.
</P>
<P>
   Chain's mother, Cyndy Allsbrooks, who lives in Coldspring north
of Houston, said Thursday she believes the Humboldt County
Sheriff's Department is conducting a ``biased'' investigation
because of its close ties to Maxxam's Pacific Lumber subsidiary,
the county's largest private employer.
</P>
<P>
   Allsbrooks and her attorney, Steven Schectman, held a San
Francisco press conference to call for an independent inquiry into
her son's death.
</P>
<P>
   But Sheriff Dennis Lewis, a former Pacific Lumber employee,
dismissed the bias accusation as ``hogwash.'' He said he would
welcome an independent inquiry if another law-enforcement agency
would do it, but he doubts that will happen.
</P>
<P>
   Chain, 24, grew up in Pasadena, Texas, but in recent years lived
in Austin. When he was killed, he was on company property with
other activists, participating in a ``cat and mouse'' practice
aimed at slowing or stopping logging.
</P>
<P>
   Allsbrooks said she returned to California ``to find out what
happened to my so so he wouldn't have died in vain.''
</P>
<P>
   She said said she was ``outraged'' when Detective Juan Freeman
told her Monday he was recommending that Chain's fellow activists
be charged with manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   She said Freeman also told her the logger, A.E. Ammons, was
``doing what any logger would have done when kids are messing with
his livelihood.''
</P>
<P>
   Surviving members of Chain's party of Earth First! activists
have released a videotape to support their contention that the
logger cursed and threatened to drop a tree in their direction.
Their attorney has said the activists do not think Ammons intended
to kill Chain, but should be charged ``at least with involuntary
manslaughter.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said he agrees with his investigators that Ammon did not
mean to harm Chain, but he does not know enough about what the
protesters ``were doing to form an opinion about whether they are
criminally culpable.''
</P>
<P>
   A decision on prosecution is up to Humboldt County District
Attorney Terry Farmer, whose office received partial results of the
Sheriff's Department's investigation on Wednesday, Lewis said.
Farmer could not be reached for comment Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Schectman, Allsbrooks' attorney, who released a letter calling
for a state or federal investigation, said Pacific Lumber shares
some responsibility for Chain's death for failing to implement
policies on dealing peaceably with protesters.
</P>
<P>
   Company spokeswoman Mary Bullwinkel said Pacific Lumber has such
a policy and tells employees at all safety meetings ``to notify
authorities when people are discovered trespassing at active
logging sites.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
