<SLUG> BC-HKN-KINGS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KINGS ADD GOALIE DEPTH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ROGER PHILLIPS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMPA, Fla. _ The Kings added goaltending depth Thursday,
acquiring Ryan Bach from the Detroit Red Wings organization in
exchange for a conditional choice in the 2000 NHL draft.
</P>
<P>
   Bach, who turned 25 on Wednesday, is expected to be the backup
to Manny Legace tonight when the Kings play the Tampa Bay Lightning
in the second game of a five-game trip.
</P>
<P>
   He was recalled Thursday from the Utah Grizzlies, where he had a
2-1 record with a 2.74 goals-against average with the IHL team.
Last season with Houston in the IHL, Bach _ the 262nd player chosen
in the 1992 draft _ was 26-9-6 with a 2.32 goals-against average.
He has never appeared in an NHL game.
</P>
<P>
   Ever since losing Frederic Chabot to Montreal in the NHL waiver
draft earlier this month, the Kings' goaltending depth has been a
major question mark, one that was exposed this week when Stephane
Fiset and Jamie Storr suffered groin injuries in the same game.
</P>
<P>
   Legace, 25, was outstanding in stopping 49 of 50 shots in his
NHL debut Wednesday, a 1-1 tie at Florida. But his backup was a
teen-ager, 18-year-old Alexey Volkov, the Kings' third-round choice
in this year's draft. With Bach's acquisition, Volkov was returned
Thursday to the Halifax Mooseheads of the Quebec junior league.
</P>
<P>
   Kings coach Larry Robinson said the small sample of the NHL was
positive for Volkov.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gets to practice with NHL caliber, where things are
happening a little bit quicker, he gets to see what the life is
like at the pro level, and it gives him something to shoot for,''
Robinson said. ``I think it's a great educational experience for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Volkov said: ``I'm so young. It's unbelievable. I still can't
believe I'm in NHL. It's like a dream come true, you know?''
</P>
<P>
   Before learning he'd been sent back to Halifax, Volkov said he
felt ready to play in the NHL if called upon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be nice,'' Volkov said. ``I'm not scared. I'm
confident in myself. I just go and play like any game. It's very
tough sitting on the bench. You never know what can happen to the
first goalie. You have to keep focused in the game. It's very tough
being second goalie. To be honest, for me it would be better if I
stay in the net. I'm not nervous in the net. I'm nervous on the
bench.''
</P>
<P>
   Loose pucks: Fiset will not play tonight because of his groin
injury. Neither will center Jozef Stumpel (hip-flexor strain) and
winger Josh Green (shoulder strain). Defenseman Steve Duchesne,
however, might return after missing a game with a mild groin
strain.... Lightning right wing Stephane Richer will miss the next
four weeks following arthroscopic surgery to remove scar tissue
from a sore left ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Nedved rumors: Pittsburgh Penguins holdout center Petr Nedved,
who is playing for the Las Vegas Thunder in the IHL, has denied
rumors that he might be coming to the Kings. Kings general manager
Dave Taylor also has denied the rumors.
</P>
<P>
   According to a source close to the Thunder, the Buffalo Sabres
have been scouting Nedved, and the New York Rangers also are
believed to be interested. Nedved, 26, has not played in the NHL
since the 1996-97 season. His best season was in 1995-96, when he
had 45 goals and 99 points for the Penguins.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
