<SLUG> BC-PALOMA-HEDGEFUND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEDGE-FUND FIRM DENIES BEING IN TROUBLE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn.)  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Paloma Partners Management, a Greenwich, Conn., firm that runs
hedge funds, acknowledged Thursday that it had been battered by the
recent turmoil in the bond markets but insisted that it was still
in sound financial health. The firm, which operates more than 10
funds and is said to have at least $1 billion under management,
issued a statement in response to increasing speculation about its
well-being.
</P>
<P>
   ``To allay concerns and set the record straight, Paloma's funds
are financially sound and our portfolios are in strong cash
positions,'' Donald Sussman, chairman and chief executive, said in
the statement.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors about hedge funds have abounded since the near-collapse
of Long-Term Capital and the recent troubles at firms like
Ellington Capital and D.E. Shaw. Despite their secretive natures,
many funds are being forced to be more open about their positions.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
