<SLUG> BC-HOMEVIDEO-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME VIDEOS: JUST WHERE DID THE GIRLS GO? 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By PETER M. NICHOLS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The young women are still nowhere to be found, but this week the
movie is back. Tied up for 15 years by various financial
complications, Peter Weir's acclaimed ``Picnic at Hanging Rock''
has returned to video in tape and DVD editions released Tuesday by
Home Vision and Criterion.
</P>
<P>
   The film, shown in theaters in 1975 (and most recently in a
revival this summer), is based on the novel by the late Joan
Lindsay.
</P>
<P>
   During a picnic on St. Valentine's Day in 1900, a group of
schoolgirls is hypnotically compelled by an unknown force to climb
a rock formation in central Australia. Three of them and a
chaperone who goes to look for them disappear without a trace.
</P>
<P>
   The movie, both spooky and sexy, broke fresh ground in at least
two respects. For one, it was the first internationally distributed
representative of what was to become a noted school of filmmaking.
``There wasn't much of a theatrical film industry in Australia
then,'' said Karen Robson who as a 17-year-old portrayed a
picnicker named Irma in the film and is now an entertainment lawyer
in New York. ``The fact that it just was a movie and not a
glorified piece of television set it apart.''
</P>
<P>
   In a riskier departure, the film dared to pose a mystery, and a
riveting one at that, and then take leave without providing a
resolution or even a suggestion as to what could have happened to
the missing persons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disappearance is to be neither dead or alive, so I thought it
was an interesting area to take a film,'' Weir said this week on
the telephone from Sydney. Caught by the seductive moodiness,
audiences generally didn't seem to mind the lack of explanation.
</P>
<P>
   The answer might have come from Irma, who at first vanishes with
the others, but is later found in a trancelike state. When she
revives, interrogators cluster around. She can't remember a thing.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lindsay's book was supposedly based on a true story, but
records reveal no such incident. ``Yet another red herring,'' Ms.
Robson said with a laugh. ``Totally typical of the author of this
book. She was a very playful woman.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Family values loom all too large in the film's formula,''
Janet Maslin wrote in The New York Times. Despite, or perhaps
because of this, ``Lost in Space,'' Stephen Hopkins'
special-effects-laden film about the Robinson clan's wanderings
through the cosmos is video's best renter and seller this week.
</P>
<P>
   In a narrower vein, however, the movie, which is distributed by
New Line, is also notable for its DVD version, which links film and
additional features to be called up in the DVD-ROM drive of a
personal computer.
</P>
<P>
   Watch the movie, remove the disk from the DVD player and plug it
into the computer for, among other things, the screenplay, deleted
scenes, commentary about space travel and links to New Line
Internet sites.
</P>
<P>
   If extras of that nature induce a yawn, remember that DVD-ROMs
are likely to become much more innovative in future. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In Don Roos' gleefully acerbic first feature, the nail-hard
teen-ager Dedee Truitt (Christina Ricci) quits boring Louisiana and
goes north to camp out for a while with her nice homosexual
half-brother, Bill (Martin Donovan), whom she hasn't seen in years.
Bill, a sensitive high school teacher who tries to lead a fairly
orderly life, never knows what hits him.
</P>
<P>
   In short order, little Dedee seduces his boyfriend, Matt (Ivan
Sergei), announces herself pregnant and runs off to California with
Matt and most of Bill's life savings. Remaining remarkably
philosophical under the circumstances, Bill is left with a scandal
that costs him his job.
</P>
<P>
   Accompanied by Lucia (Lisa Kudrow), the constantly complaining
and very funny sister of an earlier lover of his, Bill chases ``the
human tabloid,'' as Lucia calls Dedee, to the West Coast in, Janet
Maslin wrote in The New York Times, ``a busily plotted, nicely
unpredictable sex comedy with a sarcastic edge.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Columbia Tri-Star. $99.36. 105 minutes. Closed captioned.
R. Release date: Tuesday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Turn the direction of a disaster film over to a woman (Mimi
Leder) and the action drifts away from the action mode to look for
what salutary effects the calamity might have on relationships and
family. When a top government official resigns, the MSNBC reporter
Jenny Lerner (Tea Leoni) at first thinks it's because he's having
an affair.
</P>
<P>
   Later she learns that he has revealed too much about an
impending Extinction Level Event, i.e., a collision with a
meteorite the size of Manhattan below 110th Street. Though
astronauts are dispatched to deflect the big rock, as they are in
``Armageddon,'' the summer's other meteor disaster movie, here the
focus is on bonding lovers, mending family rifts and taking care of
art, antiques, elephants and flamingos.
</P>
<P>
   Remaining on that course, her film ``has a more brooding,
thoughtful tone than the genre usually calls for''(Maslin). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1998. Paramount. $105.96. 120 minutes. Closed captioned. PG-13.
Release date: Tuesday. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Under the strain of extreme physical and emotional deprivation,
a pugnacious, brazen 12-year-old named Francie Brady (Eamonn Owens)
grows steadily more twisted in a story on its way to startling
violence. The child of quarreling drunks (Stephen Rea and Aisling
O'Sullivan), Francie has no choice but to try life on his own, and
that includes hooliganism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I do believe I shall be off on my travels,'' he concludes
to himself during one of his parents' boozy fights. Work in peat
bogs, electroshock therapy and other familiar indignities follow,
``but as the real, disturbing nature of Neil Jordan's audacious
film emerges, this story moves far outside the realm of the
ordinary'' (Maslin). &QL;
</P>
<P>
   1997. Warner. $104.17. 106 minutes. Closed captioned. R. Release
date: Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Other new titles of interest, some of which may have had a
theater release at one time or appeared on television.
</P>
<P>
   OUT OF THE PAST. Michelle Ferrari's well-paced documentary,
narrated by Linda Hunt, tells the story of Kelli Peterson, 17, a
student who provoked hysterical outrage in Salt Lake City by
starting an organization called the Gay-Straight Alliance. With
that case as foundation, the film reconstructs the history of gay
rights and profiles leaders like Bayard Rustin. 1998. A-Pix.
$24.98. 64 minutes. No rating.
</P>
<P>
   THE ARISTOCRACY. A four-cassette series produced by the BBC
traces the English high-born from the days when they owned 80
percent of the land, to the 1960s when Lord Hertford water-skied
through flaming hoops to bring in the tourists, to the present day
when the surviving aristocracy packs more clout than one might
think. 1998. Home Vision. $79.95. 180 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   A LIFE APART: HASIDIM IN AMERICA. With intimate interviews,
Menachem Daum and Oran Rudevsky's documentary goes inside homes,
schools and synagogues to explore Hasidic traditions and customs
and how the community has fared in American society since the
emigration of the remnants of Europe's Hasidic community to this
country following the Holocaust. The film is narrated by Leonard
Nimoy and Sarah Jessica Parker. 1997. First Run Features. $59.95.
95 minutes. No rating.
</P>
<P>
   CHARACTER. In Rotterdam in the 1920s, a young man struggles to
prove himself personally and professionally in the shadow of a
cruel father. Based on a popular Dutch novel, Mike Van Diem's dour
film won an Academy Award as best foreign-language film. 1997.
Columbia Tri-Star. $105.77. 114 minutes. Dutch with English
subtitles.
</P>
