<HEADLINE>
ISRAEL, PALESTINIANS NEAR ELUSIVE PEACE ACCORD 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1998 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Israeli and Palestinian negotiators neared an
elusive interim peace accord Thursday after each side gained
concessions on land and security during marathon sessions with
President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   White House spokesman Joe Lockhart described the afternoon
sessions between Clinton, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
and Palestinian Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat as the most
intense so far in the eight-day summit.
</P>
<P>
   Late Thursday, the two sides said they had reached an agreement
on Israel's push for changes in the Palestine Liberation
Organization's charter that calls for the destruction of Israel.
But Lockhart warned that the issue had not been fully settled.
</P>
<P>
   Sources in the two camps told Reuters the Palestinian National
Council would ratify changes in the 1964 provisions after Israel
completed a staged withdrawal of troops from portions of the West
Bank.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press quoted sources as saying Clinton personally
would attend the PLO session but there was no confirmation from the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   The potential breakthrough on the issue, which Netanyahu made a
centerpiece of his agenda, was one of several advances in the
roller-coaster talks.
</P>
<P>
   Just 24 hours earlier, Netanyahu packed his bags and ordered his
airplane on stand-by as he threatened to walk away from the talks.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, urging the Israelis to remain, crafted a
20-page text outlining the agreements so far and proposals to
resolve remaining problems.
</P>
<P>
   Early Thursday, Clinton rushed back to Wye Plantation on
Maryland's Eastern Shore to keep the negotiations going.
</P>
<P>
   ``The hardest decisions now, at last, are on the table. Israel,
the Palestinians, the region and the world have very much at stake
today. I hope the parties will seize this opportunity and not
retreat from the clear moment to capture the momentum of peace, and
keep it moving forward,'' Clinton said before departing Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The late evening talks focused on provisions in the PLO charter
that calls for the destruction of Israel, the release of 3,000
Palestinian prisoners in Israeli jails and a third Israeli troop
withdrawal from the West Bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the events of yesterday behind us, we are in a situation
where the leaders arrived at the Wye Woods conference area and
began what I would describe as a very serious and intensive effort
to try to make the key decisions necessary for us to put the peace
process back on track,'' said James Rubin, the State Department
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made his sixth appearance at the Wye River conference
center for direct negotiations with Netanyahu and Arafat. The
president has invested more than 70 hours trying to broker a deal.
</P>
<P>
   He later was joined by Jordan's King Hussein, the ailing monarch
undergoing cancer treatment in the United States. The king flew to
the Wye River conference center briefly and has remained in touch
with both sides through telephone calls.
</P>
<P>
   King Hussein, who made peace with Israel in 1994, has played a
key role as a Middle East peace broker.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides appeared to resolve key security issues such as a
Palestinian crackdown on militant groups and arrests of suspected
terrorists. Israeli negotiators had balked at withdrawing troops
from another 13 percent of the West Bank until Arafat agreed to a
detailed security plan.
</P>
<P>
   The AP reported the Israelis considered that progress was made
on the security issue while Palestinians claimed the ``security
file was closed.''
</P>
<P>
   Rubin later said that the security issue no longer was the focus
of the talks, saying major progress had been made.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the significant gaps have not been closed. The key
decisions that need to be made today include areas where gaps
remain. We wouldn't be here, the president wouldn't have rolled up
his sleeves and urged the leaders to get down to serious business
today if there weren't significant gaps remaining,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart said that with the tough issues on the table the
president was pressing for decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president wants the parties to make important decisions
today,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lockhart declined to speculate about where the talks were
headed.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I've repeated ad nauseam we take this one meeting, one day
at a time. But again, the tough issues are on the table and we're
working toward making decisions and having the parties work through
these issues,'' Lockhart said.
</P>
<P>
   The AP quoted Ahmed Tibi, an Arafat adviser, as saying the issue
of the Palestinian charter and Israel's third-phase withdrawal of
troops had been the most difficult issues remaining. Tibi said
Israel dropped its demand that the Palestinians extradite suspected
terrorists to Israel.
</P>
<P>
   However, the delegations may be facing some artificial deadlines
that could force a resolution to the talks. The Jewish Sabbath
starts at sundown today and Clinton planned to travel to California
this weekend on a trip that was rescheduled from earlier this week.
Also, Netanyahu may face a vote of nonconfidence by Israeli
lawmakers on Monday. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
