<SLUG> BC-ISP-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 PUC's Ruling on Net Calls to Cost Pac Bell  &HT;       
 By Deborah Solomon 
 &HT;     c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
The Internet takes you into cyberspace, but the phone call that
gets you there is local, California regulators ruled yesterday.
<P>
   The 3-to-2 decision by the state Public Utilities Commission
requires local phone companies, including Pacific Bell and GTE, to
pay their competitors millions of dollars in fees.
</P>
<P>
   At issue are phone calls placed by Pac Bell and GTE customers to
Internet service providers who use competing phone companies for
local service.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal law, local phone companies must pay one another a
fee when they handle a call from each other's customers.
</P>
<P>
   Pacific Bell has refused to pay fees on calls its customers
place to local ISP numbers. Even though both numbers are in the
same local calling area, Pac Bell has argued that Internet calls
are long-distance because they could end up anywhere in the world.
</P>
<P>
   But the PUC sided with 21 other states in determining that
Internet calls to local numbers are local. What happens after the
call hits the ISP's modem makes no difference, the commission said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Competing local phone companies are entitled to compensation
for the functions they perform,'' said Commissioner Jessie Knight,
who voted in favor of classifying the calls as local.
</P>
<P>
   The commission ordered all local phone companies to start making
reciprocal payments on Internet calls immediately.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Pac Bell already owes more than $5 million to competing phone
carriers and has been keeping the money in an escrow account.
</P>
<P>
   In California, most Internet users have Pacific Bell, while most
ISPs use competing phone companies because their rates are lower
than Pac Bell's. That's why Pacific Bell owes so much to its
competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Mashek, a spokesman for Pac Bell, said the company is
``disappointed'' with the commission's ruling and is considering
whether to appeal. The company has not decided whether it will pay
the fees pending a possible appeal, he said.
</P>
<P>
   If the calls had been deemed long-distance, Pac Bell and GTE
competitors might have raised rates to make up for lost fee income.
And those higher rates might have been passed along to ISPs, who
might have passed them along to Internet customers.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  Cindy Schonhaut, senior vice president for ICG
Communications, a local phone company, applauded the commission's
decision but said she's not sure the battle has been won.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the track record from other companies is a model, then Pac
Bell is going to appeal the decision,'' said Schonhaut, whose
Englewood, Colo., company provides service to many ISPs. ``The
regional Bell operating companies in other states have done
something along those lines. They appeal and then continue to
litigate.''
</P>
<P>
   In Michigan, Ameritech Corp. appealed a ruling against it on the
same issue and refused to pay bills of $6 million to four rivals.
SBC Communications Inc. also appealed a similar ruling from the PUC
in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Four state courts have upheld PUC decisions that local Internet
calls are local.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-98 2245EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981022.0522 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 22:45 </DATE_TIME>
