<SLUG> BC-CALFED-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Cal Fed Plans More Staff Cuts  &HT;       
 By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
California Federal Bank said yesterday it will cut more jobs than
it originally projected following its recently completed takeover
of Southern California's Glendale Federal Bank.
<P>
   The San Francisco savings and loan now expects to eliminate
1,215 jobs, about 75 more than it forecast when it agreed to take
over Glendale Federal in February, Cal Fed President Carl Webb said
in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the cuts will occur in Southern California, though more
than 100 Bay Area jobs will vanish when the thrift closes 15
branches in the region. The two thrifts together had about 8,000
full-time employees.
</P>
<P>
   The job cuts, which are taking place through a combination of
firings and attrition, are aimed at slashing the combined thrift's
expenses, Webb explained.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on track to realize $160 million in (annual) cost
savings,'' Cal Fed's president said.
</P>
<P>
   The cuts include 415 positions that were vacated and never
filled while the merger was pending, 225 jobs that ended when the
transaction took effect September 11, and 575 slots that will
disappear over the next four to six months as the two thrifts
combine operations.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the cuts that haven't already been made will take place
when Cal Fed closes 56 branches across the state in mid-November,
including four in San Francisco, three in San Jose, four in San
Mateo County, two in Marin County and two in Sonoma County.
</P>
<P>
   Other jobs will disappear when Glendale Federal's loan servicing
center in San Diego and data processing facility in Burbank are
shut over the next few months. Job cuts are common in bank and
thrift mergers as institutions look to save money by shutting
overlapping operations.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Golden State Bancorp, Cal Fed's corporate parent,
reported a third-quarter net loss of $32.2 million (44 cents a
diluted share), including an extraordinary charge for refinancing
about $2 billion in debt.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding the item, the thrift earned $47.8 million (62 cents)
as it originated $2.7 billion in mortgages and other loans.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said earnings comparisons with previous periods were
not meaningful because prior reports didn't include Glendale
Federal's results.
</P>
<P>
   The thrift's future profits will depend on how many customers
pay off mortgages ahead of schedule to take advantage of lower
interest rates, it told analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Cal Fed's profits shrink when borrowers pay mortgages ahead of
schedule because it loses income from servicing loans and must
replace mortgages with assets that earn lower interest rates.
</P>
<P>
   Cal Fed is the nation's second-largest savings and loan and
California's fourth-largest deposit holder.  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-98 2245EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981022.0523 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
