r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KAISER-SFCHRON &LR;      10-22 0500
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KAISER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Kaiser Expects Big Loss  &HT;       
 By Ilana DeBare 
 &HT;     c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Kaiser Permanente said yesterday it is expecting a big
third-quarter operating loss that, unlike losses in previous
quarters, probably won't be offset by investment income.
<P>
   ``We will be reporting a loss, but until I have the actual
numbers, I can't comment on the size,'' said David O'Grady, a
spokesman for the 9.2-million-member health plan.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser, which is headquartered in Oakland, suffered $162 million
in operating losses during the first half of 1998. But those losses
were offset by gains of more than $130 million in investment
income, for a net loss of just $31 million in the six months that
ended June 30.
</P>
<P>
   Now the giant health plan is predicting more operating losses
for the quarter ended September 30. But, sources said, there are
unlikely to be any investment gains this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the stock market gone so far south, we probably won't be
able to offset our operating losses as in the past,'' said a source
within Kaiser, which will release its third-quarter numbers at the
end of this month.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser's poor financial returns this year come in the wake of a
whopping $270 million loss in 1997 _ the health plan's first annual
loss in its history.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts cited a variety of reasons for the continued red ink:
Hospitalization costs are rising throughout the health care
industry, after declining for several years. Drug costs are also
rising.
</P>
<P>
   ``These problems are unique to Kaiser only in scale,'' said
Wanda Jones, a health care analyst with the New Century Health Care
Institute in San Francisco. ``We'll be seeing more of this (kind of
loss) elsewhere, but Kaiser is big enough to really notice.''
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser also ran into trouble by adding members more quickly than
it could handle in areas such as Southern California. That meant it
had to spend extra money sending patients to hospitals and doctors
outside its own system.
</P>
<P>
   Kaiser has responded to its losses by a companywide cost-cutting
program, which included selling its money-losing Texas unit.
</P>
<P>
   It is also trying to boost its revenues through rate increases _
for instance, winning a 10.7 percent rate hike from the California
Public Employee Retirement System last June.
</P>
<P>
   But most of these rate increases won't go into effect until
1999. So they didn't add anything to Kaiser's bottom line in the
recent quarter.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear whether this round of rate increases will be enough
to offset the losses _ so there may be more rounds of rate
increases in the cards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kaiser's best recourse is going back to their purchasers and
saying, `Do you really want us around? If so, we have to
renegotiate the contracts upwards,' '' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's largest health maintenance organization, Kaiser
provides health care for 5.7 million Californians. That includes
2.7 million people in Northern California, or one-third of this
region's insured population. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
