r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GENENTECH-SFCHRON &LR;      10-22 0811
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GENENTECH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 New Life in Vacaville for Genentech  &HT;       
 By Tom Abate 
 &HT;     c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Genentech Corp. will christen a $250 million manufacturing facility
today in Vacaville, augmenting a 15-year-old South San Francisco
production line that can't keep up with demand for its biotech
remedies.
<P>
   Today's event highlights Genentech's rebound from the management
and product woes that plagued it in the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Genentech is a huge turnaround story,'' said Meirav Chovav,
with Salomon Smith Barney in New York. ``Management has taken a
company that had no new significant products in the pipeline and
not only created those products, but the facility to make them.''
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, for instance, Genentech said it would ask the Food
and Drug Administration for permission to make a new growth hormone
called ProLease. Genentech already earns a quarter of its revenues
selling hormones for children with clinical growth deficiencies.
But Chovav said the existing remedies must be administered by daily
injection, whereas ProLease, if it wins FDA approval, could spur
growth with biweekly shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mothers wouldn't need to chase the kids with a needle once a
day,'' Chovav said, making the hormone easier to administer and
thus more likely to be used.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Joel Sendek, with Gerard Klauer Mattison, said that in
addition to improving its current products with innovations like
ProLease, Genentech has introduced new remedies like Herceptin, a
protein that fights the most aggressive forms of breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main sexiness of the new manufacturing facility is that
they're bringing it on line just as their cancer lines are taking
off,'' Sendek said. ``The plant is a key element of their strategic
plan.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Jackson, general manager of Genentech's Vacaville
facility, said the five-building campus includes its own utility
building to provide the purified water, steam, compressed air and
refrigeration units that are part of the biotech manufacturing
process.
</P>
<P>
   The heart of the operation will be a 12,000-liter
stainless-steel fermentation tank, 25 feet tall and 8 feet in
diameter, where Genentech will ``grow'' Herceptin, the first
product planned for the new facility. &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   The process begins with special cells that create the Herceptin
protein as a byproduct. In a simplified sense, these cells
multiply, producing more and more Herceptin.
</P>
<P>
   Once the cells have produced enough Herceptin, this &UR;  &LR; refined
protein &UR;  &LR; must be separated from the cells and stored in smaller
stainless-steel containers. These bulk-protein containers, which
are about three times the size of a beer keg, must be chilled to
minus 20 degrees Celsius to protect the Herceptin.
</P>
<P>
   It is this bulk protein, in super-chilled tanks, that will roll
off the assembly line in Vacaville. The Herceptin then will be
shipped to South San Francisco, where existing Genentech facilities
will pump the protein into tiny glass vials destined for hospitals.
There, doctors will load the Herceptin into syringes and inject it
into breast cancer patients.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Young, Genentech's chief operating officer, estimated that
each keg of bulk protein contains about 15,000 doses _ or about $8
million worth of Herceptin. Once the Vacaville plant is in full
swing, about three or four tanks of frozen bulk protein should roll
out of the facility each week.
</P>
<P>
   But before Genentech can start this profitable process, the
facility must win FDA clearance to go into operation. Jackson said
Genentech has about 160 people at work in Vacaville, doing
shakedown tests to show the FDA that the facility can meet exacting
standards for purity and safety. Assuming all goes well _ and
analysts anticipate no problems _ the plant should go into full
operation late next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nature of our industry is that we have a long investment
cycle,'' said Young, adding that Genentech started planning the new
facility in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   The opening of the Genentech plant is another feather in the cap
for Vacaville, which quietly has become the Bay Area's
biotech-manufacturing center. Biosource Technologies, an
agricultural biotech firm, is based in Vacaville. Alza Corp. of
Palo Alto and Chiron Corp. of Emeryville already have manufacturing
sites in the city.
</P>
<P>
   Genentech's Young said Vacaville had several draws: It is close
to the R&AMP;D labs and headquarters of Bay Area biotech firms, and it
has cheap land, a responsive local government and qualified labor.
</P>
<P>
   When the Vacaville plant is in full swing, it will employ
roughly 300 people, about a third of whom will be manufacturing
technicians starting at $28,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Genentech employs about 1,200 manufacturing people at its South
San Francisco headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Its shares closed at $70.06 yesterday, off 6 cents. The company
hit a 52-week high of $74.94 on October 12.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-98 2247EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981022.0526 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 22:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2548 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WELLS-SFCHRON &LR;      10-22 0306
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WELLS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Trio of Top Execs Bailing Out of Wells Fargo  &HT;       
 By Sam Zuckerman 
 &HT;     c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Three of Wells Fargo's highest-ranking executives are leaving the
bank as a result of its pending merger with Minneapolis's Norwest
Corp.
<P>
   Those departing are Vice Chairman Joseph Stiglich, head of Wells
Fargo's retail branch network; Vice Chairman Michael Gillfillan,
the bank's credit chief; and Executive Vice President Dudley Nigg,
online banking manager.
</P>
<P>
   The two vice chairmen will get severance packages providing
three years of salary plus bonus. Because they are not among the
bank's five highest-paid executives, their salaries do not have to
be disclosed. But they are among Wells Fargo's 10 highest-ranking
executives.
</P>
<P>
   Stiglich's position won't exist after the merger and his
responsibilities will be divided among several regional managers,
Wells Fargo spokeswoman Kim Kellogg said.
</P>
<P>
   Stiglich, 51, joined Wells Fargo in 1971 and took over
management of the bank's retail network in 1994. During his tenure,
the bank moved away from traditional offices to alternative ways of
reaching customers, such as supermarket branches.
</P>
<P>
   Gillfillan, 50, agreed in July to be chief credit officer of the
combined bank but later decided not to take the job, Kellogg said.
He joined the bank in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   Nigg, 51, will retire at the end of the year. He recently bought
a boat and plans to sail to New Zealand, a spokeswoman said.
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Osberg, a division manager in the bank's online banking
unit, will replace him on an interim basis. Under the British-born
Nigg, Wells Fargo aggressively moved into Internet banking and now
has some 540,000 online customers.
</P>
<P>
   Wells Fargo's merger with Norwest is set to take effect November
2, forming the nation's seventh-largest bank.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-98 2247EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981022.0527 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 22:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2549 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STREET-SFCHRON &LR;      10-22 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STREET-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 Investors Suing S.F Fund Manager Robert Pryt and Bear Stearns  &HT;       
 By Mark Veverka  
 c.1998 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &QL; 
Hedge fund fallout is hitting full force. A group of Bay Area hedge
fund investors, including Gymboree Chairman Stuart Moldaw, is
striking back.
<P>
   In a case that is sure to capture national attention, angry
investors are suing San Francisco fund manager Robert Pryt and his
broker-dealer, Bear Stearns, for mismanaging their money and
misrepresenting the fund's performance, which was used to determine
how much Pryt got paid.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, investors contend that Pryt made unauthorized bets
on privately held companies and wildly exaggerated the value of
their shares in his reports. Pryt folded his fund, BKP Partners, in
June after losing as much as $100 million, according to investors.
</P>
<P>
   Word of the fund's liquidation rippled from San Francisco to
Hollywood because Pryt happened to blow the dough of some
star-studded investors. They included movie producer Jon Peters,
his former squeeze Barbra Streisand and O.J. Simpson's former
lawyer Robert Shapiro. Peters reportedly lost ``millions''
personally, but neither he nor the other two celebrity investors
are currently party to the lawsuit filed earlier this week in
Superior Court in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   Why the Tinseltown investors didn't join the lawsuit isn't
clear. Peters would not comment and referred inquiries to Michael
Klein, a Los Angeles broker-dealer. Klein, who is the son of former
San Diego Chargers owner Gene Klein, did not return telephone
calls.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to trusts connected to the family of Gymboree's
Moldaw, dozens of other old money trusts tied to well-heeled Bay
Area families are participating in the lawsuit. The investor group
that is suing says its combined investments accounted for a
majority stake of the fund, which at its peak had assets of about
$270 million, says Solomon Cera, a San Francisco lawyer who
represents the group.
</P>
<P>
   Above and beyond the starpower of some of Pryt's investors, the
lawsuit against the 39-year-old money manager will be eyed closely
by the investment community because it is testing how basic
principles of common law &UR;  &LR; treat hedge funds.
</P>
<P>
   No doubt, hedge funds have been grabbing big headlines, mostly
due to the multibillion-dollar bailout of Long-Term Capital. And
unfortunately for the hundreds of money managers who run these
private investment partnerships, the term ``hedge fund'' has been
thrown around so loosely that the funds are greatly misunderstood.
</P>
<P>
   Most hedge funds are, in fact, largely unregulated private funds
that usually invest in stocks. And they almost always devote
portions of their portfolios to short-selling as well as to bets
that stocks will go up. Hence, they ``hedge'' against swings in the
stock market. The investment model is supposed to outperform the
broader stock market if executed well.
</P>
<P>
   However, by definition, hedge funds aren't limited to stocks and
can invest in anything that the partners agree to, including bonds,
currency, futures, options and other vehicles. Long-Term Capital,
for example, is really a quasibank that borrowed billions from
banks and major financial firms to perform highly technical trades
on a global basis.
</P>
<P>
   The Pryt fund, on the other hand, fit the definition of an
ordinary hedge fund. But here's the chief complaint: The partners
are accusing Pryt of investing in vehicles that were not approved
by the partnership.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our contention is that (Pryt) went beyond the scope that his
investors had approved,'' Cera says.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, the investors accuse Pryt of buying stock in
private companies and inflating the value of that stock in his
reports. Stock of private companies is risky and highly illiquid,
making it difficult to sell and place a value on.
</P>
<P>
   What's more, when the fund's other investments were performing
poorly, Pryt allegedly jacked up the values of the private-company
stock to boost the performance record of his portfolio, Cera says.
</P>
<P>
   ``He basically tried to turn a hedge fund into a venture capital
fund'' without his partners' authorization, Cera says.
</P>
<P>
   And then Pryt placed grandiose valuations on the private shares
in order to pay himself full compensation, Cera says. The lion's
share of Pryt's bonus, which was 20 percent of all profits, was
paid only when his performance exceeded his best previous effort.
</P>
<P>
   When contacted at his office, Pryt would only say that ``the
lawsuit was without merit.''
</P>
<P>
   The other twist to the lawsuit, which should grab Wall Street's
full attention, is that the investor group is also suing Pryt's
prime broker, Bear Stearns.
</P>
<P>
   Bear Sterns is a securities firm with an operation that
specializes in making and clearing trades for hedge fund managers.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, a brokerage simply executes decisions ordered by its
customer _ in this case, Pryt. But the investor group is accusing
Bear Stearns of taking an active role in managing the fund and that
it should have notified Pryt's investors of any alleged wrongdoing
by the money manager.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, the investors contend that a Bear Stearns
executive became an employee of a Pryt-controlled arbitrage entity.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, like Pryt, Bear Stearns is saving its explanation
for the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think the case is completely without merit, and we will
respond accordingly,'' a Bear Stearns spokeswoman says.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Mark Veverka can be reached by mail at 901 Mission St., San
Francisco, Calif. 94103, by phone at (415) 777-8444 or by e-mail at
mveverka(at sign)sfgate.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-98 2248EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19981022.0528 </DOCNO>
