<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HORSE OF YEAR A HOT TOPIC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   There will be between 75 and 90 horses in the Breeders' Cup
races, but for the promoters and most fans, only two really matter.
</P>
<P>
   Silver Charm, with his Goodwood Handicap victory last Saturday
at Santa Anita, showed he'll be a formidable opponent for leading
Horse of the Year candidate Skip Away. This should make the two
grays' long-awaited showdown in the Breeders' Cup Classic the most
anticipated race of the Nov.7 card at Churchill Downs in Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   Silver Charm flew to Louisville the morning after the Goodwood,
and owners Bob and Beverly Lewis of Newport Beach already had a
check made out for $480,000, the cost of making the 4-year-old colt
a supplemental nominee for the $4 million Classic.
</P>
<P>
   ``This race didn't take too much out of him at all,'' trainer
Bob Baffert said.
</P>
<P>
   In the first odds posted on the Classic, the main event of the
seven-race Breeders' Cup, Skip Away was a 2-1 favorite and Silver
Charm was the 5-2 second choice of the Daily Racing form's Mike
Watchmaker. The Pat Byrne-trained pair of Awesome Again and Touch
Gold was a joined third at 4-1.
</P>
<P>
   The buildup should include plenty of long-distance banter
between Baffert and Skip Away trainer Sonny Hine.
</P>
<P>
   Hine fired the first volley Tuesday during a conference call
with national turf writers when he ridiculed Baffert's optimism
that Silver Charm could edge Skip Away out of Horse of the Year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's assuming he's going to win,'' Hine said. ``I don't think
he (Silver Charm) can be Horse of the Year off what he's done, not
at all. Grade I's are the epitome of this game, and you're talking
about a horse who hasn't won a Grade I in this country in a year
and a half.''
</P>
<P>
   Silver Charm won the $4 million Dubai World Cup overseas in
March, but his three biggest U.S. victories _ the San Fernando and
Strub Stakes and the Goodwood _ were Grade II races.
</P>
<P>
   Skip Away has won five of the six Grade I races he has started
in 1998. He has a good shot to be the first repeat Classic winner
in the Breeders' Cup's 15-year history.
</P>
<P>
   The field for the 1\-mile Classic could include Gentlemen,
Coronado's Quest and Belmont Stakes winner Victory Gallop, though
Gentlemen also will be kept eligible for the Mile when the
pre-entries are taken Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   With the major prep races in California, New York and Kentucky
complete, here's an early look at the other six Breeders' Cup
races:
</P>
<P>
   Turf: Chief Bearhart, the Canadian horse who won the 1{-mile
grass race when the Breeders' Cup was held at Hollywood Park in
'97, must contend with a platoon of foreign-trained horses. Royal
Anthem, who came from England to win the Canadian International
last weekend, is ridden by Southern California's Gary Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   Mile: The shorter turf race got a lot more interesting when
Favorite Trick, the '97 Horse of the Year as a 2-year-old but a
disappointment in '98, won his first grass start last Saturday at
Keeneland. The '97 Juvenile winner could become the first horse to
capture Breeders' Cup races on both dirt and grass.
</P>
<P>
   Distaff: Looks like a two-filly race: Sharp Cat and Banshee
Breeze, winners by 11 and 12 lengths, respectively, in their preps.
</P>
<P>
   Juvenile: The departure of Del Mar Futurity winner Worldly
Manner, who's off to Dubai after being purchased for $5 million,
leaves eastern 2-year-olds to dominate the field. Boston Celtics
coach Rick Pitino owns two of them _ Champagne Stakes winner The
Groom is Red and Belmont Park allowance winner Cryptodiplomacy.
Both are trained by Nick Zito.
</P>
<P>
   Juvenile Fillies: Baffert, whose only Breeders' Cup win is the
'92 Sprint with Thirty Slews, has two contenders in Excellent
Meeting, winner of the Del Mar Debutante and the Oak Leaf, and
Silverbulletday, a winner at Keeneland.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint: New York's Affirmed Success is the favorite, but
California has contenders in Gold Land and 3-year-old Reraise, the
latter to be supplemented for $120,000 after winning the Kentucky
Cup Sprint at Turfway Park.
</P>
<P>
   The weekend: It's the calm before the Oct.31 California Cup and
the following weekend's Breeders' Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The Oak Tree highlight is Sunday's $125,000 Carleton F. Burke
Handicap at 1{ miles on turf. Amerique, co-high-weight with Crystal
Hearted at 118 pounds, tries for his first victory since the San
Juan Capistrano Handicap, another marathon on the Santa Anita grass
course.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, the $100,000 Harold C. Ramser Sr. Handicap for
3-year-old fillies is headed by Diamond on the Run, making her
first turf start as she tries to give jockey Kent Desormeaux and
trainer Neil Drysdale their 12th stakes win together at Santa Anita
this year.
</P>
<P>
   In perspective: Alex Solis on recording his 3,000th career
victory aboard Secret Advice R.N on Saturday: ``It's a great
feeling to know I'm only 5,000 wins behind Laffit (Pincay) and Bill
Shoemaker.''
</P>
<P>
   Eighty-seven men have ridden 3,000 winners. Six are active at
Santa Anita: Pincay (8,649 through Saturday), Chris McCarron
(6,689), Eddie Delahoussaye (5,961), Gary Stevens (4,390), Kent
Desormeaux (3,666) and Solis. Shoemaker's record is 8,833. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
