<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News wishes to add the following stories
for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of Friday,
Oct. 23 and thereafter. The stories will carry the ``f'' financial
news category code unless otherwise noted. For questions about
stories, contact Jeremy Bagott at the Daily News, (818) 713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   MAG-STOCK-MEDIA (Los Angeles) _ Their screaming headlines
promise the certainty of financial success in a world without one:
``The Best New Mutual Funds'' or ``The Best Short-Term
Investments'' for you NOW. But how good are the stock and mutual
fund recommendations of personal finance magazines? A look at four
months worth of Money, Worth, Smart Money and Kiplinger's magazines
shows a disturbing trend: Out of 19 articles that recommended
stocks or mutual funds, following the advice of seven stories would
have led to losses. By Deborah Adamson (Will move in the ``f''
financial and ``a'' national news files.)
</P>
<P>
   MAG-ADVICE-MEDIA (Los Angeles) _ No, we're not going to
recommend stocks. But here's some advice on how to select your
investments. Tip No. 1: Do your own research, going to sources
outside the magazine such as the Internet. Tip No. 2: Bounce the
stock tip off your broker or financial adviser. Tip No. 3: Follow a
clearly defined investment strategy. Don't let the excitement of
this month's hot stock or fund outweigh your common sense. By
Deborah Adamson (Will move in the ``f'' financial and ``a''
national news files.)
</P>
<P>
   MAG-EDITORS-MEDIA (Los Angeles) _The experts of Wall Street have
to possess a stellar track record before any publication gives them
ink. But that's not the case with the magazines' own journalists
who step into the role of investment guru. Editors at Money,
SmartMoney and Kiplinger's said they and their staff carry years of
financial reporting experience that equip them to make good
recommendations. They also may bounce ideas off proven fund
managers for an expert opinion. But few have a formal education in
finance or credentials such as a certified financial planner
designation. By Deborah Adamson (Will move in the ``f'' financial
and ``a'' national news files.)
</P>
