<HEADER>
A2727 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MA-OBITUARY-SARGENT-B     10-22 1153
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-OBITUARY-SARGENT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER MASSACHUSETTS GOVERNOR FRANCIS SARGENT DIES AT 83 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1998 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ He was so much the archetype of the Massachusetts
Yankee _ lanky frame, sandy hair, lantern jaw, toothy grin, the
whistling S _ that Norman Rockwell painted his portrait.
</P>
<P>
   Francis W. Sargent, who governed the state with vigor and humor
from 1969 to 1974, died, of heart failure at age 83 Thursday in the
Dover, Mass., home where he'd lived for more than half a century.
His remains will be cremated, and a memorial service will be held
early next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sarge,'' as he was universally and fondly known, was a rare
species in the state's political bird book _ a liberal Republican
who relished hobnobbing with Democrats, a blueblood with an R-rated
tongue who delighted in poking fun at himself.
</P>
<P>
   He was an architect by training, an outdoorsman by nature, and a
politician by accident. If Mr. Sargent savored his six years in the
corner office (``I got a hell of a big kick out of it.''), it may
have been because he arrived there by serendipity.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Sargent, who had never held elective office, was voted
lieutenant governor in 1966 under the slogan ``Put Sarge in
Charge.'' When John A. Volpe left the corner office in January 1969
to become transportation secretary in the Nixon administration, Mr.
Sargent suddenly found himself unquestionably in command.
</P>
<P>
   So he plunked down a puckish sign (``Don't Ask Me, I Didn't Go
to Harvard'') on his desk and set about wooing enough Democratic
lawmakers to allow him to function. ``I pissed off some
Republicans,'' Mr. Sargent conceded, ``but there was no other way
to get anything done.''
</P>
<P>
   He may have been Republican by affiliation, but Mr. Sargent was
colorful Democrat by temperament. He loved marching in parades,
slapping backs, pumping hands, and hanging out with Irish pols who
loved to needle him.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Sargent golfed with House Speaker Thomas P. ``Tip'' O'Neill
Jr. (``I thought he was absolutely wonderful.''), lunched with
Boston Mayor Kevin H. White, and traded quips with state Senate
President William M. Bulger on St. Patrick's Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought I could be funny, but Bulger is the funniest
S.O.B. I know,'' Mr. Sargent said. ``There was no way of beating
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Sargent's plain talk and self-deprecating wit were
undeniably popular with the electorate. Running against White in
1970, Mr. Sargent won by more than a quarter of a million votes,
even winning the mayor's home city.
</P>
<P>
   Freed from the ``acting'' governor label, Mr. Sargent made the
most of his mandate, signing more than 1,000 laws in 1971 alone. He
created a cabinet system, approved a dozen state colleges, pushed
for special education and public housing programs, stopped the
building of new expressways within Route 128, fought forprison
reform (introducing inmate furloughs) and safeguarded privacy
rights.
</P>
<P>
   But Mr. Sargent's most enduring legacy may have been his impact
upon the state's judiciary. He filled 190 judgeships, three times
as many as any previous governor (in part because judges were now
required to retire at 70), and the quality of the appointments was
generally regarded as excellent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frank Sargent was one of the finest human beings I've ever met
and certainly the best governor I've served under,'' David Bartley,
House speaker during Mr. Sargent's tenure, once said.
</P>
<P>
   By 1974, though, with inflation rampant and Watergate
aftershocks affecting Republican candidates everywhere, Mr. Sargent
found himself on shaky footing. Michael S. Dukakis, White's 1970
running mate, unseated Mr. Sargent by 200,000 votes that autumn.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a personal rejection, Mr. Sargent concluded. It was
``the price of hamburg.'' So he segued into political punditry,
writing a syndicated column, doing analysis on television and
radio, and serving as a senior lecturer at the Joint Center for
Urban Studies of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology and
Harvard University. But he had no desire to run for office again.
</P>
<P>
   Politics had been a grand adventure for Mr. Sargent, but he had
never meant for it to be his profession. After graduating from MIT
in 1939 (I.M. Pei was a classmate and friend), Mr. Sargent joined
the prestigious Boston architectural firm of Coolidge, Shepley,
Bulfinch and Abbott, then started his own firm of Sargent and
Sweeney in 1941.
</P>
<P>
   When World War II began, Mr. Sargent enlisted as an infantry
private, ended up commanding a rifle company with the 10th Mountain
Division in Italy and was awarded the Purple Heart, the Bronze Star
for heroism and the Combat Infantry Badge.
</P>
<P>
   Though he designed his rambling Dover house himself, Mr. Sargent
soon left the drafting board for the seashore, settling his family
on Cape Cod. He founded and ran a sporting goods store (the Goose
Hummock Shop) in Orleans, operated a charter fishing boat, and was
a guide for duck hunters.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Sargent was an ardent environmentalist before there was a
label for it. After he pounded on Governor Robert Bradford's desk
to demand something be done about overfishing, Bradford named Mr.
Sargent his director of marine fisheries. ``I told him, I'm awfully
busy with my store, but I'll start in,'' Mr. Sargent said. ``I had
no idea I'd take it for 10 years,''
</P>
<P>
   That set the hook in Mr. Sargent for politics. During the next
two decades he was the state's commissioner of natural resources,
director of fisheries and game, public works commissioner, and a
member of two federal commissions.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Sargent foresaw the ``rape of the Cape'' when most of Cape
Cod was still sand dunes and scrub pines, and he was the initial
crusader for what became the National Seashore.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  ``Unless we move fast, private developers are going to move
in with their bulldozers, rip apart all this natural beauty, and
jam those areas with cottages,'' Mr. Sargent predicted. ``And there
will be `no trespassing' and `no picnicking' signs all over the
place.''
</P>
<P>
   After heart problems sent him to the hospital and a
rehabilitation center last spring, Mr. Sargent was largely
housebound. ``I'm 83,'' he shrugged. ``What the hell are you going
to do?''
</P>
<P>
   After the Boston Globe ran a feature on Mr. Sargent earlier this
month, he said he was flooded with cards, letters and calls from
well-wishers. ``From people I know and people I don't know and
people I never heard of,'' Mr. Sargent mused.
</P>
<P>
   He was flattered and amused when visitors still referred to him
as ``governor.'' ``Don't call me governor,'' Mr. Sargent cracked.
``I'm unemployed.''
</P>
<P>
   It may have been two dozen years since Sarge had been in charge,
but the memory of his salty sibilance (``I have a rather raunchy
way of speaking.''), his infectious cackle, and his angular profile
endured. F.W. Sargent was the last working model of a vanished
make.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-98 2316EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
