<HEADER>
A2629 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLOOD-FEMA-TOURS-COX     10-22 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOOD-FEMA-TOURS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Disaster chief pledges quick help for Texas
 &HT;    By Mike Ward
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Federal disaster chief James Lee Witt, pledging
to provide fast assistance to thousands of Texans whose lives and
homes have been left in shambles by record-setting floods, said
Thursday the devastation follows a pattern of increasing weather
brutality nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems the flood events we get now are more serious than
they were a few years ago,'' said Witt, the director of the Federal
Emergency Management Agency. ``Instead of a two-inch or a four-inch
rain, we get 20 inches ... Events like this are getting stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   In Texas to begin a two-day survey of flood-devastated areas in
20 counties, Witt said 1998 has been a record year for weather
disasters across the country.
</P>
<P>
   While 168 people died across the country last year in disasters,
more than 400 have perished this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The destruction this year has been unbelievable,'' Witt said.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Witt and state disaster officials toured
flood-clobbered areas of New Braunfels and Comal County with local
officials as other FEMA officials raced to establish an assistance
network for victims. Among those on the tour was Comal County Judge
Carter Casteel _ whose own home was severely damaged, state
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Witt and Gov. George W. Bush are scheduled to tour
flooded areas in Victoria and Cuero.
</P>
<P>
   Witt said he wants to get aid programs up and running as quickly
as possible _ and hopes FEMA officials can cut checks or provide
other help to victims within 10 days of applying.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make sure this goes smoothly ... that it goes
quickly,'' Witt said after a morning briefing with state disaster
relief officials in Austin. ``When you lose everything you've
worked for in your life, in just a few minutes, you are
devastated.''
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton on Wednesday declared 20 counties federal
disaster areas, making them eligible for federal aid, and state
officials put preliminary damage estimates at $400 million.
</P>
<P>
   By Thursday, Bush had asked FEMA to add five Southeast Texas
counties _ Austin, Fort Bend, Harris, Montgomery and Waller _ to
the disaster zone, and other officials said at least five others
could be added before the flooding subsides.
</P>
<P>
   Such a designation makes victims eligible for federal assistance
_ such as money for temporary housing in motels and apartments,
Small Business Administration help, counseling services and
rebuilding assistance.
</P>
<P>
   More than 60 state agencies worked with FEMA Thursday in the
recovery effort, said Jo Schweikhard Moss of the Texas Division of
Emergency Management.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Millwee, state emergency management coordinator, said the
floods have made 1998 a record year for disasters. The flood decree
is the fourth federal emergency, compared with three each in 1993
and 1989.
</P>
<P>
   The 26 deaths reported so far compare with 27 people who died
during the 1994 floods that wracked Southeast Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been a remarkable year,'' Millwee said, noting that
the emergency-operations center _ activated during significant
state disasters _ has been in use about 160 days so far this year,
first for wildfires beginning in June and later for tropical storms
Charlie and Frances that pummeled Del Rio and Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
