<HEADER>
A2639 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLOOD23-COX     10-22 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLOOD23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Flood death toll rises
 &HT;    By Kelly Daniel
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Sunshine returned to Central Texas on Thursday,
but the toll from this week's deadly flooding mounted as divers
located the bodies of five missing people and South Texas towns
braced for record water surges today.
</P>
<P>
   The death toll stood at 28 after searchers Thursday morning
recovered the bodies of four San Antonio residents and 7-year-old
Devon McCoy of Giddings, who was swept away in a vehicle in
Caldwell County. About 2,800 people _ 1,100 in Cuero alone _ stayed
in 34 shelters open across the region. Two Lockhart residents
remained missing Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so sorry for everyone's loss,'' said Kathy McCoy, Devon's
mother, after her son's body was found.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush requested that five more counties be
declared disaster areas, bringing the total to 25, with more
requests for federal aid expected. James Lee Witt, director of the
Federal Emergency Management Agency, toured New Braunfels and other
flooded areas Thursday and compared the damage to the Midwestern
floods of 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, weather forecasters were watching a tropical
depression over the Gulf of Mexico and predicting more rain for the
early part of next week if the storm system does not shift. The
skies should remain clear and sunny through the weekend, however.
</P>
<P>
   Floodwaters were receding slowly, but 30 percent of Cuero
remained underwater, and authorities said 35 percent of Victoria
had been flooded. U.S. 183 south of Goliad was still under 6 feet
of water, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Wharton officials continued evacuating residents as the town
prepared for the Colorado River to surge at a record 48.5 feet
early this morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a strange animal since we're not having any rain,
the sun is shining and it's a beautiful day,'' said Wharton County
Judge Lawrence E. Naiser. ``We keep waiting and waiting and
waiting. This is torture.''
</P>
<P>
   Bay City, the last significant city before the Colorado rolls
into the Gulf of Mexico, should escape extensive flooding tonight
since the river is projected to crest at 41 feet _ 3 feet below
flood stage, said Bill McCann of the LCRA. It would still be at a
record level.
</P>
<P>
   The Guadalupe River was back in its banks in towns north of
Gonzales, though floodwaters were receding slowly, said Judy
Gardner of the Guadalupe-Blanco River Authority.
</P>
<P>
   Early Thursday, divers found the the bodies of San Antonio
residents Donna O'Bar, 65; her son, Richard Hartman, 47; Jennifer
Allensworth, 20; and Allensworth's 2-month-old baby, Mallory
Hartman, inside a white Lincoln Town Car submerged in 10 feet of
water in muddy Salado Creek.
</P>
<P>
   A Department of Public Safety helicopter had noticed a gasoline
slick on the creek Wednesday, and divers found the car in a
follow-up check.
</P>
<P>
   Justin Hartman of Bryan, the infant's father and O'Bar's
grandson, fainted when the car was pulled from the creek. Relatives
said he was traveling in separate vehicle when the Lincoln
disappeared. The family was last seen Saturday night in suburban
Jourdanton as they left a wedding reception.
</P>
<P>
   Later Thursday morning, searchers recovered Devon's body at the
base of a construction dam at Brushy Creek, about a mile from where
he disappeared Saturday. The boy was swept away when the sport
utility vehicle his mother was driving washed into Brushy Creek,
about two miles from Niederwald.
</P>
<P>
   A ranch foreman spotted the boy's body and flagged down a nearby
Army National Guard helicopter and Caldwell County sheriff's
deputies, authorities said. Divers on Tuesday had retrieved the
body of a 10-year-old family friend also swept away with Devon.
</P>
<P>
   Still missing were Leandro Acevedo, 71, and his wife, Melva, 60,
who left their son's home in Galena Park near Houston about 11 p.m.
Saturday headed toward Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Red Cross and Salvation Army began handing out
supplies Thursday as volunteers arrived from counties across
Central Texas to assist flood victims in their long trek back to
normalcy. As many as 14,000 people have evacuated their homes since
the floods began over the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to believe this all happened only last Saturday,''
said New Braunfels retiree R.J. Thorson, 76, standing near his
ruined home. ``It seems like an eternity.'' Southeast Austin
residents gathered donations of clothes, towels, linens and other
household items for 19 families whose homes were washed away by a
bloated Williamson Creek. In San Marcos, officials distributed more
than 300 kits, including brooms, mops, shovels and wet-vacuums, to
help people remove debris from their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Damage estimates continued to trickle in, but exact numbers were
not yet available. Statewide, the tally has been estimated at $400
million.
</P>
<P>
   With so many agencies working overtime, and with so many
disasters striking the state in succession, officials began to
worry about the impact on the state budget. ``It's been one thing
after another this year,'' said Joe Allbaugh, Bush's executive
assistant and top aide.
</P>
<P>
   So far, officials said, $8.3 million of the $12.8 million in the
state disaster relief fund has been spent on hurricanes, earlier
flooding and wildfires _ most for the National Guard and Texas
Forest Service. The fund still contains $4.5 million, a Bush
spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Other developments Thursday included:
</P>
<P>
   -More than 430 National Guard troops remained deployed, mostly
in the hardest-hit areas from Seguin south to Wharton, Victoria and
Cuero, with eight helicopters and 179 pieces of equipment.
</P>
<P>
   -Police had arrested 12 people in Guadalupe County and three
people in Comal County for looting. A 7 p.m. to 6 a.m. curfew
remained in effect for flood-damaged areas in New Braunfels.
</P>
<P>
   -The Barton Springs/Edwards Aquifer Conservation District
canceled its drought alert. The agency also said the heavy rains
may be enough to carry well users through winter, a time of
typically low water levels.
</P>
<P>
   American-Statesman staff writers Kim Sue Lia Perkes, Rebeca
Rodriguez, Angela Shah, Jason Spencer and Mike Ward contributed to
this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
