<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Yankees pause `to enjoy moment'
 &HT;    By I.J. Rosenberg
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Yankees season was so unbelievable that it brought
the usually stoic George Steinbrenner to tears.
</P>
<P>
   The Boss wept.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is truly, you can say it now, one of the greatest teams
in baseball,'' the emotional Yankees owner said after his team
defeated San Diego 3-0 Wednesday night to sweep the World Series.
``We really worked for this. This is as good a team as ever played.
You can't say the best, because how do you really know?''
</P>
<P>
   Now Steinbrenner and the Yankees face the task of keeping
together a young team that has the potential to win 125 games again
and its third World Series title in four years.
</P>
<P>
   It won't be easy.
</P>
<P>
   All-Star center fielder Bernie Williams and Series MVP Scott
Brosius are free agents. New York has to make a decision on a $2.5
million option for outfielder Darryl Strawberry, who is recovering
from colon cancer surgery. Tim Raines is a free agent. And starter
David Cone has a clause in his contract that gives him the option
of accepting or rejecting a $5.5 million salary for next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not thinking about that right now,'' Williams said. ``I'd
be a fool not to enjoy this moment.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees don't act as if Williams will be back. They have
offered a deal worth $8.25 million a season, but the feeling is he
will command more than $10 million a year. Arizona has that kind of
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is there is only so much money we can play
with,'' general manager Brian Cashman said.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees have plenty of young talent in the organization,
including Mike Lowell, who is considered one of the top third-base
prospects in baseball. Rookie left fielder Ricky Ledee had a great
postseason and could replace Williams in center field.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees will celebrate for the final time today,
participating in a parade through 14 blocks of Manhattan called the
``Canyon of Heroes.'' Mayor Rudolph Giuliani will give the players
a key to the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``We deserve to be compared with the best ever,'' first baseman
Tino Martinez said. ``We were like the Chicago Bulls.''
</P>
<P>
   Designated hitter Chili Davis said, ``We had high expectations.
Our owners had high expectations. Our fans had high expectations.
We had nothing to do but fail, and we didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been astounding,'' Steinbrenner said. ``That's the
best way to describe it. They just come through day after day. You
don't believe that it will happen. You don't believe they can do it
again, and they do. It's unbelievable.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
