<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush mulls political future; Mauro camp previews TV ads
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush said Thursday he is probably
on an up-or-out path that will lead either to a presidential race
in 2000 or an end to his career as a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Between campaign stops in Temple and Corpus Christi, Bush said
he doesn't think he would be interested in a third term as
governor, or any elected office other than president, if he wins
re-election Nov. 3.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would suspect, and I would guess, barring unforeseen
circumstances, that this would be my last term,'' said Bush, who,
according to polls, is headed for a lopsided win over Democrat
Garry Mauro. ``But I don't know for certain.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said a race for the U.S. Senate holds no interest for him.
On yet another day when he spent considerable time talking to
reporters and supporters about a potential presidential bid, Bush
said he will make up his mind on that race early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, Bush is trying to become the first Texas governor
elected to consecutive four-year terms, though he is not
guaranteeing he would serve another four years if re-elected.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I sit here right now,'' Bush said as he flew to South
Texas, ``I think two terms would probably be plenty. I don't want
to rule out anything for the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked point-blank if the only other campaign he might mount
after this year would be for president, Bush said, ``Yeah.''
</P>
<P>
   Later Thursday, returning from San Benito to Austin, Bush said
he has not thought about what he might do if he skips the
presidential race and does not seek a third term in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never looked really far down the road in life. I've
always been a spontaneous person,'' he said, adding, ``I'm not
concerned about my future. I'm concerned about my immediate future,
which is getting re-elected governor of Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   And on a day when he indicated he could be involved in his final
campaign as a candidate, Bush worked hard at stops in Temple,
Corpus Christi and San Benito to make sure his huge lead in the
polls does not backfire into voter complacency.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Billy Rogers, Mauro's campaign manager, said Hillary
Clinton has been asked to come to El Paso to be the featured
speaker at an Oct. 31 rally.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the first lady comes to Texas obviously it would energize
our base,'' said Rogers, adding that Mauro is ``hopeful'' that Ms.
Clinton will be able to attend. Mauro's campaign on Thursday also
previewed five, 30-second television ads airing around the state
beginning Friday. The ads will appear in Austin over the weekend
and in Dallas and Houston next week.
</P>
<P>
   Mauro introduces himself in each ad , makes clear he's running
for governor and highlights his positions _ and criticizes Bush's _
on Indian casino gambling, HMO regulation, education reform and
teacher pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm running for governor because I can't find anyone who can
name one thing that George Bush has done to help Texas families,''
Mauro says in one of the ads.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Mindy Tucker said recent voter opinion polls,
putting Bush well ahead of Mauro, show Texans believe Bush has a
good record and good plans for Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush has upheld the laws of Texas, proposed an
additional $3.6 billion for education, including money for
teachers' salary, and signed the toughest patient protection laws
in the country,'' Tucker said. ``Is Garry Mauro opposed to these
things?''
</P>
<P>
   American-Statesman staff writer Juan B. Elizondo, Jr.
contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
