<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Weinke proving he's a big-leaguer
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Sept. 12, 1998 _ a date which will live in infamy for
Chris Weinke, the starting quarterback at Florida State. A date
when Weinke thought that maybe riding the buses in the minor
leagues really wasn't so bad.
</P>
<P>
   Weinke is the 26-year-old sophomore who gave up pro baseball to
take another shot at college football. When he threw six
interceptions in a 24-7 loss at N.C. State, a lot of Seminole fans
questioned the wisdom of that decision. They also questioned the
judgment of coach Bobby Bowden, who entrusted one of college
football's most successful franchises to a guy who hadn't played
any significant minutes in a football game since George Bush was
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people were wondering what was going on,'' Weinke
said. ``And I was one of them.''
</P>
<P>
   But one of the reasons that Bowden has won 287 games is patience
in the face of adversity. Let's hang with Weinke, he told his
staff. Let's see if he comes around.
</P>
<P>
   Bowden's patience has been rewarded. Since the nightmare at N.C.
State, Weinke has gone five games and 149 passing attempts without
an interception. He comes into Saturday night's nationally
televised showdown with Georgia Tech (7 p.m., ESPN) with two
consecutive games with 300 or more passing yards. In wins over
Miami (26-14) and Clemson (48-0), Weinke completed 35 of 67 passes
(52.2 percent) for 618 yards and six touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you want is a guy who learns from his mistakes,'' Bowden
said. ``He's continually improving. That's all you can ask of
somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   In fairness to Weinke, the Florida State coaching staff must
take some responsibility for the debacle at N.C. State. Emboldened
by his performance in the opener against Texas A&AMP;M _ 21 of 36, 207
yards _ they used an off week to add considerably more to Weinke's
playbook for the trip to Raleigh. The extra load confused Weinke
and made him tentative.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, it was frustrating,'' said Weinke, a native of St. Paul,
Minn. ``I knew what we wanted to do offensively, but I couldn't
make myself slow down. It seemed like I was always in a hurry to
make the throw instead of just waiting and executing the offense.''
</P>
<P>
   After N.C. State, the watchword for Weinke became simplicity.
The offense was scaled back to give him a better chance to succeed.
He wasn't asked to make as many complicated reads or as many
difficult decisions. The emphasis was shifted to better execution
of fewer plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't eliminate everything, but we started running the
ball better to open up the passing game,'' Weinke said. ``I just
knew that the main thing I needed to do was get better. I just
needed to slow down my motor and quit rushing my throws. I needed
to take what the defense was giving me and not try to hit the big
play.''
</P>
<P>
   The strategy worked, as Weinke began to eliminate the mistakes.
Still, Weinke said he wasn't completely satisfied with his play
until Florida State traveled to Miami on Oct. 10. Weinke completed
17 passes for 316 yards and a pair of touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the first time I thought we went out and did exactly
what we wanted to do,'' Weinke said. ``It felt really good.''
</P>
<P>
   Last week against Clemson it got even better, as Weinke threw
for 302 yards and four touchdowns to four different receivers. The
scoring throws covered 40, 48, 12 and 15 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, we feel like we're clicking,'' Weinke said. ``We're
not where we want to be just yet, but we're getting closer.''
</P>
<P>
   Bowden gives the credit to Weinke for not losing faith when all
those around him _ the head coach included _ began to doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he had six interceptions against N.C. State, he never
lost his composure,'' Bowden said. ``He never let on to us that he
was not confident. Weinke, evidently, was challenged by those
interceptions and is determined not to let that happen again.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
