<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-GATECH-KEYS23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tech's 5-game run driven by 5 factors
 &HT;    WITH FBC-FSU-WEINKE
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Georgia Tech got smacked in the face by Boston
College 41-31 to open the season six weeks ago, the Yellow Jacket
defense was embarrassed, Tech fans were irate, and prospects for
the rest of the 1998 season looked bleak.
</P>
<P>
   But something happened in the next five games. Tech won all of
them and is undefeated in the ACC with a chance at the title, as
Florida State arrives for a Saturday night showdown on ESPN.
</P>
<P>
   Five elements stand out as reasons for the turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   First is the emergence of Dez White. Second is the play of
Tech's special teams. Third, the Yellow Jackets have been able to
offset some defensive problems by scoring with turnovers. Fourth is
Tech's pass rush, which didn't exist against Boston College but
made the difference in the waning moments of the Virginia win.
</P>
<P>
   The overriding element in each of those four factors is Tech's
confidence. How else to explain erasing Virginia's 21-point lead
Saturday? How else does Tech rebound from one of its most
disappointing starts into one of its best stretches ever?
</P>
<P>
   Here's a closer look at the five:
</P>
<P>
   Dez White. Tech came into the season with doubts at receiver
because of the loss of Harvey Middleton and Derrick Steagall and
injuries to Mike Sheridan (knee) and Jon Muyres (foot). White has
done more than answer the call; he's elbowing such players as Peter
Warrick and Torry Holt for a share of the ACC spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   White started out tentative against Boston College, with a
couple drops on his way to a five-catch, 74-yard, no-touchdown day.
But at North Carolina, he repeatedly frustrated two-time
All-American cornerback Dre Bly and beat him twice for touchdowns
of 56 and 20 yards.
</P>
<P>
   He's had at least one touchdown in every game since Boston
College and three games of 100 yards receiving or more. He burned
Virginia for 243 yards and three touchdowns, two in the last 8:13.
</P>
<P>
   Special teams. The Yellow Jackets have had some blunders,
including Rodney Williams' attempt to score at North Carolina on a
failed field goal and giving up a fumble return for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Kicker Brad Chambers, who missed a 34-yard field goal and barely
made a 23-yarder against Boston College, booted a career-long
47-yard field goal in the fourth quarter against Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Also against the Cavaliers, Charlie Rogers returned a punt 54
yards for a touchdown. Williams kept Tech in good field position
with three of five punts of 50 or more yards and four of eight
kickoffs into the end zone. On the other four kickoffs, Tech's
coverage limited Virginia to an average field position of the 18.
</P>
<P>
   Tech's special teams first made a difference against N.C. State,
taking a safety on a punt snap out of the end zone and then getting
a punt block from Travares Tillman that Jason Bostic returned for a
touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive scoring. Tech has forced a quarterback fumble and
returned it for a score five games in a row now, which is an NCAA
record.
</P>
<P>
   Offenses are unable to concentrate on one or two Tech defenders.
Delaunta Cameron and Nate Stimson are repeat performers, but five
others also have contributed to the turnovers _ Jesse Tarplin,
Roderrick Roberts, Matt Uremovich, Felipe Clay and Bostic.
</P>
<P>
   Pass rush. Boston College quarterback Scott Mutryn wasn't
bothered by Tech, but N.C. State's Jamie Barnette, Virginia's Aaron
Brooks and Duke's Spencer Romine can't say the same.
</P>
<P>
   The Yellow Jackets are blitzing and rotating a number of players
up front to keep the linemen fresh. After zero sacks against Boston
College and one against New Mexico State, Tech got three against
North Carolina and five in each of its last three games.
</P>
<P>
   Tarplin called the Boston College game the worst of his career.
Since then, the defensive end has piled up seven sacks, two more
than he had all last season.
</P>
<P>
   Stimson, moved from tackle in the Boston College game to end,
proved in the Virgina game that he's a force from the outside. He
pressured Brooks on two critical plays _ one to force the fumble
that Cameron returned for a touchdown, the other on Virginia's last
play from scrimmage when Brooks drew an intentional grounding
penalty.
</P>
<P>
   Confidence. The Jackets admit they had too much, or the wrong
kind, against BC. Since then, they've used confidence to their
advantage, going into North Carolina for their first win since 1945
and winning two of Tech's ``Big Three'' conference games, against
N.C. State and Virginia, with one left to go.
</P>
<P>
   Confidence is what Tech hasn't had against Florida State since
the crushing loss in 1992. It's what could make all the difference
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
