<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS-NOTES23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    DeBerg has a number of connections on Jets
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The New York media are having a blast with the
possibility 44-year-old Falcons quarterback Steve DeBerg might
start against the Jets on Sunday, and not just because he would
become the oldest player to start an NFL game.
</P>
<P>
   A few Jets, including QB Vinny Testaverde, have beenteammates of
DeBerg. In fact, DeBerg and Testaverde still live near each other
in Tampa Bay, where they played together in 1987 and 1992.
</P>
<P>
   They even worked out together last spring.
</P>
<P>
   But DeBerg made it more fun Wednesday, when he was on a
conference call with New York reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing the media was going to ask about the possibility of him
starting instead of injured Chris Chandler, DeBerg began by saying,
``I hope you guys got the announcement that I retired this morning.
This is not part of my deal. Mop-up duty was fine.''
</P>
<P>
   Jets H-back Keith Byars, a teammate of DeBerg in Miami in 1993,
said, ``(DeBerg) is always the life of the party.''
</P>
<P>
   He remembered DeBerg showing up at practice wearing an old
leather helmet and black high-tops, like Johnny Unitas used to
wear. It only seems as if DeBerg has played that long.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's certainly one of the best coaches I've seen in the game _
even when he wasn't coaching,'' Testaverde said. ``He showed me
quite a few different things this year that I really worked on, and
I'm continuing to use.''
</P>
<P>
   Vacillating Vinny
</P>
<P>
   Testaverde has had an up-and-down career, but he's on a definite
upswing. He's 3-0 as a starter and is the No. 2-ranked passer in
the NFL (108.8).
</P>
<P>
   Still, Jets coach Bill Parcells also likes backup Glenn Foley.
For proof, consider that Foley started three games, and when he was
injured, the job remained his even though Testaverde won two games
in his absence. The job became Testaverde's, however, after a 30-10
loss at St. Louis on Oct. 11.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one works harder than (Testaverde),'' Parcells said. ``He's
very diligent. If (quarterbacks coach, and former Falcon head coach
Dan Henning) says something to him, this guy makes sure every word
is clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``He manages a game well, and he has more experience, so he does
less dumb things. But Foley has some characteristics that are
admirable. He's not afraid to pull the trigger on some things. It's
a tradeoff.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking at the Jets
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons are coming off their most physical game of the
season, and the Jets will play them the same way. They also make an
opponent adjust a lot. On offense, they are not shy about running
in passing situations, trying to take advantage because a defense
has more cornerbacks on the field.
</P>
<P>
   On defense, cornerbacks Aaron Glenn and Otis Smith are very
physical.
</P>
<P>
   ``They do a great job of scheming you ... and Glenn and Smith
play all over the field, and play a lot of bump and run,'' Atlanta
coach Dan Reeves said. ``They'll come in with a lot of different
blitzes. Sometimes, they'll have one defensive lineman and five
defensive backs and a few linebackers.''
</P>
<P>
   Police chase
</P>
<P>
   Suwanee police took off in their cars from Falcons practice
Thursday after a man set up a tripod with a high-powered lens on
his camera. They did not catch him. The man was in a gas station
parking lot at the southeast corner of the practice facility. He
got in a pickup truck when approached by off-duty officers employed
by the Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   Extra points
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons on Sunday return to Giants Stadium for the second
time in three weeks, but Reeves said there will be a big difference
between this game and the Oct. 11 game in which Atlanta beat the
Giants 34-20. It's a day game rather than night game, and, ``The
Jets crowd is totally different,'' he said. ``They're much more
rowdy than Giants fans.'' ... Former University of Georgia player
Jason Ferguson is starting at DT for New York, and former Murphy
High and University of Georgia standout Mo Lewis, a LB, has started
all 111 games in his eight-year career. ... Jets TE Fred Baxter
(knee) is out, and LB Chad Cascadden has been downgraded from
questionable to doubtful. Parcells said Cascadden will not play. DB
Chris Hayes (leg) remains questionable.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
