<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLPREVIEW23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Steelers-Chiefs a pivotal matchup for both teams
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Six years after he sold his house in suburban Kansas
City and took a considerable loss in the transaction, Bill Cowher
still regrets he didn't just rent out the place.
</P>
<P>
   The Pittsburgh coach at least could have avoided hotels during
the Steelers' near-annual visits to a place where Cowher served as
defensive coordinator for Marty Schottenheimer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you leave (a city), even after you've been there a
while, and you forget the street names and stuff like that,''
Cowher said. ``But when it comes to Kansas City, the league
apparently likes to make sure that doesn't happen to me.''
</P>
<P>
   The struggling Steelers face the cheerless Chiefs on Monday
night, and it represents the fourth matchup since '92 of Cowher and
his mentor.
</P>
<P>
   All four games have been played at Arrowhead Stadium, three on
Monday Night Football, and the Schottenheimer-Cowher series stands
at two victories apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Although the game probably won't be aesthetic, given the
offensive shortcomings of the two clubs, the coaching matchup and
the intensity of recent Steelers-Chiefs bloodlettings make it the
marquee game on the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``And both of us desperately need a win,'' Chiefs quarterback
Elvis Grbac emphasized.
</P>
<P>
   A preseason pick by many people to represent the AFC in Super
Bowl XXXIII, the Chiefs already trail division rival Denver by two
games. Pittsburgh is a game behind Jacksonville in the AFC Central
and is counting on the Broncos to top the Jaguars on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The other ``bests'' for Week 8 of the league schedule:
</P>
<P>
   Upset opportunity: By late Sunday, fans might recall the day's
events as ``(Under) Dog Day Afternoon''' so numerous are the upset
possibilities. A trifecta of New England over Miami, Cincinnati
over Oakland and Denver over Minnesota is inviting. The best bet
might be the Lions, smoked 29-6 by the Vikings five weeks ago in
Charlie Batch's debut but playing much better now that the rookie
quarterback has reduced his turnovers.
</P>
<P>
   Individual matchup: There will be plenty of collisions between
Lions tailback Barry Sanders and underrated Minnesota middle
'backer Ed McDaniel. Even more compelling is the battle between
Falcons cornerback Ray Buchanan and Jets wide receiver Keyshawn
Johnson, who finally is playing to his potential. Buchanan will
give away six inches in height but nothing in the verbal jousting.
</P>
<P>
   Fantasy play: Even if John Friesz replaces ailing Seattle
starter Warren Moon (broken rib), big-play wideout Joey Galloway
will torch a San Diego secondary forced to play the rest of the
season without injured cornerback Dwayne Harper.
</P>
<P>
   Grudge match: The Jaguars' loss at Buffalo stole some of the
luster from the Jacksonville-Denver contest. No matter, though,
because none of the acrimony has subsided. The Jaguars derailed
Denver's Super Bowl express two years ago. The Broncos countered by
trampling Jacksonville with 300-plus rushing yards in a playoff win
last season.
</P>
<P>
   Division game: New England is neither as good as it looked two
weeks ago in smashing the Chiefs nor as bad as it appeared in
Monday's loss to the Jets. The Patriots have possess more offensive
playmakers, however, than the Dolphins, however. That should be
enough to run their mastery over Jimmy Johnson to four wins in a
row.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
