<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2710 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATIONAL-GUARD23-COX     10-22 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATIONAL-GUARD23-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Austin one of 10 sites in national anti-terrorism plan
 &HT;    By Cara Tanamachi
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ When a religious cult in Japan released a highly
toxic chemical in the Tokyo subway tunnels in 1995, more than three
hours passed before officials, taken completely by surprise,
identified the toxin as sarin gas.
</P>
<P>
   The delay added to the confusion, as emergency workers struggled
to treat hundreds of subway riders suffering from exposure to the
gas, which killed 12 and injured a thousand more.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to prevent similar chaos in case chemical or biological
weapons are unleashed on American soil, Congress this month
authorized two programs that will make the nation better able to
deal with terrorist attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Central Texas will play a key role in the government's efforts
as a site for the programs _ one that will create a National Guard
special response team and another that will provide training for
local police and fire departments.
</P>
<P>
   The National Guard response team, called a Rapid Assessment and
Initial Detection or RAID team, will be one of 10 strategically
placed across the country. Austin was chosen for its relatively
central location. The teams,each made up of 22 specially trained
Guard members, will be in place by the fall of 2000 and would help
local police, fire and EMS officials respond to acts of terrorism,
said Charles Cragin,cq the senior Defense Department official
responsible for policy oversight in the military reserves.
</P>
<P>
   ``America is a wide-open society _ this is the way we have built
our nation,'' said Cragin, who was in Austin on Thursday to speak
on a separate topic at a conference of the Defense Advisory
Committee on Women in the Service. ``Because of this, we are very
vulnerable to attacks at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Cragin quoted Secretary of Defense William Cohen, who called
biological and chemical weapons the ``poor man's atomic bomb''
because they are easy to acquire and transport, and are
catastrophically lethal.
</P>
<P>
   Cragin said there have already been attempts to use chemical
agents in the United States. He points to the World Trade Center
bombing in New York in 1993, where terrorists had planned to leak a
chemical agent through an explosion, but had improperly constructed
their bomb, so it incinerated the chemical when it exploded.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't do a very good job with their plan, but if they
had, can you image the scope of the catastrophe?'' he said. ``We
also have serious domestic threats. What if the next Unabomber uses
biological weapons?''
</P>
<P>
   The RAID team, Cragin said, would have the expertise to help
local authorities quickly identify and contain a chemical or
biological agent as well as provide additional manpower to help
treat victims. In cases of biological weapons, often there is an
incubation period, as with the deadly bacterial agent anthrax. The
RAID team would help confine a spread, Cragin said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Defense Department team in Austin, Central
Texas will also be home to a federally sponsored program for
training up to 1 million police, fire and emergency medical
personnel to deal with chemical and biological attacks.
</P>
<P>
   Money for the training program was part of the massive federal
spending bill approved this week by Congress. Under the bill, Texas
A&AMP;M University will receive $3 million in the coming year to
establish the training program in conjunction with Louisiana State
University, New Mexico State University and the Nevada
nuclear-weapons test site. Each participant will receive $2 million
for training and facilities, plus $1 million each for equipment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas is taking a leading role in preparing America's
emergency response to acts of terrorism,'' said Sen. Kay Bailey
Hutchison, R-Texas, who worked to secure the money for Texas A&AMP;M
from the 1999 budget for the U.S. Justice Department. ``We are
forming the basis of a unified, national strategy to respond to
terroristic acts _ and sending a message to those with evil intent
that we mean business.''
</P>
<P>
   Staff writer Christi Harlan contributed to this report.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
