<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 23:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2711 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PHIL-GRAMM-COX     10-22 1117
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHIL-GRAMM-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gramm vs. the CRA: How Texas senator Texas killed banking bill
 &HT;    By Christi Harlan
 &HT;    c. 1998 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Congress appeared poised this year to dismantle
a Depression-era law that has prohibited consumers from one-stop
shopping for banking, insurance, stocks and bonds.
</P>
<P>
   But Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, with his objection to a tiny piece
of the overhaul, stalled a reform that had been 20 years in the
making.
</P>
<P>
   His beef: the Community Reinvestment Act, a 1977 federal law
that requires banks and savings and loan associations to record the
gender, race and income of loan applicants and report each year
whether those applicants received loans.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm said the law has been turned into an extortion device by
groups representing consumers and minorities. These ``professional
protest groups,'' Gramm charged, use the publicly available data
about lending practices to pressure banks and S&AMP;Ls to set quotas
for lending and hiring and to financially support the protesting
groups.
</P>
<P>
   The Community Reinvestment Act, designed to ensure that banks
were making loans in communities where they receive deposits, ``has
become a rich source for extortion and kickbacks,'' Gramm said in
an interview last week. Asked why banks don't complain, he said
that ``the merchants being shaken down by the Mafia don't complain
either.''
</P>
<P>
   Gramm's objection, shared by a few other senators, stopped the
legislation from coming to a vote in the Senate. Even if the bill
had passed, presidential advisers had enough doubts about the bill
that a veto from President Clinton was considered a good
possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gramm played a big enough role in stopping the
financial-services overhaul that he was blamed by some for killing
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came closer to passing comprehensive financial services
reform in the 105th Congress than we have in a generation,'' said
Dean Sackett, a vice president of the National Association of
Professional Insurance Agents, a proponent of the bill.
``Unfortunately, turf battles within the Clinton administration,
the looming threat of a presidential veto, opposition by key
senators to Community Reinvestment Act requirements and the narrow
interests of a small minority prevailed over the interests of the
country at large and those affected by the legislation.''
</P>
<P>
   Gramm's willingness to scuttle the overhaul of financial
services because it could expand the Community Reinvestment Act
beyond banks was the most recent example of his lack of compunction
about delaying or even killing widely supported bills that contain
items he opposes. Earlier this year, for example, he delayed for
weeks an agriculture-research bill because he objected to a
provision that restored food stamps to legal immigrants, including
children, whose aid had been cut off under the 1996 welfare
reforms. The agriculture bill eventually passed, unlike the
financial-services bill.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm's willingness to do in the banking bill also gives a hint
of what might be in store if Sen. Al D'Amato, R-N.Y., loses his
re-election bid Nov. 3 and Gramm succeeds him as chairman of the
powerful Senate Banking Committee, which oversees banks as well as
securities and federal housing policy. Earlier this week, the trade
groups for banks, insurance companies and securities firms that had
backed the bill conceded defeat in a joint statement.
</P>
<P>
   They also pledged to work together for passage next year. The
ease with which Gramm blocked the bill, known as H.R. 10, also
illustrates continued uncertainty in Congress about undoing the
Glass-Steagall Act, written in the Depression to prevent the
concentration of banking, insurance and securities in mammoth firms
whose failures could wreak untold havoc.
</P>
<P>
   After many failed attempts at rewrites, Congress thought it got
it right this year, but H.R. 10 squeaked out of the House in May by
only one vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``It needed some more fixes to be a really good bill,'' said
Rep. Ken Bentsen, D-Houston, a former investment banker and a
member of the House Banking Committee. Bentsen voted against H.R.
10, saying he was concerned about the assignment of regulators for
the new multipurpose entities that the bill would create. He also
said he thought the bill shortchanged small banks.
</P>
<P>
   Similar concerns by others kept the bill on hold in the Senate
until September, when D'Amato finally brought it before the Banking
Committee. It emerged from committee in mid-September and was
headed for a full Senate vote with the blessing of the banking,
insurance and securities industries, all of whom overcame historic
rivalries to back the Senate's version of H.R. 10.
</P>
<P>
   Then Gramm took to the Senate floor Sept. 30 and declared: ``I
intend to do everything in my power to impede this bill . . . to
use all of the rules of the Senate, no matter how long it takes, no
matter how difficult it may be.''
</P>
<P>
   He laid out his concerns that the bill expanded the Community
Reinvestment Act and ``literally set up the vehicle for billions of
dollars to be extorted from financial institutions in America by
people who are professional protesters.'' In an interview, Gramm
said he was thinking of groups such as ACORN, the Association of
Community Organizations for Reform Now, a consumer group that often
stages protests of businesses it considers unfriendly to the
elderly and poor.
</P>
<P>
   On hearing Gramm's charges, ACORN policy analyst Patrick Woodall
in Washington, said, ``We must be the worst extortionists and
kidnappers in America.'' The group filed objections with the
Federal Reserve to three of the five big bank mergers this year;
not one was disallowed, Woodall noted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reality is that community groups have an incredibly
difficult time with lenders who are in theory the lifeblood of the
community,'' Woodall said. ``We do end up exerting pressure because
that's what it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   ACORN and other groups also seek and receive financial support
from banks _ a practice Gramm said he would have moved to outlaw if
the bill had come to a vote. Woodall said the financial support
helps ACORN screen loan applicants for the banks; Gramm called the
practice extortion. Banks themselves said they have noticed ``some
heavy-handed tactics'' by groups wielding lending records under
CRA, but the banks have learned to deal with both the pressure and
the paper work that the law creates, according to Pattie Cinelli,
spokeswoman for the American Bankers Association. The association
supported H.R. 10.
</P>
<P>
   Was the bill worth killing over CRA? ``Not for the American
Bankers Association members,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
