<SLUG> BC-FBC-USC-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC SECONDARY EXPECTS BIG TEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With Oregon quarterback Akili Smith's vaunted
ability to elude a pass rush, the USC defensive line knows it will
have problems containing the Heisman Trophy candidate.
</P>
<P>
   But the real test could come for the Trojans secondary, which
will be forced to cover receivers for a longer time than usual.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got our hands full,'' cornerback Daylon McCutcheon said.
``It's hard enough to cover regular receivers. When you learn the
cornerback position, you get a feel for routes, but when a
quarterback scrambles, the receiver is running natural, against the
route. You don't practice against that.''
</P>
<P>
   McCutcheon is also worried Oregon may have Smith run more
against the Trojans, with starting tailback Reuben Droughns out for
the season with a broken ankle.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's able to win with his arm and win with his leg,''
McCutcheon said. ``They're probably expecting him to make even more
plays now that they're using new running backs.''
</P>
<P>
   USC coach Paul Hackett said he is confident the secondary will
meet the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have three cornerbacks and two safeties that we can play in
the nickel situation and feel very good,'' Hackett said. ``I think
our secondary has been one of the real strong parts of the team all
year long.''
</P>
<P>
   Offensive line banged up: There are no major injuries along the
offensive line, but a growing number of players are nursing nagging
injuries. Left tackle Brent McCaffrey missed Wednesday's practice
with a sore ankle, right tackle Matt Welch is still recovering from
mononucleosis and his replacement, Ken Bowen, strained his groin
Thursday. Reserve Rome Douglas is bothered by a hip flexor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today and yesterday were so up in the air,'' Hackett said.
``I've been assured everybody's injuries are so mild (that I
shouldn't) worry about it. We've got some bumps and bruises.''
</P>
<P>
   USC had Donta Kendrick work out at left and right tackle, and
starting guard Jason Grain also practiced at several positions,
just in case someone is unable to play.
</P>
<P>
   Hackett may cancel today's practice at Autzen Stadium, because
he is concerned about giving the injured Trojans more time to heal.
</P>
<P>
   Cusano might play: Although he didn't practice Thursday, Hackett
said linebacker Mark Cusano (sore left thigh) could play in an
emergency situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very discouraging today,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore Zeke Moreno, who had nine tackles last week against
Washington State, will start.
</P>
<P>
   Penalty problems: USC had 11 penalties against Washington State,
but Hackett said the Trojans are showing signs of improvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We only had six or seven major penalties,'' he said. ``I
thought we made a little bit of a stride.''
</P>
<P>
   That said, it's doubtful the Trojans can afford another
double-digit penalty performance against Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're now going to go into a couple games where every little
inch makes a difference,'' Hackett said.
</P>
<P>
   USC leads the Pacific-10 Conference with 74 penalties in seven
games.
</P>
<P>
   Moving up the charts: After his seven-catch explosion against
Washington State, wide receiver Billy Miller of Westlake Village is
now tied for the team lead in receptions (23) with R.Jay Soward.
</P>
<P>
   Woods still out: Wide receiver Quincy Woods will miss his second
straight road trip with a sore knee. X-rays performed on the knee
were negative, and Woods may take a magnetic resonance test next
week if the inflammation persists.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
