<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-PADRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROUD IN DEFEAT, AND NOT WITHOUT REASON 
</HEADLINE>
  (af) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO, Calif. _ It sounds strange to say a team that was
just swept out of the World Series did not get embarrassed as well.
But even though the San Diego Padres dropped four straight games to
the Yankees, they were never made to look foolish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, we got beat four games in a row,'' said Tony Gwynn, who
batted .500 for the Series. ``But three of them, we made them earn
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres took three-run leads into the seventh innings of
Games 1 and 3. And Game 4 on Wednesday was scoreless after five
innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely feel like the Series was pretty close,'' Kevin
Brown, the San Diego ace who struck out 13 Yankees in 141/3 innings
over two Series starts, said Wednesday night. ``We were one break,
one pitch away from it being a totally different Series. I can't
for the life of me think of one good break we had the whole Series.
They had the talent, yes. But like Wednesday night, they had
everything go their way, too.''
</P>
<P>
   There were two turning points. In Game 1, the Padres' middle
relievers, handed a 5-2 lead by Brown, could not hold it until it
was time for Trevor Hoffman, the closer supreme, to enter the game.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 3, Hoffman failed to maintain a 3-2 lead in the eighth
inning in his only appearance of the Series.
</P>
<P>
   Had the Padres taken Game 1, they would have been assured a
split in New York and there would have been less pressure on them
at home. Had they held onto Game 3, they would have been down by
2-1, with Brown, who finished with a post-season record of 46
strikeouts, pitching the next day with a chance to even the Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``You take away Game 2, and all three games were pretty evenly
played,'' Kevin Towers, the San Diego general manager, said.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Bruce Bochy said: ``We had them on the ropes and they
came back on us. They had no weakness. And whey they got breaks,
they took advantage of them. Sometimes you make your own breaks.
But I don't think we got a lot of them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees were just the better club, one that Bochy said
``should go down as one of the best teams ever.'' The Yankees had
the deeper pitching, both starting and in relief, the more balanced
lineup, the stronger bench. And aside from Gwynn, who went 8 for 16
and fittingly singled in his final at-bat, the heart of the San
Diego order was more or less silent.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Vaughn, who hit 50 home runs in the regular season, did
belt two more in his first three at-bats of Game 1, but he went
hitless in his final 12 at-bats. Ken Caminiti, the National
League's most valuable player in 1996, went 2 for 14 and tied the
World Series record for most strikeouts (7) in a four-game Series.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn and Caminiti were playing hurt, Vaughn having strained
his left quadriceps and Caminiti being bothered by a groin pull.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't help,'' Caminiti said. ``I couldn't move the right
way out in the field. And to try and hit, especially right-handed,
I couldn't put any weight down there to twist on it. I know I could
have hit them. I can hit anybody when I'm feeling good.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a great team,'' Caminiti added. ``But I still feel in
my heart that we could compete with them if we were strong and
able.''
</P>
<P>
   Caminiti, Brown, Wally Joyner and Steve Finley are all free
agents who may have played their final game for the Padres. Even if
a resolution to build a new ball park passes in a city referendum
on Nov. 3, Towers said it was doubtful he would be able to re-sign
all four.
</P>
<P>
   Brown is the first priority. The Padres are hoping to sign him
for four years at $10 million to $11 million each. Even if he
returns, the pitching coach Dave Stewart, who has greatly helped
the staff, most likely will not. He wants a front-office job, and
Toronto, if not other teams, is said to be interested.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night, the record Qualcomm Stadium crowd of 65,427
spent 20 minutes on its feet after the game, demanding a curtain
call from the Padres, who had retreated to a somber clubhouse.
Thanks for everything you have done for us, even if it was four
games short, the fans seemed to be saying.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of the most special moments in my life as an
athlete,'' Hoffman said after he and the bullpen had been greeted
with a thundering ovation as they walked off the field while the
Yankees piled on one another on the pitcher's mound.
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn felt the same way. He said he was thankful for finally
having the opportunity to play a game at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It had been 14 years between trips to the World Series for
Gwynn, the eight-time batting champion. ``I don't want to have to
wait 14 years again,'' he said. ``I'll be 52.''
</P>
</TEXT>
