<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-TALKS-1023-1STLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    EDs: re-tops with Hussein joining talks, Palestinian charter;
updates throughout
 &HT;    CLINTON URGES MIDDLE EAST LEADERS: TRY TO MAINTAIN 'MOMENTUM OF
PEACE'
 &HT;    With ISRAEL-SETTLERS-1023; MIDEAST-BUDDY-1023.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.1998 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WYE MILLS, Md. _ Israeli and Palestinian leaders were grinding
their way toward a Middle East peace agreement late Thursday night,
amid determined diplomacy by President Clinton, a dramatic appeal
by Jordan's ailing King Hussein and a reported breakthrough on the
contentious issue of eliminating Palestinian language calling for
the destruction of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Hussein, who has been in the country undergoing cancer
treatment, praised some hard-won progress in day eight of the
talks, and urged Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat to take the final steps toward
peace, for the sake of ''their children,'' and ''their children's
children,'' said U.S. State Department spokesman James Rubin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very strong push by the king,'' Rubin told reporters
at a late-night break in the talks Thursday. ``The participants
were all moved by his presence.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the mood of growing optimism, though, Rubin cautioned that
ninth-inning snags remained over issues critical to both sides.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the Middle East peace process, end-games can be longer than
perhaps one would wish,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been at some tough, hard bargaining,'' he said, but ''we
don't know how long this phase will go on.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, who journeyed for the sixth time in eight days to the
secluded compound where the talks have been held since last
Thursday, was still meeting shortly before midnight with Arafat and
Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
   Joined by U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, National
Security Adviser Samuel E. ``Sandy'' Berger and a gaggle of other
high-level foreign policy aides, the group met around a roaring
fireplace in a large dining room at the Wye River Conference
Center, while American diplomats shuttled in and out from an attic
enclave some dubbed ``the cobweb room.''
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu and Arafat, however, remained far apart, Rubin said,
on half a dozen issues that frame the heart and soul of a peace
accord.
</P>
<P>
   Among the sticking points were questions over Israeli troop
withdrawals, the treatment of suspected terrorists by Palestinians
and safe passage across Israeli-controlled land for Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   In an optimistic sign, though, Rubin signalled that both sides
had narrowed their differences over part of the Palestine
Liberation Organization's charter that calls for Israel's
destruction.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the Palestinian covenant issue, substantial progress has
been made,'' Rubin said in a statement, ``but details are still
being worked.''
</P>
<P>
   The difficulty of the issues and the severity of the remaining
gaps, after eight days and nights of negotiations, left the talks
suspended in a stomach-wrenching netherworld between culmination
and collapse.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope the parties will seize this opportunity and not retreat
from the clear moment to capture the momentum of peace,'' Clinton
said at the White House, before journeying by helicopter to the
summit, where he has spent more than 70 working hours since the
talks began. ``The hardest decisions now, at last, are on the
table.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sign of bargaining at its most earnest, Netanyahu and
Arafat held a rare one-on-one meeting for two hours in the
afternoon, as their aides huddled in side meetings trying to come
to terms with various aspects of an overall deal.
</P>
<P>
   By day's end, though, they had yet to reach agreement on a host
of important issues.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're getting there, on some of them,'' said Rubin, who
compared the atmosphere to that of a last-minute political
horsetrading session on the eve of a critical legislative vote.
</P>
<P>
   ''It had a little bit of the flavor of a legislative session,
drawing toward the close, where people were working very hard,''
Rubin told reporters gathered near the conference center, where the
talks are unfolding at a 1,000-acre riverside retreat.
</P>
<P>
   ''But that doesn't mean that they will draw to a close,'' Rubin
cautioned.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are still obstacles,'' he said. ''I would say it's in
the half-dozen category.''
</P>
<P>
   At the core of the talks is a proposal for Israeli troops to
withdraw from an additional 13 percent of the occupied West Bank,
in exchange for a Palestinian commitment to combat anti-Israeli
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement would leave some 40 percent of the West Bank
under full, or partial, control of Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   Under a U.S. proposal, agents of the Central Intelligence Agency
would assist Palestinians in handling difficult terrorist problems.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu is seeking additional promises from the Palestinians,
specifically over the issue of how to handle suspected terrorists
in territory under Palestinian control.
</P>
<P>
   Netanyahu is also insisting on the specific recension of a
provision in the Palestinians' charter that calls for the
destruction of Israel. Arafat counters that the policy-making arm
of the Palestinian Authority has rescinded the provision -- even
though it is yet to be officially excised by a broader, 700-member
legislative body.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat, for his part, is pressing for promises of additional
Israeli troop withdrawals from the West Bank, as called for in the
1993 Oslo accords that spawned the current peace process.
</P>
<P>
   That process has been stalemated for 19 months.
</P>
<P>
   The Wye talks are an attempt to advance the process toward
so-called final, or permanent, status talks, which, under the Oslo
accords, are to be completed by May 4.
</P>
<P>
   Permanent status talks would be aimed at resolving the most
difficult issues remaining in a conflict that has endured for half
a century, including the future of Jerusalem, which both Israelis
and Palestinians claim, and a host of economic, territorial and
security issues.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
