<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2789 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIAMI-CORRUPTION-540&AMP;     10-22 0818
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIAMI-CORRUPTION-540&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN MIAMI, HINTS OF LOVE TRIANGLE PUT NEW TWIST ON A CASE 
</HEADLINE>
  (dl) 
 By MIREYA NAVARRO   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ When Miami City Commissioner Humberto Hernandez Jr. was
convicted in state court of helping cover up voter fraud in last
November's election, many in this city saw the case as part of
Miami's healing from a period of widespread corruption in local
politics. Hernandez later pleaded guilty to a charge of conspiracy
to commit bank fraud in an unrelated federal case, insuring he
would face at least five years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   But now the case of Hernandez, 35, has taken another turn.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, five days after The Miami Herald reported that
Hernandez's wife and lawyer were spotted kissing at a popular
Coconut Grove restaurant, a federal judge ordered the lawyer, Jose
Quinon, to have no more contact with Hernandez and to return all
fees paid for his representation. She ordered Quinon's business and
personal bank accounts frozen until he complied.
</P>
<P>
   In issuing the order after prosecutors presented her with a
sealed motion on Monday, the judge, Joan Lenard of U.S. District
Court in Miami, did not explain why she was taking the action. But
she wrote: ``The court recognizes that these matters impact
sensitive and personal issues of great human dimension, affecting
real persons and their families. The court further recognizes that
these matters are of significant import to the legal community, to
the clients whom attorneys represent with integrity and to the
community at large.''
</P>
<P>
   The Herald reported that Hernandez screamed ``I'm going to ruin
him! I'm going to make sure he never practices law again!'' when he
read the Saturday article while at the Federal Detention Center in
Miami, where he is being held.
</P>
<P>
   But the turn of events has left Miami's legal community almost
as jarred as Hernandez. Neither Quinon nor his lawyer returned
telephone calls seeking comment, but other criminal defense lawyers
worried about the reputation of someone they regard among the best
in their field.
</P>
<P>
   A former state prosecutor, the Cuban-born Quinon, 47, has been
involved in numerous high-profile cases, representing Colombian
drug cartel leaders, politicians accused of corruption and most
recently the president of the Cuban-American National Foundation
during a federal investigation of a plot to kill Fidel Castro.
Friends said he has three children and was separated from his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always found him to be not only an outstanding human
being but a great lawyer,'' said Richard Sharpstein, a former
colleague of Quinon's when they both worked as prosecutors in Janet
Reno's Miami-Dade County state attorney's office and a friend of 23
years. ``Even though this may open up doors for Hernandez from a
legal point of view, these are doors he may not want to walk
through.''
</P>
<P>
   It is unclear whether Quinon and Mrs. Hernandez had a
relationship while Quinon defended Hernandez, or even if they have
one now. But defense lawyers said Hernandez could use any evidence
of a relationship to argue that Quinon might not have represented
his best interest. The lawyers said Hernandez could then say that
was grounds to have his plea deal in the federal bank fraud case
withdrawn and to win a new trial on the state voting fraud
conviction, which is being appealed.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But Sharpstein and other lawyers noted that Hernandez was
acquitted of the more serious charges in the state case and
convicted only of a misdemeanor, for which he was sentenced to a
year in jail. And in the federal case Hernandez, himself a lawyer,
had faced a 23-count indictment on charges of money laundering and
mortgage fraud that could have put him in jail for 13 years. But
federal prosecutors accepted his plea and agreed that at his
sentencing next month he be given a four-year prison term.
</P>
<P>
   In its Oct. 17 story, the Herald reported that Quinon and Esther
Hernandez, the commissioner's wife, were spotted together last
month at a Mexican restaurant during happy hour. Among the
restaurant's patrons who saw them that night were Judge Thomas
Wilson Jr. of the state circuit court and Miami-Dade County
Commissioner Jimmy Morales and his wife, Dori, who was quoted as
saying: ``They were hanging out at the bar, kissing. I was
horrified.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Wilson told the newspaper: ``It looked to me like a couple
that had just started going out and found each other attractive.''
Wilson refused to answer questions about the case through a bailiff
and Commissioner Morales did not return calls made to his office.
</P>
<P>
   Lenard also appointed Bob Josefsberg as a lawyer for Hernandez.
Josefsberg, who expected to meet with Hernandez for the first time
on Thursday, said he would advise Hernandez not to talk to the
media but had not decided what to do next.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
