<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NY-ENDORSEMENTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: FOR THE LEGISLATURE FROM NEW YORK CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, Oct. 23:
</P>
<P>
   Many of New York state's legislative districts are so dominated
by one party that the real elections occur in the primaries. These
are our endorsements for some of the more contested races in New
York City.
</P>
<P>
   Senate District 23 (Brooklyn, Staten Island): Sen. Vincent
Gentile, a first-term Democrat, is being challenged by a
conservative Republican, Christopher Mega, who gave up the seat
five years ago to become a judge. Recently Mega left his post as
presiding judge of New York state's Court of Claims to try to
regain his old Senate seat. If he is elected, Mega, 67, plans to
keep collecting retirement pay from his earlier years as a senator
and judge, as well as his full salary as senator. That amounts to a
six-figure income _ a spectacular example of double-dipping for a
politician who bills himself as a fiscal conservative. When he left
the Legislature for the judiciary, Mega said it was time for fresh
faces in Albany. We agree. Gentile, who is 39 and has worked hard
for his district, deserves to continue as its representative.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly District 26 (Queens): Ann-Margaret Carrozza, a
Democrat, is also facing a vigorous rematch, with Douglas Prescott,
a Republican who narrowly lost to Ms. Carrozza two years ago.
Prescott held the seat before that for 14 years, with little to
show for it. Ms. Carrozza's own political identity still seems
unformed. While she complains about the lack of independent
thinking in Albany, she has stuck close to the Democratic
leadership in her first term. But her record for hard work tops
that of her predecessor. She has been quietly fighting for seniors
and the public college system. After only two years on the job, Ms.
Carrozza should be allowed to continue to pursue these vital
issues.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly District 30 (Queens): Margaret Markey, a Democrat, is
making overcrowded schools her prime issue, in contrast to Michael
Kuzmicz, her Republican opponent, who is focusing on crime.
Kuzmicz, an assistant district attorney in Queens, has run an
energetic campaign, but Mrs. Markey gets our endorsement for her
much broader history of community service.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly District 49 (Brooklyn): Peter Abbate, the incumbent
Democrat, is being challenged by Luigi Marano, a retired state
Supreme Court justice. Marano, who is 77, says his main mission in
campaigning for the Assembly after 30 years as a judge and
assistant state attorney general is to work against late-term
abortion. His other mission may be to bring out Republican voters
for other races on the ballot this election. Although Abbate has
nuzzled too close to the tobacco interests in recent years, we
endorse him for his efforts on behalf of senior citizens, his work
pushing for improvement of legislative operations and for tax
abatements in historic districts.
</P>
<P>
   Assembly District 60 (Staten Island): This race has turned into
a bitter and expensive contest between a likable longtime
Democratic incumbent, Eric Vitaliano, and his Republican
challenger, Glenn Yost, a former New York City police detective.
Yost favors term limits but opposes limits on campaign donations, a
far more important tool for political accountability. We endorse
Vitaliano.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
