<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PUBLIC-LIVES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERIES FALLOUT  
 NAMESAKES  
 LONGING FOR HOME 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (lb) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Now is the time for all good museum directors to
collect on the silly bets they made before the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, MICHAEL HAGER, the executive director of the San
Diego Natural History Museum, wrote to ELLEN FUTTER, the president
of the American Museum of Natural History. He proposed that the
person whose team lost the Series treat the other to two nights in
the losing city. He also said that his museum had a great white
shark with a Padres cap and a Yankees jersey in its mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Futter put a Yankees cap on an allosaurus and a Padres
jersey in its mouth.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about the evolutionary superiority of the New York
animal,'' she said Thursday. ``We're a winning species. Not
necessarily gracious, but winning.'' And as far as going to San
Diego, ``we believe in the investigation of other civilizations.''
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, during Game 3, JACK NICHOLSON went to Matthew
Bourne's ``Swan Lake,'' the testosterone-fueled Broadway remake of
the 120-year-old ballet. At intermission, he went backstage.
Someone said it was the bottom of the third, and the score was ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to know,'' Nicholson snapped, sounding like a
tough guy from the movies.
</P>
<P>
   After ``Swan Lake,'' he went to his hotel, where his assistant
had taped the game. He watched it from opening pitch to final out.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, Nicholson went to a party at Lot 61, a restaurant
west of Chelsea, for ALAN FINKELSTEIN, an inventor who devised a
credit card with a built-in magnifying glass. KEVIN COSTNER, ART
GARFUNKEL and SEAN PENN were there, too. But it was Nicholson who
wanted to see Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   So AMY SACCO, an owner of Lot 61, set up a television in a back
room for Nicholson. And only Nicholson.
</P>
<P>
   Namesakes
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The invitation for the International Press Freedom
Awards dinner listed well-known news executives and television
personalities. Right between the names of RICHARD M. SMITH, the
chairman and editor in chief of Newsweek, and MATTHEW STORIN, the
editor of The Boston Globe, were ``Kenneth and Marisa Starr.''
</P>
<P>
   Has the Whitewater independent counsel decided to spend an
evening socializing with journalists?
</P>
<P>
   This is a tale of two Kenneth Starrs. The Committee to Protect
Journalists, the sponsor of the Nov. 24 event, says the one who is
coming to dinner is a business manager with his own firm on Park
Avenue. (For the record, the independent counsel's wife's name is
Alice.)
</P>
<P>
   And then there are the two George Stephanopouloses. The one who
moved from Washington to New York used to work at the White House.
The one who recently moved from New York to Washington is the
director of business affairs for Discovery Communications, a
company that runs several cable-television channels.
</P>
<P>
   Do people confuse them?
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't be the first,'' said the Stephanopoulos who
spends his time behind the camera. ``He's my first cousin.''
</P>
<P>
   Longing for Home
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Brooklyn Museum of Art gave a party fit for an
empress on Wednesday. The empress in question _ an empress in
exile, really _ was the widow of the shah of Iran, FARAH PAHLEVI.
The occasion was the opening of an exhibition of Persian paintings
from the 19th century, a time when patronage of the arts flourished
under the Qajar dynasty.
</P>
<P>
   The talk turned to the changes in Iran. Some people at the
dinner, including the philanthropist CECILE ZILKHA, expressed hope
that the increased openness could mean that Iranians who fled after
the shah's expulsion could eventually return, at least to visit.
The former empress, whose image was fixed in many Americans' minds
when she and the dying shah searched for a new homeland in the late
1970s, divides her time between Connecticut and France.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-98 2333EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
