<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TELEGROUP-OFFERS-585&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TELEGROUP SAID TO ENTERTAIN BUYOUT OFFERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Telegroup Inc., a small international telephone carrier that was
flying high just six months ago, is on the verge of running out of
cash and is weighing takeover offers from at least two
communications companies, executives close to the discussions said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   With insolvency looming, Telegroup is the first major
telecommunications casualty of the credit evaporation for companies
that are smaller than huge. As markets around the world have
devolved into turmoil, lenders have essentially halted financing
for companies whose prospects are considered uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   The crunch could become particularly acute in the communications
industry, with its high capital requirements and fierce
competition. For instance, USN Communications Inc., a new local
phone company, has seen its shares starved to 62.5 cents from a
high of $23 in March, shortly after its initial public offering.
</P>
<P>
   But while USN had only $47.2 million in revenue last year,
Telegroup had sales of $337.4 million. And that is attracting
suitors.
</P>
<P>
   Primus Telecommunications Group Inc. and IDT Corp., two of
Telegroup's brethren as new, fast-growing communications carriers,
have each made offers for Telegroup, said executives close to the
talks.
</P>
<P>
   Telegroup's market value has decreased to about $110 million
from around $775 million in April. The company expects revenue of
about $105 million for the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   The company's shares closed at $3.25 Thursday, up 71.875 cents,
in Nasdaq trading. Last Friday, the shares traded as low as
$1.0313.
</P>
<P>
   The run-up could be a product of speculation that there may be a
bidding war for the company. But the Primus and IDT bids each would
give next to nothing to the public holders of Telegroup's stock,
according to executives close to the discussions.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the offers are aimed directly at Telegroup's
bondholders, to whom the company owes about $105 million. The
largest holders of Telegroup's debt are Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co. and
Laurence Tisch's Loews Corp., according to executives close to
Telegroup.
</P>
<P>
   But Merrill Lynch and Loews do not even have the first claim to
Telegroup's assets. In August, Telegroup gave that right to
Foothill Capital Corp. as part of a $12 million credit deal.
</P>
<P>
   According to a Telegroup filing with the Securities and Exchange
Commission, Foothill's loan ``is secured by substantially all of
the company's assets and expires on November 2, 1998.''
</P>
<P>
   An executive close to Telegroup, however, said Thursday that the
company had until the end of next month to repay Foothill and that
the loan was secured only by unpaid bills owed to Telegroup.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Telegroup does not have enough money to meet its
operating expenses for much longer, said executives close to the
discussions, and could be out of cash within weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The executives said there are subtle but important differences
between IDT's and Primus' offers. Primus, according to the
executives, has asked the bondholders to put an additional $40
million into the company. In exchange, Primus would continue to
service the debt at rates only slightly lower than those being paid
now.
</P>
<P>
   IDT, on the other hand, would commit about $25 million in cash
to Telegroup's business and include performance incentives for
Telegroup's management. In exchange, the bondholders would have to
accept interest rates potentially lower than those paid by Primus,
the executives said.
</P>
<P>
   Telegroup, IDT, Primus, Merrill Lynch, Foothill and Loews all
declined to comment.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Other companies that might bid for Telegroup include Star
Telecommunications Inc. and Worldxchange Communications.
</P>
<P>
   In early August, Telegroup prepared a high-yield debt offering
of between $225 million and $250 million. But then the bottom fell
out of the credit market and the company was forced to retrench. It
entered the deal with Foothill, postponed plans to upgrade its
communications network and said it would scale back its low-profit
efforts to sell communications services to other phone companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a matter of timing more than anything else,'' said
Gregory Miller, an analyst for Jefferies &AMP; Co. ``Had these guys
caught the market 60 or 90 days earlier, they would be OK. Not
great, but OK. At least they would still be in business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
