u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FASB-MERGER-RULES-580     10-22 0773
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FASB-MERGER-RULES-580&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROPOSED ACCOUNTING RULE COULD CRIMP FUTURE MERGERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MELODY PETERSEN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Financial Accounting Standards Board has tentatively decided
on new rules that might make companies think twice about future
mergers and acquisitions because of their effect on the bottom
line.
</P>
<P>
   While working on a draft of the new rules on Wednesday, board
members decided to change the accounting method known as purchase
accounting so that companies would be forced to take bigger charges
to earnings in the early years after an acquisition.
</P>
<P>
   The decision is significant because the board is also expected
to greatly restrict or even eliminate the other method that
companies use to account for mergers and acquisitions.
</P>
<P>
   That method, known as a pooling of interest, was used in dozens
of deals this year, including the mergers of Daimler-Benz AG and
Chrysler Corp., and of Citicorp and Travelers Group Inc. With
pooling, two companies simply combine their balance sheets and thus
avoid charges they would face under purchase accounting rules.
</P>
<P>
   Some accounting analysts on Wall Street said Thursday that
Wednesday's move by the accounting board, known as the FASB, would
force many companies to give up merger plans when they see that
future earnings will be hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if the acquisition makes strategic sense, I'm quite
confident that many acquisitions won't get done,'' said Robert
Willens, a managing director at Lehman Brothers, the securities and
investment banking firm. ``I'm quite upset about this. I think FASB
will find some fairly serious opposition from the business
community.''
</P>
<P>
   But other analysts and accountants have long criticized the
current accounting rules, especially pooling, because it often
allows companies to pay hefty prices for other companies but leave
barely a trace of what may have been a dangerous decision in the
accounting ledgers.
</P>
<P>
   While Wall Street bankers and analysts have been expecting the
accounting board to restrict pooling, they were cheered earlier
this year when the board decided to make the purchase accounting
rules more desirable by letting some companies avoid large charges.
On Wednesday, the board reversed that decision.
</P>
<P>
   Under purchase accounting, the acquiring company records the
assets and liabilities of the company being acquired on the balance
sheet at their market value. Any amount paid above the net value of
the assets must be recorded as an intangible asset known as good
will.
</P>
<P>
   For some companies with valuable trademarks, patents, technology
or licenses, the good will can be valued at billions of dollars.
When Walt Disney Co. acquired ABC in 1996, Disney recorded $19
billion in good will and other intangible assets.
</P>
<P>
   Under the purchase accounting rules, companies must gradually
write off the good will by taking annual charges to earnings. Many
companies, including Disney, write off the amount over 40 years,
the maximum length of time available under the current rules, to
minimize the annual charge.
</P>
<P>
   But on Wednesday, the accounting board tentatively decided to
limit the write-offs to 20 years, which means the annual charge
will double for many companies. If that rule had been in place when
Disney acquired ABC, for example, the company's charge to earnings
from good will would have been $950 million a year for 20 years
rather than $475 million annually for 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the accounting board ruled out a plan to allow
companies to keep good will on their balance sheets indefinitely in
certain cases with no effect on earnings.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Timothy Lucas, director of research at the accounting board in
Norwalk, Conn., said the board changed an earlier decision after
testing the proposed rules. Several companies that had recently
made acquisitions tried to prepare financial statements under the
proposed rules, he said, but found it difficult.
</P>
<P>
   The board is expected to issue a draft of the new rules for
public comment early next year.
</P>
<P>
   Willens said the accounting board was ignoring the many cases in
which it made sense to leave good will on the balance sheet
indefinitely because its value did not decline over the years. For
instance, he said, many intangible assets like trademarks, patents
and trade secrets may actually increase in value.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good will is all the things taken together that make you
believe that customers will continue to buy your products,'' he
said. ``Those aren't depreciable assets. They're appreciable
assets.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
