<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA CORNERBACKS CORPS NO LONGER A CONCERN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1998 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA's defense ranks ninth in the Pac-10 in yards
allowed (408 per game) and eighth in points allowed (27.6). The
line has not recorded a sack in five games. The linebacking corps
includes two freshmen and a sophomore. Safety is a constant
concern, two players having tried (and failed) to support
All-American Larry Atkins.
</P>
<P>
   The only position not of immediate concern is cornerback. For
longtime Bruins watchers, that's a pleasant surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Bell and Ryan Roques, with a little help from reserve
Marques Anderson, have solidified an oft-troublesome position.
Playing man-to-man coverage almost exclusively, they're forcing
opponents to make difficult catches while eliminating the open
25-yarders that plagued the Bruins earlier this season.
</P>
<P>
   In September, UCLA's opponents completed 51.3 percent of their
passes; in October, 44.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting more confident every game,'' Bell said. ``And
we're getting more comfortable. Everything's going real well.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell thrives on being physical _ ``My high school coach told me
if I don't get a pass-interference penalty, I'm not playing hard,''
he said _ while Roques is a graceful athlete who converted from
tailback last season. He has four interceptions this season, tops
in the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're picking on Ryan, we talk about that all the time,''
Bell said. ``But they can only pick on him so much. He's in all the
right places at all the right times.''
</P>
<P>
   Positioning, Bell said, is the key to success. Each week
defensive coordinator Nick Aliotti instructs the cornerbacks to
eliminate one aspect of the opponent's passing game.
</P>
<P>
   Against Oregon, for instance, the defensive scheme prevented
post patterns (middle of the field), leaving Bell and Roques free
to concentrate on sideline routes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we play, we try to take away 50 percent of the
field,'' Bell said.
</P>
<P>
   Just for kicks: Chris Sailer punted Thursday _ his only exertion
of the week _ and is expected to perform all his kicking duties
Saturday despite a strained right groin.
</P>
<P>
   ``He feels considerably better,'' coach Bob Toledo said.
</P>
<P>
   Walk-on kicker Chris Griffith will make the trip. The backup
punter is quarterback Cade McNown, who averaged 71.5 yards on two
punts last year.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo is hesitant to waste Griffith's redshirt year on a few
kickoffs and will give the order only as a last resort.
</P>
<P>
   Review of the Week: All-American offensive tackle Kris Farris is
a film buff who wants to make movies when his career ends. He has
agreed to review a movie each week for the Daily News. This week:
``Everest,'' showing at the IMAX theater in Exposition Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``For those unfortunate souls who have not experienced the
gripping visual splendor of an IMAX film, `Everest' is the perfect
way to start. It is, by far, the finest IMAX film to date and has
sparked new life in an exciting film genre.
</P>
<P>
   ``The film details the ascent of six world-class climbers
following the May '96 disaster. Full of breathtaking visuals,
`Everest' enables the audience to feel as if they are part of the
expedition.
</P>
<P>
   ``What makes `Everest' special is the film's dramatic appeal,
something previous IMAX attempts had trouble accomplishing.
`Everest' is the must-see movie of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   Rating: 4 pancakes (out of four).
</P>
<P>
   Note: Reading Jon Krakauer's book on the Mt. Everest disaster,
``Into Thin Air,'' is highly recommended.
</P>
<P>
   Steppin' in: Redshirt freshman Jason Stephens will make his
first start Saturday at strong safety, UCLA's most troublesome
position. Tod McBride started three games, then was removed because
of alignment difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jason brings us a toughness,'' Aliotti said. ``I'm confident
he'll line up correctly, but he's got to learn to be more
disciplined.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
