<SLUG> BC-BKN-PLAYERS-MEETING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
240 NBA PLAYERS MEET IN UNITED FRONT 
</HEADLINE>
  (dl) 
 By MIKE WISE    
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ Karl Malone made an impassioned plea for unity.
Michael Jordan and David Robinson said the greatest obstacle their
fellow locked-out players may face was divisiveness.
</P>
<P>
   The largest assembly ever of NBA players _ 240 from all economic
classes _ stood shoulder to shoulder Thursday in a Caesars Palace
ballroom in Las Vegas. From Joe Kleine to Jordan, the message to
the owners was clear: They will not accept a hard salary cap even
if it means canceling the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're in it for the long haul,'' said Buck Williams, the
former union president. ``We cannot give the owners the cost
certainty they feel they need. It's not going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I've been in the union for a long time, but I've
never seen the resolve or the dedication to the cause like today. I
was really taken aback by it. This is phenomenal.''
</P>
<P>
   The players voted unanimously at the end of a three-hour session
that they would not accept a hard salary cap in a new collective
bargaining agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if his presence meant he would return to the Bulls, Jordan
said at a news conference after the meetings: ``I haven't made my
decision about coming back. I haven't made my decision, but that
doesn't mean I shouldn't be part of the union.''
</P>
<P>
   The league is no closer to opening for business than it was when
it canceled the first two weeks of the season on Oct. 7. The next
scheduled bargaining talks will probably be held on Thursday in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Billy Hunter, the union's executive director, boasted that the
same number of players would attend the owners' meeting next week
that attended Thursday. However, if 100 players showed, the union
would be ecstatic.
</P>
<P>
   The players listened to union leaders from other sports,
including Gene Upshaw, the executive director of the NFL's players
association, and Donald Fehr, who holds the same title with the
Major League Baseball players association.
</P>
<P>
   ``My message to them was that they have some options, but in my
opinion I really believe they should decertify soon,'' Upshaw said.
``With no progress, I think they should sue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great plea for us to stay united and stick
together,'' Charles Barkley said. ``One of the reasons they wanted
all of the stars here is to let them know we're in this together.
The league wants it to be about the haves and have-nots. I'm one of
the haves. If I never work another day in my life, I'm going to be
fine. But it's not our intention to leave the young guys or the
middle-of-the-road guys out in the cold.''
</P>
<P>
   Because ownership representatives from all 29 teams will be in
New York on Wednesday for the league's board of governors meeting,
the next talks should take place next week.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties have rejected luxury-tax proposals and accused the
other side of failing to negotiate with the notion of working
toward a new agreement. Russ Granik, the NBA's deputy commissioner,
said the league would decide whether to cancel more games after the
board of governors meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Players on Thursday were not hopeful of a quick settlement. Some
openly voiced their concern about losing a season's worth of
salary.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, our effort should be focused on making the deal,''
said David Falk, the agent for Jordan and several other superstars.
``If the league makes that goal impossible, I think you have to
explore the other options.''
</P>
<P>
   After losing a key arbitration decision on Monday that killed
any opportunity for players to be paid during the lockout, a few
players around the country voiced genuine concern and wondered
aloud whether a hard-line approach should be kept up against the
owners.
</P>
<P>
   But as they left the ballroom this afternoon, each player
sounded as if he was working toward the same goals.
</P>
<P>
   Said Juwan Howard, the executive vice president for the union,
``After today, there will be no sell-outs.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-10-22-98 2345EDT &QL; 
