<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-10-22 23:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2820 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-ZONING-ACTIVIST-57     10-22 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ZONING-ACTIVIST-575&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN SCRAPING THE SKY MAKES A CITY BLEED 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By RANDY KENNEDY   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He is polite about it, but Edward Rubin really
doesn't like to talk about himself with reporters. He will list the
firms where he worked as a young architect, before he started his
own firm in the Flatiron district. He will say that he and his
wife, Susan, a teacher at Stuyvesant High School, have two
daughters, one in high school, one in college. He will reveal that
he grew up in the Bronx, that his family was in retail (some
coaxing draws out the fact that his father ran a restaurant).
</P>
<P>
   But Rubin has often agreed to talk to reporters anyway _ he
remembers spending an hour with a television crew, just to see his
comments winnowed to a single on-air ``yes'' _ because he is
passionate about his subject.
</P>
<P>
   And his subject is one he has a hard time getting many other
people to be passionate about: zoning.
</P>
<P>
   That is, until someone starts to build an apartment tower in
their back yard. And suddenly, such soporific concepts as
air-rights transfers, zoning lot mergers and floor-to-area ratios
take on urgent meaning.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings Rubin to Donald Trump and his plan to build what he
says will be the world's tallest residential tower, an 861-foot,
bronze-tinted glass palace across the street from the U.N. complex.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin, 57, who heads the land use committee of Community Board 6
on the East Side, has long proselytized for a kind of quasi
religion practiced by an array of Manhattan architects, planners
and community leaders. They believe in the goodness of an urban
island made up of distinct neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   The problem, however, is that Manhattan neighborhoods are fast
losing their identity. And the catalyst is the 1961 zoning laws,
tattered with loopholes, that Rubin says allow developers like
Trump to build skyscrapers in neighborhoods where they do not
belong, cloaking streets in shadow and clogging them with people.
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, the laws and later interpretations of them have
allowed builders to buy rights to develop taller buildings _ known
as air rights _ from owners near their sites.
</P>
<P>
   This means that a church, for example, which has a right under
zoning rules to put up a taller building on its land, can sell that
right to someone who wants to build a tower taller than the law
allows next door or, in some cases, nearby.
</P>
<P>
   Trump, a grandmaster of this delicate legal chess game, quietly
gathered air rights from several smaller buildings near land he had
bought on First Avenue between 47th and 48th streets. Then he
combined them to double the height of his building, meaning that
the tower will dwarf the U.N. Secretariat and that the top floor
will afford views almost as grand as those from the Empire State
Building.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin pulls no punches when asked about the tower. ``When you
look at the skyline of Manhattan and see the Empire State Building,
you see a symbol of New York,'' he said the other day in his
office, where an answering machine serves as his secretary. ``When
you see Trump's buildings, you see a symbol of his ego.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Trump responded by saying he did not know Rubin but
he did not completely disagree with him. ``I think there are
certain sites and certain areas that cry out for shorter
buildings,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But of his new tower, he said: ``There are many buildings
surrounding the United Nations that are much taller than the United
Nations. Mine is taller, but there are many buildings that are very
tall in the area.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Rubin stresses that he is not a knee-jerk opponent of
development. He has helped build smaller buildings himself, and
with only a whiff of irony, he calls development a ``perfectly
legitimate occupation.'' (Jesse Masyr, a lawyer who represents
large developers, says he often disagrees with Rubin but never
seems to go away hating him. ``You run up against people who take
positions mostly for their own glory, and I never felt Ed did
that,'' he said. ``And this is a guy who didn't support anything I
ever proposed, I think.'')
</P>
<P>
   But Rubin cannot conceal his fervor when he believes that
builders are being allowed to rob Manhattan neighborhoods of their
character. In the early 1980s, he led a group that helped kill
Riverwalk, a luxury development planned for the East River between
18th and 23d Streets. In 1987, he joined hundreds of marchers,
including Jacqueline Kennedy Onassis, who opened umbrellas in
Central Park to symbolize the shadows they said would be cast by
towers planned for Columbus Circle.
</P>
<P>
   He avoids parties thrown by developers _ ``It's very easy in the
political sense to owe somebody something,'' he says _ and he loves
to tell a story about one of his design professors at the
University of California at Berkeley. The professor was talking to
a developer, who asked if he wanted to see a beautiful building.
The developer produced a balance sheet, pointed to the bottom line
and said, ``That's a beautiful building.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People have different senses of aesthetics,'' Rubin said.
</P>
<P>
   But he added that competing aesthetics, even angrily opposed
visions, can coexist within rational limits. ``There are many
loopholes that can be closed, and I don't think it will affect
development in New York City at all,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Donald Trump didn't build an 800-foot building, somebody
else would have built a more contextual tower that may have been 30
stories,'' he said. ``They would have made a lot of money and
probably done a nice job.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
