<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-YANKEES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: WORLD CHAMPS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Friday, Oct. 23:
</P>
<P>
   Now that this New York Yankee team has certified its claim to
greatness by winning the World Series, and finishing the year with
an astounding 125-50 record, the debate has turned to whether this
is the best Yankee team of all time or merely the team with the
most victories. But for our money, the really interesting thing is
that the 1998 Yankees were a team that even Yankee-haters could
like.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, egos were in unusually short supply, as were
superstars. There was little of the old Yankee swagger, and even
less of the backbiting of the Reggie Jackson/Thurman Munson era.
When Chuck Knoblauch made a silly mental error that helped the
Cleveland Indians win a crucial playoff game a couple of weeks ago,
the team rallied around him, with nary a snide comment to the
press. The players seemed genuinely to believe in teamwork and
unselfishness _ virtues reflected in the series sweep, when
everyone made an important contribution. There is not, so far, a
sure-fire Hall of Famer in the bunch. But all year long you knew
that somebody somewhere in the lineup would cause the team's
opponents some real damage.
</P>
<P>
   The likability of this team extends to its manager, Joe Torre, a
nice guy who finishes first, and even, at least for this brief
moment, to its volcanic owner George Steinbrenner, who seems to
have mellowed this year. There were no tirades, no summary
dismissals of personnel. In the locker room Wednesday night he
actually choked up as he celebrated the fourth World Championship
of his tumultuous 26-year reign. As our colleague Harvey Araton
noted the other day, Steinbrenner is a throwback, an entrepreneur
in an era of faceless corporate ownership. Like him or not, he
doesn't hide.
</P>
<P>
   So here's hoping that these Yankees will survive the siren call
of free agency and stick together. Here's hoping, too, that
Steinbrenner, softened by victory and possibly by age, will drop
his scorched-earth campaign for a new stadium. The Yankees have
done rather well in the Bronx over the last 60 or so years, and 3
million people showed up to watch them win a pennant and another
World Championship this year. There's no more reason to move the
Yankees than there is to break them up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
