<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-GLENN-REACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: JOHN GLENN'S PEERS ARE TICKLED BY HIS ADVENTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By CLYDE HABERMAN   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ All but lost in the whirl of important issues, like
which Senate candidate is proving to be rougher, was a recent
report on how federal agents arrested seven middle-aged New Yorkers
on burglary and racketeering charges. It put the lie to the slander
that the press never prints good news.
</P>
<P>
   If you are part of the fast-growing tribe that will never see 50
again, you had to be heartened by the exploits of this daring band,
which included a few men who are taking a bead on 60. One of them
even lives in a nursing home.
</P>
<P>
   For many years, or so the Feds say, the suspects broke into
thousands of homes and estates in New York suburbs _ thousands _
grabbing furs, jewelry and antiques worth millions. Then, it is
charged, they took their loot back to Manhattan and sold it to
fences. (And why not? Wasn't it Willie Sutton who said good fences
make good neighbors? Or was that from a Robert Frost poem? Can't
remember.)
</P>
<P>
   Faster than you can say Butch Cassidy, the suspects were dubbed
the ``Over the Hill Gang.'' Talk about insults! Over the hill? The
Magnificent Seven is more like it.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, stealing is wrong. Still, how can anyone not marvel at
talented men and women who have passed the test of time, who
avoided capture until well into their middle years, who favored
craftsmanship over violence and who epitomized virtues lost on many
young people, like diligence and attentiveness to detail?
</P>
<P>
   But a middle-ager's appreciation of their skills pales in
comparison with the admiration that many people of more advanced
years have for a distinguished member of their own generation who
still has the right stuff. We're talking about Sen. John Glenn,
scheduled to blast into space next week, 36 years after he became
the first American to orbit Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Too old at 77 to ride the shuttle Discovery? Nonsense, said
Carol Delmonte at the Luna Park Senior Center in Coney Island.
``Maybe he wants to make a name for senior citizens,'' she said.
``If he can do that, why can't I do that? After all, if I can still
get around and work, why shouldn't I? Why can't I?''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn's imminent return to space was Thursday's topic for a
discussion group that convenes regularly at the senior center, run
by the Jewish Association for Services for the Aged with financing
from the city's Department for the Aging. Some of the 20 men and
women gathered around a big corner table were less than eager to
disclose their ages. Let's just say that most were in their 70s and
80s.
</P>
<P>
   And most, it is safe to say, felt encouraged by the senator's
adventure, finding in it an exciting affirmation of a point all too
often lost on a society that suggests that the only people who
count are those in the absurdly broad marketing category bracketed
by the ages 18 and 49.
</P>
<P>
   The point is simple: There is no such thing as being too old,
and while life may not begin at 80, it does not end there, either.
``We're young people in older bodies _ that's all it is,'' said
Anne Fink, who gets around these days in a motorized cart.
</P>
<P>
   What the Glenn journey in space reinforces is that there is
``always a past, a present and a future,'' said Rose Miller in a
swirl of overlapping comments about the importance of remaining
active, especially mentally. In that vein, Ms. Delmonte noted that
``people are getting married at 90,'' an observation that prompted
Norma Lichtenstein to chime in, laughing, ``You mean there's hope
for me yet?''
</P>
<P>
   Don't misunderstand. Not too many at Luna Park believed that the
world desperately needs to find out what effect weightlessness in
space has on the elderly. These are people who are not about to
board the nearby Cyclone roller coaster, let alone the Discovery.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going to learn anything from this,'' said Thelma
Levine, dismissing the exercise as a waste of taxpayer money (a
remark that led some to damn the Starr report as an even bigger
waste and others to tell the latest Monica Lewinsky joke). Hy Silbe
suggested that ``John Glenn is more valuable doing what he's been
doing on the ground than going up in space.'' The flight is ``just
an ego trip,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Ezra Levine saw nothing awful in an ego trip. His point may
well apply to skilled cat burglars of middle age, although it
probably works better with a 70-something astronaut hero. ``Maybe
he just wants to see if he can still do things,'' Levine said.
``Why not, if it gives him a longer life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
