u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-AGENCIES-ABO     10-22 0431
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-AGENCIES-ABOLISH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.C.)  
 TWO FOREIGN AFFAIRS AGENCIES ARE ELIMINATED 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Two independent foreign affairs agencies were
abolished this week by a stroke of President Clinton's pen, and a
third will have its independence sharply curtailed under a
reorganization plan for the State Department that was championed by
Republican leaders in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   The two agencies, the Arms Control and Disarmament Agency and
the U. S. Information Agency, were abolished under the catchall
spending bill that Clinton signed on Wednesday night. Their
responsibilities will pass to the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation allows the U.S. Agency for International
Development to remain in business but requires it to report to the
secretary of state instead of the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The moves, which had been resisted by senior officials in all
three agencies, represented an important victory for Sen. Jesse
Helms, R-N.C., who made the reorganization of the State Department
a priority when he took over as chairman of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is one of the first things that he said he intended to do
when he became chairman,'' said Helms' spokesman, Marc Thiessen.
``Senator Helms kept pushing and it has finally happened. We've
actually shut down two government agencies. It's slimming down the
bureaucracy. It's bringing more coherence to foreign affairs
institutions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration agreed to support the abolishments
and the reorganization in part to win concessions from Helms on
other foreign policy issues.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation signed by Clinton said the purpose of the
reorganization was to save money through ``reductions in personnel,
administrative consolidation, including procurement, program
consolidation and consolidation of real properties and leases.''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton administration officials said Thursday that it was
unclear how many employees of the three agencies, if any, would
lose their jobs as a result of the reorganization. ``This is more a
reorganization than it is a downsizing,'' a State Department
official said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the legislation, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
must submit a plan to Congress describing how the State Department
will incorporate the functions of the Arms Control and Disarmament
Agency and the Information Agency into the department. The U.S.
Information Agency oversees a variety of programs, including the
Voice of America radio network and the Fulbright scholarships.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
