u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT     10-22 0365
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1998 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   Italy: Reassuring the People
</P>
<P>
   ROME _ Italy's new prime minister, Massimo d'Alema, presented to
Parliament a stay-the-course program designed to reassure Italians
concerned by the fact that he is the first former Communist to head
a government. D'Alema, who had already promised to adhere to the
same 1999 budget drafted by his center-left predecessor, Romano
Prodi, also indicated that he would not give into Communists'
demands for a 35-hour work week.
</P>
<P>
   Britain: Thatcher Defends Pinochet
</P>
<P>
   LONDON _ Margaret Thatcher, Britain's former prime minister,
protested the arrest of Gen. Augusto Pinochet, citing his record as
``a good friend'' to Britain during the Falklands War. In the High
Court, his lawyers demanded the former Chilean dictator's release,
but judges adjourned the case until Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ASIA
</P>
<P>
   Caspian Sea: Meeting on Pipeline
</P>
<P>
   The White House convened a meeting to convince officials from a
dozen oil companies to adopt its plan to build a pipeline from the
oilfields of the Caspian Sea through Turkey. The companies,
including AMOCO, Chevron, Mobil and Texaco, are interested in a
less ambitious project to extend an existing pipeline from
Azerbaijan to Supsa in Georgia. The oil would then be shipped
through the Bosphorus to Turkey. No decision was made but an
administration official said the meeting went well.
</P>
<P>
   AMERICAS
</P>
<P>
   Mexico: Crackdown on Bodyguards
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Authorities here plan to crack down on the 3,000
largely unregulated private security companies that employ 30,000
armed bodyguards, local newspapers reported. The authorities will
compile an official databank on all private guards, listing their
employers and weapons, and applicants for security jobs will be
required to undergo psychological testing.
</P>
<P>
   Canada:
</P>
<P>
   For the fourth day, a blockade set by Maine woodsmen kept
Canadian loggers from crossing the U.S. border. The Canadians had
been entering under a temporary U.S. agricultural assistance
program but local workers feared losing their jobs. No violence was
reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
